<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0187 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-MCCAIN-WRITETHRU-     08-02 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MCCAIN-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    1ST LEDE -- MORE DETAIL
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    McCain offers endorsement
 &HT;    Senator seeks to heal wounds inflicted by challenge to Bush
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By GREG McDONALD
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Sen. John McCain finally exited the presidential
campaign stage Tuesday night, delivering a ringing endorsement of
George W. Bush for the Republican nomination and steering clear of
the campaign finance reform issues that catapulted the Arizona
senator to political prominence.
</P>
<P>
   In the closing speech on the second day of the Republican
National Convention, the senator sought to heal the wounds
inflicted on the party by his primary challenge to Bush. Sounding a
note of harmony, he called on his GOP colleagues to ``build a party
as big as the country we serve.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am grateful for your kindness to a distant runner-up,'' the
senator said to cheers and long applause. ``I am proud to join you
this evening in commending to all Americans the man who now
represents your best wishes and mine for the future of our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   The rousing reception was in stark contrast to the groans of
protest that greeted the senator on Sunday when he officially
released his committed delegates and called on them to back the
Texas governor with the same kind of feverish devotion they had
bestowed on him.
</P>
<P>
   But there were some tears shed among his supporters Tuesday
night for what might have been had McCain's maverick bid for the
presidency upset the well financed Bush juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the senator's supporters seemed upset that their hero
spoke not as a reform advocate but as Bush's vanquished foe, bowing
before him to offer the lavish endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   They had expected a strongly worded endorsement, since the
senator is still, after all, a loyal Republican. But they had hoped
for the same kind of rousing reform-pushing message that helped
McCain attract so many independents and crossover Democrats in the
primary races and that alienated so many in the GOP establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Watson, a strident McCain supporter and the minority
leader of the Rhode Island House of Representatives, described the
speech as ``a bittersweet moment'' signaling finality to McCain's
quest for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would have preferred that the former Vietnam prisoner
of war at least touch on the issue of campaign finance reform, but
he added that he understood why he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised, because John McCain is a bridge-builder.
He's using his appearance to support and unite the party,'' Watson
said. ``This is George Bush's convention, and John McCain is a
loyal Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, McCain made a point of calling on independents
and Democrats to join in the effort to elect Bush, who, he said,
``believes in the greatness of America and the justice of our
cause.''
</P>
<P>
   But absent was any direct reference to the government reform
issues that drew 7 million voters to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans fear that many of those voters will not support the
GOP ticket in November with the senator out of the race. But Watson
predicted that enough would shift their support to Bush to make the
difference in the election outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain brought a lot of independents and Democrats to the
party. That's his legacy, the new faces and the new blood,'' Watson
said. ``And for him to try to transfer their support to George
Bush, that's a very gracious and proper thing for him to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his campaign, McCain talked about the greatness of
American and how its strength is built on a ``cause greater than
self-interest.'' He returned to that theme in his endorsement of
the man he once described as a ``phony reformer'' and a status-quo
Republican whose close ties to the right wing elements of the party
would be divisive to the country.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, the man who a few months ago was not
qualified to be president in McCain's view, had become a healer
instead of a divider.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants nothing to divide us into separate nations. Not
color. Not our race. Not our wealth. Not our religion. Not our
politics. He wants us to live for American as one nation,'' the
senator said, to heavy applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support him. I am grateful to him. And I am proud of him.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XX END XXX
</P>
