<P>
   (NYT36) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-15 --
Condoleezza Rice, Gov. George W. Bush's chief international affairs
adviser, speaking to the Republican National Convention, Tuesday.
Rice, who as an African American, underscores Bush's pledge to put
minorities in consequential roles, cited Bush as a man of
uncommonly good judgment. ``He is focused and consistent. He
believes that we Americans are at our best when we exercise power
without fanfare or arrogance and he speaks plainly with a positive
spirit,'' Rice said. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-14 -- A group of
delegates from Texas listen to their governor George W. Bush
speaking to the Republican National Convention via a satellite
hookup, Tuesday. For the second straight night, Bush addressed the
delegates from the campaign trail, this time from Gettysburg, Pa.,
in front of a desk once owned by President Dwight Eisenhower.
(Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-13 -- A group of
delegates from Texas cheer on their governor George W. Bush
speaking to the Republican National Convention via a satellite
hookup, Tuesday. For the second straight night, Bush addressed the
delegates from the campaign trail, this time from Gettysburg, Pa.,
in front of a desk once owned by President Dwight Eisenhower. Bush
will arrive in Philadelphia Wednesday in a newly decorated Boeing
727 painted red, white and blue with the American flag and
BUSH-CHENEY emblazoned on the side. (Chang W. Lee/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-12 -- John
McCain, who fought a fierce primary battle with George W. Bush last
spring, took the spotlight at the Republican National Convention,
Tuesday to praise his former foe as a leader of ``courage and
character'' who would restore U.S. prestige abroad. The endorsement
by the former Navy pilot, who was shot down in Vietnam and spent 5
1/2 years in a Vietnamese prison camp, provides added luster for
Bush on military issues. (Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-11 -- A group of
delegates from Texas applaud former President Gerald R. Ford during
his speech at the Republican National Convention, Tuesday. (Chang
W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-10 -- New York
City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani greets Maureen Reagan, daughter of
former President Ronald Reagan during the second session of the
Republican National Convention, Tuesday. (Chang W. Lee/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-9 -- Dick
Cheney, the 59-year-old former White House chief of staff,
congressman and secretary of defense, along with his granddaughter
during the second session of the Republican National Convention,
Tuesday. Cheney and George W. Bush plan a campaign swing by train
through Ohio, Michigan and Illinois on Friday, after the
convention. President Clinton won each state handily in 1996. (Ruth
Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-8 -- As the GOP
convention band played ``Devil with a Blue Dress,'' Barbara Bush
took the stage at the Republican National Convention, Tuesday, and
introduced her son George W., appearing by satellite from nearby
Gettysburg, Pa. ``I hope I am the first person to welcome you to
Philadelphia, the city of motherly love,'' she said, a twist on the
``brotherly'' love for which the city likes to be known. (Ruth
Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-7 -- As the GOP
convention band played ``Devil with a Blue Dress,'' Barbara Bush
took the stage at the Republican National Convention, Tuesday, and
introduced her son George W., appearing by satellite from nearby
Gettysburg, Pa. ``I hope I am the first person to welcome you to
Philadelphia, the city of motherly love,'' she said, a twist on the
``brotherly'' love for which the city likes to be known. (Ruth
Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-6 -- Eyes
glistening, Bob Dole speaking during the second session of the
Republican National Convention, Tuesday on behalf of hundreds of
thousands of ``voiceless heroes'' who never came home from wars.
Dole said that wearing this nation's uniform in battle was a grater
honor than winning his party's presidential nomination. In paying
tribute to his comrades in arms, Dole, 77, also hailed young
Americans, ``heroes in waiting.'' (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-5 -- A young
Will Stiers riding high atop father Bill Stiers, a delegate from
Alabama during the second session of the Republican National
Convention, Tuesday. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-4 -- Former
President Gerald R. Ford and his wife Betty along with former
President George Bush and his wife Barbara and Nancy Reagan during
the the second session of the Republican National Convention,
Tuesday. Nancy Reagan left her husband Ronald Reagan's side to
represent him among the former presidents at the convention.
Reagan, 89, is ill with Alzheimer's Disease. (Andrea Mohin/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-3 -- A group of
delegates from New Mexico cheer as they cast votes during the
second session of the Republican National Convention, Tuesday.
(Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-2 -- Gov. Jeb
Bush of Florida on the floor as delegates arrive for the opening
ceremonies of the second session of the Republican National
Convention, Tuesday. As GOP convention delegates trumpeted unity
and military strength, George W. Bush underscored the day's message
with campaign stops paying homage to two of the party's most
enduring heroes: Abraham Lincoln and Dwight Eisenhower. (Suzanne
DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-1 -- On an
evening honoring patriotism and service to America, veterans salute
and applaud during the opening ceremonies of the second session of
the Republican National Convention, Tuesday. For the second
straight night, Gov. George W. Bush spoke to the delegates via
remote hookup -- this time from President Eisenhower's farm in
Gettysburg, Pa., -- not far from the site of the famous Civil War
battle. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW KENSINGTON, Pa. -- Aug.1, 2000 -- HONEST-TEA-3 --
Honest Tea on the packaging line at the company plant in New
Kensington, Pa. (Gary Tramontina/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW KENSINGTON, Pa. -- Aug.1, 2000 -- HONEST-TEA-2 --
Seth Goldman and Barry Nalebuff started Honest Tea two years ago,
to fill what they saw as a neglected market niche. Well aware that
they would be competing against mass-marketed sweetened iced teas
made by their competitors, Goldman and Naalebuff wanted to make an
iced tea that promoted natural tea flavor. Their tea leaves are
high quality and expensive. George Scalf, a brew master, working on
a batch of Honest Tea at the company's plant in New Kensington, Pa.
(Gary Tramontina/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Aug.1, 2000 -- HONEST-TEA-1 -- Seth
Goldman, foreground, and Barry Nalebuff started Honest Tea two
years ago, to fill what they saw as a neglected market niche. Well
aware that they would be competing against mass-marketed sweetened
iced teas made by their competitors, Goldman and Naalebuff wanted
to make an iced tea that promoted natural tea flavor. Nalebuff,
chairman of Honest Tea, and Goldman, chief executive along with
their product. (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) HOUSTON -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- MUSIC-LIMPBIZKIT-REVIEW-HNS
-- For 2,500 Limp Bizkit fans, Monday night in Houston, Texas, the
political and legal ramifications of online music, and the future
of music distribution involving Napster certainly played out in
their favor. Many of Limp Bizkit's performances are being
underwritten by Napster, the online music download site supported
by Limp Bizket, and are free for their fans. Limp Bizkit lead
singer Fred Durst performing during the first of the band's free
shows on Monday at the Aerial Theater. (Dave Rossman/The Houston
Chronicle)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- MERRILL-LYNCH-SCHOLARS --
Twelve years ago, Merrill Lynch chose 251 first graders at random
from some of the toughest neighborhoods in 10 cities and made them
a pledge: graduate from high school by 2000, and we will pay all
your college expenses. The students, 149 of them, gathered in New
York City this week to meet one another for the first time and to
collect some last-minute advice on how to make the transition to
college. (Don Hogan Charles/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-LAZIO -- Rep. Rick
A. Lazio, R-N.Y., running against Hillary Rodham Clinton for the
U.S. Senate seat from New York, breezed through the Republican
National Convention Tuesday without participating in party
functions but seizing the chance to raise money for his campaign.
Lazio in the media pavillion adjacent to the convention. (Jim
Wilson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) JERUSALEM -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- ISRAEL-PERES -- Moshe
Katsav, elected by the Israeli parliament on Monday to be the
Israeli president, reviews an honor guard before his swearing-in
ceremony, Tuesday. Prime Minister Ehud Barak's political problems
deepened Tuesday as his right-wing opponents, sensing blood with
their stunning defeat of Shimon Peres, Barak's presidential
candidate, vowed new efforts to bring down his government. (Rina
Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- POET-LAUREATE-- In October,
when his appointment as Poet Laureate to the Library of Congress
begins, Norton is to publish Stanley Kunitz's 12th book of poetry,
a volume of ``Collected Poems.'' He would like to think there will
be at least one book after that, ``in this millennium,'' he said.
Kunitz, 92, at home in this 1995 file photo. (Sara Krulwich/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-CHENEY -- Dick
Cheney, the 59-year-old former White House chief of staff,
congressman and secretary of defense, has lived in the bubble of
public life for more than a quarter a century. Even Gov. George W.
Bush has gently poked fun at his partner's dry campaign style. So
with Cheney preparing to give the speech of his life to the
convention Wednesday night, the decision in the Bush camp has been
to let Cheney be Cheney, with a few tweaks here and there. Cheney
with his wife Lynne check the view from the podium during a
practice run of his speech Tuesday afternoon. (Chang W. Lee/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- SHADOW-CONVENTION --
Jesse Jackson goes over his notes backstage before addressing the
Shadow Convention on the campus of University of Pennsylvania,
Tuesday. Jackson said the Republican convention's ``multicultural
stage'' is a charade disguising a party that's mostly white and
wealthy and pursues policies that hurt the working poor of all
races. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CHARLESTON, W. Va. -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-BUSH -- As GOP
convention delegates trumpeted unity and military strength, George
W. Bush underscored the day's message with campaign stops paying
homage to two of the party's most enduring heroes: Abraham Lincoln
and Dwight Eisenhower. Bush waves to reporters during a campaign
rally at the West Virginia War Memorial, Tuesday. (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GDP-RDP-DOLE -- Former
presidential candidate Elizabeth Dole greets former House Speaker
Newt Gingrich following a reception in Dole's honor, Tuesday in a
hotel near the site of the Republican National Convention. Dole is
to address convention delegates Monday night. (Jamie
Moncrief/Wilmington Morning Star)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) ARTA, Djibouti -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- SOMALIA-REVIVE-3 --
About 2,000 ordinary Somalis along with most of their leaders have
been meeting in this neighboring country since March trying to
re-make Somalia, which collapsed in civil war in 1991. Asha Haji
Elmi, leader of women delegates to the peace conference, left, and
Abdullahi Ahmed Addou, a leading candidate for Somali president who
for years was the Somali ambassador to the United States. (Tyler
Hicks/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ARTA, Djibouti -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- SOMALIA-REVIVE-2 --
About 2,000 ordinary Somalis along with most of their leaders have
been meeting in this neighboring country since March trying to
re-make Somalia, which collapsed in civil war in 1991. Somalis
discuss their progress during a lunch break, Monday. (Tyler
Hicks/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ARTA, Djibouti -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- SOMALIA-REVIVE -- About
2,000 ordinary Somalis along with most of their leaders have been
meeting in this neighboring country since March trying to re-make
Somalia, which collapsed in civil war in 1991. ``Peace and Love,''
written on a street in Arta, in reference to a conference nearby
attended by Somalis on the establishment of a government in
Somalia. (Tyler Hicks/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CANTON, Ohio -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS --
Not in recent memory has there been more hype surrounding a
broadcaster than the ado about Dennis Miller, who debuted as a
commentator on ABC's ``Monday Night Football'' this week. Miller,
in the ABC broadcast booth, pumps his fist to fans on Monday.
(Matthew J. Lee/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CANTON, Ohio -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS --
Michael Bishop rolls out to elude the rush of 49er linemen Casey
Tisdale and Tyrone Johnson during the Hall of Fame Game, Monday.
Bishop did well enough in his first moments of the summer facing
real, live (if you can call the defense the 49ers cobbled together
in the first half live) professional competition during New
England's exhibition opener Monday night. (Matthew J. Lee/The
Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- AUTHOR-MIN-BOS -- The novel
``Becoming Madame Mao'' has been popping up on bestseller lists in
San Francisco, Los Angeles, and Boston, tells the tale of Jiang
Ching, the wife of Chinese communist leader Mao Tze-tung. In her
boosk, Anchee Min upgrades Jiang Ching from ``demon'' to human, if
a scheming, murderous one. Anchee during a recent interview in
Boston. (Suzanne Kreiter/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BOGOTA, Colombia -- Aug. 1, 2000 --
COLOMBIA-DISPLACED-COX -- Colombia's military has ceded huge swaths
of the countryside to the guerrillas or right-wing paramilitary
gangs. Libia Barahona stands in front of a building in the
Colombian capital she has occupied along with more than 100 other
displaced Colombians. Barahona and her five children fled a rural
town after it was repeatedly attacked by guerrillas and
paramilitary groups. (Mike Williams/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- DISPOSABLE-PAPER-PANS -- For
years commercial bakers have baked their pies and tarts in
disposable paper pans. Now these paper pans are becoming more
available to home bakers. Muffins bake nicely in paper when the
temperature was reduced. (Marty Katz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- MAKING-MAYONNAISE -- Though
most of America still depends on the stiff, oily cream in jars, to
serious cooks making mayonnaise has become as fundamental as
whisking together vinaigrette. As eggs have grown safer in recent
years, many home cooks have been emboldened to make it a part of
their regular repertory. Preparing mayonnaise with eggs and some
lemon. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
