Israeli president, reviews an honor guard before his swearing-in
ceremony, Tuesday. Prime Minister Ehud Barak's political problems
deepened Tuesday as his right-wing opponents, sensing blood with
their stunning defeat of Shimon Peres, Barak's presidential
candidate, vowed new efforts to bring down his government. (Rina
Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- POET-LAUREATE-- In October,
when his appointment as Poet Laureate to the Library of Congress
begins, Norton is to publish Stanley Kunitz's 12th book of poetry,
a volume of ``Collected Poems.'' He would like to think there will
be at least one book after that, ``in this millennium,'' he said.
Kunitz, 92, at home in this 1995 file photo. (Sara Krulwich/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-CHENEY -- Dick
Cheney, the 59-year-old former White House chief of staff,
congressman and secretary of defense, has lived in the bubble of
public life for more than a quarter a century. Even Gov. George W.
Bush has gently poked fun at his partner's dry campaign style. So
with Cheney preparing to give the speech of his life to the
convention Wednesday night, the decision in the Bush camp has been
to let Cheney be Cheney, with a few tweaks here and there. Cheney
with his wife Lynne check the view from the podium during a
practice run of his speech Tuesday afternoon. (Chang W. Lee/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- SHADOW-CONVENTION --
Jesse Jackson goes over his notes backstage before addressing the
Shadow Convention on the campus of University of Pennsylvania,
Tuesday. Jackson said the Republican convention's ``multicultural
stage'' is a charade disguising a party that's mostly white and
wealthy and pursues policies that hurt the working poor of all
races. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CHARLESTON, W. Va. -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GOP-BUSH -- As GOP
convention delegates trumpeted unity and military strength, George
W. Bush underscored the day's message with campaign stops paying
homage to two of the party's most enduring heroes: Abraham Lincoln
and Dwight Eisenhower. Bush waves to reporters during a campaign
rally at the West Virginia War Memorial, Tuesday. (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- GDP-RDP-DOLE -- Former
presidential candidate Elizabeth Dole greets former House Speaker
Newt Gingrich following a reception in Dole's honor, Tuesday in a
hotel near the site of the Republican National Convention. Dole is
to address convention delegates Monday night. (Jamie
Moncrief/Wilmington Morning Star)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) ARTA, Djibouti -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- SOMALIA-REVIVE-3 --
About 2,000 ordinary Somalis along with most of their leaders have
been meeting in this neighboring country since March trying to
re-make Somalia, which collapsed in civil war in 1991. Asha Haji
Elmi, leader of women delegates to the peace conference, left, and
Abdullahi Ahmed Addou, a leading candidate for Somali president who
for years was the Somali ambassador to the United States. (Tyler
Hicks/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ARTA, Djibouti -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- SOMALIA-REVIVE-2 --
About 2,000 ordinary Somalis along with most of their leaders have
been meeting in this neighboring country since March trying to
re-make Somalia, which collapsed in civil war in 1991. Somalis
discuss their progress during a lunch break, Monday. (Tyler
Hicks/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ARTA, Djibouti -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- SOMALIA-REVIVE -- About
2,000 ordinary Somalis along with most of their leaders have been
meeting in this neighboring country since March trying to re-make
Somalia, which collapsed in civil war in 1991. ``Peace and Love,''
written on a street in Arta, in reference to a conference nearby
attended by Somalis on the establishment of a government in
Somalia. (Tyler Hicks/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CANTON, Ohio -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS --
Not in recent memory has there been more hype surrounding a
broadcaster than the ado about Dennis Miller, who debuted as a
commentator on ABC's ``Monday Night Football'' this week. Miller,
in the ABC broadcast booth, pumps his fist to fans on Monday.
(Matthew J. Lee/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CANTON, Ohio -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS --
Michael Bishop rolls out to elude the rush of 49er linemen Casey
Tisdale and Tyrone Johnson during the Hall of Fame Game, Monday.
Bishop did well enough in his first moments of the summer facing
real, live (if you can call the defense the 49ers cobbled together
in the first half live) professional competition during New
England's exhibition opener Monday night. (Matthew J. Lee/The
Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- AUTHOR-MIN-BOS -- The novel
``Becoming Madame Mao'' has been popping up on bestseller lists in
San Francisco, Los Angeles, and Boston, tells the tale of Jiang
Ching, the wife of Chinese communist leader Mao Tze-tung. In her
boosk, Anchee Min upgrades Jiang Ching from ``demon'' to human, if
a scheming, murderous one. Anchee during a recent interview in
Boston. (Suzanne Kreiter/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BOGOTA, Colombia -- Aug. 1, 2000 --
COLOMBIA-DISPLACED-COX -- Colombia's military has ceded huge swaths
of the countryside to the guerrillas or right-wing paramilitary
gangs. Libia Barahona stands in front of a building in the
Colombian capital she has occupied along with more than 100 other
displaced Colombians. Barahona and her five children fled a rural
town after it was repeatedly attacked by guerrillas and
paramilitary groups. (Mike Williams/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- DISPOSABLE-PAPER-PANS -- For
years commercial bakers have baked their pies and tarts in
disposable paper pans. Now these paper pans are becoming more
available to home bakers. Muffins bake nicely in paper when the
temperature was reduced. (Marty Katz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Aug. 1, 2000 -- MAKING-MAYONNAISE -- Though
most of America still depends on the stiff, oily cream in jars, to
serious cooks making mayonnaise has become as fundamental as
whisking together vinaigrette. As eggs have grown safer in recent
years, many home cooks have been emboldened to make it a part of
their regular repertory. Preparing mayonnaise with eggs and some
lemon. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
