<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0194 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GOP-RDP-2NDLD-WRITETH     08-02 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-RDP-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN LEADS SHOW OF SUPPORT FOR BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to add 3 grafs at end of 1st take, re the Fords, Barbara Bush
and satellite remarks by George W. Bush.)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT 22 through 36 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Sen. John McCain shed his rebellious image to
play the admiring party stalwart at the Republican National
Convention Tuesday night, commending Gov. George W. Bush to
independents and Democrats and _ addressing one of the governor's
most pronounced vulnerabilities _ saying he would ably defend the
nation's interests abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support him,'' McCain said in his prepared remarks, trying
to erase tensions from a primary battle that had been so raw that
McCain waited two months to reluctantly endorse Bush. ``I am
grateful to him. And I am proud of him.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's speech anchored an evening whose overarching objective
was to assemble several faces, old and new, to assure the national
viewing audience that Bush could be trusted on the international
stage despite his failure to serve in Vietnam and the fact that, by
his own admission, his foreign policy experience does not stretch
beyond Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the chorus in the other high-profile speech was
Condoleezza Rice, Bush's chief international affairs adviser who,
as an African American, also underscores Bush's pledge to put
minorities in consequential roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The George W. Bush I know is a man of uncommonly good
judgment,'' Rice, a national security council official in former
President Bush's administration, said in her prepared remarks. ``He
is focused and consistent. He believes that we Americans are at our
best when we exercise power without fanfare or arrogance. He speaks
plainly and with a positive spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   The speeches were testimonials to the personal ability McCain,
Rice and the other speakers perceived in Bush, but offered little
on specific policies or countries.
</P>
<P>
   Besides trying to shore up Bush's record, a cavalcade of
speakers reminded the public of Republican presidents like Ronald
Reagan and George Bush who were known for eliciting respect for
America abroad and for their emphasis on national security.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf, commander of allied forces in
the Persian Gulf war, appeared via satellite from a battleship,
reminding the convention that ``10 years ago tomorrow, Iraq invaded
Kuwait.'' He asked: ``Wouldn't it be great for our armed forces,
and for America, if we could have another commander in chief named
George Bush?''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole, the Republican nominee four years ago who was wounded
in World War II, asked the audience to ``join me in saluting the
greatest generation of veterans and every generation of our armed
services.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, who had a starring role at the convention in
1996 when she spoke reverentially of her husband, said that
``timeless values form our first line of defense.'' Bush, she said,
``will put an end to the smash-mouth politics of recent years and
to the name-calling that tarnishes our trust and alienates so many
real people whose real problems can never be solved in a focus
group or soothed by a spin doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   To drive home the theme of military might, there was a video
tribute to World War II veterans and a musical medley of military
service anthems.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's popularity afforded him the freedom to play to a broader
audience outside the hall by giving a speaking slot (albeit not in
prime time) to an openly gay congressman, Rep. Jim Kolbe of
Arizona, who spoke about international trade.
</P>
<P>
   During his remarks, several members of the Texas delegation
protested by taking off their cowboy hats and bowing their heads in
prayer. Most of the delegates were respectful but offered Kolbe
only weak applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not all the way there with our party,'' Kolbe, speaking
of his party's policy toward homosexuals, said on ``Political
Points,'' the Webcast of The New York Times and ABC News. ``The
Democratic Party isn't all the way there yet either in terms of its
treatment of minorities and other groups.''
</P>
<P>
   So concerted was the outreach to Democrats from the stage here
that the convention played a videotape featuring the words of
Franklin Delano Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the gauzy, smiling images of moderation from the stage,
there were stirrings of resentment among some conservatives who
voiced concerns that the convention did not truly reflect their
views. At a crowded Christian Coalition rally at a downtown hotel,
delegates seemed thrilled to hear some of the conservative, red
meat rhetoric missing from the convention hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is a convention of sweetness and light,'' Pat
Robertson, the coalition's founder, declared to the crowd. ``Nobody
wants to rock the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike St. Clair, a delegate from Ankeny, Iowa, complained that
the party was not putting forth enough contrast with the Democrats.
``There must be some contrast, otherwise it is hard for people to
become passionate,'' he said. ``You have to be able to see the
differences between the parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before 9 p.m., delegates rose in applause to a tableau
representing every living Republican president: Gerald Ford and his
wife, Betty, and Nancy Reagan joined former President and Mrs.
Barbara Bush in the prime viewing seats overlooking the convention.
Mrs. Dole also sat with them.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the video tributes to Ford, the audience broke
out in applause at the mention of Mrs. Ford's hospitalization for
breast cancer _ and then, across the convention hall, rose to their
feets. Mr. and Mrs. Ford waved back in thanks.
</P>
<P>
   Then one of the most popular figures in Republican politics,
Barbara Bush, appeared unnannounced and greeted the crowd: ``I hope
that I am the first person to welcome you to Philadelphia: the city
of motherly love.''
</P>
<P>
   She then introduced her son, who appeared before the convention
by a satellite hookup for the second night in a row. This time, the
location was Gettysburg, Pa., where Abraham Lincoln delivered a
famous speech and where general-turned-president Dwight Eisenhower
once lived. Governor Bush praised McCain, saying, ``His straight
talk and strong convictions are admired across America.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the evening was clearly dominated by McCain. The Bush
campaign's decision to give a vanquished rival such a prominent
role on the second night of the convention marked a striking
departure from the last several Republican conventions. At the
convention four years ago, the prized Tuesday night slot was given
to then Rep. Susan Molinari, who had been one of Dole's most loyal
backers.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign's decision to give McCain such a high profile
underscored not only that McCain has emerged as an influential
force in his party but also that Bush is so popular among
Republicans that he does not have to worry that McCain would draw
too much attention.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, McCain clearly recognized that there was no
political upside to stirring up trouble for the Texas governor and
that he could score points by playing the loyal trooper.
Strikingly, he was so determined to fall in line behind Bush that
he did not even raise his signature issue of campaign finance
reform, something he relentlessly brings up every chance he gets.
He even played down his achievement of winning the New Hampshire
and Michigan primaries, calling himself ``a distant runner-up.''
</P>
<P>
   But his comments Tuesday night led some of McCain's most ardent
backers to privately grouse that he was being too adulatory, and
abandoning his greatest attribute _ his maverick nature.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who drew a potent following from independents and
Democrats during the primaries, implored his followers to rally
behind Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say to all Americans, Republican, Democrat or independent,''
he asserted, ``if you believe America deserves leaders with a
purpose more ennobling than expediency and opportunism, then vote
for Governor Bush. If you believe patriotism is more than a
soundbite and public service should be more than a photo-op, then
vote for Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Alan K. Simpson of Wyoming said McCain knew it was
not in his interest to be a political menace at the convention.
``He has a great future with the party,'' Simpson said. ``You never
want to be known as a poor loser. He wants to be loved like all of
us. He wants to be a player.''
</P>
<P>
   While the speakers touched on a panoply of foreign-policy
issues, the matters left unaddressed were telling. For example,
despite Schwarzkopf's praise of former President Bush for leading
the coalition to victory in the Persian Gulf, American warplanes
are still bombing Iraq and President Saddam Hussein is as firmly
entrenched as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Rice said that Governor Bush would never allow the United States
to be blackmailed by outlaw states, and urged swift construction of
a national missile defense to safeguard against missile strikes.
But she laid out no new plan to defend against stateless terrorists
who might use the much cheaper and equally deadly alternative of a
truck bomb attack.
</P>
<P>
   In her speech, Rice depicted Governor Bush as a bilingual
internationalist, meeting with leaders from Mexico, Russia and
South Africa. But, in fact, many of the meetings were little more
than handshakes and hellos. President Thabo Mleki of South Africa
called his visit to the governor's mansion in May a ``courtesy
call.''
</P>
<P>
   While in Washington in April, Bush met briefly in his hotel with
Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov to discuss Chechnya and the
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty. Beforehand, Bush told reporters he
was looking forward to meeting ``Iggy.''
</P>
<P>
   In a notable contrast to the play for moderates from the hall,
Pat Robertson, at the Christian Coalition gathering earlier in the
day, delivered a rousing speech about the stakes in this election
for religious conservatives, focusing on the Supreme Court. ``Five
people can decide the destiny of unborn children,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks as if two or three of those unelected officials are
getting ready to retire or go on up to that great court in the sky.
The next president is going to have the ability to select two or
three judges on the Supreme Court,'' he added, to cheers and
applause. ``We need to have the election of a man who will appoint
righteous judges to the court of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I frankly agree with Ronald Reagan. I think we
should do away with the federal Department of Education.'' This, of
course, put him distinctly at odds with Bush, who fought hard
against that position in the platform process _ and prevailed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
