<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0198 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-1STLEDE-CVN-GOPMAIN-H     08-02 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1STLEDE-CVN-GOPMAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    1ST LEDE: COMPLETELY NEW STORY; KILL FIRST VERSION PLS
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    A salute by McCain at GOP event
 &HT;    Backs Bush on military issue
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By BENNETT ROTH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Seeking to underscore their commitment to
military might, Republicans Tuesday turned to Sen. John McCain, the
Vietnam War hero who waged a ferocious primary battle against
George W. Bush earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's speech capped an evening devoted to projecting the
notion that Bush, who has been criticized for his limited foreign
policy experience, would restore the nation's military strength and
respect around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Although he bitterly criticized Bush during the primary
campaign, McCain lavished praise on the Texas governor during the
prime time speech. The Arizona senator did not mention the
signature issue of his failed presidential bid, curbing the
influence of money in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking more to the Republican faithful than the independent
voters who helped propel his campaign, McCain pledged to be the
loyal party soldier, noting that his grandfather had commanded
President Bush in the Pacific during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it is my turn to serve under the son of my grandfather's
brave subordinate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans had hoped to run a glitch-free convention,
they encountered several obstacles on their second day.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours before delegates were to begin arriving at the
convention center, demonstrations turned violent, as protesters
blocked traffic, slashed police tires and dumped orange paint on
police vehicles in downtown Philadelphia. More than 200 people were
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Although the clashes occurred several miles from the First Union
Center, the traffic tie-ups hindered many delegates' efforts to get
from their downtown hotels to the arena in south Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the convention hall, the tensions between conservatives
and moderates over social issues _ largely hidden from public view
this year _ surfaced again during a speech by Rep. Jim Kolbe,
R-Ariz., the only openly gay GOP member of the House.
</P>
<P>
   Disturbed by the prominent role given a man whose sexual
orientation they disapprove of, members of the Texas delegation
discussed walking out on Kolbe. Instead, they decided to pray
silently during his speech.
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe made no references to his personal life in the speech,
which mostly praised Bush's support of free trade.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bush, who spoke at rallies in West Virginia and
Harrisburg, Pa., briefly broke his vow to run a positive campaign
as he responded to several days of criticism from President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is so desperate to have his legacy intact by getting Al
Gore elected, he'll say anything, just like Al Gore,'' Bush told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview, former President Bush also threatened
to drop his self-imposed silence and join in GOP criticism of
Clinton if he continues taunting the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's convention organizers, knowing he and
vice-presidential choice, Dick Cheney, never personally saw combat,
provided a lineup of decorated war heroes to stress GOP support for
improving military readiness and developing a missile defense
system.
</P>
<P>
   In a reminder of the military high point of President Bush's
administration, the delegates heard from retired Gen. Norman
Schwarzkopf, who commanded allied forces during the Persian Gulf
War. Schwarzkopf's criticism of the Clinton administration's
defense policies were beamed to the convention hall by satellite
from the deck of the USS New Jersey, which was docked across the
Delaware River.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarzkopf decried the shrinking of the three branches of the
military and the fall-off in service enlistments since President
Bush left office. ``Wouldn't it be great for our armed forces and
for America if we could have another commander in chief named
George Bush with Dick Cheney on his team?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In another nod to the past, former Sen. Bob Dole, who was
wounded in World War II and who waged an unsuccessful presidential
bid against Clinton four years ago, offered a tribute to his aging
generation of soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a swipe at the man who beat him in 1996, Dole told
delegates, ``We look to Governor Bush and Secretary Cheney to raise
our sights and to restore honor and civility to our public life.''
</P>
<P>
   The delegates also heard from Dole's wife, Elizabeth Dole, who
made an unsuccessful primary bid for the White House last year. She
said Bush ``would put an end to smash-mouth politics of recent
years and to the name-calling that tarnishes our trust and
alienates so many real people whose real problems can never be
solved in a focus group or soothed by a spin-doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also addressed the delegates by satellite from Gettysburg,
where he was staying at the retirement home of former President
Eisenhower. ``Morale in the military is dangerously low,'' he said.
``The men and women in uniform need better pay and better
training.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention's Tuesday night session also showcased one of the
governor's top foreign policy experts, Condoleezza Rice, a former
Stanford University provost. She told the delegates that ``George
W. Bush will never allow America to be blackmailed.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to deflect questions about Bush's readiness to deal with
world leaders, Rice said she has witnessed him explaining issues to
Mexico's leaders, Russia's foreign minister and South Africa's
president.
</P>
<P>
   She told delegates that her father became a Republican in
Alabama in 1952 because Democrats in his native Alabama would not
register him to vote because he was black.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to mute criticism of Bush's environmental record in
Texas, Republicans awarded a prime speaking spot to Theodore
Roosevelt IV, an environmentalist and great-grandson of former
President Theodore Roosevelt, who helped create the national park
system.
</P>
<P>
   However, Roosevelt never mentioned Bush's name or his Texas
record, instead noting that other Republicans _ including former
President Richard Nixon and New York Gov. George Pataki _ had
championed environmental causes.
</P>
<P>
   Although Republicans devoted a portion of the evening to
addressing international affairs, polls show that the issue does
not move many voters.
</P>
<P>
   A Voter.com Battleground 2000 tracking poll released Tuesday
found that 2 percent of likely voters rank foreign affairs as the
most important issue on the next president's agenda. The
respondents put a higher priority on improving education, restoring
moral values and expanding health care.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Goeas, a Republican pollster who co-directs the poll, said
that while voters do not view foreign policy as their most
important priority they become concerned when presidents cannot
deal with their domestic needs because they distracted by
international problems.
</P>
<P>
   The poll found Bush leading Gore, 47-41, among likely voters, a
slight tightening of the race from six weeks ago when the vice
president trailed Bush by 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gore mulled his vice-presidential pick as he
vacationed in North Carolina, and Democrats kept a steady drumbeat
of criticism toward the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   At news conference in Philadelphia, Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee of
Houston joined several other politicians criticizing Bush's record
on race relations and his ties to the firearms industry.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee disputed Republican claims that their session Monday
night, filled with a parade of minority speakers, was an
improvement on their past conventions. ``It may be progress in the
Republican Party, but it is not progress in America,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
