<SLUG> BC-LA-SELL-LADN </SLUG>
 
CATALOG GIVES MEDIA SLICK LOOK AT L.A. &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALEXA HAUSSLER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Democratic National Convention organizers have
borrowed a page from the TV show ``Spin City'' in selling what a
really great place Los Angeles is to the media army due in town for
the big event. Really.
</P>
<P>
   Glossing over smog, scandal and stalled traffic, the 114-page,
glossy book titled ``Capital City of the 21st Century'' provides
glowing anecdotes and factoids _ plus listings of restaurants and
attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Paid for with corporate and city donations, the book was sent by
the convention's host committee to all 15,000 members of the media
who are expected to cover the Aug. 14-17 convention at Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``No longer will members of the media be treated to free bottles
of Visine, as they were at the 1960 Democratic National Convention
because of poor air quality,'' the guide explains. ``Today,
visitors to Los Angeles will be treated to breathtaking views
through the clearest air in decades.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, but hardly crystal clear as the city vies with
Houston for the trophy for the nation's dirtiest air.
</P>
<P>
   The booklet offers members of the media a guide to everything
including where to eat sushi in Hollywood (Yamashiro on North
Sycamore Avenue) and pastrami in Northridge (Brent's Deli on
Parthenia Street).
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Brent's is listed on (italics) Panthenia (italics
off). But if members of the national media make it all the way to
the North Valley for a deli sandwich, they can probably get correct
directions to Brent's.
</P>
<P>
   The guide also lists attractions from the Watts Tower to the
Getty Museum to CBS' Television City.
</P>
<P>
   That might seem like a long drive for journalists. Not to worry,
the guide says: The city has ``highly effective, well-designed and
integrated transportation networks that enable Angelenos to move
smoothly through the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoothly, if they stay away from gridlocked streets and freeways
and stick to the subway, which is often ridiculed as the ``Subway
to Nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Los Angeles Host Committee said the guide _
which dozens of public relations experts worked on for 10 months _
is designed to take advantage of the city's ``15 minutes in the
national spotlight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this is about telling the story of Los Angeles to the
national media,'' said Ben Austin, spokesman for the Los Angeles
host committee.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its rosy tone, the book isn't all safe streets and clean
air. It does refer _ briefly and vaguely _ to the Rampart police
corruption scandal and the Los Angeles Unified School District's
bungled attempt to build the nation's costliest school, the Belmont
Learning Center, on a toxic site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Los Angeles Police Department has experienced tough
situations in recent years but remains one of our nation's most
disciplined, effective, and respected law enforcement
organizations,'' the book boasts.
</P>
<P>
   It never actually mentions the words Rampart Division _ the LAPD
station-house name that has come to represent the department's
biggest scandal and which has city officials trying to thwart a
department takeover by the U.S. Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of printing the book exceeded $50,000, which was
donated by the city Department of Water and Power, host committee
officials said. Other funds come from corporations whose logos are
on the front cover.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of volunteers also helped assemble, write and mail the
book to the thousands of media representatives expected to come to
Los Angeles in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Planners admit that they wanted to put the most positive spin
possible on the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people know about Los Angeles, but some people know about
Los Angeles for the wrong reasons, because of riots and natural
disasters and a severe economic recession,'' Austin said.
</P>
<P>
   The committee wanted to offer a different story, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mere fact that we are hosting this convention, that we
were chosen and that we were ready to step into the national
spotlight says so much about how far our community has come in such
a short time,'' Austin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the story that we are looking to tell the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
