<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-SURF-LADN </SLUG>
 
SURF IS SWELL, RIDERS SAY &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON KANDEL 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ For Roger Kelly, work wasn't going to get in
the way of an opportunity to catch a ride on perhaps the best surf
of the summer at Surfrider Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing a little hooky right now,'' said the 51-year-old
financial adviser for American Express as he waxed his board
Tuesday. ``I'm taking advantage of the big day. This is one of the
biggest days of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   He was among hundreds of surfers who took the day off from work
to catch a wave, as high surf and unusually high tides from a
southern Pacific storm caused relatively minor damage and
positively major excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Weather officials recorded a high tide of 4.8 feet at 11:36 a.m.
Tuesday and a 6.6-foot high tide was expected to hit by 11 p.m.
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The high tides and big waves were triggered by a storm in the
South Pacific that sent a surge toward Los Angeles, and were
expected to continue through Thursday, said Bruce Rockwell, a
meteorologist with the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest so far this summer,'' Rockwell said. ``I
don't recommend any novice swimmer going anywhere near the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Lifeguards in Malibu reported 14-foot waves, with some licking
coastal homes.
</P>
<P>
   The storm surge damaged two houses in the exclusive Malibu
Colony, prompting fire officials to evacuate the affected homes,
move furniture and shut off utilities late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, with the firefighters gone, but on standby,
residents tallied their losses. One family lost a wood deck to the
ocean, another lost part of a deck, said fire Inspector Ed Martinez
of the Los Angeles County Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are problems with high tides again, we do have
sandbags available,'' Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides sending big breakers crashing on the shore, high surf
and riptides kept lifeguards on alert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of near misses today, but we kept everybody
intact, no injuries,'' said county lifeguard Norton Wisdom, 53, who
was stationed at Surfrider Beach this week. ``We have a lot of
novice and intermediate surfers out there. This is the biggest surf
it's been in five years. There's so many people out there that
sometimes there's arguments. Most are verbal.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most daring rescues Monday involved a boy who became
trapped in his life jacket and was forced underwater while he and
his father were kayaking in the area. No one was injured.
</P>
<P>
   The high surf, coupled with water temperatures in the 60s and
air temperatures in the 70s, also attracted unusually high numbers
of people to Malibu on Tuesday. At any one time, more than 100
surfers could be seen maneuvering in for a ride on a wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was real crowded,'' said Internet company owner and Malibu
native Andy DangVu, 28, sitting on the beach near his board with a
towel over his head, seeking refuge from the sun. ``There are a lot
of kooks out there coming out of the woodwork.''
</P>
<P>
   The sun glistened off glassy waves Tuesday morning as the high
tide swept the water closer to the shore. Some saw the high tide as
a blessing, others a curse.
</P>
<P>
   After a three-hour dip in the ocean, lifetime surfer and former
lifeguard John Baker, 53, was impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is phenomenal,'' he said. ``Each wave looks like it could
be on the cover of a magazine. It's a consistent swell, and
sometimes you manage to get a wave to yourself. I had about three
or four really good rides to myself today.''
</P>
<P>
   DangVu, on the other hand, decided to wait out the high tide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high tides are pushing the waves a little too far out,''
he said. ``The waves are too mushy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
