r p BC-THIRD-KAN &LR;      08-02 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THIRD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KLINE WINS NOMINATION IN THREE-WAY GOP RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLINGER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ State Rep. Phill
Kline defeated two Republican rivals Tuesday to claim the party's
nomination in Kansas' 3rd Congressional District and the right to
take on incumbent Democrat Dennis Moore this fall.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a hard-fought primary campaign, voters were giving the
conservative state lawmaker from Shawnee, Kan., 50 percent of the
vote, compared to 38 percent for Overland Park, Kan., City Council
member Greg Musil and 12 percent for Olathe physician Gary Morsch.
</P>
<P>
   Those results represented 81 percent of the precincts reporting.
</P>
<P>
   The Kline-Moore matchup will be one of a handful of
congressional races watched by party leaders and political
observers around the nation. With only a five-vote margin for
Republicans in the U.S. House, close races will be assigned even
greater importance this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Phill and congratulated him on a good race and told
him I'm looking forward to a good campaign,'' Moore said Tuesday
night. ``I think it's going to be a fun campaign. There's going to
be a clear contrast between Phill Kline and myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Kline won Wyandotte and Miami counties decisively and received
more votes than Musil in Douglas County. In vote-rich Johnson
County, Kline garnered 48.9 percent of the vote, compared to 39
percent for Musil and 12 percent for Morsch.
</P>
<P>
   Kline's campaign was built on three objectives _ raising enough
money to stay competitive with Musil, building a large grass-roots
organization and staying focused on his message of tax relief and
local control of education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to meet our goals and carry out our strategy,''
said John Kerr, Kline's campaign manager. ``We felt that if we did
that, we'd win.''
</P>
<P>
   Kline began the race with a large advantage in voter
recognition. Because of that, he was tabbed early as the
front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   He never relinquished that position.
</P>
<P>
   The Musil and Morsch camps conceded that Kline began the
campaign as the best-known candidate. He also started with a huge
base of support among the party's conservative wing.
</P>
<P>
   He was endorsed by Kansans for Life, an anti-abortion group, and
the Kansas Republican Assembly, the party's conservative faction.
But Kerr said the campaign also reached out to moderates who liked
Kline's history of backing tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Musil's strategy was to appeal to social moderates with the
evolution issue. In weeks of television ads, Musil called the state
Board of Education's decision on science standards last year an
``embarrassment to Kansas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were behind,'' said David Schlosser, Musil's
campaign manager. ``We had to make up the difference and get
ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign had to develop a message that would motivate people
to go to the polls and give Musil an identity with voters that was
different from Kline's and Morsch's. It was determined early in the
campaign that evolution and the Shawnee Mission School District's
financial problems were issues that Musil could exploit.
</P>
<P>
   The Overland Park councilman raised more money than the two
other candidates but not the $650,000 he had hoped. In the closing
days of the drive, Musil lent his campaign $50,000. The last two
weeks of the campaign, he spent about $100,000 to get his
pro-evolution message on Kansas City television stations.
</P>
<P>
   Schlosser said evolution was considered a better issue than
taxes, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (the tax issue) meets Phill on his own ground,''
Schlosser said. ``That wasn't the best territory to wage the
battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Geographically, Musil's campaign had hoped to do well in older
areas of Johnson County, especially in the far northeast. Kline's
campaign thought he would be strongest in newly developing areas of
Johnson County, such as southern Overland Park, Leawood, Olathe,
Shawnee and Lenexa.
</P>
<P>
   While Musil attacked his main rival, Kline took a ``rose
garden'' approach to the campaign. He rarely criticized his
opponents in ads and let surrogates such as Kansans for Life attack
Morsch. Only in debates and direct mail did he exchange political
jabs with the two others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to hold our cards close to the vest and run a
positive campaign,'' Kerr said. ``Greg ran a good hard campaign,
but he had a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Morsch was the last candidate to get in the race. As an abortion
opponent, it was assumed that the Olathe, Kan., doctor would take
away support from Kline, especially in Olathe.
</P>
<P>
   One of the big questions of the campaign was not whether Morsch
would win but which of the two other candidates he would hurt more.
</P>
<P>
   Spending about $200,000, less than the other two, Morsch wasn't
able to go on television. Consequently, radio and efforts by about
1,000 volunteers were used to communicate with voters.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers predicted last week that Morsch would get
about 15 percent of the vote and draw equally from Musil and Kline.
During the campaign, he portrayed himself as a nonpolitician who
would leave office after six years.
</P>
<P>
   He became the alternative candidate for people who thought Kline
was too conservative and Musil too liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout was considered a key element. The common wisdom had
Kline benefiting from a small turnout and Musil doing well if the
turnout was large.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
