r p BC-EDBOARD-KAN &LR;      08-02 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDBOARD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCUMBENT LOSES PRIMARY IN STATE BOARD RACE WITH EVOLUTION FOCUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE BEEM  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Moderates won a key
battle Tuesday and appeared to be winning a statewide war for
control of the Kansas Board of Education.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Linda Holloway, a conservative Republican who led the board last
year when it voted to downplay evolution in the state's science
education standards, lost by a large margin to moderate Sue Gamble
in the GOP primary for the board's 2nd District.
</P>
<P>
   With 97 percent of precincts reporting, Gamble had 24,133 votes
to Holloway's 15,921.
</P>
<P>
   In other races across the state, the conservative incumbent in
Wichita lost to her moderate challenger, and in Salina the moderate
candidate was leading the conservative. The conservative state
board member from Arkansas City, however, was soundly defeating his
moderate opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The high-profile 2nd District race symbolized the battle between
Kansas conservatives and moderates for control of the state
Republican party and the education board, which oversees the
state's 304 school districts.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble, 58, a real estate agent and veteran member of the
Shawnee Mission school board, said her door-to-door campaigning
made the difference in the campaign. When parents learned the
issues at stake, they turned out to vote, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a victory for parents and children and their
education, and I could not be happier,'' Gamble said Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway, 50, a former teacher, said she had been portrayed as
an extremist since the vote on evolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, propaganda still works,'' she said. ``The
campaign against me has been going on for over a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamble, who like Holloway is a Shawnee resident, faces a
challenge in the November general election from Democrat Ron
Patton, a Presbyterian minister from Fairway. The 2nd District
covers eastern and northern Johnson County.
</P>
<P>
   All the Republicans will face Democratic opposition in November,
although in Kansas in recent years, Democrats have made few inroads
into state offices.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the 10 seats on the state board are up for election this
year. Three of those seats are held by conservative Republicans,
one is held by a Democrat and one is open. The five other seats
come up for election in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The Holloway-Gamble race was closely watched by national groups.
It also was the most expensive in state board history, with
Holloway raising about $90,000 and Gamble raising close to $36,000.
Four years ago, in her first bid for the state board, Holloway
raised $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The evolution issue proved a powerful pull. Holloway was
chairwoman of the board in August 1999 when it approved new science
standards that delete references to the age of the Earth, the big
bang theory and some aspects of evolutionary theory. The standards
are important because they help determine what Kansas students will
be tested on.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after that decision, science groups and Kansas
moderates promised to work to unseat Holloway and other
conservative incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   The board's vote on evolution _ the theory that living things
share common ancestors but have changed over time _ gained
international attention, with journalists from Japan and several
European countries journeying to Kansas to cover the commotion.
</P>
<P>
   The vote also reopened a national debate over science and
religion. A set of standards the board rejected, written by a
27-member committee of Kansas science teachers, would have included
evolution as a cornerstone of science.
</P>
<P>
   The six board members who voted to downplay evolution in the
standards cited, in part, their hesitancy to include information
that would go against some students' religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   The current board is split ideologically. Generally, the two
camps are divided between moderates, who support present public
educational policies stressing accountability, and conservatives,
who think that those methods have failed and that Kansas needs a
change of course toward more choice and competition in education.
</P>
<P>
   But moderate Harold Voth of Haven, Kan., whose seat is up in two
years, has voted with the five conservatives, most notably on the
science standards.
</P>
<P>
   The triumph of Gamble and the other moderate challengers could
mean Kansas moderates finally have achieved some sort of
grass-roots organization, said University of Kansas political
scientist Burdett Loomis. That's always been a strength of
conservatives, who use their cause as a rallying point.
</P>
<P>
   This time it was the moderates' turn, and they proved they can
work in concert, Loomis said.
</P>
<P>
   The moderates' victory also confirms what political pundits have
said for years _ that conservatives fare better when the issues are
vague and the races are low profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the conservatives want attention, or they want
attention only on their terms,'' Loomis said. ``The higher the
profile, the more problems they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Val De Fever, a moderate state board member from Independence,
Kan., credited the moderates' win to their campaigning. More
national and state groups weighed in on the state board races than
ever before, which helped drive home how important the elections
are, De Fever said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Kansas Citizens for Science, a pro-evolution group
formed after the board's vote, campaigned for moderate candidates.
In mid-July, the liberal People for the American Way Foundation
sponsored a dramatization of the famous 1925 Scopes ``monkey''
trial to draw attention to the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've done a lot of the right things,'' De Fever
said of the moderates.
</P>
<P>
   Kris Van Meteren, executive director of the conservative Kansas
Republican Assembly, thinks money was the deciding factor. Although
Holloway raised far more than her challenger, the other
conservatives came up short compared with their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a testament to the fact that, yeah, you can buy an
election,'' Van Meteren said.
</P>
<P>
   But the fight isn't over by a long shot, promised conservatives.
This is an ongoing battle, and the conservatives made inroads by
even suggesting that evolution be optional in school, said John
Morris, president of the Institute for Creation Research in San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a resentment of the education elite. I think that's an
undercurrent that's undersold,'' Morris said. ``The creation
message is getting out better than ever. It will never go back to
the way it was, when people go back to doing what the education
elite say. Never again.''
</P>
<P>
   In the other races Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   - In the 6th District, with 74 percent of precincts reporting,
moderate Republican Bruce Wyatt, an attorney from Salina, was
beating conservative Brad Angell, a former teacher from Junction
City. The winner will face Eloise Lynch, a former state legislator
from Salina, in November.
</P>
<P>
   The race had no incumbent because conservative Scott Hill, who
held the seat, moved from Abilene to Montana earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   - With all precincts reporting, Mary Douglass Brown of Wichita,
the conservative incumbent from the 8th District, lost to moderate
Carol Rupe of Wichita. Brown is a former teacher, and Rupe is a
former Wichita school board member. The winner will face Democrat
Dick Williams of Wichita, a retired college instructor.
</P>
<P>
   - Incumbent conservative Steve Abrams, a veterinarian from
Arkansas City, was beating Roger Rankin of Longton, a former
schools superintendent. The winner will face Democrat Wayne Holt, a
former school administrator from Haysville.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
