<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEVINE GOES ON DISABLED LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Right-handed reliever Al Levine was placed on
the 15-day disabled list Tuesday because of an inflamed right
elbow. Matt Wise, a product of Cal State Fullerton, was called up
from Triple-A Edmonton and will join the team today.
</P>
<P>
   Levine is 2-4 with a 3.50 ERA in 41 games. His 722/3 innings is
the most by any Angels reliever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been something he's been managing most of the year,''
manager Mike Scioscia said of Levine. ``He got past the point of a
comfort level. He's never refused to take the ball. We just want to
make sure we get this knocked out. He's been too big to our
bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels decided to call up Wise instead of Ramon Ortiz
because Wise is better-suited to pitch out of the bullpen. However,
Wise has started all season for Edmonton. In 19 starts he is 9-6
with a 3.69 ERA, including two complete games and one shutout.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Ramon and his history of shoulder trouble in spring
training, we don't want to take him out of his routine,'' Scioscia
said. ``Wise has the ability to pitch out of the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Wise was part of a starting rotation at Double-A Erie early last
season that included Brian Cooper, Seth Etherton and Ortiz.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk about the young pitchers in the organization, and
Matt Wise's name is up there with any of them,'' Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   GLAD IT'S AUGUST: Other than his trip to Atlanta for the
All-Star Game, July was a month third baseman Troy Glaus probably
would like to forget.
</P>
<P>
   His power numbers _ eight homers and 15 RBI _ were fine, but he
had only 19 hits and batted .194 in the month. So, on the first day
of August, Scioscia gave Glaus the day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to play,'' Scioscia said. ``Sure, he was a little
(ticked) off. He looked at me cross-eyed. But it's important to
give him a breather.''
</P>
<P>
   As Scioscia explained his reasoning for the off-day, Darin
Erstad walked by and asked who Scioscia was talking about. When
told it was Glaus, Erstad laughed and said: ``You benched him?''
Scioscia was quick to reply: ``No, it's a day off. It's not a
benching.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said he will start giving his regular players a little
more rest this month to keep them fresh for September.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK JAUNT: After today's game, the Angels will go on a brief
road trip for three games in Cleveland. They will face ex-Angel
Chuck Finley on Saturday. On May 31, Finley and the Indians beat
the Angels 7-3 in Cleveland. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 0043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
