<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES TOP ROYALS, 5-4 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout; adds byline)   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dwight Gooden's revival continued on Tuesday night,
which meant that one of the most surprising developments of a long
season continued for the New York Yankees. Gooden pitched seven
competent innings for one of the best teams in baseball and made it
difficult to fathom how he was unemployed before George
Steinbrenner offered him one more chance.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Gooden has devoured the chance, has helped stabilize
the Yankees and has made them look shrewd for believing in him
again. While Gooden was impeccable on Tuesday night at Yankee
Stadium, the bullpen was not, so Gooden lost his chance for a
victory when Mike Stanton frittered away a two-run bulge in the
eighth and the Kansas City Royals rallied to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   But Scott Brosius saved Stanton by hammering a homer off Ricky
Bottalico to lead off the bottom of the eighth and vault the
Yankees to a dramatic 5-4 victory. Since Brosius had stranded six
runners in his first three at-bats and had not homered in 14 games,
he tossed the bat aside, raised his arms in the air like Rocky
Balboa and scampered around the bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those times where you could walk away with a
smile after struggling a bit,'' Brosius said.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden could definitely smile after continuing to do something
that was supposed to be a surprise, and is now looking more and
more like a routine. He had a sturdy fastball, precise control and
enormous confidence, allowing one earned run and four hits in his
longest outing of the season. He gave Manager Joe Torre enough
evidence to prove that the 35-year-old Gooden should stay in the
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Torre admitted that he never expected Gooden to be in a pivotal
position. But Gooden, who signed a minor league contract in June,
is 3-0 with a 1.86 earned run average for the Yankees after adding
a changeup and being more aggressive. It will be difficult for
Torre to remove him from the rotation, even if David Cone is
excellent in his next start.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't top what he did tonight,'' Torre said about Gooden.
``It's fun for me to watch. I know he has to be thrilled about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   After abominable stints with the Houston Astros and Tampa Bay
Devil Rays and a near retirement, Gooden thought about what he had
accomplished and said, ``It might sound crazy, but I'm more relaxed
now.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees trailing by 2-1 in the seventh, Chuck Knoblauch
walked and stole second, and Royals starter Dan Reichert followed
by walking Derek Jeter. After the left-hander Tim Byrdak struck out
Paul O'Neill, Bernie Williams smashed a two-run double to left.
David Justice followed with a double to make it 4-2, a refreshing
change for the Yankees, who had stranded two in the fifth and three
in the sixth after Brosius whiffed.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden was six outs from his fourth victory with the Yankees and
he had thrown only 79 pitches, but Torre turned to Stanton in the
eighth. A one-out single, a walk and Johnny Damon's booming double
off the fence in right-center field, which was a few feet from
being a three-run homer, tied the score, 4-4. The Royals later
loaded the bases against Jeff Nelson, but Nelson fanned Joe Randa
and pumped his fist as he returned to the dugout. All of the
Yankees were celebrating a few moments later when Brosius belted
Bottalico's 1-0 fastball over the left-field fence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
