<HEADER>
A0213 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-     08-02 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLANDSWORTH HAS MIXED FEELINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Even though outfielder Todd Hollandsworth's last
months of his Dodgers career weren't ideal _ his role was unsettled
and his performance wasn't up to snuff _ he said he had mixed
feelings about Monday's trade that sent him and a pair of
minor-leaguers to Colorado for center fielder Tom Goodwin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that keeps coming into my mind is it's a fresh
start,'' Hollandsworth said Tuesday from his Chicago hotel room.
``I had tears in my eyes when I left yesterday. I've been in a
Dodgers uniform since I was 18. It was different and it was
shocking. I didn't think anything would happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I was sitting on the plane going into Chicago (Monday), I
thought it was refreshing and a shot in my arm. I have a mixed
approach. They're a great group of guys (in Los Angeles) and they
have a chance to be in the playoffs, and I'm grateful I was able to
be a part of it for four months.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth, like Goodwin, joined his new team Tuesday. And
Hollandsworth had an immediate impact as his bases-loaded single in
the eighth inning gave the Rockies a 2-1 win at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   A free agent after the season, Hollandsworth, 27, is excited
about the opportunity to play for the Rockies, and at Coors Field,
and he's already spoken with Colorado general manager Dan O'Dowd
about his future. While the discussions were preliminary and a
contract extension wasn't the topic, Hollandsworth's future in
Colorado was a big part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They reiterated with me that this thing was not just trying to
reduce salary (by moving Goodwin), and that I was a part of their
plans,'' Hollandsworth said. ``I said I wouldn't mind being here in
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth never said publicly he was unhappy in Los Angeles,
but everyone agreed a change of scenery was for the best. And the
Dodgers realized their chance to re-sign him after the season was a
shade better than nil. Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone tried
to deal him before the 1999 season and also was working on deals
this season before Devon White was injured May 2 diving for a ball
in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth, the 1996 National League Rookie of the Year,
didn't perform up to expectations, partly because the Dodgers' lack
of a leadoff hitter forced him into that role when he's better
elsewhere in the order. He batted .234 with eight homers and 24 RBI
with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My role was different all the time, and as a player,
uniformity is what you seek,'' Hollandsworth said. ``At times, I
struggled with my role. But I have a lot of good memories, a lot of
good friends from my time there.''
</P>
<P>
   DEVO'S ROLE: Dodgers manager Davey Johnson met with White for
about 25 minutes prior to the doubleheader to discuss what White's
role will be now that Goodwin is with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I was going to give (Goodwin) the opportunity to
play predominantly center field and that I needed Devo, who's a guy
that I felt like could play a corner,'' Johnson said. ``I know he
could hit in the middle of a lineup for (Gary) Sheffield or (Shawn)
Green when they weren't in the lineup, and that's something that I
haven't had.''
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: The club is expected to activate utility
outfielder F.P. Santangelo today, but he won't be with the team in
Pittsburgh because, once activated, he must serve his five-game
suspension resulting from the May 16 fight at Wrigley Field. It's
likely utility player Chris Donnels will be placed on the 15-day
disabled list. ... Pitcher Kevin Brown was ejected after the top of
the seventh inning of the second game, following Gary Sheffield's
strikeout with the bases loaded. ... Dodgers right-hander Greg
Olson appeared in his first game since April 8, allowing a solo
homer to Bruce Aven in the seventh inning of the first game. It was
the first homer allowed by the Dodgers in 332/3 innings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
