<HEADLINE>
NO RELIEF FOR WETTELAND, RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The past seven days for Texas Rangers closer
John Wetteland couldn't have been that difficult. All that has
happened is:
</P>
<P>
   _ Contract-extension negotiations with the Rangers went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   _ He was subject to numerous trade rumors that had him being
sent to either Los Angeles, Atlanta or somewhere in between. All
other locations were ruled out.
</P>
<P>
   _ His wife, Michele, gave birth Monday to a son, J.D., but only
after going through a difficult delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Having endured all that, Wetteland still had to go out and
pitch, but the result wasn't a happy one. This was not a fairy
tale.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Johnson whacked a slider from Wetteland into the
left-field bleachers with one out in the ninth inning to give the
Chicago White Sox a 4-3 victory over the Rangers at The Ballpark in
Arlington on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   One look at Wetteland, both before and after the game, made it
clear this has been a weary time for him. He admitted it had been a
long time since he had slept. But he refused to blame any of that
for what happened Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still my job to go out and pitch,'' Wetteland said. ``You
don't blame one mistake on mental duress. That's silly. I made a
mistake and he hit it. If I don't make a mistake, he doesn't hit
it. There's no reason why I shouldn't be able to execute on that
one particular pitch. You saw the other at-bats. There was no
reason not to execute on that at-bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland struck out two of the four batters he faced in the
ninth. But Johnson's home run sent the Rangers to their third
consecutive loss and left them eight games behind the Oakland
Athletics in the wild-card playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also remain entrenched in last place in the American
League West, which is why there was much speculation about
Wetteland being traded before Monday's nonwaiver deadline. But
Wetteland, who can be a free agent after the season, insisted such
talk was not a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was glad the deadline had passed, Wetteland said,
``Yes ... no ... maybe. It's hard to answer that question when all
I've been saying for the past month is all that is noise. But the
noise will continue. Players are out of their minds if they don't
think they're put on waivers after the trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing definitive happened. All that happened is the trade
deadline came and went. Really, what does that mean? If Wayne
Gretzky can be traded, anybody can get traded, and I'm certainly
not in his class.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland said his mind has been more on his wife, Michele, than
contract talks or trade rumors. Michele finally gave birth on
Monday and both mother and child are doing fine, but Wetteland
admitted there were rough moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has some pretty good complications,'' Wetteland said. ``We
spent from seven in the morning until 11 at night at the hospital.
The baby had a few complications which were hard to get through.
But everything is cool, everything is under control. I was never
worried, it's just tough to see your wife and mother-in-law go
through what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss was Wetteland's fourth of the season and came on a
night when starter Ryan Glynn held the White Sox to one run through
seven innings. The White Sox got two runs off relievers Doug Davis
and Jeff Zimmerman in the eighth before the Rangers tied it in the
bottom of the inning on Gabe Kapler's two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept my team in the game, which is important,'' Glynn said.
``You're just trying to not give up runs, whether it's 10-0 or 1-0.
(White Sox starter) James Baldwin is a tough matchup. That's the
way the game goes.''
</P>
<P>
   The game is unrelenting. It offers no rest, even for a pitcher
who has gone through an incredible amount over the course of a
week. Happy endings are only for fairy tales.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
