<SLUG> BC-GLF-COUPLES-INVITATIONAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIGHTY-FINE COOK FIRES A 10-UNDER 62 FOR $125,000 PAYDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWCASTLE, Wash. _ As it turned out, 10 more players wouldn't
have made any difference at Fred Couples' Wells Fargo Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   John Cook was enough.
</P>
<P>
   He turned Couples' sixth-annual get-together into his own
personal crusade Tuesday at The Golf Club at Newcastle. He shot a
course-record, 10-under-par 62 in the final round, giving him 131
overall. That was good for a three-stroke victory and a $125,000
paycheck _ making him the event's first repeat winner.
</P>
<P>
   Someone forgot to tell the 20-year PGA Tour veteran this was an
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   He played like his career depended on it. Maybe it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're calling this one of the greatest rounds in state of
Washington history,'' quipped Couples, as Cook entered the
interview room.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, 42, brought the right kind of low numbers to an event that
had, in Couples' words, teetered from low numbers _ from player
withdrawals. He made the charity fund-raiser, attended by an
estimated 12,000 people over two days in perfect weather
conditions, a success.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, people asked him about his putting stroke, his
unflappable demeanor. Unsolicited, Cook wanted to discuss
relationships. He pointed out how he and Couples have known each
other since they were junior golfers, how he comes to this event
every year without fail.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, the players who didn't show were listening.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn things about commitment and loyalty,'' Cook said.
``We learned that from the generation before us. Hopefully, the
kids today will learn from that. That's where you start gaining
respect. This game has been pretty good for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the 18-hole exercise at Newcastle treated Cook, a
10-event Tour winner who has struggled of late, better than anyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   He had nine birdies, never going more than two consecutive holes
without lowering his score. He made eight putts from 10 feet or
less. He made a 30-footer for another birdie, a 25-footer to save
par.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an unbelievable round,'' said Couples, who finished
fifth, 11 strokes back. ``It's not like other guys were shooting
67. If we had 50 guys here, you wouldn't be seeing 64s and 65s.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook started the day trailing Brent Geiberger by three strokes.
Geiberger did nothing to hurt his cause, following up a first-round
66 with a 68. But five holes into it Tuesday, Cook had a share of
the lead. Once they made the turn, Cook had the top of the
leaderboard all to himself and never let go.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more even personalities on Tour, Cook seemed to enjoy
himself as he toured the hillside course. Nothing could upset him.
As he stepped onto the seventh tee, he good-naturedly said,
``Mute,'' to a noisy gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Cook was midway through his swing when the door on a portable
restroom slammed shut. Responsible was a tall, dark-haired woman
oblivious to the surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Geiberger,'' joked Peter Jacobsen, one of Cook's playing
partners.
</P>
<P>
   When Cook sank his 30-footer on the 15th hole, Scott McCarron,
watching from the 16th, bowed while Cook fluttered his arms around
like a bird. Everybody was having fun.
</P>
<P>
   Cook hopes it continues. The other time he won the Couples
event, in 1995, his career got an unexpected boost. He beat Jeff
Gove by a stroke at Overlake Golf and Country Club, shooting rounds
of 71 and 63. He went on to win in Mexico and then claim two tour
events in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he's 105th on the money list with a fifth-place
finish his top effort on Tour. Another resurgence would be
appreciated, starting this week at the International near Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that you forget how to win, you forget how to get
there,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   He knows his way to Seattle. And, yes, he'll be back.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Dan Raley can be reached at 206-448-8008
</P>
<P>
   or danraley &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
