<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS' GAMES BELONG TO THOSE IN UNIFORMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ My friend had a good run with his Queen Anne Little
League team this season. But when I ran into him the other day, he
had a lot of mixed emotions about whether he'll coach next year.
</P>
<P>
   In light of all the news lately about out-of-control parents, my
friend said he is seeing behavioral breakdowns on a pretty regular
basis.
</P>
<P>
   It makes you wonder whether youth leagues are any place for
kids.
</P>
<P>
   This is supposed to be my column, but today, it's my friend's
space. Here are some of the things he told me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've really struggled with how to balance doing it for the
kids versus competitive reasons. Coaches, myself included, and
parents _ everyone's ego gets involved. How much emphasis do you
put on winning versus having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   During the regular season, the coach said he stresses
sportsmanship, being a team player, hustle. Unfortunately, so many
of those ideals get undermined on game day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played some interleague games against another neighborhood
team. There were some jerky coaches and parents screaming. People
were arguing calls and getting out the rule book. It just makes you
sick. It's embarrassing. And the kids don't enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   The disappointment in his voice was obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's not easy to talk about all these things,
because all these (parents) are pillars of the community. There are
doctors and lawyers. ... During one game, we were beating this team
pretty good and it turned into a nightmare. One (parent) kept
screaming at the ump and before long, other parents were booing and
screaming, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, no one wanted to play anymore. It was cold. It was a
blowout. All the kids were just like, `Let's call the game.' The
screaming really tainted the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The stress a parent can create is alarming, the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swear, kids have better games when their parents aren't
around. It's about egos. Parents get a sense of self-worth with
regard to how well their kids play. It used to be you'd go out and
play baseball in the sandlot. It's totally changed. Now kids play
because their parents want them to play. When was the last time you
went to a park and saw kids playing ball without parents around?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some parents who undress their kids if they strike
out. They give them a whole set of instructions after they missed
the ball, and it makes them feel completely worthless.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the kids want is to be encouraged, no matter what they do.
What parents and coaches should be doing is fostering a place where
kids aren't afraid to fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of our conversation, all the anecdotes piling up
like lead weights, it seemed as if the coach was completely
discouraged with Little League. But then again ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a feeling it will get to be January and I'll start to
wonder who we should draft, who's grown three inches,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the game and hanging out on a sunny day, hearing the
kids joking with each other on the bench. It's so much fun. Little
League baseball is wild. There are the massive comebacks. There are
some incredible success stories. We had a kid who didn't get a hit
all year, and he comes up in the last game against the fastest
pitcher in the bottom of the sixth with two outs and bases loaded
and he rips a single down the line,'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was impossible, and he did it. We had this other kid, he
was like 0-for-20 but during this one stretch, he gets six hits,
makes two diving catches, and we were laughing because he almost
had his eyes closed. Still, it was pretty special.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach had gotten back to what Little League is supposed to
be about: The kids, their moments.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it might help reinvigorate him. Then again, since
the season ended a few weeks ago, the coach can't stop thinking
about an angry father who confronted him in a parking lot before a
big game about his son's playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I can even get out of my car, this guy's in my face and
he was just ranting. He wasn't even making any sense, he was so
mad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard enough meeting the expectations of a dozen 11- and
12-year-olds, but to have to meet every parent's expectation, too?
I guarantee you, someone's not going to be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   What a shame.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
