<HEADER>
A0221 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-     08-02 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Monday Night Football retools, Cosell's status as legend
secure
</P>
<P>
   By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Before we all begin to hyperventilate over the reinvention of
Monday Night Football, allow us to set the record straight. Dennis
Miller, the comic and social satirist, is not inheriting the Howard
Cosell chair in the three-man booth. No one ever has. No one ever
will.
</P>
<P>
   There is no point in trying to compare the stand-up star of his
own HBO show with the one-time Brooklyn lawyer turned sportscaster.
This may or may not be to Miller's advantage. But let us reset the
stage. In the 1970s, ABC introduced pro football to Monday night,
with Frank Gifford representing the fans who wanted to watch the
game, Cosell on hand for the ones who wanted a show, and Don
Meredith catering to those who weren't sure.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, we find ourselves at a curious intersection of
past and present, of nostalgia and nonsense yet to come. Miller is
a brilliant wit whose one-liners will add a new dimension to the
longest-running prime-time series in television history. But Cosell
didn't connect with the fans because he was funny. Of course, he
wasn't known for his restraint, either.
</P>
<P>
   Quite simply, Howard aroused in viewers emotions that they had
usually reserved for wrestlers or politicians, although not
necessarily in that order. He prided himself on bringing ``sports
journalism'' to the small screen. He also became a symbol of the
excess that television had brought to our games, of an assault upon
civility. Like Howard, TV demanded action.
</P>
<P>
   If ABC's intent is to inject this entertainment with new vigor
and sizzle, bully for them. They might actually do it. Dan Fouts is
almost the forgotten man in this package, but he was a Hall of Fame
quarterback and has the capacity to surprise us. And no one is
better at describing the drama as it unfolds than Al Michaels.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Miller and Fouts will be sharing the role of
Meredith, the ex-Dallas Cowboy and down-home, small-town Texan who
played off Cosell perfectly. ``I just waited for Howard to make a
mistake,'' Meredith recently told Sports Illustrated, ``and I never
had to wait long.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dennis isn't going to communicate with the fans, or
antagonize them, as Howard did because he doesn't take himself
seriously enough. The beard keeps him from coming across as a smug
adolescent, but we understand his role. He is there to give us a
chuckle, an offbeat remark, a fan's insight. But if his jokes make
us think too hard, the experiment won't work.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone out there in TV land is yearning for a return to the
'70s, they can forget it. This crew will never match the aura of
Gifford, Cosell and Meredith, even though that combination lasted
just five years. Dandy Don left, came back, left again, and went on
to lead a quiet life. Lung cancer stilled the distinctive voice of
Humble Howard in 1995, a decade after he had left the booth.
Gifford was eased out one step down at a time, moving to analyst,
then into the studio, then into his living room.
</P>
<P>
   Comics of the '70s rushed to imitate Cosell. Once, taking a
break from working on a book with Howard, I wandered into a New
York nightclub called Catch a Rising Star. Gabe Kaplan, then the
star of the sitcom Welcome Back, Kotter, was on the stage doing an
imitation of Cosell broadcasting the Crucifixion.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to describe Howard's voice, Billy Crystal once said,
``Think of a man with a bad sinus condition and a large
vocabulary.''
</P>
<P>
   At the peak of Monday Night Football, ABC received 5,000 letters
a week about Cosell, a majority wanting him off the air. Howard
attributed this reaction to television's weakness for ex-jock
glamour boys. ``The fans of this country,'' he declared, ``have
been fed the pablum of the ex-football Giants for 15 years. So they
ask, `Who is this guy to come out of nowhere and tell us how good
or bad a player is?'''
</P>
<P>
   It was part of Howard's nature that he would have been puzzled
if he thought Gifford, Pat Summerall or Kyle Rote, to name three
ex-Giants, would take such a remark personally. Beneath that
brilliant ego, his skin was as thin as Kleenex. One unpleasant
letter plunged him into gloom. You could imagine what 5,000 might
have done.
</P>
<P>
   The cast has changed. The game has changed. The country has
changed. You doubt Dennis Miller will get death threats, as Cosell
did. Crowds no longer demonstrate outside the local ABC affiliates
because their team didn't make the halftime highlights. Taverns no
longer give prizes to people for tossing a brick through a TV
screen at Howard's face.
</P>
<P>
   Out of respect for all the nutrition Monday Night Football has
provided us the past 30 years, you may consider this space a
tension-free zone, with no references to Miller Time or the
chemistry of the new crew in the booth.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
