<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-biggio-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Torn ACL ends Biggio's year
</P>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   It took almost 13 years and exactly 1,800 games, but on Tuesday
an injury finally got the best of Craig Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   The gritty Astros second baseman, who never has spent a day on
the disabled list, is headed to the DL with a torn anterior
cruciate ligament and a torn medial collateral ligament in his left
knee. He is out for the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The injury occurred in the seventh inning of Tuesday's 4-3
victory over the Marlins at Pro Player Stadium. Biggio was
attempting to turn a double play at second base when Marlins center
fielder Preston Wilson slid into his left leg, sending Biggio to
the ground in obvious pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I got whacked in a football game,'' said Biggio,
who also revealed he has been playing with a torn ligament in his
right ankle. ``I wasn't in a lot of pain, but it just felt weird.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just par for the course the way things have gone for
us this year. For it to end like this is a little depressing, but
I'll be back in spring training with a positive attitude, ready to
come back from this.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio injured his ankle two months ago in an outfield collision
with Lance Berkman, although the club has been calling it a high
ankle sprain.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play the game of baseball, these things are going to
happen,'' Biggio said. ``You're going to have a lot of takeouts in
the middle of the infield. Unfortunately, I got hurt on this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating, because I've never been on the disabled
list. Even though we're not having a good year, the team is
starting to play better, and I'd like to be a part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the victory, the attitude in the Astros' clubhouse was
very solemn as news spread about the severity of Biggio's injury.
Moises Alou, who missed the entire 1999 season because of a torn
ACL, could relate to what must have been running through Biggio's
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just feel bad for the guy,'' Alou said. ``You really don't
even want to say anything to him except, `I love you.' I've been
through it, and there's nothing anyone can say to you to make you
feel better.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's anything good about this, it's that he's got a
couple months left in this season and the entire offseason to try
to get strong and come back. He'll have plenty of time to get
healthy. We're going to miss him. He was just starting to come
around with the bat. I just feel really sorry for the guy right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker said Biggio will undergo
an MRI exam Friday to confirm the injury and that surgery will be
scheduled after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really no doubt about the diagnosis,'' Hunsicker said.
``It's pretty clear-cut. He'll stay with the team for the rest of
the trip. There's no sense of urgency, and that also will allow
some time for the swelling to go down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been that kind of year for us. It's been a year to forget
from many standpoints, and this just adds to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio, 34, has been an iron man throughout his career.
Ironically, Pro Player Stadium is where his club-record streak of
494 consecutive games came to an end on Aug. 5 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-time National League All-Star and three-time team Most
Valuable Player took pride in his iron-man streak and his ability
to play through injuries that might have disabled other players.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to go on the DL, you might as well go on with
the big one, and the ACL is big,'' Biggio said. ``Hey, you have to
make light of it somehow. I'm going to work my butt off over the
winter to come back from this. To be able to avoid the disabled
list for as long as I did was a nice little streak to have. It's
upsetting, but there's nothing you can do about it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Astros righthander Scott Elarton: ``The one thing you could
always guarantee is that Bidge is going to be ready to play every
day. It's going to be tough not to see him out there at second base
for the rest of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Utility man Bill Spiers replaced Biggio on Tuesday, but it's
uncertain how manager Larry Dierker will handle second base for the
remainder of the season. Spiers and Julio Lugo appear to be the
best options. As of Tuesday night, Hunsicker was uncertain of the
coinciding roster move when Biggio goes on the DL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bidge is the emotional center of our team,'' Dierker said.
``He plays with such energy; it's almost beyond enthusiasm. He
plays with a rage to win. It's pretty hard to ignore a guy who does
that. It's pretty hard not to miss him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will probably be harder for him to come back from this
injury than it would have 10 years ago. But I know Bidge, and you
can bet he's going to come back next spring with that same rage to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
