<HEADER>
A0231 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-GOP-WEBWATCH-SFCHRON &LR;      08-02 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-WEBWATCH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING SERIOUS POLITICAL DISCOURSE AMONG ALL THE ONLINE 
 ILLITERACY
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By VLAE KERSHNERc.2000 San Francisco Chronicle &QC;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy to find a decent political discussion on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Internet's biggest disappointments is that while it
is supposed to empower individuals to discuss issues seriously,
much of the discussion that really occurs is illiterate ranting.
</P>
<P>
   I hate to pick on  &UR; www.pseudo.com,  &LR; because its live cameras and
unscripted skybox conversations are the surprise hit of the
Republican convention. Still, its chatroom _ where webheads are
supposed to be able to converse with the talking heads in the
skybox _ is suffering from an intelligibility gap.
</P>
<P>
   This is a verbatim sample from Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ I would like bush to get out of the u.n. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ good wish Dan, &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ man that is just what i wanted to say media &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Isn't the us not being in the League of nations help Hitler &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Hitler ? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ If the us is not in the UN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ hitler? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ I was comenting on US getting out of the UN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Someone is trying to make a point here _ withdrawal of the U.S.
from the United Nations could produce conditions similar to
American isolationism before World War II _ but it gets lost in the
cacophony of real-time chat.
</P>
<P>
   Quite different is a format called moderated chat, used
extensively by sites such as  &UR; www.aol.com  &LR; and
 &UR; www.washingtonpost.com.  &LR; Users' comments and questions are sent to
a moderator, who then decides what to post.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an example from ABC _  &UR; www.abcnews.go.com.  &LR; The guest is
Arizona Rep. Jim Kolbe, who Tuesday became the first openly gay
speaker at a Republican convention. The questioner is someone from
out on the web.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Questioner: ``As a gay man, why should I vote for a &LR; 
 &UR; conservative republican who can easily undo the small &LR; 
 &UR; protections that our community has worked so hard to achieve?'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kolbe: `'The Republican philosophy strongly promotes both &LR; 
 &UR; individual responsibility and individual freedom. It is because &LR; 
 &UR; of this philosophy that I have remained a Republican, even &LR; 
 &UR; though I may agree with some of the positions taken by the &LR; 
 &UR; party.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Notice that Kolbe said ``agree'' when he obviously meant to say
``disagree.'' This is still chat, and it's a little rough.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if you want a serious discussion, the moderated chat
format is light years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   A NON-DEBATABLE ISSUE: You can participate in all sorts of polls
on the web, but are there any that mean anything? Well, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   The Commission on Presidential Debates _  &UR; www.debates.org  &LR; _ is
conducting a survey on what the format and topics for the
presidential debates should be, and promises to forward the results
to the moderator of the debates.
</P>
<P>
   But _ boo, hiss _ the survey doesn't ask the most important
question _ which candidates should be allowed to debate. The
commission has already decided that only candidates with 15 percent
in the polls should be included, which means only George Bush and
Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you're a fan of Ralph Nader or some other third-party
candidate, there's no way to get your message across.
</P>
<P>
   EMAIL FOR EMIL: Remember John Chancellor and the other old-time
floor reporters for the TV networks, going around to the
delegations, asking questions and gathering anecdotes?
</P>
<P>
   Emil Guillermo, the veteran Bay Area journalist, is doing that
type of shoe-leather reporting for  &UR; www.grassroots.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't quite hide the skepticism in his voice when he asked
a Latino delegate from Texas why Latinos should support the party
that was behind California's controversial anti-immigration ballot
measure, Prop. 187. The Texan didn't seem to know what he was
talking about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 0148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0232 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CAMPBELL-ADS-SFCHRON &LR;      08-02 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPBELL-ADS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPBELL GOES `EDGY' FOR KID VOTE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The ``Rage Against the Machine`' political
candidate now has a commercial to appeal to the MTV crowd.
</P>
<P>
   That's South Bay Rep. Tom Campbell, candidate for U.S. Senate,
who showed off new spots here Tuesday that are running on MTV and
Comedy Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edgy'' is how Campbell ad consultant Roy Fletcher described
them. That means fast cuts, lots of black and white, with a
high-tech feel.
</P>
<P>
   And he's being interviewed by the MTV ``Choose or Lose'' people
in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   What's up with that? This is a Republican political campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And hey, there's the tech-loving candidate, sitting at a
computer, e-mailing his Stanford students, telling young newcomers
to the political process, ``Check it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's campaign pointed out that the candidate is a college
professor. And he does have a connection to the youth vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen Sen. (Dianne) Feinstein jogging into youth
events,'' said Sean Walsh, Campbell's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's campaign manager can speak with authority on what
appeals to the youth voters. Andrea Jones, who is running the
Campbell show, turned 23 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The issues that most young voters care about ``are not issues
you guys would ever write about,'' she told reporters. Those are
things like violence in the schools, paying for education, and,
``How am I going to make money after college?''
</P>
<P>
   Traditional politicians _ not in Philadelphia _ aren't speaking
to those themes.
</P>
<P>
   So that's why Campbell's new ad is one of three spots that tout
his independence.
</P>
<P>
   It may be tough for California viewers even to get a peek at
these ads. Campbell doesn't have a lot of money to spread around on
commercial time _ just $250,000, enough for about one spot on
network television.
</P>
<P>
   But he's hoping that through the media and coverage here, he'll
get out the message: Campbell the maverick.
</P>
<P>
   The ads mention the congressman's leadership and his commitment
to education and fiscal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   They also do not mention the ``R'' word. Never is Campbell's
identification with the Grand Old Party made explicit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The script correctly portrays who I am,'' said Campbell, who
was quick to add that he is ``proud of my Republicanism.'' Did he
believe a connection with the GOP is a liability? ``No, I don't
think so,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The real reason? The all-important swing and independent voters,
some of them first-time voters _ the kind of folks who gravitated
to Arizona Sen. John McCain in the presidential race _ are the
power brokers in this election.
</P>
<P>
   So Campbell enlisted McCain _ whom he didn't endorse in the
primary _ for one spot that was to air last night during McCain's
keynote speech to the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Campbell's a fighter,'' the Arizona senator says, ``a
maverick like me.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercial ends with McCain saying, ``Tom believes in an
America where special interests don't run the country. You do.''
</P>
<P>
   Another spot touts Campbell's experience and life story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Educated in some of our nation's finest universities, for 17
years Tom Campbell has made a personal commitment to educational
excellence as a teacher,'' says the announcer. He calls Campbell
``a leader for a new generation, not a politician for the next
election.''
</P>
<P>
   The third ad is the MTV spot.
</P>
<P>
   The music, said Campbell ad man Fletcher, ``is a little bit like
Depeche Mode.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch again.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he didn't understand that's a group old enough to be
familiar to most reporters covering the campaign. We're talking
prehistoric.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Campbell, if he wants to be real edgy, needs to get out that
``Rage Against the Machine'` track: ``More (money) for Gore or the
son of a drug lord. F_ it. Cut the cord.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe that won't play, especially in Philadelphia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
