<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T BLAME RANGERS GM; HE HAD NOTHING TO TRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ You'll find no white flag atop the pole at
The Ballpark in Arlington this week.
</P>
<P>
   Don't need one. The Texas Rangers' acceptance of their season's
fate should be obvious, despite the outcry that general manager
Doug Melvin should do something dramatic, like sign a surrender on
the deck of the USS Missouri, or something.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a freak and sudden alignment of the planets, the Rangers
are not playoff-bound this season. Reasons abound, not the least of
which is that the all-world catcher was injured last week and is
lost for the season.
</P>
<P>
   But even before that, these Rangers lacked that certain ``je ne
sais quoi,'' which is French for ``dependable pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't you think Melvin saw that?
</P>
<P>
   ``What good does it do by announcing that the season is over?''
Melvin asked before Tuesday night's 4-3 loss to the Chicago White
Sox. ``I don't understand what that does, besides killing morale.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin is being rebuked in public print and on the radio talk
shows for seemingly standing pat, while more emboldened general
managers wheeled and dealed around him.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Arizona Diamondbacks were able to trade for the widely
exalted Curt Schilling. But it cost them, among others, their
once-No. 1 starter, Omar Daal.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Atlanta Braves added pitcher Andy Ashby. But Ashby cost
the Braves one of their most promising young arms in Bruce Chen.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, the Los Angeles Dodgers made their pennant push by
trading for ... Tom Goodwin?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, puh-leese. Even in accommodating Coors Field, Goodwin's
average was plunging like a rock.
</P>
<P>
   And the team at the top of the AL West, the Seattle Mariners,
made its big trade-deadline move by acquiring outfielder Al Martin.
Yawn.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, none of these are deals that the Rangers either
wanted or were in a position to make. Melvin had neither a Daal nor
a Chen to offer, and somebody needs to explain to me where a
Martin, a Rondell White or a B.J. Surhoff would have fit in.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Melvin had bullpen closer John Wetteland, and that
was it, unless the general manager wanted to take the vastly
unpopular step of shopping left fielder Rusty Greer.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Melvin's sin likely was in not trading Wetteland
in early June, right after the pitcher was coming off a month in
which he had a major-league-leading 11 saves. In early June,
however, the Rangers were still on the high side of the .500 mark.
They thought they could still find a higher gear and win the
division.
</P>
<P>
   Scold Melvin for his optimism. But while you're at it, tell me
which of the disappointing relievers would have been closing games
for the rest of this season.
</P>
<P>
   With the trade deadline staring him in the face last weekend,
Melvin simply decided that the best deal for Wetteland _ for now _
was no deal.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland GM Billy Beane woofed about Melvin stiffing him on a
packaged Wetteland-David Segui trade. But Beane reportedly never
offered the prospect that the Rangers wanted, pitching prospect
Jesus Colome, and the other piece of the Oakland offer was Matt
Stairs.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Stairs?
</P>
<P>
   At the annual late-July poker game, in other words, some teams
always seem to hold the cards. The Braves and Yankees seldom deem
themselves to be more than a player or two away. Their farm systems
have enabled them to proceed accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers enjoy no such luxury. The young pitching arms in the
system _ Tuesday night's starter Ryan Glynn, for instance _ are
mostly all in Arlington these days, trying to earn permanent
big-league jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin's trade-bait bucket was largely empty.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts have been watching the Rangers for weeks. The failure to
close a deal for Wetteland may say more about the kind of
inconsistent season that he has had _ Tuesday night being another
example _ than it does about Melvin.
</P>
<P>
   The alarmists' view is that it's time to break up the Rangers
and begin anew. But let me suggest again that that was done last
November, when two-time MVP Juan Gonzalez was traded.
</P>
<P>
   Given his diminished options, Melvin decided this week not to
give John Wetteland away. Some of us have no problem with that.
</P>
<P>
   No further dramatic gestures or flags of surrender are
necessary. Don't criticize Melvin for realizing that. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
