<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-WHITE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE-HOT ASCENT: '97 SURRENDER BEGAN SOX TURNAROUND
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-TURNAROUND-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Frank Thomas is in a good mood. The big
slugger isn't always the friendliest guy in the game, but on this
day he's smiling and almost jovial.
</P>
<P>
   And why not?
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is having a superb season, the Chicago White Sox have the
best record in the American League and an 111/2-game lead, after
Tuesday night, over the second-place Cleveland Indians in the AL
Central, and general manager Ron Schueler strengthened the team by
trading for catcher Charles Johnson and designated hitter Harold
Baines on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a positive trade,'' Thomas said before the
White Sox defeated the Texas Rangers, 4-3, Tuesday night at The
Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas was not in a good mood this time three years ago. There
were no smiles then, only scowls.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox were 31/2 games behind the Cleveland Indians at
the trading deadline in 1997, but instead of strengthening the team
Schueler traded away Roberto Hernandez, Wilson Alvarez and Danny
Darwin in the infamous ``White Flag'' trade.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas made no secret of his displeasure at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always want to win,'' Thomas said. ``That's what we play
the game for. At the time it was something that was painful. It
wasn't cool.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to smile now because the White Sox are winning in
large part because of that trade.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the prospects acquired in the deal, Keith Foulke, Bobby
Howry and Lorenzo Barcelo, are in the White Sox bullpen, but the
impact of the trade goes beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   It signaled a new direction for the team. The White Sox would
rebuild with youth, and suffer the short-term consequences for the
promise of long-term gains. Manager Jerry Manuel was hired before
the '98 season, and was allowed to concentrate on development and
not results.
</P>
<P>
   Young players like Magglio Ordonez, Paul Konerko and Carlos Lee,
and pitchers Mike Sirotka, Jim Parque, Howry and Foulke were able
to grow in a pressure-free environment. Along with Thomas, Ray
Durham and James Baldwin, they form the nucleus of the best team in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one thought that trade was going to benefit us the way it
did,'' Thomas said. ``We got over it, and the organization grew. I
think we're better now, and we'll let bygones be bygones. I'm just
happy it worked out for us.''
</P>
<P>
   With two months left in the season and a playoff berth firmly
within their grasp, it's easy to say it worked out. Going into the
season, there still were doubts.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians, Central champions since the division played its
first season to a finish in '95, once again were the heavy
favorites. The White Sox, who finished second even though they were
a game under .500 in '99, were supposed to be pushed by the Detroit
Tigers and Kansas City Royals, according to conventional wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   But if those outside the clubhouse doubted, those inside were
quietly confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realistically thought we could compete in this division,
and at the very least the wild card,'' Konerko said. ``Obviously
we're doing better. But we really thought we'd be in the divisional
race all year.''
</P>
<P>
   They're better because Ordonez, Konerko and Lee continue to
improve; because Baldwin, Sirotka and Parque had combined for 30
victories before Baldwin's start against the Rangers on Tuesday,
two fewer than they had all of last season; and because Thomas once
again is one of the most feared hitters in the game.
</P>
<P>
   There were whispers that the one-time superstar might be
finished after he hit .265 in '98 and had a career-low 15 homers
last year, but he came to Arlington with a .333 average, 29 homers
and 91 runs batted in. He's in the top 10 in the league in all
three categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people overlooked the type teams I played for the last
couple of years,'' he said. ``There were a lot of young kids, a lot
of growing, and when you've got a veteran player in the mix of all
that, it's a little different. And last year I wasn't healthy. Now
I'm healthy, and I'm playing good baseball. It's not like I lost
interest or lost talent. I'm doing the things I've always done. I'm
just healthy again and I'm able to do it on a team that's
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox haven't been winning as much lately. They had lost seven
of their past 11 games before Tuesday night. But it hasn't
mattered. They still had a double-digit lead over the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beautiful, because we've played bad and haven't lost any
ground,'' Konerko said. ``We're not going to play bad forever.
Everybody wants to get down on us, but you're going to go through
bad spurts. The fact that we haven't really lost any ground, that
just tells me more it's our year.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade for Johnson and Baines shows that the White Sox are
serious about continuing to win.
</P>
<P>
   Schueler also wanted to add a pitcher with Cal Eldred (10-2) out
indefinitely because of a nerve problem in his elbow, but the
asking price was too high. That could be a potential problem in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it shows how far the White Sox have come in three years
that their biggest worry is pitching matchups in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Thomas is smiling. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
