<HEADLINE>
RANGERS PLACE DARREN OLIVER ON DISABLED LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Texas Rangers placed pitcher Darren
Oliver on the disabled list Tuesday with fatigue in his left
shoulder and have moved Doug Davis into the rotation. Oliver, on
the disabled list for the second time this season, is scheduled to
have his shoulder examined by Anaheim Angels team physician Lewis
Yocum on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers want Yocum to examine him to make sure the injury is
not anything more serious than fatigue. If Yocum confirms the
Rangers' diagnosis, Oliver is likely to end up at Triple-A Oklahoma
on medical-rehabilitation assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I couldn't start him any more, and I couldn't count on
him in the bullpen,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``There's
just no way for him to work out of this. The first thing is to make
sure it's nothing physical.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver is 0-2 with an 11.57 earned-run average in three starts
since coming off the disabled list July 20.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers now have three pitchers in the starting rotation
with less than 11/2 years of major-league service: Davis, Ryan
Glynn and Matt Perisho. None of them were in the rotation at the
start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a chance to see what these guys can do,'' Oates
said. ``At the same time, I think our starting pitching is as good
as it has been all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers recalled right-hander Jonathan Johnson from Triple-A
Oklahoma to replace Oliver on the roster. That leaves Mike Venafro
as the only left-hander in the bullpen. SCOUTING DIRECTOR RESIGNS
</P>
<P>
   Scouting director Chuck McMichael, who has overseen the Rangers'
past three drafts, resigned Tuesday to pursue other opportunities.
The job of scouting director has many supervising duties, and
McMichael said he would like to get back to his roots as a talent
evaluator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no regrets being a scouting director; I enjoyed that
part,'' McMichael said. ``But that takes you away from the dirt and
the grass and the ballpark. I miss that part, especially without
the cellphone ringing in your ear every minute. I admit it: I was
born in a dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   McMichael's most-significant draft picks were Tulsa first
baseman Carlos Pena and second baseman Jason Romano, two highly
regarded prospects.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin said he would like to fill the
position quickly and will likely replace McMichael with one of the
Rangers' three national amateur scouts: Tim Hallgren, Dave
Klipstein or Jeff Taylor. MISSING LOAIZA
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers won't face former teammate Esteban Loaiza this
weekend in Toronto. Loaiza was scheduled to pitch Sunday against
the Rangers, but that changed after the Blue Jays acquired Steve
Trachsel from Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Trachsel is scheduled to pitch against the Rangers on Friday and
Kelvim Escobar is being pushed back to Sunday. Loaiza, traded to
the Blue Jays two weeks ago, is still in the rotation but is
scheduled to pitch Monday against the Kansas City Royals. KAPLER
EXTENDS STREAK
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Kapler waited until his final at-bat, but he extended his
hitting streak to 15 games with a two-run single to left field in
the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The streak is the Rangers' longest this season, and their
longest since Todd Zeile's 17-game streak from June 21-July 10 last
year.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kapler's streak of games with at least one extra-base
hit ended at seven, one short of the club record set by Ruben
Sierra in 1990. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Rick Helling is the Rangers' Player of the Month for July.
Helling went 4-0 with a 3.12 ERA in six starts.
</P>
<P>
   _ John and Michele Wetteland have a new son. Michele gave birth
to Jake David on Monday. J.D. is the Wetteland's third child.
</P>
<P>
   _ Darwin Cubillan, the right-handed reliever acquired from the
Toronto Blue Jays in the Esteban Loaiza trade, has pitched 102/3
scoreless innings for the Triple-A Oklahoma RedHawks, giving up
only four hits, walking three and striking out eight. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
