<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GOODRICH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' TOP PICK BACKPEDALING ON DEPTH CHART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ In roughly three months, Dwayne Goodrich has
gone from being the first of three rookie cornerbacks drafted by
the Dallas Cowboys to playing behind the other two, Kareem
Larrimore and Mario Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really get frustrated,'' Goodrich said Tuesday at
Valley Ranch, where the Cowboys held double practices before
heading for Tokyo on Wednesday for Saturday's American Bowl. ``The
other two guys are just picking up on what we're doing a little
quicker than I am. I just eventually have to come around sooner or
later, I know that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Goodrich _ second-round pick, sixth cornerback taken
overall _ finds a way to keep his pride in check, the Cowboys'
coaching staff is trying to deflect attention from a pecking order
that has gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   Larrimore and Edwards, despite being picked in the fourth and
sixth rounds, respectively, are on the second team and playing more
against slot receivers in nickel packages than the third-string
Goodrich.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new system for me,'' said Goodrich, who started on a
national championship team at Tennessee as a junior. ``In college,
you would have coaches who gave you what to do, then you did it
whatever way you felt comfortable in doing it. Here, you do it
Zim's way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Zim'' is Mike Zimmer, the Cowboys' first-year defensive
coordinator and former secondary coach. Zimmer is extremely
passionate and vocal in his coaching style and isn't afraid to chew
out a player who makes a mistake or praise another who makes a good
play.
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich ``had three or four really good practices in Wichita
Falls and was just starting to get his confidence back,'' Zimmer
said. ``Unfortunately, he has kind of been slacking in the last
couple of practices, so now we're trying to get him back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Slacking'' might be an apt description for what happened on a
slant pass completed to Goodrich's side in team drills Tuesday.
Free safety Jason Kaiser followed the receiver through a group of
idle players watching practice and tried to strip the ball.
Goodrich immediately pulled up after the catch.
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich remembers the play but apparently didn't think twice
about it, saying he always tries his hardest. But because he is the
Cowboys' top draft pick, he is beginning to realize that he will be
more closely scrutinized by fans and media.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't help Goodrich that the general perception is that
he has fallen behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to get to where I can go out there and feel
comfortable, and not have to second-guess myself,'' said Goodrich,
who achieved a degree of self-satisfaction with his play on kickoff
coverage Sunday night in the preseason opener against Pittsburgh.
``I went out there to fly around and make a few plays.''
</P>
<P>
   When Edwards was asked about his first game in the NFL, he shook
his head and said, ``I'm focusing on the next game, not the last
game. That's why the Lord put eyes in the front of our head, not in
the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Edwards nor Larrimore, who broke a bone in his right
hand against the Steelers on a corner blitz, was overly impressive
in the Cowboys' 38-10 loss on Sunday. Edwards was penalized for
pass interference in the end zone, a call that led to Pittsburgh's
first touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But both will line up at cornerback with the second team when
the Cowboys face Atlanta on Saturday night at the Tokyo Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer holds firm to his conviction that he didn't see Sunday's
loss as a total meltdown by his young cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time, they were in position,'' he said. ``They
just didn't make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   One exception, Zimmer said, is that Goodrich could have been in
better position against the Steelers' 6-foot-5 rookie Plaxico
Burress on a 2-yard ``fade route'' touchdown in the second quarter.
Goodrich earlier missed a tackle on a hitch to Burress that went
for 24 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a (cornerback) gets completely beaten on a post or on an
out, that's what worries me. That didn't happen in this game,''
Zimmer said. ``I'm a lot more encouraged than maybe some other
people were. It wasn't like, `Wow, our corners got lit up.' To me,
that's important.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also important that the Cowboys' rookie cornerbacks don't
become too much of a story right now. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
