<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT EVEN DISRUPTIVE TRIP CAN RUFFLE COWBOYS COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Some people might look at the Dallas Cowboys'
trip to Japan for the American Bowl game against the Atlanta
Falcons on Saturday as a nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, who depart Wednesday on a 14-hour flight to Tokyo,
are robbed of two days of practice. And even though they will
practice one day in Tokyo, the tours and other marketing functions
they must attend to promote the NFL in Japan will surely be
distractions.
</P>
<P>
   Considering this is his first year as head coach, Dave Campo
would love to have the camp time to keep the focus on football. But
he knows the Cowboys, who are already set to play abroad the next
few years, aren't just any team. As a result, the team is given
special opportunities and responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we will do and I like being a part of
that,'' Campo said. ``This is a special organization, no matter the
circumstances, whether they are good or bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo said he prefers all that comes with being part of the
Cowboys' organization and has impressed that thought on his
players.
</P>
<P>
   As for the game, Campo said he wants to see a good showing from
the first-team units on offense and defense. He also wants to see a
lot of the young players on the offensive line and in the
secondary.
</P>
<P>
   TWO PLAYERS ADDED
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys made several roster moves Tuesday, topped by placing
tight end Mike Lucky on injured reserve. Lucky underwent surgery to
reconstruct three torn ligaments in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Safety Sean Key, who underwent surgery Tuesday to repair the
fractured tibia and fibula in his right leg, also was placed on
injured reserve. The team also reached an injury settlement and
released rookie free-agent guard James Tenner, who fractured his
wrist in practice last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys used two of the open spots to shore up their
depleted offensive-line corps, which is without starters Larry
Allen (fractured wrist) and Erik Williams (holdout/retired). Guard
Steve Scifres, the team's 1997 third-round pick, was brought back
along with former Oklahoma guard J.R. Konrad.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, who already had one open roster spot, now have two,
one of which will surely be used for a blocking tight end to
replace Lucky. In the interim, the Cowboys are planning to use
guard Michael Lies as a blocking tight end in two- and
three-tight-end situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``That position is blocker first and receiver second,'' Dave
Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys resisted using defensive end Ebenezer Ekuban as an
emergency tight end. Ekuban, who played tight end in college, was
used as a tight end briefly last year under similar circumstances.
Campo, however, said that Ekuban's development at defensive end is
too important to split his time. Ekuban is the expected starter at
left end.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs too much work at defensive end,'' Campo said. SMITH,
WARREN RETURN TO PRACTICE
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys running back Emmitt Smith (sprained toe) and safety
George Teague (strained gluteus) returned to practice Tuesday after
missing much of the past week, including Sunday's preseason loss to
the Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   Both players are expected to play Saturday against the Falcons
in the American Bowl in Tokyo. Dave Campo said he will wait a few
days before making a decision. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
