<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-SIGNINGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS SIGN DAVIS, TRENT, THEN FOCUS ON KEEPING BUCKNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The NBA's free-agent signing period began Tuesday, and
the Mavericks wasted little time in ensuring the return of Hubert
Davis and Gary Trent.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a reserve guard and the NBA's 3-point percentage leader
last season, signed a four-year contract believed to be worth at
least $10 million. Trent, likely the starting power forward heading
into the season, signed a one-year deal for $2.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our plan all along,'' Mavs coach/general manager Don
Nelson said regarding the signings of Davis and Trent. ``We're
happy we got it done.''
</P>
<P>
   With Trent and Davis signed, the Mavs' attention turned to
restricted free agent Greg Buckner and finding a backup center.
Buckner is expected to sign a three-year, $2.5 million offer with
Vancouver, a deal the Mavs can match to keep the second-year guard.
</P>
<P>
   Mavs owner Mark Cuban and Nelson have said they plan to match
the offer. Buckner and his agent, Steve Kauffman, however, would
prefer that didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Cuban and Nelson will have some compassion for this kid,
look at him as a human being and say, `You've served us well, we're
overloaded at guard, we'll let you go,''' Grizzlies president Dick
Versace told the ``Vancouver Sun'' Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Versace said he was unsure when the Grizzlies would officially
make the offer to Buckner, leaving the Mavs 15 days to match.
Nelson said Versace's plea won't affect the Mavs' plans for
Buckner, who played a key role in the Mavs' strong late-season
finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who cares what Dick Versace says,'' Nelson said. ``That has
nothing to do with anything. We're going to re-sign (Buckner).''
</P>
<P>
   Re-signing Buckner means the Mavs would likely carry five guards
into the season, and Kauffman has said that his client doesn't
believe there are enough minutes to go around.
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman said the Mavs offered Buckner a two-year deal starting
at the NBA minimum, an offer that was quickly rejected. Kauffman
said the Mavs' plan to match Vancouver's offer has made for an
``uncomfortable situation'' for Buckner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so low-balled by the Dallas Mavericks and that left a
very bad taste in his mouth,'' Kauffman said Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman has maintained that Buckner enjoyed his first season
with the Mavs, but his career would be better served in Vancouver
because he would probably be the third guard.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs also remain in the market for a backup to starting
center Shawn Bradley. Offering the Mavs' $2.25 million exception,
Cuban and Nelson hope to find a big man as the free-agent market
settles out.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said ``there's no timetable'' on signing a backup.
</P>
<P>
   Davis had considered offers from other teams, starting as high
as $3.5 million per season, before coming to terms with the Mavs.
Though the Mavs' contract averages out to at least $2.5 million a
year, Kauffman, who is Davis' agent, said last week the security of
a four-year deal and Davis' preference to remain with the Mavs
sealed his return.
</P>
<P>
   Trent, who missed most of last season nursing injuries, has
positioned himself to sign a much larger contract with the team
next summer. The Mavs are expected to have at least $15 million in
salary-cap room in 2001. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
