<HEADER>
A0239 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-CAR-NASCAR-SAFETY-TEX     08-02 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-SAFETY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR IMPOSES SAFETY DEVICE AFTER FATALITIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Responding to the crashes that killed Adam
Petty and Kenny Irwin Jr., NASCAR has mandated two measures to help
prevent carburetor throttles from hanging up while at speed.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR officials issued a technical bulletin Tuesday requiring
Winston Cup teams to install a stop on the car's primary and
secondary throttle shafts, and an on/off ``kill switch'' on the
steering wheel within reach of the driver's thumb to cut power to
the ignition.
</P>
<P>
   The modifications are scheduled to take effect with the opening
of practice Thursday morning for Saturday's Brickyard 400 at the
Indianapolis Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``In trying to find something effective across the board, these
were two areas that were easily done and could be done before this
weekend,'' said Kevin Triplett, director of operations for NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   Triplett said the changes were being implemented despite the
fact that the sanctioning body has been unable to establish that
hung throttles caused the fatal crashes in the Turn 3 area of New
Hampshire International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Petty, 19, the first fourth-generation athlete in any sport, was
killed while practicing his Busch Grand National car May 12. Irwin,
30, was killed while practicing his Cup car July 7, not far from
where Petty crashed on the relatively flat 1.059-mile oval in
Loudon, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work we did _ the investigations _ we didn't find anything
conclusive,'' said Triplett, referring to the widely held theory
that the throttles hung open on both drivers and took them straight
into the concrete wall. ``As we continue to go through things and
talk to people to try to piece things together ... it's difficult
to recreate what happened because of damage to this piece of the
car and that part of the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through our talks with crew chiefs and drivers and car owners,
this is an area we felt like something could be done. We hope this
is a step in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Cup cars are equipped with an on/off switch on their dashboard.
Triplett said many teams already were using a throttle stop on
their carburetor assembly to prevent the rod that controls the
throttle from going past the point where it can hang open.
</P>
<P>
   ``The auxiliary ignition switch on the steering wheel is
something we added,'' Triplett said. ``That's where the driver's
hands are already. Instead of creating another thing for the driver
to take his hands off the wheel for, there's a switch where his
hand is already located.''
</P>
<P>
   Triplett said the idea of installing a toe clip to help a driver
free up a hung throttle also was considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feedback we got from that was there's a point in time
where the toe clip is not effective,'' Triplett said. ``And
honestly, some drivers were comfortable with it, some weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Cup regular Jeremy Mayfield applauded the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are changes I can't see anybody disagreeing with,'' said
Mayfield, driver of the No. 12 Mobil 1 Ford Taurus. ``They don't
take anything away from the race cars. They don't affect
competition, but they can save you from a pretty hard crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it _ it's not how fast you go, it's how fast you
stop. If you have more time when you're having problems ... to
correct a little bit, then this is a good thing. Even if you hit at
a better angle, then that's got to be good, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Helton, NASCAR's senior vice president and chief operating
officer, said the sanctioning body also is studying the HANS Device
used by drivers in the open-wheel Championship Auto Racing Teams
Series. The device is a collar designed to prevent the head and
neck from snapping violently forward and backward during a crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had drivers practice and test with them,'' said Helton,
who added that any design fitted into a Cup car would need to be
different than that used in CART.
</P>
<P>
   Triplett also said NASCAR has been presented ideas for
energy-absorbing ``soft walls'' on its oval tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a lot of things we've been presented with are still just
ideas,'' Triplett said. ``They're not in place anywhere. They're
ideas on a drawing board or in a brochure. There may be something
out there, and it may be ``the'' thing. Or maybe we haven't seen it
yet.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
