<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' CURTIS, MARTINEZ WANTED TRADE
</HEADLINE>
 TRADE-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Chad Curtis has the right to demand a trade.
His intention was not to exercise that option. His present
circumstances have forced him to change his thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Both Curtis and Dave Martinez were admittedly disappointed when
the Texas Rangers didn't trade them before the non-waiver trading
deadline expired Monday. The two were platooning in right field
until the Rangers acquired Ricky Ledee from the Cleveland Indians
last week for designated hitter David Segui but now see their
playing time decreasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping that if another club could use me, I'd be
traded,'' Curtis said. ``But I know there's no guarantee going
somewhere else would have been a better situation than here.''
</P>
<P>
   He may try to find out. Curtis is signed through next season,
the final year on a three-year contract he signed with the New York
Yankees. The Rangers acquired him in the off-season and because he
was traded in the middle of a multi-year contract he has the right
to demand a trade at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   If he does and the Rangers fail to comply by spring training, he
can become a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be an option,'' Curtis said. ``When I hear a player
doing that, I look at it as them whining or complaining. I don't
want to get into that. But you look at the situation, if you're not
being used and you think you could be used somewhere else, I'd
rather explore that option.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis said, ``I'll sit on the bench for a winning team and I'll
play for a losing team. But I don't think I should be sitting on
the bench for a losing team. That's what I'll base my decision on
at the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates said Ledee will play a lot of right field.
He said Curtis will also play right field.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll both play but how much I don't know,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Said general manager Doug Melvin, ``Chad will get enough
at-bats. The DH is not going to be filled strictly by one person.
If Chad was traded somewhere else, he probably wouldn't see any
more at-bats.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Curtis is a right-handed hitter, he could spell both
Ledee and designated hitter Frank Catalanotto, who are left-handed
hitters. But Martinez is also left-handed and was playing against
right-handed pitchers. His playing time is likely to be the most
severely affected, which is why he was hoping the Rangers might
trade him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm not going to play here, I'd like to go somewhere
else,'' Martinez said. ``If I'm in the lineup, I'll just do the
best I can. If I'm not in the lineup, I know it's not because of
something I did. I think I've played pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Martinez's 15th year in the major leagues and he has
never been in postseason play. Melvin said if a contending team
wants Martinez, he won't stand in his way and a trade would likely
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see Dave's situation,'' Melvin said. ``He hasn't been in
postseason. He came over here thinking we'd be in contention and
that's when we fell off.''
</P>
<P>
   But Melvin added, ``If they're worried about Ricky Ledee, then
we've got a pretty good player.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 0155EDT &QL; 
