<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIOLES' DEALS SIGNAL BEGINNING OF REBUILDING PHASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year's Trading Frenzy Award _ a gold-plated cellphone
mounted on a marble base _ goes to the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   In four frenetic days, the Orioles traded their All-Star
shortstop, their should-have-been-an-All-Star catcher, their former
All-Star first baseman, their former All-Star left fielder, their
former All-Star designated hitter, and their closer.
</P>
<P>
   We can only assume there were no takers for Cal Ripken Jr.,
Albert Belle, Brady Anderson and Delino DeShields. Or perhaps
general manager Syd Thrift just ran out of time.
</P>
<P>
   Program sellers should be doing a brisk business at Camden Yards
today, because it truly will be difficult to recognize the players
without one.
</P>
<P>
   When the dust settled after blowing up the team, the Orioles
definitely were younger and cheaper. No longer are they the poster
boys for the overpaying, underachieving big-market teams.
</P>
<P>
   It's quite a contrast to 1996, when the Orioles set the course
for their future with a couple of trades they didn't make.
</P>
<P>
   Then-GM Pat Gillick had deals in place to trade Bobby Bonilla
and David Wells. Wells could have gone to Cleveland in a package
for pitchers Bartolo Colon and Albie Lopez and outfielder Brian
Giles.
</P>
<P>
   But owner Peter Angelos decided to make a run at the playoffs
and vetoed the trades.
</P>
<P>
   Angelos was lauded when the Orioles made it to the postseason as
the wild-card team, and they won the AL East the next season. But
failing to make the deals doomed the Orioles to mediocrity as they
got older and more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   They finished below .500 the past two years and were a badly
beaten fourth in their division when they began dealing this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Without Mike Bordick, Charles Johnson, Will Clark, B.J. Surhoff,
Harold Baines and Mike Timlin, it's only going to get worse.
</P>
<P>
   The club is prepared to take the hit for a couple of years in
hopes that the course set over the past few days eventually will
lead the Orioles back to the promised land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody is going to be able to sit up here three years from
now and say how smart they are,'' Thrift said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. It worked for the Chicago White Sox, who arrived at The
Ballpark in Arlington on Tuesday with the best record in the
American League three years after trading some of their best
players for prospects.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps not.
</P>
<P>
   Only two of the 11 minor-leaguers they traded for are considered
top prospects, although Thrift said there could be a couple of
other gems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people can only see what they see now,'' Thrift said.
``It's hard to see what somebody has done at Double-A baseball,
Triple A or the (Class A) South Atlantic League. We have to rely on
people's judgment, the scouts, and all the people who've seen them
play.''
</P>
<P>
   The quality of the prospects is only part of the equation. The
team's remaining stars could be ready to jump ship.
</P>
<P>
   The deals freed up payroll that could be used to re-sign ace
pitcher Mike Mussina, a potential free agent at the end of the
season, but Mussina doesn't appear inclined to stay after the
purge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like we were having a little too much fun and went
too far,'' Mussina said. ``If they were trying to make a point, I
think they did that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big question mark on what I want to do now. I don't
think it takes a genius to figure out they've put the club in a
position where they aren't looking to be competitive for a couple
years. So where does that leave me?''
</P>
<P>
   In a different uniform, more likely than not, meaning the
Orioles will be even worse.
</P>
<P>
   But even with Mussina and the traded veterans, they weren't
going to be World Series contenders in the next couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   The trades might not produce a White Sox-like turnaround within
three years, but they had to be made. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 0156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
