<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BURCH-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORT WORTH/DALLAS SENIOR EVENT HITS ANOTHER HAZARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someone hit the light switch.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth-Dallas area's on-again, off-again relationship
with the Senior PGA Tour appears headed to the off position after
this season.
</P>
<P>
   It might not be a permanent withdrawal, but the Senior Tour
seems destined to bypass the area for at least one year after the
final putt drops at the Bank One Senior Championship, scheduled for
Sept. 22-24 at Bent Tree Country Club in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Bank One officials have announced plans to drop their
sponsorship of the event after this season, choosing not to
exercise an option for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporately, a different set of priorities going into next
year leads us to where we are today,'' said Norm Bagwell, president
of Bank One-Dallas. ``Golf is important to us. Dallas-Fort Worth is
important to us. But this is something we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   With no replacement sponsor rushing to step in and shoulder the
primary financial burden of the $1.4 event for next season, the
smart money is that a Fort Worth-Dallas stop will be omitted from
the 2001 tour. Tour officials anticipate finalizing next year's
schedule by Aug. 15, but the process already has been delayed
because of sponsorship shuffles, and additional delays are
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Adams, Senior Tour director of public relations, said
officials are unsure about the area's future as a regular tour
stop. The one certainty is that PGA commissioner Tim Finchem wants
to maintain a Senior Tour presence in the area, in some form or
fashion. Toward that end, tour officials include Fort Worth-Dallas
on a short list of markets under consideration to join the rotation
as a host site for the Senior Tour Championship.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, that seems an appropriate choice: intermittent
tournaments for an area with an intermittent history with the
Senior Tour. A regular stop on the Senior Tour from 1985-95, the
Fort Worth-Dallas area dropped off the calendar for three years
before resurfacing with last year's Bank One event. Now, it appears
another hiatus is inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a new sponsor emerges with interest in an annual event,
don't look for a deal to be ironed out in time for the 2001 season.
And don't look for it to be held at Bent Tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in a position to make a long-term commitment,'' said
Charlie Duty, the club's general manager. ``We wanted to be
instrumental in bringing the Senior Tour back to Dallas, but to go
beyond 2001 would have been tough for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Duty said the club plans installation of an irrigation system
and major renovations of all bunkers and greens, ideally within the
next two years. The scope of the project, he said, takes Bent Tree
out of the loop as a tournament site.
</P>
<P>
   If members of the senior circuit are to continue circulating in
the area after this season, look for one of two venues to emerge:
Dallas Athletic Club or Stonebriar Country Club in Frisco.
Officials at Stonebriar have expressed interest in landing a Senior
Tour event on their resort course, which is under construction and
will be accompanied by an adjacent hotel.
</P>
<P>
   A quick read of the tea leaves suggests that a return to
Stonebriar, where Senior Tour members competed on the club's
primary course from 1989-93, might be the most viable option in the
long run. But that could leave the area without a regular stop
until 2002 or later.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes for landing a Senior Tour Championship remain viable, but
tour officials need to find someone to run the event. Members of
the Salesmanship Club, who organize the GTE Byron Nelson Classic,
recently declined the tour's request to oversee such an event in
2001 or 2002 because they preferred to focus on their annual PGA
Tour stop.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Fort Worth-Dallas in the dark about its Senior Tour
status beyond September. Tom Watson, the defending Bank One champ,
said he's optimistic someone will hit the light switch. And soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this is a very important market to the Senior
Tour,'' Watson said. ``I hope Tim (Finchem) ... will lead us to
someone to pick up where Bank One has led us. Nothing is forever. I
think we'll find another sponsor to keep an event in the area. But
I don't know who.''
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, neither does anyone else. SPOTLIGHT ON: WALRUS AT
WORK
</P>
<P>
   For the frequent flyers on the PGA Tour, a week spent competing
at home is a welcome relief. That will be the case this week for
Craig Stadler, a Denver resident who is hoping that a little home
cooking at The International event in Castle Pines, Colo., will
allow him to regain momentum and continue his trek toward a
career-best season in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Stadler, 47, was well on his way until a rib injury sidelined
him for most of May. Because the injury forced him to withdraw from
the GTE Byron Nelson Classic and MasterCard Colonial, local golf
fans did not get to witness the sleeker Stadler, who dropped 50
pounds during the off-season and shed some long-term bad habits
while rededicating himself to golf.
</P>
<P>
   But he'll be on display this week, and Stadler figures his
physical condition is the best it has been since April 30, when he
lost a playoff to Robert Allenby at the Shell Houston Open. Even
after a three-month dry spell, during which Stadler has earned only
$20,000 while rebounding from the rib injury, he stands 65th on the
tour money list, at $492,562.
</P>
<P>
   That's more than Stadler pocketed in 1999 ($454,091) or 1998
($350,091). It puts him on pace to challenge his 1991 season, when
he collected $827,628.
</P>
<P>
   Until the injury, Stadler had missed only one day of playing
golf or hitting balls this season, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't done that since I was a kid,'' said Stadler, who
credits his revamped work habits with helping him turn a mental
corner as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten away, my whole career, without working at my
game,'' said Stadler, a 12-time winner and the 1982 Masters champ.
``I was going downhill fast ... and I just got sick of the way I
was playing. So I decided I'd have a total revamp this year. I've
got three years until I turn 50 (and join the Senior Tour). More
than anything, I wanted to prove to myself that I can still compete
with these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone from 10 beers a day to 10 miles of walking a day,''
said Stadler, whose dimensions are listed at 5-foot-10, 220 pounds
in the tour media guide. ``I'm still fat as hell. But I think I'm
on the right road to recovery now.''
CHIP SHOTS CHARITY WINDFALL
</P>
<P>
   Despite plans to drop its sponsorship after September's event,
Bank One officials presented checks totaling $150,000 to two local
charities Monday. The Rising Star Program, created in 1999 to help
fund college educations for disadvantaged youths, and the Rotary
Club of Dallas received $75,000 donations.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Mayor Ron Kirk urged another corporation to step forward
as a title sponsor to keep the Senior Tour playing in his town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love golf ... I hope we can figure out a way to keep this
going in years to come,'' Kirk said. FLEISHER JOINS FIELD
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Fleisher, leading money winner on the Senior Tour
($1,837,906) and the 1999 Player of the Year, has committed to play
the Bank One event. Tournament officials have commitments from 16
of the top 20 players on last year's money list, as well as the
three most-celebrated 50-year-olds on the 2000 tour: Tom Watson,
Tom Kite and Lanny Wadkins. LOPEZ LIKES CHANGES
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Lopez, an LPGA Hall of Famer, said she is starting to reap
the benefits of recent sessions with Dave Pelz, a noted short-game
expert. The two began working together in early July, marking the
first lessons that Lopez, 43, has taken from anyone other than her
father in her career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a lot more confident on my chipping and putting than I
have in a long, long time,'' Lopez said. ``I wish I would've
approached Dave a little earlier. We've only been working together
for a couple of weeks, but I think some big changes are coming. I
think correcting my short-game problems is going to take two or
three strokes off my game. And two or three strokes every day is
going to help tremendously.'' SORENSTAM'S QUEST
</P>
<P>
   With a victory at this week's Michelob Light Classic, defending
champ Annika Sorenstam can join Laura Davies as the only LPGA
participants to win the same event in four consecutive seasons.
Sorenstam has earned four of her 23 career victories at Forest
Hills Country Club in St. Louis, Mo., including each of the past
three years.
</P>
<P>
   Davies won the Standard Register Ping event each year from
1994-97.
LPGA GOLDEN MOMENTS May 21, 1999
</P>
<P>
   Beth Daniel unleashed the most prolific birdie barrage in LPGA
Tour history at the Philips Invitational in Austin. Daniel, a Hall
of Famer, birdied nine consecutive holes at Onion Creek Country
Club (Nos. 7-15). Daniel shot a 62 during the second round, the
lowest score of her 22-year career.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps appropriately, Daniel's record-setting run came in the
same season (1999) in which she was inducted into the LPGA Hall of
Fame. Daniel, 43, has 32 victories and one major championship (1990
LPGA Championship).
TIPS FROM THE PROS
</P>
<P>
   ``During golf season, the'' Star-Telegram ``will feature
occasional tips from professional golf instructors based in Tarrant
County. Today's tip is from Amy Fox, director of instruction at
Golf Center of Fort Worth. Fox was selected as the 1999 Teaching
Professional of the Year by the LPGA and was named one of the
nation's top 50 golf instructors by'' Golf for Women ``magazine.
Fox works with several notable amateur and college players,
including former TCU All-American Angela Stanford, a member of the
2000 U.S. Curtis Cup team.'' MATCH YOUR PUTTER, PHILOSOPHY
</P>
<P>
   Too many people try to shave strokes on the green by using the
wrong putter to accompany their putting stroke. That will never
work.
</P>
<P>
   To maximize abilities on the green, a player must settle on a
putting philosophy then pick the type of putter that matches. There
are two types of putters: those who use a straight-back,
straight-through approach and those who use an arcing motion that
is based more on feel.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of amateurs prefer the straight-back, straight-through
approach because it is a repetitive motion. Those players need more
of an upright putter, where the hands are held high. A Zebra putter
and most Ping putters are good examples. So are most blade putters.
You set up with your eyes over the ball and your hands high. It's
more of an upright stance.
</P>
<P>
   Several players on the PGA Tour, including Tiger Woods and Ben
Crenshaw, use an arcing motion that is a miniature of the golf
swing. They'll set up with their eyes inside the ball, with their
hands low. It's more of a squatting stance. The lie of their putter
needs to be flatter than those using the straight-back,
straight-through approach. Usually, there is an angle from the
putter head to the shaft. A lot of the Bullseye putters are good
examples.
</P>
<P>
   In putting, there is no right or wrong method. But everyone
tends to favor one style or the other. And you need to have a
putter to match your philosophy, or you won't be holing as many
putts as possible. If you're trying to swing straight-back,
straight-through with a flat putter, it just won't work.
</P>
<P>
   If you find yourself struggling to hole putts, you might be
using the wrong type of putter.
</P>
<P>
   The secret to saving strokes on the greens is finding out what's
comfortable for you, then matching your equipment with your putting
philosophy. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
