<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SAN FRANCISCO STANDOFF
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Remember this one? Five months ago, an
11-year-old kid was home alone in the Crocker-Amazon neighborhood,
got a scary phone call, dialed 911.
</P>
<P>
   Two San Francisco police officers responded. When the family
sheepdog, Sidney, attacked the female cop, her male rookie partner
tried to shoot the dog but missed and hit the female cop
 &UR; and  &LR; the kid with the same bullet.
</P>
<P>
   Kid got three-hour operation and possible growth problems, Mom
got scolded by cops, Dad (rushing home) got tossed to ground and
handcuffed, cop got treated for bullet and bite.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a little too edgy for a Keystone Kops reel, but it has
that same zany feel.
</P>
<P>
   End of story? Nah.
</P>
<P>
   The kid, Max Castro, had the growth plate in one knee severed by
the bullet and still uses a wheelchair part of the time. The family
says it intends to sue the city for assault, battery, negligence
and intentional infliction of emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   The family asked the female cop to take a blood test, to rule
out Max being infected by the bullet he and the cop shared. The
officer allegedly nixed the request for the test, for reasons
unknown, but some weeks later said she would take the test if the
family would agree not to sue her for any distress caused by the
delay.
</P>
<P>
   Family signed an agreement, then changed lawyers and pulled back
the agreement. The cop took the blood test, but the city attorney
is refusing to hand over the results unless the family reinstates
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't the cop take the test right away to put the family at
ease? The city says she is not legally obligated to be
blood-tested, but what the heck? She was half of a police team that
was involved in the shooting of an innocent kid.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Baumgartner, deputy city attorney, says the city is
trying to help the family, pay many of the medical bills, clear
everything up, but, ``Every step seems to be met with `Give me
more,' instead of `Thank you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Says Baumgartner, ``All she (the cop) is saying is, `Don't sue
me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But if the family has a legit lawsuit, why should it give up the
right to file? If the distress part of the suit is as bogus as the
city attorney's office insists it is, it will be tossed out in a
jiff.
</P>
<P>
   What we have is a San Francisco standoff. Meanwhile, Max
undergoes blood tests every month.
</P>
<P>
   The city attorney office's hints that perhaps the family is
being a bit opportunistic gets a rise out of Angela Alioto,
attorney for Max and the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't normally call 911 and get shot by a police
officer,'' Alioto notes.
</P>
<P>
   Sidney is doing fine.
</P>
<P>
   HAPPY HOUR: Dave Heventhal and his wife were walking along
Stinson Beach in front of the gated Seadrift community when they
came upon a Norman Rockwell scene, a youngster with a lemonade
stand.
</P>
<P>
   The crayoned sign read ``25 cents,'' and in larger letters,
``Add $2 for Kettle One with lemonade.''
</P>
<P>
   Kettle One is a yuppie-favored imported vodka. Brings out the
flavor of the lemonade.
</P>
<P>
   EYES ON THE blink, Lotta Dotz went in for a repair.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Lotta's HMO, the operation to replace the lens of one
eye cost a total of $10.
</P>
<P>
   Recuperating at the Beverly Wilshire Hotel in Bev Hills, Lotta
ordered a hot dog. It was $9.
</P>
<P>
   That's today's financial news: A gourmet hot dog is still
cheaper than a new eye. Unless you tip for the dog.
</P>
<P>
   LUCKY BOY, the artist featured here Monday for his unique relief
maps of San Francisco, now has people clamoring for his work. The
clamorers must have patience.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky makes maps large and small, in chocolate and on Frisbees,
but he isn't really set up for a retail blitz. However, if you want
more info, e-mail him at
 &UR; Nowadayssanfrancisco &LR; yahoo.com,  &LR; and eventually he'll get back to
you.
</P>
<P>
   MR. EAT urges you to eat well. He recommends a good place called
Nirvana, on Castro between 18th and 19th.
</P>
<P>
   For under $10 you get Thai noodles with chicken and a drink _ an
alcoholic mixed drink. A double, yet.
</P>
<P>
   If you're in a hurry, say, ``Gimme a double order of the noodles
and chicken, hold the noodles and chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   NOW THAT legendary bartender Mike McCourt has moved his ice and
olives to the Buchanan Grill in the Marina, the regulars there are
looking forward to playing McCourt's overs-unders obits game.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy. You place your bet (in pretend money, of course) on
whether you think there will be more than 22 or fewer than 22 death
notices on The Chronicle's obituary page the next day.
</P>
<P>
   If you lose, but one of the obits is yours, your bet is
refunded.
</P>
</TEXT>
