A0244 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-FORD-1STLD-WRITET     08-02 0347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-FORD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting; adds byline)  
 By MATTHEWE PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ _ Former President Gerald Ford was taken to a
hospital around midnight Tuesday with a sinus infection, after
leaving the Republican National Convention, where he had been
honored in an emotional tribute.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, 87, was driven by his staff to the Hahnemann University
Hospital, where he was treated with an antibotic. His spokesman,
Calvin G. McDowell, said a wax build-up led to an infection. ``He's
fine,'' McDowell said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, walking on his own, left the hospital at 1:36 a.m. on
Wednesday along with his wife, Betty. ``I feel good, that's why I'm
here,'' Ford said as he climbed into his car.
</P>
<P>
   Ford appeared frail as he sat in a VIP box at the back of the
First Union Center on Tuesday night along with his wife, former
President George Bush and his wife, Barbara, and other prominent
Republicans. He was visibly moved when a video-taped tribute to him
was displayed on the large screens inside the hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``When uncertainty troubled our nation, President Gerald Ford
renewed America's confidence,'' Gov. George Pataki of New York
said, introducing the tribute. ``His strength, his strength and
integrity defended our values at home in an ever-changing world.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd cheered when Pataki invoked ``President Ford's steady
leadership and Mrs. Ford's gentle grace.''
</P>
<P>
   He rose and waved to acknowledge the cheers of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ford did not address the convention, he told C-Span
that this would be the last convention he and his wife would
attend, calling it a ``concluding appearance to indicate our
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his health in an interview broadcast Tuesday night
on ``Larry King Live,'' the former president said, ``I couldn't be
healthier.''
</P>
<P>
   McDowell, a spokesman for Ford, said Ford had been complaining
about feeling ``uncomfortable'' and asked to be taken to the
hospital. While he was at the hospital, he was visited by Andrew
Card, the convention chairman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 0202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
