<HEADER>
A0246 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-GOP-CONVENTION-SFCHRO     08-02 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CONVENTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MCCAIN SALUTES FORMER FOE  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI and MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ In an eloquent tribute aimed at burying a bitter
rivalry, Arizona Sen. John McCain delivered a full-throated
endorsement Tuesday night of George W. Bush as a man who would not
``squander this moment in history.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who represented the only major obstacle to Bush's drive
for the GOP nomination, dismissed himself as merely ``a distant
runner-up'' before a crowd firmly committed to the Texas governor
at the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support him. I am grateful to him. And I am proud of him,''
said McCain, insisting that Bush is the best choice to restore the
nation's military strength. ``I am proud to do so, for I know that
by supporting George W. Bush, I serve my country well.''
</P>
<P>
   He then touted the credentials of the man he once belittled for
his lack of foreign policy experience and labeled as unelectable
against Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the stage to the theme from ``Star Wars,'' McCain _ who
once compared himself in his fight against Bush to Luke Skywalker _
portrayed Bush as a man who could keep the nation strong while
inspiring America to new heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``America's greatness is a quest without end,'' said McCain. ``I
have faith. I have faith in you ... and I am haunted by the vision
of what will be.''
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic speech closed out the second night of the
Republican National Convention dedicated to honoring war heroes and
America's military might. Without ever mentioning President Clinton
or Vice President Al Gore by name, speaker after speaker said the
nation's reputation on the world stage depends on Bush's election.
</P>
<P>
   The otherwise tightly controlled display of GOP unity was marred
only when Arizona Rep. Jim Kolbe took the stage to deliver a speech
on free trade. Many Texas delegates bowed their heads in prayer
when Kolbe, who is openly gay, began talking. Kolbe's speech had
been hailed by gay Log Cabin Republicans as a sign that Bush
advocates a more inclusive party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of America does not agree with the message (of) that
lifestyle,'' said Texas delegate Cathie Adams. ``Our children and
grandchildren are watching.''
</P>
<P>
   But the moment did little to upstage the evening's festivities,
which included speeches from a four-star general, two war heroes
and a Cold War expert.
</P>
<P>
   General H. Norman Schwarzkopf, commander of Operation Desert
Storm, former Sen. Bob Dole, Elizabeth Dole and Condoleezza Rice, a
former Stanford University provost and current Bush foreign policy
adviser, all preceded McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates also watched video tributes to three living GOP
presidents, Gerald Ford, George Bush and Ronald Reagan. Two of them
looked on in the hall _ Ford and his wife, Betty, and Bush and his
wife, Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Reagan, who flew from California to represent her
critically ill husband, received a warm acknowledgment from the
delegates. In a reminder of the depth of affection for the former
president, now 89 and ill with Alzheimer's disease, she also
received what may have been the night's biggest applause line when
a video tribute replayed his famous entreaty in Berlin: ``Mr.
Gorbachev, take down this wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday evening's session began, demonstrators clashed
violently with police, tying up the heart of downtown Philadelphia.
At least 280 people were arrested as confrontations continued into
the night.
</P>
<P>
   The protests were far from the arena where the convention is
being held, and other than creating traffic tie-ups that delayed
some delegates from arriving on the convention floor, they appeared
to have little impact on the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the hall, McCain, who has been grabbing headlines and
front page photos all week, had to walk a delicate political
tightrope: He needed to make a strong case for Bush _ but not so
strong as to upstage him.
</P>
<P>
   McCain barely touched on the themes of campaign finance and
political independence that galvanized his followers and made him a
thorn in the side to Bush. Instead, the former Vietnam POW appealed
to American patriotism, saying that  &LR; the nation has ``a grander
purpose`' than mere politics.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of MAIN02 (105483 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``We are part of something providential, a great experiment to
prove to the world that democracy is not only the most effective
form of government, but the only moral government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get riled up a bit, and stand up for the values
that made America great,'' McCain said to a standing ovation.
``Americans, enter the public life of your country determined to
tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   George Bush, the nation's 41st president, also offered a video
endorsement of his son's credentials in foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think George's record can stand all the scrutiny in the
world,'' the former president said. ``I think it will show a man of
honor, a man of integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole, a World War II veteran and the party's failed 1996
presidential candidate, joined those extolling Bush's virtues, as
did his wife, Elizabeth, who was once  &LR; had challenged Bush for the
GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   And Gov. Bush himself, campaigning in Gettysburg, Pa., greeted
delegates by video and introduced Rice, his foreign policy adviser,
as ``my dear friend,'' an accomplished concert pianist and figure
skater.
</P>
<P>
   She called Bush ``a nominee who knows the power of truth and
honor. We have a nominee who will be the next great president of
the United States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice said both Bush and his vice presidential nominee Dick
Cheney understand that foreign policy ``all begins with integrity
in the Oval Office. ... Friend and foe will know he keeps his word,
and tells the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   And she said Bush would lead a nation that would ``exercise
power without fanfare and arrogance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
