<P>
   SCI-GLOBAL-WARMING (Undated) _ Preparing for a new round of
negotiations over how to reduce levels of heat-trapping greenhouse
gases that may be warming the climate, the United States has taken
the stance that using forests and farmer's fields to sop up carbon
dioxide, the chief warming gas, is just as important as cutting
emissions from smoke stacks and tail pipes. The position was stated
in documents filed before a deadline with a U.N. office that is
overseeing talks aimed at implementing the 1997 Kyoto Protocol, an
international agreement among industrialized nations aimed at
averting any dangerous climate warming. By Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   RESEARCH-EARNINGS (New York) _ Columbia University's eagerness
to join forces with a start-up Internet venture reflects a
significant shift in an academic culture that once saw itself
driven only by intellectual curiosity and far removed from
commerce. While the change is occurring throughout the academic
world, few universities have moved to try to cash in as
aggressively as Columbia, which has a research capacity similar to
that of Harvard and Yale but without their endowments. By Karen W.
Arenson.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ABUSE-STRESS (Undated) _ A new study finds that women who
were sexually abused as children show abnormal physiological
response to stress as adults. By Erica Goode.
