<HEADER>
A0250 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-DAVIS-MONEY-SFCHRON &LR;      08-02 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-MONEY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GOP FUNDING SOURCES TAPPED BY DAVIS  &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL and GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Gov. Gray Davis raked in $8.1 million in the first
six months of the year by tapping traditional GOP sources of money,
including at least $370,000 from the insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   Oil companies, health care providers and Indian tribes that
operate casinos also represented a hefty chunk of the governor's
windfall, which now totals $21.4 million received since he took
office.
</P>
<P>
   The figures are contained in financial disclosure documents that
had to be filed by Monday with state election officials in
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems (Davis) cares about the interests of business, so
business cares about the interests of the governor,'' said Barry
Carmody, president of the the Association of California Insurance
Companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is the most conservative Democrat in the process.
If a governor says, `I'm going to try to do what's right for
California economically,' he'll get business support,'' Carmody
said. ``And so far, that's been his moves.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Davis is a tenacious fund-raiser, traditional GOP
contributors _ oil companies, health insurers, utilities _ also
know actions by the Davis administration can sharply impact their
bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   And contributing to his campaign coffers appears to get Davis'
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for example, three days after attending a fund-raiser
hosted by the health care industry, Davis asked lawmakers to slow
down the progress of bills increasing state regulation of the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Davis denied any connection between the two events.
</P>
<P>
   It's the appearance of pay-to-play that bothers political
observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only difference between campaign contributions and
outright bribery is pretension,'' said Robert Fellmeth, a law
professor at the University of San Diego. ``Campaign contributions
get access, and access gets results. Anybody who denies that is
lying.''
</P>
<P>
   But Davis' chief political adviser, Garry South, has said Davis
needs to raise significant amounts of money to be prepared for a
wealthy opponent in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Davis took in large sums from several high-profile industries,
including insurance companies and Indian tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the top Indian tribe contributors include the Rumsey
Rancheria, which gave $50,000, the Morongo Band, which donated
$35,000, and the Cabazon Band of Mission Indians, which gave
$50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also listed as a nonmonetary contribution, $3,490 for the
use of the Cabazon Band's airplane.
</P>
<P>
   At $125,000, Fireman's Fund insurance in Novato was third on
Davis' list of top 10 contributors for the first six months of
2000.
</P>
<P>
   But other insurers kicked in. Zenith Insurance gave $75,000.
Progressive Insurance gave $30,000. Farmers Insurance Group of
Companies cq  &LR; came in at $40,000. Contributing $35,000 was 21st
Century Insurance Group.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also tapped Silicon Valley companies and executives.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Corp. gave $10,000, while Intuit donated $25,000. Steve
Westly, a manager at eBay, gave $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett Packard gave $25,000. John T. Chambers, CEO of Cisco,
gave Davis $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Davis' top 10 list was Chevron at $120,000. It was one
of the largest contributors to Dan Lungren, Davis' GOP opponent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Health insurers _ who are now subject to regulation by a new
Department of Managed Care created by Davis _ were generous givers.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross gave $30,000. Blue Shield contributed $21,000. The
California Healthcare Association kicked in $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   The California Medical Association, which represents doctors and
often battles health insurers, contributed $50,000 to Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Another of Davis' larger contributors is the California Trucking
Association, at $75,000. One of the association's chief concerns
are air-quality decisions by the state Air Resources Board, whose
members Davis appoints.
</P>
<P>
   Among individual contributors are several of Davis appointees,
including former Rep. Doug Bosco, whom Davis placed on the state
Industrial Welfare Commission. Bosco gave $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   So did Sherry Lansing, president of Paramount Studios. Davis
named her a University of California regent.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Westwood One, Norman Pattiz, who is hosting an
exclusive party for Gray &LR; Davis and selected members of the media
before the Democratic convention in Los Angeles, donated $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' two biggest individual donors last year did not close
their wallets this year.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Perenchio, the billionaire owner of Univision, the
nation's largest Spanish-language television network, gave Davis
$250,000. He contributed the same amount last year.
</P>
<P>
   David Shimmon increased his contribution to $225,000 _ up from
$200,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Shimmon is a multimillionaire from Los Altos and president of a
subsidiary of U.S. Filters, a Palm Desert firm that is a major
player in California water issues and a large landowner in Imperial
County.
</P>
<P>
   Familiar names also popped up on Davis' list of contributors,
including all three owners of DreamWorks, SKG.: Steven Spielberg,
David Geffen and Jeffrey Katzenberg. Each gave $8,333.
</P>
<P>
   Davis received money from other major Hollywood studios: $50,000
from the Walt Disney Co.; $25,000 from Warner Bros. PAC; $10,000
from Universal Studios; and $5,000 from Paramount Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Riordan, the mayor of Los Angeles, gave $12,500, while
the Robert Mondavi Winery gave $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Zappa, the widow of Frank Zappa, donated $5,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
