<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0251 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-GOP-HIGHROAD-SFCHRON(     08-02 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-HIGHROAD-SFCHRON(ANALYSIS) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: REPUBLICANS TAKE THE HIGH ROAD IN NOT MENTIONING 
 CLINTON, GORE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  PHILADELPHIA _ From the fiery speeches at the podium to the
interviews on the arena floor, two favorite Republican topics are
conspicuously missing from the GOP convention: Bill Clinton and Al
Gore.
<P>
   Never mind that the White House's current occupant has been the
bane of the GOP's existence for nearly eight years, and that his
chosen successor is all that stands in the way of electing a
Republican president.
</P>
<P>
   After two days and nearly 10 hours of speeches, the words
``Clinton'' and ``Gore'' have hardly been uttered at the dais.
Republicans are determined to keep their message upbeat, and if
that means forgoing the traditional skewering of their rivals, so
be it.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of the nation's disgust with what Elizabeth Dole last
night described as ``smash-mouth politics,'' Republicans hope that
if they remain positive and simply ignore the Democrats, Americans
will appreciate the difference between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're not going to do is engage in the bitter, partisan
attacks that have larded our political process the last eight
years,'' insisted Ed Gillespie, the GOP convention's program
director.
</P>
<P>
   Like his selection of Dick Cheney as a running mate, which is
expected to provide little apparent electoral advantage, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush is determined to demonstrate that not every decision
is based on a political calculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are led right now by a different kind of Republican,'' said
Don Evans, Bush's campaign chairman, repeating a message he hopes
every convention viewer will pick up on &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Bush himself appeared to have trouble abiding by the discipline
displayed by his surrogates. After Clinton belittled his philosophy
of compassionate conservatism Monday night as nothing more than a
``pretty package,'' Bush shot back Tuesday with some of his
toughest language to date, describing Clinton as ``so desperate to
have his legacy intact by getting Al Gore elected that he'll say
anything, just like Al Gore will.''
</P>
<P>
   But inside the convention hall, even veterans of slash-and-burn
politics held their tongues. The once-cantankerous Bob Dole spared
Clinton and Gore the wrath of his wit, joking that 97-year-old Sen.
Strom Thurmond of South Carolina took him to Philadelphia's
Constitution Hall ``and showed me where he first met Ben
Franklin.''
</P>
<P>
   The practice of insulting the other party is a convention
tradition at least as rich as bunting and balloons. In 1988,
then-Gov. Ann Richards of Texas lampooned Bush's father for having
been born with ``a silver foot in his mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago at the GOP convention in San Diego, New York Rep.
Susan Molinari railed against Clinton's credibility in a keynote
address. ``Americans know that Bill Clinton's promises have the
life span of a Big Mac on Air Force One,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always a saturation point,'' Republican Sen. Orrin
Hatch of Utah said afterward. ``But I don't think we've reached
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, there has been no appetite for prolonged
criticism, let alone off-color jokes, about regarding  &LR; the
Democratic agenda, Clinton's libido or Gore's service to the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are fed up with it,'' Gillespie said. ``They want to
know what you're for.''
</P>
<P>
   But the strategy also risks alienating the party faithful. There
is a reason for attacks. They galvanize the base and help
crystallize the differences between candidates and parties.
</P>
<P>
   And their absence provides an opening to the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no better politician on Earth than President Clinton.
Attacking him allows him to respond, and they're afraid of that,''
said Bob Mulholland, a consultant to the California Democratic
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans seem to accept the softer tone as a wise political
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (the convention) is playing out just like they want it
to,'' Christian Coalition founder Pat Robertson said resignedly.
</P>
<P>
   Does he worry that the party is straying from its conservative
roots?
</P>
<P>
   ``Evangelical and social Christians trust George W. Bush,''
Robertson said. ``They are sophisticated enough to understand that
he's trying to win an election, and they're willing to give him a
little wiggle room here.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi, who has
engaged in his share of Clinton-Gore bashing in the past, showed
restraint when asked what sort of lawmaker Gore was when they
served together in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's no Dick Cheney,'' Lott said, before catching himself. The
convention, he quickly added, ``is about our people. It's not about
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides said the tone is the direct result of the governor's
requests and that it will be carried through tomorrow night, when
Bush delivers his acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's tone will be very positive and upbeat,'' said
Ari Fleischer, a Bush spokesman. ``He will be respectful and
polite.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the candidate, the other Republican who appears closest
to crossing that line is President Bush, his father, who was asked
on television Tuesday to respond to Clinton's recent taunts about
his son's ability to be president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm tempted to get off the reservation,'' the elder Bush
told a reporter. ``I'm gonna wait a month. Then, you give me a
call. I'll give you the home number. If he continues that, then I'm
gonna tell the nation what I think of him as a human being, and a
person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 0219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
