<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 08:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0282 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-VICENTE-FOX-AZR &LR;      08-02 1629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VICENTE-FOX-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-VICENTE-FOX-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    CHARISMATIC FOX CHANGES NATURE OF MEXICAN POLITICS(a) 
 &HT;    (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED THIS.
 &HT;    MOVING IN ``A'' AND ``K'' CATEGORIES)(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By JERRY KAMMER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A peaceful revolution rumbled across Mexico on July 2, driven by
a charismatic reformer, a Mexican original who somehow combines the
cowboy self-confidence of a John Wayne with the Latin man-from-the
country earnestness of a Juan Valdez.
</P>
<P>
   With his thundering victory at the ballot box, Vicente Fox
Quesada , who will take office Dec. 1, defied not only six months
of political polls that had shown him in a tight race with the
candidate of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party. He also
broke the spell of seven decades of Mexican history that had seen
the party dominate the political and psychological landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Peruvian writer Mario Vargas Llosa said the PRI had erected
``the perfect dictatorship.'' Until Fox's stunning victory, power
was handed down by presidents who named their successors. an
imperial gesture that made elections empty rituals. Party boss and
labor leader Fidel Velasquez once said that the PRI was so strong
that only bullets could drive it from Los Pinos, the Mexican White
House.
</P>
<P>
   After a night of celebration in town squares across the country,
Mexico awoke July 3 to a new political era. The Fox landslide had
broken the PRI spell. Almost giddy with delight, many are calling
the election their equivalent of the fall of the Berlin Wall or the
storming of the Bastille in revolutionary France.
</P>
<P>
   ``By making that old and corrupt system of power recognize for
the first time the triumph of an opposition presidential candidate,
we have achieved not just a new government but something much more
important,'' proclaimed historian Lorenzo Meyer. ``We have
accomplished a change in the very nature of our politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was fundamentally the singular achievement of a
remarkable man in black cowboy boots. Vicente Fox captured the
hearts and votes of his countrymen by making himself the defiant
champion of change in a country that was primed to repudiate the
PRI. With his relentless determination and unshakable confidence,
he inspired Mexicans to imagine what many had thought was
inconceivable: life without the PRI in the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's triumph, on his 58th birthday, culminated a long political
journey that was propelled by his father's appetite for hard work,
his spirit of social engagement instilled by the Jesuits, his
growing fury with PRI arrogance and corruption and his powerful
sense of destiny as an agent of change.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, the grandson of an Irish-American from Ohio, was born in
1942, the second of nine children in a family that owned a ranch
and farm in the central Mexican state of Guanajato. He recalls his
father as an intense, joyful man with a determined appetite for
work. ``It didn't matter what time the party ended, at 6 o'clock in
the morning - in the days before Alka-Seltzer - he was up and
working.'' Fox wrote in his autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   After completing his studies at the Jesuit-operated Universidad
Iberoamericana in Mexico City, Fox began work in 1964 for
Coca-Cola. He advanced steadily from his earliest days as a route
driver, becoming the company's marketing director in Mexico and
ultimately the head of its operations in that country. Coke sent
him to Harvard for a graduate education in business.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox always felt himself drawn to a life of social
engagement. When he was not helping Coke overtake Pepsi as the top
seller of soft drinks in Mexico, he was helping found
rehabilitation centers for alcoholics and addicts. He and his
then-wife, who adopted their four children, would later help to
found an orphanage.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a big company like Coca-Cola, there isn't much that one can
accomplish in terms of personal satisfaction,'' Fox said. In 1974,
at a college reunion, one of the Jesuits who taught at the
university fortified Fox's resolve to leave Coca-Cola. The Rev.
Xavier Scheifler stunned the group when he angrily chastised them
for ignoring social responsibilities in their quest for individual
gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an experience that solidified my conviction that I
should work with others, for others,'' Fox wrote. Five years later,
he turned down a promotion that would have made him Coke's top man
for all of Latin America. He decided to return home to the state of
Guanajuato, where his family was branching out from farming into
pigs, stables and cowboy boots.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for boots exploded after John Travolta's
(beginitalic)Urban Cowboy(enditalic) movie made Western fashion a
fad across the United States. But after bringing the Fox craftsmen
a brief flood of orders from around the world, the boom quickly
faded, leaving them stuck with merchandise they couldn't sell. Fox
recalls that the downturn cost the family about $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The upheaval that Travolta brought to the Fox family was nothing
compared to the influence of a brashly self-confident vegetable
farmer from the state of Sinaloa who in 1988 ran for the presidency
under the banner of the conservative National Action Party, or PAN.
Big, bearded and blunt, he was Manuel Clouthier, one of the
so-called broncos who were determined to buck the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   This was a time of seismic rumblings in the political terrain, a
shaking that would eventually produce the Fox earthquake of 2000.
The Mexico City newspaper (beginitalic)El
(enditalic)(beginitalic)Universal (enditalic)was reporting on a
``democratic awakening'' to challenge the political order. Octavio
Paz, the writer and intellectual and unofficial conscience of
Mexico, declared that the country had begun ``a gradual,
irreversible change toward modern democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The most determined revolt against the PRI was under way in
Chihuahua, where furious Panistas had begun taking to the streets
in 1986 to protest a massive PRI steal-the-vote campaign that had
hijacked the governor's election. They seized bridges connecting
Juarez to El Paso, drawing international attention as they mocked
the PRI's claim to have won through elections that were ``clean and
transparent.''
</P>
<P>
   Clouthier became the passionate leader of Mexican outrage. With
a bold fury that astonished Mexico, he denounced the PRI and
proclaimed his determination to ``return national sovereignty to
where it must reside, in the people themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the fresh troops whom Clouthier summoned to political
battle was Vicente Fox, who recalls a call he received from the big
Sinaloan, urging that Fox get involved politically.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `Listen, Fox, we're always complaining about the
system, about the dishonesty, the corruption,''' Fox recalls, ``But
we don't do anything to change it. Let's do it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clouthier, who died in a 1989 traffic wreck that his family
believes was a PRI-sponsored assassination, became Fox's political
patron. Clouthier inspired Fox to undertake a 1988 run for the
Chamber of Deputies, the lower house of the federal legislature.
One of Fox's first acts there was to ridicule as fraudulent the
election of President Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
</P>
<P>
   Fox took two allegedly bogus ballots, rolled them into cones,
then taped them to the sides of his head in mockery of Salinas'
oversized ears. Then, acting as if he was Salinas, he offered an
explanation of the electoral trickery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've felt obligated to ask many of my friends to set aside
moral scruples to help me achieve this victory, which I had to do
because Mexico isn't ready for democracy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's show reportedly infuriated Salinas and likely sparked the
all-out PRI effort to challenge Fox in his 1991 bid to become
governor of Guanajuato. When the PRI-dominated electoral commission
reported a PRI victory, Fox led thousands of supporters into the
streets and offered evidence of well-practiced PRI tactics of
ballot box stuffing and voter intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This government is a criminal organization that used Mafia
tactics of electoral engineering,'' Fox said in a thundering voice.
``They bought votes; they threatened to throw people out of their
jobs if they didn't vote for the official party. They told taxi
drivers they would lose their licenses. They annulled our votes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fox-led protests threw the state into turmoil and forced
Salinas to ask his machine candidate to resign. But rather than
concede to Fox, Salinas arranged for the PRI-dominated state
legislature to appoint another Panista as governor. Fox would run
again three years later and win an overwhelming victory.
</P>
<P>
   He was, by all accounts, a successful governor, who attacked
unemployment by promoting business development and attracting
investment. He also showed a spirit of inclusiveness and
reconciliation by naming a PRI member to be the state's minister of
finance.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is, above all, a pragmatist. He avoids being backed into
ideological corners and works to build consensus. On the evening of
July 2, when it had become clear that he would be Mexico's next
president, he made a magnanimous statement, promising that his
administration would be ``inclusive and pluralistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox remains the crusading idealist. He has vowed to take on
corrupt cops and judges, to build the economy from the bottom up by
providing loans to small businesses that have long been denied bank
credits. He vows that he will appoint ministers because of their
competence rather than their political capital
</P>
<P>
   Said Adolfo Aguilar Zinser, one of the Mexican liberals who
rallied to Fox's banner, ``He is going to breathe new life into a
country that for too long was politically demoralized by the PRI.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 0805EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 08:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0283 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-VICENTE-FOX-AZR &LR;      08-02 1629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VICENTE-FOX-AZR </SLUG>
  
