A0289 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MEDIGAP-AZR &LR;      08-02 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIGAP-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-MEDIGAP02-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    MEDIGAP POLICIES WON'T BE CHEAP(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By DELLA DE LAFUENTE(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona seniors dropped by Medicare HMOs in 2001 can expect to
pay higher premiums for supplemental insurance, or Medigap,
policies to cover prescription drugs than in the Midwest,
California, Colorado and Texas, but lower rates than seniors in
Florida and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Seniors typically buy Medigap insurance to help pay for health
services and prescription medications not covered by traditional
Medicare. About 13,000 rural Arizona seniors will be forced to
shift to traditional Medicare when Medicare HMOs leave Cochise,
Gila and Pima counties and most of Pinal County next year.
</P>
<P>
   But the cost of Medigap plans that provide a much sought-after
prescription drug benefit may push some seniors with fixed incomes
into financial distress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some seniors will have to choose between buying their
prescriptions, paying bills or do they eat,'' said Martha Taylor,
coordinator of the State Health Insurance Assistance Program, which
provides counseling and information for seniors on Medicare and
supplemental insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 standard Medicare supplemental insurance policies
offered by health insurers nationally, known as Plans A through J,
Arizonans pay the most for Plans H and I, starting at $1,644 and
$1,896 per year, respectively, with the most expensive plans
costing $9,681.52 and $8,619.75, respectively. Ten insurers sell
Plan H in Arizona; about half require seniors to belong to a group
plan.
</P>
<P>
   On average, Arizona seniors pay the highest premiums for seven
of the 10 Medigap plans, consistently ranking among the costliest
states, says the study of 38,000 premium quotes from 113 insurers
in 45 states.
</P>
<P>
   Data on annual premiums were collected from insurers for
(beginitalic)The Arizona Republic (enditalic)by Weiss Ratings, a
Florida-based insurance rating firm. Premium rate quotes are
average annual premiums for a 65-year-old man, the age at which
insurers are required to extend coverage, regardless of a person's
health status. (For people under 65 and those 66 &QC;  and older,
insurers are allowed to ask medically related questions and may
choose not to underwrite based on the answers provided.)
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Arizonans pay lower premiums than seniors living in
Florida and New York, the study showed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's counterintuitive to think that places like Phoenix and
southern Florida would have higher rates than larger metropolitan
areas with higher costs of living,'' said Melissa Gannon, a vice
president of Weiss Ratings. ``The risk should be less when there's
a high concentration of seniors, but it isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers and insurers say the price disparity between
Phoenix and other metropolitan areas is largely the result of costs
incurred for increased hospitalization and prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers are living longer, older and using their health
benefits,'' said Regena Frieden, a spokeswoman for Blue Cross and
Blue Shield of Arizona, which has 23,281 Arizona seniors enrolled
in two Medicare supplemental coverage plans.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,400 Arizona seniors in the Blue's Medigap plans are 90
or older and 43 members are 100 or older.
</P>
<P>
   At least one insurer, UnitedHealth Group, isn't seeing the price
disparity, says Bob Hussey, vice president of communications for
the insurer's AARP division in Minnesota. UnitedHealth provides
Medigap coverage to 40,000 AARP members in Arizona through its
community-rated plans, for which it charges the same premium
regardless of age.
</P>
<P>
   UnitedHealth's premium costs in Arizona are lower than its
premiums in other states, Hussey said.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare's 10 supplemental policies, or Medigap plans, were
created in 1992 by Congress to cover the costs of health care
services not reimbursed by Medicare. Benefits offered through each
of the 10 plans range from the basic, no-frills Plan A, which
covers hospitalization for an annual premium of $433.44, to the
high-end and very costly Plan J. The least expensive version of
Plan J includes a $1,500 deductible, a separate $250 deductible for
prescription drugs and a $250 deductible for medical emergencies
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the attempt by lawmakers to create standard plans with
uniform benefits that are similarly priced, costs to seniors vary
widely depending on the policy, insurer and where the seniors
reside, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, of the state health insurance program, advises seniors
to shop around, compare premiums and consider an insurer's
financial health as well as premium costs. Given the rates charged
for plans that include prescription benefits, Taylor says seniors
concerned about costs might rethink investing in supplemental
coverage since the high premiums, $250 deductible and $1,250 cap on
drug expenses for Plans H and I and $3,000 drug cap on Plan J could
be better spent buying medications out-of-pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Reach the reporter at della.delafuente(a)arizona &QL;
</P>
<P>
   republic.com or (602) 444-8953.
</P>
</TEXT>
