<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBS02-AZR </SLUG>
  
With two growth-related initiatives on the November ballot, KAET-TV
has decided this is the wrong time to show a new documentary about
urban sprawl.Channel 8 won't air &HT;    growth documentary
 &HT;    BC-PBS02-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    CHANNEL 8 WON'T AIR GROWTH DOCUMENTARY(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By KATHLEEN INGLEY(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With two growth-related initiatives on the November ballot,
KAET-TV (Channel 8) has decided this is the wrong time to show a
new documentary about urban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)Subdivide and Conquer(enditalic), narrated by actor
Dennis Weaver, paints a bleak picture of housing developments
devouring the vast spaces of the West, with Phoenix as a prime
example.
</P>
<P>
   Stations around the country have aired or scheduled the film.
But KAET Program Director Joe Campbell said it takes too strong a
point of view to air in the months before the Nov.7 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't feel that the issues that were raised within the
documentary were discussed in a well-rounded enough way,'' Campbell
said.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary's producer, Jeff Gersh, argues that his hourlong
film is well-balanced and that now is just the right time to show
it.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, Gersh said, isn't to assign blame for urban woes but
to ``raise people's expectations about what's possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 0812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 08:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0291 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-PBSSIDE-AZR &LR;      08-02 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBSSIDE-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-PBSSIDE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    KAET DEFENDS DECISION WHILE ACTIVIST OUTRAGED(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By KATHLEEN INGLEY(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A KAET-TV (Channel 8) official says Valley viewers won't be
shortchanged by his decision not to run (beginitalic)Subdivide and
Conquer(enditalic), a documentary about urban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many other things we've done on this issue
locally,'' said Joe Campbell, program director for the public
television station.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)Horizon, (enditalic)KAET's weekday public-affairs
talk show, has covered the debate over how to manage Arizona's
explosive growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done polls; we've interviewed all the mayors in the
Valley,'' Campbell said. ``We've done stories - about state trust
land, about Growing Smarter (Gov. Jane Hull's growth-management
plan) - that really are germane and specific to what's happening
here in Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)Subdivide and Conquer(enditalic) fails to show all
sides of the issue, Campbell said, a particular drawback when
voters will consider two growth-related propositions on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Producer Jeff Gersh, however, figured this would be one place
that would jump at the broadcast. ``For goodness' sake, Phoenix is
in the film,'' Gersh said. ``That's what's especially odd to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters are smart people, and they make their own decisions. We
don't need the media to censor information.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Bahr of the Sierra Club argues that (beginitalic)Subdivide
and Conquer(enditalic) presents a varied view of growth woes. And,
she points out, it features interviews with Scottsdale architect
Vernon Swaback, who has worked with major developers, and sports
baron Jerry Colangelo, who ``could hardly be described as a
cactus-hugger.''
</P>
<P>
   The documentary's proposed solutions, though, are not without
controversy: setting growth boundaries, allowing more flexible
zoning, refocusing development on downtowns and creating more open
space.
</P>
<P>
   And those are among the hottest debating points in the two
initiatives:
</P>
<P>
   The Citizens Growth Management Initiative, backed by the Sierra
Club, would require cities and counties to draw growth boundaries.
Opponents warn that it's a recipe for high home prices.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 100, part of Growing Smarter, would preserve up to 3
percent of state trust land from development. Foes criticize it as
far too limited.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell previewed (beginitalic)Subdivide and Conquer(enditalic)
more than two months ago, and he said he looked for a program that
would express a pro-development point of view, to air as a
counterbalance, but wasn't able find one.
</P>
<P>
   He said scheduling decisions are made independently at KAET,
which is run under the wing of Arizona State University. ``I've
been here 51/2 years,'' Campbell said, ``and I've never felt any
pressure from donors, university administrators or the state
Legislature, one way or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Named best environmental film at the 1999 Telluride Mountain
Film Festival, (beginitalic)Subdivide and Conquer (enditalic)is
among dozens of productions offered to public television stations
through several large distributors.
</P>
<P>
   The National Educational Telecommunications Association, which
distributed the documentary, surveyed major stations in May and
found 24 out of 50 had scheduled it for broadcast and five had
recorded it for possible use. Los Angeles station KLCS has
broadcast it several times.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Lugo, a publicist who handled the documentary, said the
only lack of interest she encountered was from stations in the
Northeast and South that were put off by the film's focus on the
West.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club helped sponsor a screening of
(beginitalic)Subdivide and Conquer(enditalic) in Phoenix and in
Tucson last week.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix activist Richard Corton was among those who attended,
and he called KAET's decision ``outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it presented a balanced approach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To Gersh, ``The question comes to mind: Which public is public
TV thinking about? Whose public television is it? Do they have a
particular public in mind?''
</P>
<P>
   Reach the reporter at kathleen.ingley(a)arizona &QL;
</P>
<P>
   republic.com or (602) 444-8171.
</P>
</TEXT>
