<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOPTV-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-GOPTV-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    TIGHT SCRIPT GIVES VIEWERS LITTLE TO GET EXCITED ABOUT(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL GOODYKOONTZ(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As television goes, the Republican National Convention hasn't
exactly been (beginitalic)NYPD Blue (enditalic)(despite the
appearance of Rick Schroeder on Tuesday night). But it hasn't been
(beginitalic)Shasta McNasty(enditalic) either.
</P>
<P>
   With the candidate long ago selected, Republicans are just
passing time until George W. Bush gives his acceptance speech in
Philadelphia on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the convention has been so tightly scripted, down to the
minute, that it carries all the excitement and energy of one of
those Super Bowl halftime shows starring Up With People (only with
a much smaller audience).
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, only about 13 million people, or about 15
percent of the television audience, watched prime-time coverage on
CBS and ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Surprises have been found nowhere. Bush's wife, Laura had the
proverbial deer-in-the-headlights look during her speech Monday
night. But somehow it made her seem charming instead of
overwhelmed. She came off a lot less scary than the steely
Elizabeth Dole did Tuesday night anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, maybe the compassionate bit is paying off after all.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
