<HEADER>
A0293 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-GOPKOLBE-AZR &LR;      08-02 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOPKOLBE-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-GOPKOLBE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    TEXANS QUIETLY PROTEST KOLBE(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By JEFF BARKER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As many as a dozen members of the Texas delegation removed their
cowboy hats and bowed their heads in prayer Tuesday night at the
Republican National Convention to silently protest a speech by U.S.
Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., the only openly gay GOP member of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't agree with that choice of speaker, and that was
my way of disagreeing,'' said alternate delegate Sue Hershey of
Amarillo. ``I was praying for our country, for the leadership of
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In his four-minute speech on international trade, Kolbe didn't
mention his sexual orientation or the Texas protest.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the contemplated protest before his speech,
Kolbe told (beginitalic)The
(enditalic)(beginitalic)Republic(enditalic) that he probably
wouldn't even notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many people moving around on the floor that
nobody would notice anything,'' Kolbe said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush
would fight for lucrative free trade agreements with China and
other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through free trade, we have exported our principles, as well
as our products - sharing America's freedom and democracy with the
world,'' Kolbe said.
</P>
<P>
   With his speech, Kolbe arguably became the most prominent openly
gay Republican to ever address a GOP nominating convention.
</P>
<P>
   But he said all he wanted to do was discuss free trade, his
specialty in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas delegates, more than 100 members in all, were
positioned in front of the raised podium, and Kolbe seemed to gaze
right over them. They had been wearing their straw-colored hats
during speeches.
</P>
<P>
   When Kolbe was introduced, as many as a dozen of the Texans
removed their hats and some looked at the ground. One delegate
placed her hat over her heart during the speech. One carried a sign
that said, ``There is a way out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about family values,'' one of the protesters,
Larry Stevens of Fort Worth, said afterward. Stevens and others
were concerned that Kolbe's inclusion in the program would run
contrary to the party platform.
</P>
<P>
   The platform asserts that homosexuality should not be protected
by anti-discrimination laws in the same manner as race, and that
homosexuality is incompatible with military service.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters also had discussed the possibility of walking out
of the convention hall, but concluded ``that would be
disrespectful,'' Hershey said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, Kolbe, 58, was honored at a reception by the
Log Cabin Republicans, a gay organization.
</P>
<P>
   About a half-dozen protesters stood in front of the hotel where
the event was held, and were surrounded by 40 Philadelphia police
officers. One of the protesters, Bob Kunst, said the Log Cabin
group was not pushing hard enough for gay rights and was ``selling
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe made a joke at the reception when he spotted about 10
television cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew there was such interest in trade by the media,''
he said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Getting serious, he said he was selected as a convention speaker
``because of the 16 years of work I have done on the issue of
trade.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign of Bush, who accepts the party's presidential
nomination on Thursday night, had said it hoped that Kolbe would be
treated respectfully.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 0813EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
