<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 08:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0294 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-GOPMCCAIN-AZR &LR;      08-02 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOPMCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-GOPMCCAIN-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    MCCAIN ROUSES GOP DELEGATES(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By JEFF BARKER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John McCain had once hoped to address the Republican National
Convention as its presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, the Arizona senator settled instead for
delivering a lofty, patriotic speech that earned the heartiest
applause when congratulating the man who defeated him, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support him. I am grateful to him. And I am proud of him,''
McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd rose. Among the first to stand was former President
Bush and his wife, Barbara, the parents of the soon-to-be nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor was not in the packed, hot convention hall.
He will formally accept the nomination when he makes his convention
debut Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   But he appeared on video from Gettysburg, Pa., and praised
McCain as ``a hero whose straight talk and strong convictions are
admired across America.''
</P>
<P>
   Other speakers Tuesday evening included retired Gen. Norman
Schwarzkopf; 1996 GOP presidential nominee Bob Dole and his wife,
Elizabeth; and Bush foreign policy adviser Condoleezza Rice.
</P>
<P>
   For McCain, it was the end of a long path that saw him challenge
Bush for the party's nomination, then offer a faint initial
endorsement of his victorious rival, and finally reconcile and wish
Bush well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a good man from a good family that has, in good times
and bad, dedicated themselves to America,'' said McCain, the son
and grandson of Navy admirals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many years ago, the governor's father served in the Pacific
with distinction under the command of my grandfather. Now, it is my
turn to serve under the son of my grandfather's brave
subordinate.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's speech was not only a tribute to his father's World War
II generation, but a call to follow their example of sacrifice for
a noble cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``They fought for love, for love of an idea {ndash} that America
stood for something greater than the sum of our individual
interests,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us take courage from their example. And from the new world
they built, build a better one.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's wife, Cindy, and his mother, Roberta, watched the
speech from seats off the convention floor. They sat one row in
front of former President Bush and former President Ford and his
wife, Betty.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won seven primaries, including his home state. He
released his delegates on the eve of the convention, freeing them
to support Bush. McCain has not specifically ruled out running for
president again if Bush loses to Democratic Vice President Al Gore
in November.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was greeted by the (beginitalic)Theme From Star Wars
(enditalic)when he emerged on the podium. The music was used
frequently in his presidential campaign, in which he likened
himself to Luke Skywalker's movie battle against the empire.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, McCain seemed to offer a rebuttal to Reform Party
candidate Pat Buchanan and others who think that the United States
has been too prone to intervene in foreign affairs and sign global
trade pacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isolationism and protectionism are fool's errands. We
shouldn't build walls to the global success of our interests and
values,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the chief architects of McCain's speech was Mark Salter,
the senator's chief of staff, who collaborated with McCain on his
recent book on the family's military history. He wrote many of
McCain's biggest speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Salter ``is our go-to guy,'' said Rick Davis, McCain's former
campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Reach the reporter at jeff.barker(a)arizonarepublic.com or (202)
662-7264.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 0814EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 08:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0295 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-ROBB-AZR &LR;      08-02 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBB-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-ROBB-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    GOP DROPS CONSERVATIVE MAINSTAYS(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BOB ROBB(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Republican platform adopted by convention delegates without
discussion or dissent on Monday closes two important chapters in
Republican conservatism: a commitment to roll back the mission of
the federal government, which has been a Republican mainstay since
the success of the Barry Goldwater insurgency in 1964; and a
commitment to growth-oriented tax policies, which has been the
domestic policy anchor for Republicans since President Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   The platform does mention, from time to time, the need to limit
government. But the only federal intrusion it actually calls for
retracting is OSHA's ergonomics regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast this with the 1996 platform, which specifically called
for abolishing four Cabinet departments (Commerce, Housing and
Urban Development, Education and Energy) and four agencies
(National Endowment for the Arts, National Endowment for the
Humanities, the Corporation for Public Broadcasting and the Legal
Services Corp.).
</P>
<P>
   The platform does advocate fundamental and important changes in
the way the federal government performs its mission: block grants
to the states, using faith-based organizations in the delivery of
social services, vouchers to increase choice and competition and
personal savings accounts as part of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   But the platform does not challenge the existing contours of the
federal welfare state.
</P>
<P>
   And while the platform is quick to give the Reagan
growth-oriented tax cuts credit for the current economic expansion,
it places little emphasis on expanding them in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Growth-oriented tax policy moves toward as low of a tax rate on
as large of a base as possible, particularly for income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   This increases the incentive for economically useful behavior,
such as hard work, thrift and entrepreneurship. And it minimizes
government involvement in economic decisions and allocating
resources.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has called for a growth-oriented,
across-the-board income tax rate reduction. The platform devotes a
single line to it in a prolix 73-page, single-spaced document that
manages to ramble on at considerable length about virtually every
other issue facing the nation or the world.
</P>
<P>
   No explanation of why it is needed, what it will do to increase
real incomes and economic opportunity, or how it is a centerpiece
of Republican domestic policy {ndash} which it clearly no longer
is.
</P>
<P>
   The platform also repeats the standard mantra about making the
tax system ``simpler, flatter and fairer for everyone.'' And then
goes on to call for 18 new or expanded tax deductions or credits,
for everything from adoption, to education, to housing, to elderly
care, to energy production.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, just as Republicans have largely accepted the
Democratic welfare state, they have also largely accepted the
Democratic view that the tax code should be used to reward or
induce politically approved behaviors, or to alleviate financial
burdens. In other words, that the government should use the tax
code to advance its policies, rather than be as neutral as possible
in economic decisions and the allocation of resources.
</P>
<P>
   Political platforms are often dismissed because, in the American
system, they are not binding on candidates and officeholders. But
occasionally, they reveal important truths, as this one does.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, Republican leaders, in Congress and including the
presidential nominee-to-be, are not warriors against the welfare
state. They aspire to be more responsible custodians of it.
</P>
<P>
   And while they perhaps support fundamental tax reform and
growth-oriented tax cuts as an abstract goal, they find more
immediate political allure in manipulating the tax code to advance
a social policy agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Reach Robb at bob.robb(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602) 444-8472.
His column appears Sunday, Wednesday and Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
