<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: HARDCOVER BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, Aug. 6) 
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for hardcover
books. See BESTSELLERS-HARD-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales for the week ending July 22, at almost
4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 50,000 other retailers
(gift shops, department stores, newsstands, supermarkets),
statistically weighted to represent all such outlets nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) indicates that a book's sales are barely distinguishable
from those of the book above. A (b) indicates that some bookstores
report receiving bulk orders for a book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE HOUSE ON HOPE STREET, by Danielle Steel.
</P>
<P>
   (Delacorte, $19.95.) A woman with five children
</P>
<P>
   must cope with the loss of her husband, who dies
</P>
<P>
   on Christmas Day.
</P>
<P>
   2. NOT A DAY GOES BY, by E. Lynn Harris. (Doubleday,
</P>
<P>
   $19.95.) The tumultuous romance between a football
</P>
<P>
   player turned sports agent and an up-and-coming
</P>
<P>
   Broadway star.
</P>
<P>
   3. OMERTA, by Mario Puzo. (Random House, $25.95.) An
</P>
<P>
   FBI agent targets a recently retired Mafia don who
</P>
<P>
   has tried to shield his three grown children from
</P>
<P>
   the family business.
</P>
<P>
   4. RIPTIDE, by Catherine Coulter. (Putnam, $23.95.)
</P>
<P>
   The senior speechwriter for the governor of New York
</P>
<P>
   flees a stalker as well as the police after her boss
</P>
<P>
   is shot.
</P>
<P>
   5. THE INDWELLING, by Tim LaHaye and Jerry B. Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   (Tyndale, $22.99.) The seventh volume in a series about
</P>
<P>
   true believers who confront the Antichrist after the
</P>
<P>
   rapture of the saved. (b)
</P>
<P>
   6. NORA, NORA, by Anne Rivers Siddons. (HarperCollins,
</P>
<P>
   $25.) An outsider who harbors a secret from her past
</P>
<P>
   shakes up the quiet town of Lytton, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   7. THE BRETHREN, by John Grisham. (Doubleday, $27.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Three former judges, doing time at a federal prison in
</P>
<P>
   Florida, concoct a lucrative mail scam that goes awry.
</P>
<P>
   8. HEARTBREAKER, by Julie Garwood. (Pocket Books,
</P>
<P>
   $24.95.) An FBI agent tries to prevent his best friend's
</P>
<P>
   sister from being killed by a deranged fiend.
</P>
<P>
   9. HOT SIX, by Janet Evanovich. (St Martin's, $24.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A New Jersey bounty hunter searches for her mentor, who
</P>
<P>
   is the No. 1 suspect in the killing of an arms dealer's
</P>
<P>
   son.
</P>
<P>
   10. LETHAL SEDUCTION, by Jackie Collins. (Simon &AMP;
</P>
<P>
   Schuster, $26.) Madison Castelli, a beautiful writer
</P>
<P>
   for a magazine in New York, discovers that her father
</P>
<P>
   is hiding deadly secrets.
</P>
<P>
   11.(x) SACRED SINS, by Nora Roberts. (Bantam, $18.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A psychiatrist in Washington finds herself drawn into
</P>
<P>
   the search for a serial killer whom the press
</P>
<P>
   has named ``the Priest.''
</P>
<P>
   12. THE RIVER KING, by Alice Hoffman. (Putnam, $23.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A police officer in a small Massachusetts town
</P>
<P>
   investigates the supposed suicide of a freshman at the
</P>
<P>
   local prep school.
</P>
<P>
   13. CRADLE AND ALL by James Patterson. (Little, Brown,
</P>
<P>
   $25.95.) A former nun turned private eye works on a
</P>
<P>
   case involving two virgins who become pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   14. LIAR'S GAME, by Eric Jerome Dickey. (Dutton, $23.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A Los Angeles couple's romance is complicated by the
</P>
<P>
   reappearance of her former lover and his ex-wife.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) McNALLY'S FOLLY, by Lawrence Sanders. (Putnam,
</P>
<P>
   $24.95.) Archy McNally probes the murder of an actor in
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach; written by Vincent Lardo after the death of
</P>
<P>
   Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. LIFE ON THE OTHER SIDE, by Sylvia Browne with
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay Harrison. (Dutton, $23.95.) A guided tour
</P>
<P>
   of the afterlife, by a ``working psychic.''
</P>
<P>
   2. IT'S NOT ABOUT THE BIKE, by Lance Armstrong with
</P>
<P>
   Sally Jenkins. (Putnam, $24.95.) A memoir by the Tour
</P>
<P>
   de France champion and cancer survivor.
</P>
<P>
   3.(x) TUESDAYS WITH MORRIE, by Mitch Albom. (Doubleday,
</P>
<P>
   $19.95.) A sportswriter tells of his weekly visits
</P>
<P>
   to his old college mentor, who was near death.
</P>
<P>
   4. THE DAY JOHN DIED, by Christopher Andersen. (Morrow,
</P>
<P>
   $26.) The events leading up to the plane crash that
</P>
<P>
   killed John F. Kennedy Jr., Carolyn Bessette Kennedy
</P>
<P>
   and Lauren Bessette.
</P>
<P>
   5. AMERICAN RHAPSODY, by Joe Eszterhas. (Knopf, $25.95.)
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton sex scandal as seen by the man who wrote
</P>
<P>
   ``Basic Instinct'' and ``Showgirls.''
</P>
<P>
   6. FLAGS OF OUR FATHERS, by James Bradley with Ron Powers.
</P>
<P>
   (Bantam, $24.95.) The story of the Marines who raised
</P>
<P>
   the flag at Iwo Jima, by the son of one of the men.
</P>
<P>
   7. FROM DAWN TO DECADENCE, by Jacques Barzun.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperCollins, $36.) A survey of 500 years of
</P>
<P>
   Western cultural life, from 1500 to the present.
</P>
<P>
   8. ME TALK PRETTY ONE DAY, by David Sedaris. (Little,
</P>
<P>
   Brown, $22.95.) A collection of autobiographical comic
</P>
<P>
   essays by the author of ``Naked.''
</P>
<P>
   9. IN A SUNBURNED COUNTRY, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway,
</P>
<P>
   $25.) The author of ``A Walk in the Woods'' reports
</P>
<P>
   on his travels through Australia.
</P>
<P>
   10. IN THE HEART OF THE SEA, by Nathaniel Philbrick.
</P>
<P>
   (Viking, $24.95.) The story of the whale ship Essex,
</P>
<P>
   whose disastrous fate in the early 19th century
</P>
<P>
   would later serve as inspiration for Herman Melville.
</P>
<P>
   11.(x) THE GREATEST GENERATION, by Tom Brokaw. (Random
</P>
<P>
   House, $24.95.) The lives of men and women who came
</P>
<P>
   of age during the Depression and World War II.
</P>
<P>
   12. KITCHEN CONFIDENTIAL, by Anthony Bourdain.
</P>
<P>
   (Bloomsbury, $24.95.) A memoir-expose by the executive
</P>
<P>
   chef at Brasserie Les Halles in New York.
</P>
<P>
   13. PAPAL SIN, by Garry Wills. (Doubleday, $25.) A
</P>
<P>
   chronicle of what the author sees as the evasions and
</P>
<P>
   distortions of the Vatican over the past two centuries.
</P>
<P>
   14. THE ART OF HAPPINESS, by the Dalai Lama and Howard
</P>
<P>
   C. Cutler. (Riverhead, $22.95.) What Buddhism and common
</P>
<P>
   sense tell us about everyday problems.
</P>
<P>
   15. STATE OF A UNION, by Jerry Oppenheimer.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperCollins, $25.) An account of the ``complex
</P>
<P>
   marriage'' of Bill Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. WHO MOVED MY CHEESE? by Spencer Johnson. (Putnam,
</P>
<P>
   $19.95.) How to deal with changes at work and in life
</P>
<P>
   in general. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. BODY FOR LIFE, by Bill Phillips with Michael D'Orso.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperCollins, $26.) Ways to improve one's body and
</P>
<P>
   one's life. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. TEN THINGS I WISH I'D KNOWN _ BEFORE I WENT OUT INTO
</P>
<P>
   THE REAL WORLD, by Maria Shriver. (Warner, $19.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Life lessons from the anchorwoman. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. SIMPLE ABUNDANCE, by Sarah Ban Breathnach. (Warner,
</P>
<P>
   $21.) Advice for women seeking to improve the way they
</P>
<P>
   look at themselves. (b).
</P>
<P>
   5.(x) RELATIONSHIP RESCUE, by Phillip C. McGraw.
</P>
<P>
   (Hyperion, $22.95.) Reconnecting with one's
</P>
<P>
   partner. (b)
</P>
