<HEADER>
A0370 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-CONVICTION-REVERSAL     08-02 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CONVICTION-REVERSALS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVIDENCE OF INNOCENCE CAN COME TOO LATE FOR FREEDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 By JANE FRITSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Newly discovered evidence may seem like the unjustly convicted's
dream come true, but the reality is that such evidence rarely makes
a difference in the United States. Once a jury has reached a
verdict or a judge has ruled, lawyers say, the odds are
overwhelmingly against reopening a case, no matter how compelling
the new information is.
</P>
<P>
   And actual innocence is the least effective argument to make for
a new trial because it is so difficult to prove. Although the
recent use of DNA testing, particularly in rape cases, has produced
incontrovertible evidence of innocence in some cases, and has
forced the release of the unjustly convicted, most crimes do not
involve DNA matching. Most other types of evidence _ like
confessions or new witnesses _ can be argued away or ignored,
lawyers say.
</P>
<P>
   Judges are loath to reopen cases, and state appeals courts
dislike intervening on anything but procedural issues. Decisions on
who is telling the truth and what the evidence means are best left
to the so-called finders of fact: the actual judge or jurors who
saw the exhibits and heard the witnesses. It has always been
difficult to win by taking an appeal to federal court, known as a
habeas corpus petition; when Congress passed a law sharply limiting
such appeals in 1996, it became even more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chances of any petition are dim,'' said Larry W. Yackle, a
law professor at Boston University. ``It would be a real indictment
of the system if many were successful.'' He added, ``You wouldn't
expect a system that papers over its many flaws to give up the
ghost all of a sudden when it gets to a federal judge.''
</P>
<P>
   The bar to undoing a conviction should be high, said Nancy E.
Little, a lawyer in the appeals division of the Legal Aid Society
in New York. ``But the way it's applied now, it's incredibly
high,'' she said. The courts ``have a vested interest in their
convictions. I think it's very hard for them to undo their own
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Little is handling an appeal in the case of David Lemus and
Olmado Hidalgo, who were convicted in the 1990 murder of a bouncer
at a Manhattan nightclub. Another man has since confessed to the
murder and implicated a friend, but the original defendants remain
in prison. Despite some corroborating evidence, a state judge in
Manhattan said he did not believe the new confession and refused to
order a new trial. State appeals courts refused to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the odds, Little said, she has some hope of winning a
reversal through a habeas corpus petition. But the burden on the
defendant is high. She must show, for instance, that the decisions
of the state courts were contrary to established law, and that the
state court's decision was not just incorrect, but unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
   It is not necessarily the job of the federal court to reexamine
the facts of the case. The federal judge, in this case Jed S.
Rakoff, will be looking to see whether the constitutional rights of
the defendants were violated. One argument, Little said, is that
the defendants' right to due process was violated when the state
judge refused to grant a new trial based on the confession.
</P>
<P>
   Eric M. Freedman, a professor of law at Hofstra University, said
it is highly unlikely that an appeal based on newly discovered
evidence will succeed in federal court. Freedman, who is writing a
book on habeas corpus petitions, said he knows of no recent cases
in which such petitions were granted on the basis of new evidence,
other than possibly a few that involved exculpatory DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The finding of facts by the state court judge must be found
unreasonable,'' Freedman said, ``and they must make out a truly
persuasive showing of actual innocence _ and that's tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legal system tends to defer to the fact finders, whether
that's a judge or a jury,'' he said. ``There is inertia built into
the legal system favoring the first finder of fact.''
</P>
<P>
   The best route for prisoners like Lemus and Hidalgo is to come
up with new evidence that will warrant a reopening of the case in
state court, Freedman said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, lawyers for the two thought they had just that when
they got word of the confession several years ago. Joey Pillot, a
member of a Bronx extortion gang, told a federal prosecutor
investigating the gang that he and his friend, James Rodriguez, had
murdered the bouncer. The prosecutor and a police detective looked
into Pillot's story, grilled him about the details and came to
believe that he was telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Jay Gold of state Supreme Court in Manhattan, who
had presided over the original trial, thought Pillot had concocted
the story to please the federal prosecutors, and refused to grant a
new trial.
</P>
<P>
   Now, lawyers for Lemus and Hidalgo need to come up with another
substantial piece of new evidence to have a chance at winning a new
hearing. That could be the testimony of Rodriguez, who is in prison
on another charge and is to be released in November. He has said he
will testify only if he gets immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Robert M. Morgenthau, the Manhattan district attorney, has been
reluctant to give Rodriguez complete immunity. So, Morgenthau must
decide whether it is preferable to give immunity to a murderer in
order to set free two possibly innocent men, or to refuse immunity
and let them complete their sentences of 25 years to life. Either
way, Rodriguez will walk out of prison in November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
