<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0376 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-REVI     08-02 1674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE MIDEAST, NOTHING SUCCEEDS LIKE A FAILURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 By ETHAN BRONNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stakes, U.S. officials warned, had never been higher. To
many looking in from the outside, it seemed to be make or break,
peace or war. The brink, they feared, was right there: On the other
side lay chaos, confrontation and bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   But the dirty little secret of the 14-day Camp David Middle East
peace summit is that the brink was a myth. The meeting failed; the
two sides went home without agreement. Yet no explosion in Israel
or the Palestinian territories occurred, nor is chaos expected any
time soon. This is because not only was the brink a myth; so, too,
were the fears. In truth, it was never failure of the summit that
brought with it the risk of violence. It was success.
</P>
<P>
   It is sudden compromise that really violates expectations in the
Middle East in a way that brings out the dark, violent forces
there. Now that Yasser Arafat has resisted a deal, he is hailed by
Palestinians as a hero. Now that Ehud Barak did not actually give
anything away, the Israeli government he leads is expected to
survive a no-confidence motion this week. But that does not mean
the two sides are farther apart than before. They have never been
closer.
</P>
<P>
   This is the paradox of Middle East peacemaking. Going slowly
produces impatience and despondence but moving quickly is simply
impossible. Camp David had the trappings of a go-for-broke meeting,
but it was just one more step in a process of mutual recognition
and adjustment begun in Oslo seven years ago. Its failure does not
derail that process. It is part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson from Camp David is that the alternative to
negotiations is not necessarily confrontation and bloodshed but
more negotiations,'' said Daniel Ben-Simon, an analyst with the
liberal Israeli newspaper Haaretz.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Israeli and Palestinian negotiators scheduled new
meetings on the Israeli-Gaza Strip border. Security chiefs of the
two sides kept in daily contact to prevent violence.
</P>
<P>
   Khalil Shikaki, who directs the Palestinian Center for Policy
and Survey Research in Ramallah on the West Bank, agrees that
peacemaking is far from over. He argues that the Oslo process
showed the two sides that a partial deal was feasible and might be
the solution for a longer time than many would like. This means
that no solution is likely to emerge soon on sovereignty over the
holy sites in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arafat is going to be in good political shape for some time to
come,'' Shikaki said. ``Even if there is no partial deal, both
sides have an interest in preventing violence from erupting.'' He
added that his polls show that despite the waxing and waning of
Arafat's popularity, the radical Islamic alternative represented by
Hamas and Islamic Jihad has not gained at all in popularity in
recent years. Total support for those groups has been flat at about
20 percent for five years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, nobody knows how this balance would shift if there
were concessions on Jerusalem, which stands as the symbol of the
Islamic cause in the Holy Land. Many believe that it is not up to
Arafat but to the broader Arab leadership to make concessions on
Jerusalem and that is unlikely soon. As long as negotiations
continue, that question may not have to be faced in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   Shikaki noted that the next deadline is Sept. 13, when Arafat
has warned he will unilaterally announce the existence of a
Palestinian state if negotiations have not yet produced it. But
Shikaki acknowledged that that deadline could also be stretched.
</P>
<P>
   And even if the state is declared, the impact is not clear.
Arafat declared the state's existence once already _ in 1988 _ to
little effect. It is true that Palestinians today have a large,
lightly armed force inside the West Bank and Gaza Strip, so the
declaration could have more bite and could, in fact, lead to
violent confrontation. Then again, the intifada of a decade ago is
not reproducible now since the soldiers among the Palestinians
today are Palestinian, not Israeli. A street revolt, unless
actually led by Arafat, would probably have to start as one against
him, and for now that prospect seems remote. Rogue acts of violence
could, of course, lead to sympathetic involvement of Palestinian
police. But, again, the prevalent view is that such violence would
be quelled.
</P>
<P>
   Others argue that, given the difficult issues, like Jerusalem
and refugees, that were on the table, Camp David's failure was not
only inevitable but useful. Zev Chafets, a commentator who was head
of the Israeli government press office under Prime Minister
Menachem Begin 20 years ago, even suggests that the general
reaction in the Middle East is relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come down to it, the deal was supposed to be our
giving them all this land in exchange for them saying they forgive
us,'' Chafets said. ``But they don't forgive us. We haven't reached
that stage yet. So we have to continue as is. We have reached quite
a comfortable modus vivendi. The Palestinians still run the Muslim
quarter and we still have sovereignty over Maale Adumim.'' He was
referring to a large Jewish settlement east of Jerusalem in the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Uri Dromi, who ran the government press office under Yitzhak
Rabin, compares the relationship between Israelis and Palestinians
to that between a couple going through a divorce while living in
the same house. ``Neither one is going to leave, even if they try
to make life unbearable for each other. So, in the long run, they
adjust and minimize the points of friction.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dromi points to the increasing interaction between people on
the two sides as evidence that the process of mutual adjustment is
advancing. He says that his brother, a senior police officer, is in
frequent contact with Palestinian officers and that even when
official relations have been tense, personal ones have been warm.
He notes further that every Saturday there are huge traffic jams as
thousands of Israelis drive to the West Bank cities of Nablus and
Tulkarm to shop. Thousands of others drive to Jericho to gamble.
``These are the same cities where their sons had to chase stone
throwers into the alleys of the casbah,'' he mused.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: he mused. &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The reality is indeed new. For two generations, the political
divide in Israel was between those on the left who called for ``two
states for two peoples'' and those on the right who swore there
would never be a Palestinian state. Now the whole discussion is
what the contours and powers of that state would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a major realignment going on,'' said Yoram Hazony, a
conservative who was an aide to Benjamin Netanyahu when he was
prime minister. ``There is, in effect, a condition of political
independence for the Palestinians. Today, there is no such thing as
a `not-one-inch' position. Now you hear people on the far right
saying that if we are going to trade territory, let's give the
Palestinians as many Arab villages in Israel as possible to
maximize the Jewish majority in Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there is another useful myth that animated the Camp
David peace process: that only the governments of Barak and Arafat
in their current configurations can make this peace and so a
historic opportunity is at stake. The same was said of Yitzhak
Rabin and Arafat. After Rabin's assassination in 1995 by a Jewish
extremist, the hawkish Netanyahu was elected and the doomsayers
seemed correct. But the peace process did not die, and it is
unlikely to if Barak and Arafat fail to decide how to share
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   All acknowledge that Jerusalem is the most difficult issue
because while land can be divided, it is far less clear how to
divide a symbol that is, in Hazony's words, ``at the heart of what
we think we are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is also a myth that only at Camp David did the issue of
Jerusalem first get an airing. It was certainly the first time it
was broached directly at the very top, but Jerusalem has been under
discussion for quite a while. Yossi Beilin, a senior minister in
Barak's government, negotiated Jerusalem's future with Abu Mazen, a
senior Palestinian official, in 1995. The Rabin assassination in
November of that year ended those discussions.
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons for pessimism over the Israeli-Arab
conflict. There is a huge disparity in culture and income and
numerous bases of resentment. Meron Benvenisti, a leftist former
deputy mayor of Jerusalem and an Israeli expert on the West Bank,
is dismissive of the negotiations over Jerusalem neighborhoods and
sovereignty sharing because he believes the Israelis still do not
take the Palestinians seriously as human beings. That failure, he
believes, will bring the process to a very unhappy end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sit back and feel self-righteous and convert the whole
question into whether there will be violence,'' he said. ``The
Arabs are interesting to us only as a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   But for many others, the peace process is best seen like the
stock market. It may have its frightening ups and downs, but its
positive direction in the long term is clear. The key is to avoid
irrational exuberance or utter gloom.
</P>
<P>
   Salameh Nematt, a Jordanian journalist for the Arab newspaper Al
Hayat, says he marvels at how much has happened in a decade. ``In
the beginning, they spoke of Gaza first,'' he recalled of Israeli
proposals in the early 1990s. ``Then it was Gaza and Jericho first
and Gaza and Jericho last. Then came Nablus and Tulkarm and then 9
percent of the land and then 13 percent and then talk of maybe 50
percent and now we are hearing about more than 90 percent. Any
Israeli government that moves too fast will be burned but so will
any government that moves too slowly. The final settlement may take
another 10 or 15 years, but it will come. Remember how Israelis who
met with Arafat used to go to jail? Now he's their best friend.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
