believes, will bring the process to a very unhappy end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sit back and feel self-righteous and convert the whole
question into whether there will be violence,'' he said. ``The
Arabs are interesting to us only as a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   But for many others, the peace process is best seen like the
stock market. It may have its frightening ups and downs, but its
positive direction in the long term is clear. The key is to avoid
irrational exuberance or utter gloom.
</P>
<P>
   Salameh Nematt, a Jordanian journalist for the Arab newspaper Al
Hayat, says he marvels at how much has happened in a decade. ``In
the beginning, they spoke of Gaza first,'' he recalled of Israeli
proposals in the early 1990s. ``Then it was Gaza and Jericho first
and Gaza and Jericho last. Then came Nablus and Tulkarm and then 9
percent of the land and then 13 percent and then talk of maybe 50
percent and now we are hearing about more than 90 percent. Any
Israeli government that moves too fast will be burned but so will
any government that moves too slowly. The final settlement may take
another 10 or 15 years, but it will come. Remember how Israelis who
met with Arafat used to go to jail? Now he's their best friend.'' &QL;
</P>
