with lobbyists from Kentucky, another was transfixed by a camera
trained on the Hawaii delegation, a third was consumed with
e-mailing questions to a Webcast on MSNBC _ and none paid attention
to a word of the vice presidential nominee's address?
</P>
<P>
   With more options, your water-cooler conversations are going to
be many times smaller,'' said Sam Hollander, executive producer of
Pseudopolitics.com, a Web site that will, among other things,
provide a 360-degree view through a series of cameras inside the
First Union Center in Philadelphia and the Staples Center in Los
Angeles, where the Democrats convene in August. ``There will be a
lot of two-person conversations, rather than 20-person
conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   This relentless subdividing of common ground, Hollander said, is
akin to the fragmenting of television viewership, thanks to the
multiplicity of choices on cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you need to do is look at what ratings share a network has
to get today to have a success,'' he said. ``There was a time when
if you didn't get a 30 share, it wasn't that big. Now, if you get a
20, you're a huge hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Where once the country was knit together by the collective
experience of watching the same sitcom on one of the networks, or
having the meaning of a national tragedy interpreted by Walter
Cronkite, the I-can-do-it-myself ethos engendered by technology is
on the verge of assuring that there will be no collective
electronic experience.
</P>
<P>
   TiVo, for example, is a year-old digital service based in
California that allows subscribers to program their televisions to
play only what they want to see at a time of their choosing. Its
recent television commercial depicting network programmers being
tossed out of windows asked , ``When you've got TiVo, who needs
them?'' Some networks refused to run it, say TiVo executives.
</P>
<P>
   No one as yet is confidently predicting just how all this
electronic democracy will affect the democratic process. Paul
Sagan, president of Akamai Technologies, an Internet company
selected by the Democrats to deliver all of their streaming media
convention coverage, says the interactive age is probably too new
in this election cycle to profoundly affect voters' view of events.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the cat is out of the bag, and the savviest politicians,
Sagan said, will quickly begin to look for ways to satisfy the
demands for individualized attention from users of the Internet,
who now number more than 115 million in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``In interactivity, people expect to control the query and get
back the answer,'' Sagan said, adding his own customized parable:
``I have an odd Swiss watch that requires an authorized dealer to
change the battery. I went to the company's Web site and sent them
a query: how can I get the battery replaced? I got a response from
someone in Switzerland saying thank you for your inquiring and that
the query had been forwarded to their U.S. offices.''
</P>
<P>
   Sagan never heard from the American branch. ``My watch is now
dead in a drawer and they have a disgruntled customer,'' he said.
``They did something that's worse than not trying at all. They
raised expectations and they failed to deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about scary scenarios: a political world in which every
voter gets a personalized Internet checklist of promises from the
candidate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0379 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-GOP-OUTLOOK-REVIEW-     08-02 1532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-GOP-OUTLOOK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REPUBLICAN TRYOUT FOR CLINTON'S OLD SCRIPT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ There are three things you will have to look hard
for as you tune in to the Republican National Convention here this
week: A true-blue conservative icon on center stage. (There may be
a few, but they will be sprinkled in a line-up that resembles a
Benetton commercial.) Any utterance of the word ``abortion.''
(You're more likely to hear the words, ``poor'' or ``underclass.'')
The traditional savaging of the opposition. (Instead, look for
subtle denigrations of the Clinton-Gore years and bipartisan
overtures.)
</P>
<P>
   If the Republicans seem timid about bashing President Clinton
this year, it's only fitting. That's because they've stolen his
political game plan. In fact the Grand Old Party is attempting to
refashion itself entirely, clearly using Clinton as its model.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years after Clinton captured the White House by venturing
toward the middle and running against some of the orthodoxies of
his party _ including those on welfare, teacher unions and racial
quotas _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush is trying a similar approach.
While Bush is not moving as far as Clinton in forsaking the
principles of his party, he sounds a lot like a Democrat when he
holds forth about protecting Social Security, reaching out to the
dispossessed and lavishing more money on public education.
</P>
<P>
   Bush last week startled Democrats and Republicans alike when he
spoke out about prescription drug benefits for the elderly. Bush
has even appropriated Clinton's mantra from 1992, ``a different
kind of Democrat.'' He would be ``a different kind of Republican,''
he reassures audiences.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, Republicans are advertising ``a different kind of
convention.'' This is what Americans will see on stage: A single
mom. A grandmother and granddaughter talking about Social Security.
A rank-and-file union member discussing his economic plight. A
teacher chatting about education reform.
</P>
<P>
   But to win the White House, Bush must prove that he is doing
more than muffling the vitriol by yanking the Pat Buchanans,
Marilyn Quayles and Phil Gramms offstage. His challenge is to
assemble a new Republican majority with the help of constituencies
that voted Democratic four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, he has to convince voters that he is not beholden to
the right wing. With some success, polls show, Bush is making a
play for the blue-collar Democrats and suburban women who backed
Clinton overwhelmingly four years ago. He is reaching out
aggressively to Latino voters. He even dared to speak before the
NAACP, not because he thought he could convert African American
voters _ among the Democratic Party's most loyal backers _- but
because of the signal it would send to moderates that he is
inclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the calculation, too, is that such appeals could at the
very least give minorities less reason to mobilize against
Republicans on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Bush can afford to reach out to moderates this year because the
base of his own party, ravenous to reclaim the White House, is
willing to make compromises. Not since the love fest for Ronald
Reagan in 1984 have Republicans appeared so harmonious on the eve
of their convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you spend one day of this convention making Republicans
happy, you're wasting your time because they already are,'' said
Rick Davis, a top official at four past Republican conventions.
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign intensifies, though, Vice President Al Gore and
the Democrats will increasingly portray Bush as Newt Gingrich
without the scowl. To this end, they were handed some potent
ammunition last week, when Bush picked Dick Cheney as his running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   The Cheney pairing suggested that Bush was harkening to his
party's conservative past rather than seeking a partner who could
broaden the ticket's ideological appeal. Clinton, in contrast, won
credibility as a reconfigured Democrat by picking Gore _ assembling
a Southern moderate ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not have to settle on a conservative. He has the
latitude that was denied Bob Dole four years ago when he picked
Jack Kemp as his running mate. Dole, however, needed someone to
rouse the party's conservative faithful, who had not rallied around
him, as they have around Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Robertson, the founder of the Christian Coalition, said he
was reassured by the Cheney pick. ``The fact that he's reaching out
to swing voters is not a bad thing,'' he said. ``You can trust the
candidate. You know where he's coming from philosophically. He's
not doing anything to alienate his base. That's the important
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Will he be as successful at co-opting _ or at least taming _ the
opposition as Clinton? Or will he fail, as did Gov. Michael Dukakis
in 1988? In that year's campaign, the elder George Bush effectively
branded Dukakis a Massachusetts liberal and card-carrying member of
the American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Gov. Bush and the Republicans have had it both ways.
It happened this weekend in Philadelphia. The Bush-controlled
Republican Party drafted a platform that cast off several
hard-edged party positions of the past, like abolishing the
Education Department and the National Endowment for the Arts. The
hostile language toward immigration four years ago was substituted
with a tribute to the role of new Americans. But conservatives were
not neglected. The platform contained a reaffirmation of its ban on
abortion _ with no exceptions _ despite a drive on Friday by some
party members to soften the language.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-GOP-OUTLOOK-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PHILADELPHIA: the langauge. &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It happened in Austin last week. There Bush was, introducing to
the world a running mate who had one of the most conservative
voting records in Congress. But in their oratory, they sounded as
Democratic as Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush declared that he called upon Cheney to help him
``accomplish some great goals'' for the nation: ``To save and
strengthen Social Security. To improve Medicare and provide
prescription drugs for the elderly. To reform our public schools.''
All but the last point _ ``To rebuild our military to keep the
peace'' _ sounded like they would be more likely to issue from Al
Gore's mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, of course, are already working hard not to let
Bush get away with this balancing act. They argue that many of his
proposals for new spending on social projects are modest and
symbolic. And most of these proposals, they note, offer
traditionally Republican solutions that rely heavily on the power
of the private sector, as in his plan to privatize Social Security
or his endorsement of vouchers to allow public money to go to
private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Voters may recognize that there are some real ideological
divides between Bush and Gore. A New York Times/CBS News Poll last
week showed that the public sees stark differences in how they
would handle taxes, health care, abortion and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bush's right-down-the-middle tactics may succeed. Both
parties have a history of remaking themselves. In 1952, Dwight
Eisenhower refused to tear down elements of the New Deal and spoke
loftily about retooling the Republican Party. While Bush calls
himself a ``compassionate conservative,'' Eisenhower favored the
term ``dynamic conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   William Bennett, the former education secretary, said the
convention strategy is too middle-of-the-road for his taste, but
defends it as smart politics. ``The convention is not as right-wing
as I am,'' he said. ``They're not taking advice from the old
Washington hands. They're following their own counsel _ and doing
it brilliantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet while prominent conservatives are staying silent as their
bread-and-butter issues _ school prayer and opposition to abortion
and homosexual rights _ get short shrift (or no shrift at all),
Bush could be risking his relations with others on the right, who
worry that the party is losing its soul.
</P>
<P>
   David A. Keene, chairman of the American Conservative Union,
warned that Bush had better be careful that his overtures to
moderates do not become more substantive. ``The feel-good stuff and
atmospherics is all fine,'' he said. ``But when push comes to
shove, Republicans win elections in which there is a clear
distinction between their position and the Democratic position on
the issues. If you spend all your time reaching out, you're putting
your base in danger.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Bush seems to be having more luck reassuring
conservatives than his father, the former president, who was never
fully trusted on the right.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, for one, is haunted by the elder Bush's speech,
written by Peggy Noonan, at the 1988 Republican convention at which
the nominee uttered his famous anti-tax pledge. ``I just hope and
pray he doesn't have Peggy Noonan write, `Read My Lips,'''
Robertson said. ``We don't need any tax pledge redux!''
</P>
<P>
   So the right is watching. But if the younger Bush has learned
anything from his father, it is that if you try to tack right and
then dance to the center, you can end up falling off the political
stage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
