<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Smile When You Downsize the Name, Partner
</P>
<P>
   Before signing on to the Republican Party ticket with Gov.
George W. Bush, Dick Cheney should have read the small print _ it's
his own name.
</P>
<P>
   On the new campaign placard unveiled at the candidates' first
appearance in Wyoming, Cheney's name was two-thirds the size of
Bush's _ on a second, lower line.
</P>
<P>
   Though running mates, they are not co-stars, at least in
Hollywood terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got co-stars, you've got them on the same line,
same size,'' said Elaine Goldsmith-Thomas, a senior vice president
at International Creative Management, and Julia Robert's agent.
``What's the message? Cheney needs a new agent. They're not sharing
the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   What's true for Harrison and Michelle in this summer's ``What
Lies Beneath'' _ co-stars, pica for pica _ was also true for
Ike-Dick, McKinley-Roosevelt, Clinton-Gore, Lincoln-Johnson and
Reagan-Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The exception to the graphic democracy of the last two centuries
_ President Bush in 1992. Dan Quayle's name was downsized from 30
to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other examples are rare, if they exist at all, said Larry Bird,
curator of the political history campaign collection at the
Smithsonian's National Museum of American History, whose materials
date from colonial times. ``Traditionally, they're co-equals in
point size,'' he said. ``That's the message of the signage _ that
there is a collective responsibility for perpetuating the office of
the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Sullivan, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, said there was
no intention in the official campaign image beyond the solution of
a design problem, and no nervousness about unintended
interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Number one _ because of the large block font used to spell out
`Bush' and `Cheney,' our graphic artist suggested making `Bush'
larger to make the sign easier to read,'' Sullivan said. ``Number
two _ Governor Bush is the nominee for president.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON
</P>
<P>
   A Creeping Tale for $1 a Chapter
</P>
<P>
   The horror writer Stephen King became the first major author to
self-publish over the Internet when he released the first chapter
of a serial novel called ``The Plant,'' about a vine that
terrorizes a publishing house.
</P>
<P>
   King's previous electronic book, the novella ``Riding the
Bullet,'' drew 400,000 orders in the first 24 hours after Simon &AMP;
Schuster published it in March. This time King is cutting out his
publisher, hoping to break new ground for less commercially
successful authors. Using a honor system, he is asking $1 for the
first chapter and for each monthly installment. He will stop
writing unless 75 percent of the downloaders pay, leaving fans in
suspense.
</P>
<P>
   So far 41,000 copies of chapter one were downloaded the first
day it appeared. That is far less than the initial demand for his
novella, which had Simon &AMP; Schuster's advance marketing behind it.
But it is still more than most titles sell in a year. King will
post another tally this weekend. So far more than 75 percent of the
readers are paying; Amazon.com is collecting. An envelope
mistakenly arriving at King's office was addressed only: ``Stephen
King, Rich Writer, Bangor, Maine.'' Inside was a check for $5. The
return address: ``Satisfied Downloader.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID D. KIRKPATRICK
</P>
<P>
   North Korea Finds Softer Stances in the West
</P>
<P>
   North Korea does indeed seem to be coming out of its shell. In
the highest-level talks between the United States and North Korea
since the Korean War, Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright met
with Foreign Minister Paek Nam Sun. New Zealand and Canada said
they were normalizing relations with North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   A 19-Under Wonder
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods looks as comfortable making history as he does
holding a golf club. By winning the British Open last Sunday, he
became the youngest player to complete the career Grand Slam,
winning all four major championships by age 24. If Woods wins the
PGA Championship in August, he will become the first player since
Ben Hogan (1953) to win three consecutive majors. Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CLIFTON BROWN
</P>
<P>
   Spraying for a Deadly Virus
</P>
<P>
   West Nile virus has returned to the New York region, if not
moved farther afield. Health officials had hoped that the
mosquito-borne disease _ never detected in the Western Hemisphere
prior to last year, when it caused seven deaths in the New York
area _ might be wiped out by cool weather. After finding infected
mosquitoes, New York City sprayed. So far, no human infections have
been confirmed. At least one dead infected crow was found in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ERIC LIPTON
</P>
<P>
   Economies of Scale at Ford
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1980s, automakers have made small fuel-economy
gains on some models only to make other vehicles larger and more
powerful, with poorer mileage. The result has been ever-increasing
emissions of global warming gases and more dependence on foreign
oil. Ford Motor changed course, vowing to increase the average
mileage of all its sport utility vehicles by 25 percent, to 23
miles a gallon from 18, by 2005. Ford will also improve the fuel
economy of its other models.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KEITH BRADSHER
</P>
<P>
   A Link for SIDS
</P>
<P>
   Researchers in Italy discovered a genetic link between some
