<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PEDESTRIANS (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Supervisor Mabel
Teng unveiled her Top 10 list of ideas to make the streets safer
for pedestrians, including establishing a 24-hour hot line to
report dangerous intersections and installing speed bumps to slow
down cars. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   BABOONS-FREE (Dilley, Texas) _ For 10 years they lived in a
cold, windowless laboratory, endured needle pokes twice a day and
watched television for their entertainment. Now, eight former
research baboons are free to co-exist with coyotes, rattlesnakes
and rabbits and roam among mesquite trees and cactuses near Dilley.
By LETY LAUREL.
</P>
<P>
   JESUITS (San Francisco) _ A former Berkeley seminarian settled
his sexual harassment suit against the Jesuits on confidential
terms, but he makes no secret of his pride in the case. ``Even
though it resulted in losing every Jesuit friend I had and other
unforeseen consequences, I'm very glad I did it,'' John Bollard
said. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LAZIO-SENATE (Philadelphia) _ Rick Lazio, the Republican
candidate facing Democratic First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton in
the nation's highest-profile U.S. Senate race, spent only one day
at the Republican National Convention, forfeiting a lucrative
chance to rally the troops from coast to coast behind him in spirit
and with donations. By LARA JAKES.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-TICCODE _ Actress and screenwriter Polly Draper
(thirtysomething) found a character and topic for her latest movie,
Tic Code, in her husband, composer Michael Wolff, who has
Tourette's Syndrome. By LOUIS B. PARKS. (Photo)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEONOTES _ Reviews of new videos Whatever It Takes, Romeo Must
</P>
<P>
   Die plus news on the DVD debut of The Sound of Music and a new
</P>
<P>
   Clint Eastwood Collection. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   COMEDY-MENCIA _ We talk to Mencia, Hispanic comedian and ``equal
</P>
<P>
   opportunity offender,'' touring with his ``Take a Joke America''
Tour 2000. Mencia is joined by Dave Attel and Guy Torry for a look
at life's hypocrosies, absurdities _ and of course, ethnic
stereotypes. By SHERRY
</P>
<P>
   THOMAS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BADSPORTS (Undated) _ A growing number of incidents by adult
fans and
</P>
<P>
   parents at youth sports events has some calling for mandatory
education
</P>
<P>
   for parents of kids in hockey, soccer, basketball etc. Adult
fans are
</P>
<P>
   misbehaving _ from poor sportsmanlike conduct to physical
assaults _all
</P>
<P>
   over the country. With BADSPORTS-SIDER. By DANIEL J. VARGAS
(Photos)
</P>
<P>
   BOARDGAMES (Undated) _ As computers and electronic gadgetry take
over
</P>
<P>
   our free time, there are still plenty of families who turn off
their
</P>
<P>
   hard drive and head to the kitchen table or the nearest coffee
shop.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's Trouble, Risk, Scrabble or good-old Monopoly,
interest in
</P>
<P>
   board games is increasing. More than 600 people will compete at
the
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro-sponsored Scrabble national championship next week in
providence, R.I., a three-fold increase since 1990. Also, in 1999
the sales of the company's 30 most popular classic games were up 6
percent from the previous year. By DANIEL J. VARGAS. (Photos)
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN-FATIMA (San Antonio) _ For decades, the third secret of
Fatima was shrouded in mystery, the manuscript detailing it hidden
from view to all but a few officials at the Vatican. That didn't
stop wild speculation in books, and later on Web sites, About the
manuscript's contents, ranging from predictions of the Apocalypse
to a devastating third world war. By JENNIFER A. DLOUHY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREER-EXAGGERATE (San Francisco) _ How's this for a job
interview question: When is the last time you lied about work? If
you said, ``never,'' you're probably lying _ maybe even to
yourself. Or
</P>
<P>
   maybe you're tempted to use an answer that would make President
Clinton
</P>
<P>
   proud: It depends on what your definition of ``lied'' is. By
DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   DOT-COMMERCE (San Francisco) _ San Francisco's dot-commerce has
grown nearly 500 percent in the past five years, generating nearly
$5.7 billion in revenue last year, according to a new survey. By
ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SWIM (San Francisco) _ In 1992, Angie Wester-Krieg was
described as ``the Grande Dame of U.S. Swimming.'' It's hard to say
what that makes her now. At 35, Wester-Krieg is still swimming.
Very well, in fact. She has qualified for her sixth U.S. Olympic
trials, which is a record as far as USA Swimming officials can
determine. By DWIGHT CHAPIN.
</P>
