<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS03-FILE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: FILE 1 OF 2
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com. Please include your name and hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did the late Sen. Paul Coverdell vote to impeach President
Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   A: After the House voted to impeach Clinton, Coverdell, a
Georgia Republican, voted to convict him on both impeachment
articles.
</P>
<P>
   As reported in the Atlanta Journal-Constitution Feb. 13, 1999,
Coverdell said the votes were ``horrible.'' He said he wrestled
with his decision right up until the day of the votes, even though
he had a ``gut feeling'' for several days about which way he would
go. When he spoke in closed session, he told colleagues that he
wanted to listen to the very last word of their arguments before he
rendered his own judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no adjective that I have been able to find that
adequately explains how you feel going through something like
this,'' Coverdell said at the time. ``It was a dreadful feeling . .
. and I don't believe I'm alone in this, to describe the anguish
that went through everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell had urged his colleages to conduct a trial that would
be as short as possible and still constitutionally fair. He was
known to refuse media requests to talk about the charges against
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I often see ``obo'' in classified ads following the price of
an item. What do these letters stand for?
</P>
<P>
   A: Or best offer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that Martha Stewart was married at one time. Do
you know anything about her husband?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's not much to report other than the fact that the
hearth goddess of the American home was divorced from book
publisher Andrew Stewart in 1989 or 1990 (reports differ). They
were married in 1961, when she was in her second year at Barnard
College, and had one child, Alexis.
</P>
<P>
   A 1991 article in the Detroit News reported that the divorce was
``a messy affair,'' adding that she cut off all questions about him
in an interview. An article this year in the Times of London went a
bit further, reporting that the divorce was ``so acrimonious that
Mr. Stewart reportedly sought a court order to stop his wife (from)
talking to him.'' The Times article said he subsequently married
one of his wife's former flower arrangers and had three more
children.
</P>
<P>
   A book, ``Just Desserts,'' by Jerry Oppenheimer, makes a number
of allegations about the Stewarts' relationship and divorce. Other
than that, Andrew Stewart has not been in the public eye, nor have
his recent activities been publicized.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The recent Concorde crash near Paris seemed remarklably
similar to one in Paris in the 1960s in which a number of prominent
Atlanta people lost their lives. Was a cause ever determined for
the earlier crash?
</P>
<P>
   A: Almost immediately after the crash of the chartered Air
France Boeing 707 on June 3, 1962, the airline released a history
of the aircraft stating that its weight during takeoff, the
prevailing wind conditions, and the length of runway available, all
were ``well within the limits.'' Accounts published later said
trouble developed as soon as the aircraft was beginning to roll for
takeoff at Orly Airport, and the pilot attempted to abort takeoff
by reversing the engines and locking the wheels.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, litigation finally was ended in what the book ``Atlanta
and Environs'' termed a hush-hush settlement. Before the case was
settled _ according to an account in the book's Volume III, written
by Harold Martin _ the chief attorneys for the plaintiffs had
alleged that there was ``willful misconduct on the part of the
airline because the Boeing 707's stabilizer was not set correctly
for takeoff and the pilot attempted to stop the plane after it had
passed the point on the runway where no attempt should be made to
stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 129 people who died in the crash, 114 were from Georgia.
Reports said the airline paid $5.2 million to the survivors of 62
people killed. Survivors of other crash victims settled with the
airline without litigation for undisclosed sums.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know basically what a baseball relief pitcher's ``save''
is, but can you explain the exact rules?
</P>
<P>
   A: A relief pitcher is credited with a save when he's the
finishing pitcher in a game won by his team; he's not the winning
pitcher; and he qualifies under one of these conditions: he enters
the game with a lead of no more than three runs and pitches for at
least one inning; or he enters the game with the potential tying
run on base, at bat, or on deck; or he pitches effectively for at
least three innings.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the National Council of Churches? Which denominations
make up its membership?
</P>
<P>
   A: The National Council of Churches _ full name, National
Council of the Churches of Christ in the USA _ describes itself as
``the nation's leading organization in the movement for Christian
unity.'' Formed in 1950, it's an agency of 35 Protestant, Orthodox
and Anglican denominations. Not a governing body, the council says
it ``promotes interchurch cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   The members: African Methodist Episcopal Church; African
Methodist Episcopal Zion Church; American Baptist Churches in the
USA; the Antiochian Orthodox Christian Archdiocese of North
America; Diocense of the Armenian Church of America; Christian
Church (Disciples of Christ); Christian Methodist Episcopal Church;
Church of the Brethren; the Coptic Orthodox Church in North
America;
</P>
<P>
   The Episcopal Church; Evangelical Lutheran Church in America;
Friends United Meeting; Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of North and
South America; Hungarian Reformed Church in America; International
Council of Community Churches; Korean Presbyterian Church in
America; Malankara Orthodox Syrian Church; Moravian Church in
American Northern Province and Southern Province; Mar Thoma Church;
</P>
<P>
   National Baptist Convention of America; National Baptist
Convention, U.S.A.; National Missionary Baptist Convention of
America; Orthodox Church in America; Patriachal Parishes of the
Russian Orthodox Church in the USA; Philadelphia Yearly Meeting of
the Religious Society of Friends; Polish National Catholic Church
of America; Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.); Progressive National
Baptist Convention;
</P>
<P>
   Reformed Church in America; Serbian Orthodox Church in the
U.S.A. and Canada; the Swedenborgian Church; Syrian Orthodox Church
of Antioch; Ukrainian Orthodox Church of America; United Church of
Christ; the United Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I keep hearing the word ``gravitas'' over and over on talk
shows. It is used concerning a political candidate. What does it
mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: Gravitas is a Latin word used to refer to a person's
character as conveying seriousness, dignity or authority, according
to Cassell's Latin Dictionary. It's the root word of ``gravity.''
The Compact Oxford English Dictionary, New Edition shows the Latin
word has been used by English speakers as meaning seriousness or
sobriety of conduct, bearing, speech or temperament; weighty
dignity; reverend seriousness or serious or solemn conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I always thought that Australia had seasons opposite to ours,
so does that mean that the Summer Olympics are actually being held
in their winter?
</P>
<P>
   A: The seasons in Australia are approximately six months
different than ours, says Dean Hutsell, a meteorologist for the
National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Sydney Summer Games are being held from Sept. 15
through Oct. 1. So that would be early spring in Australia while
it's the beginning of autumn in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
