r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS03-FILE     08-02 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS03-FILE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: FILE 2 OF 2
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Who does the government provide with security? Does the
Secret Service also protect members of the Supreme Court and
Congress?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Secret Service, an agency of the Treasury Department,
provides protection for the president, vice president, and their
families. They also protect presidential candidates, vice
presidential candidates, and their wives and children.
</P>
<P>
   The president can assign the Secret Service to anyone he feels
is in need of protection, according to James Cool, spokesman for
the Secret Service's Atlanta field office.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court Police protects the Supreme Court justices and
the U.S. Capitol Police protects members of the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When are the presidential candidates eligible for Secret
Service protection, and are their running mates, wives, children
and family also protected?
</P>
<P>
   A: When protection begins for a presidential candidate varies
with each candidate. The Secret Service said George W. Bush started
receiving protection in February.
</P>
<P>
   James Cool, the agency's spokesman in Atlanta, explained that
the secretary of the treasury, advised by the speaker of House, the
House minority leader, the Senate majority and minority leaders and
one additional member of Congress chosen by the first four, decide
when a candidate has sufficient support from the public and his
party to qualify for Secret Service protection.
</P>
<P>
   Agents currently are protecting Bush, his wife, Laura, and
recently named Republican vice presidential candidate Dick Cheney
and his wife, Lynne. Vice President Al Gore, his wife and children
continue to be protected as they have been throughout Gore's terms
as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read about protection pertaining to the president and vice
president, Supreme Court justices, members of Congress, and
presidential and vice presidential candidates, but what does the
Federal Protective Service do?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Federal Protective Service is part of the federal General
Services Administration, which is primarily responsibility for
administering and maintaining government buildings and vehicle
fleets. GSA spokeswoman Mildred Quinley said the agency also is
responsibile for protecting the buildings, the tenant in them, and
the surrounding property. The FPS also provides workshops on safety
for the tenants, and does outreach to residents of the surrounding
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many passengers does the Concorde carry?
</P>
<P>
   A: The supersonic Concorde generally carries 100 passengers. The
aircraft, however, was designed to carry a maximum of 144
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If George W. Bush is elected president, will this be the
first time that a father and son have been president?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. John Quincy Adams served as president of the United
States from 1825 until 1829. His father, John Adams, was president
from 1797 until 1801.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Didn't Bobby Jones, the great golfer during the 1920s and
'30s, win the Grand Slam also when he was about the same age as
Tiger Woods?
</P>
<P>
   A: When he was 28, Robert T. ``Bobby'' Jones won the Grand Slam,
that is, all four major championships of his time, in one year. No
one else has ever done that. Tiger Woods, 24, won the British Open
on July 23 and became the youngest man to have won all four majors
in his career.
</P>
<P>
   The four majors in 1930, the year Jones won the slam, were the
British Amateur, British Open, U.S. Open and U.S. Amateur.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Grand Slam events are the Masters, U.S. Open, British
Open and PGA Championship, and no longer include the amateur
championships. Woods won the U.S. and British Opens this year, the
PGA Championship last year, and the Masters in 1997. He also won
three consecutive U.S. Amateurs (1994-96).
</P>
<P>
   The next youngest golfer to win the career Grand Slam was Jack
Nicklaus, at age 26.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it true that golfer Bobby Jones never turned pro and was
always an amateur?
</P>
<P>
   A: Bobby Jones was an amateur golfer when, at age 28, he became
the first man to achieve the Grand Slam in golf. From 1923 through
1930, he won 13 championships in those four major annual
tournaments of the era: the British Amateur, British Open, U.S.
Open and U.S. Amateur.
</P>
<P>
   Jones never became a professional golfer, and rarely played in
tournaments after 1930. An attorney, he went on to practice law in
Atlanta. He died in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Professional golfers have traditionally used gold tees in
tournaments. What kind of tees do the women and senior players use?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Professional Golfers Association and the Ladies
Professional Golf Association say they do not have a standard tee
used during any
</P>
<P>
   of the tours. The golf courses and the rules officials for each
tournament select the type of tees used during individual
competitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``On tour, it's going to vary because of sponsors, so (you) can
go to four different tours and see four different colors,'' said
Kathy Lawrence, spokeswoman for the LPGA.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've been reading about problems with the overuse of
antibacterial products. Will regular soap and water remove the
harmful germs from your hands if you've been handling raw meat or
fish?
</P>
<P>
   A: Soap and water will do the trick, according to Judy Harrison
of the University of Georgia College of Family and Consumer
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to wash your hands to remove bacteria is to scrub
them for at least 20 seconds under warm running water, using soap
and rubbing your hands back and forth,'' Harrison said. The
friction loosens the bacterial cells and helps to rinse them
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: When a pilot breaks the sound barrier, does he hear the boom?
</P>
<P>
   A: Master Sgt. Larry Orluskie, a spokesman for the Air Force,
said pilots do not have any indication that they are breaking the
speed of sound other than the speed registered on the intruments in
the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't even have any sensation of how fast you're going,''
Orluskie said.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots do not hear booms, because the sound falls behind the
jet. A sonic boom forms because the fuselage breaks through the
pocket of air surrounding it when the aircraft reaches Mach speed
and breaks the sound barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Mach 1, the speed of sound, is about 750 mph at sea level and
approximately 660 mph at 30,000 feet above sea level.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A newspaper article reported that the Internal Revenue
Service owes money to people. Is there a Web site or some other way
to find out who is due a refund, and how to get it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Mark Green, a spokesman for the IRS, said there is not a Web
site for people to check whether they're due a refund. People with
questions, however, can call the IRS toll-free: 1-800-829-1040.
</P>
<P>
   An audit by the independent Treasury inspector general for tax
administration, David C. Williams, according to The Associated
Press, found that 29,820 of 436,00 tax payments should have been
refunded or credited to tax payers who filed returns late but
within the legal requirements of generally three years after the
initial due date -- usually April 15. The audit found that the
agency had not credited or refunded $25 million in income tax
overpayments.
</P>
<P>
   The audit was done on tax returns from taxpayers nationwide
whose records had been
</P>
<P>
   transferred as of March 1999 to the IRS Excess Collections
Account.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any reader who thinks money is due back can call that 800
number and we'll be happy to help them,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
