<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pomegranate: The politically exciting fruit
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anybody who says Dick Cheney is dull is nuts.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Gov. George W. Bush's running mate is pretty darned
interesting. Cheney, after all, is allergic to pomegranates.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some of you folks may be thinking to yourself, ``I don't
know if I could vote for a man who is allergic to pomegranates.''
Not so fast. This is an unusual trait. I know a guy who can play
the ``Aggie War Hymn'' under his armpit. But I don't think I
personally know anybody who is allergic to pomegranates, an obscure
squishy red fruit with a lot of seeds.
</P>
<P>
   The former secretary of defense has had three minor heart
attacks and bypass surgery. No big news there. You could fill Texas
Stadium with guys who have had three minor big ones and a go-around
job. But what sets Cheney apart from the rest of the field is that
he also is allergic to pomegranates. That's pretty exciting.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so it's not that exciting. But by major political candidate
standards these days, this is pretty exciting. I have a hard time
imagining Bush, Cheney, Al Gore, and the inevitable stiff Gore is
going to pick later as his running mate doing the Bunny Hop. Thanks
to Bill Clinton, both parties are distancing themselves from, uh,
exciting.
</P>
<P>
   So by comparison, this makes pomegranates pretty darned fun.
</P>
<P>
   There are special times in your life when you should seize the
moment because something this big may never land in your lap again.
</P>
<P>
   Such a moment came last week for the Pomegranate Council in San
Francisco when it was revealed in the news that Cheney is allergic
to pomegranates.
</P>
<P>
   Don't you just know that news people all over the world,
including myself, raced to the phone to call the Pomegranate
Council to gather important pomegranate information? It could have
been a key day in the history of the Pomegranate Council, because
I'll bet most of their calls are wrong numbers, or from
telemarketers trying to sell them discount auto insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, however, when I called the Pomegranate Council, Tom
Tjerandsen, the executive director, was on vacation in Africa. Even
more tragically, Tjerandsen had forwarded his phone calls to Jay
Bell, a business associate who doesn't know jack about
pomegranates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's news to me,'' Bell said, when I told him Cheney was
allergic to pomegranates. ``If you asked me a question about
raisins, I'd know all about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, buddy. Find me a candidate who is allergic to raisins and
call me back.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party ought to run with this pomegranate thing
this week at its national convention. Being allergic to
pomegranates is perhaps the most unusual thing you can say about
any of the major candidates. Unless Gore has a corn we don't know
about.
</P>
<P>
   Another step the Republicans could take to make Dick Cheney more
appealing to younger voters is to come up with a colorful nickname
for him. How about Dick ``Guitar'' Cheney? Or Dick ``Night Train''
Cheney, Dick ``He's Got His Mojo Workin' '' Cheney or Dick
``Lightnin' '' Cheney?
</P>
<P>
   How's this for a bumper sticker: Dick Cheney _ Hold the
Pomegranates.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso can be reached at 512-445-3606 or at
jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
