<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN0803-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV, nation tuning out candidates
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Forget what they say on the Sunday morning
news shows. The key to understanding this year's elections is The
Boredom Factor.
</P>
<P>
   This presidential election is going to see record levels of
voter absenteeism. Levels that go beyond apathy into something
resembling a voter boycott.
</P>
<P>
   This is a strange year. For the first time there was more
suspense in the Mexican presidential race than in the American.
</P>
<P>
   People running for Congress and state Cabinet and County Council
and Mosquito Control District will not be able to count on the
national race to scare up a few willing participants in democracy.
These candidates will need to get voters to the polls despite the
national race.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer, 75 percent of Americans were paying little
or no attention to the national elections, according to polling by
the Shorenstein Center on the Press, Politic and Public Policy. Its
Vanishing Voter Project found 69 percent of the public think the
presidential campaign is boring. Those numbers will go up, party
spokesmen say. Just wait for the conventions!
</P>
<P>
   There was a time of yore when political conventions were
bubbling cauldrons of party intrigue. Where platform positions were
fought out with fists and table legs. Where factions contended,
demonstrators outside howled, delegates walked out and decisions
were made.
</P>
<P>
   But the modern political convention is a combination trade show,
focus group and infomercial. The delegates are a mere studio
audience with its eye on the applause sign. The speakers display
the product line with the wit and spontaneity of Academy Awards
presenters. No wonder the broadcast networks are planning not much
more than four hours of convention coverage.
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons for this lack of interest. But let's be
clear: It is not because people are dumb, uninformed and don't give
a hoot about their country.
</P>
<P>
   One big reason is the lack of anything like a meaningful primary
process. One that road-tested themes and forced candidates to meet
real people. Money and party discipline nipped all that in the bud.
</P>
<P>
   But more important, people have rightly sensed that the things
candidates are saying have little connection with real life. Does
anyone really vote for a candidate baselues day on the campaign,
and Bush is famous for staying on-theme.
</P>
<P>
   And that's indicative of the kind of presidential campaign we've
got and conventions we're getting _ clean, on-theme and like a
machine.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the nation is tuning out. Their time will be better
spent listening to their school board candidates. And the weather
outside is so nice.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at mark.lane(at)news-jrnl.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
