<HEADLINE>
FALL FASHION IS GLAMOROUS AND FEMININE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release August 2, 2000.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's TRENDS-NEXTGEN column. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of TRENDS-NEXTGEN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  FALL
<TEXT>
<P>
   I know there's still plenty of summer ahead of us, but it's not
too early to check out the hot fashions for fall. When it comes to
fashion, no one seems more interested (or influential) than today's
Gen Xers and Whyers. These are among their must-haves:
</P>
<P>
   COLORS
</P>
<P>
   When the economy is good, people tend to shy away from dour
colors and prefer a look in line with their upbeat attitude. True
to this spirit, fall will bring us many purples (it is the shade of
royalty, you know), plums and berry colors. But burnt orange and
olive will also abound. Some designers are also showing lots of
bright red.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, as they say, will be this year's black _ the
go-everywhere, do-anything color for fall _ but by spring we may
well see white, beige and black on the runways and in trendsetting
wardrobes.
</P>
<P>
   And, in fact, the most interesting innovation in color isn't a
color at all. It's the use of texture and sheen. From opalescent to
iridescent, fabrics are being designed to reflect light, flow as
you move and make you look like a mermaid out of water.
</P>
<P>
   ACCESSORIES
</P>
<P>
   This season, all eyes will be on the details. Forget the big
snakeskin skirts of spring and the hardly-there halter tops of
summer. Fall will produce a crop of classy ladies decked out in
strands of pearls. But if you can't see yourself in the preppy
look, go for the gold. From chain belts to big hoop earrings, the
hottest accessories will glitter.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest trend for fall may well be a freestanding fur
collar. However, as someone who is anti-fur, I'd forego the entries
from Prada and Michael Kors and instead find something faux but
equally fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   As for shoes, well, no one ever said that it was easy or
comfortable to be fashionable. This season's sellers will make you
wish for espadrilles. Stiletto boots will soar to new heights in
everything from snakeskin to supple leather. But if your feet just
can't stand the pinch, go for some semi-open-toed heels that look a
bit _ and I mean only a bit _ more practical.
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS
</P>
<P>
   From herringbone to stripes, checks to plaid, fall fashion looks
like a cross between jackets from the Friars Club and your old
girl's school uniform. Oversized geometric prints and art deco
images abound. This year, the patterns are bigger and bolder than
in the past. You'll have to decide whether they're better.
</P>
<P>
   SUITS
</P>
<P>
   Look, it's not my fault, but the '80's are back with everything
from leg warmers to power suits. The good news? Women are embracing
suits because they want to, not because they feel they have to
dress like a man. Suits for the fall are very feminine and free and
a welcome relief from the snug skirts of spring.
</P>
<P>
   TRENCH COATS
</P>
<P>
   The great thing about this trend is you'll actually look forward
to rainy days. Today's trenches are made of funky material combined
with fashionable cuts. It is, as they say, the key outerwear
statement for the fall!
</P>
<P>
   BIASED TOWARD BLOUSES
</P>
<P>
   From satin blouses to slash-front blouses, sheer blouses to
cape-sleeved ones, blouses are more interesting than ever. Most of
them are feminine, relaxed and even fun. Gone are over-structured
and over-stiff shirts. This fall, look for free-flowing fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   GLAMORAMA
</P>
<P>
   When in doubt this fall, dress up rather than down. That doesn't
necessarily mean it's time to break out the tiaras _ although, on
second thought, sure, why not? But forget the sweat pants as well
as the hippie thing. Instead think lady-like glamour and elegance.
</P>
<P>
   DESIGNERS
</P>
<P>
   If you have money to burn, run to buy whatever you can from
Miguel Androver, Michael Kors, YSL and Christian Dior. But if your
budget is more limited, try Katayone Adeli, Theory, Rebecca
Dannenberg and William B, who follow fashion but at a more
reasonable price. I'm also a big fan of Club Monaco and Express,
both very affordable _ and if you're in New York City, be sure to
stop by the new H&AMP;M store at 51st St. and Fifth Ave. where the
lines are long but you can get hip outfits for such a low price you
can practically toss them out as soon as they go out of style.
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
<P>
   BE ON THE LOOKOUT FOR:
</P>
<P>
   Anklets
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Ghost (singer)
</P>
<P>
   Joey cosmetics
</P>
<P>
   Jane Rinzler Buckingham is the president of Youth Intelligence,
a market-research firm specializing in the 7- to 35-year-old
market. Her company publishes the Cassandra Report, a comprehensive
survey focused on identifying emerging trends among Generations X
and Why?
</P>
<P>
   -----------------------------
</P>
