A0417 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN03-COX     08-02 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will Bush's use of Clintonian tactics come back to haunt him?
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When non-Texas Democrats learned that Gov. George W. Bush was a
likely Republican presidential candidate, they immediately
ridiculed Bush's message of ``compassionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   These Democrats felt they owned compassion. They considered the
words ``Republican'' and ``compassion,'' or even ``conservative''
and ``compassion,'' as polar opposites _ notions that could not be
put together without violating the laws of nature.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ridicule and charges of hypocrisy, Bush stuck with
his message through the primaries and on to the Republican
convention in Philadelphia where compassionate conservatism is
choreographed for all the world to see.
</P>
<P>
   The opening night of the Republican convention either proved
that the Democratic charges of hypocrisy are correct or that Bush
really is a new breed of Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's wife, Laura, talked about her husband's values. She
talked about her husband's commitment to education where no child
would be left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Colin Powell, a man who probably could have become the
first African American president in 1992 or 1996 had he chosen to
run, was the keynote speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Powell and Mrs. Bush advanced the message that the
Republican Party needed and wanted women, minorities, independents
and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   A lively African American gospel choir on stage followed a live
remote feed of a black preacher at a gospel church in South
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Powell received applause from the Republican conventioneers when
he talked about the need to support affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party must follow Gov. Bush's lead and reach out to
minority communities, and particularly the African American
community, and not just during an election-year campaign,'' Powell
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be a sustained effort,'' he continued. ``It must be
every day. It must be for real.'' The Republican convCould these be
the same Republicans who tried to scrap the Department of
Education, who heard former Republican presidential candidate Pat
Buchanan declare a cultural war, who proposed a constitutional
amendment to deny citizenship to children born in America if their
parents were ``not long-term residents,'' or who have opposed
affirmative action quotas and preferences for minorities and women?
</P>
<P>
   Democrats who say it's all an act may be speaking from
experience. They have given their unswerving support to Bill
Clinton and Al Gore, who invented New Democrats. Their invention,
introduced in the 1992 presidential campaign, called for filching
all the traditional Republican campaign issues to show that they
were realistic liberals.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Gore defined New Democrats as champions of welfare
reform, free trade, tougher crime laws, a stronger military, a
balanced budget and other traditional GOP positions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush likes to say that his presidency will be guided by
principles and not by public opinion polls. It's impossible to know
if that claim is accurate until Bush is elected and builds a track
record.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Gore administration has a track record of flip flops
based on public opinion polls. The administration dropped support
of friends, appointees, programs and positions based on polling
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   By and large, Democrats have supported the Clinton-Gore shift to
``New Democrats'' by claiming it was smart politics to steal
traditional Republican issues and gain wider public support.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether Bush is doing the same thing or if he
means what he says. It's informative that in Texas many old-line
and religious right Republicans consider Bush their enemy. History
will be the best judge of charges of hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is the Senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald . E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
