<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 12:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0444 &Cx1f; tab-z
u d BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV23-     08-02 1404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV23-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV23  
 HEALTHY 20-MINUTE MENUS: VEGETABLES AS THE MAIN ATTRACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDITORS: For use Wednesday, Aug. 23, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's 20MINUTE-MENUS. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of 20MINUTE-MENUS _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 Foxcraft Ltd.    
<TEXT>
<P>
   An entire column devoted to vegetables is not going to appeal to
you if you are someone who prefers steak. Still this column is
dedicated to you because I think that if you will just give these
vegetables one chance, any of these recipes you will change your
mind, however grudgingly, about how good vegetables can taste.
</P>
<P>
   I admit I have chosen the time of year to tempt you when most
vegetables are at their peak: they are local; they are still fresh
and maybe they are even organic.
</P>
<P>
   Stop and think about it for a minute. Don't you just love corn?
That's a vegetable. And Baba Ghannouj, the side dish or dip that is
served at so many parties: it's main ingredient is eggplant. Even
if you are not an arugula fan, when you pair it with goat cheese
and mango, how could you possibly turn it down?
</P>
<P>
   To make these dishes even more appealing here are a few hints.
</P>
<P>
   The corn I added to the Baba Ghannouj _ certainly not a
traditional version of the dish _ gives texture and a bit of
sweetness to the eggplant. But remember many of the modern breeds
of corn, like the supersweets, barely call for cooking at all.
Forget the three minute rule and think, instead of the 30 second
rule. In fact I've eaten supersweets uncooked. Oh yes, don't salt
corn water before cooking: it makes the skin of the kernels tough.
</P>
<P>
   The mango in the arugula salad should be ripe but still very
firm so there is a lot of acid left in it. Its texture provides a
nice contrast to the crispness of the arugula and the softness of
the cheese.
</P>
<P>
   I created the zucchini and tomato recipe because I was given the
Japanese version of a mandoline, a French piece of equipment that
slices food thinner than possible by hand. But the Japanese version
of the mandoline is not only considerably cheaper than the French
it also works better. Many kitchen equipment stores carry the
Japanese slicer, but you can also try a Japanese market if you have
one nearby. I sliced everything on it for this dish: the onions,
squashes, tomatoes and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Baba Ghannouj, the zucchini-tomato dish can be prepared
a day ahead and refrigerated covered. Take the chill off the Baba
Ghannouj before serving, off the zucchini dish before cooking.
</P>
<P>
   BABA GHANNOUJ
</P>
<P>
   2 two-pound eggplant
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil pan spray
</P>
<P>
   1 large ear corn
</P>
<P>
   2 large cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons tahini
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons plain, nonfat yogurt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   Few shakes salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Garnish cilantro or parsley sprigs
</P>
<P>
   1. Turn broiler on. Cover broiler pans with aluminum foil. Wash
and dry eggplant; trim off ends and slice the rest of each eggplant
in 1/2 inch thick slices. Arrange slices on foil-covered pan (will
probably have to do this in two batches). Spray each slice with pan
spray and place on lowest shelf in broiler. Broil eggplant on one
side until it browns, 5 to 7 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, shuck corn and cook quickly in a little water or
steam.
</P>
<P>
   3. With food processor running add garlic through feed tube. Add
tahini, yogurt, lemon juice and cumin. Remove and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   4. Remove corn and cool.
</P>
<P>
   5. Turn eggplant, spray with pan spray and continue broiling
until the second side is browned and slices are soft, another few
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   6. When eggplant is soft, remove and cool until it can be
handled. Then remove the skin, place the flesh in the processor
bowl and puree.
</P>
<P>
   7. Stir the puree into the tahini mixture. Remove kernels from
corn and stir into the eggplant-tahini mixture. Season with salt
and pepper. Garnish with washed, dried cilantro or parsley sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 as side dish.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil pan spray
</P>
<P>
   Garlic
</P>
<P>
   Plain nonfat yogurt
</P>
<P>
   Lemon
</P>
<P>
   Ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Whole black pepper
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   2 two-pound eggplant
</P>
<P>
   1 large ear corn
</P>
<P>
   Small jar sesame tahini (sesame paste)
</P>
<P>
   Bunch cilantro or parsley for garnish (few sprigs)
</P>
<P>
   ARUGULA, MANGO AND GOAT CHEESE
</P>
<P>
   1 medium bunch arugula
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sherry wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 large ripe but firm mango
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh reduced-fat goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   Few shakes salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1. Remove tough stems from arugula and thoroughly wash and dry.
</P>
<P>
   2. In salad bowl whisk the oil and vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cut mango flesh into bite-size cubes. Add the arugula and
mango to the salad bowl. Sprinkle with salt and pepper and crumble
over the cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 to 3 servings.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Sherry wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Whole black pepper
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   1 medium bunch arugula
</P>
<P>
   1 large ripe but firm mango
</P>
<P>
   Small log reduced-fat goat cheese (3 tablespoons)
</P>
<P>
   PARMIGIANO BAKED ZUCCHINI, TOMATOES AND ONIONS
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds red onions
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds ripe tomatoes, any color
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds zucchini and yellow squash mixed
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup packed cut basil strips
</P>
<P>
   5 ounces thinly sliced Parmigiano-Reggiano
</P>
<P>
   Few shakes salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1. Thinly slice the onions.
</P>
<P>
   2. Heat a very large nonstick pan until it is very hot. Reduce
heat to medium high, add the oil and onions and saute until onions
brown and soften.
</P>
<P>
   3. Meanwhile, very thinly slice the tomatoes and add to the
sauteed onions, cooking until liquid from tomatoes has evaporated.
Watch carefully or vegetables will burn.
</P>
<P>
   4. Wash, trim and very thinly slice the squash; wash and slice
the basil into strips; thinly slice the cheese.
</P>
<P>
   5. Divide the zucchini in half. Arrange half evenly in bottom of
shallow baking pan. Top with tomato onion mixture; top with half of
Parmigiano and the basil. Arrange the remaining squash on top;
season with salt and pepper and top with cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerate, if desired, covered with wax paper.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, preheat oven to 350 degrees and bake about 30 minutes,
until squashes are soft and cheese is browned. If the dish has been
refrigerated allow it to sit at room temperature for a half-hour
before baking
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings as side dish; 2 to 3 servings as main
dish.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Whole black pepper
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds red onions
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds ripe tomatoes, any colors
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds zucchini and yellow squash, mixed
</P>
<P>
   Bunch basil (1/3 cup strips)
</P>
<P>
   5 ounces Parmigiano-Reggiano
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING:
</P>
<P>
   BABA GHANNOUJ _ 155 calories, 6 grams fat, 0 saturated fat, 0
cholesterol, 55 milligrams sodium, 24 grams carbohydrates, 7 grams
fiber, 5 grams protein.
</P>
<P>
   ARUGULA SALAD _ 205 calories, 9 grams fat, 4 grams saturated
fat, 10 milligrams cholesterol, 165 milligrams sodium, 30 grams
carbohydrate, 3 grams fiber, 6 grams protein.
</P>
<P>
   TOMATO ZUCCHINI SALAD _ 275 calories, 13 grams fat, less than 1
gram saturated fat, 20 milligrams cholesterol, 240 milligrams
sodium, 25 grams carbohydrate, 7 grams fiber, 15 grams protein.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
