<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0448 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-RESTORATION-08     08-02 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-RESTORATION-0803-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMERICAN ARCHITECT HELPS TO RESTORE RUSSIAN HERITAGE
 &HT;    With Photos in the International folder on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARKANGELSKOE, Russia _ In these halls trimmed in gold leaf and
adorned with elaborate frescos, coat-tailed men and bejeweled women
waltzed all night in annual balls that were the talk of salons from
St. Petersburg to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   In the shadows of flickering candles, swirling feet and
sumptuous feasts that epitomized 18th-Century European grandeur
were up to 20,000 serfs. They, like African slaves in the old
American South, grew crops, tended horses, cooked and cleaned house
until the Bolshevik Revolution swept this lifestyle and their
owners into the dustbin of history.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the homes that sparked literary masterpieces and
political upheaval lay mostly forgotten, in heaps of crumbling
plaster and overgrown weeds _ a neglect that a dedicated group of
Russians and Americans, including Atlanta architect Rodney M. Cook
Jr., hope to remedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame to let history be forgotten. These beautiful
buildings were of unique designs and home to untold treasures. We
in America and the rest of the world don't know what's here,'' Cook
told Cox Newspapers. ``We should.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook recently completed a two-week tour of Russia along with the
American Friends of Russian Estate Homes, a fund started in 1997 by
Priscilla Roosevelt, a great-niece of former U.S. President
Franklin D. Roosevelt. Its goal is to help restore Russian manors
as national museums.
</P>
<P>
   With the aid of seed money attracted through the Washington
D.C.-based fund, they hope to rebuild the stately homes and turn
these national monuments into money-making enterprises supported by
a tourist infrastructure that includes hotels, restaurants and
roads _ all in short supply in post-Soviet Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a project to revive local pride, local history and local
economies. It shouldn't take a dedicated traveler to tackle the
Russian countryside and uncover these homes,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, the designer of Atlanta's World Athletes Monument, is a
lifelong devotee of Russian culture, especially its architecture.
His fascination with Russian manors started as a boy, when he
remembers searching in vain for details about rare photographs of
old palaces and buildings in St. Petersburg and other Russian
cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the ache I would feel as a kid trying to find out
about these things. But it was the 'Evil Empire.' Everything
Russian was off-limits,'' he recalled. ``It was back then that I
caught what Priscilla and I call the 'Russian disease.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Cook boasts the second-largest private library of Russian
architecture books in the United States. He has even embellished
his Buckhead home with Russian flourishes, including onion domes
and an Orthodox cross on the roof.
</P>
<P>
   His own infatuation aside, Cook says there is plenty to draw
tourists to Russian estate homes; from the elegant, exotic
furnishings to the similarities with the old Southern plantation
homes that can still be found in places like South Carolina's low
country and Natchez, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Arkangelskoe, a 10-acre sprawling estate some 15 miles from
Moscow's Kremlin and one of three estates that Roosevelt's
non-profit group is working with, is reminiscent of famous U.S.
landmarks. The main building, the living quarters for the former
owner, Prince Nikolai Usupov, is lined with columns like Thomas
Jefferson's Monticello and topped with a dome like the Capitol
rotunda in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules of building (both plantation homes and Russian
estates) were the same. The only thing that differed was the
climate,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   The bitter Russian climate and neglect of the properties during
70 years of Soviet rule are the two biggest reasons why the
mansions are in disrepair.
</P>
<P>
   At Arkangelskoe, Usupov had built a magnificent 200-seat
theater, where for nearly a century guests of his family would
enjoy art and music while perched in blue, velvet seats in a
wood-paneled hall. Now, the theater's roof is collapsing,
endangering a priceless art collection.
</P>
<P>
   With Cook's help, the theater has been named by the World
Monument Fund as one of the world's 100 most endangered sights.
This listing brought the directors of the Arkangelskoe (pronounced,
``ark-an-gul-skoy-ya'') museum their first foreign grants totaling
nearly $1 million to rebuild the theater. Now, Arkangelskoe is
looking for funds for the other 13 buildings on the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Yuri Lomakin, Arkangelskoe's vice director, says he has an
accurate idea of how the estate looked in its heyday. The details
are known through records kept by the Usupovs, as well as letters
penned by famous writers and diplomats who visited the sprawling
manor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have details about everything, from the colors of the walls
and the type of wood needed for parquet floors. We now have money
we need to restore. The only enemy standing between us and our goal
is time,'' said Lomakin, who oversaw the renovation at Moscow's
famous Tretyakov Art Gallery, which now draws more visitors and
more money than during Soviet rule.
</P>
<P>
   The first order of business at Arkangelskoe is to rebuild roofs
and walls to protect the art before the onset of winter. Once that
job is done, Lomakin said he would need another two years to get
Arkangelskoe's other buildings restored and a hotel built to
accommodate tourists.
</P>
<P>
   In between other projects, including the Millennium monument in
Washington, Cook expects to return to Russia to consult with
Lomakin and other craftsmen. He says cooperation is the key to
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russians want to revive these symbols of national heritage,
and we want to help them. With us both working together, we should
be fine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information see:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.nationaltrust.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
