<HEADER>
A0455 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-MUSIC-ALJARREAU-HNS &LR;      08-02 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ALJARREAU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
JAZZ MASTER &HT;    By MICHAEL D. CLARK
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five-time Grammy winner. The only singer in history to win
best-vocalist awards in three categories _ jazz, pop and R&AMP;B. A
tenor larynx so uniquely clotted with cream it draws comparisons to
Johnny Mathis.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to know which title best suits Al Jarreau.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can call me Al,'' laughs the golden-voiced singer,
crooning the chorus from the 1986 Paul Simon hit of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   Jarreau is calling from a hotel in Nice on the French Riviera,
an apple's throw from the Mediterranean. It's nearly 11 p.m.
paradise time, but the 60-year-old singer hasn't yet eaten dinner
or settled into his evening.
</P>
<P>
   With a tour schedule to keep, a band to front and a new album of
smooth R&AMP;B and jazz, ``Tomorrow Today,'' to promote, it's tough to
wind down. Jarreau may be in his third decade of recording music,
but his energy level still runs like that of a clubbing young
jazzman.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after this conversation, Jarreau was scheduled to
head back to the United States to headline the first Montreux
Festival on Tour. A traveling version of the premier Swiss jazz
celebration, the show also features Roberta Flack, saxophonist
David Sanborn, Houston-born jazz pianist Joe Sample and the George
Duke All-Star Band.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I can turn on a fastball like I used to, but
I've found something in my life that makes me feel healthy,''
Jarreau says. ``I simply woke up on March 12 (his birthday) and
said, `Thank God I'm alive.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jarreau is much more than alive. He's revitalized. In recent
years, fans have seen him stretch from the concert stage to the
theater spotlight. He sang ``Teen Angel'' in the Broadway
production of ``Grease'' and did a guest spot on TV's ``Touched by
an Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   Musically, Jarreau spent a 19-year career on the Warner
Bros.-Reprise label but left the music giant after 1994's
``Tenderness'' album. He spent his hiatus from the studio working
on classical music, singing Bach and modern pieces by composer Lou
Harrison with the California Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow Today'' marks his return to recording the smooth jazz
and adult-contemporary music that have made his voice as distinct
as Nat King Cole's once was. After moving to Universal's GRP label,
a sister label of the Verve Music Group, Jarreau is recording on
the same brand name as did such past jazz greats as Ella Fitzgerald
and Count Basie.
</P>
<P>
   GRP/Verve is a much better fit for an artist like Jarreau. When
he started with Warner Bros.-Reprise, it catered mostly to artists
such as Joni Mitchell, Frank Sinatra and Eric Clapton. These days
it's better-known for younger, rock-oriented acts, such as Green
Day, Filter and Alanis Morissette.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leaving Reprise was as amicable as necessary separations can
be,'' Jarreau says. ``It was evident that I didn't fit in with
their interests anymore. (GRP/Verve) knows what I need. They've
been doing it for great artists for some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Reprise did not return phone calls regarding the
separation. Jarreau may not fit with its current lineup, but the
absence of his human harp of a voice is definitely a loss.
</P>
<P>
   A breathy, tailing collection of high notes, his croons have
sparked many romances, highlighted many weddings and even turned on
many TV sets. He was a Tuesday night prime-time mainstay when he
sang the theme song to the popular '80s Bruce Willis-Cybill
Shepherd detective comedy-drama ``Moonlighting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thrill still comes from the guy on the street who
remembers a record or a song and says to me, `Al, I just wanted to
come over, shake your hand and say thanks,''' Jarreau says.
``That's a bigger thrill than a singer who says he wants to sing
like me.''
</P>
<P>
   His many studio albums have been well-received, but it was his
first live recording that won him critical and peer favor. ``Look
to the Rainbow'' earned him his first Grammy for best jazz vocal
performance in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   The double album was a masterpiece of scats and vocal
intonation. Jarreau was backed by a crack jazz quartet of
vibraphonist Lynn Blessing, keyboardist Tom Canning, bassist Abe
Laboriel and drummer Joe Carrero. Crisp live performances also have
been the linchpin keeping his career vital, especially during his
recent time between record labels.
</P>
<P>
   ``My work on the stage is a shared experience. The audience is
the other instrument,'' Jarreau says. ``The studio can fix things
and go back and change things. Live is raw, and I come from that.''
</P>
<P>
   His personal influences, Mathis and Cole, also come from the
live tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Jarreau never met Cole, who died in 1965, at age 47, of lung
cancer. He says that he and Mathis have been in the same room only
once, and that was during the 1985 studio sessions for the USA for
Africa benefit song ``We Are the World.''
</P>
<P>
   The obvious idea of trying to get Mathis and Jarreau on tour
together is mentioned, and the notion excites Jarreau.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gives me an idea,'' Jarreau says. ``People know that
Johnny can sing, but most don't know that he can also swing. I'd
love to tour with him, even if it was just a brief holiday tour of
seasonal music.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarreau has worked with and alongside a bevy of other
celebrities in his career. He and a young Harrison Ford were
classmates at small Ripon College in Wisconsin in the late '50s and
early '60s. The list of artists he's worked with runs from David
Benoit and Chick Corea to Nile Rodgers and Quincy Jones.
</P>
<P>
   His new album is as packed with guest stars as Carlos Santana's
``Supernatural'' was last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Puddit,'' a remake of Sample's Jazz Crusaders number ``Put It
Where You Want It,'' features the pianist and is newly ornamented
with lyrics by Jarreau. Another instrumental for which Jarreau
supplied lyrics is ``Something That You Said,'' featuring trumpeter
Rick Braun. Fans of the Weather Report may recognize the tune
formerly called ``A Remark You Made.''
</P>
<P>
   The adult-radio pop of the duet ``God's Gift to the World,''
with Vanessa Williams, is accompanied by such romantic mood music
as ``Let Me Love You,'' featuring sax lines by Boney James. It's
contrasted with the salsa and scat of the title track and the soul
groove of ``In My Music.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarreau hints that he and Sample might play ``Puddit'' on tour.
He offers little else about what fans can expect with him, Sample,
Flack, Sanborn and Duke in the same building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being involved with Montreux is special,'' says Jarreau, who
follows in the footsteps of Count Basie, Miles Davis and Chuck
Berry. All played the festival when it was an annual event in the
Swiss city it's named for.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shows will be a celebration of tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Just call his voice a treasure.
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
