u l BC-BADSPORTS-TIPS-HNS &LR;      08-02 0178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BADSPORTS-TIPS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
BADSPORTS-TIPS &HT;    BE A GOOD SPORT
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are some tips on how to be a model youth-sports parent:
</P>
<P>
   1. Remember that where we practice and play games is like your
child's classroom _ respect the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   2. Make only positive, encouraging comments to the players on
both teams.
</P>
<P>
   3. Making mistakes is part of the learning process _ don't
criticize.
</P>
<P>
   4. Discuss your concern away from the players and, in
particular, away from your child.
</P>
<P>
   5. Respect the officials.
</P>
<P>
   6. Focus on fun and participation rather than winning and
losing.
</P>
<P>
   7. Control your emotions.
</P>
<P>
   8. Learn the rules of your child's sport.
</P>
<P>
   9. Reinforce the coach's instructions when practicing with your
child at home.
</P>
<P>
   10. Remember, positive reinforcement is the key to improvement.
</P>
<P>
   11. Don't undermine team morale.
</P>
<P>
   12. Participate in team activities.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Source: National Alliance for Youth Sports (http://nays.org) &LR;  &QL; 
X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
