<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0462 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-BADSPORTS-2TAKES-HNS &LR;      08-02 1379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BADSPORTS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHINERS AND LOSERS: IN THE GAME OF GOOD SPORTS, MANY PARENTS AND
FANS ARE FOULING OUT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo; sidebar, BADSPORTS-TIPS) &HT;    By DANIEL J. VARGAS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED)_They can strike terror on the field _ huffing and
puffing at the referee, stomping their feet and swearing up a new
storm of the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of (bleeping) call was that, zebra?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ref, you $%!''
</P>
<P>
   Not the kids. These are the parents. Adults who drive their
children by minivan to sporting events that traditionally preach
sportsmanship over winning.
</P>
<P>
   Lately it seems that once they set foot near an athletic field,
some moms, dads and coaches lose their grasp on sportsmanship,
civility _ even reality.
</P>
<P>
   A Massachusetts man is accused of fatally beating another father
this month in a dispute over a youth hockey game. The father and
coach of a Little Leaguer in Florida broke an umpire's jaw because
he disliked a call. And a Virginia mother slapped a 14-year-old
official during a soccer game.
</P>
<P>
   Youth sports experts and referees say parents are becoming
increasingly involved in their children's sports activities, and
they need to learn two things: the rules of the game and the rules
of conduct for spectators.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston area lacks clinics or workshops dedicated to
teaching parents how to behave at their children's baseball, soccer
or basketball games.
</P>
<P>
   But that's about to change.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   Shifting directions &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Timberline Youth Soccer Association will have an online
training class for parents by fall. It will teach them the basic
rules of soccer and sideline etiquette and give them parenting
tips. Parents who complete the course will receive a discount on
membership fees.
</P>
<P>
   The association, which handles games for about 11,000 kids who
live north of Houston, is launching the class because of parental
behavior problems, says president Ed Loucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big problem. It really is,'' Loucks says. ``I don't
want to blow it out of proportion, but I don't want to minimize it,
either. We've got about 10 percent of the people causing 100
percent of the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past year a parent was banned from games for bumping
a referee, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Loucks says most of the troublemakers are parents who want to
relive their glory days or make up for their dismal sports careers
through their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognized a couple of years ago that parents' expectations
of their kids far exceeded their abilities,'' he says. ``So now
we're working on education to give parents some yardsticks to
measure their kids _ in the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   Loucks can speak this way of other parents because, well, he was
one of them.
</P>
<P>
   He was never abusive to coaches or referees, he says, but he was
guilty of ``over-encouraging'' his teen-age daughter. This from a
father who played in a state championship football game 25 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pushed her too hard,'' Loucks recalls. ``I would stand on
the side of the field and shout instructions at her: `Look over
your shoulder!' `Watch the ball!' You spend so much time trying to
make them the best they can be, you forget they just want to have
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, it happened. His daughter spoke up after a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said `You know, I'd have more fun if you didn't yell so
much,''' Loucks says.
</P>
<P>
   So he changed for the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an example of a bad parent gone good,'' Loucks says. ``And
others can do it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   Model programs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, the Jupiter-Tequesta Athletic Association, which has
about 6,000 kids in six sports including baseball and soccer,
requires parents to attend such a workshop. Otherwise their
children don't play. This group was the first in the nation to make
such a bold move in November 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit National Alliance for Youth Sports, based in West
Palm Beach, Fla., offers a national program called Parents
Association for Youth Sports, which provides training and a code of
ethics for parents. Only three such programs are in place in Texas
_ in Copperas Cove, El Paso and Nueces County (Corpus Christi).
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents are behaving and acting the way they do because no one
has ever told them they couldn't,'' says Fred Engh, founder and
president of the national alliance and the author of ``Why Johnny
Hates Sports.`` ``No one is there to tell them if they keep acting
like this, they're out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   He contends that parents, coaches and administrators should take
orientation courses, sign a code of ethics and be held accountable
for bad behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``This finally raises the standards for children's sports,''
Engh says. ``Implement this, and you will have a dramatic change
(in parents' behavior).''
</P>
<P>
   Parents interested in the association's program for parents,
which costs $5 to join, should tell the directors of their leagues,
clubs or associations, who can contact the national alliance about
creating a chapter.
</P>
<P>
   Once a chapter is approved, parents then sign up and watch
training videos, participate in a discussion with other parents and
sign an 11-item Parents' Code of Ethics pledge. They then get
buttons with positive slogans to wear at games _ reminders to be on
their best behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Slogans include ``Having fun is No. 1'' and ``All kids are
winners'' and ``Good sports make good sports.''
</P>
<P>
   About 5,000 parents nationwide have gone through the alliance's
training program since it began in February, Engh says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Aggressive behavior &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Still, spokesman for the 19,000-member National Association
of Sports Officials, says referees saw an increase in violence
coming years ago, among both players and spectators.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been more physical contact with officials than ever
before,'' he says. ``We're a more violent society, and sports is
life with the violence turned up.''
</P>
<P>
   Still says parents and coaches have lost touch with what youth
sports are supposed to be about: sportsmanship, physical fitness
and fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think today we're teaching `gamesmanship' _ do whatever it
takes to win the game,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Ellinger, a Houston lawyer who has been a referee for 25
years, is an advocate of more parental education.
</P>
<P>
   He says people see coaches berating officials and players
striking coaches in college and professional games, and they think
it's ``fashionable'' to be aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   At youth sports games, he says, this scenario is common: parents
who know little about the game, no security and inexperienced
officials. The result: rampant verbal and physical abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier for a parent to yell at the official than go
through a training class,'' Ellinger says. ``If ignorance is bliss,
then there are a lot of happy people out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, who officiates high school, college and semipro games,
says officials are quitting because they're tired of being berated
by parents and coaches. In youth sports, most officials are working
as volunteers or for little pay. The field is seeing a nationwide
shortage at all levels, Still says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many good officials are turning around saying they no longer
want to do this,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen states have laws that provide stiff penalties for
assaults on sports officials, Still says. He expects the Texas
Legislature to take up the issue during the 2001 session.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a representative of authority, it's no different than
hitting a police officer,'' Still says.
</P>
<P>
   He says leagues should develop or implement an education program
for parents. If such a program doesn't modify a parent's bad
behavior, then that parent should be banned from the league, Still
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be zero tolerance,'' he says. ``Leagues need to
step up and manage themselves properly. They need to be able to
say, `We don't need this person around.' It's for the greater good
of everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   The right way to act &LR;
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Alliance for Youth Sports, a 1999
survey of 500 adults found that 82 percent believe parents behave
too aggressively at youth sports events. Fifty-six percent said
they had seen such behavior, and 72 percent said such aggressive
parents should be banned from youth sports.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   To get back on the right track, Engh says, parents must first
give their children unconditional support.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are growing and developing lifelong characteristics of
who they will become,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid negative criticism and derogatory language.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never, never humiliate them,'' says Engh, a father of seven.
``That will destroy your relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Let your children choose the sports they want to play.
</P>
<P>
   It's OK to cheer and clap in the stands, he says. But don't tell
them they made a mistake. They already know it.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, tell your children that it's OK to lose or to fail.
``Tell them they can learn from it,'' Engh says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   Reaction &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Randy Conger, president of the Bay Area Youth Soccer Association
south of Houston, says the last violent episode in his association
happened in April 1999, when a teen-age player punched a
19-year-old referee.
</P>
<P>
   The player was suspended for a year by the South Texas Youth
Soccer Association and has not reapplied to the Bay Area
association, Conger says.
</P>
<P>
   Some referees drop out because of parents' behavior, says
Conger, who's been involved in youth soccer for 16 years. But
despite high-profile instances of violence in youth sports, he
isn't expecting a drop in participation when play begins in
September. Bay Area has 17 clubs with about 10,000 kids ages 4-18.
</P>
<P>
   Conger says the South Texas association is finalizing a code of
ethics for parents, coaches, managers and players. It should be
ready by February, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been wanting it for a couple of years,'' he says. ``I
think anything that will make the game safer, we could all use.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the association created sportsmanship awards
for 6- and 7-year-olds and their coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes everyone remember why they are there,'' Conger says.
</P>
<P>
   Conger says education may help curb the problem. The Bay Area
association offers coaching clinic for parents so that they can
gain a better understanding of the game. About 30 percent take
advantage of that, Conger says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   Better safe than sorry &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Timberline Youth Soccer Association expects _ and wants _
thousands of parents at its games this fall. The overwhelming
majority will be supportive of all players, coaches and referees.
</P>
<P>
   To monitor the rest though, the association is going to dispatch
its 100 board members this fall to check for overzealous or
dangerous behavior in the stands or on the fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens. We know it happens, and we're on guard to watch
out for it,'' Loucks says. ``If you only came to say negative
things, don't come at all.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
