<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0486 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      08-02 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT CAME OUT OF THE BLUE, OR DID IT? 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   The mothers take turns grieving
for each other.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It must be such a shock,'' Mary says to Johanna about her
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``But such agony for you,'' says Johanna to Mary.
</P>
<P>
   You think, is it possible that one is worse than the other? For
your child to suddenly die. Or your child to slowly die.
</P>
<P>
   The mothers are in their 60s and their children are adults, but
no matter the age, for your child to get sick and die before you do
is out of whack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not part of the natural scheme,'' says Mary.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that cancer ever makes any sense, or that children
don't die. These women are plenty familiar with unfairness, but on
this they seem desperate to find an explanation for what made their
able, healthy children suddenly vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Living in environmentally-sensitive Sonoma County, Calif., they
don't whisper their fears that their children may have been
poisoned by something they lived with. Maybe when their children
were babies there was something in the tap water, or maybe they
unknowingly walked through a noxious cloud on the way to school.
</P>
<P>
   The women know about communities looking to factories and wells
to figure out why a neighborhood has so many cancers. For a time in
the San Francisco Bay Area environmental causes were suspected for
a high incidence of breast cancer, although studies now link it to
women delaying childbearing, which prolongs their exposure to
estrogen, and also to early detection methods.
</P>
<P>
   Still, you always want to know: Why cancer, why now?
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the Viking family,'' says Johanna, her face full of
pain and puzzlement. Her children, like her and their father, were
tall and blond and athletic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we were arrogant,'' she says, as if cancer was a
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Johanna's son Bruce, 35, died in May of a rapidly moving
leukemia. He went into a Michigan hospital on a Friday with
abdominal pains and on Wednesday Johanna was told he had leukemia
and was being given massive doses of chemotherapy. The mother was
on her way to fly to Michigan when she called the hospital and was
told her son was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `I'm sorry. He has expired.' I said, `No. You don't
understand. I'm calling about my son,' and they said, `Yes, that's
the name.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Mary's daughter Diane, 44, mother of four and a computer
graphics student, had pains in her chest last Christmas which she
blamed on a lingering cold. It turned out to be breast cancer and
she had a mastectomy. Now the cancer is in her bones.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report in the New England Journal of Medicine said that
cancer is more often tied to lifestyle than genes. While family
history is a factor in 30 percent of cancer cases, the report cited
lifestyle choices in diet, exercise and tobacco use as more apt to
influence who gets cancer.
</P>
<P>
   What about toxins and pesticides, the runoff from factories,
those contaminants people discover and make crusading movies about,
Johanna and Mary want to know.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Johanna's son had chosen a career in environmental
management and had a new job heading a recycling center. Maybe he
was sickened by something when he worked at an airport in
Massachusetts or at a lab in California, Johanna says, seeking a
connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lived in Spain for a while. Maybe there was something
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary says there is no cancer history in her daughter's family.
As for lifestyle causes, she says, ``Diane eats better than anyone
I know and drinks filtered water. She's far more health conscious
than me and I'm as healthy as a horse.''
</P>
<P>
   I know a 30-year-old with lymphoma who grew up near a large
chemical company. She used to sit on the town bridge and throw
rocks at the mounds of white gunk that floated on top of the river.
Is that what got her?
</P>
<P>
   Johanna and Mary are not Erin Brokovich types, ready to go on a
rampage. Right now Johanna is too fragile to do much more than
travel to Michigan to ask more questions of her son's doctors.
Mary, who is caring for her daughter and her youngest grandchild,
is too much ``in overwhelm'' to raise a ruckus.
</P>
<P>
   But you can expect them to point fingers if and when they find
something to point at.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of my friends tell me that it's time to seek closure for
Bruce's death,'' says Johanna. ``I hate that word, closure. I'm
just starting.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
