<HEADLINE>
MORE SETBACKS FOR BARAK AS FOREIGN MINISTER RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated by 9 p.m. EDT with a
Jerusalem datelined story by John Kifner.)  
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Israel's embattled Prime Minister Ehud Barak suffered fresh
political setbacks Wednesday when his foreign minister, David Levy,
resigned and the parliament approved the first reading of
legislation calling for early elections.
</P>
<P>
   The problems came just before a three-month parliamentary recess
that Barak hopes will give him enough breathing space to shore up
his government.
</P>
<P>
   His governing coalition lost its parliamentary majority last
month, when three right-leaning parties quit to protest his
decision to attend the summit meeting with the Palestinian leader,
Yasser Arafat, at Camp David, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Since Barak's return from Camp David, he has survived two
no-confidence votes sponsored by the opposition Likud Party, which
objects to making any concessions to the Palestinians. The same
hostility contributed to the humiliating defeat Monday of former
Prime Minister Shimon Peres, a Nobel Prize laureate, in
parliament's election of a new Israeli president.
</P>
<P>
   Levy, 62, complained that he had ``no option'' but to resign
because Barak had offered irreversible compromises on the status of
Jerusalem to the Palestinians at the Camp David summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, on the issue of Jerusalem, we were
prepared to divide Jerusalem, and even at this moment there is no
way back from this promise,'' said Levy, who left Likud a year ago
to join Barak's coalition. As foreign minister, Levy refused to
attend the Camp David summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gone down a path leading to the division of Jerusalem,
not just Arab areas, but the very heart of the old city of
Jerusalem,'' he complained Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The summit meeting collapsed after Barak continued to maintain
that Jerusalem was indivisible, though he offered limited
administrative control to the Palestinians in the Arab
neighborhoods of east Jerusalem, which Arafat rejected. The
Palestinians insist upon sovereignty over east Jerusalem, which
Israeli troops captured in the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister told reporters that he could not pretend to
have no regrets about Levy's departure. ``I have a great deal of
respect for David Levy,'' Barak said, according to Agence
France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I am committed to the principles that government came into
power to implement,'' he continued, ``and consequently I will
continue to work towards strengthening peace and security and
further developing our economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak expressed confidence that his coalition would be
revitalized once the ``hubbub of the last few days'' died down over
the next few weeks. ``We will be able to broaden the basis of the
government and continue into the future to achieve our
objectives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the rambunctious parliamentary session Wednesday, Likud and
its allies pushed through the preliminary reading of a bill that
would dissolve the government and hold new elections, which
otherwise are not due before 2003. Four of five motions on the bill
received the necessary majority of 61 votes in the 120-seat
legislature, and the fifth received 60 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Likud's victory has no immediate practical effect, because the
bill now goes to a parliamentary committee controlled by Barak's
party. The proposal must be approved in three more readings before
it can become law.
</P>
<P>
   The parliament's recess in theory gives Barak until late October
to reshuffle his government, which has been reduced to 42
parliamentary seats, and to show enough progress in continuing
talks with the Palestinians to allow Barak to call new elections to
present his peace policy to Israeli voters.
</P>
<P>
   However, the parliament could call back its members from
vacation if 25 legislators formally request it, an unusual step
that Likud and its allies have sufficient strength to take.
</P>
<P>
   (With reporting by John Kifner in Jerusalem.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
