<HEADLINE>
THE LATEST IN SUMMER REALITY CHECKS: `AMERICAN HIGH' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
AMERICAN HIGH 
Directed by: R.J. Cutler 
On: Fox 
Time: Wednesdays at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someday soon, someone will make a reality TV series about the
making of a reality TV series. It will be called ``Big Brother's
Big Brother'' or ``The Real Real World,'' and it will show us
exactly how a reality series is filmed and edited over time. But
until that doubly self-conscious moment arrives, we must settle for
the sort of plain old ordinary keyhole-peeping that has become the
TV format of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ``American High,'' which follows a year in the lives
of 14 suburban Chicago high school kids, is a reality series that
has some relatively serious, documentary aspirations. Yes, it is
edited with the same rhythmic exuberance and sass of ``The Real
World'' and other MTV nonfictional programming. And it is indeed a
kind of TV-sanctioned spying, as we follow these teens from their
morning-hygiene rituals to the evening dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   But because the overall themes are the pains of post-adolescence
and the anxiety of facing adulthood in an uncertain world, the show
ends up seeming like more than an exercise in MTV hipness. It's not
quite fantasy reality.
</P>
<P>
   The half-hour show _ the premiere featured back-to-back episodes
_ is meant to provide a medium-deep portrait of ``kids today.''
Many of the 14 subjects in ``American High'' hang out in different
cliques, and they have been chosen, like most reality casts, to
cover a range of types. There's an alternative singer-songwriter
who wears funky glasses; a pair of easygoing football jocks; a
troublemaker with attention deficit disorder issues; and, of
course, an openly gay student who wants to be an artist.
</P>
<P>
   The show jumps quickly from one life to another, but it's
carefully organized by the director, R. J. Cutler (who also helmed
``The War Room''), to keep you from being confused about who's who.
It also maintains a nice balance between home-life shots,
school-corridor action, and the ``diary'' footage filmed by the
students themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the expected tales of unrequited love and peer pressure,
Cutler follows an unusual friendship between mellow jock Robby (who
says, ``On the inside I just got a lot of love'') and Brad, the gay
kid. They are from very different segments of the school
population, but that doesn't appear to threaten their playful
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Robby's girlfriend, Sarah, is uncomfortable with the friendship,
though, and Brad shakes his head in disbelief when Robby shares
that information with him. Sarah, meanwhile, is painfully attached
to Robby _ ``You're all I have really in life,'' she says _ and
when Robby gets a college acceptance letter, fear is written all
over her face. Clearly, Sarah has a long journey of
self-realization ahead of her.
</P>
<P>
   The kids in ``American High'' appear extraordinarily comfortable
being filmed, which may be indigenous to either their tender age or
their generation, steeped in media-heavy culture. Some of them,
Kaytee the musician, for instance, are natural-born performers, but
none of them appears to be using the show as a professional
steppingstone. (See: ``The Real World.'') They're too steeped in
the immediacy of homework assignments, homeroom crushes, and angst
about the future to be plotting a path.
</P>
<P>
   The sequences that focus on Morgan, a hyperactive kid who is
both angry and needy, are the show's most powerful. Intelligent,
mouthy, and tightly wound, he harasses his younger brother, tests
his father's patience, and rejects the idea of improving his
grades. He works overtime to hide his compassion, which surfaces
briefly during his gym play with retarded adults. With his snarl,
his acne, and his drug perscriptions, Morgan is the character
you're least likely to find on TV's countless fictional teen
dramas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
