<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPRECIATE-MAXWELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM MAXWELL: WRITER-EDITOR OF ELEGANT SENSIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Maxwell, one of America's most esteemed novelists and
short-story writers and for 40 years a fiction editor at The New
Yorker magazine, died Monday at his New York City home. He was 91.
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorker's editor, David Remnick, paid tribute to Mr.
Maxwell Tuesday. ``William Maxwell's prose was deceptively simple,
made of the deepest American feeling. His editorial judgment and
sympathy was also a thing of great beauty and it helped create the
best of The New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the writers Mr. Maxwell edited at The New Yorker were
Vladimir Nabokov, Eudora Welty, Isaac Bashevis Singer, John Updike,
John O'Hara, J. D. Salinger, John Cheever, and Harold Brodkey, the
last two of whom were among the many authors to dedicate books to
Mr. Maxwell.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Maxwell's own writing _ fastidious, unemphatic, carefully
observed _ long ago earned him a place alongside such celebrated
names. He published six novels, three short-story collections, a
memoir, a collection of essays, and a children's book. His 1980
novel, ``So Long, See You Tomorrow,'' won an American Book Award.
He was a member of the American Academy of Arts and Letters and a
winner of the academy's William Dean Howells Medal. He was also a
recipient of the Brandeis Creative Arts Medal.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Maxwell's fiction was rooted in, though not restricted to,
his Midwestern upbringing. The son of an insurance executive and a
housewife, he was born in the small Illinois town of Lincoln on
Aug. 16, 1908. In his fiction, Lincoln was ``Logan'' or
``Draperville,'' a place of brick-paved streets shaded by elms. He
spent his first 14 years there, later living in Bloomington, Ill.,
and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from the University of Illinois, earned a master's
degree at Harvard, then returned to Illinois to teach. He published
his first novel, ``Bright Center of Heaven,'' in 1934 and financed
a move to New York with the $200 advance for his second novel. The
New Yorker hired him to work in its art department, and he soon
began to edit fiction.
</P>
<P>
   A slender, fine-featured man, Mr. Maxwell had the look of a
literary cleric. He had the manner as well: civilized, circumspect,
sympathetic. ``As a writer,'' Mr. Maxwell once said, ``I don't very
much enjoy being edited. As an editor I tried to work so slightly
on the manuscript that 10 years later the writer would read his
story and not be aware that anybody was involved but him.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many writers who have supported themselves editing, Mr.
Maxwell found working on others' prose helped improve his own. ``I
came, as a result of being an editor, to look for whatever was
unnecessary in my own writing,'' he once recalled. ``After 40
years, what I came to care about most was not style, but the breath
of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether as reader, writer, or editor, Mr. Maxwell found his
greatest satisfaction, as he once put it, in ``the forward movement
of prose that is bent only on saying what the writer has to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Maxwell's wife, Emily Gilman (Noyes) Maxwell, died on July
23. They had been married 55 years. Mr. Maxwell leaves two
daughters, Katharine and Emily, both of New York; a grandson; and a
brother, Robert, of Oxnard, Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0128 </DOCNO>
