<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0496 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-HONOR-BOS &LR;      08-02 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HONOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ACCOUNT OF LIVES LOST IN SERVICE FOR THE CIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE BOOK OF HONOR 
Covert Lives and Classified Deaths at the CIA 
By Ted Gup 
Doubleday, 390 pp., illustrated, $25.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the north wall of the large lobby of the Central Intelligence
Agency headquarters in Langley, Va., is a field of black stars
chiseled into the white Vermont marble. Above the five rows are
engraved the words: ``In honor of those members of the Central
Intelligence Agency who gave their lives in the service of their
country.''
</P>
<P>
   After five decades of CIA operation, more than 70 stars line the
wall. But the lives _ and deaths _ represented by more than half of
those stars have remained secret. Until now. Ted Gup's accomplished
reporting in The Washington Post, Time magazine, and now this book
provides details of the exploits of about a dozen of the agency's
covert agents. Among those honored:
</P>
<P>
   --Douglas S. Mackiernan, a Stoughton native who became a CIA
intelligence officer in western China, only to get stuck at his
post (ostensibly, he was a vice consul) at the time of the
communist takeover in 1949. Mackiernan sought to escape by trekking
across the Himalayas to Tibet in winter. Three months later, within
sight of the border, Mackiernan and two anticommunist Russians who
were accompanying him were shot to death by Tibetan guards who
likely mistook them for bandits rustling sheep.
</P>
<P>
   --Thomas Ray, a member of the Alabama National Guard who
volunteered for the CIA operation helping train Cuban exiles to fly
the planes that were to provide air support for the Bay of Pigs
invasion in 1961. Although President Kennedy had decided at the
last minute to minimize the actual involvement of US military in
the invasion, Ray and a colleague were allowed to fly a B-26 from
their Nicaraguan training base to Cuba to aid the landing. Their
plane was shot out of the sky; though Ray survived the crash, he
was subsequently killed in a firefight with Castro's militiamen.
</P>
<P>
   --Lawrence N. Freedman, a rough kid out of Philadelphia who
became a member of the elite military Delta Force (often assigned
to CIA missions) after earning two Bronze Medals and a chestful of
other awards with the Special Forces in Vietnam. Although he
survived the disastrous attempt to rescue the 81 Americans held
hostage at the US Embassy in Tehran in 1980, Freedman's luck ran
out several foreign operations later, in 1992, in Somalia. By then
he was with the CIA, and was one of the first Americans to arrive
in the African nation on the failed mission of pacifying it in
support of relief efforts. Freedman was killed as the jeep he drove
hit a land mine.
</P>
<P>
   The stories that Gup reveals are not confined to covert
derring-do. What motivated these men and women to join the agency,
particularly knowing the rigors of the job and the strain that it
placed on their families, is also explored _ mostly through rich
reporting that Gup did with those who were left behind: the
spouses, parents, sons, and daughters of the agents.
</P>
<P>
   In many instances, these families were unaware of their loved
ones' exploits until long after their deaths. The CIA, maintaining
its position of never revealing ``sources or methods'' of its
operations (particularly the most dangerous ones, in hostile
foreign countries), customarily arranged to have either the State
Department or the Pentagon claim the deceased agent as its own.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it is difficult to understand why the CIA would
have gone along with Gup's project. Even though he does not admit
that the CIA assisted him, it seems likely (judging from the
documents he quotes and the access he received) that the top
echelon of the agency, particularly director George Tenet, believed
there was good reason for Gup's book to be written.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Possibly because with the end of the Cold War, the danger
of having the Soviet Union use the information for propaganda
advantage has passed, and the time is overdue for the heroics of
these individuals to be told. It may also have occurred to the
CIA's leaders that the agency _ whose history has been replete with
embarrassing disclosures, from wrongheaded operations to fumbled
opportunities to double-dealing spies _ can only benefit if more
people know about the valiant dedication of its best operatives.
</P>
<P>
   Gup does not go overboard; his praise goes mostly to
individuals. These agents were brave, resourceful, and patriotic;
the agency they worked for often let them down. Consider John
Merriman, who was badly injured in a plane crash in the Congo in
1964 while participating in a CIA mission there. Because the US
Embassy was contending that no Americans were involved in the
operation, Merriman was forced to remain in country, denied
adequate hospitalization for more than a month. He died on the
flight home _ and his family was told he had died in a car accident
in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Or consider Hugh Redmond, captured in Shanghai in 1951 and
imprisoned as a CIA spy. He was 31 when he was arrested. He
remained in Chinese prisons until his death in 1970, even though it
is likely that an acknowledgment by the US government that he had
been an intelligence agent would have procured his freedom. But
such an admission, Gup implies, would have embarrassed the CIA,
which was intent on maintaining covert operations at whatever costs
were necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Gup's book is a fitting tribute to the people who actually paid
those costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0497 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-     08-02 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS GET OFF ON THE RIGHT FOOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Ohio _ A sentence can now be written that has not been
written in New England in years. The Patriots ran the football.
</P>
<P>
   Monday being the opening game of the exhibition season against
what seems destined to be one of the worst teams in the NFC, that
fact may prove to be meaningless a month from now. But, for at
least a few days, it at least can be honestly stated.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots ran the football against an NFL opponent. Ran it,
and ran it, and ran it again. Ran it down the throats of the San
Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, it was against a lousy defense made worse by the
absence of six of the starting front seven plus the expected
starting strong safety. But when you have not averaged 4 yards a
carry in a season since 1985, to rush for 193 yards in 38 carries
and average 5.1 yards against anyone is cause for elation, even if
only until Friday night, when the Patriots will try to do it again
against a considerably more formidable Detroit Lions team.
</P>
<P>
   What is significant from New England's point of view is that it
ran for those yards without three likely offensive line starters
(Bruce Armstrong, Grant Williams, and Todd Rucci) and without
rookie running back J.R. Redmond, all of whom were nursing
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   So what we know is this: A lineup of backup 49ers massed at the
line of scrimmage couldn't prevent a line of 60 percent Patriot
backups from knocking them on their backsides often enough to allow
Raymont Harris to run for 58 yards in the first half on nine
carries, an average of 6.4 yards per rush.
</P>
<P>
   What this tells us is subject to debate, but it is still summer,
and no time yet for pessimism or debating. There will be time
enough for that later. Like Saturday morning, perhaps, if the Lions
stuff the Patriots. Although there are ample reasons to find
Monday's numbers suspect, the fact is the Bill Belichick Era opened
with a 20-0 victory _ the first time a Patriot team had shut out
its first preseason opponent _ and it was accomplished in large
measure by running the football.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, at least, it is enough just to say that.
</P>
<P>
   New offensive coordinator Charlie Weis called 38 running plays,
a figure the Patriots topped only twice last season. What this
shows, it would seem, is a sense of purpose. This year, unlike
recent seasons, the ball will be run because that is what Weis and
Belichick believe must be done. That being the case, there was no
time like the present to give it a try.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I liked was that our backs ran hard,'' Belichick said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed they did, and no one ran harder than Harris, who did not
play last season because of a broken leg and had not played in an
NFL game since Nov. 15, 1998, when he carried 10 times for 33 yards
with the Green Bay Packers. That should mean he's well rested, and
he looked it, although he is still a far cry from the back who
rushed for 1,033 yards and 10 touchdowns for the Chicago Bears in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Those are numbers Harris believes he can put together again now
that he is fully healthy, but there are many skeptics when he
mentions such a thing because his career has been littered with
litters used to carry him off the field. Still, Monday night he ran
with abandon through the makeshift 49er defense, showing
acceleration, power, a willingness to plow over people, and enough
speed into the holes not to always have to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the idea that Harris is going to average 6.4 yards a
carry or that the Patriots are going to have the kind of running
game that averages 5.1 yards a rush with regularity.
</P>
<P>
   But take heart in this. What happened Monday night is at least a
start toward giving quarterback Drew Bledsoe the kind of balanced
attack he hasn't had since it was decided by some genius that a guy
named Curtis Martin could be easily replaced. That was four years
ago, and Martin hasn't been replaced, and neither Raymont Harris
nor J.R. Redmond is likely to do it either.
</P>
<P>
   Still, on Monday night the Patriots ran the ball.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it is enough just to be able to write such a sentence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
