<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0498 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BABOONS-FREE-HNS &LR;      08-02 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABOONS-FREE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RESEARCH BABOONS RETIRE TO FIVE-ACRE SANCTUARY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LETY LAUREL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILLEY, Texas _ For 10 years they lived in a cold, windowless
laboratory, endured needle pokes twice a day and watched television
for their entertainment. Now, eight former research baboons are
free to co-exist with coyotes, rattlesnakes and rabbits and roam
among mesquite trees and cactuses near Dilley, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It took a few hours, but by mid-afternoon Friday, all of the
male research baboons, along with one female baboon whose former
owner went to prison, were roaming in a five-acre enclosure at the
Animal Protection Institute's Texas Snow Monkey Sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Normally euthanized after their research duties end, or placed
in small cages until they die, these are believed to be the first
research baboons to be released into a free-ranging enclosure in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel these guys worked for us in their laboratory for 10
years,'' said Lou Griffin, director of the sanctuary. ``They were
taken from their families in Africa so they could be used for
research. We think it's only fair to let them live out the rest of
their lives in a comfortable fashion, not just a cage.''
</P>
<P>
   The male baboons were used in vascular research at the Boston
University Medical Center. They were brought to the sanctuary in
April for rehabilitation. Of the original nine given to the
sanctuary, eight survived. One was euthanized Thursday because of a
brain tumor.
</P>
<P>
   The only female, Nikki, was once featured in parades, but she
was brought to the sanctuary after biting several people and after
her owner was convicted of contract murder.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctuary received $20,000 from Boston University Medical
Center to build the five-acre enclosure for the baboons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Previous to this, when people were done with the animals,
there was not a place like this to send them so we were forced to
put them to sleep. But now that there is a facility like this, it's
nice because they have an option,'' said Kathy Brasky, a
veterinarian with the Southwest Foundation for Biomedical Research.
</P>
<P>
   Since April, the former research baboons have slowly adjusted to
being outside, but they are extremely vulnerable to nature after 10
years of living in air-conditioned cages, Griffin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once these first 24 hours are under our belt, I will know
things will be okay,'' she said. ``The one thing we couldn't teach
them was to avoid rattlesnakes.''
</P>
<P>
   From snakes and falling tree branches to their own aggression
against each other, the baboons will encounter numerous challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see if they can handle the heat,'' she said. ``They have
been exposed to cactus, but they still have a lot of thorny lessons
to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Using caramel cubes, peanuts, cereal, orange slices and finally
water, the baboons were coaxed from their cages through a wire
tunnel that opened into the enclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes turned to hours before the baboons grudgingly entered
their new home.
</P>
<P>
   But after the first tentative steps, they were soon climbing
trees, eating hay and chasing each other in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm almost moved to tears,'' said Howard Klein, an API board
member from Sacramento. ``After being confined in a cage almost the
size of a postage stamp, look at them bouncing in the trees.
Amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the enclosure, Griffin sat in her truck, observing the
baboons and noting their behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since they're wild-caught, we're hoping they will form normal
social troops and turn back into baboons,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their fur and weight, the animals are currently in
good condition, Brasky said. In the following weeks, keepers will
monitor the animals' activity levels and interactions to ensure
they are adapting well.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will probably fight, because that is the nature of their
society,'' Brasky said. ``There must be a dominant male, so they
may fight until they figure out which one it will be, but it
probably won't be that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   But with summer temperatures reaching above 100, they may crave
their old air-conditioned labs and the TV, Griffin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far they don't seem to miss TV, but when they are out here,
they have the coyotes and birds to keep them busy,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
