<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0499 &Cx1f; ttj-z
f f BC-CAREER-EXAGGERATE-HNS     08-02 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-EXAGGERATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TIPS TO ELIMINATE WHITE LIES IN THE WORKPLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ How's this for a job interview question: When is the
last time you lied about work?
</P>
<P>
   If you said, ``never,'' you're probably lying _ maybe even to
yourself. Or maybe you're tempted to use an answer that would make
President Clinton proud: It depends on what your definition of
``lied'' is.
</P>
<P>
   We're being purists here, so when is the last time you
deliberately misled someone about a work-related subject? If you
still say ``never,'' here are a few follow-up questions: Ever call
in sick when you weren't? Or tell your boss that you liked his idea
when you really didn't? Or say you had almost finished a project
when in reality you had barely started it? Or say you were too busy
to do something when you really weren't? Or tell employees or
shareholders that things were better than they were?
</P>
<P>
   If you still consider yourself pure, let's try a few more: Ever
exaggerate on your resume? Or say you were enthused about a company
when in reality you were so desperate that you would have taken a
job as Attila the Hun's administrative assistant? Or say that you
were leaving to pursue more challenging work, when you really just
wanted to escape a nasty and incompetent boss? Did you tell the
truth when a prospective employer asked, ``What's your biggest
weakness?''
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry. None of this will be on the final exam. No
interviewer will ask such a blunt question about lying unless you
are already dead meat, and the interviewer simply wants to bat you
around in his paws like a cat with a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the interview will be the same dance it always is,
with the interviewer saying how the company is always looking for
wonderful applicants, and you saying how much you admire the
company. Remember: Even if every tobacco company on Earth goes out
of business, Corporate America will still be addicted to blowing
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry to say it, but in much of the American workplace, there is
a corporate culture of lying. And it seems to be getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   All the layoffs of the last 15 years have eroded the trust and
respect between employers and employees. And just as parents tell
their young children when they catch them in a white lie, people
can get into the habit of lying. Once they do, it's a hard habit to
break.
</P>
<P>
   If you're an employer and you value honesty (and you're not
lying about it), here are some steps you can take:
</P>
<P>
   _ Stop with the euphemisms already.
</P>
<P>
   People don't get downsized, rightsized or outsourced. They get
fired. It's a traumatic experience, and trying to downplay it with
a buzzword is like trying to put out a fire with fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   I can hear you talking to your children now, telling them the
old story about George Washington and his father: ``I cannot tell a
lie. I rightsized that cherry tree.''
</P>
<P>
   If you can't bring yourself to say that you fired 200 people,
maybe it's time to let your conscience do a little talking.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hire honest people.
</P>
<P>
   If you develop a reputation for thoroughly checking applicants'
backgrounds and refusing to hire those who lie, it will set the
tone for the rest of your workplace. On the other hand, if
employees learn from Day One that they can get away with lying to
you, it will set a different tone.
</P>
<P>
   Before you check their backgrounds, ask candidates if there are
any surprises you will find. That provides the chance for the
honest ones to give their side of the story if a problem occurred.
</P>
<P>
   If you ask an applicant, ``What's your biggest weakness?'' and
you get some canned answer like ``sometimes I just push myself too
hard,'' follow it up with, ``What's your second biggest weakness?''
Keep going like this until you get to the 23rd biggest weakness _
or an answer with at least a grain of honesty.
</P>
<P>
   After he won the British Open last weekend, Tiger Woods said he
still has weaknesses in his golf game. Keeping that in mind, look
across the table at Mr. or Ms. ``Sometimes I Just Push Myself Too
Hard.'' Are those people better at their jobs than Tiger Woods is
at his?
</P>
<P>
   Not bloody likely.
</P>
<P>
   Good workers know they have weaknesses. They either work hard to
overcome them or work smart to get around them. People who say they
have no significant weaknesses are either lying or oblivious.
</P>
<P>
   _ Encourage honest feedback.
</P>
<P>
   Act on employee suggestions whenever you can. A lot of bosses
say they love to empower (see euphemisms, stop with them already)
workers, but that tends to be done with the lips instead of the
heart. Do you really listen to employees, or do you just say that
you listen to employees (see lying, through your teeth)?
</P>
<P>
   Where is the suggestion box at your company? Next to a corner
office or right above the trash can?
</P>
<P>
   _ Eliminate sick days.
</P>
<P>
   No, don't reduce the number of days off, but label days off as
personal days rather than sick days or vacation days. Sometimes
people are so desperate for a day or two off that they will call in
sick even if they're perfectly healthy. That can lead to resentment
among your equally-tired-but-honest workers.
</P>
<P>
   If people need a personal day, let them take it without having
to lie. It actually works to your advantage, not just because it
rewards honesty, but because they may be able to give you warning
in advance of the personal days off. You always get last-minute
notice with ``sick'' days.
</P>
<P>
   White lies are always going to be a part of the workplace, just
as they're a part of everyday life. But at least you can make them
a little less casual. If someone asks, ``When is the last time you
lied about work?'' you ought to give your answer by checking your
calendar, not your watch.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Murphy edits the career section of the San Francisco
Examiner. E-mail him at murphy &LR; examiner.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
