<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0505 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OLY-SWIM-HNS &LR;      08-02 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      WESTER-KRIEG AGES GRACEFULLY IN HER ELEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DWIGHT CHAPIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In 1992, Angie Wester-Krieg was described as
``the Grande Dame of U.S. Swimming.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say what that makes her now.
</P>
<P>
   At 35, Wester-Krieg is still swimming. Very well, in fact. She
has qualified for her sixth U.S. Olympic trials, which is a record
as far as USA Swimming officials can determine.
</P>
<P>
   She certainly will be one of the oldest competitors in
Indianapolis next week _ if not the oldest.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not a big deal to her, so it probably shouldn't be to
anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Wester-Krieg is the Energizer bunny of swimmers. Unlike some of
her contemporaries _ notably Dara Torres, who took seven years off
from the sport before returning to the pool recently for one more
try at Olympic glory _ she has never dried off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just kept right on swimming,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This has required a number of adjustments, not to mention
several understanding people in her life.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, those include her bosses at Ernst and Young, for
whom she has long worked as a tax accountant based in San Jose, and
her husband, Santa Clara Swim Club coach Peter Krieg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look on my employer as a big part of the reason I've been
able to continue swimming, because it has allowed me to work
part-time for almost 14 years, to accommodate my training,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   And husband Peter, she added, ``has never pushed me, never said
I should do this or that. He has kind of let me do my own thing and
make decisions for myself. He has always made me feel very
supported.''
</P>
<P>
   Wester-Krieg is the youngest of four children of Ernest and
Margaret Wester, who came to Cupertino from Austria in 1955, after
discovering California through a copy of Reader's Digest. Ernest
became a butler and Margaret a cook on an apricot ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Angie started swimming when she was 7 and did well early, but
didn't really break through until she went to San Jose State, where
she became a six-time All-America under coach Jack Mutimer and
consistently finished high in the 100 and 200 butterfly at the NCAA
championships.
</P>
<P>
   But a pattern developed. She had a lot of trouble winning the
big prizes. After her third unsuccessful bid to make the U.S.
Olympic team, in 1988, Mutimer told her he thought she should
retire and get on with her life.
</P>
<P>
   She stuck with it, however, and began working under Krieg, who
became her coach and then her husband. In 1990, she swam just off
her lifetime best at the U.S. nationals, and she and Peter decided
she should ``go with the best,'' Stanford and Olympic coach Richard
Quick.
</P>
<P>
   And with Quick's guidance, she finally became an Olympian in
1992, finishing second behind Summer Sanders in the 200 butterfly
at the U.S. trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget what she told me before that race,'' Quick
recalled. ``She said, `Richard, I don't know whether I'll get first
or last tonight, but I know I'm going to swim a great race.' That's
an approach that lets the best come out in you.''
</P>
<P>
   Wester-Krieg didn't medal in Barcelona, but she did keep going.
And going. Into the 1996 trials and now into the 2000 trials, where
she will compete in the 100- and 200-meter butterfly events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very similar to the way I felt in 1992,'' she said.
``Your goals and aspirations don't change that much. I don't know _
I can't know _ how I'll compare with the other swimmers at the
trials, but I'm confident I can swim well.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick said, ``She's going to have to swim the best race of her
life to make the team. What I think she's hoping to do is put
herself into a position where if the door is open for her to make
the team, she won't slam it on herself, she'll go through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick added that Wester-Krieg ``has been a joy to coach because
she enjoys training and racing so much. It's pretty extraordinary
for someone to be swimming at that high level for that period of
time. I think she's been able to do it because she enjoys the sport
so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Wester-Krieg said there has never been any grand plan behind her
longevity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like when I was a teenager, I said to myself, `I'll
still be swimming competitively 20 years from now,' `' Wester-Krieg
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swimming is a learning process, like everything in life. This
is just the arena I've chosen to live and grow in.''
</P>
<P>
   Wester-Krieg said she faces a lot more job and life demands that
she once did, more than most of her training partners with the
Stanford Swim Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the Stanford girls are on break from their schooling
right now,'' she said. ``After the morning workouts, they'll say,
`I can't wait to take my morning nap.' I just look at them and
think, `I wish ' `'
</P>
<P>
   Wester-Krieg never focuses on the age difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think about what they have versus what I don't have,''
she said, ``or about what I have that they don't have. I'm sure
it's a mixed bag for them. Some admire me, some wonder why I don't
give it up. But no one is able to understand why another person
does something. If anyone enjoyed this sport as much as I do, they
might stay in it as long as I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Wester-Krieg's competitive career likely will end in
Indianapolis, or _ if she's lucky _ in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   She and Peter have talked of having children, and she said, ``We
want to have time for ourselves, too. It's time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   But, one way or another, Wester-Krieg figures she'll be involved
in swimming as long as she's on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just really, truly love the sport,'' she said. ``I don't see
myself as a coach, necessarily. It probably will become more of a
here-and-there type of thing. And I'll be able to live it
vicariously, through my husband.''
</P>
<P>
   If Peter has his way, however, Angie will not wind up merely a
vicarious swimmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes me to come to his practices,'' she said. ``He makes
me race his kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
