<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FUTURE RETIREE, FIXED INCOME IS THE GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. I plan to retire at 55; I will need $2,600 a month. Am I on
track to retire on schedule?
</P>
<P>
   J.V., Beaumont, Texas &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I see no problem. If your returns average 9 percent over the
next six years, and if you continue saving at your current rate,
you would accumulate $389,029. Why assume 9 percent, especially
since the funds you have been using have been producing
double-digit returns? Because now is the time to begin adjusting
your savings, moving toward more conservative investments as you
approach retirement.
</P>
<P>
   At retirement, you will need a $1,600 a month to supplement your
pension. Let's suppose you will be able to earn 7 percent from a
fixed-income portfolio _ perhaps bond funds, perhaps CDs, or a mix.
To get $1,600 monthly, you would need $275,000 in your fixed-income
account, leaving you with a little more than $114,000 that you
could leave in the various stock funds, designed for the capital
growth you will need later in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to begin building that fixed-income account so it
will be in place by the time you retire. I'd stop contributing to
the stock funds and put both the 401(k) contributions and your
additions to your mutual fund accounts into a good fixed-income
portfolio. I don't know what specific funds are available with your
401(k), but a good Vanguard fixed-income portfolio might consist of
50 percent Vanguard GNMA and 25 percent each in Vanguard High-Yield
Corporate Bond and Vanguard Short-Term Corporate Bond.
</P>
<P>
   For this year, switching ongoing savings to the fixed-income
side should be enough, but in subsequent years you should slowly
begin moving some of the money from the stock funds to the
fixed-income side.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I plan to give my grandchildren $10,000 each. No further
contributions will follow. What type of investment would you
recommend for maximum long-term growth?
</P>
<P>
   D.B., Charleston, S.C. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The investment you choose will probably reflect your appetite
for risk. The old adage in my family: The gift must please the
giver.
</P>
<P>
   One investment vehicle that comes to mind is a mutual fund for
children _ designed to provide both long-term growth and to teach
them about investing. This is the Stein Roe Young Investors fund,
which invests in large-growth stocks its managers deem to be stocks
of companies that affect the lives of children. Clearly, the
managers apply this requirement broadly, since the largest current
holding, according to Morningstar Mutual Funds, is Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
   The fund also delivers both the reports traditional investors
are familiar with that are blessed by the SEC and reports written
so children can slowly build an understanding of investing.
</P>
<P>
   Like many growth funds, Stein Roe Young Investors has been
taking its lumps this year, with a 3.56 percent year-to-date loss
as this is written. But its five-year record shows a 22.84 percent
average annual gain, slightly beating the Standard and Poor's 500
</P>
<P>
   Index.
</P>
<P>
   You might want to look carefully at the risk profile. The fund's
portfolio has a price-to-earnings ratio of 47.9, compared to 37.2
for the S&AMP;P 500. In other words, it's assuming more risk than the
S&AMP;P and providing owners very faint reward for assuming that extra
risk. A conservative investor might decide much the same results
are likely with something like Vanguard's Index 500 fund, which
will predictably deliver the S&AMP;P 500 Index results without
additional risk.
</P>
<P>
   One tactic is to invest $9,500 traditionally and put the other
$500 in an education IRA. Each year, you could then suggest $500 be
moved from the taxable accounts into the education IRAs. This
wouldn't solve all the tax problems, but it certainly would help.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 75, and a conservative investor. You have mentioned
Vanguard's Small-Cap Index fund. Vanguard has three small-cap index
funds: Small-Cap Index, Small-Cap Growth Index, and Small-Cap Value
Index. Which is the fund to invest in? Is it wise to invest in
mid-cap and small-cap funds?
</P>
<P>
   M.N., Quincy, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. To begin with, the small-cap universe is not the arena of
choice for conservative investors. The companies tend to be untried
and often competing with larger, well-established, and
better-financed companies. But it's also true that a lot of
tomorrow's Oracles and Intels are probably lurking in that universe
today. Thus, I frequently suggest growth-oriented investors might
include both small- and mid-cap funds to represent small segments
of a portfolio, typically 10 percent to 15 percent for each.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard's small-cap funds provide an easy way to gain exposure
to this segment of the market, but it's far from perfect. Here's
why:
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of a truly excellent company that blinks into
the small-cap world. What happens if it's a real mover? The stock
market notices it and bids up its shares, and it quickly becomes a
mid-cap stock. At that point, according to its charter, the
Vanguard Small-Cap Index funds sell the stock and the Mid-Cap Index
funds buy it. As the company's success continues, the market cap
continues to grow, and eventually it will join the big fellows. The
holders of the Mid-Cap Index fund will then be sold out of the
stock.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a traditional small-cap fund, the managers can
simply hold onto a fast-growing company, treating it is a small-cap
success story. Thus, if you look at a number of companies that
advertise themselves as small-cap funds, you'll find not only that
the overall portfolio qualifies it as a mid-cap fund, but there
also some large-cap stocks in there, as well.
</P>
<P>
   In short, being obligated to sell off the big winners is an
inherent disadvantage of any small-cap index fund. This may be
offset, in part, by the indexing discipline that requires the
managers to buy everything in their target universe. Doubtless
included are stocks of great value that have not yet been
discovered by the market as a whole. Still, if an investor is
willing to do his or her homework to sort out the many small-cap
funds, I would select a managed small-cap fund over an index fund.
</P>
<P>
   The three Vanguard small-cap funds are roughly modeled after the
relationship between Vanguard's flagship Index 500 fund and its two
offshoots, Index Growth and Index Value. In the case of the
small-cap funds, Vanguard Small-Cap Value breaks out the issues
with the lowest price-to-book value ratio; Small-Cap Growth Index
builds the opposite portfolio, those with the highest price-to-book
ratios. Accordingly, Vanguard's Small-Cap Value fund has a
price-to-book ratio of 2.2, while the Small-Cap fund has a ratio of
6.3, and Small-Cap Growth has a ratio of 8.8.
</P>
<P>
   When I suggest small-cap index funds, I tend to go with the
straight Small-Cap fund, figuring a small-cap value investor is
pretty much an oxymoron (entering a high-risk arena and then
hedging his or her bets), and the small-cap growth arena is just
too rich for my blood. In 1999, the funds performed pretty much as
might be expected, with Small-Cap Growth returning 19.8 percent,
the Small-Cap fund delivering 23.1 percent, and Small-Cap Value
producing a meager 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Year-to-date, the worm has turned, with the Value fund leading
with a 4.64 percent gain, the growth fund producing a token loss of
0.18 percent, and the Small-Cap fund losing 2.10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
