<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO SHOWS WHAT BALLPARKS CAN DO FOR A CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAN FRANCISCO _ The location looked dicey: old warehouses,
parking lots, and controversy. A new ballpark was being debated,
and neighborhood opponents reacted as though they smelled an
incinerator or a glue factory.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Coyle, as he had done before, took a chance. He
committed $72 million in AFL-CIO housing trust money toward
building One Embarcadero South, a 233-unit condominium project
across from what would become Pacific Bell Park, home of the San
Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, neighborhood activists _ a mix of old lefties,
Naderites, and other naysayers _ predicted disaster. San
Francisco's nearby parks, roads, and homes ``are citywide assets,
and they will be made useless by the stadium. This housing will be
less desirable now,'' one opponent said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week One Embarcadero South condos went on sale. Prices
start at $700,000 and rise to $2.3 million. Coyle feels vindicated.
``Of the 100 deals the trust has done, this was the most
successful. It brought a return of 41 percent, the best in our
history,'' he says. ``When the ballpark opened, we realized this
was the Carlton Fisk home run.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyle, who guided redevelopment in Boston during the 1980s, says
``Condo return is now better than the return on offices. It was
housing in the '70s, offices in the '80s and now it's condos. We're
working with Mayor Brown on more projects in San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Willie L. Brown Jr., who heard the prophecies of doom, now
hears nothing. Most San Franciscans admire the ballpark, some
comparing it to Coit Tower, Golden Gate Bridge, and other civic
adornments. ``All of the critics have gone totally silent. They
don't step forward and acknowlege what a positive thing this is,''
Brown says. ``In San Fransisco, NIMBYs have made an art form of the
process of maintaining the current character of their neighborhoods
at the expense of smart growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Cities that do not change calcify and die. Cities that do not
encourage luxury, market-rate housing do not have the tax base to
build affordable housing. Cities that do not offer big, bold plans
pay the price of timidity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fenway project needs a serious economic plan,'' Coyle says
of his old hometown. ``It needs a Turnpike ramp to serve the needs
of the future and a land bridge to knit back the city.'' You mean
something like Copley Place or the Pru between Kenmore Square and
Lansdowne Street? ``Exactly,'' Coyle replies. ``This is an economic
engine here. It transforms values upward. You need an economic plan
with infrastructure that works, so the entire community will
benefit, a plan big enough to address all the issues, including
affordable housing.''
</P>
<P>
   Karl Marx is dead. Lenin, too. To build affordable housing,
cities must sponsor unaffordable housing, lots of it.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO's gamble that towers above Willie Mays Plaza here
``stands for the proposition that ballparks create a new economic
zone where people come 81 days a year, or 90 if they make the
playoffs, to enjoy the game and also restaurants and retail. It
makes other parts of the area work. It adds value in a way not
dissimilar from Faneuil Hall. In the '80s, we talked of catalysts
for development,'' Coyle says. ``This is a catalyst.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, he adds, ``What will happen is that the area under
the current Fenway Park will be developed, a 10-acre site for
research or whatever. People will live there and live there
happily. It will create a more exciting environment, and for those
small businesses affected, there will be mitigation.''
</P>
<P>
   When Coyle travels, he sees ``evidence in San Francisco, Denver,
and Cleveland how ballparks bring added value to the urban fabric.
Football stadiums and arenas don't create that livable sense of
excitement.'' When he came here in 1996, his board members were
skeptical, but he told them: ``Forget that across the street it'll
be a ballpark with crowds or whatever. Instead, look at it as a
$400 million investment.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
