<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-NAMES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME COLLEGES STRUGGLE WITH THE NAME GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL AND PATRICK HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pity the students at Beaver College in Pennsylvania, the butt of
so many jokes based on the school's unfortunate name.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word `beaver' too often elicits ridicule in the form of
derogatory remarks pertaining to the rodent (and) the TV show
`Leave It to Beaver,' '' Beaver's president lamented.
</P>
<P>
   Things aren't much better for Dyke College in Cleveland, whose
name is slang for lesbian. Or even the University of Rio Grande, a
name that would be fine if the school was near the Mexican border.
It's actually in southern Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   For colleges, which depend on their name to help attract
students as well as financial backers, perception can all too often
be reality. And in some cases, the name can be grossly misleading _
or just plain gross. Last month, Beaver trustees began the process
of changing its name. Dyke made the change in 1995; Rio Grande,
meanwhile, may do so soon.
</P>
<P>
   Now, New Hampshire College officials are joining the name game,
announcing next year the school will be known as Southern New
Hampshire University. ``University,'' school officials believe,
carries more cachet than ``college.'' Administrators are so ardent
on this point that they plan to spend about $1 million on marketing
the new name, changing everything from the signage to the
stationery at its eight New England sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reflects more of what we've become,'' said the president,
Richard A. Gustafson, since the school increasingly offers graduate
programs that are more characteristic of a university than a
college.
</P>
<P>
   At Beaver College, whose name has brought laughter since the
suburban Philadelphia college opened in 1853, the ridicule began to
cut into the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, according to Beaver officials, market research found 30
percent of prospective students wouldn't even consider attending
the college because of its name. The college, which administrators
hope to rename by next year, has had to send out nearly three times
as many mailings as similar schools to attract equal numbers of
students.
</P>
<P>
   Beaver also had another problem: Internet filters set up to
screen out smut often blocked access to the college's Web site,
www.beaver.edu, because ``beaver'' is a vulgar reference to the
female anatomy. Some programs even censored e-mail messages sent
from Beaver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believed the name was hindering us too much,'' said Beaver
College spokesman Bill Avington. And, he said, they're just
following the lead of nearby Philadelphia College of Textiles and
Science, which is now called the less-limiting Philadelphia
University.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way, after years of fending off cheap, wearying
insults, Dyke College five years ago became David N. Myers College,
named after a longtime benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the small college in Cleveland, however, didn't
need any studies to tell them they had a public-relations problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original name, particularly among high school kids,
solicited snickers and it made it more difficult to recruit,'' said
James Zaferopolos, a spokesman for the 152-year-old college. ``When
we changed it, it was a big burden off our backs.''
</P>
<P>
   Mockery was not the reason Belleville Area College transformed
into Southwestern Illinois College, school officials insist. Even
though students long joked that the college's previous initials
meant Bring All (Your) Crayons, officials said the new moniker
accounted for the college's expansion beyond the city of
Belleville.
</P>
<P>
   Still, officials at the community college of 23,000 students
didn't fail to account for the value of a new name. ``The name just
sounds more impressive, and it may look better on a resume. We hope
it helps attract more students,'' said Jim Haverstick, a spokesman
for the college.
</P>
<P>
   Those hopes are echoed at the University of Rio Grande, which
has long relied on distinguishing itself from an institution near
the Mexican border by mispronouncing the ``i'' in Rio as an ``i,''
instead of an ``e.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the small college in south-central Ohio is only discussing
the move, said Kathleen Gierehart, a school spokeswoman. Like
others there, she hopes the college can soon remove a tagline on
its Web site, saying, ``We're not in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   As for New Hampshire College, not everyone is rallying to its
new banner. Officials at the University of New Hampshire have
complained to the New Hampshire secretary of state that the new
name was ``deceptively similar'' to the university's. Both are
located in the state's southern region.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you use a state name in your name, you're usually
associated with a public, state-supported university,'' said
Phyllis Bennett, a UNH spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The college tested out several names with alumni, students, and
professors, and the new one was the favorite, Gustafson said. The
catchiest, he said, was Amoskeag University, from the name of a
local spot on the Merrimack River where Native Americans used to
fish.
</P>
<P>
   All too aware of the confusion names can generate, college
officials shelved that idea. ``While it had a lot of local
appeal,'' Gustafson said, ``we also heard a lot of, `How do you
spell it?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
