<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADOFF IS A HIGH PRIORITY FOR THE RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Leading off. Setting the table. Hitting from the top
spot in the batting order.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots and 49ers led off the 2000 Monday Night Football
season. House Speaker Jay Dennis Hastert (R-Illinois) was first to
the podium at the Republican National Convention. Three decades
ago, Richie Havens led off at Woodstock.
</P>
<P>
   The leadoff hitter is an important part of any baseball team,
and with 59 games left to play, the Boston Red Sox find themselves
without a dependable, daily leadoff guy. Jose Offerman is on the
shelf for at least two weeks with a deep bone bruise in his knee
and Jimy Williams is bound to employ more leadoff men than
Elizabeth Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Leading off for the 2000 Red Sox is like opening for the Rolling
Stones: Some fans are not yet in their seats when you come out to
perform. Many patrons are simply waiting for Nomar Garciaparra to
come up. Your job is to help out the main act.
</P>
<P>
   No less than six players have hit first for the Sox this year.
In six games on this trip, we've already seen Darren Lewis, Trot
Nixon, and Mike Lansing there. Donnie Sadler and Jeff Frye, too.
Before it's over, maybe we'll see Clydesdale Jason Varitek in the 1
Hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lineup is game by game,'' said the manager. ``We want the
top people in our lineup to be scoring most of the runs. I'm not
saying we could use anybody, but Trot did a good job and Darren is
a prototype leadoff hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Sox fans with short memories might have forgotten that Nomar
batted leadoff in every game of his 1997 Rookie of the Year season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't change the way I hit,'' Garciaparra said. ``The game
dictates how you hit. Right now we're going with a lot of different
people there because we've got a lot of people out, but that's
nothing new.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a happy coincidence for a man writing about leadoff
hitters that the Red Sox are playing at Safeco Field this week
because Seattle is the new professional residence of the greatest
leadoff hitter who ever lived: Rickey Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   There are always going to be hardball arguments regarding Walter
Johnson vs. Cy Young vs. Bob Gibson vs. Sandy Koufax. Babe Ruth,
Willie Mays, Ted Williams, and Henry Aaron inspire similar debate.
But there can be no argument when it comes to leadoff hitters.
Henderson is the all-time stolen base king, a man who still led his
league in walks at the age of 39 and who most recently reached base
eight times Sunday and Monday against the Jays and Sox,
respectively. He holds the big league record with 78 career leadoff
home runs and ranks third all time in career walks, trailing only
Ruth and Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Tell us, Rickey, what is the most important thing a leadoff man
must do?
</P>
<P>
   ``Be patient and know the strike zone,'' he said. ``The leadoff
man is very important for a team. You've got to get a lot of
runners on base and create situations where you can steal a run.
That's how you create runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said a man batting leadoff doesn't have to alter his
batting game plan. Red Sox batting coach Tommy Harper, who led off
for the majority of his starry career, said, ``As a leadoff man,
you've got to take some pitches. You sometimes have to take the
3-and-1 pitch late in the game. You want to make the pitcher use as
many pitches as you can and you've always got guys coming up to you
and asking, `What's he throwing?' ''
</P>
<P>
   At the lower levels of baseball, it's not unusual to have the
best hitter on the team batting leadoff. Little League coaches
often put the big home run hitter in the top spot because it brings
that kid to the plate an extra 10 or 20 times a season. This theory
was used at the big league level when the Giants had Bobby Bonds
batting leadoff.
</P>
<P>
   Legendary Orioles manager Earl Weaver sometimes used trickery in
the top spot when Baltimore was on the road. In the late 1970s,
when the Orioles were carrying only eight or nine pitchers and had
a raft of available pinch hitters, Weaver would occasionally burn
one in the first inning. Kiko Garcia would lead off the game, only
to be replaced by light-hitting Mark Belanger at short in the
bottom of the first. It riled Belanger but got Baltimore an extra
chance for a first-inning homer.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Remy led off for much of his career, but batted second for
the 1978 Red Sox because Rick Burleson was more comfortable in the
top spot. Wade Boggs hit third, second, and first for most of his
career. Boggs's on-base percentage was always tops in baseball but
he clogged up the basepaths once he got there. John McNamara liked
to put Dwight Evans in the leadoff spot because Evans had a good
eye and could score 100 runs.
</P>
<P>
   Lansing said he led off for the Expos in 1994 and spent some
time in the top spot for the Rockies before he had back surgery in
'99. Nixon led off for Pawtucket in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it,'' Nixon said. ``It teaches you to be patient at the
plate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Trot's a good candidate,'' said Harper.
</P>
<P>
   Not against Seattle lefty John Halama, Trot sat while we watched
Lewis, Gilkey, and Izzy Alcantara in another weird Jimyworld lineup
that had Lansing leading off.
</P>
<P>
   Lansing was 1 for 8 through 16 innings and couldn't get a bunt
down in the 15th.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by
e-mail at dshaughnessy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0533 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-SHARON-BOS &LR;      08-02 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SHARON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGTIME BATTLER SHARON FIGHTS FOR HOLD ON JERUSALEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In May 1948, Ariel Sharon, then a young platoon
commander for the nascent Israeli army, was wounded in the battle
of Latrun, fighting to break the siege of Jerusalem by Arab forces.
</P>
<P>
   Now 52 years later, the legendary general and leader of the
conservative Likud party is still fighting for Jerusalem, which
Sharon believes is under siege once again _ this time by Prime
Minister Ehud Barak's peace moves.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Sharon announced the formation of a
coalition dedicated to preserving Jerusalem and said he would
oppose efforts to yield parts of the holy city to Palestinian
control.
</P>
<P>
   The last of the 1948 generation of leaders still left standing
on Israel's political landscape, Sharon finds himself once again on
the front lines of the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   If, as many analysts believe, Barak is forced to call early
elections, Sharon, 72, is considered a likely candidate to face
him. To do so, he will have to stave off challenges from former
prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu, now mired in a corruption
scandal, and Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert, who was edged out last
year by Sharon as Likud's leader.
</P>
<P>
   Some political analysts wonder if Sharon could yet be tapped by
Barak for a national unity government, a scenario that Sharon has
ruled out, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for two hours with a group of foreign reporters, Sharon
explained why he felt Barak had compromised Israeli security and
undermined the nation's hold on Jerusalem as its ``eternal and
united'' capital by offering too many concessions at last month's
Middle East summit at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   The interview became as much about Sharon, the man, as Sharon,
the potential candidate. He offered the reflections of an aging
warrior as he said, ``All the rights of the land are Jewish
rights,'' and ``There is no sharing of Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   Known in Israel by his nickname, ``Arik,'' Sharon is a political
lightning rod, loathed by the left and adored by the right.
</P>
<P>
   Zev Chafetz, a columnist for the English-language magazine
Jerusalem Report, said, ``You'd be hard-pressed to name anyone who
has had such a big influence in his country over such a long time _
not just in Israel but anywhere in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon created the mold for Israel's legendary commando units
after being hand-picked by Israel's founding father, David
Ben-Gurion, to create and lead the first such unit, the 101. He was
seen as an heroic commander and cunning strategist, credited with
helping save Israel from defeat in the war of 1973.
</P>
<P>
   But Sharon's policies also polarized the nation. As defense
minister, he was blamed for Israel's Vietnam, a quagmire in Lebanon
that would claim hundreds of Israeli lives and tear at the
country's moral fabric. It would take 22 years for Israel finally
to crawl out.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon's career was stained by the massacre of Palestinian
civilians at the hands of Israeli-allied Lebanese Christian forces
at the Sabra and Shatila refugee camps in Beirut in 1982. Sharon
took on Time magazine in a libel battle over his role in the
massacre. A New York jury ruled that Time defamed him but denied
damages. In 1983, an Israeli government commission declared that
Sharon bore ``personal responsibility'' for ignoring warnings of a
massacre.
</P>
<P>
   As a Likud stalwart, Sharon embraced the aggressive construction
of Jewish settlements on the West Bank. Those settlements are among
the core difficulties in achieving peace.
</P>
<P>
   As Yoel Marcus, a columnist for the Haaretz newspaper, put it,
``Only the person who built the time bomb called the settlements
really knows how to dismantle it without us all exploding.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon's shifts on the settlement issue reflect just how much
the peace process has changed Israel. In 1998 Sharon, as
Netanyahu's foreign minister, agreed to an interim pact that would
cede 9 percent of the West Bank to Palestinian control ``and not an
inch more,'' as he said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Now Barak is talking about Israeli troop withdrawals from 95
percent of the West Bank. And Sharon, vaguely hinting at
flexibility, said that ``in peace, concessions are made. We are
ready to make concessions. But not to the degree that Barak has
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon maintains that Barak, at Camp David, was ready to yield
too much ground to Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, especially by
outlining a formula for shared sovereignty of Jerusalem. By that
move, Barak has lost the confidence of the Israeli people, Sharon
says, resulting in Monday's stunning defeat of Labor party veteran
Shimon Peres in a parliamentary vote for president.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon, who grew up on a secular collective farm and admits he
is ``not at all religious,'' has grabbed the issue of Jerusalem,
perhaps sensing that the language of Israeli-Palestinian politics
is often cast in religious terms. In the last month the religious
debate intensified during the US-mediated talks on the future of
Jerusalem, claimed as a capital by both Israelis and Palestinians,
and held holy by Christians, Jews, and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Sharon announced the formation of the ``Jerusalem
Coalition,'' 58 parliament members from the major conservative and
religious parties, including Likud, Shas, the Russian immigrant
party, and the National Religious Party.
</P>
<P>
   He sidestepped suggestions that Jerusalem's shrines were not
seen a half-century ago as central to the secular, Zionist founders
of Israel. ``Jerusalem is the capital of the Jewish people for
3,000 years,'' Sharon replied. ``The Temple Mount is the holiest
place of the Jewish people, and don't think for a minute we will
give up sovereignty there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon, whose wife Lily died of cancer in March, lives on a farm
in the Negev desert. But recently, he said, he has also been
staying at his home in the Muslim quarter of Jerusalem's Old City.
</P>
<P>
   He leased the home in 1987, just as the Palestinian uprising was
getting under way, after an Arab family was evicted for failure to
pay rent. The move was seen as a provocation by Palestinians and
many liberal Israelis, including the then-Jerusalem mayor, Teddy
Kollek.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Sharon has a 20-foot Israeli flag on the towering wall of
the home that faces out on the Muslim quarter. He erected a roughly
10-foot steel menorah with plastic-encased lights that looks as
much like military hardware as a symbol of the Jewish faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Symbols are important,'' he said. ``Symbols are sacred.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Sharon has executed a stunning political return in the
past two years from the dark days after the 1982 Lebanon invasion.
Once passed over by the Labor elite, observers said, he has been a
Likud stalwart for two decades and and now stands as Barak's main
domestic rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sharon made his comeback already. It was a tough climb,'' said
Zeev Schiff, military and political affairs commentator for
Haaretz. ``He wants to climb even higher, but I have my doubts. We
would need a real crisis for people to want to turn to Sharon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
