<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0534 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-ART     08-02 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORECAST OF WEB BUSINESS FUTURE NETS FORTUNE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Chances are you have heard the analogy comparing frenetic
development of the Internet to a gold rush, in which the big
winners are not prospectors but the people who sell picks and
shovels.
</P>
<P>
   The virtual-world equivalents, Web infrastructure giants such as
Cisco Systems Inc. and EMC Corp., in fact have made a killing. But
no gold rush ever placed a value on advice or information.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that sell technical research to other companies
spending billions of dollars buying equipment and even turning
business models on their heads are reporting dramatic surges in
revenues and profits this year.
</P>
<P>
   None of those companies have captured the stock market's
attention like Forrester Research Corp., the Cambridge, Mass. firm
launched by chief executive George Colony from his basement as a
one-man shop 17 years ago. The large interest he still retains in
Forrester, about 38.5 percent, is worth nearly $500 million today.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester shares are up 71 percent so far this year and have
nearly quadrupled in the past 12 months. The stock has advanced
nearly 15-fold since it went public in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are attracted to Forrester's huge business growth and
the prospects for more. Last week, the company said its
second-quarter revenue soared by 95 percent and profits more than
doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester is hardly alone. Companies such as International Data
Corp., Jupiter Communications Inc., Giga Information Group Inc.,
the Yankee Group, and the biggest of them all, Gartner Group Inc.,
are enjoying sharply growing business.
</P>
<P>
   They are riding a wave of expensive technology change that will
require technical advice and information for years to come,
according to the people selling the research.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a two-year thing,'' said Robert Weiler, chief
executive of Cambridge-based Giga. ``This is a 5- to 10-year rise,
just on the technology we can see now, as companies have to go out
and change their business models.''
</P>
<P>
   But Forrester has captured greater attention among investors by
convincing them the company's broad research is more likely to be
ahead of the technology curve, that its ideas will matter more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether they are knowledgeable or not, they have branded
themselves as being the most knowledgeable source in the new
economy,'' said stock analyst Ullas Naik of First Albany Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Ideas, visibility, and marketing drive that image. Forrester's
researchers are paid based on a complicated formula that considers
their involvement in closing sales and appearances in the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be visible,'' Colony said of his company. ``You
have to be quoted, to be on CNBC.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also those predictions about the future, especially
the billions of dollars to be spent someday on this or that via the
Web. Those numbers often turn out to be way off, but they regularly
get attention in newspapers and on television.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who follow the research company say no one really takes
the actual numbers very seriously, but instead are interested in
the direction of electronic business forecast by leading research
companies.
</P>
<P>
   It has all paid off for Forrester so far. The company's stock
market value modestly exceeds that of the Gartner Group, though its
revenues are just one-fifth as large. Jupiter, the company seen to
be its closest head-to-head competitor, agreed to be sold last
month for about a third of Forrester's stock value.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester makes some of its money by advising big corporate
clients how to move parts of its business onto the Internet, such
as its work with General Motors and its ``EGM'' Web project and
with Federal Express to move shipping onto the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But 75 percent of Forrester's revenues are generated by research
reports sold to about 1,900 clients around the world, typically
companies spending big money on technology and looking for
information to help direct their decisions.
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of ``baseline'' research categories available on
Forrester's own Web site Tuesday: the best practices for online
marketing, business-to-business Internet trends, and the ``European
ECommerce Experience,'' each a bundle of research reports available
with the click of a mouse for $2,495 per.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester and Jupiter are distinguished from some other research
firms because they focus on broadly changing business strategies
driven by the Internet and other technology. Others supply more
tactical information about vendors, individual products or
services, how they work and what they should cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forrester is not an information business at all,'' said
Colony. ``Information is a commodity, the Web has proven that. We
are an idea factory. Ideas have to be at a level that's compelling
so they move infectiously through the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   But the research business is generating so much money it is
growing in ways that probably will change the competitive
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Gartner Group, the big information company, has started to move
into Forrester's strategy business. Jupiter is being acquired by
Media Metrix Inc., which will be able to blend strategy with
proprietary raw data.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all sort of converging, melding their offerings,''
said analyst Anthea Stratigos of Outsell Inc. ``But Forrester and
Jupiter are both still considered thought leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, smaller shops such as the Aberdeen Group of
Boston are able to carve out lucrative niches in the research
market. Another, Mainspring Inc. of Cambridge, went public just
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, big consulting firms such as Bain Consulting, the
Boston Consulting Group and others may be more direct competitors
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Colony believes Forrester will become a multi-billion-dollar
company amid all that competition as it expands in Europe and
around the world. He thinks the company has developed just the
culture to compete in that kind of environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're highly paranoid at all times,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
