<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0537 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TORIES-BUSH-BOS &LR;      08-02 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORIES-BUSH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORIES' LEADER STOPS SHORT OF ENDORSEMENT FOR BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It was appropriate that William Hague, leader of the
British opposition, all but endorsed George W. Bush in the
Philadelphia suburb King of Prussia, speaking before Republican
activists on the fringes of their convention.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Pennsylvania town that is best known to Americans
as having one the biggest shopping malls in the United States is
better known to Britons as having been named in honor of Frederick
the Great, who helped the British defeat the French in the Seven
Years' War.
</P>
<P>
   Hague, whose Conservative Party has mostly floundered since Tony
Blair's Labor Party won the biggest parliamentary majority in
nearly two centuries in May 1997, envisions a new ``special
relationship'' between Washington and London. His hope: that the
Republicans can retake the White House and become the Tories'
allies in ousting Labor at the next general election in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   After suffering nothing but humiliation for nearly three years,
the Tories are on something of a roll. Blair's Teflon image has
slipped, as has Labor's popularity, which is now in the single
digits over the Conservatives. A series of recently leaked internal
Labor memorandums show a government on the defensive, worrying that
the Conservatives are more in tune with British public opinion on
patriotism and being tough on crime.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise, then, to hear Hague sing the praises of Bush and
the Republicans. Still, in keeping with British diplomatic
protocol, which frowns on endorsing candidates in elections abroad,
Hague's not-quite-an-endorsement was coached in the language of
those who prepare for the hurly-burly of British politics at Oxford
and Cambridge universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not for me to tell the voters of America how to vote,
but let me say this: George W. Bush is an impressive man with a
proud record,'' Hague told Republican activists at a Radisson hotel
Monday. ``We wish him well.''
</P>
<P>
   Hague's study and guarded courtship of the Republicans mirrors
Blair's efforts eight years ago. Then, Labor strategists, and Blair
himself, assiduously researched how Bill Clinton marginalized
left-wing activists in the Democratic Party, moved the Democrats to
the center of the American political spectrum, and ended 12 years
of Republican control of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Beholden to special interest groups, most notably the labor
unions, Blair's party was even more unelectable than the Democrats.
But he ended 18 years of uninterrupted Tory power by ignoring the
notoriously loud but politically impotent left wing of his party
and convincing an overwhelming majority of Britons that his vision
of Cool Britannia offered more for the future than the Tory vision
of Britain being, as the last Tory prime minister, John Major, put
it, ``a country of long shadows on county grounds, warm beer,
invincible green suburbs, dog lovers, and pools-fillers and, as
George Orwell said, old maids cycling to holy communion through the
morning mist.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, British politicians run a risk when they inject
themselves into US politics. The Clinton administration never
forgave Major after he gave Bush's father a similar endorsement in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   British diplomats remain convinced that Major's intervention on
the elder Bush's behalf was part of the reason the Clinton
administration injected itself into the Northern Ireland peace
process, and why it took less of a pro-British stand.
</P>
<P>
   Before Clinton was elected, the White House steered clear of
Northern Ireland, viewing it as a domestic British matter. But
Clinton, who became interested in the conflict while studying at
Oxford, decided American involvement could help bring about a
compromise. The Clinton administration broke precedent, treating
the Irish government and the British government as equals and
dispatching George Mitchell, the former Senate majority leader from
Maine, to mediate.
</P>
<P>
   Those same diplomats who believe Major's backing of Bush hurt
the ``special relationship'' also acknowledge that the Americans
played a mostly positive role in bringing about the Good Friday
Agreement of 1998, the compromise brokered by Mitchell aimed at
ending violence and turning the dispute over Northern Ireland into
one resolved strictly through peaceful, democratic means.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Clinton, the peace process wouldn't have happened,''
said a senior official at the British Foreign Office.
</P>
<P>
   Already, some of the conservative standard bearers in Britain
are worried about Hague's enthusiastic embrace of Bush's
``compassionate conservatism,'' not for ideological reasons, but
because of the downsides should Al Gore win.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Daley, the Boston-born columnist for the Daily Telegraph,
the voice of British conservatism, Tuesday warned Hague to go easy
on imitating Bush, or at least to put compassionate conservatism in
context. Daley said Bush and Hague both believe in less taxes, less
government, and more individual choice in public education. Both
are tough on crime. But, she said, while Bush's positions are
considered compassionate conservatism on the American political
spectrum, Hague's views have been widely described in Britain as
extreme and hardline.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Republicans talk about compassionate conservatism, they
mean that they will refrain from kicking murderers all the way to
the electric chair,'' Daley said. ``When Mr. Bush talks soft, he is
only reining back on the virulent right-wing fundamentalism of the
American backwoods: the sort of people who shoot up abortion
clinics and want the babies of single mothers to be exposed to the
elements like rejected Chinese female infants.''
</P>
<P>
   Capital punishment, meanwhile, remains a political minefield in
Britain, where opposition to the death penalty is widespread and
cuts across party lines. Last year, Hague visited Bush at the
gubernatorial office in Austin to talk about compassionate
conservatism. After plans for that trip were announced, the Globe
asked Hague's spokesman, Gregor Mackay, to comment on how Bush's
enthusiastic embrace of capital punishment squared with
compassionate conservatism. Mackay declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Blair, who personally visited the convention floor when
the Democrats met in New York in 1992, Hague is leaving that
assignment to about a dozen senior party members.
</P>
<P>
   The Tories' visit to the Republican convention is only the first
British incursion at the American conventions. When the Democrats
convene in two weeks, Johnny Rotten, former lead singer of the punk
band the Sex Pistols, will cover the convention for the Web site
eYada.com.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Meyrowitz, eYada.com's founder, promises Rotten, whose 1970s
anarchist anthem ``God Save the Queen'' claimed the monarchy
represented a ``fascist regime,'' will ``turn this convention on
its head.''
</P>
<P>
   Rotten's lyrics are an indictment of the establishment,
especially politicians. In ``Liar,'' which attacks politicians
among others, he snarls that ``I know what I know. You're in
suspicion. You're a liar!''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Hague, it is doubtful that Rotten will be making an
endorsement that isn't really an endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I,'' declared the punk rocker, ``will never sit on the
fence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
