<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0538 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-COWBOYS-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      08-02 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOYS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SPACE COWBOYS' STILL HAVE THE RIGHT STUFF
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clint Eastwood's latest geezer fantasy is, basically, John Glenn
does ``Armageddon.'' Amiable to a fault _ by the time things mosey
around to a save-the-world third act, any potential for suspense
has been pleasantly frittered away _ ``Space Cowboys'' is much more
successful as an easygoing character comedy than as awesome
astronaut adventure. Wrinkled charm is this vehicle's real solid
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The concept could not be simpler, nor a more comfortable fit for
its macho-mellow stars. Eastwood's Frank, Tommy Lee Jones' Hawk,
Donald Sutherland's Jerry and James Garner's Tank were all hotshot
test pilots in the 1950s (the very nice, black-and-white opening
flashback offers young ringers for the famous actors dubbed by the
icons' unmistakable voices) who were bypassed for the space program
when NASA commandeered it from the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-some years later, a key Russian communications satellite's
orbit is degrading, and it can only be fixed Up There. Since all
the current astronauts are too young to understand the obsolete
bird's operational system, the space program has to turn to the guy
who designed it _ that's right, Frank.
</P>
<P>
   What his work is doing in a 30-year-old Soviet craft is a good
question that is later answered in the most alarming way imaginable
(it's a Clint movie, so even though they may not be commies
anymore, you still can't trust those Russkies). Time's running out,
the vice president insists we help, and so Frank's hated ex-boss,
Gerson (James Cromwell), now a NASA bigwig, has to agree to the
snarling senior's demand that his old team be sent up on the
mission.
</P>
<P>
   If, of course, they can pass the physical. Training turns out to
be ``Space Cowboys''' most genial stretch, as the old buckaroos do
their best to feign fitness for the assignment. After all these
years, Tank's devolved into a boring, scatterbrained Baptist
minister, half-blind Jerry is happy test-driving roller coasters
and young mistresses, and Hawk, who has the most contentious
relationship with Frank, still hasn't gotten over his beloved
wife's death.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, they all want their long-postponed shot at
space. Prep time, some of which was filmed at the actual Johnson
Space Center and Cape Canaveral in Florida, is a jokey affair; the
boys are constantly told about old colleagues who've died and the
few still around inevitably greet Frank with a cheery, ``You never
were a team player.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the supposed urgency of the situation, there is time for
a May-December romance (Marcia Gay Hardin is the comely scientist
half), a bar brawl and new Clint one-liners like ``Clock's ticking,
Bob, and I'm only getting older.'' Later, there's a cancer scare,
orbital complications and opportunities for noble self-sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   It all gets steadily more preposterous, and the dramatic
possibilities in the seniors' frailties remain frustratingly
unexplored.
</P>
<P>
   But you do leave the proceedings going ``Old guys rule!'' The
superannuated ensemble serves up effortless rapport, and it's all
agreeable, midrange Eastwood entertainment, nothing profound but
put across with smooth aplomb by his usual crack team of
cinematographer Jack N. Green, production designer Henry Bumstead
and composer Lennie Niehaus.
</P>
<P>
   Even though ``Space Cowboys'' is fundamentally meaningless, I
have little doubt that, in a quarter century or so, it'll mean a
whole lot more to me. &QL; 
------------------------- &QL; 
The film: ``Space Cowboys'' (PG-13; mild swearing and tense
action). &QL; 
The stars: Clint Eastwood, Tommy Lee Jones, Donald Sutherland,
James Garner, James Cromwell, Marcia Gay Hardin, William Devane,
Loren Dean. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Clint Eastwood. Written by Ken
Kaufman and Howard Klausner. Produced by Eastwood and Andrew
Lazar. &QL; 
Running time: Two hours, 10 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
