<HEADER>
A0542 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-02 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRESSIVE STREAK SEEN IN RELIGIOUS VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think of the recent examples in which politicians have overtly
courted religious voters: George W. Bush speaks at the
fundamentalist Bob Jones University and meets with Boston's
Cardinal Bernard F. Law, Hillary Rodham Clinton speaks at an
Orthodox synagogue in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Protestants, Catholics and Jews have become visible
and influential players in national politics, and conservative
religious values have become an important part of many policy
debates.
</P>
<P>
   But a prominent Princeton University scholar argues that the
focus on groups like the Christian right has overshadowed a reality
of the relationship between religion and politics: there is a
strong progressive streak among religious voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception that religious groups are really only
interested in conservative issues is not true,'' said Princeton
sociologist Robert Wuthnow. ``They are not only focused on issues
such as abortion or prayer in the schools. Progressive issues do
seem to be of enormous importance to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Wuthnow, who is leading a major study on mainline Protestantism
in America for the Pew Charitable Trusts, recently surveyed more
than 5,600 Americans of varying religious faiths about their views
on public policy.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that beyond the hot button church-state issues,
nearly 60 percent of voters of all faiths, including evangelicals,
are interested in seeing government do more to protect the
environment, help the poor, overcome discrimination against women,
and promote international peace. Those polled were significantly
less interested in relief programs for Third World countries,
legislation that would reduce intolerance toward homosexuals, and
campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have too often assumed that mainline Protestants are
politically dormant,'' Wuthnow said. ``These results show they are
politically interested and active.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, those polled seemed to suggest that their
priorities were not the same as those articulated from the pulpit.
Sixty percent said they had not over the last year heard a sermon
on government policies toward the poor, and 56 percent said recent
sermons had not touched on environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
   But they generally reported social action by their churches.
Seventy-nine percent said their congregation had sponsored a soup
kitchen or food pantry in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   The poll found broad consensus on some matters of religious
faith and practice: 84 percent said the Bible is the inspired word
of God, 64 percent said they pray every day, and 87 percent said
spiritual growth is at least fairly important to them.
</P>
<P>
   But Americans seem to be somewhat ambivalent about exactly how
religous groups should interact with the political world.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, 76 percent said religious leaders should express
their views on social and political issues. But they were wary of
some modes of expression associated with the Christian right: 66
percent want fewer religious leaders to criticize elected
officials, 59 percent want fewer religious leaders to form
political movements, and 52 percent said they would like to see
fewer religious leaders on television talk shows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
