<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0544 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-UGLY-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      08-02 1353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGLY-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTIES AND THE BEAST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Coyote Ugly,'' superproducer Jerry (``Flashdance'')
Bruckheimer's latest contribution to the collapse of Western
Civilization, is a movie about beer, dancing on bars and, of
course, self-empowerment. It charts the misadventures of five
lovely young women who work at the title tavern (which actually
exists) in New York City, where they're encouraged to strut, holler
and otherwise keep drinking men occupied.
</P>
<P>
   Before you get the wrong idea, these girls are not strippers or
hookers (this phenomenon, after all, is pretty specific to Rudolph
Giuliani's brave new puritanized Manhattan). They're just trying to
serve up some nice, clean fun between shots. They also wear a lot
of tight leather.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, ``Coyote's'' five lead actresses seem to have had a good
time making the movie. Maria Bello (``ER''), Piper Perabo (``The
Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle''), Tyra Banks (Victoria's
Secret), Bridget Moynahan (``Sex and the City'') and Izabella Miko
(she's from Poland) spoke to the Daily News about their wild nights
in the big city.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Like all the members of the movie's target audience, we're
mainly interested in the girls' personalities. Can each of you
describe what your coyote is like?
</P>
<P>
   Bello: I play the character Lil, who's the boss of the bar. She
owns this place, she's worked her whole life to own and operate her
own business. She hires only women, and it's a great training
ground for them to go on and achieve their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Miko: I play the role of Cammie, who works at the bar. She's a
very happy girl but she's a little bit naive and falls in love
constantly with, I guess, all the wrong guys because she doesn't
have a steady boyfriend. She makes friends with Violet; she's the
nice one.
</P>
<P>
   Perabo: I'm Violet, the sweet, innocent girl from the New Jersey
suburbs who's come to New York to make it as a songwriter. She
never wants to perform her own work, and that's where Coyote Ugly
comes in. She just gets a job there to pay her rent, but being
around all these loud, rowdy, raucous women begins to rub off on
her, and eventually it's what helps her get over her stage fright.
</P>
<P>
   Banks: My character, Zoe, is at the Coyote Ugly to make money
for law school. I consider her to be the crazy one. It wasn't
really written that way, but I noticed really strong personalities
when I read with the other girls: one was heavy flirtatious; one
was very, very tough; one was really shy; and one was really sweet.
So I just decided to make mine nuts, just screaming and dancing on
the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is that any way for an aspiring attorney to pursue her dream?
</P>
<P>
   Banks: Definitely! You have to be very animated in court, able
to intimidate and raise your voice.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which means you, Bridget, must be ... ?
</P>
<P>
   Moynahan: ... The tough chick, Rachel. She sort of runs the
show, underneath Lil. She's definitely antagonistic toward the new
girl; it's sort of Rachel's game to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: OK, now that that's out of the way, just how sexy is this
thing?
</P>
<P>
   Bello: It's kind of like ``Flashdance,'' put in this new
setting, which is edgier. It might be wild, but it's not overtly
sexual; it's not violent in any way; it's not degrading to women or
to men in any way. It's certainly not a G Disney film, but it's
sexy without being too much, I think.
</P>
<P>
   Q: That's not exactly how they're selling it. The promotional
campaign makes it seem like one long drunken orgy.
</P>
<P>
   Moynahan: Well, we are working in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Banks: In terms of moviemaking, you kind of have to sugarcoat
something to get people in there and get your message across. It's
like, I have a camp for young girls now called T-Zone. Its message
is about self-esteem and finding yourself and having a good body
image and pride about your heritage ... But we're not gonna sell it
like that! It's like, ``Oh, come to camp! We're gonna do ropes
courses and swim and play and have fun!''
</P>
<P>
   And that's kinda how it is with ``Coyote Ugly.'' You don't wanna
do ``Message!''_ cause who wants to be preached to? But if girls
are dancing on the bar and you're getting this message but don't
know you are ... It's like propaganda!
</P>
<P>
   Perabo: I mean, it doesn't hurt that the girls are awful pretty.
But for my character, there's a love story in it and it's a lot
about making it as a songwriter. The bar's just this kind of, like,
wild center in the film. But it's a fine line for me, as a woman,
whether you are exploiting yourself because you're pretty. I don't
know; it depends on how they cut the movie, really.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the wildest thing you do in the movie?
</P>
<P>
   Miko: We all do a water dance, which I think is pretty wild. We
pour pitchers of water on each other, which I thought was so fun.
Sexy, but cool.
</P>
<P>
   Moynahan: I set the bar on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you do any research at the real Coyote Ugly?
</P>
<P>
   Bello: I've trained for this movie for 15 years, just being a
real bartender. But I stopped in at Hogs &AMP; Heifers and Red Rock
West, which are the same sorts of bars. I loved the vibes there,
and every time I went in, they were completely packed. Similar
stuff as in the movie goes on, for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Perabo: Actually, I was just in Coyote Ugly a couple of days
ago. The real Lil who owns it was there, with her baby. It's a lot
smaller than the set they built for the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Banks: Yeah, Hogs &AMP; Heifers is tiny, too.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Dance on the bar there?
</P>
<P>
   Banks: Yeah. I didn't want to, but they made me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was the dancing the hardest thing to do in the movie?
</P>
<P>
   Banks: No, I had dance training when I was a little girl. It
comes very naturally to me; I have a strong kind of street dancing
thing like Janet Jackson or Britney Spears, that kind of hip-hop
dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Perabo: I went to theater school, where it was requisite to take
ballet and modern. Learning to play the guitar was the hardest part
for me. To learn an instrument is no small task, and especially the
guitar because you need calluses on your fingers or forget it,
those chords. I play it OK now.
</P>
<P>
   Miko: I'm a professional dancer, so for me it was great just to
kind of let go instead of being very restricted, like in ballet.
There, you could do whatever you wanted; there was choreography,
but it was pretty loose.
</P>
<P>
   All of the bar stuff, trying to speed serve, that was pretty
challenging. They brought in professional jugglers to show us how
to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Moynahan: The bartending wasn't difficult for me. I'd never
taken a dance class, though, so it was lots of hard work just to
get to the level of Izabella, who had trained all her life. But I
think it came over; I think it worked.
</P>
<P>
   Bello: I own the place. I didn't have to dance.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you develop much camaraderie or, well, hate one another?
</P>
<P>
   Moynahan: Contrary to what everybody wishes went on, we all got
along.
</P>
<P>
   Perabo: Even though the dance rehearsals were kicking my butt,
they were really good for the movie itself because these women know
each other well and work hard together. They're bar-backing the
bar, too; there's no guys carrying the liquor up from underneath.
These girls work long hours together, and dance rehearsal was a
good way to build that bond between us.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So, like the women you portray, are you all ready for
``Coyote Ugly'' to help you achieve your dreams?
</P>
<P>
   Perabo: I don't know what to expect. It appears to be such a
surreal thing, that people would know you but you don't know them.
But even if you're not famous, people are crazy. You meet crazy
people, you walk away. You meet cool people, you hang.
</P>
<P>
   Banks: Piper got picked from all of these thousands of girls to
star in this movie. She's gonna be the next hot thing but she's
not, like, smellin' herself, and I'm impressed with that. People
are like, ``Tell her not to change, tell her how you didn't change,
Tyra.'' But I don't have to tell her that. You can just see that
she's gonna be all right.
</P>
<P>
   Moynahan: My dream, ultimately? I don't know, but I'm living
part of it right now. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0547 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-BEHR-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-A     08-02 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BEHR-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BARNET, Vt.: ... to serve.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Behr is one of those people who is very critical about the
quality of food. And it's hard for him to feel satisfied with his
local ingredients. He used to be more interested in the simplicity
of life than he was in anything else.
</P>
<P>
   After college, he went shopping for a beautiful place to live.
He considered central Maine, which is desolate and filled with
scrub pines; St. Lawrence in New York, which is gray for six weeks
in the fall, ``but you could get a whole dairy, all the cattle, and
the family _ for $19,500''; and the Northeast Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   At first he lived in Newark, Vt., a hill town. ``There were 175
people, it was quite poor, very high. Not a lot of towns in New
England that were that poor and depopulated.'' He built a stone
house at the end of an unpaved road, then did carpentry and some
printmaking, courtesy of a small grant from the Vermont Council on
the Arts. He also returned to his home near Washington, D.C., to
teach learning-disabled children for a while.
</P>
<P>
   He moved to Barnet in 1982. His long hair was already cut into a
crew cut, which he still has. Now it's gray, and he's traded
workman's clothes for black Italian shoes, slim jeans, small
European silver wire-rim glasses, and a dark olive-green polo shirt
that also looks Italian.
</P>
<P>
   When he began The Art of Eating, it combined his love of good
graphics with his intense curiosity about how things are made. In a
way, Behr had always been around the word business. His father was
a ``rewrite man'' for The Wall Street Journal and now acts as
Eating's informal editor. ``He reads everything,'' says Behr. ``He
doesn't know anything about food so he asks all the right
questions.'' Behr used to have other family ties. He is divorced
from Grace DiNapoli, who used to be his printer.
</P>
<P>
   The house in Barnet was built on the top of 15 acres that
overlook three dairy farms. ``Not a lot of places around here where
you can see that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside, his efficient, tidy, butter-yellow kitchen is open to a
room that serves as an office for his assistant. One corner is
stacked with computer paper and back copies of The Art of Eating,
but someday it will be home to a fireplace and stone oven. Boulders
for the project sit outside the front door in a huge mound,
sprouting weeds after their many years in the same spot. The pile
of stones is about the only unsightly thing in an otherwise
meticulous place.
</P>
<P>
   From his travels, Behr has all kinds of unusual cooking
implements, including a vinegar-making barrel on a shelf near the
site of the future fireplace. Old stoneware holds cooking tools and
flour. An open cabinet door reveals Mediterranean earthenware
pottery and two outsized mortars.
</P>
<P>
   One piece of pottery, from the Charentes in France, is ``cheap
peasant cookware,'' says Behr, because it's an all-purpose pot that
would be used even in the poorest households. It has the shape of a
deep round casserole, dark brown glaze inside, with an unglazed
earthenware surface, and it goes directly on a heat diffuser over a
flame for roasting chestnuts and potatoes. ``Eventually it will
crack,'' he says. Its only protection from heat is that he rubbed
garlic all over it before he used it _ a widespread peasant
superstition. Behr also returned home with a clockwork spit for his
fireplace, of the sort used for hearth cooking for hundreds of
years before the introduction of modern ovens.
</P>
<P>
   Everything about the place speaks to style, to a deep
appreciation of both ancient and contemporary design. A household
that is filled with old equipment has a dining room table
surrounded by molded iridescent-green Italian chairs and a tall
lamp on an aluminum photography light stand.
</P>
<P>
   He has thought about every single item on the table, including
the French plates and flatware, pink checkerboard cloth, and pink
windowpane napkins. It seems cheerful and thoughtful, but Behr, who
spends his life recording the movements of the people who make some
of the best food in the world, isn't so cheerful as he contemplates
the future. He frets that the little farmers in Europe who have
worked so long to maintain the highest standards of quality will
one day be ignored and finally forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of what I'm doing is recording the end of good
food,'' he says. Then he passes a plate of beautiful, oozingly rich
local Brie.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Art of Eating is published quarterly for $36 by Edward Behr,
Box 242, Peacham, VT 05862. Telephone 800-495-3944, fax
802-592-3400, or go to the Web site www.artofeating.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SIDEBAR &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For years Edward Behr wrote The Art of Eating by himself.
Lately, he has commissioned short pieces, which run at the end of
the newsletter. The summer issue, for instance, contains a piece on
Darjeeling by Montreal writer Kevin Gascoyne, and another on the
Egyptian dish melokhia by Nancy Harmon Jenkins. ``The logic is that
the (newsletter) has a life of its own,'' says Behr. ``It wants to
be more of a magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Behr will continue to write the major pieces, which have
recently focused on the region of Emilia Romagna, considered to
have some of Italy's best food; the Iowa pig farm that supplies
pork to Chez Panisse in Berkeley, Calif.; and a tour of a
cooperative olive press, an oyster farm, and a bread bakery in
Sonoma, Calif. Behr is as interested in wine as he is in food, so
he is as likely to write about a vineyard as he is about, say, a
cheesemaker. Many newsletters end with several related recipes,
written in a loose, chatty style. This recipe for eggplant and
tomato came in the pork issue, along with a simple brine for
roasting pork, sweet-and-sour shallots, and a white wine-rosemary
sauce for pork. The recipe for potato cakes was printed at the end
of a discussion of dry-aged steak.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
EGGPLANT AND TOMATO
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Behr took this recipe from an 1886 French cookbook by Marius
Morard, ``Manuel complet de la cuisiniere provencale.'' Morard, a
hotel cook, suggested pureeing this mixture through a sieve.
</P>
<P>
   1 pound eggplant
</P>
<P>
   1 pound tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Black pepper
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen branches flat-leafed parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peel the eggplant, cut in 3/4-dice, and mix with the salt. Allow
the eggplant to release its liquid for at least 1/2 hour. Rinse and
drain, and cook until tender in olive oil, stirring from time to
time. While the eggplant is cooking, peel the tomatoes (you can
loosen the skins by dipping the tomatoes for no more than 60
seconds in boiling water; cool in cold water). Halve the tomatoes
crosswise, scoop out the seeds with your finger, and chop the flesh
coarsely. Cook the tomato in olive oil until tender. Combine the
two vegetables, seasoning well with salt and pepper. Finely chop
the parsley and garlic shortly before serving, and sprinkle on top
or stir in.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
POTATO CAKES
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 2 pounds of floury potatoes, such as russets
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons unsalted butter, plus more for frying
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Bake the potatoes and cut them in half. One at a time, holding
the hot potatoes in a hand protected with a pad or folded towel,
spoon out the insides. Mash with butter and salt and pepper (no
liquid). Melt a tablespoon of butter in one or two large heavy
frying pans. Divide the mashed potato into four pieces. Flatten
each portion to form a roughly 3/4-inch-thick cake. Brown the cakes
well on one side before turning to brown the other side well.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
