<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0551 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-BEHR-2TAKES-ART-     08-02 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BEHR-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 NORTHWOODS PUBLISHER EDWARD BEHR WRITES FOR ADVENTUROUS FOODIES 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARNET, Vt. _ Edward Behr, publisher of The Art of Eating, a
food and wine newsletter that just celebrated its 10th year, was
fairly new to writing when he was invited to tour Italy with five
American authors. His fellow travelers _ Carol Field, Nancy Harmon
Jenkins, Corby Kummer, Fred Plotkin, and Faith Willinger _ are all
well-known authorities on Italian food, all fluent in Italian, all
so well versed in the history and culture of Italy that guidebooks
are superfluous when they're around.
</P>
<P>
   Behr tried to prepare for the trip. He has a good ear for
languages, he says, and, hoping to be able to keep up with his
illustrious companions, he listened to Italian language tapes.
</P>
<P>
   It helped his Italian, but not his self-confidence. ``I was
intimidated by Fred,'' says Behr, ``who spoke perfect Italian, by
Carol, whose name I knew very well, and by Nancy, who was a
journalist.''
</P>
<P>
   They must not have noticed. Behr was embraced by the group,
which named itself ``La Banda'' and went on to travel together many
more times. Books produced by members of the group invariably
credit ``La Banda'' followed by a list of first names, reading
something like: ``Carol, Corby, Faith, Fred, and Ed.''
</P>
<P>
   So Ed Behr passed muster. Now he knows many of the major food
professionals in this country and Europe. But a decade into his
newsletter, which goes to 3,000 subscribers (most of whom renew
faithfully every year), Behr is relatively unknown. Such devotion
and mystery inspires curiosity. Who is Ed Behr? He hears this
question all the time. New readers ask ``Why haven't I heard of you
before?'' Behr attributes his anonymity to his isolation in the
Northeast Kingdom, to the fact that word-of-mouth spreads slowly _
it was only recently that he had a piddling 1,000 subscribers _ and
to the idea that he writes and publishes ``a small, eccentric''
newsletter. ``I'm quirky,'' says Behr. ``I have an audience who
demands depth and accuracy. I'm writing more than most editors
think their readers want.''
</P>
<P>
   If you read Ed Behr (no one calls his newsletter by its real
name), you have paid $36 for four issues, each 32 pages of
advertising-free writing on a single subject, printed on very
high-quality paper, about topics like Sauternes, the sweet white
wine from Bordeaux; dry-aged steak, for which he bought and ate
several _ and wasn't knocked out; the caves of Roquefort, where the
famous blue-veined cheese has been made for some 500 years; and
Catalan cooking as it is found in and around Barcelona. Behr has a
straightforward way of presenting his information, which is well
reported _ he doesn't write extensively about anything he hasn't
visited _ and descriptive in the most appealing way. He writes the
kind of intellectual, thoughtful pieces you would expect to read in
The New Yorker if it regularly covered food.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this guy because he gets interested in a topic and
devotes a whole issue to it,'' says Chris Kimball, publisher of
Cook's Illustrated magazine, another publication without
advertising. ``He could care less about cover notes, entertaining
his readers, or providing vicarious thrills to make them renew. If
you want an in-depth look, it's one-of-a-kind stuff. He's not
pandering to anybody but his own curiosity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To report, Behr sometimes uses Italian, which he gets along in
now. He is also fluent in French. People have told him that they
think he prefers Italy to France, which isn't true, but he does
like Italians. ``The Italians are so much more fun than the
French,'' he says. ``If you wanted a fun party, would you invite
the French? No. You'd invite them if you wanted an interesting,
cerebral party.''
</P>
<P>
   He understands both cultures through their land. He isn't afraid
to get on the road and roll up his sleeves to see agriculture at
its roots. As you travel with him, you get what he gets. In the
case of Roquefort, for instance, Behr went to the sheep farms where
the cheese is made. You can picture the hills and valleys, hear the
difference in dialect (when someone offers thanks, the other person
says ``with pleasure,'' rather than the usual ``it's nothing''),
and understand the passion of people who have made the same product
for so long that when they notice cheeses becoming oval from
sitting on their sides, they are distraught. The cheese should be
round, and it won't be accepted at market.
</P>
<P>
   In Catalonia, Behr went in search of calcots, which are pungent
onions set on a grid and cooked over vine prunings. ``The sweet
calcots blacken rapidly and they are turned once,'' writes Behr.
``The grid is quickly taken from the fire before the calcots are
hopelessly charred. Then they are tightly packed in the concave
side of an old clay roof tile. For half an hour they cook through
by their own heat. The clay tile bearing calcots arrives steaming
at the table. They should be so hot they almost burn your fingers.
You take one and search the black top for the pale green inner
leaves. You hold them tightly and with the other hand slide off the
charred sheath.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Behr will have you running to your grill to reproduce the
Catalan onions. He undoubtedly understands the hard-working
farmers, cooks, and winemakers he meets partly because his own
life, by choice, isn't that removed from theirs. Of course he's
writing instead of tending sheep or cooking outdoors, but the
setting isn't dissimilar, and neither is his rather spartan way of
life.
</P>
<P>
   He lives in a two-story white clapboard New England house in one
of the southernmost towns of the Northeast Kingdom, a house he
designed himself _ he was a carpenter before he became a writer.
Barnet, he says, which is located in the county of Caledonia, isn't
on everyone's map of the Northeast Kingdom. Some locals,
apparently, don't recognize this county. Barnet ``doesn't have the
trailer grittiness that some towns have,'' he says. ``A generation
has died, and enormous numbers have moved in from outside. At one
time a majority of the buildings were old. Now a majority are
new.''
</P>
<P>
   Behr, 49, is one of the newcomers, though he's been in the
region ``more than half my life.'' He came to New England to attend
Phillips Exeter Academy for his last year of high school. He had
been at Bethesda-Chevy Chase High School outside Washington, D. C.,
when he began doing ``hippie revolutionary things'' and was shipped
north. He was indifferent to academics back then and attended
Hamilton College, which he thinks accepted him because his
great-grandfather went there, and then Bennington College.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a poor student and very lazy,'' he says over a
French-style midday dinner at his home. ``Now I'm a good student
who is not lazy at all.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also a self-conscious but capable home cook who makes
honest, simple dishes. He begins lunch for visitors with Spanish
Arbequina olives, ``one of the great underappreciated olives,''
then warm bread, or what he calls ``reheated bread, just to give it
the illusion of freshness.'' A bowl of his own small turnips is
drizzled with olive oil, and a delicious roast pork dish,
reinvented from a meal he made earlier in the week, is surrounded
by caramelized onions. There is also salad, tossed with a dressing
made from his own vinegar, Vermont Brie, and finally roasted
peaches with soft whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   He is almost too serious about the quality of every single
ingredient, worrying about whether the bread is OK and the pork has
enough taste. ``I tried to buy the fattiest cut because it means it
may come from a local producer,'' he says. He has already put away
a bowl of roasted eggplant he began preparing because he decided it
wasn't good enough to serve.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
