<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0556 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HARP-TEACHER-ART-BOS &LR;      08-02 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARP-TEACHER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 FORMER HARPIST, 92, IS STILL TEACHING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, Maine _ Alice Chalifoux, the 92-year-old teacher of some
of the world's best harpists, paused midthrow recently to offer
some insights that come after so many years. She held a Frisbee in
her right hand, while her dog Patch stood at her feet awaiting the
toss like a coiled spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't dwell on failures,'' she said. ``I'm able to close
doors, open new ones.'' That said, she launched Frisbee and dog
into the crisp morning air of Penobscot Bay, then walked briskly
toward a breakfast of warm blueberry muffins and a day full of
students eager to open new doors.
</P>
<P>
   Chalifoux directs the Salzedo Harp Colony, a 59-year-old New
England institution that brings 54 harpists to the Camden area each
summer to study with her. Mind you, she is Miss, not Ms.,
Chalifoux. Nor is she Mrs. Rideout (her late husband, John Rideout,
died a half-century ago). She's ``miss'' because this is how a
proper young lady just out of an Alabama convent school was
addressed when she joined the Cleveland Symphony as the principal
harpist in 1931.
</P>
<P>
   But she is no milquetoast playing the instrument of angels. The
tiny harpist who still speaks with a hint of Alabama could hold her
own with the coarsest of Maine loggers _ with whom she would be
happy to hoist a glass if the invitation were extended. The
``miss'' has stuck, but the southern-belle propriety was cast off
during her first year with the symphony when Chalifoux countered
the chauvinism of the almost-all-male orchestra with language she
never learned from the nuns. It was particularly useful in showing
her displeasure when she had to use her harp case as a lockerroom,
since most symphony halls provided changing rooms for men only.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was expecting this mousy, quiet girl,'' said Ann
Hobson Pilot, a former student and the principal harpist for the
Boston Symphony Orchestra. ``They got something quite, quite
different.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they got someone whose students now play principal harp
in three of the five leading orchestras in the nation _ Boston,
Cleveland, and Philadelphia, according to professional musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss Chalifoux teaches by inspiring. She draws it out of you
because she works so hard. You don't take a lesson from her and
futz around,'' said Douglas Rioth, who plays the first harp for the
San Francisco Symphony. How much does he value her today? Rioth
will be a guest performer at Tanglewood on Aug. 13, and said he'll
play such a challenging piece that he plans to swing through Camden
first for a brush-up lesson from Chalifoux.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Ericsson is another student. Eight years a member of the
Boston Symphony Orchestra, Ericsson resigned two years ago to start
a solo harp career.
</P>
<P>
   ``She makes a complete commitment to her students. She is a shot
of vitamin B12, always helping take the harp to another level,''
Ericsson said.
</P>
<P>
   When Chalifoux was growing up in Birmingham, Ala., the harp _
introduced to her by her mother _ was considered a piece of angelic
parlor furniture, more music box than serious instrument.
</P>
<P>
   Then along came Carlos Salzedo, a French harpist who moved to
Philadelphia in the 1920s to write some of the first music designed
specifically for the harp. He also bought a small house in Camden,
where he invited promising students to take lessons each summer.
Salzedo's pieces required players not to just pluck the strings,
but to pull them for greater volume and range. It became known as
the Salzedo Technique, and Chalifoux was one of his youngest
students.
</P>
<P>
   For the decades that followed, Chalifoux studied with Salzedo _
then taught with him, eventually inheriting the nonprofit Harp
Colony in 1961 while continuing to play with the Cleveland
Symphony, raise a daughter, and teach music at two Ohio institutes.
</P>
<P>
   Today she lives with her daughter's family in Virginia, spending
the three summer months in Camden. She has retired from all
professional responsibilities except for teaching in the shingle
house at the end of Marine Street.
</P>
<P>
   The Camden house is decorated in the art deco style of Salzedo's
day. Except for a harp, about the only other object that makes any
noise in the house is an old Zenith AM radio. Chalifoux doesn't
come here to tend house, to vacation, to shop for Down East
knickknacks, to sail aboard aboard a Camden schooner.
</P>
<P>
   She comes here to work.
</P>
<P>
   Chalifoux has a shock of white hair; her hands are arthritic,
but still able to bang out chords on the harp. And she is small; 5
feet would be generous. Because she looks through her car's
steering wheel, not over it, folks hereabouts say they know she is
in town when they see her blue Buick Century station wagon cruising
down Main Street with no one in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't afford an accident. They'll take my license away. And
I won't be able to apply for another one until I'm 95,'' Chalifoux
explained the other day between lessons. She gives seven a day,
about 550 lessons a summer. Students travel around the world to
learn from her, bringing video cameras to tape sessions for further
study back home. She charges $75 per lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I could make more money,'' she said. ``But what am I
going to do with it?''
</P>
<P>
   Students say that one of her greatest skills is zeroing in
immediately on the ability of a player, then advancing it a notch.
Melissa Tardiff, 23, from Salisbury, Md., had just completed a
session with Chalifoux. Jillian Jones, 14, of Wichita, Kan., was
next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now let's start with some exercises,'' Chalifoux instructed.
``Right hand . . . beautiful! Nice hand position. . . . Now the
left hand . . . louder, dear, sock'em more . . . ba-ba-BING!''
</P>
<P>
   Chalifoux was up and down in her wicker chair, plucking notes,
then pushing Jones to do the same. There did not seem to be time
for the girl to breathe, much less make the corrections, but the
elder woman continued to smother the younger woman with
instructions _ and Jones stayed with her, the girl's mother and
grandmother watching from seats against one wall of the living
room, exhausted just listening to the pace of instruction.
</P>
<P>
   When the lesson ended and the trio left, Chalifoux offered this:
``That Jillian's a smart girl. She can take it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 4 p.m., another lesson was on deck, but Chalifoux
appeared more charged than ever, as if she had just opened another
door a bit wider.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
