<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, Aug. 3:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE REPUBLICAN CONVENTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times is planning a package of articles on the
Republican National Convention in Philadelphia. A detailed budget
of stories, GOP-BUDGET-NYT, will move by 3 p.m. EDT. Stories
contained in that package will move in ``p'' category and include:
</P>
<P>
   GOP-RDP (Philadelphia) _ Ledeall on the Republican National
Convention, where Gov. George W. Bush and Dick Cheney will receive
the presidential and vice-presidential Republican nominations
Wednesday. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   GOP-BUSH (Philadelphia) _ Man in the News: Gov. George W. Bush
is almost an accidental candidate, a cocky and cheerful fellow who
drifted through much of his life and who was largely unknown in
America until he assumed his first political office five years ago.
Yet he now leads the polls and will become, if elected, the
president with the least experience in public service since Woodrow
Wilson was chosen in 1912. But there still is a great deal about
his beliefs and leadership style _ about the kind of president he
would be _ that remains unknown. By Nicholas D. Kristof and Frank
Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   GOP-CONSERVATIVES (Philadelphia) _ On the reaction of the right
wing of the Republican Party to the convention, and on their
visibility in Philadelphia and their satisfaction with the ticket
and platform. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-FORD (Phildelphia) _ Former President Gerald Ford is
hospitalized after suffering a minor stroke.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-POWER (Undated) _ In California, energy deregulation and
the rising cost of energy have collided. With prices going through
the roof, politicians are pushing to end the state's four-year
experiment with deregulation. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   KAN-SCHOOLS (Undated) _ Three of four creationist candidates
lose Republican primaries for the Kansas state school board in a
repudiation of their decision to remove evolution from the state
curriculum. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   WILDFIRES (Denver) _ On the spread of the wildfires. By Michael
Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's coalition unraveled further over his peace policies
Wednesday as his foreign minister resigned and parliament approved
early elections in a preliminary vote. But Barak will be able to
cling to power at least until late October because parliament is
heading into a three-month summer recess. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-STRIKES (Harare) _ Zimbabwe ground to a halt Wednesday
as workers went on a one-day strike to try to force President
Robert Mugabe to end violence against his political opponents and
to end the occupation of white-owned farms. By Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   KASHMIR-ATTACKS (New Delhi, India) _ India and Pakistan traded
accusations Wednesday over an unprecedented rash of guerrilla
attacks in Kashmir that left at least 90 people dead and dozens
injured, casting a shadow over tentative moves for peace in the
insurgency-plagued Himalayan territory. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-MEDIA (Moscow) _ An official in the Putin administration
confirmed Wednesday that Media-Most is holding talks on settling
its debts to Gazprom by giving up some of its assets. That could
potentially give the Russian government control of the country's
three major television stations. By Sabrina Tavernise.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-POLITICS (Tokyo) _ The government of Prime Minister
Yoshiro Mori was slammed by its second political scandal in a week
Wednesday, as one of his top advisers admitted accepting millions
of yen in questionable political donations. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   BRITIAN-QUEEN-MOTHER (London) _ Queen Elizabeth, the Queen
Mother, turns 100 years old Friday, and the British have been
commemorating the event with what could be the last full-throated
hurrah for the crown. There have been full dress parades, Royal Air
Force flyovers, pageant-filled church services, ``God Bless You
Ma'am'' tabloid headlines and editorials crediting her with having
saved the monarchy from perils ranging from the abdication of her
brother-in-law to the bombing of Buckingham Palace by the Germans
to the dysfunctional family behavior of modern-day Windsors. A
Foreign Journal by Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MEDICAL-DEVICES (Undated) _ The FDA steps into the debate
over reusing medical devices labeled ``single use only.'' The
agency announced Wednesday that it will require companies who
reprocess the devices to prove the reprocessed devices are safe and
effective before they can sell them. By Kenneth Chang.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME-CHOLERA (Undated) _ The genome of the bacterium that
causes cholera has been decoded, paving the way for devising better
vaccines and drugs against a major killer that has caused seven
pandemics since 1817. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GM-FUEL-ECONOMY (Pontiac, Mich.) _ General Motors announces its
own program to improve fuel economy for sports-utility vehicles and
light trucks, including building pickup trucks with gas-electric
hybrid engines. GM says its measures go beyond those announced by
Ford Motor a week ago. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-FORD (Shanghai) _ Ford Motor is negotiating with the
Chang'an Automobile Group to build an affordable passenger car in
China, the latest sign yet that the country is loosening its grip
on the industry ahead of China's expected entry to the World Trade
Organization later this year. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-MEDIA (Montreal) _ Conrad Black, the international press
baron who just sold most of his Canadian newspapers to Canada's No.
3 television network, said in a telephone interview that he is
happy with the deal because it will vastly reduce his company's
debt and allow him to enjoy the prominent properties he has left.
By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-BANK (London) _ The British bank Standard Chartered,
which has nearly 70 percent of its assets in Asia, said Wednesday
that it will eliminate 6,000 jobs, or about a fifth of its work
force. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ The Treasury announces plans for future
refundings, but does not retire the 30-year bond as some investors
had speculated. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The Economic Scene column:
Increasingly, economists are challenging the orthodoxy that
financial markets process all the new information about securities
so efficiently that no one could get a consistent advantage over
other investors. The best summary of the position is found in a new
book, ``Inefficient Markets,'' by the Harvard professor Andrei
Schleifer. By Jeffrey Madrick.
</P>
