<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAFE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GUV LOVES MCGREGOR CAFE'S CHICKEN-FRIED STEAK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BUD KENNEDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush can load up on Philly cheesesteaks this week.
</P>
<P>
   But easy on the Cheez Whiz, Guv. Save those fat grams for the
cream gravy back home at the Citrano Bros. Coffee Shop Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   The name Citrano sounds as if it belongs on a cheesesteak stand.
Instead, it's on Bush's favorite home-cooking cafe, in a small town
close to his ranch in central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Citrano brothers _ Donald, 39, and Sammy, 44 _ own the
70-year-old landmark George's Restaurant in Waco, where young
adults from across Texas go for the legendary ``Big O,'' a frosty
18-ounce beer. For the Citranos' second venture, they bought a cafe
20 miles west in the town of McGregor.
</P>
<P>
   They had owned the cafe six months in April 1999 when a caller
warned, ``You're going to have Governor Bush in your restaurant in
30 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's a neighbor and a regular customer at the Coffee Shop,
1005 W. McGregor Drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ecstatic. He brags on the chicken-fried steak and the
pies,'' Sammy Citrano said, adding with a laugh: ``We told him
we're so happy, we named our other restaurant after him.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps concerned for the future of the nation, Donald Citrano
has suggested that Bush try the pork chop with dressing, the
featured entree on the Sunday buffet. But the governor insists on
the chicken-fried steak.
</P>
<P>
   The Citranos had been counting on the old George's Restaurant to
make them famous. They just added a 150-seat ``George's `Big O'
Party Deck'' at their first restaurant, off Interstate 35 at 18th
Street in Waco. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bud Kennedy writes a food column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7538, or e-mail:
budk(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
