r d BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX     08-02 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAUERKRAUT SOUP RECIPES ARE WORTH THE WAIT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BEVERLY BUNDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alan Perry of Fort Worth writes looking for the recipe for the
sauerkraut soup once served at Theo's Saddle &AMP; Sirloin on Exchange
Avenue in the Fort Worth Stockyards.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that although Theo's closed, Riscky's Sirloin
Inn has opened in that location. And the Sirloin Inn still serves
the soup. The bad news is, they won't share their recipe.
</P>
<P>
   But not to worry. The following two recipes for kraut soup ran
in this column in the 1980s. The first was sent in by Kitty Gentry
of Fort Worth, and the second was submitted by Maudene Vernon of
Chico.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Hallford of North Richland Hills sent in the requested
recipe for potato salad made with frozen potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SAUERKRAUT SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, chopped fine
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   6-ounce can vegetable juice cocktail
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sauerkraut
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon red pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon dry mustard (preferably hot)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sweet relish
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   Dash garlic salt
</P>
<P>
   Saute onion in oil until soft but not brown. Add other
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Bring to boil. Cover and lower heat. Simmer for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 104 calories, 7 grams fat, 10
grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 924 milligrams sodium, 62
percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   KAPUSTA SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   2 quarts beef broth
</P>
<P>
   16-ounce can sauerkraut, drained
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   16-ounce can tomato puree
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons hot pepper sauce, optional
</P>
<P>
   Combine stock and sauerkraut and simmer for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cook onion in vegetable oil until tender. Add onion and tomato
puree to sauerkraut/stock mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Combine flour and enough vegetable oil to make a paste and cook
in small skillet until it turns brownish. Add to soup.
</P>
<P>
   Add salt, pepper and sugar. Adjust seasonings to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 321 calories, 9 grams fat, 58
grams carbohydrates, trace of cholesterol, 2,269 milligrams sodium,
25 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   QUICKIE POTATO SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   1 (2 pound) bag frozen Southern-style hash browns or potatoes
O'Brien
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 ribs celery, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup each finely chopped onion and green or red bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons pickle relish
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup each light mayonnaise and sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon celery seed
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Place potatoes in a large microwave-safe mixing bowl, cover with
vented plastic wrap. Stirring midway through cooking, microwave on
high 13-15 minutes or until potatoes are cooked.
</P>
<P>
   Break eggs into 3 (6-ounce) custard cups. Pierce yolk twice with
fork. Cover each cup with vented plastic wrap. Rotating cups midway
through cooking, microwave on medium (50 percent) 4 to 4 1/2
minutes. Let stand 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Chop eggs and add to potatoes along with celery, onion, bell
pepper, pickle relish, mayonnaise, sour cream, mustard, celery
seed, salt and pepper. Chill 4 hours before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 170 calories, 8 grams fat, 23
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 87 milligrams cholesterol,
305 milligrams sodium, 42 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Requests:
</P>
<P>
   Eva Heinen of Fort Worth has lost her recipe for millionaire
fudge. She cut the recipe from the Fort Worth Star-Telegram about
10 years ago. The recipe yields 6 pounds of fudge and includes 5
pounds of sugar, two 7-ounce bars of Hershey's chocolate and a
7-ounce jar of marshmallow creme.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Byrum writes in search of a remembered cookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am looking for a recipe for a cookie bar that was once made
by the Arlington school district. In the late '60s and early '70s,
they had a brownielike bar (not chocolate) called Chinese chews on
the menu. They were great, and I've never been able to find the
recipe.''
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
