<SLUG> BC-PEDESTRIANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN FRANCISCO LOOKS TO MAKE CITY'S STREETS SAFER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RACHEL GORDON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco Supervisor Mabel Teng unveiled her
Top 10 list of ideas to make the streets safer for pedestrians,
including establishing a 24-hour hot line to report dangerous
intersections and installing speed bumps to slow down cars.
</P>
<P>
   Teng's proposals, unveiled Monday, are contained in a
comprehensive report on pedestrian safety that includes 105
recommendations that sprang from a special summit on the topic held
in May.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the suggestions in the report, such as banning the use
of cell phones while driving, banning right turns on red lights and
restricting vehicles on Market Street, are controversial. And none
made Teng's Top 10 list. The supervisor said she wanted to tackle
recommendations that were likely to win support first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some can be easily adopted,'' Teng said of the total package
of recommendations. ``Some are thought-provoking and will require
additional public input and dialogue. Some will take longer-term
efforts before we see results.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In speaking with everyone involved, there seemed to be at
least 10 proposals that all groups support,'' she said, adding that
she would push for immediate implementation.
</P>
<P>
   She called the report a living document that would be reviewed
and amended as time went on. She already called for a formal update
in March.
</P>
<P>
   Teng said The City must move forward to combat its serious
pedestrian safety problem. Eighteen pedestrians have died in San
Francisco this year, with hundreds more seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the hot line and the speed bumps, Teng's
fast-track list includes:
</P>
<P>
   A citywide pedestrian safety advertising campaign that targets
drivers, bicyclists and pedestrians. In fact, the Goodby
Silverstein &AMP; Partners advertising firm, of ``Got Milk?'' fame, is
drawing up such a campaign aimed at the start of the new school
year.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing crossing times at all intersections with signals, an
effort
</P>
<P>
   already being undertaken by the Department of Parking and
Traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Making the signals red in both directions at dangerous
intersections for a brief interval to provide pedestrians a head
start crossing the street before traffic starts to flow.
</P>
<P>
   Installing more lighted sidewalks to make crosswalks more
visible and putting in countdown clocks at intersections with
traffic signals so people know how much time is left to safely
cross the street. Both programs are budgeted already, as are plans
for more traffic calming measures, such as speed bumps.
</P>
<P>
   Studying the connection between cell phone use and traffic
accidents. Supervisor Amos Brown already requested such a review.
</P>
<P>
   Funding a plan to make Market Street safer for pedestrians and
bicyclists.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing dull ``school crossing`` and ``senior crossing`` signs
with ones that are more visible, and erecting ``pedestrian
crossing`` signs at all intersections that do not have traffic
lights or stop signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supervisor Teng's Top 10 proposals for pedestrian safety will
go a long way toward making San Francisco's streets safer for all
users,'' said Leah Shahum, program director of the San Francisco
Bicycle Coalition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1411EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
