<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0574 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-COMEDY03-COX     08-02 0290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-COMEDY03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ho-hum effort no laughing matter
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe old material is a good thing to use for a new movie
(``Shaft'') or a hit Puff Daddy record, but not comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Five weeks after Elian Gonzalez flew back to Cuba with his
father, the 6-year-old's situation just doesn't resonate the same
way; nor does a reference to the 1993 movie ``Indecent Proposal.''
But TV comics Steve Harvey and D.L. Hughley, who kick off this
soundtrack to the movie that opens Aug. 18, actually try to mine
these faded moments for laughs.
</P>
<P>
   They would have been wise to follow Cedric ``The Entertainer''
and Bernie Mac's leads as they smartly spin forward topics like
what golf courses are like now that a lot of black, aspiring Tigers
are on the greens (``We're out there with wave caps on (our
heads),'' Cedric remarks playfully. ``Wearing Timbaland (boots)...
out there barbecuing.''). Or Mac, using Chris Rock's acerbic style
to find something funny in the struggle to raise a crack-addicted
relative's kids.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the five songs that divide the comedians'
sketches isn't timeliness; it's sluggishness. Rap's Hot Boys
(Mannie Fresh, Baby, Juvenile, Lil' Wayne) perform ``1 Stunna'' and
``What's Up With That'' with no energy. Only the duet from R&AMP;B
singers' Monifah and Chico DeBarge, ``Na Na,'' has any real steam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Original Kings of Comedy''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Universal. 26 tracks. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on the Original Kings of Comedy and
Universal Records: www.universalstudios.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1414EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0575 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS03-COX     08-02 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    By Eileen Drennen, Miriam Longino, A. Scott Walton and Shane
Harrison
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  POP/ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Water to Drink''
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Williams. Atlantic. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Still mining the soulfully whimsical character sketches
(``Gladys and Lucy,'' ``Grandma's Hat Pin'') and tenderly
off-kilter odes (``Little Bird'') that have been her signature
since her first album 13 years ago, singer-songwriter Victoria
Williams has rounded the corners of her eccentricities over the
years. She doesn't squeak or squawk as much, and she's tamed the
wilder edges of her oddball compositions so that her shambling
country-gospel-pop sound has steeped into something you might call
homespun jazz _ especially on the scat-heavy title track. She still
has a gift for love songs (``Joy of Love'') and a fondness for
standards (``Until the Real Thing Comes Along'') and has upped the
atmospherics this time out by re-teaming with studio whiz/master
arranger Van Dyke Parks.
</P>
<P>
   _Eileen M. Drennen
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Victoria Williams:
www.thegrid.net/creekdipper or www.victoriawilliams.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``People Like Us''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Tippin. Lyric Street. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   In today's bottled-water world of slick country music, Tippin is
as refreshing as the sound of someone popping open a Schlitz. His
muscle-flexing, roadhouse country is unapologetically blue-collar,
from the finger-flipping opening tune, ``Kiss This,'' to lines
about rusty pickup trucks and ``The Night Shift.'' Many of the
tunes here are built on a rock beat as subtle as a pumping oil rig,
but Tippin can also serve up a ballad so sweet (``Always Was'')
that you can almost see him showing up at the front door with
flowers. This first album on Lyric Street may be one of his best.
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Aaron Tippin: www.aarontippin.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   ``Ella Fitzgerald: In the Groove''
</P>
<P>
   Ella Fitzgerald. Buddha Records. 21 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   This rangy compilation adoringly captures the fledgling talents
of an iconic performer. Ella Fitzgerald was in her early 20s _
fronting her Famous Orchestra at venues like the Savoy and Roseland
ballrooms in New York and the Grand Terrace in Chicago _ when these
recordings were captured live in front of glass-tinkling,
smoke-exhaling, exuberantly appreciative audiences. The songs span
the gamut of the jazz singer's onstage characters: from the chirpy
ingenue (''A Tisket A Tasket,'' ``Betcha Nickel''), to the comedic
cutup (''The Yodelin' Jive,'' ``The Jumpin' Jive''), to the
temptress (''My Wubba Dolly,'' ``Well Alright ... Tonight's the
Night''). Decades before becoming the ambassador of song behind
pop-bottle glasses, the young Ella could see her way clear to the
essence of lyrical interpretation. Sixty years ago, ``In the
Groove'' proved she was a prodigious talent. Sixty years after
these recordings were minted, Fitzgerald's vocal mastery sounds
endearingly fresh.
</P>
<P>
   _A. Scott Walton
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Ella Fitzgerald:
www.users.globalnet.co.uk/(tilde)mcgoni/ella/
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Alone With Everybody''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Ashcroft. Virgin. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   The former frontman of Brit rockers the Verve steps out on his
own with a surprisingly good solo debut. The symphonic grandeur of
``Brave New World'' recalls the Verve's ``Bittersweet Symphony,''
and Ashcroft knows his way around an epic ballad. The rumbling,
syncopated riff of ``New York'' threatens delicate speakers, but
the entire album is quieter and more introspective than the Verve's
rock swagger. Lyrics? Who needs lyrics. Ashcroft's won't win any
prizes, but they're good enough for rock 'n' roll. And that's what
this is. Classically British rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Richard Ashcroft:
www.richardashcroft.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Drennen, Miriam Longino, A. Scott Walton and Shane
Harrison writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
