<HEADER>
A0576 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE03-COX     08-02 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chutney: Fancy name, simply saucy relish
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year, many food-trend watchers tapped chutney as the
accompaniment to monitor in the new millennium _ ``the next
salsa,'' many said. And sure enough, chutney has been popping up
all over the pages of slick food magazines and in the scripted
recitations of white-jacketed waiters in upscale restaurants.
Chutney this, chutney that. Chutney sounds a whole lot more
highbrow than Aunt Cora's chowchow. But the fact is, chutney is
just a fancy (read British) way of saying relish.
</P>
<P>
   Chutney came to England via India, where the word means relish.
And what does relish mean? According to Webster's: ``an appetizing
flavor ... pleasing taste ... pleasure ... enjoyment ... zest.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is what chutney and relishes are all about. In the
chemistry of a dinner plate, a little dab can be the catalyst that
puts the taste buds on high alert and becomes the counterpoint that
ignites the flavors and textures of everything else on the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Now that fresh fruits and vegetables are available year-round,
chutneys and relishes no longer have to involve complicated canning
and preserving procedures. While chutney emerges in the culinary
spotlight, chefs everywhere are experimenting with an amazing
number of creative variations that can be made fresh and stored in
the refrigerator for up to three weeks. Chutneys and relishes,
after all, are mainly chopped fruit and vegetables with vinegar and
spices added. The difference is primarily in texture.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the familiar cucumber, onion, carrots and peppers,
you will see chutneys made with bananas, tomatoes, blueberries,
strawberries, raspberries, peaches, pears, plums, apples,
cranberries, mangoes, papaya, pineapple, cherries and coconuts all
being used to accompany hot and cold meats, fish, shellfish, fowl,
eggs, cheese and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   WEB SITES
</P>
<P>
   To get on the chutney bandwagon and add interest and surprise to
your cooking, check out these Web sites for some ideas and
inspiration:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Drummond Farms at www
</P>
<P>
   .organicchutney.com/dfrecp1.html offers some enticing organic
chutney recipes with appropriate entrees that include Salmon in
Raspberry Chutney Marinade, Chutney Baked Pork Chops and Roast
Turkey With Apple Currant Chutney Stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Scroll down at the Food Day site for a book review of
``Chutneys &AMP; Relishes'' by Lou Seibert Pappas. It offers some
enticing pairings and sample recipes, such as cranberry shallot
chutney and cilantro corn relish. See www.globalgourmet.com
</P>
<P>
   /food/foodday/fd1097/fd102897.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  See www.ivu.org/recipes/indian-chutney/ for a savory list of
authentic Indian chutney recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  There are chutneys for every season using seasonal fruits and
vegetables at www.hannibal.net
</P>
<P>
   /stories/091599/feagardengoods.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For some imaginative recipes for hot-weather chutneys and
relishes, see www.mail-archive.com
</P>
<P>
   /hot-weather-recipe(at)onelist.com
</P>
<P>
   .msg00063.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SOAR lists 169 chutney recipes from apple to zucchini at
soar.berkeley.edu/recipes/chutneys.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Saving the best for last _ you don't even have to make the 70
recipes for chutneys, relishes and salsas at Epicurious' Pick a
Pack of Pickles. Just reading the recipes _ which use everything
from mangoes and watermelons to pineapples and pears _ is enough to
make your mouth water. See www.epicurious.com/eeating/e02pickling
</P>
<P>
   /pickledrecipes.html.
</P>
<P>
   Spicy Tomato Chutney
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 1 1/2 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30-35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 1/4 to 1 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   This recipe originally accompanied Roast Beef, Basil and Spicy
Tomato Chutney LaVash Sandwiches. It would also pair well with
grilled fish or chicken, or would be a nice pasta topping.
</P>
<P>
   1 pound vine-ripened tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper, stem, ribs and seeds removed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup red-wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons mustard seeds
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup chopped green onions, green parts only
</P>
<P>
   Chop tomatoes and bell pepper into medium dice. In a medium
saucepan, bring vinegars to a boil with sugar, salt, mustard seeds,
black pepper and red pepper flakes, stirring occasionally. When the
sugar and salt are dissolved, stir in the tomatoes, bell pepper and
green onion. Simmer mixture, uncovered, stirring occasionally,
about 1 1/4 hours, or until thickened and reduced to about 1 1/2
cups. Cool chutney completely. Chutney keeps, covered and chilled,
2 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Per 1/4-cup serving: 115 calories, 1 gram protein, 1 gram fat
(percent calories from fat, 5), 29 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 402 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Pineapple and Mint Chutney
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 3 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 45 minutes or less
</P>
<P>
   Standing time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   This is closer to relish than chutney, as it is not cooked.
Fresh-tasting, it's a real crowd-pleaser and can be served with
grilled fish or meat (pork tenderloin would be especially nice), or
as a small side offering.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup loosely packed fresh mint leaves, rinsed, spun dry and
chopped fairly fine
</P>
<P>
   1 (4 1/2-pound) pineapple, peeled, cored and cut into 1/3-inch
dice
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup minced red onion
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup granulated sugar, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl, combine mint with pineapple, onion, sugar and a pinch
of salt. Stir until well-combined. Cover and let stand for 1 hour.
(The chutney may be made 1 week in advance and kept covered and
chilled; however, we found that after a few days the minty flavor
became overwhelming. We would recommend using it within a day or
two.)
</P>
<P>
   Per 1/4-cup serving: 37 calories, trace protein, no fat, 9 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 23 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
