<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cabbage soup that's worthy of restaurant
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marion Schnerr of Trenton, N.J., asked for cabbage soup like one
she enjoyed at a Pennsylvania restaurant. That prompted Mariettan
Aldo Fabbri to remind us of his soup recipe that was published with
a story featuring him two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Our tester likes the soup, noting that it freezes well so you
can serve half now and half later. We hope it meets with Schnerr's
complete approval.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Hungarian
</P>
<P>
   Cabbage Soup
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 1 hour, 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   2 medium onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 (15-ounce) can diced tomatoes, undrained
</P>
<P>
   2 (14 1/2-ounce) cans beef broth
</P>
<P>
   2 (14 1/2-ounce) cans chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1 small cabbage, chopped (about 5 cups)
</P>
<P>
   1 large potato, peeled and cut into bite-size pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup uncooked rice
</P>
<P>
   1 (15-ounce) can light red kidney beans, undrained
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground black pepper, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in Dutch oven over medium heat and add garlic and
onions. Cook and stir for 3 minutes until onions are transparent.
Add ground beef and cook over medium-high heat until browned, about
10 to 12 minutes, stirring infrequently to ensure larger pieces.
Add salt and cook 3 minutes. Add tomatoes, beef broth, chicken
broth and chili powder. Bring to a boil and add cabbage. Cover,
reduce heat to low and simmer 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Skim off excess fat. Add potato, rice and beans. Cover and
simmer 15 to 20 minutes or until rice is done. Add pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 374 calories, 26 grams protein, 16 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 39), 31 grams carbohydrates, 67
milligrams cholesterol, 1,713 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   D.C. Taylor of Piedmont, Ala., is looking for an unusual rice
pudding recipe she recalls from an out-of-print Dinah Shore book.
Taylor says it took five or six hours to make and was ``absolutely
delicious.''
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Spinks of Powder Springs is looking for Lemon Blender Pie
using a whole lemon _ rind and all _ chopped and mixed in the
blender.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
