</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Blood Simple' an early look at inimitable Coens
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You had to be there.
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1984. The place: The New York Film Festival. It had
been the usual festival mix with the big names ranging from Sergio
Leone to Wim Wenders. The new boy in town was Jim Jarmusch,
premiering his deadpan ``Stranger Than Paradise.'' But no one was
expecting much from something called ``Blood Simple,'' a low-budget
independent first feature by a couple of nobodies named Joel and
Ethan Coen.
</P>
<P>
   The picture _ a tale of lust and murder in the prairie dust of
Nowhere, Texas _ hit the jaded, bleary-eyed press corps like a
re-discoveing, think again. The two would-be parents are played by
two barely knowns (at the time) named Holly Hunter and Nicolas
Cage.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Barton Fink'' (1991): Probably my favorite of the Coen films
if only because it's so mean about intellectuals as well as
hilariously berserk and mind-teasingly perverse about writer's
block. In the early '40s, a high-minded New York playwright (John
Turturro) is lured to Hollywood to impart ``that Barton Fink
feeling'' to a Wallace Beery wrestling picture.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, the movie is about his ``Day of the Locust''
encounters with moguls, stars and washed-up Southern novelists
who've sold out to the flicks. But there's also the eerie hotel
where Barton stays _ a place worthy of ``The Shining'' where, as
Barton slowly goes mad, his neighbor, a deceptively genial
traveling salesman (John Goodman), has his own unhinged feelings
abo
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
