 &HT;    Cool stuff for school
 &HT;    By Sabine Morrow
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The carefree days of vacation are quickly giving way to the
grueling days of school. For the summer slackers around the house,
that means a rude awakening to endless stretches of math, a bit of
lit, poking around in a lab and actually working on a personal
computer rather than blasting sworn enemies into another universe.
</P>
<P>
   Bummer.
</P>
<P>
   But in the likely event your anxious offspring think the
situation is simply too grim to bear, show them these cool tools
for school. We're not talking totally boring yellow No. 2 pencils
and blue-lined notebook paper. These awesome finds are guaranteed
to brighten up the bus ride, lunch time _ and maybe even class.
</P>
<P>
   Soaps on a rope
</P>
<P>
   Feeling young and restless because of withdrawal from a summer
of watching your favorite soap operas? We think this Sony color TV
Watchman might help. This cool mini-tube-on-the-go comes with a
combination neck strap/antenna, headphone jack and a 2-inch color
screen. When it's not around your neck, it stashes neatly in your
backpack.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At most Circuit City stores. $99.
</P>
<P>
   Time of your life
</P>
<P>
   If you're too cool for a wristwatch but still want to make it to
class on time, check out these clever timepieces. The K-9 Dog Tag
Watch by Chaos (top) hangs around your neck and gives you the time,
date and temperature in cool LCD readings. It comes in neon colors
and even glows in the dark with the press of a button.
</P>
<P>
   And from tic-tic we snagged some fun timepieces that clip to
your bookbag, lunchbox or belt loops (VW Beetle, left, and robot,
above). They come in a wide variety of shapes, ranging from cowboy
boots and handbags to sassy high-heeled pumps and even feet.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At Rich's stores. K-9 Dog Tag, $29.99; tic-tics, $19.99 each.
</P>
<P>
   Tunes to go
</P>
<P>
   If you must have music wherever you go, consider this affordable
metallic blue personal CD player by RCA. It features a two-step
bass boost, shuffle/repeat function, 24 tracks programming and
comfortable earphones. To store those discs we found a super rugged
CD wallet by EXO that's fairly soft but with hard reinforced edges.
It holds 32 CDs and is perfect for cramming into your locker or
backpack.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At most Best Buy stores. RCA personal CD player, $39.99. EXO
CD wallet, $14.99.
</P>
<P>
   Neon madness
</P>
<P>
   You can make school work more exciting with these neon
accessories. These jazzy IBM-formatted Neon Colors floppy disks by
Imation make a bold statement ($2.98 for five). Glittery pencils
(49 cents each) and neon erasers (79 cents a dozen) get the work
done in a colorful way, while these hot Gellyz pens ($4.98 for
five) will have your teachers seeing tangerine, lemon, aqua, bubble
gum and lavender.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At Staples stores.
</P>
<P>
   Stay in touch
</P>
<P>
   We thought Spectra's cool blue electronic phone and e-mail
address book would be perfect for staying organized this school
year. It stores up to 1,200 names and addresses. It also has a
calculator, a seven language LCD prompt, two separate business and
personal directories and various alarms. That's not all. There's a
clock with an hourly chime, nine metric conversions, five
programmable currency conversions and a memo mode. Want to know the
time in 30 major world cities? This will tell you. And for those
oh-so-secret bits of information, there's even a secret memory
function.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At Target stores. $12.99.
</P>
<P>
   Snap out of it
</P>
<P>
   The trendiest piece of jewelry is a rubberband bracelet. You can
find vividly colored Wordstretch rubberbands on the wrists of
celebrities such as Janet Jackson, Georgio Armani, Jimmy Jam and
even Oscar De La Hoya. These funky bracelets come in a bunch of
bright colors and all have something to say ranging from
``Princess'' to ``What Would Scooby Do?''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At Outwrite Bookstore and Coffeehouse, 991 Piedmont Ave.,
404-607-0082, and through the Web site www.wordstretch.com. $1.75
each.
</P>
<P>
   Sabine Morrow writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
