A0581 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CUT-CORNERS03-COX     08-02 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUT-CORNERS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One Atlantan gives her home the look for less
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jackie Cottrill knows how to cut corners _ and, more important,
when not to. After all, the Atlantan has decorated, and in some
cases designed, 18 houses for her family over the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet she's not a professional designer or decorator; she's a
homemaker who's learned dozens of tricks of the trade by working
closely with architects, builders and other experts. She's also
stumbled onto scores of ideas by scanning magazines and by shopping
flea markets, salvage yards and closeout sales. Other ideas come to
her through trial and _ yes _ error.
</P>
<P>
   Cottrill knows not to scrimp on some things, such as installing
limestone tile or painting interior trim. At the same time, she's
figured out how to get the look of expensive custom bathroom
cabinets by attaching $1 table legs. Every top dollar she's paid on
one project can be justified with the savings on another.
</P>
<P>
   Among her best advice to those building or remodeling is to make
sure they communicate with professionals. For her latest project, a
French manor house in Buckhead, she hired architect Tim Adams of
Harrison Design Associates and builder Warren Sirzyk of Renaissance
Development.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what I wanted and what I didn't, so I made lists,''
Cottrill said. ``That way, we didn't end up making a lot of
changes, which run up the fees. If you're prepared, you'll save.''
</P>
<P>
   The photos of her home on these and the following pages show how
Cottrill gets great looks for less.
</P>
<P>
   K I T C H E N S A N D B A T H R O O M S
</P>
<P>
   1. STAGGERING IDEA: Give kitchen cabinets the look of custom
furniture by pulling them out slightly from the wall and covering
them with wider countertops. Don't be afraid to mix hardware
styles; in this case, wooden knobs play up more expensive nickel
drawer pulls.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE PLOT THICKENS: Create the look of thick granite
countertops by gluing a decorative beveled edge of granite to the
granite slab, saving 25 percent to 40 percent on the cost of a
solid piece, depending on the grade of stone.
</P>
<P>
   3. NOT FOR SALE? Watch for sales on floor samples. Cottrill
saved on her powder room vanity by buying this sink off the floor
and dropping it into a cabinet. The cabinet's marble top was
cracked, so she replaced it with a slab of limestone left over from
her bar.
</P>
<P>
   4. DETAILS, DETAILS: High-end custom cabinets like hers can be
emulated by adding details such as balusters to the ends of
islands.
</P>
<P>
   5. A LEG UP: Bathroom cabinetry takes on a custom look when
anchored to the wall and dressed up with inexpensive furniture legs
glued to the bottom. Cottrill buys the legs for 50 cents to $2 each
at Scott Antique Market.
</P>
<P>
   F L O O R S
</P>
<P>
   6. ROAD NARROWS: Reserve wide-plank flooring for heavy-traffic
areas and install less expensive, narrower boards in less visiible
areas. Cottrill used 5-inch oak in hallways and 3-inch oak in
bedrooms, abutting above, for savings of about $1.50 to $2 per
square foot.
</P>
<P>
   7. RISING HIGH: Oak treads and runners are appealing, but for
about one-third the cost consider pine treads covered in carpet.
While you're at it, you can mimic this stairwell's paneling by
getting creative with moldings.
</P>
<P>
   L I G H T I N G
</P>
<P>
   8. SHADY BUSINESS: Spiff up a chandelier by adding lampshades.
Cottrill's favorite sources are Finders Keepers Home Accents
(404-355-2600) and Outrageous Bargains (770-497-9577).
</P>
<P>
   9. BRIGHT IDEAS: Chandeliers can be a big-ticket item,
especially when you have large spaces to light. Cottrill saved by
buying an inexpensive outdoor fixture for her rear stairwell,
allowing her to invest more in lighting for more visible rooms.
</P>
<P>
   C E I L I N G S
</P>
<P>
   10. GRIDLOCK OPTION: Coffered ceilings like this one can be
expensive. One alternative is to use decorative moldings to create
a grid on a plain ceiling. It may not be as three-dimensional, but
the effect is similar and about half to one-third the cost.
</P>
<P>
   11. BEAM ME UP, JACKIE: Exposed beams made of oak or cedar are
popular ceiling details. A less expensive alternative are boxed
beams, a hollow but decorative touch.
</P>
<P>
   12. BOARDS OR PANELS? Who doesn't like the homey feel of a
tongue-and-groove ceiling? To save money, consider paneling with
that look, available at hardware chains.
</P>
<P>
   Savings hints
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Buy a piece of furniture, accessory or object you love, if you
can afford it; you'll make it work somewhere at some point in your
house.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Never scrimp on tile installation. If need be, choose a less
expensive tile and pay more to have it properly installed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Invest in intricate moldings for a few special rooms if you
can't afford molding for the entire house. Shop salvage yards for
interesting pieces.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Create the look of wide moldings by leaving several inches of
wall between a standard crown molding and a thin strip, then paint
the space in between white.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Invest in good-quality paint, mechanical systems and windows
and doors.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rewire old chandeliers to save the cost of new ones. Scout
garage sales and antique markets for deals.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use expensive items and materials sparingly for biggest
impact.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Be practical about color schemes. By using only three colors
in her house _ beige, black and white _ Cottrill is able to move
furnishings and accessories from room to room.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pre-wire for sound and theater systems when you build, even if
you don't plan to add those amenities until years later. It's more
expensive to retrofit a house.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Save about 40 percent on the cost of kitchen granite by
installing granite slab on islands and other work areas and less
expensive tile on countertops.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Save 25 percent to 50 percent of the cost of limestone on
fireplaces by using similar-looking cast stone instead.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Install commercial grades of carpet in heavily traveled areas
for withstanding wear and tear.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dress up bathroom wall and floor tiles with inexpensive
insets. For about $30, you can buy a sheet of mosaiclike tiles that
can be cut into 2-inch-square decorative pieces. But hire a
professional to install them.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Choose inexpensive door hardware for less visible rooms and
hallways; use the savings to upgrade your choices for more visible
areas.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Buy inexpensive wooden rods for window treatments (unless
drapery weight is an issue) and make a statement with finials and
other accents.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie's bargain spots
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Garage and yard sales for unusual items.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Scott Antique Market for overruns on table and chairs legs and
table bases, which can be combined with other materials to create
interesting pieces.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Salvage yards in the Howell Mill Road area for deals on
overstocked moldings, ceiling medallions and windows and doors.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Closeout sales on marble and tiles.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Retailers popular with interior designers, such as those along
Buckhead's Bennett Street and Miami Circle.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Demolition sales for interesting old hardware. Check newspaper
classified ads under ``Building Materials.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Brick dealers for seconds on
</P>
<P>
   bricks.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Annual warehouse sales of plumbing suppliers for deals on
overstocked faucets and floor-sample fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The spring public sample sale of furnishings and accessories
by showrooms in the trade-only Atlanta Decorative Arts Center.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Closeout rooms in the carpet warehouses of Dalton, the carpet
capital of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
