<HEADER>
A0582 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE03-COX     08-02 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An on-again, off-again love affair with orchids
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Orchids really have a hold on me. It's been a while since I've
been in an orchid period, about five or six years. Way back in the
1990s, I bought several, and together we had a roaring failure. I'd
pick out stunningly beautiful plants, with blooms and buds that
looked like lovely winged creatures. Like many orchid dabblers, I'd
enjoy the blooms for months _ that's always been one of the appeals
_ and then I'd watch the plants just sit there for the next year or
so. I'd inspect my orchids, looking for the next crop of wings.
Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, my only success at getting one to bloom again (aside
from the jewel orchid, one that grows in dirt and is quite
different from those that have provided so many prom corsages) came
a few years ago when I stashed a worn-out plant in the back garden
and forgot about it. After several months of benign neglect, I
happened to look it up in its home, hidden near a rhododendron. The
poor plant not only had survived without me, but it had bloomed,
too. Alas, no more; that single burst of beauty was the orchid's
last gasp.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a fading orchid entrusted to me by a friend met a
similar fate when I was unable to keep it going, no matter how much
I ignored it.
</P>
<P>
   Now I have returned to orchids with zeal, if not skill. So go
the rhythms of gardening. You embrace a plant, then you let it go,
returure, then out, and in again. Sometimes, of course, love burns
hot and bright, only to burn out, never to be rekindled. It's not
necessarily so that the end of such a love negates its existence.
</P>
<P>
   In her poem ``Passer Mortuus Est,'' Edna St. Vincent Millay
wasn't talking about orchids, but she could have been: ``After all,
my erstwhile dear, / My no longer cherished, / Need we say it was
not love, / Just because it perished?''
</P>
<P>
   My love for orchids perished, only to flourish again. It rose to
new heights about a month ago, when I could no longer garden
without these flowers growing, gracing, sometimes perfuming my
indoors, adding exotic color and style to any space they visited
outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   What's not to love? Orchids always have seduced and inspired
photographers and painters who can't resist the sprays of sexy
flowers that hang like butterflies on long stems. Television
producers, too, find them irresistible when they need a touch of
elegance on a simple set occupied by a talking face: A blooming
orchid in a simple container that does not compete with the flower
makes just the right visual statement.
</P>
<P>
   How delightful it is to be in love again. To be, again, under
the spell of phalaenopsis, dendrobium, cattleya, held tighter.
Tighter. This time around, I am determined that orchids and I will
make a go of it. I even put several in those special pots with the
holes around the bottom. What fun it'll be to see roots sprouting
through.
</P>
<P>
   And I feel so horticultural, now that I have them planted in
either fir bark or a special orchid mix containing everything from
coconut husk to lava rock. I'll study knowledgeable opinions on
care and feeding, use rain or distilled water.
</P>
<P>
   All the expert advice in the world won't guarantee new blooms
after these lovely ones have gone, of course. But I do take comfort
from a friend who explains why her orchids have done so well over
the years: ``I put them where they like to be, feed and water them
once in a while _ when I think about it. Otherwise, I just leave
them alone.''
</P>
<P>
   I can do that. A man in love can do anything.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
