r l BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION0     08-02 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shopping destination: Hartwell, Ga.
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTWELL, Ga. _ When past and present meet in this former mill
town in northeast Georgia, the result is a comfortable pace and
sense of place.
</P>
<P>
   A Georgia Main Street City for three years, the 144-year-old
town of Hartwell boasts a charming 12-block area of buildings
constructed during the boom period, 1879 to 1925. These brick
structures range from warehouses and theaters to a livery stable
and have been turned by local entrepreneurs into trendy art
galleries, gift shops and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Hartwell Company Wearhouse, which sells
sportswear, is in a cotton warehouse on Depot Street. The Corner
gift shop, at Jackson and Depot streets, is housed in a former
gristmill, while the owners of the Wooden Shoe on North Forest
Avenue rehabbed a former five-and-dime for their home
accessories/lodge-style furnishings store.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the shops are within easy walking distance, whether you
are looking for an antique washboard, a planter-shaped boot for
your garden or a one-of-a-kind Brighton handbag.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Friday, we caught up with Lilburn resident Carol
Mamay, who was shopping at the home decor store Your Hart's Desire.
``If I could move tomorrow, I would,'' she said. ``I'm decorating a
new lake house, and Hartwell has a lot to offer, in terms of
furnishings. And the people are so friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Another home furnishings shop/art gallery that's causing a stir
is the year-old Artworks of Hartwell. Owner Robyn Trimm and husband
Gary were weekenders for 18 years when Gary suggested his artist
wife open a gallery. ``I call Artworks `an eclectic gallery
influenced by styles of Buckhead (upscale Atlanta district) and
Savannah,''' said Robyn. She currently sells lots of art by artists
Mayte and Martha Rogers as well as painted country furniture and
decorative wrought-iron ``Savannah garden'' pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its enviable location _ at the base of the Blue Ridge
Mountains on Lake Hartwell _ the historic town of 5,000 attracts
tourists as well as residents and lake home owners. Hartwell is the
county seat of Hart County, named after the Revolutionary War
heroine Nancy Morgan Hart. It's the only county in the state named
for a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to promote Hartwell as a place to visit _ and live _
every day of the week, not just on weekends,'' said Pat Fritz,
promotions chairman of the Main Street program, which encourages
economic improvement and renovation of the downtown commercial
district. ``We already advertise in north Atlanta. And next year we
plan to put in new sidewalks, relocate the utilities underground
and add benches and landscaping to further restore downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, the historic district will soon have its first loft
apartments, in an 1890s building that housed a livery stable, then
a Coca-Cola bottling plant and a Western Auto dealership.''
</P>
<P>
   Championing the economic boom in Hartwell, which started more
than 20 years ago, is longtime Mayor Joan Saliba, who is in her
early 70s. ``We don't realize what we have in Hartwell,'' said
Saliba, who has been in office 21 years. ``The size of the
buildings (for rehab) is great, and the prices are reasonable. In
the early '80s, I renovated one of the buildings on Depot Street,
then someone else did another and it became contagious. Soon
everyone started sprucing up their property.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to shopping, Hartwell boasts a thriving
entertainment district on Depot Street. The old cotton warehouse
that Mayor Sabila owns was turned into the Bluegrass Express and
hosts bands and bluegrass fans from around the country every
Saturday night. The Hart County Community Theater, which regularly
sells out its performances, is located in a former grain warehouse.
The new Arts Center, which opened June 30 on Howell Street, hosts a
variety of events, including a quilt show that runs through
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It's this sense of community that makes Hartwell a charming
place to shop in, or to live in.
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Hartwell is about 110 miles from Atlanta. Take
I-85 north to exit 177, which is Ga. 77. Follow the signs. It's
about a 14-mile drive to Hartwell.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Generally, store hours are 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Shop closings
vary Mondays-Wednesdays, but every store is open
Thursdays-Saturdays. Call ahead if you want to visit a particular
shop.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Plenty of free parking in the downtown area. Also
available at two municipal lots one block from the Hart County
Courthouse square, on Howell Street at Carter Street, and Johnson
Street at Carolina Street.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: During business hours weekdays, use the restrooms
in the courthouse on Courthouse Square.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Handicapped access: Most stores are wheelchair accessible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Hart County Chamber of Commerce, 706-376-8590.
Main Street Hartwell Office, 706-376-0188. Or visit
www.hartwellga.com.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rio's of Hartwell. Housed in the old freight depot, this
restaurant dishes up Mexican food. For lunch, dig into a taco salad
($3.99), eggs rancheros ($4.95) or a steak fajita burrito ($4.50).
Chicken soup ($3.25) and black bean soup ($3.50) are house
specialities, and so is the fried ice cream ($2.50), yummy and
large enough to share with a friend. Prices are slightly higher for
dinner. Before eating, check out the scales used for weighing
freight, which are located in the floor. 11 a.m.-10 p.m.
Mondays-Fridays; noon-10 p.m. Saturdays-Sundays. 41 Depot St.,
706-376-6460.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Vickery Parke. For upscale dining, try Parke and Terri
Skelton's casual yet elegant restaurant in the turn-of-the century
Horton-Vickery cottage. The owners are both chefs; Parke is a
native of Hartwell. To start, choose a bowl of soup, including
black bean, scallop and mushroom bisque or corn chowder. Then
proceed to crab-stuffed jumbo mushroom caps with melted sharp
cheddar in butter sauce. An entree might be shrimp and scallops
over fettuccine or roast rack of lamb. Finish with a slice of
peanut butter mousse pie or praline cheesecake. Soups, $3-$4;
appetizers $5-$7; entrees, $12-$24; desserts, $4 and up. 11 a.m.-2
p.m. Tuesdays-Fridays; 6-9 p.m. Tuesdays-Saturdays. Reservations
recommended. 21 Vickery St., 706-376-2006.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Downtown Cafe. If you want Continential food, go no further
than this little cafe, which specializes in Greek and Italian
dishes starting at $3.99. Dinners are slightly higher. 11 a.m.-9
p.m. Mondays-Thursdays; 11 a.m.-10 a.m. Fridays-Saturdays. 63 Depot
St. 706-377-3055.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Skelton House. After shopping all day, this elegant
bed-and-breakfast is the perfect place to plop. Each of the seven
guest rooms in the 1896 Victorian house is named for the children
of the original owners, Hartwell attorney Jim Skelton and his wife,
Jessie. The rooms feature private bath, TV, phone and climate
controls. After a breakfast that includes eggs, bacon and sausage
and homemade jellies, you can relax in the parlor, read a book in
the morning room or sit on the wide, comfy porch. Innkeepers are
Ruth and John Skelton, whose son owns the restaurant Vickery Parke.
$85-$100 includes breakfast. 97 Benson St. 1-877-556-3790.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond shopping
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lake Hartwell, Hartwell Dam and Powerhouse. Lake Hartwell, a
U.S. Corps of Engineers lake, offers a variety of outdoor
activities. The lake was designed and built for flood control and
to provide a constant supply of water for those down stream on the
Savannah River. Hartwell Dam is located on the Savannah River,
about eight miles east of Hartwell, on U.S. 29. The free guided
tour of the dam and powerhouse includes a panoramic view of
Hartwell Lake and the Savannah River from atop the dam. Tours begin
at the Office of the Project Manager, one mile west of the dam on
U.S. 29. Shoes must be worn and children under 16 must be
accompanied by an adult. Times: 2:30 p.m. Wednesdays; 10 a.m.
Saturdays through Labor Day. Also, a tour will be conducted at 10
a.m. Sept. 4. 1-888-893-0678 or 706-856-0300.
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for r the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
