<SLUG> BC-SHOPPPING-GUIDE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Locate hard to find items
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But because of the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It,The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com
(please include your name, the city you live in and daytime phone
number); or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have tried without success to locate Calm-X, a motion
sickness medication. Two pills taken on a plane would make me
drowsy enough so that I could fall into a light sleep to Europe and
wake up totally refreshed with zero side effects. Help!
</P>
<P>
   _ Jean Salazar, Suwanee, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Calm down. We tracked down your favorite medication at
Miller's Rexall Drugs, 87 Broad St. N.W. (404-523-8481). A box of
12 dimenhydrinate tablets is $2.39. Republic Drug, which
distributes Calm-X, says the tablets are ``for the prevention and
treatment of nausea, vomiting or dizziness associated with motion
sickness.'' Hopefully, you will have smooth flying, or sailing, on
your next trip.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My husband remembers Maypo, a favorite cereal he ate as a
child in Michigan. For years, we have searched the shelves for it
and have not been able to find it. Any idea if this cereal is still
around and where we might find it?
</P>
<P>
   _ Pam Brown, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: Your search is over. Faye Culver, a consumer affairs
representative with International Home Foods, says Maypo is not as
popular in the South because ``it's a cooked cereal.'' However, you
can order Maypo from Hometown Favorites, a Florida mail-order
business that specializes in hard-to-find candies, cereals,
condiments and everyday food items. Order at
www.hometownfavorites.com. Enter the ``store,'' click on cereal,
then scroll down to Maypo. A 14-ounce box of Maypo Instant Maple
Oatmeal Cereal is $2.85; a 19-ounce box of Maypo Vermont Style
Maple Cereal, which you cook, is $3. Or call 1-888-694-2656. And
the benefits of a bowl of Maypo? It's low in sodium and fat and
cholesterol-free.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for a hot sauce that I had in Tennessee called
Red Rooster. I've looked for the product everywhere but, you
guessed it, I can't locate it. Can you offer any assistance?
</P>
<P>
   _ Britt Tucker, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: Made in the heart of Cajun country, Red Rooster Louisiana Hot
Sauce is available at Market Grocery, 16 Forest Parkway, State
Farmers Market, Building K, Forest Park (404-361-8620). A case, 24
3-ounce bottles, is $7.60. Or order it through the company at
1-800-299-9082. The heat level of Red Rooster is ``medium,'' says a
company spokesman for Bruce Foods, of New Iberia, La., which has
been turning out the red sauce since 1928.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am trying to find The Cheapskate Monthly newsletter by Mary
Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sandra Orndorff, Jonesboro, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: For penny pinchers, this monthly is well worth the $18 yearly
subscription fee. Send your payment to The Cheapskate Monthly, P.O.
Box 2135, Paramount, CA 90723. Or order by calling 1-800-550-3502
noon-8 p.m. Mondays-Fridays. You can read the preview issue and
subscribe online at www.cheapskatemonthly
</P>
<P>
   .com. Editor Mary Hunt, who describes her publication as
``bringing dignity to the art of living within one's means,''
offers readers a variety of topics. For example, seven to 10 tips
are published each month to save you time or money. Another feature
is Turning Point Stories _ real stories of success, struggle and
hope _ as well as letters from readers. Sometimes a timely book is
reviewed and Hunt always weighs in with her own money-saving hints.
The goal of every reader should be ``debt-proof living,'' Hunt
says.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I find Baron men's cologne? It comes in a silver
barrel-type bottle with a round top. Help!
</P>
<P>
   _ Celina Branton, Calhoun, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   And another Baron plea: My wife bought The Baron for me when we
were dating. Since our anniversary is coming up, I thought it would
be fun to buy a bottle, but I can't find it anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chris Green, Lilburn, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another Baron inquiry: I've had no success locating The
Baron, a men's cologne that was popular within the last 10 years.
It was in a silver can with a red label.
</P>
<P>
   _ Randolph Kinder, Fitzgerald, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: This men's fragrance will bring back happy memories for many
men _ and their companions or wives. We found The Baron cologne,
created by LTL Fragrances in 1964, at Perfumania in Northlake Mall
(770-723-1404). A 4.5-ounce bottle is $49.99. Or order online at
www.perfumania.com. Described as ``boldly masculine,'' the scent
sparkles with top notes of bergamot, lemon and coriander. Then it
yields to vetiver, citrus and basil. The base of the fragrance is
sandalwood and cedar. We love the advertising note for The Baron:
``It is clearly the mark of a man who appreciates the finest things
that life has to offer.''
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
