<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0588 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-LAZIO-SENATE-HNS &LR;      08-02 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAZIO-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAZIO STEERS CLEAR OF GOP CONVENTION TO KEEP GORE VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LARA JAKES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Rick Lazio, the Republican candidate facing
Democratic First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton in the nation's
highest-profile U.S. Senate race, spent only one day at the
Republican National Convention, forfeiting a lucrative chance to
rally the troops from coast to coast behind him in spirit and with
donations.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who whipped through the convention hall on Tuesday for a
series of media interviews before heading home, has stayed away
from Philadelphia most of the week to attend private campaign
events _ mostly fund-raisers _ in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not running for national office here,'' he said. ``I'm
running to be the senator from New York. And it is important for me
to be able to communicate with the people and answer their
questions and to be back in New York where I belong.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a news conference outside the convention hall, the
self-described moderate called the party platform archaic,
signaling one more reason why he would miss most of the partisan
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the platform, frankly, has been largely obsolete,''
Lazio told reporters, adding that he wants to appeal to New Yorkers
with a ``mainstream sense.''
</P>
<P>
   While in some ways more inclusive than in the past, the 2000
Republican platform still takes a hard-line conservative stand
against abortion and key gay rights. Embracing such planks could
hurt Lazio's hopes to woo moderate Democrats and independent
voters, who might split their tickets to support Vice President Al
Gore but oppose Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Other moderate state Republicans _ most notably Lazio booster
Gov. George Pataki _ support GOP presumptive presidential nominee
George W. Bush's platform, if not every detail. But Lazio, running
even or just slightly ahead of Clinton in statewide polls, cannot
risk alienating any voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a simple matter of mathematics,'' said Lee Miringoff,
director of the independent Marist Institute for Public Opinion.
``He's already got the Bush supporters wrapped up. Where else are
they going to go? He needs a lot of Al Gore people to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that Gore carries New York by a 10-point margin in
November, ``Bush plus 10 percent equals Senate,'' Miringoff
declared. ``And you don't get Gore people voting for you if you've
taken a high-profile role in Philadelphia. They don't want to be
associated with a platform that is not salable to voters in New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a week where anti-Hillary T-shirts and bumper stickers
are being snapped up from vendors, and similar campaign buttons are
proudly worn on the convention floor by other states' delegates,
Lazio's absence from most of the convention is all too evident.
Especially among New York delegates, some of whom have quietly
wondered if Lazio was purposely kept out of the loop.
</P>
<P>
   Convention officials indicated they were loath to risk marring
their purposely upbeat display of playing nice by giving prime time
to a candidate engaged in a negative campaign. ``There has been a
real ... effort not to take swings at the record of the last eight
years,'' said Republican strategist Jim Lake, a top convention
coordinator. ``We're going to talk about what we're going to do,
not resort to angry, bitter attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Coordinators had offered the lectern to Lazio during the Monday
morning session, at a time when few delegates were on the floor and
none of the network television cameras were turned on. He had
turned it down.
</P>
<P>
   And though he insisted he would not get down in the ``mud'' over
the next three months, Lazio nonetheless went on the offensive in
Philadelphia, asking New York delegates at a brunch if they ``want
to be lectured for the next six years by Hillary Rodham Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we believe in character? Do we believe in honesty? Do we
believe in integrity?'' Lazio asked the state delegates in a speech
that inevitably drew comparisons between his candidacy and
Clinton's. ``I believe the answer is yes.''
</P>
<P>
   State Democrats, led by party chairwoman Judith Hope, wasted no
time in hitting back. Hope jumped on a train Tuesday morning to
hold a news conference outside the hotel in Philadelphia where the
New York delegation is staying to blast Lazio for failing to make
his income tax returns public.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't seem to think this is a subject worth serious
discussion,'' Hope said. ``So we just decided to follow him here to
Philadelphia ... and once again, on his own turf, tell him we're
not going away. We really think he should do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   She later added: ``It is not my intention to be negative.''
</P>
<P>
   On the tax returns, Lazio promised to make the documents public,
standard procedure for statewide candidates, ``by the summer.''
Reminded that summertime is already halfway over, Lazio responded:
``Listen, I don't have all the information in front of me ... We're
going to release them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
