<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0589 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NUTSANDBOLTS0803-COX     08-02 1360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTSANDBOLTS0803-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fireplace might not be ready for use after insert is removed
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - Fireplace inserts and wood stoves seemed to be
everywhere during the 1970s and 1980s. More recently, high-tech gas
fireplaces seem to be dominant.
</P>
<P>
   This week we answer a question from a family that has gotten rid
of its old fireplace insert.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  C.T. and S.T. used a Craft Stove wood-burning fireplace insert
made of heavy cast-iron in their home for about 20 years before
removing it this year. The inside of the fireplace where the stove
was placed was covered with a black residue. They believe the
residue is creosote from the fires and want to know how to return
the fireplace to its original look.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestion: Several sources gave several pieces of advice _ some
of it conflicting _ about cleaning the inside of the fireplace.
Also, they offered some advice on re-using the fireplace as an open
burning unit. For starters, the residue inside the fireplace is
most likely made up of creosote and soot, natural byproducts of
burning wood. Rick Schneider, customer service manager for National
Steelcrafters, a company that made the insert, said that when an
insert is installed with a direct vent these days, there are pipes
included to send the smoke up the chimney. But they often weren't
installed that way 20 years ago. Then the installers sealed around
the face of the stove so the smoke could swirl around the outside
of the firebox before going up the chimney. The black residue is
the result of that swirling smoke. Schneider suggests a light
scrubbing with a wire brush to get rid of most of the crud. Then
wash the surface with vinegar to remove the burnt smell.
</P>
<P>
   Christi Lux, owner of Centerville Chimney Works, and Caryl
Hoelscher, owner of Abbey Road Chimney Sweeps Inc., suggested using
products specifically designed for hearth cleanup. They said a
product called Speedy White does a very good job of cleaning
fireplace glass and might also clean your brick. Stores that sell
fireplace equipment should carry Speedy White or something similar.
</P>
<P>
   If all else fails, Schneider said a coat or two of latex paint
will make the brick look clean and new. He said paint also seals in
and eliminates any old smells from burning residue that has
permeated the porous brick of the hearth.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the fireplace insert has been removed, the fireplace is
not ready for burning wood in an open fire again. Most people with
fireplace inserts used them as supplemental heat sources, so they
were used fairly often. C.T. and S.T. said they had their fireplace
serviced regularly, but many people with inserts did not have
chimney sweeps in for regular cleaning and maintenance. Inserts
typically produce lots of creosote, so the walls inside the chimney
where an insert has been used can be heavily coated. If creosote is
allowed to build up until it hardens, that's called glazing, and it
must be removed before the fireplace can be safely used. Creosote
is flammable, and a fire inside a chimney is frightening and can do
expensive damage to the chimney lining.
</P>
<P>
   When the fireplace damper has been removed to install a
fireplace insert, the damper must be replaced. Typically, the
original damper has been discarded, so a chimney-repair specialist
will have to install a new one. The most popular kind being used
today sits on top of the chimney and is controlled by a chain that
hangs down in the fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  R.J. said many of the brick, ranch-style houses in his
neighborhood were built with wood siding at the ends of the houses,
where the roof comes to a peak. Over the years, white, streaky
stains have developed on the bricks below the gable areas on many
of the houses. R.J. covered his gables with vinyl siding and hasn't
gotten any new stains, but he wanted to know what caused the stains
and how to remove them.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestions: The stains on the brick apparently come from
pigments that have washed down the wall as the paint has
deteriorated, a couple of experts said. Mark Mangan, sales manager
for Coronado Paint Co. of Edgewater, Fla., said some inexpensive
latex paints readily break down from exposure to rain and sun, and
the pigments in the paint become dissolved in rainwater and flow
down the wall. He also said self-cleaning paints marketed in the
1960s and 1970s were designed to allow surface layers of the paint
to rinse away to keep the paint looking fresh. Either situation is
a problem when the pigments run into an area of a different color.
Bob Bonadies, do-it-yourself product coordinator for Benjamin Moore
Paints, said R.J.'s installation of vinyl siding will keep the
problem from getting worse because the siding keeps rainwater from
reaching the paint. But he and Mangan said others in the
neighborhood can achieve the same result by repainting the area
with quality latex paint and painting again at the first signs of
deterioration, perhaps as often as every five years. Repaint when a
finger run across the surface picks up paint.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaning paint pigment from brick can be tricky, they said.
Bricks come in many different varieties, and what would work on one
type of brick might be too harsh for another type. Some bricks are
baked very hard and may have a surface glaze that keeps liquids
from penetrating. Other bricks are relatively soft and porous, and
liquid-borne stains sink in deeply. Mangan and Bonadies suggested
experimenting with various cleaning methods, starting with the
least aggressive and progressing to the harshest options only if
nothing milder works. Test the methods in an inconspicuous spot
before attacking large, prominent areas.
</P>
<P>
   First try a mild detergent and a scrub brush and rinse with a
garden hose. Trisodium phosphate, also known as TSP, is a good
choice to try. You'll find it where paints are sold. If that
doesn't work, try a power washer. Start with a wide spray on
moderate pressure and increase the pressure and narrow the focus of
the spray until you get results. If power washing doesn't work,
consult with a company that does sand blasting. Sand blasting is
expensive, can damage brick and might not get rid of all the
stains. After cleaning the brick, Mangan suggests using a masonry
sealer that protects the brick from water without blocking the
natural movement of air through the brick.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is painting or staining the brick to a uniform
color. Remember, though, that painted brick must be repainted
periodically, just like any other painted surface.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  S.L. of Kettering has a 40-year-old houseg, and some years ago
the family had central air conditioning added. The ductwork to
bring cool air to the house originates in the attic, and S.L. said
several of the ducts have developed cracks.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestion: Walt Hibner, manager of Dayton Power and Light Co.'s
Energy Resource Center, says an air-conditioning system with leaky
ducts is a major energy waster. The system uses considerable
electricity to remove heat from the air, and the cooled air
traveling through the ducts is a resource for which you have paid
dearly. You might be able to make effective temporary repairs by
covering the leaks with aluminum-insulated duct tape. But if the
leaks are numerous or large, you'll need to call in a
heating-and-ventilating professional to make repairs. Is the system
new enough to be under warranty? Contact the original installers to
see what they're willing to do to make the system right.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up an important point: Always hold on to
documentation for any appliance you buy or any work you have done.
Even if you do no more than toss your purchase receipts into a
drawer, you'll at least be able to prove where you bought a
product. If you're going with the junk drawer method, also toss in
your owner's manuals, assembly instructions and labels from empty
paint cans and other products you've used so that, if a problem
develops, you'll know where to go for information.
</P>
<P>
   Contact James Cummings by e-mail at
jamescummings(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
