<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0603 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-DACHAS-$ADV06-     08-02 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DACHAS-$ADV06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIAN WEEKEND GETAWAYS HIGHLIGHT DISTURBING GAP BETWEEN RICH,
POOR
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Troitsa is about 50 miles
northwest of Moscow; and Pokolnoyoe Gora is about 10 miles
northwest of Moscow.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Aug. 6 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROITSA, Russia _ So much for a quiet weekend in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Radio reports starting at noon on Friday catalog miles-long
traffic backups on every thoroughfare leaving Moscow. Boxy, rusting
Soviet-era Lada cars filled with stressed-out families vie on the
roads with air-conditioned sport utility vehicles driven by
cellphone-wielding stockbrokers and their girlfriends. They're all
trying, if only for two days, to get away from it all.
</P>
<P>
   For millions of Russians that getaway is their dacha, a country
house that until recently, has been synonymous with time-honored
traditions of honest work on the land, work that in Soviet times
was not only idealized, but that equalized all.
</P>
<P>
   However, in today's raucously capitalistic Russia, this
tradition has changed, and weekend pursuits at the dacha highlight
the widening gap between rich and poor. As wealthy Russians add
wings and Jacuzzis to their country homes in an orgy of
keeping-up-with-the-Ivanov acquisitiveness, the poverty-stricken
rely more and more on their homegrown food just to survive.
</P>
<P>
   The change leaves many lamenting the bygone days.
</P>
<P>
   ``My weekends are forever ruined,'' said 50-year-old Andrei
Kazakov, who has owned a dacha here in the village of Troitsa, 50
miles northwest of Moscow, for the past 10 years. ``Instead of two
days to relax, I spend hours siting in traffic and then putting up
with the noise from the neighbors' hammers as they build a new
home. People are adding this and that, trying to outdo each other.
The neighborhood has definitely changed.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1960s, when the Soviet Union was gripped by famine,
the government relaxed land laws, allowing an individual to buy
what Russians call ``Shchest Sotki,'' or 6/100s of a hectare, a
small plot roughly equivalent to 1,200 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Rules strictly governed what could be built on allotted land _
until 1991, for example, owners were forbidden to build a two-story
house because the Communist Party viewed it as an excessive sign of
wealth. But buying a dacha was not a bid for a genteel weekend
home; they wanted a plot of land to grow vegetables and a
less-polluted spot to take their kids in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Those Soviet rules seem quaint now, as it's de rigueur to flaunt
one's wealth _ if you have it.
</P>
<P>
   In the countryside, tumbledown wooden huts now lie in the
shadows of massive brick and cement mansions built by New Russians,
the country's newly rich businessmen. On the income scale, the top
10 percent of Russians own 35 percent of the country's wealth,
while the lowest 10 percent control only 2 percent, according to
government statistics released last week.
</P>
<P>
   For Gocha Alibayev, who owns his own interior design company in
Moscow, these wealthy few, who are disparaged by most of society as
cruel and gaudy, are a godsend.
</P>
<P>
   ``For them, its nothing to order $15,000 worth of work, and when
it's done decide they've changed their mind and tell us they'll
give another $10,000 to start again,'' Alibayev said. ``I wouldn't
be in business without them.''
</P>
<P>
   In an otherwise lackluster economy, the New Russians' dacha
excesses have fueled their own spurt of consumerism, from Home
Depot-style warehouse stores, where one can buy plastic lawn chairs
for $100 a piece and weed-whackers to a host of Russian-language
magazines about gardening.
</P>
<P>
   In Pokolnoyoe Gora, Moscow's most elite dacha community where
politicians hobnob with movie stars, a real estate agent can help
find a five-bedroom ``cottage'' with swimming pool for only $5,000
per month, plus commission _ more than 50 times the average annual
salary in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   All this leaves Kazakov, and his long-time neighbor Igor
Kabanov, nostalgic for the Soviet days when a family without a
dacha could go to any village in the vicinity of Moscow and make a
deal with a dacha owner to pay 100 rubles (less than US$4) for a
month's rent.
</P>
<P>
   Kabanov, a 72-year-old retired navy officer and his wife Irina
spend their weekends at the dacha from the start of spring until
the first snow, usually in early October. They travel to suburbs
like Pokolnoyoe Gora and sit by the side of the highway to sell a
bushel of potatoes and flowers they've grown because Kabanov's
pension, the couple's only source of income, isn't even enough to
buy his heart medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can earn about 15 percent more, because those fools have
money to throw away,'' Kabanov said of the New Russian communities.
``But anyway, our (produce) is worth it. We've been gardening all
our lives, and we know all the tricks.''
</P>
<P>
   On summer evenings, Irina will pickle and can their fruits and
vegetables to store through the winter. On weekends, though, even
she takes a break to visit with the dwindling number of old timers
in the village, friends they've known their whole lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world might change around us, and new folks may move next
door, but we always have our memories,'' Kabanov said.
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
