<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0604 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-MICHELLE-PFEIFFER-AZR     08-02 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHELLE-PFEIFFER-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-MICHELLE-PFEIFFER-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    PFEIFFER SOAKS UP UNUSUAL ROLE IN ``WHAT LIES BENEATH''(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    (RETRANSMITTING FOR THOSE WHO MAVE HAVE MISSED IT)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS -- Michelle Pfeiffer's biggest problem making the
psychological thriller (beginitalic)What Lies Beneath
(enditalic)wasn't learning her lines or even holding her own with
co-star Harrison Ford.
</P>
<P>
   It was her buoyancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to weigh me down because I kept floating up,'' says
Pfeiffer, whose character has a long, crucial scene in a bathtub.
``And my robe kept billowing, and so I had weights holding my robe
down and then I had this sandbag they would put on my stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, a member of the crew had to climb in the water with
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was this big guy - they called him Moose - and he would
hold me down during the scene,'' Pfeiffer says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moose and I became very close,'' she adds with a mischievous
grin.
</P>
<P>
   The tub sequence took two weeks to shoot, and Pfeiffer says she
was wet most of the time. But her character also played the cello,
so the actress had to find time to practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how pitiful (it was),'' she says. ``I'd be in my
trailer, soaking wet with my robe on, with my wet nightgown
underneath, with my cello, with my soaked fingers, practicing my
cello like a drowned rat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so unglamorous.''
</P>
<P>
   The dunking aside, Pfeiffer, 43, says (beginitalic)What Lies
Beneath (enditalic)was a reach for her, especially since she had
never done a horror movie. She has always had range, playing roles
from a sultry singer in (beginitalic)The Fabulous Baker Boys
(enditalic)to a drug dealer's moll in (beginitalic)Scarface
(enditalic)to the seductive villainess Catwoman in
(beginitalic)Batman Returns(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer, who has twice been nominated for Oscars, made her film
debut in the teenage comedy (beginitalic)The Hollywood
Knights(enditalic), starred in (beginitalic)Grease 2 (enditalic)and
made a big splash in (beginitalic)Dangerous Liaisons(enditalic)
opposite John Malkovich and Glenn Close.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer became interested in (beginitalic)What Lies Beneath
(enditalic)after learning that Robert Zemeckis
((beginitalic)Forrest Gump, Back to the Future(enditalic)) was
directing and that Ford had decided to star.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably would not have done it had it not been Bob
Zemeckis,'' she says, ``because I think these movies, the reason
they don't make so many of them is that they're hard to do, which
is why they always just resort to cutting people up when they want
to scare people.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Zemeckis was happy to have Pfeiffer. He describes
her as a great actress with screen presence, a combination found
only in a few.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just gifted with this thing that you can't take your
eyes off them,'' Zemeckis says. ``They have power that just comes
off that screen, plus they have all this talent.''
</P>
<P>
   About Pfeiffer, Zemeckis added, ``You can't stop watching her.''
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Pfeiffer's character, Claire, is married to Norman
Spencer (Ford), a respected researcher with a dark secret. The
truth starts to seep out as Claire begins to see the ghostly form
of a young woman and hears mysterious sounds around her house.
</P>
<P>
   Claire grows more paranoid and frightened as the supernatural
events escalate. She slowly transforms from a happy wife to a
suspicious woman to, ultimately, a frightened victim.
</P>
<P>
   Though it didn't dawn on her during filming, Pfeiffer later
realized that she was on screen in almost every scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suddenly started to think that it's just me walking around a
house for hours. It's going to be boring {hellip} but the other
character that is always with me is the camera,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In her own life, Pfeiffer says, she's never experienced a
supernatural occurrence like those in the film, but she's open to
the possibility that such things exist:
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people who have, and they're people that I really
respect {hellip} they're not crazy. So I would have to lean toward
being a believer.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Muller at bill.muller(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
