<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-RDP-ART-560&AMP;ADD-N     08-02 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-RDP-ART-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ARRIVES IN PHILADELPHIA TO CLAIM REPUBLICAN NOMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated by 9 p.m. EDT with a story
by Richard L. Berke.) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DANIEL J. WAKIN and JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Gov. George W. Bush made his calibrated entry
into Philadelphia Wednesday, the day the delegates at the
Republican National Convention are to select him as their nominee
for president.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving at Philadelphia Northeast Airport Wednesday morning
amid patriotic pomp, Bush walked down a red carpet and rang a
replica of the Liberty Bell. A fife and drum corps played.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was off to a Latino music festival outside the
Philadelphia Museum of Art, where he declared, ``If all goes well,
you're looking at the next president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush appeared with his wife, Laura, and Sen. John McCain and his
wife, Cindy. McCain addressed the convention Tuesday night, and
Bush praised the speech, calling the senator a ``living example of
duty, honor and country.''
</P>
<P>
   He added ``Senator, I can't wait to campaign with you all across
our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Children sang ``America the Beautiful'' in what an announcer
described as Spanglish. In the crowd was a large group of
college-age Republicans holding ``Viva Bush'' signs, some of whom
came from as far away as Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Bush, former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney and their
wives appeared together before convention-goers for the first time
at a fund-raising luncheon at the Pennsylvania Convention Center in
downtown Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Standing before a backdrop of a huge image of the White House,
Bush received a standing ovation and cheers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling America is ready for change,'' he said. ``They
don't want four more years of Clinton-Gore. They want someone to
appreciate our better angels, not our darker impulses.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the convention center, a small cluster of protesters
gathered, including two representatives of People for the Ethical
Treatment of Animals wearing pink pig suits.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, an unidentified group held a banner that proclaimed
``Republicans Plus Democrats (EQ) 1 Corporate Party.'' But except
for occasional shouts, the demonstrations were peaceful, and the
police officers far outnumbered the protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney and Bush are to receive their party's official
nominations Wednesday evening at the 37th Republican National
Convention, returning to the city where Republicans held their
first convention, in 1856.
</P>
<P>
   Before Bush came to the stage at the luncheon there was a moment
of silent prayer for the health of former President Gerald R. Ford,
who was hospitalized here Wednesday after suffering two minor
strokes.
</P>
<P>
   In a departure from tradition, the vice presidential nominee
will speak on Wednesday instead of addressing the convention just
before the presidential nominee does. That schedule will focus the
spotlight solely on Bush on Thursday evening, when the candidate
delivers his address in the convention's climax.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans expect to finish their roll call of the states
Wednesday evening shortly before 10 p.m. EDT, completing the
largely ceremonial process of giving Bush the Republican
nomination. The delegates will then, on a voice vote, nominate
Cheney as the Republican vice presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,066 delegates started voting two days ago and are building
up to Wednesday night, when the count will surpass the required
1,034 delegate votes that Bush and Cheney need for their official
nominations.
</P>
<P>
   After accepting the nomination, Cheney will address the
convention.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, Cheney has given only relatively brief
speeches. He has appeared far more comfortable on Sunday talk shows
than on the road, where he has seemed awkward and ill at ease with
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney will use his speech to reassure independent voters that
he shares their positions on many causes. Democrats have attacked
Cheney for voting against a ban on plastic guns, funding for
pre-school education programs, environmental protection measures
and sanctions against South Africa when it was under an apartheid
government.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have used the convention to present an image
that tries to appeal not only to the hard core members of their
party but also to independents and swing voters. Bush has worked to
soften his party's reputation by calling himself a ``compassionate
conservative'' and arguing that he represents a new kind of
Republican party.
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade ago, Democrats began a slow and divisive
transformation from a party many people linked to liberal
northeasterners like Sen. Edward M. Kennedy to a group represented
by the more moderate centrist politics of President Bill Clinton.
Bush has attempted to carry out a faster transformation of the
Republican Party over the course of an election.
</P>
<P>
   But as a result, the delegates to the convention represent a
more conservative brand of politics than the Bush-Cheney ticket
presents to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates to the convention have gone along with Bush's strategy
because they believe he will win in November and restore them to
power. But Bush's decision to make Cheney his running mate has
become something of a gesture to the rank and file of the party.
While Democratic criticism of his conservative voting record almost
appeared to catch the Bush camp off guard, it has reassured the
party faithful that despite Bush's rhetoric of inclusiveness and
reaching out to independents he is at the core as conservative as
he is compassionate.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign has said Cheney will promote Bush's record of
bipartisanship in Texas, while criticizing the administration of
Clinton and Gore as divisive. The speech will also be somewhat
biographical, as Cheney describes his service under three
Republican presidents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
