<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0606 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      08-02 1493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR(a) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED IT --
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: MOVING IN ``E'' AND ``L'' CATEGORIES)
</HEADLINE>
 NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR 
 &HT;    ANNE STEPHENSON'S ``NEW &AMP; NOTABLE'' BOOK REVIEWS(a)  &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ANNE STEPHENSON(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of eight new books:
</P>
<P>
   ``AMERICAN RHAPSODY''
</P>
<P>
   ByJoe Eszterhas
</P>
<P>
   (Knopf, $25.95)
</P>
<P>
   We'll say right upfront that we felt as if we earned our salary
for the next five years as we struggled through this book, a
quagmire of gonzo posturing and other strange liberties to which
Eszterhas believes he's entitled. The former (beginitalic)Rolling
Stone(enditalic) writer, having made his money with screenplays to
such scintillating films as (beginitalic)Showgirls(enditalic) and
(beginitalic)Basic Instinct(enditalic)(beginitalic), (enditalic)
now shows us the real Bill Clinton or, as Eszterhas' friend, Jann
Wenner, called him, ``the first rock and roll president in American
history.'' Eszterhas was mesmerized by the Monica Lewinsky sex
scandal. He devoured the Starr report, watched it on television,
read about it in magazines. Maybe they are his sources for the
garish ``non-fiction'' sections here, but he never really makes
that clear (there are fictional parts too, including a chapter
narrated by ``Willard,'' the most famous part of Clinton's
anatomy). Read this at your own risk. And remember: No one's paying
you to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Log online to azcentral.com/rep/ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   books to read the first chapter of (beginitalic)American
Rhapsody(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   ``LOCO FOR LIZARDS''
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Cherry
</P>
<P>
   (Northland, $7.95)
</P>
<P>
   Lizards, Cherry notes, predate dinosaurs, continents, even -
gasp! - (beginitalic)S(enditalic)(beginitalic)trom
Thurmond(enditalic). If that doesn't leave you hungry for more, you
are a hard sell. This brief, well-illustrated book tells you
everything you always wanted to know about lizards and a lot you
could have done without but aren't troubled to hear, such as the
fact that a monitor lizard can run 10 mph to catch the wild pigs it
likes for supper or that its mouth is so full of bacteria that its
bite will kill its victim within a day or two even if it gets away.
Cherry also includes general information on lizards in myth, art
and advertising and in film (we were delighted to see not just
(beginitalic)Godzilla(enditalic) and (beginitalic)Journey to the
Center of the Earth(enditalic) but also (beginitalic)The
Freshman(enditalic), Andrew Bergman's comedy in which a Komodo
dragon gets loose in a shopping mall). This is a good book to hand
over to visitors from the East as they watch geckos skitter across
your block wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``POOR RICHARD'S ALMANACK''
</P>
<P>
   By Benjamin Franklin
</P>
<P>
   (Modern Library, $10.95)
</P>
<P>
   Early to bed and early to rise makes a man miss pretty much
everything good on TV. That's Ben Franklin updated by Dave Barry in
his introduction to this new edition. Barry is hilarious, in fact,
as he questions the wisdom of a few of Franklin's statements -
particularly ``if your head is wax, don't walk in the sun'' - and
heartily endorses others. ``Poor Richard advocates diligence,
self-reliance, frugality and honesty,'' writes Barry. ``He disdains
laziness, extravagance, pretense and immodesty. It goes without
saying that he hates lawyers.'' This is one of the first four books
in the Modern Library Humor and Wit series. Others are
(beginitalic)Mark Twain's Library of Humor(enditalic), with an
introduction by Roy Blount, Jr.; (beginitalic)Most of the Most of
S.J. Perelman(enditalic); and (beginitalic)Crazy Salad: Some Things
About (enditalic)(beginitalic)Women(enditalic) by Nora Ephron. The
series is edited by Steve Martin, who insists that Perelman stole
his material.
</P>
<P>
   ``BE THE ONE''
</P>
<P>
   By April Smith
</P>
<P>
   (Knopf, $24)
</P>
<P>
   Cassidy Sanderson is a formidable woman - tall, blond, athletic
and savvy enough to be a baseball scout for the Dodgers, the only
female scout in the major leagues. The competition to find new
players is stiff, and when she gets a call from an old friend in
the Dominican Republic, she quickly flies down to see the ``pure
hitter'' he has discovered. Alberto Cruz does have talent so
Cassidy signs him and brings him back to Los Angeles, but soon
Alberto begins receiving mysterious blackmail notes. Flashbacks
throughout this novel reveal that the notes are tied to a
mysterious night in the Dominican Republic when Cassidy, Alberto
and a wealthy American businessman drove drunkenly through a
hurricane just before their return to the United States. The novel
is suspenseful and well characterized although longer than it needs
to be. Smith will appear at the Poisoned Pen bookstore. See Book
Signings for details.
</P>
<P>
   ``AN INVISIBLE SIGN OF MY OWN''
</P>
<P>
   By Aimee Bender
</P>
<P>
   (Doubleday, $22.95)
</P>
<P>
   Bender's odd but very effective first novel is narrated by
20-year-old Mona Gray, a troubled young woman who struggles with
psychological scars and obsessions even as she forms attachments to
some very strange second-graders at her hometown elementary school,
where she has been hired to teach mathematics. Emotionally affected
by her father's poor health since she was 10, Mona is the ultimate
unreliable narrator, her sanity seemingly so fragile that for a
long time we don't know what to make of her. She finds comfort in
numbers - they are the constant force in her mind, her only
reliable port in life's storm. In a voice that is both witty and
spooky, Mona tells us about her students, her family and her inner
life, hinting at potential violence even as she embarks on a sweet
romance with a fellow teacher. It's a mark of Bender's subtle
virtuosity that such a surreal story is ultimately so appealing.
She's a writer to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE DAY JOHN DIED''
</P>
<P>
   By Christopher Andersen
</P>
<P>
   (Morrow, $26)
</P>
<P>
   Andersen opens this book by trying to justify it, alluding to
the ``ocean of grief'' into which we all allegedly plunged upon
hearing of John F. Kennedy Jr.'s death and pointing out Kennedy's
similarities to Princess Diana (which amount to little more than
that both were ``lit from within,'' and we were obsessed with
them). You'll forgive us if we tell you that books like this make
us feel squirrelly as if we're watching a bank heist in progress
and doing nothing to stop it. But Andersen has cased this joint
before (he wrote not only (beginitalic)The Day
(enditalic)(beginitalic)John Died (enditalic)but also
(beginitalic)Jack and Jackie (enditalic)and Jackie After Jack), and
he knows where the money is. Happily, Kennedy comes off well. His
marriage was doing better; his rebellious youth was spent; and he
was, to all appearances, a good man. And we defy you to remain
unmoved at the description of the funeral service, marked by a
stunned and battered family's grief over another gone too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``FROM OUR HOUSE: A MEMOIR''
</P>
<P>
   By Lee Martin
</P>
<P>
   (Dutton, $22.95)
</P>
<P>
   This memoir begins with a ghoulish tragedy but becomes the oddly
uplifting story of the author's determination to understand the
dynamics of his own family. In 1956, when Martin was a baby, his
father, Roy, lost both hands in an accident with a harvesting
machine on their 80-acre farm in Illinois. Roy Martin was already a
coarse, difficult man, but his misfortune instilled in him a new
level of anger. Over the years, he beat and berated his son while
Lee's mother looked on. ``I was too young to know then,'' Martin
writes, ``that she was as helpless in my father's house as I.'' But
to dismiss Roy as a villain is to deny the complexities that exist
in unhappy families. Martin explores his own responses to his
father, and so takes his story beyond self-pity and makes it an act
of salvation. His book is an unflinching look at the bonds between
a wounded man and his son and at the stoic perseverance of the
woman who loved them both.
</P>
<P>
   ``WHY WE HURT''
</P>
<P>
   By Frank T. Vertosick
</P>
<P>
   (Harcourt, $24)
</P>
<P>
   It's unsettling, reading about pain. We suspect that any amount
of discourse on specific pain would be easier to take - you have a
migraine, you have a bad back, you're looking for solutions. But
this book, subtitled (beginitalic)The Natural History of
Pain(enditalic), covers the whole gamut of discomfort, and it made
us squirm. Cancer pain, spinal pain, migraine pain, the pain of
childbirth, of carpal tunnel syndrome, of kidney stones or worse.
Vertosick, who is a neurosurgeon, eases the way with his friendly,
nonchalant tone, and he reminds us often that in the grand scheme
of things, pain has a purpose. It is, he says, ``a teacher, the
headmaster of nature's survival school.'' He discusses some of his
own patients and how he alleviated their pain and gives lots of
time, bless him, to the miracle of anesthesia, which he ranks as
one of the great achievements of our age. So do we, but right now
we're going to take some aspirin. We're not sure why.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1436EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0608 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TEXAS-DANCER-TEX     08-02 1411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DANCER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S JUST A HOP, SKIP AND SEVERAL JUMPS FROM FORT WORTH TO FAME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DAVE FERMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You may not know her name, but you have seen Nancy Anderson over
and over again.
</P>
<P>
   She is one of the dancers on Christina Aguilera's ``What a Girl
Wants'' and ``Come on Over'' videos and has toured with Aguilera.
</P>
<P>
   She is a high school cheerleader in the scene in ``American
Beauty'' where Kevin Spacey's character lusts after another
cheerleader.
</P>
<P>
   She's dancing again on Ricky Martin's ``Livin' la Vida Loca''
video.
</P>
<P>
   That's Anderson, as Madonna's body double, walking down the
beach in the Material Girl's ``Power of Goodbye'' video.
</P>
<P>
   She's the young lady in blue in those Gillette razor
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Still not sure you've seen her? Well, we know you've watched
those Gap ``khakis swing'' ads on TV. Anderson is one of the
dancers in those, too _ the one who is flipped upside down.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Anderson is a 1996 Paschal High School grad who just
turned 22 and celebrated during a 27-hour bus ride on the Aguilera
tour. She may be largely unknown to the public, but she is one of
the most popular _ and sought after _ dancers in her adopted home
of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Not that any of this is going to her head. ``I still worry about
it; you never know how much work there's going to be,'' Anderson
said in a recent telephone interview. ``I feel comfortable I'll be
able to work with people I like, but there's always a feeling of,
`What's going to happen next?' They can want to hire you but need a
girl with brown hair. You can be a great dancer and never get any
work, be in the wrong place at the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than four years after arriving in LA, Anderson is a popular
and respected member of the dance community. Her praises are sung
by well-known choreographer Travis Payne and Kitty McNamee,
artistic director of the Hysterica Dance Company.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's one of my favorite people in the city to work with,''
says Payne, who choreographed the Gap ads. ``You don't find many
people with great attitudes and (who are) always on time and never
complaining. Everybody likes her.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne worked with Anderson on the new movie ``Coyote Ugly,'' the
story of five women who run a New York bar of the same name who
become legends for their ability to dance on the bar, sometimes
while it's aflame. Anderson is a body double for Izabella Miko,
which means when you see close-ups of the fancy footwork, you'll be
seeing Anderson's legs, not Miko's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ended up clogging!'' Anderson says, laughing because the
dance is one of those she learned in Fort Worth. ``We'd rehearse,
but they didn't want it to look like choreography _ not TOO good.
I'd run and slide on the bar, and at one point they had fire on the
bar _ we danced to Kiss and Def Leppard and Kid Rock, and we had a
blast doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd start dancing at 2 a.m. and were on a bar in 3-inch heels
and trying to clog and look cute at 4 a.m. I hurt myself _ I
sprained my ankle. It was really hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, her sister, Audrey, and mom Sandra moved to Fort Worth
when Nancy was 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a delightful little girl,'' Sandra Johnson says. ``And
she always had a passion for dance. She did what most kids do; she
took dance when she was young, and when she was 12 or 13, she
didn't want to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson had taken ballet and tap dancing when she was ``3 or
4,'' she says, and then clogging and tumbling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't serious about it at all,'' she says. ``It was a
hobby.''
</P>
<P>
   It became her passion after a weekend in Arlington, a Fort Worth
suburb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 15, I hadn't had any real good training, and I went to
L.A. Underground _ it's a dance convention,'' she says. ``And I
stood in back of the room and I was so timid, and I was there all
weekend and when I walked out Sunday I realized I had forgotten
about everything else. I told my mom I wanted to be a dancer and
that (dance teacher) Dian West was really good and really strict.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson attended West's school three blocks south of Texas
Christian University in Fort Worth _ and discovered how little
dance training she'd had.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was coming to the game late,'' she says. ``There were
11-year-olds who could do more than me _ I went home crying every
night. I lacked confidence, and it took awhile to get it. I was
timid.''
</P>
<P>
   She progressed quickly, however, and by her senior year in high
school she tried out for New York University's Tisch School of the
Arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I had been in New York, I had had so much fun,''
she says, ``and in high school, every teacher was breathing down
your neck about where you were going, so I said there. They have a
great program. They told me they were full, and I wasn't
disappointed, because we couldn't have afforded it. (But0 I always
knew I'd end up dancing _ it was just kind of core to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds West: ``She had so much potential. I didn't want her to get
lost in the crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, also in her senior year, she auditioned for the Edge
Performing Arts Center in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all knew Nancy, because she had attended events with
Dian,'' Edge director Bill Prudich says. ``She was a quiet,
unassuming young lady _ she didn't make a big noise when she
danced. Her forte at the time was her technical ability. We decided
to see what we could do with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson won a one-year scholarship to Edge. She began attending
the school in September 1996 and, over the course of taking three
to five classes a day and getting a few commercials (among them
Mystic Iced Tea), she blossomed. Prudich says he really saw the
difference several months after she started.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started in the middle of the rehearsal for our showcase,''
he says. ``All of a sudden she just appeared _ who she was, who she
was trying to be. By the end of the show it was like, `Who is this
person?' And she never looked back. In the commercial world, she
has such a sellable look _ so much what little girls look like. ...
Her gifts are innate. She's not manufacturing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The key was confidence,'' Anderson says. ``I stopped judging
myself. Dancing is about your love for it and what you want to
express _ once I realized that and didn't worry about it and
started having fun, people were attracted to that.''
</P>
<P>
   One of them was Kitty McNamee, founder of the Hysterica Dance
Company in Los Angeles. Anderson has been part of the troupe for
two years, when her schedule permits. ``My choreography is very
theatrical,'' McNamee says, ``and one of Nancy's strengths is,
she's very expressive and brings a lot of theatricality to her
work. She has an amazing presence and incredible intelligence _ not
only physical but also emotional. She's a huge asset to the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hysterica has to share Anderson with moviemakers and touring
teen-age singers and producers of TV commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson got the part for the Gap ads, for instance, by
attending an open casting call. She was picked as one of the four
principal dancers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had about five days of rehearsal for the swing one,'' she
says. ``I'd never done swing dancing before. And we shot the whole
thing with no stops and no cuts. It took hours to shoot. We did it
in one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne choreographed the commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The khakis ads were unique in that we had choreographed camera
movement,'' he says. ``They used 360-degree camera rotations and
stop motion. The moves had to happen at exactly the same time every
time _ they had to match each take exactly. Nancy was really great,
and they loved the way she looked.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson says she had no idea that the commercials would be so
popular; at the time, she said, she just knew they were good and
that they paid well. Seeing them on TV, she says, ``made me smile''
_ and certainly helped her career.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, she was appearing as Madonna's body double _
walking down El Matador Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all shot from the back,'' Anderson says. ``They dyed my
hair brown and put extensions in it. And I wore her clothes. All I
had to do was walk down the beach and kick off my shoes and walk
into the water. I got to go to her home and meet her daughter.
Madonna was very businesslike.''
</P>
<P>
   Did she like the video?
</P>
<P>
   ``I never even saw it!'' Anderson says. ``I don't have cable.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
