<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0609 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-VATICAN-FATIMA-HNS &LR;      08-02 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VATICAN-FATIMA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     VATICAN'S ACCOUNT DOESN'T HALT FATIMA THEORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JENNIFER A. DLOUHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ For decades, the third secret of Fatima was
shrouded in mystery, the manuscript detailing it hidden from view
to all but a few officials at the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop wild speculation in books, and later on Web
sites, about the manuscript's contents, ranging from predictions of
the Apocalypse to a devastating third world war.
</P>
<P>
   Neither has the Vatican's release of a copy of the manuscript,
handwritten years after the event by one of three shepherd children
who said the Virgin Mary appeared to them in a series of visions
that began outside Fatima, Portugal, on May 13, 1917.
</P>
<P>
   Even a statement by Cardinal Angelo Sodano at the May 13
beatification ceremony for two of the witnesses, who are now dead,
and a commentary by another top Vatican official, Cardinal Joseph
Ratzinger, haven't put the speculation to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Far from it. Conspiracy theorists and Web chatters have burned
up the Internet with accusations of a Vatican cover-up of what was
revealed to the children in the third vision.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, church leaders said the first two apparitions painted
a vision of hell, foretold the rise of communism in Russia and
predicted the end of World War I and the beginning of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   But Rome maintained its silence on the third vision for decades.
The Vatican now says the apparition predicted the 1981
assassination attempt on Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   The pope has long had a personal devotion to Our Lady of Fatima.
The attempt on his life occurred on May 13, the same date the
visions began 64 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But other Fatima watchers have found the Vatican's
interpretation not just anticlimactic, but a deliberate falsehood _
to them, it simply doesn't fit the evidence, especially the
manuscript the Vatican released.
</P>
<P>
   Written in 1944 by Lucia Dos Santos, the surviving witness who
is now a 93-year-old cloistered nun, it describes a vision in which
the Holy Father, bishops, priests and religious men and women climb
a steep mountain, topped by a cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``On his knees at the foot of the big cross, he was killed by a
group of soldiers who fired bullets and arrows at him,'' reads the
Vatican's English translation of the manuscript. ``In the same way
there died one after another the other bishops, priests, men and
women religious and various lay people of different ranks and
positions.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most vocal critics of the Vatican's interpretation of
this vision, Father Paul Kramer of The Fatima Centrein Fort Erie,
Ontario, is using the fatima.org Web site to lambaste what he calls
``a Vatican whitewash.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The vision described in the text is a scene in which the pope
is shot by soldiers, and then bishops, priests and so forth are
killed in the same way, one by one, after they have all gone
through a half-ruined city,'' Kramer said in a statement posted on
the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``This clearly has nothing to do with Pope John Paul II not
being shot dead by (Mehmet) Ali Agca,'' he wrote, referring to the
Turkish gunman who wounded the pope and served a prison term for
the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Even Agca himself has gotten into the act, declaring the Vatican
``the enemy of God'' two weeks ago in a Turkish courtroom, where he
was taken after his release from an Italian prison to face
unrelated charges that predate the assassination attempt.
</P>
<P>
   In a handwritten statement, distributed outside the courtroom,
Agca praised the pope but claimed the Vatican had altered the
prophecy.
</P>
<P>
   Online, Catholics and non-Catholics alike wonder why the
disclosure came 19 years after the assassination attempt it was
said to have foretold.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it only pertains to (the) shooting of JPII, why wasn't it
released 10 years ago?'' asked one believer.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics have even called for a handwriting analysis to
compare the known writings of Dos Santos with the letter explaining
the third secret.
</P>
<P>
   Online discussions peaked just after the May 13 announcement and
seem to be tapering off. Father John Leies , chairman of the
theology department at St. Mary's University in San Antonio,
predicted the controversy would gradually die down once conspiracy
theorists heed the information provided by Vatican officials,
including the pope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually,'' Leies said, ``I think reason will prevail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
