<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0620 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-HEAT0803-COX     08-02 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT0803-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's not really not enough to fry an egg, it just seems that way
 &HT;    By LAURENA MAYNE DAVIS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. - Is is hot enough to fry an egg?
</P>
<P>
   Well no it isn't. The raw egg, cracked crisply into a puddle of
canola oil on the blacktop, just kind of languished there without
frying, sizzling or even sputtering once.
</P>
<P>
   If you've been outside lately, where the temperature's been
threatening to boil up to a hundred degrees or so, you can identify
with that egg.
</P>
<P>
   Just wanting to languish. Too wiped out to even sputter.
</P>
<P>
   It's typical August, in many ways. The dog days of summer are
howling, 100 degrees is not unusual and a hammock in the shade's
looking much more inviting than a volleyball game in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   But August is starting off atypically, too, with below-normal
rainfall leading into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been fairly dry,'' said David Nadler, meteorologist for
the National Weather Service in Grand Junction.
</P>
<P>
   Not that western Colorado will ever be confused with a tropical
clime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically in July we only see a half an inch of rain, anyway.
July is one of our driest months,'' Nadler said.
</P>
<P>
   And temperatures have been, on average, slightly hotter, and
expected to remain that way. Five degrees above normal, on average,
for the whole month of August, according to the Climate Predictions
Center.
</P>
<P>
   So while everyone else is busy moaning about the heat, we set
out to actually show just how hot it is outside _ to see if there
is any empirical truisms behind the hot weather idioms.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the egg. And a slew of other attempts to prove the
blistering power of the August sun on the Colorado Plateau.
</P>
<P>
   So we tried to make s'mores on the blacktop and a candle in the
parking lot and to affix an iron-on transfer on a T-shirt, using
only the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Then we left a Barney tape on the dash of a minivan _ with the
windows rolled up _ all day.
</P>
<P>
   (Don't feel too bad about the tape, it was a ``Barney Songs''
sing-along. Actual lyrics: ``Oh I'm brushing my teeth on the
bottom, 'cause I wouldn't wanna say that I forgot 'em!'')
</P>
<P>
   (Consider it a mercy killing.)
</P>
<P>
   Our attempts were met with mixed results, detailed here for your
reading pleasure and coming soon to a scientific journal near you.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST OF ALL THE S'MORES _ the graham cracker, marshmallow and
chocolate bar sandwich of scouting and summer camp cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult part of this exercise was sacrificing a
perfectly good chocolate bar. But we did, and a few hours later,
the bar was oozing nicely between the crackers, though the
marshmallow puffed only slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Hypothesis: Solar heat will undramatically but effectively puff
up a marshmallow and melt a chocolate bar, remotely echoing the
blending of flavors in a campfire-roasted s'more.
</P>
<P>
   Finding: Never waste chocolate. Not even for science.
</P>
<P>
   NEXT THE CANDLE. It is widely known that it is possible to make
a variety of decorative candles at home, involving molds, wicks,
wax and third-degree burns all over your hands from the wax that is
about 400,000 degrees Fahrenheit when in liquid form.
</P>
<P>
   On the blacktop, we simply poured some Candle Magic wax crystals
into an aluminum, star-shaped mold.
</P>
<P>
   Hypothesis: Sunlight will melt the flaked wax into a solid
candle form.
</P>
<P>
   Finding: Indeed, this exercise worked beautifully, as many who
have placed candles on their window ledges at home can attest.
</P>
<P>
   THE IRON-ON TRANSFER, admittedly, was a long shot, a dark horse.
The instructions call for simply ironing on the wool/cotton
setting, no steam, letting the transfer cool, and peeling off the
paper backing.
</P>
<P>
   Hypothesis: Enough heat will be generated from the sun shining
on the blacktop that an iron-on transfer can be applied to a
T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Finding: You will get only a hot T-shirt, which should be
reassuring to people actually wearing T-shirts with iron-on
transfers in this weather.
</P>
<P>
   AS FOR THE BARNEY TAPE, it was unchanged, probably because it
was white (as opposed to black) and possnot the happy fate of most
videotapes, said Mary Garcia, store director for Hollywood Video.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a couple of hours it'll warp,'' Garcia said of a videotape
left in a car. ``I've actually had a rash of them the last couple
of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw a few of them at the beginning of the summer, but this
last month has been a doozy. The moral of the story is don't leave
your dog in there, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Hypothesis: Videotapes will melt, warp and contort when left
inside your car in this heat.
</P>
<P>
   Finding: For every tape but Barney, this is true.
</P>
<P>
   Laurena Mayne Davis can be reached via e-mail at
lmdavis(at)gjds.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
