<HEADER>
A0635 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-LAREDO-HOCKEY-$ADV06-     08-02 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAREDO-HOCKEY-$ADV06-HNS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
BC-LAREDO-HOCKEY-HNS-2TAKES &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients. Eds.: LareDOS
in the 9th graf is cq)
 &HT;    Investors Hope the Puck Stops in Laredo 
By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle  &HT;     LAREDO, Texas _ Initially, some Laredo residents gave their
<TEXT>
proposal a snowball's chance, but a group of Houston businessmen is
increasingly confident it will bring professional ice hockey to
this sizzling hot border city.
<P>
   The investors, led by a former co-owner of the Houston Aeros
professional hockey team and the developer of the Aerodrome where
that team plays, first must convince voters to support a
quarter-cent sales tax increase to build a new arena. The proposed
Laredo Entertainment Center would cost $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   If residents approve the plan Aug. 12, proponents say that by
fall 2002 they could bring hockey to a city yearning for new
diversions. Officials also hope to lure concerts, wrestling,
graduations and other events to the 10,000-seat facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that Laredo needs entertainment desperately,'' said
Kiki DeAyala, president of the Arena Ventures partnership and
developer of Houston's Aerodrome. ``The only way to make it viable
was to have an anchor tenant.''
</P>
<P>
   DeAyala and former Houston Aeros co-owner Glenn D. Hart are
eyeing as the anchor an expansion team from the Western
Professional Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Laredo is one of three expansion teams the 15-member league
hopes to add by 2002, said WPHL spokesman Steve Cherwonak.
</P>
<P>
   As the nation's second-fastest growing city after Las Vegas _
bursting at the seams with construction, traffic and Mexican
commerce _ Laredo has many competing needs for its public dollars.
Most city council members and several key business leaders back the
arena, but some council members, joined by anti-tax campaigners and
advocates for the poor, are urging ``no'' votes, citing other
spending priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the arena debate erupts, invariably the term ``quality
of life'' surfaces. Many contend Laredo must move quickly to
provide more amenities for residents and visitors. But others say
water, sewerage, streets and other services should be improved
first.
</P>
<P>
   In the LareDOS weekly newspaper, which editorialized against the
plan, former Mayor Aldo Tatangelo said the council should address
the ``real issues in Laredo: a dirty river; the antiquated sewage
treatment plant built 70 years ago that is a health hazard;
substandard housing in all sectors of the city; 3,000 families
waiting for public housing; a city landscape covered with litter
and filth; creeks choked with tires and old appliances; abandoned
buildings; a work force that does not meet the skills criteria for
new businesses wishing to locate here. These are what I call
quality of life issues.''
</P>
<P>
   He and others doubt the arena can make ends meet, even with a
hockey franchise guaranteeing 35 home dates. Further, foes claim a
sales-tax increase would unfairly burden the city's poorest
residents, who might be unable to afford arena events.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Betty Flores, a project supporter, said she is often
asked, ``What have you done for downtown? What have you done for
housing? Is this council just worried about putting in an
entertainment and sports venue?''
</P>
<P>
   Her short answer could be no, but instead Flores recited a
litany of $28.8 million in downtown improvements, including a
transit center, theater acquisition and parking lots; and $17.9
million in federal and other expenditures in the past five years
for new home construction, repairs and down-payment assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Flores said Laredo recently built a police station and two fire
stations and the law enforcement budget has increased 67 percent
since the mid-1990s. Since 1997, four recreation centers opened and
parks were expanded to 345 acres, she said. The bus and library
systems also were augmented, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of issues that are being addressed by the city
council as we move along with this entertainment center,'' Flores
said at a contentious public hearing July 20. Chief among the
concerns is the city's long-term water supply, Flores said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we have spent a lot of time and a lot of effort on this
venue because the citizens of Laredo demanded it. They wanted it.
They asked us for it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Flores emphasized that if the proposal is approved, the city
would have 180 days to agree with Arena Ventures on issues like
site acreage and rent. She's confident the investors will carry
their share of financial risk.
</P>
<P>
   Hart, who heads Michael Petroleum Corp., said he's been doing
business in Laredo since 1986, has witnessed its growth and is sure
it can support a hockey club. From 1994-96, Hart was founding owner
of the Aeros International Hockey League franchise. Currently, he
owns the company that holds the lease for the Compaq Center, home
of the Houston Rockets. Hart is also a limited partner of the New
Orleans Zephyrs AAA baseball club.
</P>
<P>
   Hart said even he had doubts about the viability of hockey in
South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``But one of the final pieces of the puzzle that made this
situation all come together in my mind was the fact that Corpus
Christi has a franchise in the WPHL, they've been in business for
two years and they've sold out every game in the history of the
franchise,'' Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
