<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0636 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-LAREDO-HOCKEY-$ADV06-     08-02 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAREDO-HOCKEY-$ADV06-HNS-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
LAREDO-HOCKEY-HNS-2nd TAKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO: Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project is not about hockey,'' he insisted. ``It's about
a multipurpose entertainment center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city has stated ... loud and clear that they do not want
to be at risk for the potential of operating the facility at a
financial loss. Arena Ventures has conclusively and clearly stepped
up to say that we are willing to take that financial risk,'' Hart
said.
</P>
<P>
   The WPHL's Cherwonak said a franchise in the border town of
Hidalgo will begin league play in 2001. Beaumont also is hoping to
enter the league, joining teams in Austin, San Angelo and several
smaller cities. But why is hockey catching on in Texas?
</P>
<P>
   ``We can point directly at Wayne Gretzky for leading the charge.
He really took the sport from being regional to being national and
international,'' Cherwonak said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Laredo we've got a rock-solid ownership group, with
tremendous experience in business and sports. They'll have an
unrivaled facility. That right there gives us an excellent shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say professional hockey or a new arena is
more important than hospital beds or a police force. Of course not.
But it is a quality of life issue that we hope to be a part of.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for the arena to be built in a booming area in
northeast Laredo on Bob Bullock Loop near Sinatra Parkway. The site
would be close to the airport and Laredo's Texas A&AMP;M International
University, although some residents prefer a downtown site.
</P>
<P>
   In an appeal to Laredoans' fierce pride, proponents have noted
that slightly larger Lubbock has three arenas. And to make the tax
increase more palatable, they have portrayed it as imperceptible.
For every $4 in taxable purchases, shoppers would contribute one
cent to the arena, pro-arena advertisements point out.
</P>
<P>
   But that's no bargain, said opponent Jaime Mendoza.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we, the poor people, pay a sales tax to help these
gentlemen from Houston to get rich,'' he asked council members.
</P>
<P>
   Rolando Raymond said he wouldn't object to the city developing
an arena on its own, but he doesn't want an independent operator
like Arena Ventures involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Laredo are so hungry for entertainment, they're
not looking at the deal,'' Raymond said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're expecting us to pay for a $40.5 million
state-of-the-art facility, and then to simply hand it over to Arena
Ventures rent free, tax free ... and they get to keep all the
profits,'' Raymond said.
</P>
<P>
   But other Laredoans said the city is long overdue for a new
venue, something that would encourage residents to spend their
dollars at home rather than across the Rio Grande or in San Antonio
or Houston. Two proposals to build a new convention center were
defeated in the early 1990s, and now there's no adequate place for
large gatherings such as concerts and circuses, residents said.
</P>
<P>
   As resident Hector Ramirez put it, ``There's nothing to do here
but go to family reunions.''
</P>
