<HEADER>
A0662 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-RELIGIOUS-ICONS-TEX     08-02 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGIOUS-ICONS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STROGANOFF EXHIBIT REVEALS RICHES OF ICONOGRAPHY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By TARA DOOLEY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ They are considered ``windows into heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   From gilded backgrounds, stylized images of Jesus Christ, the
Virgin Mother or a pantheon of saints meet the gaze of the
faithful.
</P>
<P>
   In the images, their eyes are large, their noses elongated and
their bodies rigid.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than offering lifelike representations of human
beings depicting religious themes, the icons of Eastern Orthodox
churches are conduits for the faithful to reach out to the divine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Icons are very crucial in terms of Eastern Orthodox
practice,'' said Scott Ruby, assistant curator of The Jewish Museum
of New York. ``... We believe that people who pray with them are
helped by them through the intercession of the saints or Christ or
the Virgin Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   As devoted members of the Eastern Orthodox church in Russia,
generations of the wealthy and influential Stroganoff family
contributed to the iconography of the church, their patronage
creating a body of work known as the Stroganoff school.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the icons of that school and others can be found in
``Stroganoff: The Palace and Collections of a Russian Noble
Family,'' through Oct. 1 at the Kimbell Art Museum in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church in orthodoxy is considered an iconic pattern of the
kingdom of God,'' Ruby said. ``The icons that fill the church
reminds (us) of the work of God already accomplished in the
saints.''
</P>
<P>
   The word ``icon'' comes from a Greek word meaning image, said
Dean McKenzie, professor emeritus of art history at the University
of Oregon in Eugene.
</P>
<P>
   The use of religious images in Christianity dates to the first
century, when Christianity was literally an underground movement,
practiced in the catacombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was always the need to see, to visualize the basic
tenets of the Christian belief,'' McKenzie said.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the images depicted were mostly scenes from the Old
Testament, he said. But gradually, images of Jesus, the Virgin Mary
and the early saints appeared.
</P>
<P>
   In the first Golden Age of the Byzantine Empire, the sixth
century, iconography flourished. Usually, these icons were painted
for altar panels, but some were painted on metal.
</P>
<P>
   This period was followed by the iconoclasm of the eighth
century, a period when icons were condemned and many of the images
were destroyed. The Orthodox church resolved the conflict in the
mid-ninth century, and the icons were restored to their roles in
the life of the church, McKenzie said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike paintings of religious themes by masters of the Western
church _ or the Roman Catholic Church, which broke with the Eastern
church in the 11th century _ icon painters are not permitted to
interpret Christian themes, McKenzie said. Artists usually did not
sign their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Eastern church, there was an obligation of the artist
to depict it (the scene) in the way it had been depicted before,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, icon painters still follow established patterns in
depicting images. The ritual of creating the icon requires that the
painters _ often monks _ have the materials and finished works
blessed by priests, McKenzie said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, schools of icon painting emerged, particular painters
gained recognition and deviations snuck in.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the Stroganoff school, Nikifor Istomin Savin
became one of the masters, McKenzie said. And the Fort Worth
exhibit includes examples of icons painted by Savin, including one
that depicts St. George slaying the dragon.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, icon painters commissioned to produce work for
Stroganoff family chapels, homes or the family's Annunciation
Cathedral were not beyond making the icon resemble the guy paying
the bill. For example, an icon of St. Nikita, commissioned by a
member of the Stroganoffs, was altered from the depiction of a
warrior to show the saint as a wealthy prince, McKenzie said.
</P>
<P>
   But icons are hardly museum pieces in Orthodox churches.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, icons have a strong influence in the life of the
church, said the Rev. Luke Kontgas, priest at St. John the Baptist
Greek Orthodox Church in Euless, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us keep icons; we put them in our cars,'' Kontgas
said. ``The saints watch and protect us; they intercede for us.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, among the icons hanging on his office walls,
Kontgas keeps one of St. Luke and Jesus Christ. But believers also
often keep icons in their homes, he said, and churches are adorned
with them.
</P>
<P>
   In general, icons serve as teaching tools and as objects of
devotion, Kontgas said.
</P>
<P>
   Kontgas uses some of the many icons in St. John the Baptist to
illustrate the Gospels as he teaches Sunday school.
</P>
<P>
   The icons are a part of daily worship for many Orthodox
believers, Kontgas said. But it's not the images themselves that
are worshipped, he said. Instead, believers honor the saints or
scenes through the image represented in the icon, Kontgas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a part of their religious life, part of their spiritual
life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
