A0671 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KASHMIR-ATTACKS-440&AMP;A     08-02 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KASHMIR-ATTACKS-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LEAST 90 DEAD IN KASHMIR MASSACRES  
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ In a killing spree remarkable even for the
bloodied mountains and forests of Kashmir, at least 93 people were
slain late Tuesday and early Wednesday in six separate massacres.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the dead were innocents: pilgrims on their way to pray
at a holy site, laborers working at a brick kiln, villagers
awakened from their beds and lined up for slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   To many in India, the cause of all this murder seemed
straightforward enough: a peace process begun last week by one
militant group has been deemed a contemptible betrayal by others,
requiring sabotage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that after the Hizbul Mujahideen called for a
cease fire and talks, other militant groups have been instructed by
Pakistan to step up their attacks on innocent and unarmed people,''
India's prime minister, Atal Behari Vajpayee, told parliament.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I will tell these terrorists that we will not bow
down to their threats.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pakistan, as well as several of the militant groups critical
of the recent peace initiative, denied any responsibility for the
multiple attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan's foreign ministry issued a blunt statement, asserting
that the blame may belong to India: ``On previous occasions,
terrorist acts aimed at civilians have been carried out by renegade
elements at the behest of the Indian security forces, to malign the
Kashmiri freedom struggle internationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Kashmir is as tragic as it is beautiful. Once the Himalayan
domain of a maharajah, it has been the source of a 53-year custody
battle between India and Pakistan _ and the direct cause of two of
the three wars fought between the countries since they gained
independence in 1947. Each country now occupies part of Kashmir,
though India's share is far larger and includes the valley that is
the heart of Kashmiri culture.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, Pakistani-backed militants have rebelled against
Indian rule. Some of these guerrillas favor an independent Kashmir
while others want the region to be joined with Pakistan. Some
groups are primarily Kashmiri, but others are mainly foreigners lit
with jihad, dedicated to wresting the predominantly Muslim land
from the grasp of largely Hindu India. An estimated 25,000 to
40,000 people have died in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Hizbul Mujahideen _ one of the main insurgents
_declared a unilateral three-month cease fire, a surprise
announcement that brought an offer of talks from India and angry
condemnation from other Islamic militants in the fray.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Kashmir dispute is a deep morass, and while little common
ground would seem to exist between the Hizbul and India, plans for
discussions had seemed to be going forward _ and hence violent
efforts to derail the process could hardly be unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pakistan and its lackeys have stooped to the lowest point,
indulging in such barbaric acts to sabotage the peace process,''
Farooq Abdullah, the chief minister of the Indian state of Jammu
and Kashmir, heatedly charged Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But many in India have presumed that the Hizbul Mujahideen would
not have declared a cease fire without at least the tacit approval
of Pakistan's military government, which has been under pressure
from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Inflamed rhetoric aside, the attacks then raise questions about
whether Pakistan indeed favors the new dialogue _ and how much
capacity it has to control the militants.
</P>
<P>
   The recent attacks were particularly jarring and heinous _ and
the victims were overwhelmingly Hindu. In the worst incident,
gunmen opened fire on pilgrims on their way to a religious shrine
at Pahalgam, 55 miles south of Srinagar. The death toll in that
incident has risen to 33, according to hospital officials.
</P>
<P>
   In a small brick-making community near the town of Anantnag,
attackers forced people from their homes, lined up the men and shot
them. Eighteen died there.
</P>
<P>
   Curfews have since been imposed in parts of the state. The
authorities say they fear a violent Hindu backlash against Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   The Hizbul Mujahideen were loathe to suggest that any militant
groups took part in the massacres. Instead, the group's chief, Syed
Salahuddin, raised the heat under India's leaders, demanding that
they come to the negotiating table without any preconditions and
ready to discuss Kashmiri secession.
</P>
<P>
   He warned that even his group's guns would not stay silent
forever. ``Cease fire does not mean the giving up of jihad,'' he
warned. ``I'm sorry to say it means a breathing period.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1537EDT &QL; 
