<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0674 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-SOFITEL-ARCHITECTURE-     08-02 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFITEL-ARCHITECTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ARCHITECT EARNS THE RIGHT TO BUILD THE BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   By HERBERT MUSCHAMP    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Along with a room, the usual luxury amenities and a
gift shop stocked with beautiful books on Paris, guests at Sofitel,
the new hotel on West 44th Street, are rewarded with an unexpected
privilege. They get to participate in the education of an
architect. His name is Yann Leroy. He is a partner at the New York
firm Brennan Beer Gorman. He is 41. Sofitel is his solo,
stand-alone-building debut in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel is a coltish performance, more promising than
accomplished, of interest mainly on account of where it might lead
Leroy in the future and where it sits in relationship to his
bad-boy past.
</P>
<P>
   It takes most architects half a lifetime to build a stage. Leroy
is not the first to begin by setting up a soapbox in the street. In
1986, soon after moving to New York from Paris, he was like a one
man band against the city's architectural establishment. His
specialty was distributing leaflets outside lectures by prominent
practitioners like Michael Graves and Cesar Pelli. When the Museum
of Modern Art opened its ``Deconstructivist Architecture'' show in
1988, Leroy turned up on West 53rd Street to protest the Modern's
appropriation of ideas from a similar show that never got off the
ground but that was to have included his work.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Leroy's experimental work at that time did not fit
comfortably within the deconstruction mold. Instead of the warped
planes and sliced diagonals featured at the Modern, Leroy used
biomorphic shapes that anticipated today's computer-driven blob
design. Leroy's design process, which involved computer-based
collaboration with colleagues overseas, was also ahead of its time.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to his design work, Leroy's activism was charmingly
out of date. Did he think this was still 1968? In those ``Big
Chill'' years, many architects were trying to live down their
obstreperous student days. Along came Yann Leroy, popping up like
an old Jefferson Starship refrain: naive, independent, authentic
and mercifully not defanged.
</P>
<P>
   I first became aware of his work in 1987, in connection with a
show of designs for low-cost housing organized by the Architectural
League. Titled ``Vacant Lots,'' the show was the league's response
to the alarming rise in homelessness in the Reagan years. Leroy's
presentation was notable mainly for its graphic punch. In his
rendering, a study in washed-out, urban grays, the architecture was
pushed into the background behind a scene of urban violence.
Policemen stood in the rain around a shrouded corpse lying in the
street. The picture suggested that society prefers to solve the
homeless problem by killing people instead of housing them.
</P>
<P>
   You can detect a vestige of the ``Vacant Lots'' project in the
bow front of Sofitel's 44th Street facade. But I regret to report
that the edgy spirit of Leroy's polemical work is otherwise not in
evidence here. What is on view, however, is his ambition to become
a builder of New York, and this quality, given the architect's
ideological background, is worth noting. From sinister policemen to
white-gloved doormen is a stretch. Leroy has made it without
falling on his face. This is a pleasant surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel is also yeoman's work. To my eye, it does not depart
substantially from the collage aesthetic that we've seen in Fox &AMP;
Fowle's Times Square skyscrapers (Conde Nast, Reuters) and other
recent towers in Midtown. This aesthetic was a yawn when Kohn
Pederson Fox used it for the Shearson Lehman tower in TriBeCa (the
one that now sports that red neon umbrella) and it has not perked
up since then.
</P>
<P>
   The collage for Sofitel recalls the traditional recipe for
bridal wear: something old, something new, something borrowed,
something blue. Here, old is represented by the hotel's base, a
four-story classical composition in French limestone. New is a
bow-shaped tower of blue glass, set back from 44th Street, that
rises 30 stories above the base. Flanking the tower are two
20-story, limestone-clad wings.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel's public spaces are borrowed, old and made me blue. A
sequence of lobby spaces has been designed to recreate the ambience
of upper-middle class apartments in the 16th Arrondissement:
gilt-framed mirrors, Empire-style tables and side chairs,
chandeliers. Gaby, the hotel restaurant, is decorated in an
unpersuasive Art Deco style. Its features include an actress who
enacts the role of the brasserie's namesake. Wearing a flapper
dress and a cloche hat, Gaby sashays around the premises waving a
long cigarette holder. Ask not, as Angus Wilson might have put it,
for whom the cloche tolls.
</P>
<P>
   Squint. If you can look beyond the period appointments, you will
see that the progression of ground floor spaces is good. You enter
through a small rotunda of a reception lobby that opens onto a
larger, rectangular area furnished with small tables, where drinks
are served. Directly ahead is a second rotunda, from which a grand
staircase ascends to a ballroom on the second floor. Make a left to
reach the check-in desk. Adjust sunglasses, walk swiftly through
Gaby, on the right, and exit on 45th Street. Call this procession
Boutique Monumental. But the organization of these spaces within
Sofitel's awkward, T-shaped site is the outstanding feature of
Leroy's design.
</P>
<P>
   Sofitel's 398 rooms are small but thoughtfully laid out.
Ship-shape. Rooms with bow windows, especially fine, but the suites
have one too many big TV sets for such diminutive accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, Sofitel will be compared to LMVH Tower, a more
successful Midtown high-rise design by the French architect
Christian de Portzamparc. In study models for his project,
Portzamparc also played with various combinations of drum and box
forms, with contrasts in glass and masonry cladding. But the design
didn't resolve itself until he abandoned this collage approach and
arrived at an all-glass facade unified by an overall composition of
free-form, organic contour.
</P>
<P>
   Leroy progressed in the opposite direction. In an early scheme,
Sofitel's two wings were clad in glass. The plan recalled a set of
residential towers Frank Lloyd Wright designed in 1928 for a site
adjacent to St. Mark's Church, in the East Village. Like Wright's,
Leroy's earlier plan emphasized the tower's horizontal dimension,
as well as the vertical. As built, the glass wings have turned to
limestone. Leroy has tried to give the wings a skyline silhouette,
thus creating a push-pull effect between the tower and its
surroundings. But an all-glass tower would have strengthened this
effect considerably.
</P>
<P>
   All of us now are feeling kindly again toward glass. But the
appeal of tinted blue glass escapes me. A gem in old small-town
drugstores, this material has become debased by overuse in the
lesser suburban office parks. The tint obstructs views of the
interior, especially the underside of the floor slabs. This is
particularly regrettable compared with all the supertransparent,
so-called white glass in recent French architecture.
</P>
<P>
   White glass exacerbates the problems of glass buildings: lack of
privacy, for instance, or the unsightliness of messy interiors.
Perhaps these objections should be turned around. What's so sightly
about contemporary cast stone facades? Even real stone often looks
trashy, the way it's used today. As for privacy, a good hotel
should always stock its rooms with extra towels.
</P>
<P>
   I've been tougher than I might have been on Sofitel because
Leroy is talented. I wasn't just being cute in suggesting that
clients often foot the bill for an architect's education. Early
work by Le Corbusier, Wright and Gehry bears this out. It's healthy
for architects to engage with bricks and mortar before they're
ready. That is how they mature.
</P>
<P>
   The city gets educated in the process. Sofitel's weaknesses are
mostly a result of prevailing wisdom on how new buildings should
relate to old ones. Low, limestone bases make good neighbors, etc.,
etc. Unless they don't. Put up. Don't shut up. That's the way
cities learn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
