r k BC-CVN-MURRAY-GRAMM03-CO     08-02 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MURRAY-GRAMM03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gramm predicts big Bush victory
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Last time I talked with U.S. Sen. Phil Gramm
(R-Texas) I asked him about his dogs, knowing that his best old
hunting dog had recently passed on.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm talked at length, but never once asked me about how were
my dogs.
</P>
<P>
   I commented later to a mutual friend that maybe the senator had
been in Washington too long.
</P>
<P>
   You ask a man about his dogs, and he asks about yours. That's
common courtesy.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Philadelphia for the GOP national convention, I was able
to hook up with the senator by phone for an interview. First words
out of his mouth were:
</P>
<P>
   ``How're your dogs?''
</P>
<P>
   I'll say this for our Texas senator. When he knows he has made a
mistake, he'll make up for it.
</P>
<P>
   Last time, too, I had asked about the possibility of his being
Secretary of the Treasury if George W. Bush is elected president.
Gramm, who is chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, had
stressed that he had no ambition to join a Bush cabinet. But he
added something to this effect:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have served under every president since Carter, and I have
never refused anything the president has asked of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. Sounded like a ``maybe.'' So, in Philadelphia, I asked him
again: Anything to the speculation of the Treasury job:
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing was there before and nothing is there now, that I know
of,'' he said. ``I'm not looking for a job, and I think I can help
George Bush best where I am. I'm happy doing the job I'm doing, and
I expect to be doing what I'm doing for some time to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. Wonder what he meant by, ``that I know of''?
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Gramm could be out of the job as banking committee
chairman if the Republicans fail to maintain a majority in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   He predicts they will prevail, but concedes the House is a
tossup. As for the presidency ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm expecting our governor to win by maybe double digits. I've
thought it all along, and I'm more convinced now than before. But I
know he'd be mad at me if he knew I was saying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing frightens a candidate like overconfidence among his
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Texans can't help but wonder what it would be like to have a
Texan back in the White House. LBJ saw to it that most everywhere,
even the smallest crossroads communities, got a new post office
building. Then, too, there was the matter of NASA headquarters
coming to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm will tell you that he thinks ``90 percent of the benefits
will come from his (Bush's) good policies, and that they will
affect not just Texas but all of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Having said that, he allowed this: ``There's no doubt having
George W. Bush in the White House will help Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm gives the example of the highway bill, in which he had
asked $700 million for the new I-69 through Texas, touted as the
dominate trade route between Mexico and Canada, second only to the
parallel I-35.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected we'd get half that money.'' he said. ``But with
Clinton, we got 10 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Bush is in office, Gramm says ``we'll get our half.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of fairness,'' he said, ``we should get half.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas can also look to a fair share of military contracts under
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to rebuild national defense, which has been cut 20
percent by Clinton, and I believe we'll be a beneficiary of that.''
</P>
<P>
   He was quick to add: ``We're not going to do it because it helps
Texas but because it helps the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm also predicted:
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to use about 40 percent of the Social Security
surplus to cut taxes, to give some of this money back to the people
who earned it in the first place, and to eliminate the death tax
and the marriage tax, letting people put more money into their
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm going to be able to appoint federal judges and
get more done for the state and the country.''
</P>
<P>
   For Gramm, it will be nice to again have a president to whom he
can feel personally close.
</P>
<P>
   It's a relationship, he said, he has had with every other
president he's served under.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've never felt personally close to Clinton, and I'm sorry
that's the case.'' Much of the reason, he said, is due to Clinton's
``own problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm like my mom is,'' Gramm said. ``Most Americans
want to feel good about their president whether they agree with him
or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known George W. most of his life. It's exciting for
someone who's your friend to be president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something that happens often in a lifetime,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. It wasn't until after we hung up that I remembered I should
have asked about his mom. A man mentions his mom, it's just common
courtesy to ask how she's doing. Maybe I've been in Philadelphia
too long.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
