   FOOD-RECIPESWAP _A weekly recipe exchange column. This week:
Cabbage Soup. (Langhenry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CYBERSPICE _ A weekly column looking at the plethora of
recipes on the Internet. (Parham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-VIDEOS _ Let's set the record straight. The nation's first
music video show didn't start in New York in 1981, and it wasn't
MTV. The video revolution happened in Atlanta, over a fleeting,
duringh a nine-month period in 1970, when a group of young deejays
and film producers (eventually with the help of Ted Turner)
launched a 28-hour weekend block of music videos called ``Now
Explosion.'' (MLongino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   TV-FUGITIVE _ SAVANNAH _ Savannah is the first stop as the crew
of ``The Fugitive'' tapes its first post-pilot episode. Star Tim
Daly will be on location Wednesday and will talk with us between
takes. The show, which premieres in early October on CBS, will be
shot on locations around the country. How, why Savannah first? How
does it play in the town of Midnight? (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKNOTES _ Linda Howard has come a long way from her first
literary effort about children lost in the wilderness. Of course,
the Alabama writer was only nine at the time, and her audience
consisted of her family. Since then she has attracted a larger
audience and landed seven novels on the NYT best seller list. Her
latest, ``Mr. Perfect,'' is a suspense novel about four women who
become targets of a killer after their list of the attributes of
``the perfect man'' is released to the media. Howard will be in
town next Wednesday. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 19.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-ROMEO _ Video of the Week: Jet Li's ``Romeo Must Die.''
Grade: B- (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-RINGEL _ With the Coen brothers' 1984 ``Blood Simple''
returning to the big-screen, Eleanor Ringel Gillespie looks at
other works from the guys who made ``Fargo,'' including ``Raising
Arizona,'' ``Barton Fink'' and ``Miller's Crossing.'' (Ringel,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   AUDIO-COMEDY _ A review of ``Kings of Comedy'' as lede review.
Grade B-. (SoMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 5.
</P>
<P>
   AUDIO-MINIS _ Mini reviews of new CDs by Aaron Tippin (Grade B),
Victoria Williams (Grade B+), Richard Ashcroft (Grade B+),Ella
Fitzgerald (Grade A). (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLING 0803 BUDGET
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLING-LEAGUES _ The leagues carry ominous-sounding names:
Outlaw. Hardcore. Violent. The performers' names sound even worse:
Filthy the Clown. Reckless Youth. Suicide Solution. And almost
weekly somewhere in southwest Ohio, you can find them in local
gymnasiums, VFW halls and National Guard armories taking punches,
jumping off ring posts, sometimes even rubbing their opponent's
head on ropes laced with barbed wire. All the while dreaming of one
day becoming the next pro wrestling superstar. (Chow, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE _ News, gossip from the wrestling industry.
(Allen, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   END OF COXNET PAGE
</P>
