<HEADER>
A0680 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-TINY-CHURCH-TEX     08-02 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TINY-CHURCH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH FOUNDED BY EX-SLAVES SERVES AZLE'S SMALL BLACK COMMUNITY
</HEADLINE>
  (for use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By PEYTON D. WOODSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AZLE, Texas _ Inside tiny Wesley Chapel Christian Methodist
Episcopal Church, a choir of six children boldly sings: ``Watch ye,
therefore, you know not the day that the Lord will call your soul
away.''
</P>
<P>
   From the pulpit, the Rev. T.M. Berry listens carefully to the
melodic voices, most of which belong to his grandchildren. His
daughter, Sheryl Kimble, almost rocks the church with her forceful
piano playing.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that only 10 people are in the congregation this
scorching summer day. That's regular attendance at Wesley Chapel,
the only African-American church in Azle, with only about 20
members on its rolls. So small is the congregation, it gathers only
twice a month, the first and third Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the storied megachurches with tens of thousands of
members, state-of-the-art audiovisual equipment and
multimillion-dollar budgets. Members of the small white brick
church in a grove of trees on Park Street are fiercely loyal,
faithful and dedicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my church,'' says 73-year-old Margaret Crump of Azle,
the oldest member of the nearly 100-year-old church. ``It ain't but
a few of us, but I come on anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   On this particular Sunday, half the worshippers at the 11 a.m.
service are guests. Most of the members are in their 40s or older.
</P>
<P>
   With so few members, congregants have to double up on duties or
bear assignments alone.
</P>
<P>
   On the recent Sunday, Berry doubles as Sunday school teacher,
the only one needed for the class of four. During church, a single
usher greets worshippers at the door, and at the appointed time,
Crump quietly rises to pass the offering plate.
</P>
<P>
   From its beginning as a worship place for ex-slaves, Wesley
Chapel has been small but has served as the spiritual center for
the few blacks who live in and around Azle.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-slaves are responsible for founding the entire denomination.
In 1870, 41 delegates, angry over the interracial Methodist
Episcopal Church's refusal to condemn slavery, created a separate
denomination, the Colored Methodist Episcopal Church. It became
Christian Methodist Episcopal Church in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Wesley Chapel will celebrate its 100th anniversary.
The church began in a brush arbor across the street from its
current location and has twice served as a school. This is the
second church on the present site.
</P>
<P>
   Glenda Smith, who has lived in Azle all of her life and attended
Wesley Chapel during that time, says her grandparents helped found
the church. Crump is her aunt.
</P>
<P>
   The coming anniversary helps her to remember the struggles of
those who went before her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody had four or five hats they wore to keep the church
doors open,'' Smith says. ``My mother told me that when you go to
church, go prepared. You never know when you're going to be on
program. My mom was president of the Mission Society up until the
day she died.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith reminisced about a time when ``dinner on the grounds''
meant tables of food outside, underneath the trees _ not in the
church cafeteria, as it is today.
</P>
<P>
   Crump says she also remembers a simpler time in Azle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when you had to yell across the way to your
neighbor,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Azle once had two predominantly black churches, Wesley Chapel
and a Baptist church, which has since folded.
</P>
<P>
   With so few African-Americans around Azle, young people move to
find more diverse communities, Smith says. Of the 9,750 Azle
residents, an estimated 0.8 percent are African-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``When kids grew up and began to see we didn't have things like
the other churches, some began to move to Fort Worth,'' Smith says.
</P>
<P>
   Crump said she, too, has spent her life living between Fort
Worth and Azle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my church,'' she says. ``It's the only church I've ever
belonged to. Just like when a child leaves his parents, they always
come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Crump says she knew Berry long before he was appointed pastor 10
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Berry was assigned to Azle at a life stage when many ministers
are enjoying retirement.
</P>
<P>
   A man with graying hair and glasses, Berry wears a simple black
suit with a gold lapel pin that reads ``Try God.'' When greeting
members and guests between services, he often hugs them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's dedicated,'' says Gail Berry, the pastor's granddaughter
and a frequent visitor to Wesley Chapel. ``He's always here through
the week; he's always cleaning up. He's here more than he is at
home. I just know he's a God-sent person.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry said he spends most weeks visiting the many older, infirm
members who cannot attend Sunday service.
</P>
<P>
   He takes praises of his work in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``My responsibility is to try to help those that are in need,
whether they be black or white,'' he says. ``My job is to preach
the word to every creature. My job is to have my doors open to
those that will come.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry's assignment to Wesley has become a family affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to come out here to praise the Lord,'' says his
13-year-old granddaughter, Cnae Gray of Fort Worth. ``I like the
openness and I like to support my grandpa.''
</P>
<P>
   However, even those who are not related to Berry say Wesley
Chapel members feel like family.
</P>
<P>
   A few, such as Jearlene Releford of Fort Worth, say they have
regular churches but like to visit the tiny Azle church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like it's a family-oriented environment,'' says
Releford, who has visited Wesley Chapel for about 20 years. ``You
can adjust better than going to a church where the minister doesn't
even know your name.''
</P>
<P>
   The church rolls contain only the names of African-Americans,
but white Azle residents also visit.
</P>
<P>
   Azle Mayor Leck Heflin, a minister at a nondenominational
church, has visited several times and has preached at the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of them are longtime friends _ schoolmates,'' Heflin
says. ``They've always been appreciated and respected in the
community. The historical significance of that small community has
significance to our whole community.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of its amicable relationship with the community, church
members weren't very concerned when they discovered ``KKK'' painted
on the outside walls one day recently. Church leaders put the
graffiti down to a prank rather than vandalism and racial hatred.
</P>
<P>
   The young suspect arrested in the incident insisted that he
painted the letters on a lark, not because of racial hatred.
</P>
<P>
   The Wesley Chapel members expect no further incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's come through many a storm, but she's a good church,''
Smith says. ``She's shook from side to side, but she's still
standing. I love this old place.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
