<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0683 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-BILLY-JOEL-YACHT-ART-     08-02 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILLY-JOEL-YACHT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPT. BILLY JOEL,   DESIGNER MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT2, 3, 4 and 5 have been sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEPHEN P. WILLIAMS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST HAMPTON, N.Y. _ They say a boat is a hole in the water you
dump money into, and Billy Joel has emptied his wallet many times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a disease,'' he said last week from the deck of his
65-foot yacht, the Islander, moored in East Hampton's Three Mile
Harbor. ``I don't know how I'd kick it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely he'll ever try. Long before stepping into the
recording studio and selling more than 100 million records, Joel
began his nautical career by swimming out to other people's
moorings off the North Shore and ``borrowing'' their boats. He has
owned many since and now also lures other millionaires into the
boater's morass with a high-end speedboat he helped design, called
the Shelter Island Runabout _ with a base price of $300,000. A
stereo to blast Joel's sentimental song of the sea, ``The
Downeaster `Alexa,''' will set you back an additional $1,900.
</P>
<P>
   This day, under an extraordinary blue sky, Joel, 51, hopped
barefoot about the deck of his yacht as though his true calling
were the sea, not MTV. Peter Needham, who builds the 36-foot
runabouts, had just roared across Gardiners Bay in one to take the
singer to lunch. Joel busied himself catching lines so he and Trish
Bergin, a 29-year-old news reporter for Long Island's Channel 12
who shares his stateroom these days, could board. Then he paused to
smile down at the speedboat like a proud parent, admiring its
celadon hull and upholstery white enough to blind a Modernist.
</P>
<P>
   Joel's ideas for the boat's graceful lines were drawn from Long
Island lobster boats. And the idea of keeping it fast came from the
large commuter yachts that industrialists like J.P. Morgan used to
speed from Great Neck to Wall Street in less than an hour. Joel,
who has no training in design, began by sketching on the proverbial
cocktail napkin, in consultation with Needham. A naval architect
translated their ideas for a lightweight, fast boat into detailed
blueprints.
</P>
<P>
   Joel owns the patent on the hull design, and collects a royalty
on every runabout that Needham builds _ about seven a year _ at his
Coecles Harbor Marina on Shelter Island. The first boat was
christened in 1996. Now, the yard employs 14 carpenters and
electricians.
</P>
<P>
   At midcentury, Long Island was home to dozens of mom and pop
boat builders, but Joel can name only four other companies now in
business. So he takes great pride in having revived boat building
on the East End.
</P>
<P>
   The same people who buy mansions buy boats. Recently, one man
ordered a 50-foot version at $1.5 million. But most people are
satisfied with the regular model, which can hit 48 knots (about 55
miles per hour). That's perfect for the mogul who wants to crack
lobsters in Newport, followed by a swim off Block Island before
heading back to East Hampton for the evening. At a mile a gallon of
gasoline at top speed, the twin 415 horsepower MerCruiser motors
would make an SUV owner feel saintly. With Joel offering his hand,
Bergin stepped gamely aboard Needham's runabout in clunky, heeled
sandals, ready to cruise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I neglected to bring my boating shoes,'' she said, with a
pronounced Long Island accent. With her puffy lips and sparkling
eyes, Bergin appears to possess the same television-friendly genes
as Deborah Norville. Joel, with his T-shirt, chinos and sun-baked
cragginess, looks more like the guy who would clean the fish for
you once you got dockside. Still, they make a good pair.
</P>
<P>
   As Joel took the helm, Bergin said, ``I'm a good mate, aren't I
Billy?'' He laughed and set the boat in motion.
</P>
<P>
   Bergin and Joel met five years ago when she interviewed him for
a news program. She's a South Shore girl and he's a North Shore boy
_ a few miles inland in Levittown _ and they got along well. But
they didn't start dating until a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got married first, and then I got divorced,'' Bergin said.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Christie Brinkley, Joel's wife until 1994 and a
friend of Bergin, called Joel to say, ``Did you notice that Trish
isn't wearing a wedding ring anymore?'' Joel asked Bergin out.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the two spend much of their free time out on the water,
trying, often unsuccessfully, to escape notice. ``People come out
of nowhere,'' Joel said. Pointing across the harbor to the
photographer Patrick Demarchelier's house, he added, ``One day that
guy came screaming up to us in his boat saying, `Billeee, tout le
bla bla bla.' I couldn't understand a word.'' His challenge one
recent day was slipping past the crowds at the waterfront East
Hampton Point restaurant. With its teak details and classic look,
Joel's runabout is so distinctive that it's not the boat for
shrinking violets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even sailboaters who look down their noses at all powerboats
wave to this one,'' Joel said, as the restaurant came into view.
Two other Shelter Island Runabouts were tied up near the
restaurant, looking distinguished and serene in the ostentatious
flotilla of fiberglass and chrome.
</P>
<P>
   During lunch, a couple more passed in the harbor. Needham
remembers the details of each one. He becomes so attached to the
boats while building them, he said, that he cried the first time he
had to ship one off to a Microsoft millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I'd never see it again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most buyers add custom woodwork, upholstery, tuna towers and
other extras that easily raise the price to $10,000 a linear foot.
</P>
<P>
   Although the excess of tropical hardwoods makes the galley and
cabin feel luxurious, the space holds little more than a microwave,
a refrigerator and a sink, with room in the bow for two to sleep in
a pinch. (Joel designed the head twice as large for comfort.) Some
owners hire interior designers to tweak the teak, but the clean
design doesn't take well to froufrou.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, I've developed a pretty good idea of what a
boat should look like,'' Joel said. ``And it shouldn't look like
you started with the screening room and designed out from that.
It's also easy to overyacht a boat with too much nautical stuff. I
see those curtains printed with anchors, and every light fixture
designed like an old boat lamp, and I want to say, `Hey, I get the
point _ we're on the water!'''
</P>
<P>
   While Shelter Island Runabout owners will probably never drag a
bleeding swordfish up over the transom, Joel likes that utilitarian
illusion. It's all part of his workingman fantasies. For years,
he's been identified as a friend to bay men on the East End. He's
fought, unsuccessfully by and large, to preserve their fishing
lifestyle, and he's done countless benefits for local causes. But
the reality is that nostalgic millionaires are snapping up Joel's
surrealistic versions of the old fishing boats just as the bay men
are disappearing into history.
</P>
<P>
   This partly explains why Joel recently sold his East Hampton
estate, complete with a collection of boats on the lawn, to Jerry
Seinfeld, after more than a decade of living year-round on the
South Fork.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry asked me, did I want to sell the place,'' Joel said. ``I
threw out a number and he said OK. So I asked my daughter, `Should
I sell this house?' And she said, `Daddy, change is good.'''
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't talking small change _ $34 million. Joel is looking
for a waterfront place on the North Shore. ``As celebrity spotting
became a sport, it became hard for me to leave my driveway on
weekends,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
