<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PUTTING PHOTOS OF WARES ONTO eBAY AUCTION SITE  
 (Circuits)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am a computer novice and would like to sell items on the
eBay auction site. How do I add pictures of the items I wish to
sell? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. To display pictures of your wares on the eBay site, you must
have electronic copies of the photographs. Using a digital camera
to take the photographs makes it relatively simple to upload the
files to your computer and will save some steps.
</P>
<P>
   If you do not have access to a digital camera, you can take
regular photographs and convert them into digital files with a
scanner.
</P>
<P>
   If you do not have a scanner, you can have your photographs
scanned at a copy shop or desktop-publishing outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have the electronic copies, there are several ways to
place them on the eBay site. The site itself offers a thorough
tutorial on the subject at
pages.ebay.com/help/basics/phototut-index.html. The site is also
testing a photo-display program for some categories, like pottery
and glass, which might help simplify the process.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a computer running Windows 98 that I wish to sell to a
friend. How can I make sure none of my personal files and Internet
cookies are left on the machine before I give it to him? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Security experts say that it is truly difficult to erase
files completely from a hard drive, but for most people, the tools
offered by DOS or third-party programs like Norton Utilities or the
Eraser freeware (www.tolvanen.com/eraser/download.html, recommended
for advanced users) are adequate.
</P>
<P>
   Although it may take some additional time, one reasonably safe
way to prepare the computer for its new owner is to erase and
reformat the hard drive and reinstall Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   You should make sure that all your personal documents and
Web-browser favorites have been copied to your new computer before
you erase the contents of the old one.
</P>
<P>
   For one basic reformatting method, all you need is a blank
floppy disk and your Windows 98 CD-ROM. With the floppy, make a
bootable startup disk that can be used to start the computer before
reformatting. (Go to the Start menu, to Settings, then to Control
Panel and double-click on Add/Remove programs to see the StartUp
Disk tab and instructions.)
</P>
<P>
   Start the computer from the floppy to make sure that it works
and that you have the ``Start computer with CD-ROM support'' option
before continuing. Starting the computer from the floppy disk is
recommended so that you can still boot the computer if something
goes wrong, and to sidestep any viruses that might be on the hard
drive.
</P>
<P>
   You should also have the original disks for your video card,
modem and other hardware ready to reinstall.
</P>
<P>
   After booting the PC from the floppy (and again opting for the
``CD-ROM support'' menu choice), you can use the DOS ``format c:''
command to erase the drive's contents. The on-screen prompts will
warn you that all your data will be lost. The formatting process
takes about 15 minutes for a two-gigabyte drive. If you have other
drives, you should also format those. After formatting, type the
command ``setup'' after the letter of your CD-ROM drive (usually D:
or E:) at the prompt to begin installing Windows 98 from the CD.
</P>
<P>
   That is one basic way to reformat and reinstall. The ZDNet Web
site (www.zdnet.com) has a good Help and How-To section that can
offer more details, along with other tips. Microsoft's Knowledge
Base on the Web (search.support.microsoft.com) might also help to
answer questions about reinstalling the system.
</P>
<P>
   A freshly installed version of Windows 98 will ensure that your
buyer starts with a clean machine. If you are selling any old
programs along with the computer, you should reinstall those by
using the original disks, and be sure to give the computer's new
owner all of the floppy disks, CD-ROM's, manuals and serial numbers
for the software.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
e-mail to Q&AMP;A(at)nytimes.com or mail to Questions, Circuits, The
New York Times, 229 West 43rd St., New York, N.Y. 10036-3959. This
column will answer questions of general interest, but letters
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
