<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MAC USERS, HELP FROM AN UNLIKELY QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER H. LEWIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's never easy living as a Mac user in a Windows world, but it
is a lot easier than it used to be. Microsoft, maker of Windows,
was once thought to be Apple's greatest enemy. I will admit to
referring to Microsoft as ``the Borg'' (taken from the dominating
alien race on ``Star Trek: The Next Generation'') in those dark
days of '97 when Apple's future looked shaky. But then things got
better.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of trying to squash the Mac, Microsoft has actually spun
off a unit to create Mac software from the ground up, instead of
merely recycling old Windows code into Mac versions of its
programs. Microsoft's Internet Explorer 4.5 browser for the Mac
featured many techno-goodies, like a page-print preview option,
that were not included in the concurrent Windows versions, and
Internet Explorer 5 for Mac has even more.
</P>
<P>
   The Mac version of Microsoft's Office suite, which includes the
Word 98 word-processing program, Excel 98 for spreadsheets and the
PowerPoint 98 presentation program, also had features that didn't
appear on the other platform until the release of Office 2000 for
Windows. At the Macworld exhibition in New York last month, I saw a
demonstration of Microsoft's Office 2001 for Macintosh, which
featured some enticing additions like Entourage, an e-mail and
personal-information manager that can be fully integrated with
current Office programs and can synchronize with Palm organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Toolbars and icons within the Office suite have been redesigned
to make them more intuitive and Mac-like, and QuickTime movie clips
can be easily incorporated into PowerPoint presentations. Microsoft
Office 2001, available only for Macs, is due in October. More
information is available at www.microsoft.com/mac.
</P>
<P>
   Computers are all about communication in one form or another,
and having your Mac files be compatible with Windows files from the
ubiquitous Office suite is often a real concern among those of us
in Clan Macintosh. Microsoft promises that Office 2001 will sustain
``seamless compatibility'' with Windows Office 2000, which means
that a Mac user can write a memo in Word 2001 and send it as an
e-mail attachment to a Windows user running Word 2000 and magical
things will happen _ the file will open with no problems and all
the formatting will be intact. The Save As dialogue box in Word
2001 will even let Mac users save their files with a three-letter
Windows file extension appended to it, making things move even more
smoothly between the two systems.
</P>
<P>
   Not every document I get has been sent in a Windows Office
format _ some are in WordPerfect by Corel or the AppleWorks
software, and I also receive graphics, spreadsheet and database
files that are not Mac-friendly. I usually run those types of
hard-to-open files through my copy of Mac-Link Plus, by DataViz
(www.dataviz.com). That little $99 lifesaver will convert just
about any text, graphics or spreadsheet file into something my Mac
can read. It will also convert my own files into formats that a
Windows user can probably handle.
</P>
<P>
   Third-party software like Mac-Link Plus is designed to bridge
the gap between the two systems. But helpful software is sometimes
right there in the Mac operating system. Mac users have been able
to read and use PC-formatted floppy disks on their machines for
years, thanks to the system's PC Exchange utility, even if they
have to buy an external floppy drive to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The small size of my New York apartment will not allow me to
indulge my dream of having several computers scattered around, all
running different operating systems. For those times when I
absolutely have to use Windows at home (for, say, one of those
genealogy programs that come with what seems like 47 CD-ROM's, all
of them Windows only), I resort to Virtual PC 3.0 from the
Connectix Corp. (www.connectix.com).
</P>
<P>
   Virtual PC, which will emulate a Windows system on your Mac and
let you run Windows-only software, is for users willing to part
with roughly $180 and more than 500 megabytes of hard drive space
to store the program. It runs more slowly than a real Windows
system, but you can configure the settings to make your Mac's ports
function like those on a PC running Windows.
</P>
<P>
   You can drag and drop graphics and files from the Mac desktop
onto the Virtual PC faux-Windows desktop and open them. The program
also lets a Mac user surf the Web and get e-mail while in Windows
mode without bothering with dial-up or network settings. Virtual PC
comes in five versions: Windows 95, 98 and 2000; PC-DOS; and Red
Hat Linux for the especially adventurous.
</P>
<P>
   For current news, reviews and Mac-related information, I
regularly check the MacInTouch (www.macintouch.com) and Mac
Observer (www.macobserver.com) Web sites. For example, the Mac
Observer recently reported that 3dfx, a maker of powerful graphics
cards for PC gamers, had released its first made-for-the-Mac add-in
card. Fans of game-playing on the Mac will probably be cheered by
this news, as well as by the fact that Blizzard Entertainment just
released the Mac version of its popular game Diablo II
(www.blizzard.com), less than a month after the PC version's debut.
For Mac gamers, that's progress.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the demand for software, other companies that
produce Windows software are beginning to release the Mac versions
around the same time. Grolier Interactive (www.grolier.com), which
makes the robust Grolier Multimedia Encyclopedia reference suite on
CD-ROM, plans to release the 2001 Mac version of the suite just a
week or so after the Windows version hits the shelves in early
September. And some companies are still making great software just
for the Mac, like the SoundJam MP program by Casady &AMP;
Greene(www.soundjammp.com), which gives the Apple faithful a
full-featured program for creating and playing MP3 music files.
</P>
<P>
   I will also be scouring the Web for news of Mac OS X (as in 10),
the long-awaited revamping of Apple's operating system. The
drumbeats have been sounding about it for years, and Apple plans to
release a public beta version for impatient Mac-heads to play with.
Mac OS X includes enticing treats like a new graphical design,
protected memory and pre-emptive multitasking _ fancy words that
mean that when the goofy shareware of the giant eyeball
self-destructs, your entire system won't crash along with it. The
final version of the operating system isn't expected until at least
January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Even though using a Mac can be a bit more expensive than using a
PC because of the extra software it takes to be fluent in Windows,
I will keep using the Mac until a computer system I like better
comes along. In the meantime, I have my eye on one of those new G4
Cubes. Apple has stuffed a lot of firepower into that little box,
and the design of the thing has entranced me.
</P>
<P>
   And as I mentioned before, I have a small apartment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
