<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HIGH' SCORES: HONEST TEEN-AGE DOCUMENTARY MAKES THE GRADE ON FOX
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
 C.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``American High'' is pretty straightforward: It's about what
happens when a producer and his camera crew shadow a group of high
school students throughout the school year. How ``real'' the
situations are depends on which student is being shot, what they're
dealing with at the moment, and what producer R.J. Cutler thought
would make interesting television, since hundreds of hours have
been whittled down to a precious few.
</P>
<P>
   The series, Wednesdays on Fox, is at least somewhat of a
departure from the current reality TV craze. At least on ``American
High,'' no one is voted out of the school. Nor is the setting
false; it's Highland Park High School in suburban Chicago. The
situations aren't contrived. When Sarah Mages, a junior, talks of
being sad and lonely, it's because she really is.
</P>
<P>
   No one will walk away with a big money prize; the school was
paid, for the most part, in camera equipment donated to the
audio/visual department.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, ``American High,'' which uses hand-held cameras to
capture the honest, challenging and touching things that go on
during a school year, certainly isn't new on cable and PBS. But it
is new to network television, which has long been leery of trying
anything in documentary form, since there are no scripts and the
filmmakers can't necessarily control what the ``characters'' say or
do. They can't create cliffhangers, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   That's the beauty of ``American High.'' Cutler followed the
students during the 1999-2000 school year, starting with the first
day of the term and going through graduation. (Those who stay with
the program will see an interesting growth through the year.)
</P>
<P>
   Also featured are hundreds of hours of video diaries shot by the
students. This allows an up-close and personal look into the lives
of the teen-agers living in the suburb, which is a largely wealthy
enclave. (Cutler was able to be somewhat economically diverse,
including students who are on the lower end of the area's economic
scale. Race, however, is another matter. Not many black or Hispanic
students are found in Highland Park. At least one student, however,
is black.)
</P>
<P>
   It's a pretty eclectic group. There's Kaytee, a gifted
singer/songwriter whose love songs are often heard in the halls
(most students simply think she's weird). Mike is the football
kicker whose future seems to hinge on a successful season. Anna has
beauty and nearly everything else except a boyfriend. Robby, the
star jock and popular kid, is confronting the uncertain future of
his relationship with his girlfriend, Sarah. (Robby and Sarah have
some of the more touching moments; he's leaving for college and
she's got another year, which means an end-of-the-year breakup.)
Brad, meanwhile, is the first mainstream kid at the high school to
come out of the closet.
</P>
<P>
   Also included is Allie, who is the sad product of her parents'
messy divorce. Suzy is a self-described diva who pursues a career
as an opera singer with singular devotion (but who really just
wants to experience a first kiss). Pablo is a poet whose wild
parties and unruly ways seem destined to undo his future. Tiffany
is a black girl who is having difficulty managing both worlds: a
white world at school and a black one at home.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Morgan, the most colorful of the students, who is
one of the best reasons to watch. Morgan moves through life with a
``So what?'' attitude, literally scolding his friends for studying
when they ought to know that education means nothing in their lives
at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan has bad grades and doesn't care. He talks constantly
about having fun and doing whatever strikes him. But he's also a
kid who is dedicated to helping others; his life is complex, like
all our lives.
</P>
<P>
   What makes ``American High'' worth watching is not that it's
``reality TV,'' but that it manages to give a generally honest
glimpse of what's on the minds of teen-agers. Adults in shows like
``Survivor'' are there for the money and fame. Most of the kids are
on ``American High'' just because, as Robby put it during an
interview, ``It's pretty cool.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, it is.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
