<HEADLINE>
IF WOMEN RAN `MONDAY NIGHT FOOTBALL'.....
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By GAILE ROBINSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don Ohlmeyer, producer of ABC's ``Monday Night Football,'' hired
comedian Dennis Miller of the preternaturally fluffy hair and
biting tongue to boost the ratings slippage.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad move, but not a brilliant one. Diversity Don, it's a
whole 'nother sex. Thousands of women who would tune in if the show
were more of a turn-on.
</P>
<P>
   No need to change the game, just give us more about the game
players.
</P>
<P>
   We want some up-close-and-personal moments in between downs.
This shouldn't be hard to do _ ABC invented the five-minute video
sob story for the Lake Placid Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what we'd like to see.
</P>
<P>
   We'd like to see more skin. The players' uniforms and those of
the team cheerleaders should be of equal fabric yardage. The World
Wrestling Federation knows what we're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   We'd like to be introduced to the player's family. His wife and
children, mother and father. We want to know his people, his
hometown. Show us his picture in the high school yearbook. We're
pretty sure ``America's Most Wanted'' does this.
</P>
<P>
   Is he a good dad? Does he help with the chores? Tell us about
the kid sister he's putting through med school. Tell us about his
volunteer work for his favorite charity, what he does in the
off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Can he cook? Not just barbecue, but really operate a range? What
are his favorite recipes? We want a brief tour of his kitchen and
then a quick, Martha moment of food preparation; think Kraft Music
Hall and its multiminute recipe commercials.
</P>
<P>
   If he's a rookie, he's spent a lot of money on a new custom
wardrobe. Let's see it; have hin spin around a few times. Love that
jacket. Hire James Brown away from Fox to perform the Elsa Klensch
duties. He always looks fabulous, and those shoulder pads! Whose
are bigger, Brown's or Ronnie Lott's?
</P>
<P>
   Don, baby, (Dennis likes to say ``baby'' a lot) we're offering
you these suggestions completely free of charge in the hope you
will see their commercial value. And, Don, just imagine the new
advertisers you could get: feminine hygiene products, yogurt,
vitamins, soaps, detergents and shampoos. Cha-ching. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
