<HEADER>
A0714 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CIR-LYRIC-GENERATORS-     08-02 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-LYRIC-GENERATORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANYONE CAN WRITE A LYRIC WITH THESE WEBSITES 
</HEADLINE>
   By   EDWARD BOLAND Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Musical lyrics, perhaps more than most art forms, range from the
inspiring to the inane. With an eye on the latter, lyric generators
have turned up on the Web, supplying characteristic lyrics for
songs in the musical genre of your choice.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing from country music generators that know the long road
from ``flirt'' to ``hurt'' or Goth-inspired generators that will
search for that perfect rhyme for ``pierced skin'' (``fierce
kin''?), phonetically challenged songsmiths and Web surfers looking
for distraction can now pick up the mouse and sit back as the
poetry springs forth from the computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part there are two types of lyric generators. One
creates new lyrics typical of a particular artist or genre each
time you click on the generator button. The other asks you to fill
in various words, which are then used in the lyrics of your new
song.
</P>
<P>
   While it may be more entertaining to use your own material, some
automatic lyric generators have captured the spirit of the original
artists. Those who want to mimic lyrical works in the tradition of
boy bands like 'N Sync and the Backstreet Boys should seek out the
Cheesy Song generator
(smople.thehub.com.au/cathyst/c(underscore)songs1.html). It raises
the question, though, of whether a soulless Web site can produce
lyrics on par with the pop poetry that these bands produce.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, if you take four cute boys, put them in silver
pants and have them croon generated lyrics like ``Babe you know I
need you more/Than I've needed anything before/I'll walk beside you
in the rain/Kiss me once again,'' there won't be a dry eye in the
house.
</P>
<P>
   If you want a musical career that lasts longer than raw seafood
on a hot sidewalk, you might want to skip boy-band lyrics and take
a look at two Web sites that generate country music lyrics:
www.binary.net/dturley/js/song/song.html and
www.outofservice.com/country. The sites seem to use the same lyric
generator because the words and phrasing are uncannily similar.
</P>
<P>
   The lyrics focus on the timeless country music theme of love
lost and are usually no less poignant than those of some of today's
biggest country music stars. You can almost hear Alan Jackson
singing ``Well. . . . She asked me if I'd swear off booze
forever/She said our love would never die/But who'da thought she'd
get drunk with Marv Albert/She sealed me in the vault and smirked
goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   In the tradition of Nine Inch Nails and Marilyn Manson, the Goth
lyric generator will let you connect with
gloom-doom-I'll-be-in-my-room teen-agers. While it might not
provide the eloquent, subdued social commentary of such Manson
classics as ``Dried Up, Tied and Dead to the World,'' the Goth
lyric generator (scribble.com/dghq/gothlyric) will provide you with
dour nuggets like ``Evil curses yearning manacles/Rats suck
nocturnal rapture/Foolish mortals destroy lonely needles/Serpents
collapse from infernal psychosis.'' Most of the lyrics created by
this generator look as though they could have come right off the
back of a math notebook belonging to a high school student snubbed
at prom time.
</P>
<P>
   Those looking for a bit more artistic control should try lyric
generators that require more participation from the user. At the
Write a Spice Girls Hit site (www.amused.com /aom/stop.html), for
example, you provide 15 words, each limited to specific syllable
counts. In the end, you'll have your very own sugary pop hit with
lyrics like ``Hey, you always on the run/Gotta slow it down, baby,
gotta have some fun/Do Do Do Do always be together/Ba da Ba Ba
(sung three times) stay that way forever.'
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular lyric generators on the Web is the
Alanis Morissette lyric generator. It was created by David Neilson,
a company manager from Los Angeles who maintains a humor Web site.
The idea came to him while he was listening to his newly purchased
Morissette CD. ``I was listening to the album and I noticed that
all the songs were pretty similar,'' he recalled, ``no rhyme, no
meter, and I thought to myself, `Hey, I can do this.''' Thanks to
Neilson, now millions of other people can do it as well, at
www.brunching.com/toys /toy-alanislyrics.html)
</P>
<P>
   By filling in 10 fields, including a word for something you hate
and the name of an ex-boyfriend or ex-girlfriend, you can generate
three songs: ``Will to Live,'' ``I Think'' and ``Why.'' ``Will to
Live'' deals with an unpleasant relationship that has scarred you
for life. ``I Think'' also deals with an unpleasant relationship
that has scarred you for life, and ``Why'' deals with. ... Well,
you may already be familiar with Morissette's oeuvre.
</P>
<P>
   To get a sense of how the lyric generator might handle
Morissette's emotional terrain, I entered the name of an ex
(Nicole) and something that an overwrought adolescent might hate
(corporate pigs).
</P>
<P>
   From that outline, the generator produced this angst-ridden
testimonial: ``Is it because of corporate pigs I feel this way/Or
am I lost in a tale of Yeats, adrift far from home/Nicole broke my
will to live/Nicole broke my will to live/I was getting better but
then/Nicole broke my will to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Now if I could only learn to play the guitar.
</P>
</TEXT>
