u a BC-PRES-CREDENTIALS-NEWH     08-02 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRES-CREDENTIALS-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACKING DAD'S RESUME, GEORGE W. HAS DIFFERENT STRENGTHS
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 2, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADVISORY: WITH A GRAPHIC SUMMARIZING RESUMES OF FATHER-SON
BUSHES 
 By MILES BENSON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ As a potential president, George W. Bush's
credentials look strong -- until you compare them to his father's.
</P>
<P>
   When the senior Bush was elected president in 1988, at age 64,
he had already served eight years as vice president under Ronald
Reagan. Before that, Bush had been CIA director, ambassador to
China, U.N. ambassador, Republican National Committee chairman, a
member of Congress, a successful businessman and a Navy combat
pilot.
</P>
<P>
   His son, George W. Bush, 54, now in his sixth year as governor
of Texas, has never held any other public office.
</P>
<P>
   Though former President Bush does not generate the kind of
excitement, enthusiasm and veneration among converntion Republicans
of, say, a Ronald Reagan, party leaders have always argued that he
was uniquely qualified by experience to be president.
</P>
<P>
   The new Bush GOP presidential nominee has different strengths.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said he is well
satisfied with the younger Bush's qualifications, even if they are
not his dad's.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been governor of one of the largest states in the union
and he's been very successful at that,'' Hastert said. ``He's been
in the political arena his whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to compare the resumes of the two Bushes. Hastert said,
``It's all relative. I just think he (George W.) brings different
qualities. His father was never the governor of a state and had to
make those decisions and pass legislation and do all the things
that a governor has to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans acknowledge a big difference in experience
between the two Bushes, but do not necessarily regard that as a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody looks as good as Bush senior when you're comparing
resumes,'' said Rep. Tom Davis, R-Va. ``But a lot of Bush senior's
resume was in foreign policy, which didn't help him much in 1992,''
when voters denied him a second term and elected Democrat Bill
Clinton, Davis recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Cheney on the ticket, that neutralizes any concern about
experience,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was referring to Dick Cheney, Bush's choice for vice
president, a former defense secretary, White House chief of staff
and former member of Congress, seen by some as training wheels on
Bush's bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He conveys the image of a steady hand to help guide the
country,'' said independent pollster John Zogby.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John Engler, R-Mich., said the younger Bush's level of
experience to be president is ``comparable'' to Ronald Reagan, who
had served for eight years as governor of California.
</P>
<P>
   Governing a big state, making executive decisions, dealing with
budgets and legislatures, is good preparation for a future
president, in Engler's view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, you're not negotiating nuclear arms treaties, or trying
to broker peace among warring nations, and I'm not going to suggest
that being commander-in-chief of the Michigan national guard is
quite the same as being commander-in-chief of the United States,
but there are at least some experiences that have some
application,'' Engler said.
</P>
<P>
   Most governors are qualified to be president, claims Jim
Gilmore, Virginia's Republican chief executive. ``governors are in
the executive branch and therefore they are used to the exercise of
power and authority,'' Gilmore said.
</P>
<P>
   The qualifications required for presidents under the U.S.
Constitution are quite simple. Any natural-born citizen over the
age of 35, who has lived in the United States for 14 of those
years, is eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Zealous partisans brush aside the issue of the new presidential
candidate Bush's level of experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eisenhower was just a soldier. He didn't know diddly-squat
about welfare reform,'' said Laura Donahue, a GOP convention
delegate from Quincy, Ill., recalling President Dwight D.
Eisenhower, who served two White House terms, from 1952 to 1960.
``I just want somebody who will have honor and integrity and will
do what is good for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline Skurla, of Chudds Ford, Pa., the mother of three,
calls herself ``a supermarket Republican,'' who browses among
issues like a shopper buying groceries, likes the younger Bush but
does not think his record matches his father's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compare resumes?'' she laughed. ``Forget it. Hang up.''
</P>
<P>
   Independent experts acknowledge that the senior Bush's
qualifications list is more extensive than the son's, but question
whether it matters much.
</P>
<P>
   ``His father had enormous foreign policy experience, but very
little domestic political experience. He did not have the feel for
politics and, as a result, he made all kinds of mistakes,'' said
Karl Von Vorys, a political science professor at the University of
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush is quite the opposite,'' Von Vorys said. ``He
does not have all the credentials of his father. They are mostly
domestic and mostly political, negotiating and building coalitions.
That's what the younger Bush does well.''
</P>
<P>
   John Aldrich, a political scientist at Duke University, notes
that many of the senior Bush's important positions were appointive
posts, before he became president, while his son has twice won
election to a very important state-wide office.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the qualifications voters must compare are not Bush
vs. Bush, but Bush vs. Al Gore, the man he is running against, vice
president for the last eight years, who served in both the Senate
and House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question if you're simply talking about resumes, Al
Gore has a tremendous resume,'' said Vin Weber, a former Republican
congressman from Minnesota, and political adviser to Sen. John
McCain. ``I wouldn't begin to argue that Gore, whom I served with
and like as a person, is anything other than fully qualified to be
president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   But so is George W. Bush, ``who has risen to political
leadership in a big state, acquitted himself well, and assembled a
national campaign, which is not an absolute qualification for the
presidency,'' Weber said,''but if you can't assemble a national
campaign it's hard to say you could govern the country
successfully.''
</P>
<P>
   \roMDBO\ &UR; -(OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)\roMDNM\ &UR; -
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many Repuiblicans argue that their 2000 presidential
candidate is better qualified by sheer governing experience than
was President Bill Clinton when he was elected after serving as
governor of the much smaller state of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Still, late-night comedians continue to ridicule George W.
Bush's intellectual fire power.
</P>
<P>
   The nominee will have a chance to dispel any doubts about his
capacity to be president when he delivers his acceptance speech to
the convention Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Pollster Zogby said Bush does not need to be brilliant in his
appearance before a national TV audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's already won the affability war,'' Zogby said., ``People
tend to like him. Basically, he just has to read his speech and
stay standing up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1630EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
