u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-N     08-02 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE SHOPPING: BLEMISHED GOODS FOR BARGAIN HUNTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was common knowledge in the 1970s that my mother-in-law
trafficked in broken Godiva chocolates that she bought in unmarked
plastic bags at insanely low prices from an outlet store near her
home in Reading, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   She was the one to see if you wanted chipped dark chocolate
leaves, imperfect toffees or cracked pralines.
</P>
<P>
   Living at the epicenter of the outlet store revolution that
created a national obsession with blemished merchandise, she was
also known to lug home bags full of misshapen pretzels, sets of
dishes with the glaze marred by air bubbles and Izod shirts whose
alligators were missing part of a snout.
</P>
<P>
   But things went sour over the years as the nature of outlet
stores changed. These days you will not find much blemished
merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   (When I phoned Godiva's outlet store in Reading, the clerk who
answered said, ``Oh, no, Godiva does not sell anything
imperfect.'')
</P>
<P>
   Nor will you find my mother-in-law working the aisles in vain
pursuit of partial snouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outlets sort of killed themselves, because a lot of
manufacturers started to produce a separate lower budget line for
the outlets, and suddenly it wasn't so cheap anymore,'' said
professor Christina Lindholm, chairwoman of fashion design and
merchandising at Virginia Commonwealth University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen a genuine outlet in a long time selling stuff
that once had been full price, then got marked down, then became
truly a bargain,'' Lindholm said.
</P>
<P>
   Don't bother boarding a bus for a day trip. These days, the best
place to shop for old-fashioned, outlet-quality blemished bargains
is online, where a growing number of retailers are offering seconds
along with factory close-outs and severely marked-down examples of
first-quality items that failed to sell in a store.
</P>
<P>
   From panty hose with an imperfect seam at Onehanesplace.com to
baseball bats with a smudged label at Hq4sports.com to computer
monitors with a scratch on the case at Surplus-pc.com, you can find
examples of almost any category of (legal) merchandise simply by
typing ``blemished'' into a search-engine's query box.
</P>
<P>
   And according to online retailers who sell first-quality
merchandise along with blemished products, there is a growing
appetite among online shoppers for the slightly imperfect stuff if
it is offered at bargain prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually do more business on our seconds page than on our
regular site,'' said Steven Kundrat, who sells ethnic musical
instruments online at Mid-east.com.
</P>
<P>
   About 75 percent of the site's retail sales are of blemished
instruments, like the sitar with ``finish blemishes,'' priced at
$400 plus shipping (compared with $640 for one listed in perfect
condition).
</P>
<P>
   To anyone who lived through the golden age of outlets, the
popularity of blemished merchandise online should come as no
surprise. But there is an underlying reason for the enduring
allure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a country of great excess, in all things,'' Lindholm
said, ``and the American shopper is very much into quantity and
bargains and good deals.''
</P>
<P>
   But she added that ``many people will not spend very much on any
one thing, but overall will end up spending more money than if they
had just bought a single good-quality item that they needed.''
</P>
<P>
   That raises a philosophical question that has been nagging at me
since a certain weekend jaunt to Reading in the mid-1980s: Which is
better to own, a chipped example of an enormous blue enamel baking
dish that you don't need or a mint version of one you actually
wanted?
</P>
<P>
   ``A bargain is only a bargain if you need it and can use it,''
Lindholm said (nearly 15 years too late to help me, I might add).
</P>
<P>
   So if you troll for blemished merchandise online, you should
bear a few things in mind:
</P>
<P>
   _ Make sure you really need that extra pair of shoes from
Classicpumps.com or that book with a scuffed cover from
Bookzone.com or that dented wine rack from Wineracks-unlimited.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be fussy as you home in on your quarry. ``If you're going
through a bin,'' said Carol Davis, spokeswoman for
Onehanesplace.com, ``you can pick the thing up and say, `Do I
really want to live with this color?' But online you don't have
that luxury.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, many online retailers will pick through the
blemished items for you. ``We don't sell any marginal stuff because
of that,'' said Keith Richardson, owner of Sierratradingpost.com,
``and generally the response from customers once they get it is
that they can't even find the flaw.'' The company sells both
blemished and first-quality name-brand clothing at discounts that
typically range from 35 percent to 70 percent off retail.
</P>
<P>
   The company cuts out the labels from imperfect items from
manufacturers like L.L. Bean. ``They're very picky about what
merchandise is out there with their name on it,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buy only from sites that clearly describe the imperfection.
Sierratradingpost.com, for example, clearly explains the difference
between items described as overstocks and close-outs (``always
first quality'') and seconds (``cosmetic blemishes/irregular'').
</P>
<P>
   _ Before you buy, make sure the site posts a clear return
policy. And don't be afraid to ask questions, either by phone or
e-mail, before you purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to be sure they know what they're buying, so I
don't have a shopping basket on the site,'' said Kundrat of
Mid-eastcom. ``We like to talk to the customer on the phone before
they place the order.''
</P>
<P>
   I certainly learned my lesson with the enamel baking dish. I
won't buy any more imperfect merchandise unless it serves a
genuinely useful, practical purpose.
</P>
<P>
   And as for my mother-in-law, she went retail.
</P>
<P>
   Note to Godiva.com: We would both reconsider if you would.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
