<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0726 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX     08-02 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF RELIGIOUS BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Two Views of Hell'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Edward Fudge and Robert Peterson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (InterVarsity Press, $12.99) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Edward Fudge and Robert Peterson agree that there is a hell, and
that you certainly don't want to go there. But on this subject,
that constitutes most of the common ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two Views of Hell'' presents an evangelical debate on the fate
of the unrighteous: traditionalism (perpetual torment) vs.
conditionalism (eventual annihilation). Peterson, a St. Louis
seminary professor, stands on the former view; Fudge, a Houston
theologian and lawyer, makes the case for the latter. Both work to
build an argument based on Scripture.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict boils down to the concepts of ``death'' and
``everlasting destruction.'' Fudge sees both as essentially
extinction of existence. Peterson understands death as separation _
of the body from the soul (the end of earthly life) and of a person
from God (damnation, or the ``second death'').
</P>
<P>
   The dispute is sometimes sharp, although both authors subscribe
to a goal of courtesy in the debate. Peterson seems to get the best
of the battle, but Fudge may succeed in making readers think
twice. &QL; 
_ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtual Tibet, Searching for Shangri-La From the Himalayas to
Hollywood'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Orville Schell &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Metropolitan Books, $26) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tibet has always enchanted the Western mind. The accounts of a
handful of intrepid explorers have provided fodder for Hollywood's
creations of Shangri-La. And, no doubt, the frequent visits by the
Dalai Lama and other Tibetan teachers have had something to do with
the growing numbers of Americans turning to Tibetan Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
   Megabuck films, such as ``Seven Years in Tibet'' and ``Kundun,''
have fed us with lavish portrayals of Tibet's ancient splendor and
timeless mysteries. Movie stars such as Richard Gere have been been
influenced by Buddhism and have helped the Tibetan cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtual Tibet'' is a thoroughly absorbing examination of the
bizarre grip this little country exercises on the Western
imagination. It is written by one of the foremost China/Tibet
watchers of our times, Orville Schell, who has given us a book that
is entertaining and informative.
</P>
<P>
   Schell, who has visited and written about Tibet several times
since the 1980s, says that his captivation began at age 13, when he
read Heinrich Harrer's memoirs of the seven years he spent there as
the tutor of the child Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
   He traveled to Austria to interview Harrer in his later years.
Heinrich Harrer, it turns out, had a Nazi past. There are
fascinating portraits of various other personalities who have
helped to ignite the dreamlike image Americans have of Tibet,
including glimpses of His Holiness the 14th Dalai Lama, whose
earthy wisdom flies in the face of Beverly Hills'
pseudo-spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of the Hollywood groupies described in Schell's
insightful and lively book, readers are left with a clearer idea
about Tibetan fantasies and realities. &QL; 
_ Reviewed by Amrita Shlachter &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
