<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0728 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-BULLOCK03-COX     08-02 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-BULLOCK03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEMOCRAT'S WIDOW WILL INTRODUCE BUSHBy KEN HERMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ One goes out of his way to get along with people.
The other seemed to craft a successful career by figuring out how
not to get along with people.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow George W. Bush, the gregarious one, and Bob Bullock,
who thrived on closed-door confrontation, became fast friends.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, in the kind of bipartisan symbol coveted by the
Bush presidential campaign and more poignant to Texans that the
rest of the country will know, Jan Bullock, the widow of Democratic
Lt. Gov. Bullock, will introduce Bush as he accepts the GOP
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   It's a major step along a path predicted on June 20, 1996, by
Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he will be (president),'' he said that day, a propos
of nothing, as he joined Bush in the Senate chamber for the
swearing-in of state Sen. John Carona of Dallas. ``There's no other
governor in the country today that has the rapport with the
Legislature and with the people that I find George Bush has. He's
an extremely nice person and he's all Texan.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days short of three years later, Bullock died of congestive
heart failure and lung cancer as the Bush campaign took off, and
the Bullock prediction began to look prophetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting Governor Bush elected is unfinished business for
Bob,'' Jan Bullock said of her late husband, a crusty, insistent
man who didn't much care for unfinished business.
</P>
<P>
   She married Bob Bullock (20 years her senior and previously
married four times) at Austin's Green Pastures Restaurant in 1985.
She is an Austin native and University of Texas graduate. In
addition to her career as an interior designer and Realtor, Mrs.
Bullock has served on the Texas Historical Commission and been
active in projects of the State Preservation Board and Daughters of
the American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's speech is not Mrs. Bullock's first appearance
on the Bush presidential campaign trail. Back in March, when Bush
clinched the nomination, she was on the stage as he spoke to the
nation from his victory rally at the Dell Jewish Community Campus
in Northwest Austin.
</P>
<P>
   For the GOP, getting Bullock to speak is a coup for a party
eager to change its image and attract independent and Democratic
votes. Along the campaign trail, Bush frequently offers Bullock as
an example of his ability to cross party lines to get things done.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 40 years, including stints as secretary of state,
comptroller and lieutenant governor, Bullock was a force in the
Democratic Party, the only political show in town for most of his
life. Bush moved quickly after winning election in 1994 to find a
way to work with Bullock, who, as lieutenant governor, controlled
the flow of legislation in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   And through his decades in state government, Bullock had
developed a network of well-placed people positioned to kill
anything Bullock wanted dead. Bush quickly got the lay of the land
and visited Bullock at the lieutenant governor's home.
</P>
<P>
   To the consternation of many Texas Democrats, the Bush-Bullock
ties grew, both personally and politically. In 1998, Bullock
endorsed Bush for re-election over Democrat Garry Mauro, a longtime
Bullock friend and ally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish my old friend Lieutenant Governor Bob Bullock was here
to describe what it was like working with a newly-minted Republican
governor, because I can tell you what it was like working with a
tough old Democratic lieutenant governor,'' Bush told supporters
from around the nation in Austin last month. ``I learned a lot, but
both of us decided to put aside our partisan differences and work
for what was best for Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   At Bullock's request, Bush offered the eulogy at his friend's
funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was fearless, occasionally outrageous _ a neon personality
in a world of gray,'' Bush said of Bullock, who had survived
alcoholism, illness and four divorces.
</P>
<P>
   In his autobiography ``A Charge to Keep,'' published to coincide
with the presidential race, Bush recounted his final meeting with
Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, we wept together,'' Bush wrote. ``He was so proud,
so eager, so convinced that I had a great chance to be the next
president. He had told friends that he looked forward to watching
me take the oath of office. Bullock, a man who had lived for years
on his sheer strength of will, realized that if it happened he
would not be there to see it. If it happens, he will have been a
huge part of making it so.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman's e-mail address is kherman(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
