<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0731 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-HOLOCAUST-FOOTAGE-NEW     08-02 2391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-FOOTAGE-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLOCAUST FILM FOOTAGE DEFINES NOT ONLY THE EVENT, BUT OUR
RELATIONSHIP TO IT
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 2, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADVISORY: With a graphic of statistics on Holocaust archives
and five photos, of museum experts and panelists in group shot
(NNS1), concentration camp survivors in barracks (NNS2), Eisenhower
viewing bodies of executed prisoners (NNS3), American journalists
viewing corpses (NNS4) and surviving Jewish boy (NNS5) 
 By DELIA M. RIOS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Millions of stunned Americans got their first look
at the human devastation inside the Nazi death camps from newsreels
screened in their local movie theaters after the Allied invasion of
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   So that the atrocities could never be denied, Gen. Dwight D.
Eisenhower, the European Allied commander, insisted that military
cameramen document them in that spring of 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Americans know those haunting images so well that a single frame
of skeletal Jewish survivors is now cinematic shorthand for the
Holocaust. It is why Steven Spielberg could film his 1993
``Schindler's List'' in black and white, evoking the wartime
newsreels.
</P>
<P>
   Film defines our public memory of the Holocaust, and it is how
most of us initially encounter its horrors, whether through the
historical footage or the documentary and dramatic films that
footage has influenced. In fact, the word Holocaust -- a biblical
term for ``a burnt offering to God'' -- did not come into general
use until the airing of the 1978 television miniseries of the same
name.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this familiarity explains a commonly held belief that
the images speak for themselves. But do they?
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion of a panel of international scholars, simply put,
is no.
</P>
<P>
   They convened for two weeks at the U.S. Holocaust Memorial
Museum in late July, drawn by a shared belief that these images
would tell a story not only about the Holocaust, but of our
relationship to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Context is everything in Holocaust history, no matter the
medium,'' said Raye Farr, director of the museum's film and video
collections.
</P>
<P>
   The Nazis and European Jews intuitively understood the power of
images, and deliberately created visual records of the events that
consumed them more than 50 years ago. Yet few scholars have given
critical thought to the original footage or to the films that
followed.
</P>
<P>
   The slaughter of 6 million Jews -- two-thirds of Europe's Jewish
population -- is paramount to us today. But as the war in Europe
ended, their deaths were not singled out. It wasn't until the
mid-1970s that the Holocaust assumed cultural prominence. Survivors
began to speak publicly, and movies and museums followed. Along the
way, ambiguities receded behind moral absolutes.
</P>
<P>
   Film, to a great degree, influenced those developments. But only
a handful of scholars have wondered why or how.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Shandler, who has written about television's portrayal
of the Holocaust, chronicled how the footage came to be regarded as
privileged and unimpeachable. The film bore witness to heinous
crimes and so, as Shandler explained, ``It does not invite
questioning.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas Doherty of Brandeis University's Film Studies Program
believes that deference is misplaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your respect for the event has to include a demand for
historical integrity,'' Doherty said.
</P>
<P>
   The need for vigilance is underscored by a still photograph that
very nearly made its way into the Holocaust Museum. It was
purported to be an image of actual events, but was discovered to be
from a postwar movie about the concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   A 1992 public television documentary about black American
soldiers as camp liberators is another argument for scrutiny. The
film relied heavily on personal recollections. But survivor
testimony and the documentation do not always match, leading
scholars to suggest that some survivors confused historical footage
seen over the years with their personal memories -- a reminder of
just how deeply those newsreels have seeped into the public
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Images, especially in the computer era, are malleable. If they
are manipulated and misused, historical accuracy degrades and opens
the door to the denial that Eisenhower feared.
</P>
<P>
   Asking questions about the images is a way to ensure their
integrity, but the central truth of the Holocaust provides the
framework.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to the Holocaust, although interpretation of
information may differ, the facts are indisputable,'' said
Alexander B. Rossino of the museum's Center for Advanced Holocaust
Studies, which brought the scholars together. ``It happened in a
certain way, it happened to certain people, and the killing
procedures were carried out with certain methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important that we maintain a firm grasp of the
facts,'' Rossino said, ``and to accept that they exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Another panelist, Dutch filmmaker and historian Chris Vos, was
struck by how Americans not only have embraced that truth, but
imprinted the Holocaust story with their own values and lessons. As
Shandler put it, there is a sense of catharsis, of being a better
person morally for having seen Holocaust footage.
</P>
<P>
   This imprint extends beyond American borders through television
and movies,and is so pervasive that scholars speak of the
``Americanization'' of the Holocaust. American captivation with the
subject is visible every day in the lines of people outside the
Holocaust Museum; 14.4 million have walked through the doors since
they opened in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a remarkable, perhaps singular phenomenon. ... The
Holocaust touched only a small number of Americans directly ... yet
the Holocaust looms large in the American moral landscape, where it
has become commonplace to articulate the high magnitude of a social
wrong by deeming it `another Holocaust,''' Shandler wrote in
``While America Watches: Televising the Holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel of seven, headed by Doherty, joined the museum's own
historians and film experts each day to view films made between
1933 and 1985, including Nazi propaganda, U.S. Army Signal Corps
footage of the concentration camps, and both wartime and postwar
dramas and documentaries.
</P>
<P>
   As Michael Hoffman, an English professor from the University of
California at Davis, observed of one film, ``We are here analyzing
it as if it were a great poem.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in a sense, that is what they did.
</P>
<P>
   They compared, for instance, the ending of ``Schindler's List''
with that of ``Shoah,'' the 91/2-hour 1985 documentary whose name
means ``Holocaust'' in Hebrew. Spielberg's movie ends with a scene
in Israel, leaving viewers with the sense of something vital and
hopeful being created out of persecution and destruction. But there
is no redemption at the end of ``Shoah,'' no happy ending for
viewers to take home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're supposed to ponder what's missing,'' Rossino said.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists carefully decoded images, identifying one woman in a
French documentary as a Nazi collaborator -- although some
initially mistook her for a camp survivor because of her shaved
head, a punishment imposed on collaborators. And they took note of
an early tendency in postwar films not to identify the victims of
the Nazis as Jews. As Vos explained of Dutch filmmakers, ``They
didn't want to do that, to do the same as the Germans by setting
apart the Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   Doherty wondered about the use of silence in some of the films
-- on what Vos called the film's ``soundscape.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think of film as having so much of an aural component, but
we have very little of what the Holocaust sounded like,'' Doherty
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rossino described the panel's task this way: ``We're dealing
with history and evidence, and the reconstruction of that evidence
into a memory.''
</P>
<P>
   In the language of Holocaust scholars, that includes
``perpetrator images'' -- Nazi film and photographs. The bulk of
the museum's Poland, for example, were taken by the Nazis. They are
part of the historical record, Rossino said, ``whether we like it
or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The repulsion still felt for Nazi images influenced video
exhibits in the museum itself.
</P>
<P>
   David Thaxton, whose company created those videos, refrained
from using footage of ``Triumph of the Will,'' a 1935 Nazi
propaganda movie, to depict the Nazi rise to power. Doherty asked
why.
</P>
<P>
   Thaxton replied that, ``in the heart of this institution,'' to
do so would be ``morally reprehensible.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the panel's analysis only reaffirmed the power of
what Doherty calls ``perhaps the most horrifying footage of the
20th century.'' Near the end of their two weeks, he encouraged
guest speakers to fast-forward through the most gruesome frames,
saying, ``We've seen enough.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rossino was shaking off nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   He'd been unable to get out of his mind's eye the faces of Jews
forcibly crowded into the Warsaw Ghetto -- recorded by German
filmmakers before the Jews were deported to Treblinka, a Nazi
extermination camp in Poland. The panel had listened several days
earlier to a chilling account of that camp in ``Shoah.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The stink was carried on the wind,'' a former Nazi officer
told director Claude Lanzmann, describing mass graves up to 20 feet
deep. ``The brass was in a rush to clean out the Warsaw Ghetto.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, President Jimmy Carter created the Holocaust Commission
that led to the building of the museum within sight of the
Washington Monument, ``to ensure that we in the United States never
forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Remembering requires a story, and Eisenhower's order to turn the
camera on the camps imposed a narrative that persists. Shandler,
who briefly joined the panel for its deliberations, explained how
the liberation footage was perceived as a ``virtual witness of mass
death.'' Its viewers became witnesses. And Americans began to
attach a moral value to that.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Signal Corps and commercial newsreel cameramen
documented the horrors of the camps not only for American viewers,
but for future war crime trials -- such as the one held at
Nuremberg and dramatized recently in the TNT miniseries of the same
name.
</P>
<P>
   Germans were compelled to watch the films to confront their
individual and collective guilt, said panelist Susan Carruthers of
the University of Wales. There is even film of shaken Germans
leaving movie theaters. And, as Germany fell, the films were potent
evidence for the Allies of their moral superiority.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers have recycled this footage ever since, and often
without explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Carruthers, a cultural historian, spoke of the ``profound
afterlife of the footage taken in 1945.'' The films, she said, can
perpetuate ``things that we think we know about the Holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   There is the myth, for one, that the corpses of Jewish prisoners
were used to make soap. ``Never been proven,'' Rossino said. The
myth's origins, Vos explained, were in World War I Allied
propaganda that the Germans made soap out of dead battlefield
horses. Ironically, rumors of World War II atrocities were
initially dismissed, in part because the first war's stories were
so exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   The adaptation of historical footage for television and the
movies can create what Rossino calls a strange mix of confusion and
clarity. An Allied documentary on the Nazi concentration camps, for
instance, was shown during the war crimes trial at Nuremberg. That
footage was seen again in a 1950s teleplay about the trial, and
then again in TNT's ``Nuremberg.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossino's trained eye easily distinguishes between images shot
in different camps. But ordinary viewers are left to assume that
they depict a particular place. So while the television
dramatizations accurately used the footage shown at Nuremberg, the
images themselves left a misimpression. That may seem like a fine
point, but it clouds the historical accuracy of events that occupy
a sacred place in our memory.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Just as important as what the films show, Shandler argues, is
what has been edited out.
</P>
<P>
   The screened newsreel footage was only a fraction of what was
shot, and it was subject to both military censors and the
commercial sensibilities of film producers. The selected images
``reflect an agenda to depict Nazi atrocities at their most
thorough, extensive and graphic,'' Shandler wrote.
</P>
<P>
   And that, he believes, was at a cost to the survivors' humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Missing, Shandler wrote, were newsreel scenes of ``survivors as
striving to resume active lives, caring for themselves, expressing
religious, political and national identities, assisting in the
documentation of the atrocities committed by their former
persecutors, or paying homage to fellow inmates who did not
survive.''
</P>
<P>
   The narration of one early newsreel had admonished viewers:
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't turn away -- look!''
</P>
<P>
   So many Holocaust films have been made since that some panelists
argued that they comprise a separate film genre. At the very least,
they reveal our continuing compulsion to confront the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Panelist David Brenner, of Kent State University's Ethnic
Heritage and Jewish Studies Program, commented during one session
on director Lanzmann's technique in ``Shoah.'' Lanzmann, long past
the point of comfortable silences during interviews, allowed the
camera to linger on his subjects. The camera held steady even on a
camp survivor struggling for composure, as she bit her lip and
gazed into the distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suffer with her,'' Hoffman, the UC-Davis scholar, observed.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Brenner explained as well as anyone why we, like the
camera, can't look away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the person's face long enough, you'll get it,''
he said quietly. ``If you just stare long enough, you'll get it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
