<HEADLINE>
RELIGION SHAPES BELIEVING TEENS' LIVES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By TARA DOOLEY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Even for a 12-year-old, God looms large in
daily life.
</P>
<P>
   Take Malcolm White.
</P>
<P>
   Before dinner, Malcolm thanks God in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   He reaches out to God for inspiration before a difficult test.
</P>
<P>
   He has stayed awake wondering about topics discussed during
worship services at Christ Chapel Bible Church in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   He has even, on occasion, asked for a little help on the ball
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play first base,'' said Malcolm, a seventh-grader. ``If I
know there is a lefty who pulls toward me, maybe I'll sneak in a
little prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Gratitude, inspiration and divine intervention may seem like
heady concerns for a small boy with sandy blond hair that peeks out
from under a baseball cap, but they are among the considerations
that occupy Malcolm, he said. God is the primary guide in his life,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aside from my parents, God is the main factor,'' he said.
``Even with my parents, God is the main factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Malcolm may be an unusual 12-year-old in the earnestness
with which he expresses the convictions of his faith. But he is
certainly not alone in considering faith important in his youthful
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I think without religion, I would be lost,'' said
16-year-old Omair Peracha, who attends prayers and religious
education classes at the Islamic Association of Mid-Cities in
Hurst, a Fort Worth suburb. ``I don't know what it would feel like
not having Islam as a belief system.''
</P>
<P>
   Faith is a matter of ultimate importance for believing teens,
they say. And their religious institutions become places where they
find responsibility, acceptance and comfort, teens say.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of religious institutions for believing teens
surprised author Laura Sessions Stepp as she followed 18 teens for
her book ``Our Last Best Shot: Guiding Our Children Through Early
Adolescence.''
</P>
<P>
   In observing teens from throughout the country _ 12 of whom she
wrote about _ Stepp discovered that it was often at religious
institutions that children found adults who listened with both
ears. These were adults who did not judge the teens and were free
from domestic distractions such as grocery bills, spouse trouble
and daily chores, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Religious institutions also encouraged teens to undertake
meaningful work, at soup kitchens or housing projects, for example.
And they were given positions of respect in choirs and
responsibility as event organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Religious organizations also encouraged teens to explore big
topics, such as life, death and their role in it all.
</P>
<P>
   Religion ``was a platform on which they could discuss issues
very close to their hearts with adults who took time to listen,''
said Stepp, who writes about family issues for The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can be the dumbest person on the Earth and still come here,
and it doesn't matter,'' 12-year-old Caroline Disney said of the
middle school Bible study she attends with Malcolm at Christ Chapel
Bible Church.
</P>
<P>
   Churches, mosques or temples were not the only places
adolescents found such guidance, support and encouragement, Stepp
said. But religious institutions were the places it occurred most
regularly, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Religious youth groups can also be simply the source of a good
time, teens say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a lot of fun,'' said 17-year-old Sarah Rousch, an
officer in the Fort Worth Federation of Temple Youth, a group of
teens associated with Congregation Beth-El in Fort Worth. ``It's
not all religious.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to pool parties, Rousch includes cleaning food
pantries and sorting clothing for shelters as part of the fun.
</P>
<P>
   But faith is important to 14-year-old Jaclyn Jones, although the
Weatherford teen does not count herself among the most pious
members of her synagogue, Congregation Beth-El.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider myself really, really religious, but when I'm
in trouble I always turn to God,'' Jaclyn said.
</P>
<P>
   When discussing theology, Jaclyn said she often turns to her
best friend, a Baptist, finding similarities and differences in
each faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both kind of agree that you should believe what you feel in
your heart is true and what rings true to you, and that helps us
get along a lot better,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At religious education classes, Jaclyn learns many of the values
that shape her life, as well as the history and traditions of the
Jewish people _ lessons that taught her to feel proud of her faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only 14, and I'm still trying to establish what faith
means to me,'' Jaclyn said. ``I think people should establish for
themselves what they believe in. They have that right. ... But I
think it would be hard to have nothing to believe in. It must be
hard to live.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
