<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERSHIP OF FALUN GONG MOVEMENT IS DISPUTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ Falun Gong followers in Hong Kong and the
United States are squabbling over claims by a woman in the southern
Chinese territory that she is the ``true Master'' of the spiritual
movement, having taken over from its founder, Li Hongzhi, who has
dropped from view.
</P>
<P>
   The power struggle is a potentially important one for Falun
Gong, which drew millions of adherents in the late 1990s, because
most of its followers are on the Chinese mainland, across the
border from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong, a former British colony, reverted to Chinese rule in
1997. Whoever controls the group there has a chance of influencing
Falun Gong's development in the rest of China.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, the recent revelation that matronly 37-year-old
Belinda Pang is the ``Lord of Buddhas'' has led to more of a cat
fight than catharsis for the movement, which went underground on
the mainland after Beijing banned the group a year ago. Li, who now
is based in New York, and Pang have traded accusations on competing
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The episode began on May 11 _ celebrated as Buddha's birthday
and, according to Li, his birthday as well (though birth records in
Li's hometown in China show otherwise). Pang, who had become a
tireless organizer in Falun Gong's Hong Kong chapter, organized a
march through the city to commemorate the day.
</P>
<P>
   Although only two dozen people turned up, most of them said they
had experienced a vision of Pang seated in outer space while angels
flew around her plucking flowers and dropping them to Earth. The
flowers turned into raindrops when they hit the skin, according to
Mary Qian, one of the people who saw the apparition.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when we realized Ms. Pang was the Lord of Buddhas,''
Qian said by telephone Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   They announced the revelation on the Web site,
www.falundafa.com.hk.
</P>
<P>
   Li was quick to denounce Pang on Falun Gong's official web site
(www.minghui.ca), calling her ``a vile person'' suffering ``demonic
interference from her own mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Pang retorted by saying all recent messages from Li are fakes
because he has left the affairs of men to ``quietly watch
practitioners and people in the world'' from his perch on a cliff
somewhere in the United States, where he is pictured sitting on a
pillow in his last photograph posted on Falun Gong's Web site in
January.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Pang has only drawn about 30 hard-core believers. But,
Qian says people will slowly recognize Pang for what she is.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jesus appeared, how many people believed him?'' she
asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
