<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0743 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HTHOMASCOLUMN8/2-HNS &LR;      08-02 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HTHOMASCOLUMN8/2-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
VOTERS WILL HAVE A CLEAR CHOICE IN NOVEMBER &HT;    By HELEN THOMAS
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Make no mistake about it: American voters will
have a clear-cut choice in the presidential election in November.
They will have to decide whether they want to turn the country to
the conservative right or continue on the current path of moderate
liberalism.
</P>
<P>
   In the leadup to the fall campaign, the Republican National
Convention has provided a choreographed showcase for Texas Gov.
George W. Bush to present the Republican Party as one big happy
family, marching in lockstep in what it hopes will be a parade to
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The beatific facade may just work for the Republicans because
the ultra conservatives in the party have decided for the sake of
unity and the chance of victory to play ball with the man they
think can return them to power.
</P>
<P>
   The rightwingers of the party, however, did not have to swallow
everything to give Bush a chance to steal a page from President
Clinton's playbook and move to the middle. They were mollified by
the party's platform that would ban all abortions _ with no
exceptions for the life of the mother, incest or rape. And the
platform continues its hard line against any federal legal
protection of homosexuals against discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   As famed football coach Vince Lombardi used to say, ``Winning
isn't everything _ it's the only thing.'' Following that credo, the
uncompassionate conservatives _ assuming they are to the right of
Bush's self-identified ``compassionate conservatives'' _ have
pulled in their horns and decided that winning the White House is
more important than squabbling over issues. All is sweetness and
light in the City of Brotherly Love _ so much so that Ben
Kachigian, a master strategist of past Republican conventions is in
awe.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also won points with the conservatives by picking former
Defense Secretary Richard Cheney, a multimillionaire from the oil
services industry, to be his running mate. Cheney's record of
conservative votes in Congress appears extremist _ much more
conservative than the views of President George Bush who chose
Cheney to be secretary of defense.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bush and his tightly-knit Texas team planned the
Philadelphia convention down to the minutes allotted each speaker.
They wanted no surprises and used an iron fist in a velvet glove to
get their way on everything. Discussing the lack of controversy and
confrontation that sometimes marred past conventions, Ken
Kachigian, former speechwriter and adviser to President Richard M.
Nixon, said on CNN that Nixon ``would have been impressed by the
control. He would have been envious.''
</P>
<P>
   Governor Bush has learned from the past. He did not want to
repeat the mistakes made at the 1992 GOP convention in Houston
where strident speeches by conservatives Marilyn Quayle and Patrick
Buchanan helped doom his father's reelection chances. Quayle told
the party faithful in Houston that not everyone in the sixties
``demonstrated, dropped out, took drugs, joined in the sexual
revolution or dodged the draft.'' Buchanan told the delegates that
there was a ``religious war going on for the soul of America, a
cultural war critical to the kind of nation we will be.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of challenging language is missing in this convention,
where harmony is the theme.
</P>
<P>
   Parents are usually more conservative than their children, but
the opposite appears to be true in the Bush family. The Texas
governor has taken a rigid anti-abortion stand compared with that
of his mother, Barbara. Mrs. Bush refused to reveal her position on
the touchy subject when she was first lady, but right after she
left the White House, she promptly revealed her view that abortion
was a private matter between a woman and her physician.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's wife, Laura, refuses to disclose how she feels
about abortion, leading to speculation that she probably disagrees
with her husband on the subject that preoccupied the GOP candidates
throughout the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bush seems to have missed his father's interest _
and ability _ in foreign affairs. But not to worry. He said he will
rely on ``good advisers,'' referring to the impressive big names he
has assembled from the Reagan and Bush eras who are waiting for
their second acts.
</P>
<P>
   When I looked at his biography for evidence of preparation for
the presidency, I found hardly anything in his past that reflected
a driving interest in public service until he suddenly made an
unsuccessful run for Congress in 1978. After hobnobbing with Texas
pols in that race, and later assisting his father in his vice
presidential and presidential campaigns, Bush was able to sharpen
his own political skills. For example, when he made that run for
Congress from West Texas, Bush was defeated by state senator Kent
Hance who portrayed himself as a ``good `ol boy'' populist
candidate. After that, Bush vowed that he would never be
``out-countrified'' again.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, when he was running against Sen. John McCain
of Arizona in the Republican primaries, Bush soon figured out that
his aloofness toward reporters was getting him nowhere and getting
McCain everywhere. So Bush began to cozy up to the traveling
reporters, charming them with his friendliness, backslapping and
anointing them with nicknames.
</P>
<P>
   It worked, guaranteeing Bush media exposure as a likeable
fellow, given to banter with reporters. As one explained,``Who
wants to pass up a chance to talk to a future president?''
</P>
<P>
   In a year when the public has tuned out the campaign because the
nation is at peace and the economy is strong, Bush's ``likability''
may be his biggest plus. Al Gore, by contrast, is aloof and
reserved. But he is an expert on national issues by virtue of his
years in Congress and his eight years as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   When the voters begin to buckle down and really focus on the
election issues, they will see big philosophical and political
differences between the two parties. And that will give them a
clear-cut choice.
</P>
<P>
   (Helen Thomas can be contacted at 202-298-6920 or via e-mail:
Helent(at)Hearstdc.com)
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
