<SLUG> BC-GOP-FORD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-PRESIDENT FORD HOSPITALIZED AFTER TWO MINOR STROKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By DANIEL J. WAKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Former President Gerald Ford suffered two minor
strokes and was hospitalized early Wednesday morning, hours after
suffering dizziness and slurred speech at the Republican National
Convention, doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, 87, first went to Hahnemann University Hospital after
leaving the convention, where he had been honored in an emotional
tribute. He was misdiagnosed with a sinus infection and released.
Hours later, he returned with additional symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, the former president was in the hospital's
intensive care unit and underwent an MRI scan that showed he had
suffered two small strokes in the last two days, said Dr. Robert J.
Schwartzman, the hospital's head of neurology.
</P>
<P>
   There was no apparent brain damage, the doctor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing well,'' Schwartzman said. ``He's perfectly awake, a
little weak in the left arm and a little unbalanced.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor said the stroke occurred ``mainly in his balance
center in the back of his brain.'' When asked about possible brain
damage, he said, ``I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford would be in the hospital five to six days, Schwartzman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford first went to the hospital around midnight Tuesday, and he
was given an antibiotic for a sinus infection and released. Calvin
McDowell, a spokesman for Ford, had said a wax build-up had led to
the infection.
</P>
<P>
   Ford left the hospital at 1:36 a.m. with his wife, Betty. ``I
feel good, that's why I'm here,'' Ford said as he climbed into his
car.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, Ford asked to be taken back to the hospital after
complaining of feeling ``uncomfortable, McDowell said. The former
president walked in, after refusing a wheelchair, McDowell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just thought we had a routine sinus infection, but then he
had other problems and he was brought back,'' McDowell said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford appeared frail as he sat in a VIP box at the back of the
First Union Center on Tuesday night along with his wife, former
President George Bush, former first lady Barbara Bush and other
prominent Republicans. He was visibly moved when a video-taped
tribute to him was displayed on the large screens inside the hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``When uncertainty troubled our nation, President Gerald Ford
renewed America's confidence,'' Gov. George Pataki of New York
said, introducing the tribute. ``His strength, his strength and
integrity defended our values at home in an ever-changing world.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd cheered when Pataki invoked ``President Ford's steady
leadership and Mrs. Ford's gentle grace.''
</P>
<P>
   He rose and waved to acknowledge the cheers of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Ford did not address the convention, and told C-Span that this
would be the last convention he and his wife would attend, calling
it a ``concluding appearance to indicate our support.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his health in an interview Tuesday night on
CNN's ``Larry King Live,'' the former president said, ``I couldn't
be healthier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0748 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-DUES-GAME-NYT &LR;      08-02 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DUES-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FREE-SPIRITED PLAY, A DEPARTED SPIRIT LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER OLAFSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ghost of Looking Glass Studios hovers about me as I explore
Deus Ex. The specter of that celebrated game developer, which
closed its doors in May, whispers in my ear as the story folds
conspiracy upon conspiracy. It cackles softly as I fumble for
equipment to master the game's electronic locks and struggle to
recall passwords. It curls about my ankles like an unseen cat as I
stand in darkness and debate my next direction. I have many choices
and, in most of them, the ghost follows close upon my heels.
</P>
<P>
   Looking Glass did not participate in the design of Deus Ex, an
action and role-playing game that was developed by Ion Storm in
Austin, Texas. But the producer of Deus Ex, Warren Spector, worked
on Looking Glass' two Ultima Underworld games, System Shock and
Thief, and he appears to have brought to this new game the restless
spirit and the delightful sense of freedom associated with that
studio's best work.
</P>
<P>
   The appearance of Deus Ex within weeks of Looking Glass'
shutting down had the feel of an epitaph. But it is a grand,
poignant epitaph that pays a compliment both to the Looking Glass
legacy and to the skill of Spector and his team.
</P>
<P>
   Computer and video games tend to slide into the nearest
convenient hole. Although the details vary, you can reasonably
predict that a role-playing game will be driven by relentless
combat. An adventure game will unfold a story in puzzles. An action
game will send you out to kill.
</P>
<P>
   Looking Glass games were different. Beginning with the Ultima
Underworld games in the early 1990s, Looking Glass consistently
expanded the boundaries of the genres in which it worked. Terra
Nova: Strike Force Centauri was one of the first 3-D games to offer
squad-based combat. Even when Looking Glass spread its wings and
delved into unfamiliar genres _ flight simulation, with the Flight
Unlimited series, and sports, with British Open Championship Golf _
it did so with panache. The flight simulators were written for
passengers as much as for pilots and the golf game had wonderful
crowds.
</P>
<P>
   But Looking Glass found its true calling in its 3-D
action-adventure games. Games like System Shock, Thief: The Dark
Project and their recent sequels belonged to no single genre. They
were action, role-playing and adventure games living under one
roof, mingled so closely that you could not easily tell where one
genre left off and the next began.
</P>
<P>
   The result was the purest, freest kind of play, unhindered by
categories, rules or expectations and, finally, not even by the
machine on which it operated. (Looking Glass Games always seemed to
hover in the ether between the player and the screen.) The typical
measures of role-playing games _ the experience points and
character statistics _ became irrelevant as you effectively became
the on-screen character. Just as the genres melted into one
another, the player melted into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to Deus Ex. Set in a plague-ravaged world, the
game casts you as a technologically augmented agent named J.C.
Denton, who is working for a United Nations anti-terrorist unit.
The story laid out for him at the end of the first of 15 missions
sounds like a paranoid's nightmare. (The government started the
plague for population control. The Trilateral Commission is behind
a secret government. I am just waiting for a reference to black
helicopters.) The paranoia gains in strength and resonance as the
game progresses. Soon enough, you will not know what to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Like its Looking Glass antecedents, Deus Ex presents the player
with a wide range of fascinating and well-distributed tasks. It is
pleasantly, albeit sinisterly, full of alternate approaches, things
to do and things to find and use. It never does the same thing for
too long and thus never allows you to grow weary with a single
conceit.
</P>
<P>
   There are newspapers to be read, locked doors to be unlocked,
characters to be questioned (and re-questioned). There are people
to shoot, and people to avoid. There are enhancements to bestow
upon your character. There are experiments to perform with exotic
inventory items. There are computers to be hacked. There are
out-of-the-way places to be explored (with attached
experience-point bonuses).
</P>
<P>
   The twist in Deus Ex is the psychological state of the player.
In the Looking Glass games, your actions were always imbued with
purpose, but in Deus Ex, they come to be imbued with doubt. After
an initial aggressive foray up a headless and torchless Statue of
Liberty, I found myself growing steadily more tentative, shocking
enemies into unconsciousness instead of shooting them, asking
questions first and paying more attention to who I wanted my
character to be than to what he could do. Almost without knowing
it, I had slipped into his skin.
</P>
<P>
   These are a few of my favorite things. It is not the end of the
list, and I am not even sure that I can make a list. I can't begin
to remember all the loose ends I want to follow up _ missions are
still tugging at my cuffs, begging to be replayed in different
fashion _ and I have no doubt that there are other, looser ends I
will discover if I look long enough and hard enough.
</P>
<P>
   Deus Ex is not quite perfect. It lacks some of the sense of
balance and grace of the Looking Glass games, and since it is
spread over disparate levels around the world, it lacks some of the
wholeness of being sited in a single ominous place. But its open
structure and varied play should serve to encourage movement toward
games that are less defined by genre and more by immersiveness and
fun. At the very least, it should help foster a fertile climate for
coming transgenre efforts like Loose Cannon, an action-driving
game; Giants: Citizen Kabuto, an action-strategy game; and Oni, an
action-fighting game. Then again, playing mix-and-match with genres
can be risky. In 1997 and 1998, two action-strategy hybrids,
Uprising and Battlezone, garnered much critical acclaim but failed
to capture the public imagination.
</P>
<P>
   If Deus Ex is a hit, Looking Glass will not be around to
celebrate. But its reflection lingers.
</P>
<P>
   (Deus Ex, developed by Ion Storm; published by Eidos Interactive
for Windows 95 and 98, $39.95; published by Aspyr for Macintosh 8.1
and later, $49.95; for players 17 and older.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
