<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0749 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-SELLERS-AR     08-02 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SELLERS-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE SELLERS VULNERABLE TO CREDIT CARD FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By LISA GUERNSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Connie Bacon, a regular seller on eBay, thought that she had
brokered an excellent deal. On behalf of a consignment shop in
Charleston, S.C., she had sold a Rolex watch for $13,500 in an
online auction, and everything had gone smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   A man who identified himself as Kelvin Johanis had put the money
in an escrow account, assuring Bacon that the payment was good, and
the shopkeeper had shipped the package to a house specified by the
buyer in Lynwood, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, Bacon got an urgent e-mail message from
I-Escrow, the company holding the payment. I-Escrow said the buyer
was suspected of using a stolen credit card. Please, the message
pleaded, do not ship the watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shaking,'' Bacon said. ``This was a $13,500 watch that
wasn't mine.''
</P>
<P>
   She had good reason to be concerned. Online sellers are even
more vulnerable to fraud than online buyers, experts say. Those who
buy faulty or fake goods through online auctions or Web shops have
some recourse; insurance programs and credit-card companies will
often come to their rescue and credit their accounts, at least up
to a certain amount.
</P>
<P>
   But individuals who are selling goods in online auctions have
little protection. Stolen credit cards, fake money orders and
bounced checks are risks they face. For them, the adage is turned
on its head: Seller beware.
</P>
<P>
   In Bacon's case, she was not the only Ebay seller who did
business with the person who called himself Johanis. His real name
was Michael Prime, according to court documents, and he turned out
to be a 19-year-old unemployed high school graduate in Brier, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   According to I-Escrow's investigators (informally known as the
fraud squad), Prime had opened 25 accounts on the I-Escrow system
and had been in contact with at least nine sellers. He had used
stolen credit cards to get almost $20,000 worth of merchandise,
including laptop computers, other Rolex watches and three
remote-controlled scale-model helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   When people worry about fraud in online auctions, they do not
usually think about buyers like Prime. They assume that they are
most likely to be deceived by sellers _ particularly by people
hawking counterfeit or broken merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is really not true,'' said Dr. Audri Lanford, a
sociologist and editor of an e-mail newsletter, Scambusters.org.
``Fraud is a huge issue, but it is from the seller's perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, online sellers are 1O to 18 times as likely as bricks
and mortar merchants to lose merchandise to people using stolen
credit cards, according to a survey by the Gartner Group, a market
research company. The survey, which was released in July and polled
166 retailers, showed that 1.13 percent of all online transactions
were conducted with stolen cards.
</P>
<P>
   Once online sellers accept a stolen card, they often find that
the credit card company is of no help. Under federal law, the owner
of the credit card would not have to pay for those items. The
credit card companies do not have to cover the cost either; they
are only liable for the purchases if the seller received a
signature from the card holder. So the seller bears the cost and
will never be paid.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, that might not have sounded like an issue for
consumers to worry about. But now, with auction sites like those
offered by eBay, Yahoo and Amazon.com, consumers can be sellers as
easily as they can be buyers. Today, millions of people are selling
goods online, with no background in running a business and none of
the resources used by traditional businesses if things go awry.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, most individuals selling through online auctions
have not been able to accept credit cards and have had to worry
only about bounced checks. But this spring, the introduction of
credit-card services like Billpoint have made it possible for
anyone _ even someone selling one item _ to take credit cards
online. Now people who have no business savvy, and who may simply
be selling miscellaneous items to clean out their basements, are
vulnerable to the same credit card fraud that is plaguing online
merchants.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon, an antique-glassware trader who can often be spotted on
eBay under the name GrayHorse, was an experienced online auctioneer
when she decided to help a consignment shop sell the Rolex last
summer. She had already run into only a few problems, mainly with
buyers who retracted their bids. But she still was not prepared
when she heard that sellers she was acting for had been defrauded
by Prime. ``I felt very violated,'' she said. ``It made me very
angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime, it turned out, was doing more than simply using stolen
credit cards. Those involved with the case say that he is a whiz
with computers, though he has little education beyond high school.
His lawyer, Tim Tesh, described his client as ``one of these
self-taught kids who can just pick it up.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   According to I-Escrow, Prime first registered for accounts using
stolen cards in July 1999. But I-Escrow detected that the accounts
were based on stolen cards and quickly canceled them.
</P>
<P>
   So Prime tried to get around the system. According to I-Escrow,
he told sellers that he wanted to use I-Escrow and would start the
process of setting up accounts. But instead of completing the
transaction through the escrow service, officials said, Prime would
close the deal by pretending to be an escrow agent and sending
messages from ``I(underscore)Escrow(at)Hotmail.com,'' an e-mail
address that looked a lot like I-Escrow's official messages, which
end with ``IEscrow.com.'' Using that disguise, he told sellers that
the money had been deposited and that they should go ahead and ship
their items.
</P>
<P>
   The first person to be deceived, I-Escrow said, was a
Bellingham, Wash., man who was selling a Macintosh Powerbook G3 in
July 1999.
</P>
<P>
   According to I-Escrow's records, he also purchased two
remote-controlled helicopters and two Rolex watches a week later
using fake e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   But one other case involving a remote-controlled helicopter
worked a little differently. The seller, Bobby DeRosa, was a Web
designer in San Diego, and Prime did not try to use a fake e-mail
address. Instead, I-Escrow said, he used a credit card that had not
yet been listed by banks as stolen and then asked DeRosa to direct
the shipment to an address that was different from the one on the
card.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of July, I-Escrow had been tipped off by the seller
of the Apple computer, who had checked the company's Web site to
view his account's status and had been baffled to find that the
transaction was listed as ``still pending.'' He forwarded to
I-Escrow the fake message that included the real shipping address:
14501 Highway 99 in Lynwood, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   I-Escrow officials called the sheriff's office there, in
Snohomish County. A detective, Matt Trafford, drove to the address
on Highway 99, a four-lane commercial road, and found what looked
like an abandoned house that had been ``sitting there rotting for
years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the house, Trafford said, he found credit card receipts
and registration papers for a nearby storage business.
</P>
<P>
   Trafford wanted to be waiting when the next shipment was
delivered to the house. He asked I-Escrow if its records showed
another shipment. Yes, it looked as though another Rolex watch was
about to be purchased, from an eBay seller in South Carolina:
Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   This was the same week that Bacon received that urgent e-mail
message telling her not to ship the watch. The minute she saw that
message, Bacon had called the consignment shop but had discovered,
to her dismay, that the watch had already been packed and delivered
to the post office. ``I called the post office,'' she said, and
found to her relief that the package was still there. ``I said: `Oh
thank you, Jesus. Please do not send that watch out.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon then agreed to help I-Escrow and the sheriff's office. She
found an old chipped soap dish that weighed about as much as the
watch, wrapped it up and sent it to her buyer. Across the country
in Lynwood, Wash., Trafford was waiting, watching the abandoned
house through the windows of a nearby store.
</P>
<P>
   But the soap dish never made its way to the abandoned house.
Prime picked it up at the Federal Express office instead and threw
it into a gasoline station's trash can after he opened it.
Detective Trafford, however, was still able to find Prime. By
talking to witnesses at the Federal Express office, the detective
learned that Prime rode a blue-and-white motorcycle and used a
nearby storage business. On a visit to the site, the detective
spotted the motorcycle and noted its license plate number. The
number led him to find snapshots of Prime that were on file from a
previous arrest. ( Prime said he had pleaded guilty a few days
earlier to stealing a laptop computer.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, with help from I-Escrow and eBay, the detective had enough
information to make an arrest. Prime was picked up at his mother's
house, and the police said they had found a Rolex watch and two
stolen credit cards there. Prime said he took the cards after
finding them in automated teller machines. He was charged with
theft and two counts of possession of stolen property. He denied
the charges at first, posted bail and a few months later moved from
his mother's house.
</P>
<P>
   That move led to another visit from the authorities, this time
from a probation officer who had been assigned to Prime after he
pleaded guilty to the previous theft, which was in King County. The
officer came to do a routine check of Prime's new residence. During
a search of the apartment, he found a tin can in a cabinet. As soon
as the officer opened the can, a firecracker rocket inside ignited,
according to Prime's affidavit. The flame from the rocket was
apparently intended to destroy the contents, but detectives were
still able to identify them: another stolen credit card, a stolen
debit card and fake identification cards.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Prime eventually pleaded guilty to five felony counts (the three
earlier charges plus a count for possessing an incendiary device
and a count of forgery), and he was sentenced to 22 months at the
Airway Heights Correctional Center in eastern Washington. In the
interview this week, he said he had learned his lesson and was
hoping to take a computer-related job someday. ``I was emotionally
depressed and doing stupid things,'' he said. ``I made a bad
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The case of Prime may sound more complex than most cases of
credit-card fraud, but officials at companies like I-Escrow and
CyberSource, which provides verification services to online
merchants, say they have been seeing more incidents like this
recently. ``The con artists today are getting much more crafty,''
said Vince Gottman, i-Escrow's senior director for customer support
and the leader of the fraud squad.
</P>
<P>
   I-Escrow, for example, recently caught a buyer trying to
complete a transaction using a check stolen from his employer.
CyberSource officials said they had seen an increasing number of
international cases. A buyer will ask that goods be sent to a
location outside the United States but will use a credit card with
a billing address inside the United States. In many cases, they
say, the credit card being used is a stolen card.
</P>
<P>
   ``One bad buyer out there can do a lot of damage,'' said Tom
Arnold, chief technology officer at CyberSource.
</P>
<P>
   Most businesses already know this. ``You have to build that into
the cost of business,'' said Janet Crane, chief executive of
Billpoint, the credit-card system used by many people on eBay.
Crane acknowledged, however, that most eBay users did not have the
business experience to protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Billpoint works like most credit card companies and will not
cover a seller's costs when a transaction has gone bad. This week,
the company started offering a new feature to give sellers more
protection. The service, called Electronic Check, will let sellers
receive money directly from a buyer's checking account, instead of
through a credit card. But the service has a three-day waiting
period, so Billpoint can make sure that the check clears. If a
fraudulent check goes through, the service will reimburse sellers
up to $200.
</P>
<P>
   A few services offer guarantees if a card is used and later
determined to be stolen. I-Escrow, for example, gave refunds to the
sellers who were defrauded by Prime. The company now asks its users
to ensure that messages are legitimate by comparing the information
they get in e-mail messages that appear to be from I-Escrow with
what I-Escrow shows in their Web-based accounts. But if sellers do
everything that is asked of them and are still defrauded, I-Escrow
says, it will cover the cost of any lost items.
</P>
<P>
   Ecount, a service that enables people to use credit cards on the
Web, also says that it will cover the cost of bad transactions and
cover payments that are owed to a seller even if a credit card
turns out to be stolen. PayPal, another payment service, also
offers a guarantee, but only if users have completed a three-step
verification process when setting up accounts. About 10 percent of
PayPal's customers do so, said Elon Musk, chief executive of X.com,
the company behind PayPal.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, experts say, sellers should not panic. Kevin
Pursglove, eBay's spokesman, added that ``99.997 percent of
transactions have satisfactory buyers and sellers.'' Yahoo Auctions
and other auction sites also stress that most sales are completed
without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bacon said she had not been dissuaded from selling her
glassware on eBay, and she is still using I-Escrow for high-priced
items. In addition, it is likely that she may have been protected
from having to pay the cost of the watch, since she was selling it
for another shop.
</P>
<P>
   But she is also wary. Now she warns sellers to review the
procedures on auction and escrow services before using them.
``Fully understand what the process should be,'' she said, ``so you
can't get fooled like I did.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A NEW CAVEAT FOR eBAY USERS: SELLER BEWARE
</P>
<P>
   Sellers may be 10 times as likely to run into credit card fraud
over the Internet as in the physical world. Here are some things
online sellers should watch:
</P>
<P>
   SHIPPING _ Ship the item only to the address listed on the
credit card. People using stolen cards, of course, want purchases
to come to them, not to card holders.
</P>
<P>
   TIMING _ Don't sell to a buyer who appears anxious to purchase
an item and offers a premium to buy it before the auction ends. A
holder of a stolen card is usually in a hurry to use it before the
theft is reported.
</P>
<P>
   SHIPPING _ Be wary of any buyer who requests expensive overnight
shipping and offers to cover the costs.
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL _ Be wary of buyers using free e-mail services like
Hotmail or Juno.com. Many honest people use free e-mail, but these
accounts allow senders to be anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   PAYMENTS _ Don't let the buyer split up the payment for an item
by making, say, 10 payments of $500 instead of one $5,000 payment.
The buyer may be trying to stay under the radar of credit card
companies, who pay extra attention to large purchases. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1728EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
