<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA WILL NO LONGER RELEASE STATISTICS ON CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ South Africa's minister of safety
and security has ordered an indefinite moratorium on the release of
crime statistics, saying the system for collecting such information
here in one of the world's most crime-plagued countries is flawed
and unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   After reportedly denying plans for a blackout _ an idea
unpopular with some legislators and specialists _ the minister,
Steve Tshwete, and the national police commissioner, Jackie Selebi,
have in the past week reversed themselves and acknowledged the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Selebi, the first black commissioner to lead the 120,000-member
national police service, has been the man in the spotlight on
crime, planning a national initiative with quick and dramatic
results that have yet to materialize.
</P>
<P>
   Many critics concede that methods for collecting and analyzing
crime statistics are problematic; they support the work of a task
force that began meeting this week to hammer out a plan for
correcting the problems.
</P>
<P>
   But some also argue that keeping the public in the dark about
crime rates for months, even as the information in question
continues to be used to plan an anti-crime strategy, is
questionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say, `We know the statistics are flawed, and we're going
to correct them,''' said Eric Pelser, who studies the South African
Police Service for the Institute for Security Studies in Pretoria.
``At the same time they have a crime control strategy that is
dependent on these statistics. They're focusing on places that have
been identified based on these crime statistics, which raises the
question of how they were identified.''
</P>
<P>
   Few of the country's problems have done more to discourage
foreign investment and international tourism than the high
violent-crime rate. Selebi's response has been the initiative,
called Operation Crackdown, which he began in April, three months
after taking office.
</P>
<P>
   Carjackings and other types of robberies, widely considered a
barometer of personal safety, have climbed steadily since 1994,
according to the last crime statistics released by the police
before the moratorium took effect this month.
</P>
<P>
   The murder rate has declined modestly during the past five
years, to 55.3 per 100,000 in 1999 from 69.3 per 100,000 in 1994,
according to an analysis by the Institute for Security Studies. But
it remains among the highest in the world, and much of the decrease
has been attributed to the gradual falloff in politically motivated
killings that racked the country in the mid-1990s, during the
transition to black-majority rule.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner's spokeswoman, Sally De Beer, insists that his
request for a moratorium on the statistics is not an attempt to
deflect attention from the challenges facing the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we're covering up or trying to clamp down on bad
news,'' she said. ``We've been totally open.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``Commissioner Selebi uses these crime statistics to
plan operations and to deploy personnel, and he doesn't want to
plan his operation on what could be faulty data.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the moratorium would last ``months, not years.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Gibson, chief whip of the opposition Democratic Party
and a frequent critic of the police service, said the explanations
offered so far were unconvincing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the biggest load of nonsense I've ever heard,''
Gibson said. ``I think it's like the minister of education saying
we have education problems and I'm not letting anyone take final
examinations until we've sorted them out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The flaws and limitations of the police system, particularly the
lack of precision in classifying types of crimes and pinpointing
where they occur, were identified more than two years ago in a
major study of the police service. However, with expectations of
year 2000 computer problems, the police decided to put off the most
ambitious changes to their statistics systems, according to Chris
De Kock, director of the police crime information analysis center.
</P>
<P>
   Given the new commissioner's emphasis on tackling crime in the
most vulnerable communities, De Kock said, upgrading the system has
become a priority. ``You need to work with very accurate data,'' he
added, particularly on the location of crimes. ``Unfortunately, the
systems of the South African Police Service, where we derive our
statistics from, were never geared for that.''
</P>
<P>
   When the system has been fixed, he said, he does not expect huge
changes in crime totals, but he does expect a more accurate picture
of where, when and why the crimes are occurring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our murders are not suddenly going to go from 20,000 to
10,000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does Gibson expect such dramatic changes in the figures. But
he said what he did anticipate was disturbing nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that they are going to provide false figures,''
he said, ``but I do say that I suspect that they want to apply some
spin, and they want to manage the news, and I think that's a
mistake in a democracy. In democratic countries the voters and the
public are entitled to know what's going on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
