<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0760 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RUTH-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-02 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUTH-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DROWNING RUTH': RIVALRY AND MEMORIES OF A SPOOKY DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By JANET MASLIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An eerie, watery death is at the heart of ``Drowning Ruth,'' and
the only reliable witness was 3 years old when it happened. What's
more, Ruth Neumann's memory of the event seems to have played some
strange tricks. Ruth remembers the night her mother, Mathilda, fell
through the ice on a frozen lake, and she knows her mother drowned
there. But she also clings to the peculiar thought that somehow,
she herself drowned, too.
</P>
<P>
   Christina Schwarz, the author of this suspenseful, unusually
well-crafted first novel, cleverly contrasts Ruth's impressions
with those of her aunt, Amanda Starkey, whose recollections are
darker. On the night in 1919 when her sister died, not long after
their mother and father succumbed to influenza, Amanda wound up
with a bite mark on one hand, and the book creates a sinister sense
of how it got there. ``Who would have thought she would struggle so
fiercely?'' Amanda later thinks to herself. ``I found my father's
whiskey and dabbed a little on my wounds. Then I drank a glass.
People said it made you forget.''
</P>
<P>
   It's clear from the start, in a book that intersperses Amanda's
and Ruth's voices with a predominant third-person narrative, that
Schwarz can make a great deal out of the mystery of what really
happened. Sparingly and expertly, in a richly textured book with an
enveloping sense of the sisters' Wisconsin farm life, she doles out
the details. It develops that Carl Neumann, Mathilda's husband and
Ruth's father, was away in the Army when his wife died, and that he
must depend on Amanda for an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   It also develops that the strain of keeping a lid on her
emotions is enough to land Amanda in a psychiatric asylum soon
afterward. ``After all, it must have been hard for her,'' thinks
Clement Owens, a married man whose involvement with Amanda becomes
one of the book's most volatile ingredients. ``All those deaths,
the parents, then the sister. Anyone might crack.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz is able to deploy a line like that in casually chilling
fashion, so that the book stirs up powerful undercurrents of
foreboding. She fuses this suspense with such strong period detail
that ``Drowning Ruth'' creates a visceral sense of the forces that
constrain its women's lives. ``My mother's dresses smelled of
lavender water,'' Amanda recalls, with typical attention to
evocative particulars. ``She kept them perfectly, the sleeves and
bodices stuffed with paper to hold their shape, old shawls draped
over their shoulders to keep the dust off. It looked as if there
were six copies of my mother in the wardrobe, each without a
head.''
</P>
<P>
   No less frozen, in her own way, is Amanda, whose options in the
Wisconsin of 1919 are severely limited by her spinster status and
who clings desperately to her new role as Ruth's surrogate mother.
Throughout a book whose abundant plot twists would be spoiled by
too much discussion here, Amanda behaves in ways that make her
motherly side frighteningly apparent. She wants Ruth. She wants
Carl out of the way. Maybe she wanted her sister out of the way,
too. When Ruth grows up and becomes close to a girlfriend named
Imogene, her aunt's most agonizing maternal instincts are put to
the test.
</P>
<P>
   With deft pacing and a clear, vivid evocation of its principal
setting (the family farm and the isolated nearby island where
Mathilda drowned), Schwarz's homespun-sounding book has a
noticeably cinematic style. So Wes Craven, the ``Nightmare on Elm
Street'' director who showed a surprising flair for the womanly
aspects of ``Music of the Heart,'' is scheduled to bring it to the
screen, no doubt drawn to such frissons as the sudden sight of
Mathilda frozen in the lake, ``the blue eyes staring, the mouth
open, screaming without sound, trapped in that bottomless black
hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Other nicely horrific aspects include the book's hint of
reincarnation, its stirrings of a revenge plot and the mountingly
Gothic tone of Ruth's traumatic memories: ``Under the bed was where
to go the day the noises were scary. ... Under the bed is a good
place to hide when you hear the screaming, when you hear the
breathing, when you hear the `God, oh, God, oh, God.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the real shock in ``Drowning Ruth'' is the
realization of how deeply its story of sisterly love and rivalry
supplants everything else. In an ambitious book that sees its
characters through to 1941, moving from suspense-tinged,
romantically rustic farm life (meals of bacon and turnips,
honeysuckle and black-eyed susan braided into wreaths, a local
cheesemaker having excellent luck with white cheddar) into the more
urbane lives of the next generation, the full meaning of Amanda and
Mathilda's final struggle is saved for the story's revelatory
ending. In this assured last stroke, Schwarz affirms the
psychological underpinnings of a book that would have worked
page-turningly well as a straightforward mystery alone. She gives
it the extra wisdom that marks ``Drowning Ruth'' as the chilling,
precociously good start to a bright new novelist's career.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DROWNING RUTH'
</P>
<P>
   By Christina Schwarz
</P>
<P>
   338 pages. Doubleday. $23.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
