<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., AUG. 20, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish Bernard Gladstone's ``Home Improvement
Questions and Answers'' it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndication Sales. For purchase
information call toll-free 1-888-269-8796.) 
 (The NYTSS sales representative also has information on how to
subscribe to Gladstone's ``Home Improvement Questions and Answers''
weekly column which moves on Wednesdays.) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: I want to rent a machine for cleaning our living room carpet,
but a friend warned me these machines use water and a foaming
detergent which leave the carpet very damp.
 &HT;    As a result, when he replaced his coffee table and end tables,
the wood legs on each one formed dark stains on the carpet.
 &HT;    Is there a way to protect the carpet from such marks?
 &HT;    A: Most carpet cleaning machines do leave the carpet damp, but
this should dry up in a day or so _ faster if an air conditioner is
on or there is good ventilation in that room.
 &HT;    However, one precaution to take when reinstalling the furniture:
Place squares of plastic or aluminum foil under each wooden table
leg to prevent moisture in the carpet from drawing the stain out of
the wood.
 &HT;    This is probably what happened in your friend's case.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: I built a small office room onto my house, with a single door
connecting it to the family room.
 &HT;    But even with the door closed, anyone in that room can hear me
talking on the phone or to clients in that office _ which makes it
difficult to maintain confidence with my clients.
 &HT;    What I can do to better insulate the door connecting the two
rooms so that sound won't pass through so easily?
 &HT;    A: Most interior doors are not much of a sound barrier because
they are either hollow or made with a single thin panel of wood set
into a frame.
 &HT;    A thick, solid door would do a better job of stopping sound
transmission, so you might want to try installing this type of door
in place of the one now in place.
 &HT;    In addition, it's a good idea to install foam type weather
stripping around all the edges of the door, including the top and
bottom, in order to further cut down on sound transmission.
 &HT;    The best method, however, is to install a second door in the
same frame so there are two doors blocking the entrance, one
opening in each direction.
 &HT;    When both doors are closed there will be a dead air space
trapped between them, and this will provide the best sound
insulation of all.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: We have a storm window on the outside of our large picture
window and in cold weather, condensation covers the inside of this
storm window.
 &HT;    All putty has been replaced on both windows and all new weather
stripping was installed around the window.
 &HT;    What else can we do to solve this problem?
 &HT;    A: When condensation forms on the inside of the storm window it
means that warm moist air must be getting trapped in the space
between the two windows.
 &HT;    If you are certain that the weather stripping is good and
there's none missing, chances are you can cure the problem by
drilling a few one-quarter-inch ``weep holes'' along the bottom of
the storm window.
 &HT;    These holes will allow trapped moisture vapor to escape
harmlessly to the outside instead of condensing on the cold glass
of the storm window.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: We have a constant problem with algae growing on our stone
patio, even though it slopes properly so that water drains off
after it rains.
 &HT;    I know that algae can be removed with bleach, but I am afraid
this will kill the plants and ground cover around the patio.
 &HT;    A commercial algaecide that I tried last year did work, but the
moss has come back.
 &HT;    Can you suggest a more permanent solution?
 &HT;    A: Moss only grows where there is moisture and a lack of
sunlight, so prune any trees or large shrubs that are shading that
patio from sunlight.
 &HT;    Also, try to improve drainage from the surface of the patio, as
well as from the ground around it.
 &HT;    Additionally, you may want to apply a clear masonry sealer to
the patio. That will help shed water and thus prevent it from
soaking in and keeping the patio damp.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NOTE: Drawing captioned ``PROTECTING NEWLY WASHED CARPET'' goes
with this column.
 &HT;    CAPTION: Squares of plastic or aluminum foil under each table
leg will keep damp carpet from drawing stain out of wood.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
