<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ONLINE BROADCASTS ADD NEW DIMENSION TO POLITICS
 &HT;    500&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Thanks to the Internet, television viewers
enraged by pontificating politicians can vent their frustration by
talking back live.
</P>
<P>
   The cutting-edge technology is getting a heavy-duty workout at
the Republican National Convention. For the first time, online
broadcasters have built their own electronic nests alongside the
major networks and cable outlets.
</P>
<P>
   The long-anticipated world of interactive political TV became a
reality the other night when Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania came to
Skybox 33 overlooking the First Union Center floor, the working
quarters of pseudopolitics.com.
</P>
<P>
   As Ridge explained his belief that abortion should be kept
legal, viewers challenged his views by sending Internet messages to
a chat room directly below the site's streaming video interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor was able to enter into a serious dialogue with
his critics,'' said Jeanne Meyer, the Web site's senior vice
president. ``It was really cool. There's no way we could have done
something like this two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Pseudopolitics' rise to the rafters here offers a clear sign
that Web-based news operations are muscling their way into the news
coverage mainstream even before their technology is perfected.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to offering online interviews from its $20,000
leased skybox, the Web site pumps out Webcam pictures from six
positions in the converted sports arena, each of which provide
360-degree views.
</P>
<P>
   As these broadcasts unfold in cyberspace, viewers are invited to
e-mail messages to an ``EJ'' _ a kind of electronic disk jockey _
who puts them on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The youthful EJs sit overlooking the convention floor in what
could pass for a standard TV convention setup. One difference is
the red sign lit up behind them with the words ``ON THE NET''
instead of ``ON THE AIR.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Gersh Kuntzman, the site's editorial director and a former
newspaper editor: ``Newspapers aren't going to be replaced. TV
won't be replaced. But we're going to have a role to play.''
</P>
<P>
   To mark the changing scene, pseudopolitics.com invited to its
skybox Robert Trout, whose long career at CBS radio and television
began before Franklin Roosevelt's first term and who covered his
first national political convention in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's now in his early 90s, but be performed online as the star
he once was,'' Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even on computers with fast links to the Internet, the
live video streams of Ridge and Trout, hardly larger than postage
stamps, often arrived as fuzzy and jerky images.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not quite there yet,'' conceded Kathy Bushkin, senior
vice president and chief communications officer of America Online,
pseudopolitics' next-door neighbor on Skybox Row. AOL sees its
operation here as a precursor to its plans to couple traditional TV
audiences with its online services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure,'' Bushkin added, ``that one day video streaming that
anyone can watch easily on the Internet will be a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Meyer: ``It's a bit like watching the first guy who walked
on the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The two pioneering Internet-based skyboxes have set up shop on
the Center's exclusive suite level. They operate at the far flanks
of much larger glassed-in units that house both the
well-established TV outlets and the plush invitation-only alcoves
that cater to the biggest Republican givers.
</P>
<P>
   With the TV networks scaling back on their convention effort
this year, AOL and pseudopolitics.com hope to seize an opportunity
to fill in the coverage gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our aim is to puncture conventional wisdom and inject fun,
intelligence and voter participation back into politics,'' said
David Bohrman, chief executive of Pseudo Programs Inc., the
political site's parent company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our approach to convention coverage this year will be a
powerful illustration of the next-generation medium we are
creating. Pseudo's production team will be pushing the limits of
technology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.pseudopolitics.com
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass' e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
