<SLUG> BC-EDLIFE-NEWZEALAND-2TAKES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTRODUCING `EDUCATION MARKET' IN NEW ZEALAND HAD UNINTENDED
CONSEQUENCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS.: For release Sunday, Aug. 6) 
 By EDWARD B. FISKE and HELEN F. LADD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 Edward B. Fiske, an education consultant and a former education
editor of The New York Times, and his wife, Helen F. Ladd,
professor of public policy studies and economics at Duke
University, spent five months in New Zealand studying its school
reforms in 1998 and visited the country again recently. They are
the authors of ``When Schools Compete: A Cautionary Tale''
(Brookings Institution Press, 2000).  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLINGTON, New Zealand _ When Trevor Mallard became New
Zealand's Minister of Education several months ago, one of his
first steps was to bolster direct government assistance to troubled
urban schools.
</P>
<P>
   Although the programs he announced were hardly unusual _ more
money for early-childhood education, clustering of schools with
common problems, a bigger national investment in teacher training _
they were notable far beyond this island nation. The reason: they
signaled the end of a decade-long flirtation with the notion that
parental choice and competition among schools would, in and of
themselves, improve the educational offerings of troubled urban
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely moving away from the nonintervention
approach,'' Mallard said in a recent interview in his office here.
``Our goal is to close gaps between rich and poor schools, not
widen them.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last 10 years, New Zealand has provided a laboratory for
many of the educational theories that have become increasingly
popular among would-be reformers in the United States in recent
years, most notably charter schools and vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   With a population of 3.8 million, New Zealand is roughly
comparable to an American state, and its Ministry of Education is
the functional equivalent of a state department of education in the
decentralized American system. It has social, cultural and
political traditions similar to those in the United States and,
perhaps most important, a significant minority population.
</P>
<P>
   Those minorities, Maori and Pacific Islanders, many of whom live
in urban areas, make up 20 percent of the population, and schools
affirm their cultures, both through the formal curriculum and
through extracurricular activities and festivals.
</P>
<P>
   As in the United States, success in school correlates closely
with socioeconomic status. Large numbers of Maori and Pacific
Island pupils come from low-income families, and their collective
achievement levels are well below those of white students. At high
schools _ which are called colleges _ administrators have taken
steps to deal with such obstacles to learning as iron deficiency,
high cholesterol rates and family violence. For example, they have
created a health clinic at Tamaki College in South Auckland.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, New Zealand embarked on what is arguably the most
radical overhaul of a state education system ever taken by an
industrialized country. The first step was taken by a Labor
government that abolished the country's heavy-handed central
educational bureaucracy and turned the running of all primary and
secondary schools over to locally elected boards of trustees
dominated by parents.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, in 1991, a new national government committed to
free-market principles added to the reform mix by giving parents
the right to choose which school their children would attend.
Schools that attracted more applicants than they could accommodate
had considerable discretion over which ones to accept.
</P>
<P>
   Under the package of reforms, known collectively as Tomorrow's
Schools, the central Ministry of Education continues to fund
schools, draft national curriculum guidelines and operate an
accountability system under which teams from an independent
Education Review Office visit schools.
</P>
<P>
   Many school reformers in the United States and other developed
countries see governance changes like those adopted in New Zealand
as a key to improving the quality of public schools, including
those serving disadvantaged students. The core argument is that if
schools are freed from bureaucratic controls and forced to compete
for students, they will have both the means and the incentives to
become successful.
</P>
<P>
   Since New Zealand has no national standardized tests, it is not
possible to measure the impact of Tomorrow's Schools on student
achievement. Nevertheless, it is evident that self-governance and
parental choice were generally popular and that they had an
energizing effect on many primary and secondary schools, at least
those in middle- and upper-middle-income communities.
</P>
<P>
   The Gladstone Primary School in Auckland, for example, has
prospered by offering a program organized around the theory of
multiple intelligences articulated by Howard Gardner, a Harvard
University psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is restricting us,'' said Colin Dale, the principal.
``The potential is now there to do whatever you want. It's all
about meeting needs and performing. If you get it right, people
will flock to you.''
</P>
<P>
   On the negative side, however, the educational marketplace has
polarized enrollment patterns by ethnicity and seriously
complicated the problems of schools serving large disadvantaged
populations.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Research shows that New Zealand parents of all races judge the
quality of schools in part by the ethnic mix of their students.
Schools with a preponderance of European students are seen as
superior to those with large numbers of Maori and Pacific
Islanders. In the new educational marketplace during the 1990s,
student transfers caused schools that had served predominantly
white students to grow in size, while those that served large
numbers of minorities saw their rolls decrease.
</P>
<P>
   Data from the Ministry of Education show, for example, that here
in Wellington the proportion of Maori and Pacific Island students
in primary and intermediate schools who ranked lowest in
socioeconomic status increased to 84 percent from 76 percent
between 1991 and 1996. A recent study by the government-supported
New Zealand Council for Educational Research also reported that the
intended reforms ``appear to have acted in an unintended manner,
which has increased ethnic polarization.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, competition has produced both winners and
losers. Popular schools have been able to fill their rolls with
students from family backgrounds conducive to academic success,
while undersubscribed schools, which by law must accept all comers,
must now cope with greater concentrations of difficult-to-teach
students _ those from impoverished homes, with weak English skills
or with learning problems. Ministry data show that suspended
students are likely to end up in a school with a higher
concentration of poor and minority group students than the school
from which they were suspended.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1990s New Zealanders had come to speak of downwardly
``spiraling'' schools in which declining enrollments and the
subsequent loss of teachers and other academic resources compound
the challenges they face. A student at one such high school in
Auckland, Tangaroa College, said that she dreamed of going into
medicine but feared that she would not be adequately prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``At our school, dreams seem so far away,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Market theory holds that if schools lose the capacity to attract
a sufficient number of students, they will close their doors and
other schools will come along to serve their students. But that
shift rarely occurred in New Zealand, partly because it is
politically difficult to close a school and partly because there
were few incentives for educational entrepreneurs to move into
unpromising situations.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with mounting political pressure to rescue troubled urban
schools, the national government began in the late 1990s to look
for ways to assist them. Policy makers did so reluctantly, however,
knowing that under the theory of the educational marketplace, there
was no justification for direct intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Initial efforts centered on improving the management skills of
principals in troubled schools. It soon became evident, though,
that while good management was important, it was not sufficient in
and of itself to turn around spiraling schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the benefit of hindsight, there was far too much optimism
about what managerial reform could accomplish,'' said Howard Fancy,
a civil servant who was secretary of education under the national
government and continues in that post in the Labor-led coalition
government that was sworn in last December.
</P>
<P>
   The ministry then initiated a School Improvement Project aimed
at assisting struggling schools through means that included
substantial direct investment. A plan for Hilary College, a high
school in Auckland, provided the equivalent of approximately $1
million for such purposes as buying out ``underperforming'' staff
members, an anti-violence program, counseling services and new
equipment. A similar plan for nearby Tangaroa College provided
funds for staff buyouts, new equipment and support of a guidance
clinic, a nurse, a truancy officer and a part-time sports
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   The new government has vowed to strengthen the School
Improvement Project. Eighteen primary, intermediate and secondary
schools in a low-income and immigrant section of Auckland have now
formed a coalition to address common problems, and leaders say they
are ready to try new approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to think long and hard about pedagogy,'' said Terry
Bates, director of a new project linking schools in Auckland. ``The
teaching methods that we developed after World War II are not
suitable for inner-city kids who have all kinds of interruptions in
their lives that do not hinder middle-class kids. We need to
provide more one-on-one instruction. We need to find ways of using
technology in ways that allow pupils to take greater control of
their own learning. We need to train teachers to be enablers of
learning rather than sources of information.''
</P>
<P>
   The new government has taken other steps to address what it
views as some of the excesses of the Tomorrow's Schools reforms. In
an effort to rein in the ability of popular schools to cherry-pick
easy-to-teach students, new legislation requires schools that have
more applicants than they can handle to hold a lottery to determine
who can enroll.
</P>
<P>
   Fancy, the education secretary, pointed out that while
Tomorrow's Schools had exacerbated the problems of some urban
schools, many of those schools were failing well before 1989. In
highlighting the negative impact of a competitive environment on
troubled schools, he suggested, the reforms had the effect of
drawing public attention to their needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow's Schools has sharpened our focus on educational
failure,'' he said. ``Only now, 10 years into the reforms, are we
seeing a serious effort to turn schools around.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
