<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0774 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0803-COX     08-02 2465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0803-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Ladies and gentleman, the (next) president of
the united states
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush, voicing confidence that ``you're looking at the
next president of the United States,'' arrived in Philadelphia
today to formally accept his party's presidential nomination. After
a warm-up tour through six states and two brief appearances by
satellite, the Texas governor's first stop was a Hispanic rally
where he alternated between English and Spanish as he told a crowd
of more than 1,000,
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a better day for America; there's a better day for
all. . . . Together we can make sure every child can read in
America.'' Bush will be officially nominated for president at the
Republican National Convention tonight, but the stage will then
belong to his vice presidential running mate, Dick Cheney, who _ in
his first major appearance as Bush's pick _ will ``draw some
contrasts'' with Vice President Al Gore in his speech, according to
a campaign spokesman. For Bush, the finale will be on Thursday when
he accepts the nomination in the most important speech of his life.
</P>
<P>
   FORD `DOING WELL' AFTER STROKE
</P>
<P>
   Former President Gerald Ford suffered a stroke while attending
the convention, but was described by doctors as ``doing well''
today and thinking clearly. The 87-year-old Ford had a small stroke
that affected the base of his brain, causing him some trouble with
his balance and his speech, but he seemed to be understanding
everything. He is expected to stay in the hospital for five or six
days. Ford went to the hospital after last night's convention
session and was released within a half-hour with what doctors said
at the time was an acute sinus infection. But he returned to the
hospital this morning. ``I think he probably had a stroke maybe two
days ago and had another little one'' overnight, said Dr. Robert
Schwartzman, chief of neurology at Hahnemann University Hospital.
The doctor said the stroke was not detected earlier because ``it
looks like an ear infection.''
</P>
<P>
   STIRRING IT UP AT THE REPUBLICAN LOVEFEST
</P>
<P>
   About 120 demonstrators peacefully protested George W. Bush's
record on Latino issues outside the Philadelphia Museum of Art
today, where Bush was addressing a Hispanic audience. A few blocks
away, 40 demonstrators denouncing the death penalty and calling
attention to other issues chanted and waved banners at an entrance
to a downtown arena where Bush was arriving for a fund-raiser. The
demonstrations today have so far contrasted sharply with the angry
brawls with police a day earlier. Protesters slashed tires on
police vehicles, dumped orange paint on some and spray-painted
graffiti denouncing the death penalty and police. Police responded
with batons after being hit by protesters, leaving several
demonstrators bleeding. Some demonstrators were upset about the
more- confrontational behavior. Said Patricia Maxey, a 16-year-old
member of New Yorkers Against the Death Penalty: ``If it gets like
this again, I'm going home. I don't want to be beaten up because
some idiot in a mask wants to get on television. I came here to
talk about injustice.''
</P>
<P>
   HAVING HIS CAKE AND EATING IT TOO
</P>
<P>
   On the day Dick Cheney is set to formally introduce himself to
the world as George W. Bush's vice presidential nominee, the Texas
governor kept introducing John McCain. At a rally today, Bush
called McCain's address the night before ``a touching tribute to
America.'' That cued McCain's surprise stroll onstage, where Bush
wrapped him in a hug and whispered something in his ear. At a $10
million fund-raiser _ an event boycotted by the reform-minded
McCain _ Bush blessed his former rival. With Cheney off stage and
out of site, the Texan declared, ``I can't wait to campaign with
John McCain. Together we can win this election!'' Bush, who lost
seven primaries to the Arizona senator last winter, knows better
than most about McCain's appeal to independent voters. But when it
came time to fill out his ticket, the Texan selected loyalty over
political potency _ giving off the impression that he's trying to
have it both ways.
</P>
<P>
   TAX CUTS? EXIT STAGE LEFT
</P>
<P>
   Tax cuts have always been central to the GOP's agendum but in
the party's drive to broaden its appeal, little was said from the
podium about the subject during the convention's first two days.
This, despite the rush by Republicans in Congress to pass bills
beforehand to eliminate the tax penalty on marriage, repeal
inheritance taxes and cut taxes on Social Security benefits.
Indeed, the only GOP political figures to dwell at length on tax
cuts during the first two days of the convention were the 29
congressional candidates who spoke during Monday's little-noticed
afternoon session. The Republicans will, however, deliver a
tax-cutting message tonight, but in a soft-focus way: a single mom,
a computer company president and a family farmer will join Virginia
Gov. Jim Gilmore in helping describe the GOP's tax relief vision.
</P>
<P>
   THE WHOLE WORLD IS WATCHING _ SOMETHING ELSE
</P>
<P>
   Television ratings for the first night of the convention
indicated that only a small fraction of the total television
audience watched the prime-time portion of the event. On ABC and
CBS, the two networks that offered just an hour of prime-time
coverage each, only about 13 million, or 15 percent of the total
television audience, tuned in. The coverage on both networks was
beaten by a repeat episode of the show ``Third Watch'' on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   MARYLAND HIS MARYLAND
</P>
<P>
   Maryland saved the day for Wyoming and the Republicans during
the introduction of Dick Cheney at the convention. When Cheney and
his wife, Lynne, arrived at the floor, the Wyoming section on the
floor was empty _ just a few folks in the seats. Knowing the
cameras would pan to the delegation right after Cheney was
introduced, someone drafted part of Maryland's delegation to sit in
those empty seats, said Audrey E. Scott, a member of the Prince
George's County Council who has played head cheerleader for her
state's delegation. ``He's pointing to us like we're his best
friends, and we're waving and pointing back,'' she said today. As
luck would have it, Republicans couldn't have wished for a better
surrogate delegation: Marylanders have been among the most vocal,
enthusiastic of any of the delegations.
</P>
<P>
   RNC BODY-SLAMMED, SOME WANT WRESTLER TOSSED OUT
</P>
<P>
   A small band of incensed conservatives has put Republican
officials in a headlock over their inclusion of professional
wrestler The Rock in tonight's program. The Parents Television
Council is protesting the Rock's appearance because they ``object
to the violent and raunchy nature'' of the World Wrestling
Federation's programming. ``By giving `The Rock' such a prominent
role at the convention, the GOP is, in effect, saying that the
values of the WWF _ violence, profanity, graphic sexuality, the
demeaning of women, and the promotion of racial stereotypes _ are
shared by the party,'' said PTC chair Brent Bozell. Rep. J.D.
Hayworth (D-Ariz.) responded, ``As a social conservative . . . let
me say with all candor and proper respect, lighten up. This is a
convention. It's supposed to be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   FORGET ABOUT THE ROCK, HOW ABOUT THE BODY?
</P>
<P>
   The buzz around certain circles at the convention today is that
Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura will endorse George W. Bush for
president, according to the Washington Times. Ventura could not be
reached for comment, and officials in the Bush campaign did not
return telephone calls seeking comment. If true, a Ventura
endorsement would effectively eliminate a potential last-minute
White House run by the popular maverick politician who has proven
himself a capable governor. It would also be a departure from views
the former professional wrestler expressed a few weeks ago when he
said both Al Gore and Bush were ``too rehearsed'' and ``too spun''
to capture the independent vote, which he could easily garner.
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKING OF R.O.C.K
</P>
<P>
   Rocker John Mellencamp's ``staying mum'' on George W. Bush's
liberal use of his song ``R.O.C.K. in the U.S.A.'' on the campaign
trail. Bush has been playing the song on his pre-convention tour.
He also used the tune when he announced Dick Cheney as his running
mate. Mellencamp's ``R.O.C.K.'' hasn't reached the status of
Fleetwood Mac's ``Don't Stop Thinking About Tomorrow'' from
Clinton-Gore '92 as an official campaign song for Bush, but it's
been played enough to strike a chord at rallies. ``While Mellencamp
isn't a Bush supporter, he won't comment on the matter unless it
becomes used in a more prominent way,'' said the New York Post,
reporting on the story. Right now, it's only the first song of a
tape that also includes music by Gloria Estefan and John Fogerty.
Mellencamp's been in this position before, refusing to give
permission to Ronald Reagan who wanted to use his ``Pink Houses.''
Four years ago, Bob Dole angered Bruce Springsteen after Dole used
``Born in the U.S.A.''
</P>
<P>
   THE SINCEREST FORM OF FLATTERY?
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Defense Fund, a Washington think tank, is
considering suing the Republican Party for using its trademarked
slogan,''Leave no child behind'' as the official theme of its
convention's opening night. ``They shouldn't hijack the phrase
without acting on behalf of children,'' said founder and president
Marian Wright Edelman. She said George W. Bush has yet to respond
to the think tank's complaints; Republicans said nobody has the
exclusive rights to helping kids.
</P>
<P>
   THE DEVIL IS IN THE DETAILS
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, George W. Bush is not a detail man. In his
fourth month as governor of Texas, Bush pared the time generally
reserved for final review of each scheduled execution from 30
minutes to 15. And he never read the 261-page report on the Texas
A&AMP;M University bonfire collapse, nor did he read the 36-page
executive summary. ``I highlighted half a page; he read that,''
Clay Johnson, Bush's chief of staff, told the Los Angeles Times.
Daily appointment calendars obtained by the newspaper show that as
governor, Bush focused on a few issues, preferred short meetings
and insisted on a two-hour midday break centered on a rejuvenating
run. He had many more meetings on education than on any other
subject, and met frequently with representatives of oil, insurance
and other industries, but seldom with labor, environmental or
consumer activists. And nearly half the 469 business leaders,
energy executives and lobbyists who came through his doors donated
to his political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   BREAKING UP IS HARD TO DO
</P>
<P>
   Delegate S.G. ``Vet'' Payne couldn't bring himself to back
George W. Bush at the convention. The Rhode Island retiree, a
fervent John McCain supporter, planned to abstain when his state
pledged itself to Bush in the roll call of states. Then, someone
tapped him on his shoulder and asked him to step to the back of the
convention hall. There stood John McCain's wife, Cindy, who asked
him to change his mind, saying her husband had urged his delegates
to support Bush ``I said, 'OK, I am a loyal McCain supporter. I
will at your very specific request change my position,''' Payne
said. The two hugged and went their separate ways. Another delegate
however went against McCain's wishes and cast the only McCain vote
of the convention. Dr. Dwight Stowell Jr., of the Massachusetts
delegation, said he wanted to send a message to Bush about the need
for campaign finance reform with his vote.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH CLAN GOES BALLISTIC
</P>
<P>
   Former president George Bush came to the defense of his son
today when he told a breakfast for farm groups that his son is
disciplined enough to ``stick to the message'' despite goading from
the opposition. ``He can dish it out if he has to, but he's going
to stay on his message. You don't believe me? Ask Ann Richards,''
the elder Bush said of George W. Bush. Richards is the Democrat
whom George W. Bush ousted from the Texas governor's office, and
who is remembered for deriding the elder Bush at the Democratic
convention in 1988 for being born with a silver foot in his mouth.
``Well, she may have been right about that, but anyway, they
cheered like hell and then George came along two years later and
showed her what she could do with that silver foot,'' the former
president said. The elder Bush was responding to an earlier comment
by President Clinton that the only reason the Texas governor was
running was because his ``daddy was president.'' If Clinton doesn't
back off, he said, the family might unleash ex-first lady Barbara
Bush. Indeed, the candidate's mother jumped in _ in comments on
ABC's ``Good Morning America,'' saying Al Gore would not be able to
return respect to the office her husband lost to Clinton in the
1992 election.
</P>
<P>
   RAGIN' CAJUN ALL THE RAGE
</P>
<P>
   When Democratic strategist James Carville, the most vociferous
and recognizable defender of the Clinton-Gore administration, shows
up on the convention floor, the man Republicans love to hate on the
political talk shows is treated like a rock star instead of being
scorned and jeered. ``I get more picture requests at the Republican
convention than at a Democratic convention,'' Carville marveled.
``I've had my picture taken with 150 delegates here,'' he said.
Carville has been invited to the convention by NBC News, which
broadcasts his political analysis from their skybox several times
each evening. The man who snuck onto the GOP convention floor in
1996 says he has ``gone legit'' this time around.
</P>
<P>
   AT LEAST THE DIDN'T SAY IT WAS IN THE MAIL
</P>
<P>
   There's been a lot of talk about campaign contributions floating
around at the convention. At least one was just lying on the ground
waiting to be picked up. Two reporters for the Philadelphia
Inquirer happened upon a $5,000 check for New York Rep. John
McHugh's re-election campaign that was sticking out from under a
motorized cart outside the convention center. The check was from
Advo Inc., a direct-mail company based in Windsor, Conn., which
gives regularly to McHugh, who chairs the House Government Reform
subcommittee on the Postal Service. McHugh told the newspaper he
had met with Advo representatives in a hotel bar, but they couldn't
find the check they had meant to give him. ``They said they just
couldn't find it. I don't think they knew where it was,'' McHugh
said. The Inquirer returned the check.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Saeed Ahmed from staff and news reports.
</P>
