<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Aug. 3, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will drench parts of New York and New
England as a cold front pushes eastward into the Appalachians. A
flow of tropical air preceding the front will supply enough
moisture to cause flooding in some areas from central New York to
western Maine.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure near Bermuda will circulate very warm and humid
air from the Gulf of Mexico into the Southeast. Thundershowers will
blossom in the sultry air mass in the afternoon. The approach of a
cold front in the central Appalachians and Tennessee Valley will
lead to several potent storms.
</P>
<P>
   Refreshingly cooler, drier air will spread from the upper Great
Lakes into the Ohio Valley. A return flow of humid air into the
western Plains will cause a few thunderstorms. Torrid air over the
West will lead to thunderstorms each afternoon in the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: COLD JULY
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a year makes, at least at Central Park. July
1999 was the warmest summer month ever for New York City, while
this past July was one of the coolest in nearly a century. For only
the second time since 1900, the mercury failed to reach 90 degrees
at Central Park in July. In Binghamton, N.Y., the temperature only
topped 80 on the last day of the month. Albany tied its coldest
July ever with records dating back into the middle 1800s. While the
jet stream has relaxed some this week, another batch of cool air
will arrive late this week in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
