<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKYDIVING-QUEST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'CHUTE, THIS GUY'S GOING FOR THE RECORD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By LIZ STEVENS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENTON, Texas _ Meet Mike Zang, the nuttiest guy this side of
the stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Zang is completely sane. He just has this one crazy
scheme up his, uh, flight suit.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to break the world record for the most sky dives in a
24-hour period.
</P>
<P>
   Guess how many that is.
</P>
<P>
   30?
</P>
<P>
   Keep going.
</P>
<P>
   50?
</P>
<P>
   Try again.
</P>
<P>
   103?
</P>
<P>
   No, kids. The record is 476, and Zang thinks he can beat it by
up to 75 jumps. At 9 a.m. on March 7, 2001, he'll begin his attempt
at Skydive Texas in Denton, north of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   You're probably wondering _ as we were _ what the heck he's
thinking. The simple answer is the 30-year-old Zang loves sky
diving and has since his first jump in autumn 1991. He put himself
through sky-diving school the next spring and has racked up 2,569
jumps total. (He proposed to his wife during No. 68.)
</P>
<P>
   Zang, who lives in Dallas, spent March in Arizona working toward
his FAA license to be a parachute rigger (the rigger packs and
maintains the reserve parachute, the sky diver's last chance for
survival). Jay Stokes, who broke the world record for jumps in
November 1999, just happened to be Zang's mentor that month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one who got me into doing this in the first place,''
says Zang, a Continental Airlines co-pilot during weekdays and
father of two. ``He wants somebody to break his record so he can
break that again.''
</P>
<P>
   The operation will require 30 parachute rigs, two Pilatus Porter
airplanes, approximately 150 volunteers (including Stokes), a
doctor, two sky-dive judges and two attorneys (to notarize the
paperwork for the Guinness folks). Zang's attempt will be the first
using two single-engine turbine aircraft, which can climb 2,000
feet per minute at sea level, and his state-of-the-art parachutes
will save him 3 to 5 seconds per jump.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one glitch: money. Renting the two planes that
might carry him to victory will cost Zang a cool $20,000. He's
looking for individual and corporate sponsorships and hopes to
raise $100,000 for Special Olympics. So far he's up to 200 bucks,
but he's hoping that his Web site, www.jump4kids.org, will draw
more attention to the event.
</P>
<P>
   We'll be checking back with Zang every so often, right up to his
attempt, and trying all the while to figure out why a seemingly
sane guy would do such a thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very much a Type A,'' Zang admits, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   That's ``A'' for Airborne.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
