u a BC-CIR-HUMAN-POWER-ART &LR; -     08-02 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HUMAN-POWER-ART </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER FROM THE PEOPLE BREAKS THE HOLD OF BATTERIES AND PLUGS 
</HEADLINE>
 - (2TAKES)-NYT  (ART ADV: Photo NYT8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CHRISTINE KENNEALLY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   While living in Iowa two years ago, I saw the sky turn green. A
number of events rapidly followed: The tornado sirens blared, my
husband and I took shelter downstairs, and the Weather Channel
visuals blipped off the television set. Then the electricity went
out, and I frantically wondered if I had remembered to recharge the
radio's batteries so we could monitor the tornado's movement.
</P>
<P>
   Had I? Of course not. For me, and for most people in the
developed world, the occasional power disruption cannot disrupt the
expectation that as sure as the sun rises, the lights will go on in
the morning when the bedroom switch is clicked. But there are
increasingly more situations where it is desirable or necessary to
be independent of the electricity grid and freed of what Rory
Stear, the chief executive of Freeplay Energy, a company that makes
hand-powered radios and flashlights, calls ``the tyranny of the
disposable battery.''
</P>
<P>
   Situations where you might not want to be _ or cannot be _
tethered to an electrical socket include boating and camping, as
well as crises that knock out power, like tornadoes, hurricanes and
earthquakes. In many places in developing nations, there is no
electricity grid to knock out, but people there still need
electricity. And the need for easily available energy is compounded
as laptops, cell phones and personal digital assistants put
portable computing into more hands.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative energy source is old-fashioned. All you need are
some calories, H2 O, O2 and maybe some vitamins. The human body is
a powerful source of energy. Many electrical devices now taken for
granted had human-powered antecedents that date to only a
generation ago. My farm-girl mother can remember churning butter by
hand, and my father recalls starting a friend's Model T Ford, ``a
temperamental beast,'' with a hand crank. Today, companies are
looking at ways to use the human body to power CD players, cell
phones and even home computers.
</P>
<P>
   Most human-powered devices are entirely mechanical, with a
direct relationship between input and output. Simple human-powered
devices that use electricity, like bicycle lights, can generate
energy but not store it. But the human-powered devices being
developed today are designed to use energy more efficiently and,
most important, are built to store energy.
</P>
<P>
   Freeplay Energy, which was formed in 1995, sells a human-powered
flashlight lantern and human-powered radios. Cranking the handle on
its newest handheld radio for 30 seconds yields about 45 minutes of
play (larger models play for an hour with 30 seconds of cranking).
The same effort provides three to six minutes of light from the
Freeplay lantern.
</P>
<P>
   The Freeplay products use a mechanism that winds a steel spring
from one spool to another. When the spring returns to its original
position, it drives a DC generator, which sends current to the
device. Successive cranking can also store energy in the lantern's
rechargeable battery, or the lantern can be plugged into an outlet.
Some Freeplay radios can capture solar energy.
</P>
<P>
   Similar products on the market include the Nightstar flashlight
made by Applied Innovative Technologies. The company's president,
Steve Vetorino, said, ``Thirty seconds of shaking at three shakes
per second will provide high illumination for five minutes and a
lesser light (enough to read by) for about 20 minutes.'' For longer
illumination, Vetorino said, the Nightstar should be turned off
every two to three minutes and shaken for 10 to 15 seconds. The
shaking makes a magnet move through a wire coil, generating
current, which can be stored.
</P>
<P>
   Hand-cranked products are sold for diverse reasons all over the
world. The Freeplay radios are bought and distributed by many
international aid agencies working in remote places, like Kosovo.
In the United States, the radios and lights are bought by campers
and by some households to keep for emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   Freeplay's sales rose significantly in the United States at the
end of last year because of concerns about Year 2000 problems. The
sales in this country indicated an Olympian level of panic, while
sales were calm and orderly in Britain and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   As the Web increasingly becomes liberated from wire, the
application of human power to computing and communications will
become more crucial. If you have the latest laptop, pager, cell
phone or PDA, you can go a fair way without recharging, but you
cannot go on safari in the Serengeti. A number of companies and
institutions are addressing that problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Freeplay lantern can already be used to power another
device, like a personal stereo. Freeplay is also developing pocket
devices to power things like cell phones or PDA's and larger
hand-cranked generators for writers who have laptops and good upper
arm tone and who want to escape to desert islands.
</P>
<P>
   For the past year, the Bridges Equipment Co. has has been
selling AladdinPower devices _ human-powered electricity generators
invented by Nissho Engineering, a Japanese company. AladdinPower
was recently spun off as its own company, based in Tampa.
AladdinPower's handheld rechargers and its Stepcharger, which is
pumped by stepping on it (but it is now out of stock), can be used
to power cell phones, handheld radios, personal CD players and, in
the case of the Stepcharger, which operates at a higher voltage,
laptops.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Collins, president and chief executive of AladdinPower,
said that about two to three minutes of pumping on the handheld
charger gave a cell phone user approximately 20 minutes to use the
phone, depending on the vigor of the pumping. Tens of thousands of
AladdinPower units have been sold, Collins said. He predicted that
``300 million units will be sold in the next 10 years because of
the expansion of cellular markets worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Media Laboratory is
working on human-powered electric devices, but in a far sneakier
way. The idea of this parasitic power harvesting is to generate
power in an ancillary way while people are doing things like
walking or typing, or to pick up energy from the body as it
breathes, pumps blood and generates heat. All of these potential
sources of power were examined in 1995 by Dr. Thad Starner, who was
then a graduate student at the Media Lab and is now an assistant
professor at the Georgia Institute of Technology; he concluded that
the heel strike would be the most easily tapped and potent source
of energy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
