<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0790 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-HUMAN-POWER-2NDTA     08-02 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HUMAN-POWER-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: of energy.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since then, Dr. Joseph Paradiso, a researcher at the Media Lab,
and his students have developed various shoe inserts that convert
walking energy into electrical current. The inserts are made of a
piezoelectric material, which generates voltage when placed under
mechanical stress. Paradiso said the Maxwell Smart-like shoe could
power pagers, health monitors and emergency receivers, or it could
be used to charge a battery to power devices like phones or small
computers. ``It's probably the best way to take energy out of the
body,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the balance between energy harvesting and a comfy shoe isn't
easy to achieve. ``If you do it wrong,'' Paradiso said, ``they'll
be the worst shoes you ever wore.'' His research group is not the
only one hoping to develop a power shoe prototype. The Electric
Shoe Co., based in Britain, is also working on the technology.
</P>
<P>
   For such a shoe to be a viable commercial product, people would
have to find it to be durable, affordable and worth wearing as a
fashion statement.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to scavenge power from the human body is also of
interest to the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency, or
Darpa, which is also developing shoe-power programs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Nowak, a program manager at Darpa, said researchers
wanted to generate one to two watts per shoe. He said, ``Most
similar technologies produce only milliwatts, which won't have much
practical value for the military user.'' The shoes will be used to
power radios, computers and night vision and navigational
equipment, as well as to recharge batteries. They could also power
detectors that could warn soldiers away from mine fields
</P>
<P>
   One challenge for harnessing human power is finding ways to
match various systems with the energy needs of any given machine.
Radios and small lights require relatively small wattage, but
current human-powered generators could not be easily used to run
the family television. The Seiko kinetic watch, Auto Relay, is a
particularly good fit between the energy harvesting ability of the
device and the wattage it requires. All the wearer has to do is
move, and the watch works.
</P>
<P>
   Human power also lends itself to products like toys; to a land
mine detector that Freeplay is developing with Battelle, a military
product developer; and to a variety of transportation alternatives.
In addition to the commonplace, like bicycles and rowboats, the
human-powered transportation found on various Web sites includes
four-wheel bikes that drive like cars, landrowers (a tricycle that
is powered by pulling on the handlebars), watercycles and
submarines. One of the oddest sites features a human-powered
ornithopter, which perfectly captures the slightly kooky nature of
using the human body to power other devices. It raises the ancient
_ and some would argue, answered _ question, Can we fly with
human-powered flapping?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
