<SLUG> BC-CVN-SOCIAL-CONSERVATIVES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
SOCIAL CONSERVATIVES SHUNNED AT GOP CONVENTION &HT;    By DAN FREEDMAN
 &HT;    c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ There is no time allotted at the Republican
National Convention to a right-to-life speaker or any other
hard-core social conservative, but GOP planners did manage to find
a speaking slot for the World Wrestling Federation champ, ``The
Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   Within that contrast lies a bitter truth for the Republican
Party's right-wing true believers: They're being kept out of sight
as Texas Gov. George W. Bush's strategists bring on a parade of,
well, people you wouldn't expect at a Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   Take ``The Rock,'' for instance. Named Dwayne Johnson at his
birth, ``The Rock'' (aka ``the people's champion'') is the star of
Smackdown!, a wildly popular WWF wrestling show.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, ``The Rock'' helped House Speaker Dennis
Hastert, R-Ill., a former high school wrestling coach, call the
convention to order.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives were miffed.
</P>
<P>
   L. Brent Bozell III, a veteran social conservative activist who
is chairman of the Hollywood-based Parents Television Council,
condemned ``The Rock'' and ``Smackdown!'' as anti-woman, anti-black
and grotesquely violent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I highly doubt that a man of your character would want to
share the podium with (a wrestler) who regularly uses obscene and
profane language, has taken metal chairs, a shovel and a
sledgehammer to opponents, and refers to women's genitalia'' in
slang words Bozell wrote Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Bozell argued that an appearance by ``The
Rock'' would undermine any Republican effort to reduce television
violence or tone down popular music lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll come back to haunt them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rock'' is only the most visible representative of the
non-traditional speakers and performers at the Republican
convention. The first three nights have featured Hispanic
businessmen, pelvis-thrusting entertainers, students from a Houston
charter school, an openly gay member of Congress and a speech by
former Joint Chiefs of Staff chairman Gen. Colin Powell about his
support of abortion rights and affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   But for Republican social conservatives, there's been a
deafening silence on topics such as banning abortion and halting
gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``There ought to be someone on the convention schedule who
exemplifies the pro-life cause; helping women through alternatives
to abortion,'' said Charles Donovan, head of the conservative
Family Research Council. ``We're more concerned about the messages
they're not sending than how some of those messages are being
interpreted at this convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, who campaigned for the Republican presidential
nomination earlier this year as an anti-abortion conservative, said
the convention's tone would be different had he been chosen as the
party's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wasn't,'' he said in an interview. Still, he added, ``on
Election Day voters will not be confused about which party is
pro-life and which party is not. If there is confusion, Bush will
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   While conservatives weren't invited to address the convention,
they did score victories in the GOP platform, getting tough
language on abortion and gays.
</P>
<P>
   Bush operatives smile when asked about the social conservative
freeze-out.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's ``style of leadership is `we're all God's children,'''
said Don Evans, his campaign manager. ``It's `leave no child
behind,' whether that child is African-American or Hispanic or
grows up to have a different sexual orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are having fun with Republican angst over contentious
social issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've put their crazy aunts in the attic ... and they're
rolling out all this diversity imagery to make the party look like
what it's not _ tolerant,'' said Craig Smith, a former aide to
President Clinton and briefly Vice President Al Gore's campaign
manager.
</P>
<P>
   At least one social conservative is philosophical about
invisibility on the podium.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were insurgents, it was more important for one of our
people to speak,'' said Randy Tate, former head of the Christian
Coalition and now the head of Republican affairs for the political
website, Voter.com. ``Now religious conservatives are mainstreamed
into the party, so there's less of a need to have `your guy' up
there. They feel comfortable with Bush. They're not being put in
the back seat.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or via e-mail:
dan(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
