<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0793 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-GOP-CONVENTION-AR     08-02 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GOP-CONVENTION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATHER BE IN PHILADELPHIA? GOP CONVENTION'S ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT9 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ In the media tents off the floor of the
Republican National Convention here, in a corner dubbed Internet
Alley, the crowd is young, the style is geek chic and the latest in
computer gadgetry is on display. It's all part of a not-so-quiet
Internet revolution, say those who work here, that has the
potential to shake up the world of politics.
</P>
<P>
   Just as television made its political debut at the Republican
convention in Philadelphia in 1948 _ and politics has never been
the same _ the Web has made its way to the convention here. Whether
it is a way of connecting delegates and building party loyalty or a
means of promoting grass-roots political activism among those not
present, a wired world has been constructed here to link the
convention floor to cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   There are ``dot-com delegates'' participating in a virtual
convention. Politicians who once never knew the difference between
e-mail and eBay are now lining up to participate in political chat
rooms with ``e-jockeys'' as hosts. One Web site, with five
360-degree cameras, offers streaming video that allows site
visitors to scan the convention floor, zooming in and out for
close-ups of individual delegations and delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Polls are being taken online while speakers are on the podium,
providing a real-time reaction to their speeches. And there are
chat rooms, feedback forums, discussion groups and ways for Web
users to talk back and talk about politicians.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to break down the physical barriers between those
who are at the convention and those who are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not replacing any medium _ we are a new medium,'' said
David Borhman, chief executive of Pseudo.com, which offers the
360-degree cameras and online chats with politicians. ``We are
going to have a role in politics, but we don't know what it will
be. This convention is a test for us, just as the first television
cameras here 52 years ago were a test.''
</P>
<P>
   The Webmasters here say their sites are superior to television
because they are interactive while television is not. Television
provides viewers with a set body of information at a set time that
is selected by the network. Web surfers, not bound by the same
constraints, are able to turn to these sites to pull up candidates'
speeches, videos of the proceedings and party position papers or to
engage in political chat rooms when and for as long as they want.
Television networks have tapped into the Web world, too, offering
live video and audio from the convention and message boards.
</P>
<P>
   Those in Internet Alley say that the Web has the ability to
encourage grass-roots political involvement at a time when voter
participation is declining and that it can challenge the ability of
parties and pundits to set the political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is hard to determine the exact impact these sites
are having. Their audience is still small _ none of the sites are
on any list of the 100 most popular sites. But Pseudo.com says its
chat rooms are filled with people saying they are new to the
political process. And on MTV's ChooseOrLose.com, the most heavily
visited part of the site is its SpeakUp section, where Web users
share political opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Schneider, a research fellow at the Annenberg Public
Policy Center at the University of Pennsylvania, said: ``Can we
measure the impact on this election? Not at this time. But what we
are seeing is political junkies turning to the Web for information,
and Web junkies turning into these political sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert B. Vanasse, vice president for programming at Voter.com,
said, ``What we are doing is not just chats and message boards.''
The site offers text and video of the convention floor proceedings,
comparisons of the candidates' records, chat rooms with politicians
and a daily topic for political debate with an interactive poll.
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting to miss an opportunity, the Republican Party has
also jumped on the Web bandwagon. Its convention site,
www.gopconvention.com, not only provides information on daily
events to delegates, but also connects the activities here to some
15,000 dot-com delegates who are participating online.
</P>
<P>
   Dot-com delegates _ anyone who wants to be one can register _
receive daily e-mail messages telling them the ``talking points''
the party gives to every delegate each morning in case they run
into reporters. The online delegates can submit questions to be
answered each day by Republican leaders here, receive daily news
reports about their state's delegation and participate in surveys.
</P>
<P>
   For the party, it's a way of capturing e-mail addresses for
future mailings in the fall campaign and a way of building
enthusiasm. ``E-mail, e-mail, e-mail,'' said Lawrence J. Purpuro,
deputy chief of staff for the Republican National Committee,
explaining the site's purpose. ``We are out to build relationships
with the party. For us, the Web is a powerful medium. We can give
folks the information we want; we can ask them what issues they
care about. Because it is interactive, it is essentially the best
focus group money can buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many in Internet Alley see information flowing in the
other direction, from ordinary voters and to the parties.
SpeakOut.com, a nonpartisan site designed to increase political
activism, has the ability to record a visitor's response to a
convention speaker during the speech on something called,
informally, a ``mood meter.'' Once signed in, a person watches the
speech on MSNBC and then continually scrolls along an online bar
recording reactions, favorable or less favorable, to each line of
the speech.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   SpeakOut.com puts these analyses online. For instance, of 1,200
people using the mood meter to judge the first convention night
speeches, Laura Bush scored particularly well among women who were
undecided. Colin L. Powell scored as high as George W. Bush's taped
presentation among Bush voters, but he was outscored by Bush among
undecided voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I explained to one congressman what was going to be happening
during his speech,'' said Rekha Chalasani, director of public
affairs for SpeakOut.Com. ``He just looked at me and said, `You've
got to be kidding.' But we aren't. Conventions are so scripted.
This gets beyond the pundits and prognosticators and shows how
people are really reacting.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Vitale, director of political programs for Voter.com, said:
``We were able to use our site as a channel to give the Republican
party input on the platform. The Web is making it hard for those in
Washington to be so isolated.''
</P>
<P>
   There are computer kiosks put up by Voter.com in the hotels
where delegates are staying to provide information on daily
convention events. Congressional Quarterly and Motorola are
distributing pagers with e-mail capability and access to news
stories to anyone asking for them. (The Republican Party turned
down an offer to provide every delegate with one, but the Democrats
will be giving them to all delegates at their convention in Los
Angeles, Aug. 14 to 17.)
</P>
<P>
   Where will this all lead? ``I could see the day,'' said Burton
Pines, director of Internet operations for the Republican National
Committee, ``when we have a three-day virtual convention and a
one-day real one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
