<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author finds new winner in perfect man
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Linda Howard has come a long way since she wrote her first book
about children lost in the wilderness. Of course, the Hokes Bluff,
Ala., writer was only 9, and the story's readership was limited to
her family.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the 50-year-old author has attracted a wider
audience. Seven of her novels have been best sellers, and her
newest, ``Mr. Perfect'' (Pocket Books, $24.95), appears headed that
way.
</P>
<P>
   Part romance novel, part suspense thriller, ``Mr. Perfect''
begins with four women jotting down a list of attributes that make
a perfect man. Some of the qualities include faithfulness,
dependability, a sense of humor and certain sexual abilities. The
women never imagine the list will make them the targets of a
killer.
</P>
<P>
   Howard says she didn't bother polling women about their
requirements for the perfect man. ``I was cleaning up the kitchen,
and this conversation started playing in my head between a group of
friends as to what would make a perfect man,'' she says. ``The
whole book was built around that conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, she adds, most women wouldn't want a perfect man. ``If
he was perfect, they'd want to mess him up. The whole point of the
book is that no one's perfect; you have to work and adjust and
compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   In the novel, the men are threatened by the list. Howard doesn't
have that problem with her husband, Gary Howington.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't read my books,'' she says, laughing. ``He's an
outdoorsman, and he fishes the Bass Masters tournaments. That's
what he does for a living. He hasn't even seen the list.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
