<SLUG> BC-TV-FUGITIVE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV's `Fugitive' goes on run in Savannah
 &HT;    By Jill Young Miller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Dr. Richard Kimble resumed his harried flight
from police Lt. Philip Gerard here this week. ``Yesterday I spent
10 hours sprinting, in the heat, on the cobblestone streets, up and
down the stairs,'' said Kimble, aka Tim Daly, who plays the
doc-on-the-lam in the upcoming CBS revival of ``The Fugitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the grinding workout, Savannah's allure wasn't lost on
the actor. ``I love all these little parks,'' Daly said Wednesday,
cooling down as an SUV ferried him from a shoot at the riverfront
to another location, near Chippewa Square. ``The Spanish moss. It's
a really nice little town.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the town ``Fugitive'' producers chose for the revival's
first episode, expected to air in October, following a pilot that
starts the saga in Chicago. As in the classic '60s series, Daly's
Kimble is wrongly convicted of murdering his wife, then is chased
from city to city by Gerard, in turn pursuing the real killer, a
mysterious one-armed man.
</P>
<P>
   The series will be shot on location in places around the
country. ``I'm choosing cities that are very identifiable,'' said
R.W. Griffin, an executive producer. From Savannah, Kimble scurries
to Charleston, S.C., Philadelphia, Atlantic City, N.J., New Orleans
and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   And Atlanta? ``Atlanta's not ruled out,'' said John McNamara,
another executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a hitch. ``What we're looking for are things you
couldn't see elsewhere,'' McNamara said.
</P>
<P>
   Savannah has lured many a production company with its
live-oak-lined streets. Savannah police officer Julia Krebs works
security at enough movie and TV shoots every year that she can fund
her vacations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pretty low-key compared to what I've seen,'' Krebs
said. ``When Clint Eastwood was here, people were going crazy.
Screaming. Trying to rush him to get his autograph.'' Eastwood
directed 1997's ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil,'' which
was both set and filmed in Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   When Robertut Ryan likes it when TV and movie stars visit.
``It's great for the city, because they shoot a lot of the scenery,
and tourism is one of our biggest assets.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
