<HEADER>
A0802 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      08-02 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP CABINET MEMBER ADMITS ACCEPTING QUESTIONABLE DONATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The government of Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori was
slammed by its second political scandal in a week Wednesday when
one of his top advisers admitted accepting millions of yen in
questionable political donations.
</P>
<P>
   The chief Cabinet secretary, Hidenao Nakagawa, who is the
government's top spokesman, acknowledged that he had received 8.5
million yen, or $77,810 at current exchange rates, from two persons
in 1997. The maximum donation an individual can lawfully make to a
politician is 1.5 million yen, and the amounts that came to
Nakagawa above that limit arrived in a round-about way.
</P>
<P>
   Nakagawa holds what is arguably the second-highest ranking job
after the prime minister's. Additionally, he is a member of the
inner circle of ruling party politicians that call the shots behind
the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no legal violations involved, and I reported to the
Home Affairs Ministry,'' Nakagawa said, denying any impropriety.
``But I will be careful in the future not to repeat it.''
</P>
<P>
   While the donations were questionable, they may not have been
illegal, and it remains to be seen if Nakagawa will be forced to
step down or face any legal action.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday, Kimitaka Kuze, another Cabinet member, was forced
to resign as head of the Financial Reconstruction Commission after
acknowledging that he had received 230 million yen, or $2.1
million, for advisory work he did for Mitsubishi Trust and Banking
Corp. over 13 years that ended in 1996. He also accepted 100
million yen, or $915,000, from the head of a condominium developer.
</P>
<P>
   There has been much speculation inside the ruling party, as well
as in the private sector, about why the scandals are breaking one
after the other. Many believe that it may even be the result of
turmoil inside the party, as members jockey to determine who will
take on the mantle of Noboru Takeshita, the former prime minister
whose influence shaped Japanese politics for three decades until he
died shortly before the recent election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, money politics is nothing new in Japan, so the
question is why are all these revelations coming out now?''
Marshall Gittler, a currency strategist at the Bank of America,
asked in a report to investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks as if someone has it in for Prime Minister Mori,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Mori's Cabinet, appointed after general elections in June in
which his ruling Liberal Democratic Party suffered a drubbing in
urban areas, is suffering some of the lowest approval ratings of
any government since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister, who is currently undergoing a grilling
during a special parliamentary session over various financial
matters, has been limited to using prepared scripts because of his
penchant for unwittingly making politically incorrect comments.
During the parliamentary debate on Tuesday, he read the same answer
in response to three different questions.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Nakagawa's insistence that he did nothing illegal, the
way in which the money arrived suggests that someone involved knew
the donations were not entirely legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a Hiroshima businessman donated a total of 4.5
million yen to Nakagawa. The amount allowed by law, 1.5 million
yen, was accounted for as a donation, according to a Home Affairs
Ministry report. But an additional 3 million yen went to two
political groups that then turned the money over to Nakagawa, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Nakagawa received 1.5 million yen from another unidentified
businessman, who also contributed another 2.5 million yen through
two political groups, one of which was used by the first
businessman as well.
</P>
<P>
   The three political organizations, the report said, all have the
same Tokyo address.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1808EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0806 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-OPERA-FIGARO-HNS &LR;      08-02 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-FIGARO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
SANTA FE OFFERS AN AUTHORITATIVE `FIGARO' &HT;    (Photos available from
http://www.santafeopera.org/PressPhotos/PressPhotos.htm.)
 &HT;    By CHARLES WARD
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. _ What is it about nobility and opera?
</P>
<P>
   On Monday evening, Santa Fe Opera allowed Verdi's libertine Duke
of Mantua to forage the stage for sexual conquests. The next, it
trotted out Mozart's lecherous Count Almaviva to remind the
audience that _ in opera, at least _ noblemen are from some other
sexual galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the two ``gentlemen'' were treated in very different
ways. In ``Rigoletto,'' Verdi left his cad unscathed _ he's just
the catalyst for another operatic tragedy. In ``The Marriage of
Figaro,'' Mozart used Almaviva to drive home fundamental lessons
about social inequality.
</P>
<P>
   Mozart and librettist Lorenzo da Ponte did their teaching with
humor, thanks to Pierre Augustin Caron de Beaumarchais, author of
the original 18th-century French drama. Aided by an English
libretto projected electronically to each seat, Tuesday's capacity
audience tittered and cackled as Almaviva's household thwarted his
fundamental goal _ reviving the (began ital)droit du seigneur,(end
ital) which he had recently revoked in a gesture of enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   The four-act ``Figaro'' occurs in a still-feudal household of
servants and nobility. Almaviva has a simple, base motive. Susanna,
his wife's maid, is about to marry his valet, Figaro. Once more he,
the master of the house, wants the right to enjoy first sexual
relations with a female servant on her wedding night.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone else thinks the count is despicable, for this
and other antics. His long-suffering wife leads the servants in a
conspiracy to teach him a lesson about faithfulness and chastity.
He gets the message in a nighttime garden scene when Susanna and
the Countess swap clothes. The Count ends up trying to seduce his
own wife.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the entire household mirrors Almaviva's own
ambiguity about relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the Count's moral example, the freshly pubescent
Cherubino is constantly underfoot, even after Almaviva tries to
send him off to the army. During the young man's many attempts to
be near the ones he loves, he hides behind a chair, locks himself
in the Countess' dressing room and dresses up as a maid presenting
flowers to the royal couple. Always there is complicity from
someone with a weak spot for his youthful innocence.
</P>
<P>
   This maelstrom swirls around the Count. Seemingly all-powerful,
he is actually helpless in the face of his household's collective
determination. They thwart every ploy he uses to get to Susanna.
Even a plot to blackmail Figaro into marrying the maid of the
count's friend, Dr. Bartolo, fails. Figaro turns out to be the love
child of maid Marcellina and Bartolo.
</P>
<P>
   Almaviva is right when he complains that his servants have
become brazen. Their capacity to eviscerate his power is the reason
``The Marriage of Figaro'' remains more powerful than
``Rigoletto.'' That's especially true when a cast like Tuesday's
delivers Mozart's extraordinary drama and music with such authority
and pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Crucially, director Thor Steingraber encouraged the lead men to
play their characters with a democratic nonchalance. German
baritone Jochen Schmeckenbecher and Canadian bass-baritone John
Relyea, respectively, portrayed Almaviva and Figaro with a lanky
physicality that destroyed any pretense to the manor. With a rich
sound, Schmeckenbecher ranged from smoldering sensuality to
smoldering rage. With a more ringing tone, the tall Relyea found
Figaro's backbone in the sense of injustice of the otherwise
easygoing husband-to-be.
</P>
<P>
   The quiet star was English soprano Catrin Wyn-Davies as Susanna.
With dignity, outrage and a show of camaraderie, she held her own
among American veterans of operatic comedies, especially Kevin
Langan as Bartolo and Judith Christin as Marcellina.
</P>
<P>
   English soprano Alwyn Mellor gave the Countess a wounded dignity
in her two great arias, delivered with fuller but less pointed
sound than other major cast members. Joyce DiDonato was bubbling
and exuberant as Cherubino.
</P>
<P>
   Irishman Kenneth Montgomery, who has conducted at Santa Fe
regularly since 1982, led a zestful accompaniment that occasionally
needed a touch more legato and lyricism.
</P>
<P>
   The production was a revival, with sets and costumes by Robert
Perdziola.
</P>
<P>
   Footnote: With a 9 p.m. starting time, ``Figaro'' ran past 12:30
a.m. A sizable portion of Tuesday's audience left during the
intermission before Act Four.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
