<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0808 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-EASTERN-EUROPE-2800(2     08-02 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EASTERN-EUROPE-2800(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FOUR SEMI-UGLY AMERICANS' OFFICIAL BUT MOSTLY USELESS GUIDE TO
EASTERN EUROPE'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MIKE COCHRAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST, Hungary _ We got robbed in Prague, sunburned at a
quaint German village and bombarded by an American rock band as we
hiked through the Brandenburg Gate in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   We checked out Checkpoint Charlie, paddlewheeled up the Elbe
River at Dresden, knocked down Hungarian goulash in Budapest and
pigged out shamelessly on wienerschnitzel all across Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Late one evening, en route to a lake resort, we stumbled into a
secluded countryside inn and watched quietly from the terrace as a
frisky doe played hide-and-seek along the grassy riverbank below.
</P>
<P>
   We did all this in 21 hectic but mostly fun-filled days and
nights while composing what we cleverly called ``Four Semi-Ugly
Americans' Official But Mostly Useless Guide to Eastern Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   However, my editor decided ``Iron Curtain: 2000'' was a mite
more stylish.
</P>
<P>
   With no hotel reservations and only a vague itinerary, our
mission was to explore the former Iron Curtain countries of
Czechoslovakia and Hungary and the former communist enclaves of
East Berlin and Dresden. We would also look in on the officially
neutral but pro-Western country of Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Our friends Bob and Mona joined wife Sondra and me on our June
odyssey, which unfolded more than a decade after the four of us
traveled together across non-communist Western Europe. Motivated
now by collective curiosity, and packed in a rented Lancia station
wagon, we would pierce the phantom partition and visit the people
and places that were pretty much off-limits during our previous
trip.
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of research, we would also sample Europe's
world-famous beers and wines and such local delights as wild boar,
grilled goose and goulash laced with horse meat. I'll confess
upfront that when faced with a dilemma, we invariably opted for
wienerschnitzel. This is fried veal cutlets coated with eggs and
bread crumbs, and roughly equivalent to our chicken-fried steak
without cream gravy.
</P>
<P>
   It normally is served with one of the basic food groups: french
fries. &QL; 
--- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As luck would have it, we arrived in Europe along with a record
heat wave, a surge of soccer hooliganism at the European
Championships and our own President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Our first major destination, we decided, would be Berlin, via
Nuremberg, Bamberg and, most notably, Rothenberg. Medieval
Rothenberg and its lovely Tauber River anchor the ``Romantic
Road,'' which runs from the River Main at Wurzburg south to Fussen
in the foothills of the Swiss and Austrian Alps.
</P>
<P>
   We rolled into Rothenberg during a wine festival and, at a
sidewalk cafe, discovered the country's seasonal obsession with
spargel (asparagus.) Many restaurants feature it daily in a variety
of dishes.
</P>
<P>
   We discovered also that nearby tables were filled with young
German men and that a group of Japanese tourists had appeared on
the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty-five years ago, we were killing each other,'' I
observed. &QL; 
___ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arriving on the outskirts of Berlin in late afternoon, we
realized the pitfalls of scorning room reservations. Hotels and
guest houses were full, and we spent the night in a hovel called
the Hong Kong Haus.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but just being in the reunified city was worth any
unpleasantness.
</P>
<P>
   Yielding to popular pressure, the wall was opened in 1989 after
separating the eastern and western zones since the Cold War days of
1961. This created what some call a new Germany. Eleven years
later, we could tell little difference between East and West,
although there is a building frenzy and fewer English-speaking
Germans in the eastern sector.
</P>
<P>
   A tour guide points out that within its unified boundaries,
Germany remains a nation of diversity, ``where the people and
cultures vary as dramatically as the landscapes.''
</P>
<P>
   A young German financier would tell me later that many East
Germans have been slow to grasp capitalism and to reap the economic
benefits it offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The East German people have another way to think,'' was the
way he put it. ``They don't know how to realize the dream. If you
come from communism to capitalism, you have to turn around. You
must change completely, not only for yourself, but your family and
your friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is changing. ... Some people find their way fast,
but most people don't.''
</P>
<P>
   While our mates toured the nearby museum, Bob and I researched a
Berliner Pilsner outside the Cafe Adler at the spot known worldwide
as Checkpoint Charlie. A sign remains as a permanent reminder of
that grim period, during which 152 people died while trying to flee
to the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``YOU ARE LEAVING THE AMERICAN SECTOR,'' the sign warns.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a historical marker of sorts that recounts the
Oct. 27, 1961, checkpoint confrontation between U.S. and Soviet
tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day later,'' it says, ``the tanks withdrew as neither the
first secretary of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union Nikita
Khrushchev nor the US President John F. Kennedy wanted a military
confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Europeans remain enthusiastic admirers of Kennedy,
and often buttonhole American visitors to discuss his presidency
and his assassination.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving the checkpoint, we walked down the street and
took pictures of the crumbling wall above a bunker that once housed
the World War II Gestapo headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, we strolled through the former ``no man's
land'' beyond Brandenburg Gate, where an American rock band
entertained hundreds of Sunday afternoon bikers, skaters, lovers,
families and tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the tune ``Come Together,'' a red-haired woman
wiggled from the crowd and, trancelike, danced about crazily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Must be an American,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably a Texan,'' Bob replied. &QL; 
___ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We spent the night on a small lake outside Berlin, then headed
for Dresden via the autobahn, which has no official upper speed
limit. The recommended 130 kilometers, the equivalent of 80 mph, is
routinely ignored.
</P>
<P>
   We crossed the historic River Elbe at Dresden and parked beside
the heavily bomb-damaged, 14th-century Church of Our Blessed Lady,
which is undergoing meticulous restoration.
</P>
<P>
   The church is called the crown of Dresden, the heart and soul of
the city.
</P>
<P>
   A cultural metropolis, the war-ravaged city itself is an
architectural masterpiece, and its skyline above the Elbe is one of
the most striking sights in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   This is all the more astounding since Allied bombers reduced
much of the city to rubble in a series of raids, the three most
devastating on Feb. 13-14, 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Historians say that more than 3,000 tons of incendiary bombs and
explosives killed thousands in those two days and destroyed a
10-square-mile area of the city. In a book on Dresden, author
Gerhart Hauptmann, who called the city the ``bright morning star of
my youth,'' said of the incredible devastation: MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever has forgotten how to cry, learned it again during the
destruction of Dresden.'' &QL; 
___ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was in a beer garden on the Elbe that we met Frank Molitor,
the Dresden financier who in turn introduced us to Ines Wilhelm, a
beautiful young opera singer.
</P>
<P>
   Molitor told us how the country changed dramatically for the
better after the lifting of the Iron Curtain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a better way of life because you can do what you want.
... You can grow, you can work and you can fail,'' he said. ``You
can make mistakes, and you have to make mistakes to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilhelm said a unified Germany is on the verge of greatness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now Germans on our own,'' she explained, then dismissed
the Russians as ``unimportant'' and declared: ``They sold out
Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   Our party closed down the garden that night, and Molitor joined
us the next morning on the paddleboat Dresden for a quick trip up
the Elbe. We left the boat several miles upriver and took a railway
car to a hilltop high above the distant city.
</P>
<P>
   It was but one of countless extraordinary sights. &QL; 
___ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We left that afternoon for Prague but got sidetracked in the
quaint little river town of Konigstein. Rarely moved by castles and
cathedrals, I was awed by Festung Konigstein, the mountain fortress
above town with a smashing view of the Elbe as it winds gently
through German farmlands and forests.
</P>
<P>
   After hiking up another mountainside, where we drank beer and
wine with a bored cat, we drove along the river to the border and
crossed into the Czech Republic at Hrensko. Our unofficial greeting
party consisted of young prostitutes in revealing shorts and tops,
slinking provocatively along the highway.
</P>
<P>
   Our guide book did not mention the girls of the afternoon but
did point out that since 1989, when the country discarded 40 years
of communist rule, the Czechs had been finding their footing as a
new republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the dawn of the 21st century,'' it said, ``the country is
coping with the difficulties and benefits of adapting to Western
capitalism and establishing a new social and economic order.''
</P>
<P>
   As we drove through the lush green hills and farmlands, it was
clear that, while beautiful, the country did not possess the clean,
crisp, prosperous look of Germany or Austria. But Prague, the
``Golden City,'' was a wondrous discovery, its center bursting with
energy and embracing the Vltava River on its east and west banks.
</P>
<P>
   On our second day in the capital, we parked outside Prague
Castle and spent hours walking the cobblestone streets, alleys and
passageways and exploring the gardens, museums, cathedrals,
palaces, concert halls, shops and outdoor cafes.
</P>
<P>
   We crossed the river on the famous Charles Bridge, all abubble
with street musicians, puppeteers, vendors and artists, and entered
the Old Town and its historic and cobbled Old Town Square.
</P>
<P>
   As we marveled over the city's spheres and domes, two thugs were
busily breaking into our station wagon and rifling through our
luggage. &QL; 
___ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A man and his young son interrupted the thieves and called
police, which no doubt prevented them from wiping us out totally.
As it was, they escaped with suitcases, money, clothes, a tape
recorder, toiletries, books and prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The Czech police and the American Embassy were sympathetic,
although of little help. But it was the purloined drugs that
triggered a bureaucratic nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of phone calls and e-mails, a friend shipped our
medications from the States to Vienna for delivery to my former
employer, The Associated Press. The medications arrived promptly,
but we never got them. I'll spare you the gory details, but be
assured, and warned, that Austrian Customs officials have few
rivals when it comes to bureaucratic stubbornness.
</P>
<P>
   We fled Prague but spent two more days driving through Czech
towns and villages and allowing Bob to practice his German-flavored
pronunciation on the unsuspecting populace.
</P>
<P>
   We crossed the border into Austria on a Sunday and were speeding
toward Vienna at 110 mph when once again we tumbled into the
clutches of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Bob thought that Austria, like Germany, had no upper speed limit
on the autobahn. He thought that until a motorcyclist dressed in
black, including helmet, goggles and boots, waved us over.
</P>
<P>
   After Bob paid the equivalent of a $45 fine and returned to the
car, Mona asked: ``You think that was a real cop?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't know,'' grumbled Bob. ``But his gun was.'' &QL; 
--- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We caught our first glimpse of the Blue Danube approaching
Passau on the Czech-Austrian border and celebrated at a sidewalk
cafe with wine and nut-encrusted trout. Passau is a prime tourist
destination, the city where the rivers Danube, Inn and Ilz
converge.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, we invaded Hungary, arriving 56 years after the
German occupation and 52 years after the communists seized power.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, the Hungarians rebelled against communist rule, but the
revolt was crushed by Soviet troops. It was not until 1989 that the
Iron Curtain began to lift.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Czech Republic, Hungary is still undergoing tremendous
change, a decade after the lifting of 40 years of Soviet-imposed
communism.
</P>
<P>
   We rolled into Budapest on a Tuesday and wasted no time plunging
into bowls of spicy goulash soup at one of the many sidewalk cafes
hugging the river.
</P>
<P>
   I'm ashamed to admit that it was almost as good as chili.
</P>
<P>
   I'm also ashamed to admit that I did not previously know that
Buda and Pest were two totally different cities separated by the
Danube until the 19th century, when linked by the Chain Bridge.
What emerged was Budapest, the ``Queen of the Danube.''
</P>
<P>
   A bull's-eye, that.
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon, we drove up Gellert Hill on the west side of the
river and, with birds serenading us from the treetops, took in the
magnificent view of the city sprawling below. The architecture is
not only ancient but grand, and among the most famous in Europe.
And in the distance is Margaret Island, a cluster of gardens in the
middle of the Danube.
</P>
<P>
   We left Budapest reluctantly and all too soon, but the cooler
Hungarian lake resort of Balaton beckoned, and beyond that a
whirlwind tour of Austria, the crossroads of modern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   I have seen little to rival the grandeur of the Austrian Alps
and the breathtaking beauty of the mountains, lakes, rivers and
forests east of Salzburg. We spent three unforgettable days in the
latter, at a charming lakeside village called St. Wolfgang.
</P>
<P>
   From the balcony of our hotel on the water, we watched two
golden-orange sunsets, one moonrise and an unexpected, late-night
fireworks display that lit up the lake and startled our new
friends, a pair of snow-white swans.
</P>
<P>
   The idyllic little hamlet provided a perfect, peaceful ending to
a frenetic three-week excursion. The toppling of the Iron Curtain
did indeed open the once-hostile borders to free and easy access,
richly enhancing the European experience, not only for foreigners
but visitors from sister countries, as well. With stormy but
storybook histories and ancient architecture, the two river cities
of Prague and Budapest are among the most exquisite and exciting in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Because of morning flights, we spent our final night on the
outskirts of Frankfurt, researching for the last time the hops and
grapes of Europe. We pronounced them universally excellent. Over
nightcaps at an intimate little Italian cafe, the four worn-out,
semi-Ugly Americans also agreed to return one day for a similar
European escapade.
</P>
<P>
   One, we vowed, without cops, robbers and Customs.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
