<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-HOLLYWOOD-REVIEW-N     08-02 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HOLLYWOOD-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WITHOUT LYING DOWN': WOMEN WIELDING POWER IN A WIDE-OPEN
HOLLYWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Broadcast notes at end of review) 
 By JULIE SALAMON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's great that Turner Classics Movies has revived many rare old
films that were written, directed or produced by women for its
Women Film Pioneers series. So I'll take it as a backhanded
compliment to women (and interested men, of course) that the cable
network is broadcasting many of these 37 films in the middle of the
night. Someone must be assuming that all of us know how to program
our VCRs.
</P>
<P>
   The five-week-long series begins, however, in prime time, with
an 8 p.m. premiere of a documentary called ``Without Lying Down,''
based on Cari Beauchamp's insightful book about the screenwriter
Frances Marion and other powerful women in early Hollywood.
Beauchamp also produced and wrote this spirited piece of work with
Bridget Terry, and it will be immediately followed by an overnight
retrospective of Marion's films.
</P>
<P>
   Without being sentimental or star-struck, Thursday night's
documentary evokes a comparatively innocent Hollywood after the
turn of the century, when movies became the lodestone for writers
and actors. Women quickly filled the ranks _ before people figured
out how much money there was to be made in the business. Almost
half the screenwriters were women, and they weren't relegated to
``women's pictures.'' Bess Meredyth was co-screenwriter of the
original ``Ben-Hur.'' Lois Weber, a successful director, ran her
own production company.
</P>
<P>
   This was the world that drew Frances Owens, a young woman from a
good San Francisco family who had worked as a photographer's model
but had larger ambitions. She headed for Hollywood, sketchbook in
hand, and was drawing in a park when the vaudeville star Marie
Dressler came by. They had met before, in San Francisco, so it
wasn't entirely strange for Dressler to stop and urge Owens to jump
into the ``cement mixer'' of the movie business.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, who soon became Frances Marion during a brief acting
career, would have jumped anyway. The woman portrayed in this
documentary was adventuresome and extremely talented. She would
write the screenplays for more than 150 movies during her career,
direct, act and become one of the first women correspondents to go
overseas during World War I.
</P>
<P>
   She was also loyal. When talking pictures arrived, she
discovered that her old friend Dressler, who had become a silent
movie star, had been dismissed as obsolete and was about to take a
job as a housekeeper. By then, Owens-Marion had become one of
Hollywood's most prominent screenwriters, assigned to adapt ``Anna
Christie'' for Greta Garbo. She wrote a part for her old friend
Dressler, whose career was revived in the medium's new incarnation.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary deftly uses the Frances Marion story to
illuminate how she and other women were able to capitalize on the
freewheeling creativity that kept the movie business humming in the
early years. It helps that this prolific writer left behind plenty
of commentary, which the actress Kathy Bates reads with a strong,
bright voice, evoking real feeling for Marion and her vigorous
outlook.
</P>
<P>
   The women helped one another. Marion was the host of weekly
parties for Hollywood's female producers, writers and actors where
they screened their movies and complained about the business.
Marion briskly described these relationships like this: ``In the
picture business you can spend your life searching for a man to
look up to without lying down.''
</P>
<P>
   Her career was jump-started by her friendship with Mary
Pickford, with whom she collaborated on more than a dozen silent
movies, many of them adaptations of classic children's literature.
It is fascinating to see clips of Pickford, in her 20s,
convincingly playing adolescent girls in movies like ``The Little
Princess'' and ``Pollyanna.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from its historical interest, the documentary cogently
discusses Marion's screenwriting skill, using a scene from ``The
Scarlet Letter'' starring Lillian Gish to illustrate the challenge
of translating prose into a silent film _ and to make a novel about
Puritans accessible to a Jazz Age audience. Later, when movies had
sound and she was writing ``The Big House,'' her Oscar-winning
screenplay about prison life, Marion toured San Quentin and
listened to the inmates talk. ``My ears became attuned to their
vernacular,'' she reported.
</P>
<P>
   An elderly Jackie Cooper, recalling the part she wrote for him
as a child star in the 1931 film ``The Champ,'' says, ``Everything
was so believable, what this boy had to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Marion's private life had the ingredients for a Hollywood
bio-pic _ with her overseas reporting adventures and her loving but
tragically curtailed marriage to Fred Thomson, who trained to be a
Presbyterian minister but became one of his era's most famous
Hollywood cowboys, until his death at 38. But she was not
self-pitying, even when the business became an industry and women
lost their foothold. Lois Weber, who gave Frances Marion her start
in the business, died so poor that Marion paid for her funeral.
After Marion herself was demoted to script doctor by Louis B.
Mayer, she had the wherewithal to turn to painting and sculpture as
well as other forms of writing.
</P>
<P>
   Modern female filmmakers (including the director Martha Coolidge
and the producer Polly Platt) comment on Marion's craft and legacy,
offering smart analysis but with the earnestness and
self-consciousness of our age. They appreciate and perhaps envy
Frances Marion, who was from a different time, before the industry
hardened, when possibilities seemed endless because it was all new.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `WITHOUT LYING DOWN': Frances Marion and the Power of Women in
Hollywood
</P>
<P>
   Turner Classic Movies, Thursday night at 8, ET. (conform local
listings). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Documentary based in part on the book ``Without Lying Down:
Frances Marion and the Powerful Women of Early Hollywood'' by Cari
Beauchamp. Written and produced by Bridget Terry and Beauchamp.
Directed by Terry. Eric R. Anderson, director of photography.
Original music by Glenn A. Jordan. Tamera Dougherty and Eve Gage,
editors. Produced in association with the UCLA Film and Television
Archive. Hugh Hefner, executive producer; Carl Lindahl, executive
producer for TCM. Narrated by Uma Thurman, with Kathy Bates
supplying the voice of Frances Marion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
