</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW YELLING AT YOUR PC CAN ACTUALLY BE USEFUL
</HEADLINE>
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frustrated Web surfers who yell at the computer when they can't
find something online now have a little friend who won't take it
personally.
</P>
<P>
   One Voice Technologies has just released IVAN, a voice-activated
on-screen servant of sorts, which never loses its cool.
</P>
<P>
   IVAN, which stands for Intelligent Voice-Activated Navigator,
appears on the browser screen as a small cartoon character
resembling a smiling globe with skinny legs. (Web surfers not
enamored of such anthropomorphic whimsy can choose to turn off the
visual aspect of the program.) Instead of the traditional Web
point-and-click action, users can simply tell IVAN things like
``Show me the current price of Cisco stock'' or ``I need to buy a
book,'' and the software will present a Web site or a page of
search results that matches the spoken keywords. Although the IVAN
program will not restrict access to any pages, companies that are
partners with One Voice will usually be at the top of the hit list.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking out loud to browse the Web has been possible for a
while. Dragon Systems, a company that makes speech-recognition
software, incorporates a feature into many of its programs,
including Naturally Speaking Preferred, that lets users surf pages
by saying Web addresses out loud. But IVAN will actually interact
with the user and even ask questions it needs more information. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IVAN, which combines IBM's Via Voice speech recognition software
with complex search strategies and Internet Explorer 5.0, can be
downloaded from the Web free at www.myivan.com or ordered on CD-ROM
from the site. The Windows 95 and 98 version is available now, with
a Macintosh edition in the works. With all its features, IVAN is
not quick to download _ the full version is more than 100
megabytes, and the program has some demanding minimum system
requirements: a Pentium-level 233-megahertz processor, a headset
microphone, 48 megabytes of RAM and almost 300 megabytes of hard
drive space. It may be a big chunk of digital real estate, but just
think of it as the butler's room on your computer. _ J.D.
BIERSDORFER &QR; 
 &QL; 
Model efficiency
</P>
<P>
   Palm Inc. has announced its new celebrity-endorsed PDA. And what
public intellectual did the company choose for this honor? Was it
Stephen Hawking? No. Stephen Jay Gould? Close. The Palm Vx Claudia
Schiffer Edition, named after the German runway model and actress,
will go on sale in time in the fall. Buyers may also want to
download www.utilware.com/mirror.html, which is free. It turns the
Palm screen into a handy mirror.  &QL; 
Software Tells Wireless E-Mail To Please Get to the Point
</P>
<P>
   Long e-mail messages are rarely welcome by busy computer users.
But they can be almost unbearable when viewed through the tiny
screens of wireless gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   AmikaNow, a Canadian software company, now offers a service that
it says will automatically extract only the most important
sentences before passing them on to a wireless device.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want e-mail highlights,'' said Suhayya Abu-Hakim, the
company's president and chief executive. AmikaFreedom.com is a
Web-based variation of software the company has been selling for
about a year.
</P>
<P>
   To use it, users must fill out a long registration form to
indicate, among other things, the address of their main e-mail
servers. AmikaNow's servers copy e-mail messages as they arrive at
customers' main mail servers. The software then does the chopping,
first by selecting the most important sentences, then by further
reducing them.
</P>
<P>
   The software is largely based on artificial intelligence
research by Abu-Hakim at the Canadian government's National
Research Council.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the decisions about cuts are made using complex
algorithms. The first sentence is usually the first to go,
Abu-Hakim said, because ``a lot of people begin e-mails with some
nicety like `it was good to see you again.'''
</P>
<P>
   By the company's estimate, the software has a success rate of 75
percent to 80 percent. That is partly because of the current
software's limitations, Abu-Hakim acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   But she said there was another important factor: ``Not everyone
writes well. In the case where the e-mail makes no sense and the
writing is poor, the highlight is going to be poor.''
</P>
<P>
   The service is currently free as it is still in development.
Abu-Hakim said the company planned to start charging users $2 to $5
a month for the service by the end of the year. _ IAN AUSTEN &QR; 
Your Car Can Double as a Paid Advertisement
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you thought that the surface of every public space _
including stadium walls, shopping carts and airplane seats _ had
already been appropriated for advertising, you were mistaken. A
company called AutoWraps has found yet another canvas that until
recently was untouched by commercialization: your car.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30,000 people have signed up for the privilege of
having their cars used as rolling advertisements, said Daniel
Shifrin, president of the company. Those who are selected receive
payments of $100 to $400 a month, depending on how much of the car
is covered.
</P>
<P>
   The cars are wrapped in a vinyl adhesive that is guaranteed not
to damage the paint when removed. Many of the cars are also
equipped with a Global Positioning System unit that tracks speed
limits and driving patterns. Applicants must fill out a three-page
registration form on the Web, at www.autowraps.com.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers use a password-protected section of the site to find
the cars they want to wrap, searching on specifics like the age of
the drivers, where they work and which highways they travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is commercialization of just about every free space that
there is,'' said Mary Houser, director of communications for Scenic
America, a lobbying group that fights what it calls billboard
blight. ``There are some people who don't like living in one huge
advertisement.'' _ LISA GUERNSEY
</P>
<P>
   New Rewritable Drive Offers Relief From the Slow Burn
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, computer users measured out their lives in
downloading times. Now there's an even slower, more agonizing
measurement of time discovered by those who copy or create their
own CD's: burning time.
</P>
<P>
   Most CD-rewritable drives copy data at a ratio of about eight to
one, meaning that they can record about 60 minutes of music (or 545
megabytes of data) onto a compact disc in about 7{ minutes. The new
veloCD (pronounced ``velocity'') burner from TDK can record 60
minutes' worth of music in about five minutes, a big difference for
those who are already late for the party.
</P>
<P>
   Those speeds refer only to write-once discs (CD-R). Copying data
onto rewritable discs (CD-RW), an increasingly popular option for
people who want to back up their data, is slightly slower, although
the veloCD still copies data on a rewritable disc in about half the
usual time.
</P>
<P>
   But you'll pay for that higher gear. The suggested retail price
for the PC-compatible internal burner is $399, which is more
expensive than many similar devices. To achieve full speed, it's
also necessary to use TDK's high-speed discs, which run about $4.99
each, more than twice the price of most generic rewritable discs.
The veloCD also comes with music management software and
Burn-Proof, a licensed technology that allows users to open other
applications on the computer while information is being copied.
BRUCE HEADLAM &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
