<HEADER>
A0816 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-GOP-SPEECH03-COX     08-02 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GOP-SPEECH03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH CONFIDENT ON EVE OF KEY SPEECH950&AMP;trim.By JENA HEATH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ He is more comfortable with a wink and a nod than
he is with impassioned oratory, but Gov. George W. Bush will step
onto the stage Thursday night at the Republican National Convention
and deliver the most important speech of his political career.
</P>
<P>
   Designed to unite the GOP and light a fire under the crucial
swing voters Bush is battling Vice President Al Gore to win over,
the 3,900-word address, about 30 minutes long without interruption,
will introduce Bush to a nation that still doesn't know him nearly
as well as Texas does.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be watched by millions of Americans who really get
their first chance to size up George W. Bush,'' said Scott Reed,
who managed former Sen. Bob Dole's 1996 White House race. ``He
really needs to round out who he is, where he's from and where he's
heading in one national speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush told an audience at a Republican National Committee
fund-raising gala Wednesday, ``the first thing I'm going to do is
share with America how proud I am and how much I love my parents.''
</P>
<P>
   He joked, too, that, ``a crowd this big makes me want to go
through the whole speech,'' but his campaign has jealously guarded
its contents, only hinting at what he might say.
</P>
<P>
   The overall theme _ that the nation, poised at a moment of peace
and prosperity, is free to take on some thorny problems _ echoes
his stump speech.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will talk about tax cuts, Social Security, strengthening
the military and education _ the four pillars of his campaign. He
is also likely to talk about prescription drug coverage for the
elderly, a relatively new campaign theme and one that polls show
plays well with voters.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said Bush will also emphasize his by-now familiar theme
of bringing honor and dignity to the White House. And while he will
contrast his proposals and philosophy with the Clinton
administration's, Bush won't make sweeping attacks.
</P>
<P>
   He won't point out, as he has for days on the campaign trail,
that running mate Dick Cheney knows what the meaning of the word
``is'' is _ a not-so-thinly veiled reference to the Monica Lewinsky
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has also begun working a new line into his stump speech, on
e that will perhaps appear Thursday night. He tells audiences that
Americans want ``somebody who appeals to their better angels, not
their darker impulses,'' and that he and Cheney will fulfill that
desire.
</P>
<P>
   Communications director Karen Hughes said this week that Bush
will ``needle his opponents a little,'' but she describes the text
as ``a positive speech ... an uplifting speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed said Bush must both rally the GOP and appeal to key swing
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the emphasis of the speech should be focused on
independents, swing suburban women in the Midwest, because that's
where this whole election will be won or lost,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The speech has been in the works since mid-May, when Bush
huddled in the library of the Governor's Mansion in Austin with
chief speechwriter Mike Gerson, campaign strategist Karl Rove,
Hughes, media adviser Mark McKinnon and policy director Josh
Bolten.
</P>
<P>
   Gerson, 36, who worked as a speechwriter in Dole's 1996 White
House race, has largely crafted Bush's address, submitting at least
16 drafts for his review. Only a handful of insiders have seen the
speech.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   That's not unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, his wife, Elizabeth, and a small speechwriting team,
Dole shared his convention address with five people: former
President Bush, conservative commentator and author William F.
Buckley, former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, retired Gen. Colin L.
Powell and Haley Barbour, then chairman of the Republican National
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He chose them for all different reasons,'' said John Buckley,
who oversaw Dole's speechwriting team and also reviewed the speech.
``He chose George Bush Sr. because he was the last person to have
delivered a Republican nomination speech, and he wanted his
opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole asked Powell if he would review the speech during a flight
the two shared, Buckley said.
</P>
<P>
   And Dole worked with a coach and spent the four weeks before he
delivered the speech practicing at the podium. The work paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is notable that the only time in the entire political year
in 1996 that Bob Dole was within five points of President Clinton
was the morning after his speech because he did succeed,'' Buckley
said. ``People viewed him as a potential president.''
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   Bush tinkered with the speech _ and practiced it aloud for small
private audiences of friends and colleagues _ during the five-day
pre-convention tour through the swing states of Arkansas, Missouri,
Kentucky, Ohio and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   He told reporters aboard his campaign plane Wednesday morning
that the speech is ``done, ready to go.'' Earlier, Bush said he
hopes the speech will tell the American people that he is ``a
decisive, firm leader who's got good judgment and is ready to lead
the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush first read the speech aloud on July 21 at his ranch near
Crawford, Texas, behind a podium set up in an exercise room and
with his inner circle seated on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   He has been through four full practices since _ two in Austin,
one recently at the Cincinnati home of longtime friends Bill and
Kathie DeWitt, and one on Tuesday in a large room on the first
floor of the Governor's Mansion in Pennsylvania. He said Wednesday
morning that he had not decided if he would practice again.
</P>
<P>
   Media adviser Stuart Stevens watched the Tuesday rehearsal. So
did Gov. Tom Ridge, whom Bush vetted as a possible running mate and
who will be one of the people introducing Bush tonight. Stevens
said Ridge's 11-year-old son, Tommy, was also there, along with
Hughes and Bush's personal assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Just back from speaking at a rally of some 5,000 people, Bush
changed into casual clothes, including a Texas Rangers T-shirt,
stood behind a podium and delivered the speech using a TelePrompter
and with background crowd noise that Stevens had on a compact disk.
</P>
<P>
   He has used the TelePrompter at least twice. Stevens said Bush
did just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd just gone through that big speech at the rally,'' he
said. ``It was like having a guy pitch batting practice after
already having a game. He was relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckley said Bush, like any other nominee, will need to convince
voters that ``this is somebody who they are comfortable with in
their living rooms on television for the next four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed credits the campaign with using the past three months to
firmly advance Bush's policy agenda and the last five days to set
the stage for his biggest performance ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have very effectively had a positive lead-up to the
convention,'' he said. ``He's been in the hall every night via
satellite rolling out the beginning of his message. But it all
culminates tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Jena Heath's e-mail address is jenah(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
