<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0820 &Cx1f; taf-z
s a BC-EDLIFE-CATHOLIC-SCHOO     08-02 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDLIFE-CATHOLIC-SCHOOLS-$ADV6-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADITIONS CHANGING AT CATHOLIC SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Calif., Ore., Wis.)   (For Release Aug. 6) 
 (Timothy Egan is a national correspondent for The New York Times
based in Seattle.) By TIMOTHY EGAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They slouch into chairs, faces rumpled and downcast, a sluggish
clot of high school juniors in Gonzaga Prep's 8 a.m. religion
class. Members of a generation stuffed with Pokemon and Simpsons
reruns, they are about to get their daily dose of Roman Catholic
Church history, focusing today on the eighth century.
</P>
<P>
   The bell rings. The day begins with a quick prayer, followed by
individual pleas on behalf of a hospitalized sibling and the track
team. Shuffle, shuffle, cough, cough. And then class gets under
way, run by the rarest kind of teacher in a U.S. Catholic school at
the dawn of the new century: a priest.
</P>
<P>
   I look around for familiar signs from my days at this very
school 27 years ago. The most startling thing is the presence of
girls. Gonzaga was an all-boys institution until two years after I
left. Young Catholic men would not be able to learn Latin or the
history of the Peloponnesian War with the distraction of girls, the
thinking went.
</P>
<P>
   The hack paddle _ nearly three feet of solid oak, an inch thick
and perforated for maximum pain delivery _ is long gone. On several
occasions, I was sent down to the office of a 240-pound,
chain-smoking Irish-American priest who made me bend over and
understand what a baseball feels like when it's hit by Mark
McGwire. Gone, also, is Rockpile, the after-school cleanup detail
for the discipline-challenged.
</P>
<P>
   On the wall today, I spot the two icons held up for veneration
from my earliest days at school: the first Roman Catholic
President, John F. Kennedy, and the crucifix.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 756, Pepin defeats the Lombards and gives control of
central Italy to the pope,'' says the Rev. Tom Lamanna, a young
Jesuit, who has never strayed far from his roots here in his
hometown, Spokane, Wash. ``What this does is eat away at spiritual
authority. Popes and bishops shouldn't be involved in this sort of
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no religion by rote for these 17-year-olds, no
word-for-word rehash of doctrine. Lamanna, one of the few priests
in the nation teaching at a Catholic school, is suggesting that
conversion by sword was not such a great idea.
</P>
<P>
   A student raises her hand to ask a question, and Lamanna's face
brightens. ``Is this going to be on the quiz?'' the student asks.
The important things never change.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 10 years after many educators had written them off for
dead, Roman Catholic schools in the United States are in the midst
of an extraordinary revival. Enrollment is up across the nation.
Hundreds of new schools have opened. And more than 40 percent of
all Catholic elementary and secondary schools have waiting lists
for admission.
</P>
<P>
   More remarkably, Catholic schools, once staffed primarily by
nuns, priests and brothers from various religious orders, are
nearly devoid of clerics _ reflecting the crash of vocations in the
last 25 years as priests have become more urgently needed in the
parishes. In the nation's Catholic schools, priests account for
fewer than 1 percent of the 157,000 teachers. Ninety-three percent
of the teachers are laity, while nuns make up 5.5 percent and
brothers less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There are 10,000 fewer priests now than there were 25 years ago.
And the ranks will continue to shrink: nearly one-fourth of the
nation's 47,000 Catholic priests are over the age of 70.
</P>
<P>
   Schools that were once Dominican or Franciscan now speak of
being in the Dominican or Franciscan ``tradition.'' Gone are the
days when virtually every Catholic parish in the country supported
a teaching staff of nuns or priests living year-round near the
school grounds, laboring for compensation well below the poverty
line.
</P>
<P>
   As the Roman collars and the black-and-white habits have
disappeared from the halls, so too, has the overwhelmingly Catholic
makeup of the typical student body. A record 13.4 percent of the
2.6 million students are non-Catholic _ more than four times the
percentage of 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And in many of the old industrial cities where immigration led
to a flowering of Catholic schools in the 1880s, a majority of the
students at some schools named for saints and holy days are not
Catholic. In Lower Manhattan, for example, Buddhists make up a
large segment of the students in two schools, Saint Patrick's Old
Cathedral School and Transfiguration School. Throughout the
Archdiocese of New York, 20 percent of the students are
non-Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers of non-Catholics could dramatically increase if
various voucher or tax credit proposals, which subsidize private
school education, are enacted in some of the states now considering
them and upheld by the courts. This fall, California will vote on a
voucher program that Catholic educators in the state say could lead
to waiting lists for nearly every Catholic school in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``With or without vouchers, the problem for us now is not demand
_ it's supply,'' said Leonard DeFiore president of the National
Catholic Education Association.
</P>
<P>
   All of which raises a basic question: How can Catholic schools
be flourishing, yet still maintain their religious identity when so
many of the teachers and students have no formal attachment to the
religion whose imprint is on the school? In some schools, the
Catholicism seems almost an after-thought. With no way to measure
whether they have moved students to look at the world through a
spiritual lens, Catholic educators shrug and speak of anecdotal
triumphs, of students who may have picked up a habit of daily
prayer to go with high College Board scores. It is a long way from
the glory days of post-war Catholic schools, an era that seems as
distant as Pepin and the Lombards.
</P>
<P>
   As Lamanna said after his religion class: ``The kids I teach are
a lot less churched than their parents were. And we have
fundamentalists, Muslims, even an occasional Jewish student.''
</P>
<P>
   I returned to Gonzaga and also visited other schools, trying to
get a sense of what a Catholic education is like today. The one
thing I heard repeatedly was that, if anything, the schools are
more consciously Catholic now than they were a generation ago.
Without nuns or priests to guide students, principals have tried to
institutionalize Catholic education _ a tough act for the spiritual
aspects. It is one thing to require all students to study theology,
go on retreats and attend Mass four times a year _ as most Catholic
secondary schools do. What is more difficult is putting down the
cultural imprint.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
