<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0821 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-HOLLOWMAN-REVIEW     08-02 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HOLLOWMAN-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
By ERIC HARRISON
<TEXT>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   In ``Hollow Man,'' Kevin Bacon plays the kind of scientific
genius who wears periwinkle shirts with purple ties, drives a
Porsche convertible with its stereo blasting, and struts like a
rooster in a coop full of hens.
</P>
<P>
   His second-in-command on a top-secret government project is the
head hen _ his former squeeze, played by Elisabeth Shue with a
suggestive swivel and a wide-eyed, adoring gaze.
</P>
<P>
   Her current beau is dreamboat researcher Josh Brolin though
she's trying to keep it quiet because Bacon, who wants her back,
already considers him a professional rival.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, in other words, treats its high-level Pentagon
research lab as if it were high school, with all the sexual heat,
petty jealousies and wounded pride that implies. The team also
includes four other youngish though less-gorgeous members. They
celebrate breakthroughs with high fives, loud whoops and pumping
fists, as if they were at a hockey game.
</P>
<P>
   Any audience that can take this rock 'n' roll crew seriously as
scientists won't have any problem with the rest of the movie, which
adds adrenal overkill and a high-tech, digital gloss to the kind of
monster-within plot you'll remember from black-and-white horror
movies of the '30s.
</P>
<P>
   Sebastian Caine (Bacon) is the hollow man. The movie makes it
clear that he was lacking something _ a conscience? a moral center?
_ even before he turns transparent. He's a jerk, out only for glory
and power. He lies. He mistreats lab animals. He cuts corners.
Being invisible only gives him the license to act on his desires.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to be the first invisible man so badly that he's not
above injecting himself with invisibility serum before he's
finished testing the antidote. He becomes instantly enraptured with
his power to do mischief.
</P>
<P>
   He spies on people, gropes co-workers and plays silly games.
This soon escalates. As he tells himself before he sneaks with evil
intent into the apartment of a beautiful neighbor he's long lusted
after: ``Who's going to know?''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon is terrifically venal. He gives the kind of performance
that people would praise as courageous if he were Tom Cruise or
Harrison Ford _ stars who think audiences only want to see them as
heroes. Bacon long ago defined himself (or got defined) as an actor
rather than star. With his easy sneer, licentious moves and
exaggerated tough-guy swagger, he's a natural heavy.
</P>
<P>
   The special effects here really are special. When invisible
creatures receive the antidote, we watch first their veins, then
their hearts, then lungs turn visible. Organ by organ, they come
into view. Trapped between visible and invisible, Bacon spends part
of the movie looking like a moving, lifesize drawing from a medical
textbook.
</P>
<P>
   Among this movie's problems is that it ventures too far out of
the realm of metaphor into horror movie cliches. It isn't enough
that Caine behaves like a monster; he turns into a creature along
the lines of the shape-shifting android in the second
``Terminator'' movie _ he will not be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Set him on fire, bash him over the head with a pipe, electrocute
him _ he comes back for more. He has more lives than the invisible
cat we see rip apart a rat in the movie's first scene. It makes for
exciting action and chase sequences _ director Paul Verhoeven knows
how to push the right buttons _ but button-pushing is all it is.
</P>
<P>
   Just when you think the movie's over and you can rest easy, a
hand juts clawlike onto the screen. These rising, sequential
climaxes have become so predictable in horror films, you can almost
set your watch by the monster's resurrections.
</P>
<P>
   A major difference between ``Hollow Man'' and B movies of yore
is that the heroic character who saves the day is a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Shue gets top billing, though for the first half of the
movie her character, Linda McKay, spends a lot of time standing
behind Bacon's Caine, looking on admiringly, watching the genius at
work. She also does a lot of heavy breathing, the better to show
she's more than a little tempted when he puts the moves on her.
</P>
<P>
   As if to telegraph, though, that she will become a
larger-than-life heroine before the proceedings are through, she's
given to outsized gestures. She strides into a room more like
Wonder Woman than Lois Lane. She's silently shouting ``Look at me''
over Bacon's shoulder in each of those early scenes.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end, she no longer has to shout. With her quick wits
and stamina, she steps to the fore, and we'd watch her even if
Bacon weren't invisible. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``Hollow Man'' &QL; 
Starring:  &LR; Elisabeth Shue, Kevin Bacon, Josh Brolin &QL; 
 &UR; Director:  &LR; Paul Verhoeven &UR;  &QL; 
Screenwriter: &LR;  Andrew W. Marlowe &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;  &UR; Rating: &LR;  R for strong violence, language and some
sexuality/nudity. &QL; 
 &UR; Running time:  &LR; 114 minutes &QL; 
 &UR; Grade: B- &LR;  &QL; 
$$$
</P>
