<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0823 &Cx1f; taf-z
s a BC-EDLIFE-CATHOLIC-SCHOO     08-02 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDLIFE-CATHOLIC-SCHOOLS-$ADV6-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: cultural imprint. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At age 7, I walked into first grade at Assumption of the Blessed
Virgin Mary elementary school in Spokane and was confronted by an
enormous poster depicting the fall of Adam and Eve in the Garden of
Eden. Our school was blue-collar, the second- and third-generation
Irish and Italian children from huge families. We had nine in ours,
but could not compete with the Flynns, down the street, who had 13,
or the Phillipses, who had 19.
</P>
<P>
   Every teacher but one was a sister. The nuns were mysterious,
all but the front of their faces veiled by the habit. We called
them penguins, not always a pejorative.
</P>
<P>
   We all knew who the handful of non-Catholics at the school were.
And if we walked down the street and came to a Protestant church,
we crossed to the other side, as we were taught.
</P>
<P>
   Religion was part of everything; even math and science lessons
usually got around to the divine magnificence of the universe. John
F. Kennedy's picture was in every classroom, and Notre Dame
football was the sports extension of the church.
</P>
<P>
   Religion class, at first, was the Baltimore Catechism, starting
with the basic questions: Who made me? God made me. Why did God
make me? To know, love and serve him on this earth. It was memory,
nothing more. And everything that could not be adequately explained
was referred to as a mystery, as the comedian George Carlin later
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Second Vatican Council, in the mid-1960s, which
brought the Catholic Church into the modern age. And before long
the nuns were showing some hair and lower leg, and plugging in
electric guitars at Masses that were celebrated in English, not
Latin.
</P>
<P>
   The era of Catholic schools in the United States dates to 1884,
when the bishops, responding to complaints about Protestant
domination of public schools, ordered every parish to build a
school. Waves of mostly poor, immigrant children were educated at
these schools, which engendered a backlash. The most extreme bias
came in Oregon, in the 1920s, when the Ku Klux Klan helped pass a
law _ later thrown out in court _ that banned children from going
to Catholic schools.
</P>
<P>
   At the peak of enrollment, in 1964 _ I was in the third grade _
more than 5.6 million students attended 13,000 Catholic elementary
and secondary schools. Of course, the numbers reflected the surge
of baby boomers, but it was also a time when there were sufficient
nuns and priests to run the schools.
</P>
<P>
   Tuition was nearly free, in part because of support from church
members and dioceses, but also because the schools could depend on
an army of cheap labor, with nearly everyone from the principal on
down living under a vow of poverty. Now there is but a single nun
at Assumption.
</P>
<P>
   Tuition at Assumption is $3,000 a year _ cheap by the standards
of most private schools, but higher than the national average for
Catholic elementary schools, which is $1,800. And it is flexible. A
family pays what it can afford. Nationwide, because so many
students are given tuition breaks, Catholic schools face perennial
budget crunches _ except in wealthy suburban districts.
</P>
<P>
   My niece, Lindsey Egan, is a seventh grader at Assumption, and
she loves it, speaking enthusiastically of the sports, a cocoon of
good friends and the challenge of two hours of nightly homework. I
doubted she loved that part.
</P>
<P>
   What about religion? ``Oh, sure, that part's OK We go to Mass
almost every week.'' No mysteries. No Gothic punishment. She seemed
untouched by the load that many students of my vintage are still
trying to sort through, and had no concern about who was Catholic
and who was not.
</P>
<P>
   The lone nun is revered. There is a waiting list to get in. And
the students outperform children in the Spokane public schools. The
poster of Adam and Eve has disappeared. Mysteries are explained by
science. But the children still wear uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   When I entered high school, there were 47 Jesuits at Gonzaga,
many with advanced degrees. The older priests tended to be
rock-jawed and thick-armed; some were World War II veterans who had
gone into the priesthood after the horror of the war. The priests
were rarely out of clerical garb, whether they were shoveling snow,
rewiring an electrical panel or showing the baseball team how to
hit a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   We deconstructed the rock opera ``Tommy,'' by The Who, in
sophomore religion class. By my senior year, we had vigorous
debates that spilled into evening arguments over the very existence
of God. The Jesuits did not want us to believe in church teachings
just because they told us to; they wanted us to arrive there by
intellectual deduction, reason and _ failing all that _ simple
faith.
</P>
<P>
   We read ``Portrait of the Artist as a Young Man'' by James Joyce
and ``Catcher in the Rye'' by J.D. Salinger and ``The Invisible
Man'' by Ralph Ellison _ all prompting some parents to complain,
but the Jesuits held firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take nothing else away from here, remember the lesson
of Moby Dick,'' said my senior English teacher. ``Be in constant
search of your God and your self.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, on my return, I asked the principal of Gonzaga, Al
Falkner, if the Moby Dick moral still applied. A former English
teacher who has been at the school for 26 years and sent all four
of his children there, Falkner said yes, but that the school was
trying to impart other lessons as well.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nearly 1,000 students at the school, about 20 percent are
non-Catholics. Only two of the 65 teachers are Jesuit priests, a
ratio similar to that at the nation's 45 other Jesuit high schools.
Yet, Falkner says, ``We are more Jesuit now than we were 40 years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
