<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0826 &Cx1f; taf-z
s a BC-EDLIFE-CATHOLIC-SCHOO     08-02 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDLIFE-CATHOLIC-SCHOOLS-$ADV6-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: 40 years ago.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lay principals at other Catholic schools said somewhat the same
thing. It seemed incongruent. But after Catholic schools hit bottom
in the late 1980s, when many of them were adrift and uncertain as
to how to operate without priests or nuns, there was a concerted
effort to institutionalize the education for a new era.
</P>
<P>
   At Gonzaga, the lay staff is required to stay within the bounds
of Jesuit teaching principles, something the priests would not
always do. The fathers were assumed, by virtue of their vocations,
to be strong adherents of an order that values deductive logic and
reason in the classroom. But in practice, many Jesuits were simply
bad teachers, say some of the older priests.
</P>
<P>
   Falkner produced an instruction manual that every teacher is
required to follow. It details a number of teaching techniques
intended to make sure students understand certain principles. They
teach reflection _ ``a real challenge in math,'' said Falkner _ and
action, which usually takes the form of community service. The term
``social justice'' is used a lot. Grades count, of course; 96
percent of Gonzaga graduates go on to college. But the intention is
for students to have an epiphany of the spirit as well, an outcome
that is not easily manufactured, no matter how it is prescribed in
the teacher's manual.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every classroom, there should be a moment of truth when you
experience God,'' Falkner said. ``It may be the point where, all of
a sudden, you realize what Huck Finn is dealing with in that
book.''
</P>
<P>
   In the hallways, I bumped into the Rev. Robert A. Goebel, who
took over the hack paddle in my sophomore year. He is 74, still
wiry, with a full head of hair, and now works primarily with
alumni. I brought up those painful hacks he used to give me on my
rear end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good for you,'' he said with a laugh. ``And you know
it.'' In truth, I was not sure. I did not resent the priests for
corporal punishment of a kind that would probably bring a lawsuit
today. Twice, I talked my way out of hacks, which is a backhanded
way of saying I learned something, even if it was not the intended
lesson. I asked him how it felt to be one of the few priests left
at a school he has been associated with since 1957, and whether
Gonzaga had changed for better or worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be for the better,'' said Goebel. ``Because you wore a
collar, you were supposed to be able to teach. But a lot of the
priests from my generation were not very good teachers. Everyone
assumed that just because they were priests, they could provide a
good Catholic education.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled the full-service life, the teaching that never
ended. ``I can remember teaching kids how to blow their nose in a
proper way, and how to open a bottle of Champagne and not have it
spill on you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Goebel's much younger colleague, Lamanna, lives in an apartment
a few blocks from the school. Handkerchief etiquette and the
intricacies of cork removal are not among his duties.
</P>
<P>
   As at Assumption, the students at Gonzaga seem to be in awe of
the rare priest or nun.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I've ever had a priest teach me,'' said
Jessie Serghin, a junior in the church history class at Gonzaga.
``He's awesome.'' She was less enthusiastic about the story of
Pepin and the Lombards that Lamanna was trying to impart. ``Some of
this is probably not relevant to our lives,'' she said. ``But
that's OK''
</P>
<P>
   The students at Gonzaga _ like those at most Catholic high
schools _ are required to take four semesters of theology:
Scripture, morality, church history and a senior-year elective
usually involving community service. ``We've made a conscious
decision to call it theology, not religion,'' said Lamanna,
explaining that the word of choice is more expansive, less narrow
and dogmatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest challenges I have is teaching Scripture to
the non-Catholics,'' he added. ``Some of them believe every word of
the Bible is literally true.'' He tries to get these students to
see the Bible _ especially the Old Testament _ as allegory and oral
history, not always the literal word of God.
</P>
<P>
   Proselytizing is rare, he said, echoing the comments of
religious order teachers at other Catholic schools. Lamanna is a
spiritual counselor, a role that consists mainly of listening to
the problems of struggling adolescents. ``As a priest, I have
access to their interior life,'' he said. ``That's a very humbling
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   I sought out Jack Delehanty, a drama teacher who has been at the
school since I was a student there. Though 58 years old, he still
looks the way he did to us boys who were making the transition from
sports obsession to noir movies and poetry _ hip in an understated
way. He stages plays, in the school's new 350-seat performing arts
center, that deal with racism, homophobia and misunderstood youth,
as well as crowd-pleasing musicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids have changed,'' Delehanty said. ``We wanted to live
our high school life, have fun, try different things. Now they are
so pressured by the culture to succeed at an early age.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked him if he was a practicing Catholic, and how religion
trickled through the drama class curriculum. ``My faith is
Catholic, but my approach is humanistic,'' he said. ``That isn't a
conflict here. In the old days it was do it the Catholic way. It
was doctrine. Now, it's about values.''
</P>
<P>
   No city in the United States has opened the doors of Roman
Catholic schools to taxpayer-subsidized education as has Milwaukee.
Five years ago, the state of Wisconsin allowed poor families in
Milwaukee to send their children to parochial schools, with tuition
reimbursed by taxpayers at up to $5,000 a year per student. It is
the largest voucher program in the country, and has been upheld by
the Wisconsin Supreme Court. The U. S. Supreme Court refused to
hear an appeal of that court's decision. Programs elsewhere have
run up against constitutional questions over separation of church
and state.
</P>
<P>
   In Milwaukee, where about 3,000 students attend Catholic schools
under the voucher program, students may opt out of participation in
religious activities at the schools. But the schools say there has
not been a single such request.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0827 &Cx1f; taf-z
s a BC-EDLIFE-CATHOLIC-SCHOO     08-02 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDLIFE-CATHOLIC-SCHOOLS-$ADV6-4THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: such request. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest beneficiary in Milwaukee has been Messmer
High School, a clump of Depression-era brick situated near a
freeway in one of the city's poorest neighborhoods. Messmer was
nearly closed in the mid-1980s and disowned by its archdiocese. It
stayed alive with private donations, only to flourish beyond all
expectations with the voucher students. It now has a waiting list.
Catholic educators point to Messmer as an example for Catholic
schools in other poor areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be a Catholic to get a great education at
Messmer High,'' says the school brochure. ``Most students aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, about 80 percent of the school's 400 students are
non-Catholic. More than half the students are there because of the
voucher program. ``I believe we have reinvented Catholic
education,'' said Jeff Monday, the school principal. ``If we had to
follow the old Catholic model, the church probably would have
closed us down.''
</P>
<P>
   But religion is not hidden. The Ten Commandments are posted in
the entrance. Amid classroom banners that read ``Believe in
Yourself'' are others exhorting students to ``Open Wide the Doors
to Christ.'' The day begins with a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Tuition is $3,100 a year, and more than 90 percent of the
students cannot afford to pay it. Those who are not on vouchers
receive tuition money from private donations, scholarships and
fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   The school dynamo and president is a black Capuchin monk of the
Franciscan order, Brother Bob Smith. Messmer is overwhelmingly
black, and parents describe Smith as a role model.
</P>
<P>
   An easy-to-laugh, personable man with two cell phones by his
side at virtually all times, Smith cheerfully cites the
contradictions of maintaining a Catholic identity at a school where
most people have no attachment to the religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to give these children a religious foundation,'' he
said. ``Not values.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he is not an absolutist. ``I don't believe in this thing
that one religion is right and everyone else is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   At Messmer, students pray every day, go on spiritual retreats,
and attend at least four Masses a year. They take one religion
class every year, five days a week. The school is clean and
remarkably quiet. Even at the end of the day, around 6 p.m.,
students are hanging around, loathe to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are friendly, but we tell students we are not their buddies
or their friends,'' said Smith, who grew up in Chicago and worked
for a time as a parole officer in Detroit. ``And don't even think
of calling a teacher here by their first name.''
</P>
<P>
   Messmer does not cherry-pick the best students, as do some
Catholic high schools; there is no admission test for entry. It has
been, by nearly all accounts, a big success, with 85 percent of the
graduates going on to college _ three times the rate of neighboring
public high schools.
</P>
<P>
   But again, grades are one thing; imparting Catholicism is much
tougher, the teachers say. Smith defined the ultimate goal in terms
remarkably similar to the words used by the Gonzaga principal. ``At
some point in a student's life here we want them to come face to
face with God,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and the other Messmer teacher who belongs to a religious
order, Sister Elayne Hill, are exotic creatures at the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell the students about our vows of poverty and chastity,''
said Smith. ``I tell them that they may have a different pair of
tennis shoes for every day of the week, but I live on less than
$10,000 a year, and don't mind. I say I would love to have kids, a
family of my own. But I have given that up because of my belief.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Hill does not wear a habit; she is a young, light-skinned
black woman from Washington, D.C. ``I have to explain a lot to the
kids,'' she said with a grin. ``The students say, `You're a nun? A
real nun?' What they are most upset about is chastity. That just
blows their mind.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked her if she taught the concept of heaven, hell and that
in-between destination in the hereafter, purgatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there is a heaven and a hell, and we talk about it,'' she
said. ``Purgatory _ um, that's another matter.'' She said her job
was not to convert non-Catholics. ``I'm on a journey with them, an
invitation,'' she said. ``It's not `do this or die.'''
</P>
<P>
   But she worries about the minority of students who are strong
Catholics. ``I do think that the Catholic kids almost get lost at
some of these schools.''
</P>
<P>
   And that may be the ultimate irony in the renaissance of
American Catholic schools: some of the brightest stars _ and
certainly, the fastest-growing schools _ are the ones with the
fewest Catholics.
</P>
</TEXT>
