<SLUG> BC-MA-BUSINESS-CONFIDENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS ACTIVITY SLOWS AS LACK OF WORKERS HITS FIRMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Business confidence in Massachusetts slipped for a
second month, according to a survey of companies reporting they
were concerned they could not hire enough workers to expand.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Industries of Massachusetts reported Wednesday
that its index of future business activity fell in July to 66.9
points, down from 68.1 in June and from a 2 1/2-year high of 68.3
in May. The index is based on a survey of manufacturing and other
companies operating in the state.
</P>
<P>
   While the drop in Massachusetts' business confidence seemed to
bolster a smattering of evidence that the US economy may be cooling
off, Alan Clayton Matthews, professor of economics for the
University of Massachusetts at Boston, said the state's economy is,
in fact, still very strong.
</P>
<P>
   Employment is growing about 2 percent a year, which is
``incredible, given our tight labor market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, exports are up, and consumer confidence and personal
incomes in New England are high, Matthews said, noting that AIM's
index is still well above levels during all of 1999. A year ago, in
July 1999, the index was 67.9.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the national level, there's a question of whether we're
slowing down or not _ the signals are mixed,'' he said. ``At the
state level, more of the signals are still pointing toward strong
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   AIM spokesman Raymond Torto said companies responding to the
survey reported their sales were softening somewhat. But he
confirmed that the slowdown may, oddly, be a boom-time curse: The
``most-cited constraint on expansion remains the tight labor
market,'' Torto said.
</P>
<P>
   A shortage of workers continues to pressure wages. The US Bureau
of Labor Statistics reported Wednesday the employment cost index of
total compensation _ a measure of wage increase _ surged 0.9
percent in the Northeastern states for the April-to-June quarter, a
drop-off from the 1.4 percent gain the prior quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But wages in the region are rising faster than inflation: the
employment cost index for the 12 months ending in June was 4.3
percent, a full percentage point higher than inflation, the
government said.
</P>
<P>
   AIM's confidence index is biased toward the sentiments of
manufacturers, which make up a large part of its membership. The
survey also included business services, high-tech and other
non-manufacturing concerns. When exports declined in the wake of
Asia's financial meltdown in 1997 and 1998, the index sank. As
manufacturing rebounded, the index hit record highs in the first
quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The worldwide economy may be in for a slowdown in coming months,
according to a separate index of international economic activity,
also released Wednesday. The Economic Cycle Research Institute in
New York said its estimate of global growth rates in coming months
fell to a 3.4 percent annual rate. By comparison, predictions made
six months ago had pegged future growth at 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ECRI said interest-rate ``tightening moves over the past year by
most central banks around the world'' would cause an international
slowdown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
