<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, Aug. 2 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   GOP-RDP-NYT (Philadelphia) _ A convention roundup: Gov. George
W. Bush makes his calibrated entry into Philadelphia, as delegates
at the 37th Republican National Convention select him as their
nominee for president. Bush and Dick Cheney are to receive their
party's official nominations, and Cheney will speak to the
convention. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-BUSH-NYT (Undated) _ Man in the News profile: Just six years
ago, when George W. Bush ran for governor of Texas, even his own
parents expected him to lose; it was his younger brother Jeb who
held the family's confidence. Friends and family members say that
the elder Bushes worried that George W. would be forced to bow
again, as he had several times before, to failure. But that story
had a surprise ending: While Jeb lost, George won. And in the
process, George Walker Bush launched himself, without any grand
plan or intricate forethought, on a trajectory that on Thursday
will place him in the spotlight as the Republican nominee for
president. By Nicholas D. Kristof and Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   3,200 words; an abridged version will also move.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT6,7.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-CONSERVATIVES-NYT (Philadelphia) _ How does the right wing
of the party view it all? How visible are they, and how satisfied
are they with the ticket and platform. And what is it like to have
a GOP convention without Pat Buchanan? By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT23,24.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-POWER (Undated) _ In California, energy deregulation and
the rising cost of energy have collided. With prices going through
the roof, politicians are pushing to end the state's four-year
experiment with deregulation. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   KAN-SCHOOLS (Topeka, Kan.) _ Sending a strong signal in the
debate over how to teach about the origin of life, Republican
primary voters chose three candidates for the Kansas Board of
Education who promised to back science standards with a greater
emphasis on evolution. Two incumbents and another candidate who
support the state's current standards that play down the importance
of evolution were defeated in Republican primaries Tuesday.
(Summary from wires) By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIAN-CAMP (Nablus, West Bank) _ It is summer camp time
for 25,000 Palestinian teen-agers, and unusual camps they are. As
devised by the men who handle psychological warfare for Yasser
Arafat, the Palestinian leader, there is no horsing around in the
dorm, no fun-in-the-sun by a cool clear cool lake. Instead, there
is the chance to stage a mock kidnapping of an Israeli leader,
ending with the Israeli's bodyguards sprawled dead. In the summer
of the latest Camp David talks, the summer that was supposed to
produce a final peace settlement between Israel and its Palestinian
adversaries, the Palestinians' idea of how teen-age boys can best
use the summer days is a reminder of how deep old enmities run. By
John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT15,16, and a map.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-KIDNAP (Bangalore, India) _ The legendary outlaw Veerappan
has ranged through the jungles of South India for a generation,
slaughtering elephants, smuggling sandalwood and playing Robin Hood
to the people of the forest. For the past decade, hundreds of
policemen have been dedicated to nothing but hunting him down. He
has been charged with murdering dozens of them. This week he put
into action his boldest, most diabolical plan yet to win a pardon
for his crimes. On Sunday, he abducted Rajkumar, a movie star whose
half century-long career portraying Hindu gods, ancient kings and
heroes of every kind has endowed the actor himself with mythical
stature. The kidnapping has provoked mobs of fans to stone passing
cars, blockade major roads with flaming tires, pressure shopkeepers
to pull down their metal shutters _ and brought life in a bustling,
modern metropolis to a shuddering, grinding halt. By Celia W.
Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
</TEXT>
