<HEADER>
A0840 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-NOTEBOOK03-COX     08-02 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-NOTEBOOK03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With photo.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Tidbits from the Republican National Convention:
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr is bringing in a rock star to help him with his
campaign down in Georgia. In the midst of a re-election bid, Barr
said rocker Ted Nugent _ a hunting enthusiast _ would give an
archery demonstration at Jim Miller Park in Marietta on Aug. 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably won't sing _ it's a Sunday,'' the congressman said
here Wednesday. Barr said he admired Nugent's ``raw, unbridled
passion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They say he gets out there on that stage, and he blasts the
Clinton administration. He's not afraid of it. He doesn't shy away
from it,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   George P. is hot, hot, hot.
</P>
<P>
   But schoolmates from Gulliver Prep in Pinecrest Village near
Miami said George Prescott Bush, the candidate's nephew and the No.
4 bachelor in People's list of the 100 Most Eligible, wasn't
regarded as the No. 1 hunk on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you should know that Enrique Iglesias also went to our
school,'' said Tzaicel Hernandez, 22, one of several GOP Youth
Convention delegates from Miami who attended the private academy
with George P. and his sister, Noele, the children of Florida Gov.
Jeb Bush and his Mexican-born wife, Columba.
</P>
<P>
   George P. ``is really a nice guy. Down to earth. Really smart,''
said Olga Arguello, 22. ``When I see him, I don't think, 'Oh, now
you're a celebrity.' He's just a regular guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a good head on his shoulders. I say that first
because all anybody ever asks about are his movie-star looks,''
said Alany Cruz, 22.
</P>
<P>
   So is he as good-looking as a movie star?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yes,'' said Cruz. ``He will one day be president.''
</P>
<P>
   Ann Stone, leader of Republicans For Choice, is hoping to start
working next year with a new first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laura Bush is someone we can work with'', Stone said at a
briefing for foreign media Wednesday. ``Laura talks about common
ground in the discussion on abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans for Choice favors voluntary action to reduce
abortion by reducing unintended pregnancies. ``This issue should go
away, and non-legislative programs are the best way to achieve
it'', Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she does not expect George W. Bush to mention the issue
during Thursday night's acceptance speech. The party's platform is
strongly anti-abortion, although Stone claimed that half the GOP's
voters and two-thirds of its donors are pro-choice.
</P>
<P>
   Costumes are the big thing among protestors these days, to the
point that it's tough to separate the angry from the just plain
weird. During the height of a confrontation on downtown streets
this week, police radios crackled with a report of two dozen men
and women _ all wearing red dresses and make-up _ sprinting
pell-mell through the streets.
</P>
<P>
   What was their beef? They didn't have one. Turns out the fashion
plates were members of a local running club. The dressed-up dash is
simply something they do once a year.
</P>
<P>
   For his MSNBC client, pollster Frank Luntz has assembled a focus
group of swing voters who wouldn't be caught dead watching the GOP
convention unless they were paid. The big convention story so far,
as Luntz sees it: ``Colin Powell hit a home run with his 1966
speech to the Republicans in San Diego. But this time he hit a
grand slam.''
</P>
<P>
   The strong positive reaction was due as much to his style as
what he had to say, Luntz reported. The former general's focus on
education scored well among the undecideds, while his praise of
affirmative action played better among those who lean to the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't know the pledge of allegiance to the Texas flag,
ask a Republican convention delegate. The Texas Delegation each
morning at its breakfast here pledges allegiance not just to the
United States of America, but to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a National Federation of Independent Business
gathering, Rep. J.C. Watts, an African-American Republican who grew
up in Eufala, Okla., said raising the minimum wage might make it
tough for his brother's barbecue business back home.
</P>
<P>
   It's not right, Watts said, for the government to tell his
brother how much to pay his four employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends, in my opinion, that is communism,'' Watts said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
