<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0841 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-DUNKIN-TOGOS-BOS &LR;      08-02 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUNKIN-TOGOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLIED DOME HAS A NEW PLAN FOR DUNKIN' DONUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (attn.: calif.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may be a nutritionist's nightmare _ or a trencherman's
delight _ but put doughnuts and $5 sandwiches under one restaurant
roof, and maybe add ice cream, and one restaurant company thinks it
has a winning formula for rapid growth and a menu that will appeal
to consumers all day long.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans are familiar with Dunkin' Donuts. In 1997
Dunkin's British parent, Allied Dome &UR;  &LR; Plc, acquired the Togo's
sandwich chain, and for the last few years, Allied Dome's Randolph,
Mass.-based quick-service restaurant division has been testing
``combo'' formats where Dunkin' Donuts and Togo's share a location
and, often, a parking lot and a drive-through window as well.
</P>
<P>
   After much experimentation, Allied Dome &UR;  &LR; thinks it has the right
formula, and if it can line up enough real estate, it hopes to
rapidly expand from about 25 of these combo restaurants to as many
as 400 nationwide by the end of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Dome &UR;  &LR; also owns Baskin Robbins, the ice cream chain.
Where enough space is available, some new restaurants could be
``trombos.'' At triple combination sites that sell sinkers, subs,
and sundaes, the hope is that there will be a variety of foods that
appeal to consumers morning, noon, and night.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes called ``multi-branding,'' the combining of two or
more restaurants such as a Dunkin' Donuts and a Togo's into a sort
of mini food court has been around for years but is now gaining
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   The company that owns Pizza Hut, Taco Bell, and KFC has toyed
with the idea. And Papa Gino's Holdings Corp. of Dedham, Mass.,
which in 1997 bought D'Angelo sandwich shops, opened its first
``dual unit'' last year in Norwood, Mass. Over the next few months,
plans call for the opening of seven or eight more locations that
combine a Papa Gino's and a D'Angelo.
</P>
<P>
   Multi-branding can be ``a winning strategy'' for quick-service
chains, said executive vice president Dennis Lombardi of Technomic
Inc., a firm that tracks the fast-food industry.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, grouping restaurants together offers more choices
and one-stop convenience. For chains, operating three different
food concepts at one location can mean a lot less overhead expense
than operating three separate restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Multi-branding may be ``the future for individual niche
concepts,'' said Groton restaurant consultant Joyce Faiola.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Allied Dome's quick-service restaurant division now
seems poised for an aggressive rollout of its combos and trombos.
</P>
<P>
   On the East Coast, plans call for the Dunkin' Donuts brand to
introduce and promote Togo's to its customers in New England, the
mid-Atlantic region, and some Southern states.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Togo's, which got its start in San Jose, Calif., is
expected to play a big role in bulking up Dunkin' Donuts' small
presence on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Dunkin' Donuts eyes a California invasion next year as it looks
to going from a handful of West Coast units to at least one hundred
Dunkin' Donuts-Togo's combos in a brief time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we go, we'll go fast,'' said Mark Richardson, vice
president for multi-branding at Allied Dome's quick-service
division.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to raise its awareness in New England, Togo's is airing
its first radio and TV ad campaign in Greater Boston.
</P>
<P>
   With loving closeups of pastrami and barbecued chicken, ads
extol the virtues of the Togo's sandwich. The tagline for the ads:
``Let us make you one.'' Ads were tied to a promotion in which
Dunkin' Donuts customers received coupons for Togo's sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to expose the Dunkin' Donuts customer to Togo's,''
Richardson said. ``Once we have awareness, Togo's does well.''
</P>
<P>
   Allied Dome &UR;  &LR; doesn't expect to sell doughnuts, chicken
sandwiches, and ice cream to a single consumer all at the same
time. Rather, it aims to offer consumers different products at
different times of day.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Dunkin' Donuts' 4,100 restaurants reported sales of
$2.14 billion, and consultant Lombardi reckoned a big chunk of
those sales came before noon.
</P>
<P>
   Togo's gets the chain into the lunch business, something Dunkin'
Donuts couldn't do on its own. And Baskin Robbins is generally at
its busiest between 4 p.m. and 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   By combining the three concepts, ``you can appeal to people
throughout a 12-hour period,'' consultant Faiola noted.
</P>
<P>
   With about 300 restaurants and 1999 sales of $167 million,
Togo's is competing in a tough $6.4 billion market for
quick-service sandwiches, in which one of the biggest players is
Subway, a chain with nearly 14,500 units. Privately held Subway of
Milford, Conn., does not report sales.
</P>
<P>
   With ``made-for-you'' sandwiches in the $5 range, Togo's aims to
keep it simple. It doesn't do french fries. It doesn't do pockets
or wraps, said Richardson, who claims that Togo's fare is more
upscale and of a higher quality than Subway's.
</P>
<P>
   Subway spokesman Les Winograd strongly disagreed with that
characterization. Subway, he said, offers a far wider variety of
sandwiches, including gourmet subs, at a range of prices.
</P>
<P>
   At roughly 205 D'Angelo locations, many entrees fall into the $5
range. D'Angelo also offers a line of grilled sandwiches, and its
bread is made daily at a company-owned bakery.
</P>
<P>
   Togo's features ``a lot of sprouts and avocado and West
Coast-type vegetables,'' said Bill Chiccarelli, Papa Gino's
director of marketing. ``D'Angelo is more into mainstream
mom-and-pop vegetables like pickles, onions, and tomatoes.''
</P>
<P>
   After upgrading D'Angelo's systems, Papa Gino's looks to grow
more rapidly. One potential growth vehicle is the ``dual unit''
restaurant, with D'Angelo aiming at a lunch customer and Papa
Gino's going after the dinner trade. The company also has high
hopes for a new D'Angelo format configured for mall food courts.
</P>
<P>
   As chains try to expand, they all face the same problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real estate market is fairly tough right now,''
Chiccarelli said.
</P>
<P>
   A Dunkin' Donuts veteran, Chiccarelli recalled that when
Starbucks Corp. arrived in the Boston area, dire predictions were
made about Starbucks taking business from Dunkin' Donuts.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, both chains thrived, in part because consumers began
drinking more coffee. Chiccarelli thinks something similar could
happen with sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible in this era of concern about health, vanity, and
cholesterol that consumers can increase their food intake? Don't
bet against it. In 1999 spending on quick-service pizza and
doughnuts rose nearly 9 percent, according to Technomic.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to health food and diets, said consultant Faiola,
``People talk the talk, but they don't walk the walk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
