<HEADLINE>
TELEFONICA SAYS LYCOS DEAL WILL BE SET BY NEXT MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spain's Telefonica SA said Wednesday it expects to complete by
mid-September a $2 billion rights offering to help in its pending
purchase of Internet portal Lycos Inc. of Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Under the offering, current shareholders in Telefonica's Terra
Networks unit may purchase additional shares in the company for
about $56 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish regulators, meanwhile, have reportedly dropped their
insider-trading probe of Telefonica's former chairman, Juan
Villalonga, following his resignation last week.
</P>
<P>
   Villalonga had expanded the Madrid-based telecommunications
company but attracted much criticism for his high pay and
aggressive management style. Last week, he was replaced as
Telefonica's top officer by another board member, Cesar Alierta,
who said he would continue with the company's $12.5 billion Lycos
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Plans still call for Lycos to be combined with Terra Networks to
form a global Internet and content provider. In a statement this
week, Telefonica also reiterated its guarantee to purchase any new
shares of Terra Networks not purchased by Terra Networks' current
holders.
</P>
<P>
   The closing of the Lycos purcahse ``could take place during the
month of October,'' Telefonica said. Terra shareholders have
approved the transaction, which still requires approval from
regulators and Lycos shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Spain's securities regulator dropped an insider
trading case against Villalonga, Bloomberg News reported. The
National Securities Market Commission said there wasn't enough
evidence to conclude that he had broken securities law.
</P>
<P>
   Villalonga had denied wrongdoing, though he admitted buying
options on 264,244 Telefonica shares in January 1998, two months
before his company announced a partnership with WorldCom Inc. to do
business in Latin America and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   The regulator's report found ``the known facts and circumstances
in the current investigation don't amount to sufficient evidence to
proceed to a penalty phase for wrongfully using privileged
information.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision was expected by many analysts and investors, who
said the charge would be hard to prove against any investor, let
alone a man considered the country's most powerful executive. Only
one case of insider trading in Spain has been successfully
prosecuted in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was too difficult to prove Villalonga used privileged
information,'' Roberto Mingot, an attorney at law firm of Squire,
Sanders &AMP; Dempsey in Madrid, said before the decision was made
public. ``Considering they consulted (telephone company) MCI and
U.S. regulators, and still couldn't nail him, there must not have
been enough evidence'' under Spanish law, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
