<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COL-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WETTELAND SEEMS TO BE TOP SUSPECT IN RANGERS' DEMISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no positive proof it was John Wetteland, acting alone,
who stole our Texas summer. But that was him driving the getaway
car, right? Locally, the beautiful baseball months of August and
September have turned up missing. Gone forever. Vanished in the
night, like another Wetteland fastball with the game on the line.
</P>
<P>
   But with the crime, comes the whine, although certainly not from
Wetteland. The Rangers are cement-loafers, and I've got a multitude
of witnesses who will join me in testifying that the $6 million
closer is the guy who booked this club into Hotel Grouper.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, he didn't,'' answered manager Johnny Oates, perturbed.
``That's not fair to John Wetteland.''
</P>
<P>
   But if you want unfair, Mr. Oates, take a swig of this
injustice:
</P>
<P>
   The demise of the Rangers has now turned August over to the
Cowboys' exhibition season. There is no known boredom like NFL
preseason boredom. You say, Mr. Oates, that Wetteland doesn't
deserve to be horsewhipped, or at least indicted. I say, Mr. Oates,
that I don't deserve to watch Flozell Adams sweat in Wichita Falls.
But there is now no choice.
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, Wetteland never hides in bad times. He's a
standup guy, one who certainly hasn't waffled in this area even as
his days as a premier closer appear to be over. Wetteland, however,
doesn't need to defend himself. So many others have. At the moment,
Wetteland is the Dick Cheney of baseball when it comes to instant
defenders. And that includes local media gushing, particularly when
general manager Doug Melvin debated dealing the closer before
Monday's trading deadline. Never around here has there been such
supportive whining over a pitcher gone bad.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin held on to Wetteland only because he was offered no more
than a sack of fungoes in return. Which just proves that other
teams have scouts watching this stuff and Wetteland's ``stuff.''
He's still here because no one else wanted him _ not at the moment,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Getting back to the Oates' ``fairness'' issue when it comes to
blame for the bummer summer of 2000, Wetteland ranks high on the
guilty list, but no more so than Tim Crabtree, Rusty Greer, Darren
Oliver and about 10 others, including even Rafael Palmeiro, who
doesn't have the usual stellar numbers. Because of his job
description, Wetteland is the last link when he blows a game. This
year, he has blown too many. Book him, Dano. Plus, there's Melvin
in the front office. Blame is also splattered all over Doug.
</P>
<P>
   But now comes the hardest part. A one-season burial is
forgivable, but how do the Rangers recover in time for 2001? In the
AL West alone, Seattle and Oakland are better clubs this season
and, on paper, will be much better next season. So also might be
Anaheim. A year ago, the Rangers appeared to own the division. Now
they have to rent space in the cellar, and that's not necessarily
going to change in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland had been the No. 1 difference between the Rangers and
the rest of the division. He was the proven closer no one else had.
But a high Melvin-Oates priority for 2001 has suddenly become
finding a closer. This is not easy. This is also not Wetteland. No
way he comes back. Not based on what is now being seen in the late
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the rotation, which has become the strength of both
Seattle and Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of this week, we've finally got our five best pitchers in
the rotation,'' Oates said. Yes, it's true. The trio of youngsters
_ Ryan Glynn, Matt Perisho and Doug Davis _ has joined Rick Helling
and Kenny Rogers. ``We'd have been better off going with those
three kids,'' added Oates, meaning as opposed to Mark Clark, Darren
Oliver and Esteban Loaiza.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, August and September will provide great
seasoning for the young pitchers, and also give clues about them
being rotation-ready for 2001. There is no doubt, however, Melvin
will attempt to add a veteran starter in the off-season, although
he's going to be gun-shy after the disasters of Clark and Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   The third major question of the off-season is what happens in
the outfield, which has become shy in run production. Is Gabe
Kapler's sudden resurgence for real? Much faith is placed in
hitting instructor Rudy Jaramillo, who had patience with Kapler
when the rest of us were screaming, ``hopeless.'' Jaramillo is a
big reason the Rangers wanted Ricky Ledee in that trade. Can Rudy
``fix'' Ricky after the Yankees couldn't?
</P>
<P>
   For all his potential, Ruben Mateo continues to be hounded by
health issues, now more than ever. And with Rusty Greer, there has
to be the assumption that he bounces back. He's simply better than
this.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few weeks ago, the Rangers appeared to be confused over
direction. There was indecision about playing for this season or
preparing for 2001. The Pudge Rodriguez injury answered much of
that, then Wetteland's repeated failures left no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Summer ended early around here. It's a crime, don't you think?
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0846 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BAYREUTH-RING-2TAKES-     08-02 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAYREUTH-RING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RING': JUERGEN FLIMM'S VERSION TELLS STORY ADMIRABLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAYREUTH, Germany _ To a Bayreuth Festival torn between
tradition and the call of modern times comes Juergen Flimm's new
production of the ``Ring des Nibelungen.''
</P>
<P>
   Flimm, known to Germans as a theater, not an opera, director,
brings to Wagner's week-long tetralogy a kind of low-key
iconoclasm. If the temple is not torn down, it is at least
redecorated.
</P>
<P>
   A new ``Ring'' arrives every four years or so at the summer
shrine built by the great man and dedicated to himself. The first
cycle began last week and continued into this one, ending last
night with ``Goetterdaemmerung.'' In place was the true Wagner
audience: reverently quiet, fiercely opinionated and at some
distance from the relatively clamorous crowd at the opening night's
``Parsifal.''
</P>
<P>
   Flimm and his set designer, Erich Wonder, give us a contemporary
landscape and fiddle extensively with the minutiae of Wagner's
stage directions. Valhalla is a high rise in the making, a
construction site framed by concrete slabs. Wotan and Alberich are
businessmen competing for hegemony. The descent into the caves of
Nibelheim ends in a contamination-free microchip factory.
</P>
<P>
   Loge, brightly done by Kim Begley, is a lawyer type with a
briefcase and a creamy three-piece suit. The Valkyries appear as a
squadron of airborne commandos in combat fatigues. The hall of the
Gibichungs is modular glass and stainless steel.
</P>
<P>
   Critics here have sniped at Flimm's alleged lifting of details
from previous radically updated performances of ``Ring,'' but they
may be missing the point.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, neither the pros and cons of 21st-century capitalism nor
the Freudianisms of dysfunctional family life seem to be much on
the director's mind. Past competitors have used the mythic
barbarism of the ``Ring'' to project a worldview of current events.
Flimm, on the other hand, is just trying to tell a good story and
thinks that recognizable props will do it better. The modern world
is helpful to the narrative, but not the subject of a tract.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the metaphor ceases to tell the story, Flimm abandons
it. Wotan's spear is an accessory to his gray business suit and
lies across the architect's drawing board in ``Das Rheingold.''
There are real giants (albeit got up like American Indians); real
swords, not tommy guns; real shields instead of bulletproof vests.
Are the Rhinemaidens waterfront hookers or bathing beauties in
one-piece suits from Bayreuth's local H&AMP;M? I don't think we are
being asked to decide.
</P>
<P>
   Fafner in dragon form is a curiously writhing rock formation.
Elsewhere, Wonder has built walls as arcs that rotate and enclose.
Bruennhilde's resting place is a tall cylinder, the Magic Fire a
red band that encircles it.
</P>
<P>
   Most people seemed delighted by the simplicity and originality
of ``Das Rheingold'' and ``Die Walkuere,'' but Flimm ran into
trouble at Saturday's ``Siegfried,'' and his stock continued to
decline, bottoming out with the wave of boos at the end of
``Goetterdaemmerung.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Siegfried'' dragged, but then almost any interpretation of it
does. And by the time this third ``Ring'' opera arrived, Wonder's
visual coups had lost any power to amaze. The singing was more
damaging. Such is the labor shortage for ``Ring'' productions that
intendants seek out not the ideal talent, but the least
objectionable. Bayreuth is at least fortunate in its Wotan; Alan
Titus gathered command and confidence with every appearance.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Placido Domingo and Waltraud Meier played Siegmund and
Sieglinde, one bringing luxurious delivery to Act I of ``Die
Walkuere,'' the other white heat. Meier, who blasted the festival's
competence in a farewell press interview, contributed her customary
hair-raising intensity to the stage. Domingo's nicety of
articulation and beauty of sound may not be Wagnerian, but they
have much to teach any Wagner tenor.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Gabriele Schnaut is battle-scarred by a few too
many Bruennhildes. She was ferociously loud, and her wobble so
favored its upper extreme that the impression was of persistent
sharpness. Schnaut's Bruennhilde bore down on the helpless listener
like a sopranic freight train threatening derailment at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   Schnaut was at least in better control of her assets than her
counterpart, Wolfgang Schmidt. The people who hired Schmidt surely
knew his shortcomings, but I don't think they deserved his
near-collapse at the end of ``Siegfried.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Goetterdaemmerung'' he became merely coarse, a distinct
improvement. When Schmidt sang quietly, one heard remnants of a
once-attractive tenor voice. But Wagner is a notorious destroyer of
techniques. In moments of pressure this Siegfried could offer only
strangled desperation. When we were lucky, Schmidt landed on no
pitch at all, creating a kind of 19th-century German Romantic rap.
</P>
<P>
   Flimm, to his credit and our relief, had coached both singers
into theatrical believability, but their performances did not repay
him well. Yet rest assured that neither singer has squandered
further chances for employment. Wagner roles constitute a seller's
market, and casting them is the art of the possible.
</P>
<P>
   The production had better luck elsewhere, especially in Guenter
von Kannen, a marvelously blowsy and disreputable Alberich, and in
John Tomlinson's Hagen, which did much to rescue
``Goetterdaemmerung.'' Birgit Remmert in the tailored suits of a
soccer mom created a Fricka of dignity and poise. Mette Ejsing as
Erda boomed attractively. Violeta Urmana, so effective as Kundry in
``Parsifal,'' was a finely passionate Waltraute in
``Goetterdaemmerung.'' Others (Philip Kang as Fafner, Michael
Howard as Mime) were certainly acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Giuseppe Sinopoli seemed a strange choice to conduct the
``Ring.'' The Bayreuth acoustical aesthetic (clear, resonant vocal
sound in a largely wooden enclosure; warm, almost muffled orchestra
sound emanating from a covered pit) does not exactly play into this
conductor's hands. Sinopoli is small, thin and nervous, and his
music-making sounds much the same. I admired some of the nearly
out-of-control passions surrounding Siegfried's death and also
forgave a lot of ragged ensemble work and vague accompaniments.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Sinopoli's prominent winds and brass and his noticeably
reticent string sound (more expansive in ``Goetterdaemmerung'')
were the proper companions for Flimm's high-tech production.
Sinopoli sustained a lot of booing after ``Siegfried,'' appeared
for only one curtain call and did not appear at Saturday's news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Flimm's production seems caught in the center of a long-running
war over Wagner style, and this is one instance where the middle of
the road guarantees no safety. Radical revisionists want his
``Ring'' to dare and provoke more than it does. Others, like the
American millionaire and patron I overheard at intermission,
consider Flimm ``eccentric.''
</P>
<P>
   This production also appears in the midst of yet another power
struggle for control of Bayreuth. Blustery and combative at 80,
Wolfgang Wagner, the composer's grandson, holds on. But his
attackers this year are not only family members, but also
distinguished Bayreuthians like the bass Hans Sotin, who withdrew
from ``Parsifal,'' and Meier, who has made no bones about her
disgust with current policy. Wagner has been bolstered by a large
sum of American money to produce a new ``Tannhaeuser'' two years
from now.
</P>
<P>
   It is in such turmoil that Flimm has had to operate. Some of the
operas, ``Siegfried'' especially, need work, but once the clamor
for spectacle has died down and a more acceptable Bruennhilde and
Siegfried have been found, Wagnerites might find that this is a
``Ring'' that tells its story rather well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1847EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
