<HEADER>
A0849 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-SHOWER-REVIEW-HN     08-02 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SHOWER-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
A pleasing `Shower'
<TEXT>
<P>
   By ERIC HARRISON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes into ``Shower,'' a touching new film from China,
you pretty much know how it's going to end. For maybe half the
movie, this seems like a serious strike against it. But then,
gradually, something begins to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Telling details of what life is like for the working-class
characters slowly begin to accumulate. Daily rituals grow in
resonance. Our affection for the place (Beijing) and its people
deepens.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, the familiarity starts to feel like less of a
liability. I came to appreciate this movie the way I would a new
recording of a fine old song: The melody's the same, but it's a
different arrangement, and the singer brings to it shadings that no
other singer could.
</P>
<P>
   It would be more accurate to compare ``Shower'' to an ancient
fable or parable. It's the Prodigal Son with a twist.
</P>
<P>
   Stories similar to that New Testament tale exist in Buddhism and
other religions, and the basic outline appears again and again in
literature and film. It is one of our primary myths that carries a
wisdom recognized in every culture.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Shower,'' Da Ming, a successful businessman in a modernized
region of China, returns to the scuffed-up corner of Beijing in
which he was born; a postcard sent by his mentally disabled brother
had made it appear that their father had died.
</P>
<P>
   Played by Pu Cun Xin, who appeared in ``The Blue Kite,'' Da Ming
plainly is uncomfortable with his past and relations. His wife, who
we never see, doesn't even know about his brother's mental
handicap.
</P>
<P>
   The father, Master Liu (Zhu Xu, who starred recently in ``King
of Masks''), runs a deteriorating bathhouse that is the center of
life to a community of men who cling to the old ways. It is their
refuge, a place of companionship and peace where they go to bicker,
to stage cricket fights and to have their hurts massaged away.
</P>
<P>
   Da Ming, used to a faster pace, takes showers. The looks
exchanged between him and his father speak eloquently of old wounds
and reproaches, of lingering fears, and finally of love.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the simple, uncomplicated affection and joy that Liu
shares with his other son, Da Ming begins to long for same; he
misses the safe harbor of family. At the same time, he comes to
appreciate the important position his father and the bathhouse hold
in the community. Master Liu acts as priest, doctor and
psychologist, attending to the spiritual, physical and emotional
needs of his flock, and he takes his roles very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Through the eyes of Da Ming, we see the way people live their
lives, the little rituals and details that make up their days _ the
leisurely talks, the daily rubdowns, the recurring conflicts. He,
like us, is an outsider to this culture, made that way by his long
exile.
</P>
<P>
   The story isn't moved along by dialogue or by the linear
propulsion of plot so much as by repetition. We mark changes in
characters and mood by variations in routine _ someone new enters
the bathhouse or something happens to disrupt the natural order of
things. Or a character falters, and another steps in to ensure that
things continue.
</P>
<P>
   As mundane as these rituals are, it is their repetition that
forms the foundations of these characters' lives, just as they also
form the basis of a culture. Their accumulation in this movie
generates a power greater than any single event. It is almost
magical. That makes the men who perform the rituals shamans.
</P>
<P>
   When Da Ming becomes reintegrated into this world, he approaches
a state of almost spiritual grace.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Shower &UR;  &QL; 
Starring:  &LR; Zhu Xu, Pu Cun Xin, Jiang Wu &QL; 
 &UR; Director:  &LR;  Zhang Yang &UR;  &QL; 
Screenwriters:  &LR;  Liu Fen Dou, Zhang Yang, Hou Xin, Diao Yi Nan, Cai
Xiang Jun &QL; 
 &UR; Rating: &LR;  PG-13, for language and nudity &QL; 
 &UR; Running time: &LR;  92 minutes &QL; 
 &UR; Grade: &LR;  B &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
