<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FLORIDA DELEGATE SKIPS CONVENTION TO RAISE MONEY
 &HT;    By MARCIA GELBART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ State Rep. Mike Fasano is one of Florida's 80
alternate delegates here, but as of Wednesday he still had not set
foot on the convention floor.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the New Port Richey Republican, who is
coordinating his party's state House campaigns, has been spending
his time in the lobby of the Loews Philadelphia Hotel, joining
state Rep. Tom Feeney, R-Oviedo, in meetings with big GOP
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, Fasano expects to have enriched the Republican Party
of Florida by $100,000. ``Being 1,000 miles away from the state of
Florida, that's a very good thing,'' he said Wednesday at a Florida
GOP breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   By giving to the party, contributors are not limited to the $500
donation caps they would face if they gave to individual
candidates. Republicans control the House 75-45, and Feeney expects
his party's numbers to stay the same or increase by no more than
six, despite the 51 open House seats being contested because of
term limits.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday and Wednesday, Fasano and Feeney hosted more than a
half dozen small events, usually with just four or five people
apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're individuals who want to give money to our House
campaigns,'' said Fasano, though he declined to give names. Their
identities will become known in a few weeks, though, since election
laws require political parties to identify their contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Gelbart's e-mail address is
marcia(underscore)gelbart(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
