</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROXY-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARGEST PROXY-SOLICITATION FIRM ACQUIRES A RIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two of the biggest companies that solicit proxies
from shareholders during major mergers and acquisitions are doing a
deal of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Georgeson Shareholder Communications, the world's largest proxy
solicitations company, will announce Thursday that it has acquired
Corporate Investor Communications, the third largest firm in the
rather insular industry of shareholder communications. Terms of the
deal are not expected to be disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   As consolidation continues across most major industries at a
quick clip, companies like Georgeson and CIC work with the affected
companies to communicate with their shareholders about their deals.
</P>
<P>
   According to the two companies, their deal will give them the
capacity to communicate with more than 100 million shareholders a
year by mail, e-mail, telephone, fax and the Web. The combined
company communicates with 200,000 shareholders a day by phone,
representing 3,000 corporate clients and dealing with most of the
mutual fund industry.
</P>
<P>
   While Georgeson, based in New York, is known for its proxy
solicitation business during hostile takeovers, CIC, based in
Carlstadt, N.J., works much more behind the scenes on major deals,
responsible for the actual printing and mailing of proxies, annual
earnings reports and such.
</P>
<P>
   William M. Crane, Georgeson's president, said the acquisition
was prompted by a fundamental change in his company's market. ``The
need of our clients has changed as the individual investor has
become a significant part of the market,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
