A0857 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELTA-DIVERSITY0803-C     08-02 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-DIVERSITY0803-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta adds executive to push diversity
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines has created a new executive-level post
to promote work force diversity.
</P>
<P>
   The airline named Belinda Stubblefield, previously director of
marketing planning, as vice president-global diversity. She will
push company efforts to ``attract and maintain a team of highly
skilled, diverse people who have full and equal opportunity to grow
as professionals,'' the airline said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta spokesman John Kennedy said the move wasn't prompted by
high-profile racial discrimination lawsuits against three other big
Atlanta employers: Coca-Cola Co., Georgia Power Co. and Lockheed
Martin Corp.
</P>
<P>
   He also said it was unrelated to complaints on behalf of five
black female Delta employees filed with the Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission by a lawyer connected to the Coke case.
</P>
<P>
   The EEOC complaints, which were filed in May and could grow into
a lawsuit, allege systemic discrimination in promotions,
evaluations and pay. The women are represented by Birmingham
attorney Byron Perkins, a co-counsel with Washington lawyer Cyrus
Mehri in the Coke case.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins, who wouldn't identify his clients, said it's no
coincidence Delta created a new diversity post and put an
African-American woman in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was definitely in response to my clients' EEOC charges
and probably others,'' he said. ``The timing is too close. What
they're doing is what I call 'blackening up' and getting ready for
a court fight similar to what Coke did.'' Coke formed a diversity
advisory council, headed by two top executives, after being hit
with the lawsuit. Georgia Power named a diversity action council
after it was sued last week.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy wouldn't respond directly but noted that Delta first
established a diversity office in 1999. It was initially headed by
a general manager but now will be headed by Stubblefield.
Stubblefield, 37, joined Delta's marketing department last year.
Previously she was vice president-work force diversity at Nestle
USA Inc. and has also held marketing jobs at Nestle, Procter &AMP;
Gamble and IBM. The Michigan native is a graduate of UCLA and has
an MBA from Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Chairman Leo Mullin, in an employee memo accompanying the
announcement of Stubblefield's promotion, said diversity among
employees and suppliers is essential ``for any large, global
business that expects to thrive in the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullin said ``Delta's diversity commitment has produced
significant results'' in both areas but will be more effective
under a vice president.
</P>
<P>
   As of April 1, minorities composed 22 percent of Delta's work
force of 74,741, according to figures previously released by the
airline. The proportion drops to 15 percent among managers and 5
percent among executives at the director level and above.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
