<SLUG> BC-FBC-FALCONS-FINNERAN0803-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lanky wide receiver Finneran hopes to parlay his size into a job
with the Falcons
 &HT;    By Ken Sugiura
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Brian Finneran might have made an excellent swimmer.
</P>
<P>
   His arms dangle down his sides. Striding down the field, his
legs gobble up ground. His long, narrow frame looks as if it would
slice through the water. He even comes from one of the sport's
hotbeds, Mission Viejo, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran wouldn't merit a second look on a pool deck. But he is
trying to make a living catching footballs, and, among those who
ply that trade, he stands out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been my niche,'' said Finneran, the 6-foot-5 wide
receiver who has been catching eyes by catching passes in the
Falcons training camp at Furman University.
</P>
<P>
   His height helped him win a scholarship to Villanova, where as a
senior he caught 96 passes and won the Walter Payton Award as the
most outstanding player in Division I-AA. It also might gain him
entry onto the Falcons' regular-season roster.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday against the Colts, Finneran caught four passes for 68
yards, including a 13-yard touchdown pass from Danny Kanell in the
fourth quarter to win the game for Atlanta 20-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the ball's thrown to you, you've got to make
plays,'' he said. ``That's what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran's height, reach, leaping ability and dependable hands
have endeared him to the Falcons passers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thrown some ``out'' routes that I thought were high, and
he just reached up and got them,'' quarterback Chris Chandler said.
``But he catches the low ones good, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Kanell compared Finneran to two of the best receivers
in the league, Denver's Ed McCaffrey and Minnesota's Randy Moss.
Rookie Doug Johnson called Finneran ``the real deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran has fended off Falcons defensive backs throughout camp,
``He's got the big body,'' defensive backs coach Greg Brown said.
``It's hard to reach around him and make a play when you're a
small, little defensive back.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran is one of only nine wide receivers on an NFL roster
this summer who is 6 feet 5 inches. He is four inches taller than
the Falcons' next tallest wideout, Jammi German. As a whole, the
Falcons' pass-catching corps is more point guard than small
forward. Starters Shawn Jefferson and Terance Mathis are 5 feet 11
inches and 5 feet 10 inches, respectively. Tim Dwight is 5 feet 8
inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can just kind of throw it up there in his area,'' Chandler
said, ``and he usually comes down with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran isn't a cinch to make the team. Jefferson, Mathis and
Dwight probably have spots. Finneran is one of four going for
probably two slots, and coach Dan Reeves called wide receiver the
most competitive position in camp.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran undoubtedly is motivated by the experience of having
been let go in the past. In 1998, he signed with Seahawks as an
undrafted free agent, and was cut. He didn't play that season, but
after tearing up NFL Europe he was picked up by the Eagles last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   However, he bobbled a crucial pass in the first game of the 1999
season, and the Eagles sent him packing four weeks later. He hung
around Philadelphia, practicing on his own, going to four tryouts
and working two weeks on a construction site, before the Falcons
signed him to their practice roster in December.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his impressive performance last week against the Colts,
Finneran knows that he needs to continue to impress the Falcons'
coaching staff Saturday against the Cowboys in Tokyo and in the
three preseason games following.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just make the team,'' he said. ``That's the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
