u e BC-CABLE-TV-MOVIES-2TAKE     08-02 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE-TV-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABLE TAKES UP MANTLE OF TV FILMS, AS TRADITIONAL NETWORKS LOOK TO
REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ FX is one of those cable networks that many channel
surfers glide past because it offers reruns of enduring hits like
``NYPD Blue,'' ``The X-Files'' and ``Married with Children.''
</P>
<P>
   But Peter Liguori, president of FX Networks, which is owned by
the News Corp., said that like other cable stations, FX was trying
to get more attention and reinvent itself in the face of an
increasingly competitive network arena obsessed with reality
programs like CBS's ``Survivor'' and quiz shows like ABC's ``Who
Wants to be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Original television movies are now being minimized in the
world of the networks,'' Liguori said. ``This opens up
opportunities in the world of basic cable to fill the void.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is a provocative FX drama, ``Deliberate Intent,''
which will have its premiere 8 p.m. Sunday, the first dramatic film
on a network not known for original films.
</P>
<P>
   FX is hardly alone. MTV, VH-1 and E! Entertainment _ which are
known for their music videos, lightweight interviews and
documentaries _ are joining the ranks of HBO, Showtime, TNT,
Lifetime, A&AMP;E and other stations in the quest for audiences seeking
dramatic films and series. ESPN, the sports network, is also
considering making dramatic films.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is straightforward: cable networks like MTV and E!
want to solidify and expand their audiences by moving into new
areas like dramatic shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic that cable and the broadcast networks are coming
from different directions and moving toward the middle _ the
broadcast networks once had scripted and fiction shows, and are now
moving towards the reality side, while the cable networks are
moving from reality to fiction,'' said Mindy Herman, president and
chief executive of E! Networks, which is planning 10 to 15 series
and four to six films a year.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Brian Graden, president of programming at MTV, said
the network was adding dramatic shows and series to its mix of
music videos and interviews, largely aimed at 12- to 24-year-olds.
Starting Wednesday at 10 p.m., MTV will offer a 13-part series
called ``Live Through This,'' a multigenerational drama about a
reunited rock band of the '70s that goes back on tour accompanied
by their teen-age children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly crossing the line, creating dramas and series
around music,'' Graden said. ``MTV is such a special brand that as
the head programmer, I want to take it slowly. We don't want to put
all our eggs in one basket. Our model is HBO. I want to make sure
that we don't end up as a traditional television channel.''
</P>
<P>
   Home Box Office, under its former chairman, Michael Fuchs, began
making films and series in 1983, serving as a model for other cable
networks. (HBO's first film was ``The Terry Fox Story,'' about a
one-legged runner, and its first series was ``Not Necessarily the
News,'' with news clips in sketch comedy).
</P>
<P>
   Though the broadcast networks are still dominant, in recent
years they have been envious of and a little irritated by HBO's
success with free-wheeling shows like ``The Sopranos'' and ``Sex in
the City,'' which have few constraints on language and sex, and are
the darlings of critics. Last year, despite 16 nominations, ``The
Sopranos'' did not win the best dramatic series award at the Emmys,
which has been taken as a sign of resentment toward HBO for its
daring treatment of sex and language. Instead, ``The Practice'' on
ABC won for the second straight year.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For the cable networks, the risks of competing in this new arena
are largely financial. A two-hour drama on cable often costs $3
million to $5 million, and sometimes much more. A reality show may
cost $200,000. The payoff in producing dramatic shows, they hope,
is higher advertising rates and larger audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk is that these are expensive pieces of programming,
and we know how difficult the movie business is,'' Liguori said.
``What you hope to do is make intelligent bets and promote them
wisely. It's a high-risk reward for cable to do this, while
traditional networks are squeezing back on writing and storytelling
and heavying up on reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this, there's a more intangible risk for some cable
networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't create the right type of movie or drama and you
are a very branded channel like VH-1 or MTV or ESPN, then you risk
watering down your brand by providing the wrong type of product,''
said Jeffrey Gaspin, executive vice president of programming and
production at VH-1. ``So our movies are about music.''
</P>
<P>
   The VH-1 films have been about the lives of the Monkees, about
the performer Meat Loaf and about Ricky Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   To writers and directors struggling in the face of diminishing
numbers of dramas and series on network television, the entry of
cable into the arena is clearly a boon. FX, for example, plans four
films a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opens up a whole new world of venues where you can tell
stories that in some cases are edgy and will get attention, and are
certainly not what the networks are doing,'' said Andy Wolk, the
director and co-author, with Lisa Mohan, of the adaptation of
``Deliberate Intent.'' The harrowing legal drama is based on a book
by Rodney Smolla, a First Amendment lawyer and expert on
Constitutional law.
</P>
<P>
   The drama is a true story about a hit man hired by a former
Motown record executive to kill his ex-wife, their paraplegic son
and a nurse for insurance money that paid for the boy's medical
care. In murdering the three, the killer meticulously used the
details provided in a mail-order book called ``Hit Man: A Technical
Manual for Independent Contractors,'' published by Paladin Press.
The result was a lawsuit against Paladin Press and its owner, Peder
Lund, a former Green Beret.
</P>
<P>
   The cast includes Timothy Hutton as Smolla, who represented the
plaintiffs _ the victims' family _ in the groundbreaking lawsuit.
Other members of the cast include Ron Rifkin as another family
lawyer, and two well-known television actors, James McDaniel of
``NYPD Blue,'' who plays the former Motown executive, and Clark
Johnson of ``Homicide,'' who plays the killer for hire.
</P>
<P>
   Other networks joining the drama bandwagon include E!, which has
completed four films so far. One, ``Best Actress,'' a drama about
Oscar contenders, was presented last year about the time of the
Academy Award ceremonies. Another, ``Becoming Dick,'' about a
Hollywood actor who realizes that the only way to succeed is to
turn into a jerk, will be shown on Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Herman, the president of E!, said that one factor easily
overlooked is what she calls the halo effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing these movies does have an effect on your brand and your
position in the marketplace,'' Herman said. ``When you launch these
shows, you get higher ratings. You get more press and publicity. It
creates a halo for your network that hopefully trickles down to the
other shows you have.'' She added: ``Ten years ago HBO was the
archetype network when they started doing movies. It added a
certain cachet. We're learning from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bewkes, HBO's chairman, said his network was not troubled
by the trend of cable networks to move into films and dramatic
series. During the last two years TNT and Showtime have sought to
compete with HBO: TNT last year announced a schedule heavy on
classics like ``Animal Farm,'' ``Don Quixote'' and ``David
Copperfield.''
</P>
<P>
   Bewkes said that the many cable networks creating feature film
and series ``should actually reinvigorate these genres.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're right to do this, and I'm not surprised it's
happening,'' he said. ``A network needs to have distinct
programming. And movies and series are a way of doing that.'' He
added that HBO did not view just other cable networks as
competition. ``NBC, CBS, ABC and Fox are our competition too,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
