u f BC-DELL-STOCK0803-COX     08-02 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-STOCK0803-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dell Computer stock continues slide
 &HT;    By John Pletz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Dell Computer Corp. stock continued to tumble
Wednesday when one industry analyst downgraded the stock and fueled
continued speculation about whether the computer maker's growth is
slowing more than previously thought.
</P>
<P>
   After falling 5.4 percent Tuesday to $41.56 per share, Dell's
stock slipped another $2, or 4.8 percent, Wednesday to close at
$39.56. Since July 17, the stock has fallen $14, or 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ashok Kumar, an analyst for U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray,
downgraded Dell to ``buy'' from ``strong buy.'' He questioned not
only the company's short-term prospects, but also suggested that
Dell's glory days of runaway growth and soaring stock price may be
behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Kumar, who has been sharply critical of Dell recently for its
acquisition last year of storage-technology company ConvergeNet,
questioned whether the PC maker can hit its own revenue-growth
targets.
</P>
<P>
   Dell spent the past year persuading Wall Street to lower
expectations for earnings and revenue growth to about 30 percent
annually from the 50 percent rate the company had enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   Kumar wrote that while Dell might be able to meet the earnings
target, ``we are skeptical that the company will be able to meet
the 30 percent revenue-growth expectations on a sustainable
basis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to believe that Dell does not have adequate
earnings power in notebooks, server and nonsystem revenue to offset
the secular weakness in consumer and commercial desktops.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell, which is scheduled to report second-quarter results next
Thursday, did not comment. It is subject to ``quiet period''
restrictions that prohibit discussing company performance in
advance of quarterly earnings announcements.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect Dell to earn 21 cents per share, according to a
survey by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   In general, analysts remain bullish on Dell: 19 rate it a
``strong buy,'' while five call it a ``moderate buy,'' and four tag
it a ``hold,'' according to Zacks Investment Research Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have been skittish about PC makers in general in
recent weeks since two market-research firms reported that the
industry's second-quarter sales were weaker than expected.
</P>
<P>
   IDC and Gartner Group's Dataquest both said overall
second-quarter shipments grew more slowly this year than in 1999,
though last year's results were unusually high because of buying in
advance of Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Both firms also suggested that the U.S. and European markets,
which grew more slowly than the rest of the world, are beginning to
mature. That's of particular concern with Dell, which does 70
percent of its business in the United States and 21 percent in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   IDC estimated last week that Dell actually lost a very small
percentage of market share in the Europe/Middle East/Africa segment
during the second quarter, slipping to 9.1 percent from 9.3 percent
a year ago. Its shipments increased 6.4 percent from a year ago,
slightly below the overall market rate of 9.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet.com reported Tuesday that another analyst, Andrew Neff
of Bear Stearns, also raised some concerns about Dell's short-term
revenue prospects in a note to the firm's staff. Neff did not put
out a note to clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's probably some concern over the IDC numbers, and the
slower rollout of Windows 2000. That's more of a fourth-quarter
story,'' David Bailey, an analyst who follows Dell for Gerard
Klauer Mattison, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   More important to investors, Kumar questioned whether Dell's
stock _ which split six times between October 1995 and March 1999 _
will break out of the $35-$60 funk it's been in for the past 18
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock does not possess anywhere near the momentum it did
in 1997/1998,'' he wrote. ``The stock has now dropped below its
two-year, moving-average line, at $42, which is beginning to
flatten out. Bottom line _ real technical deterioration has set
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
