<SLUG> BC-GEBEL-WILLIAMS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIRCUS LEGEND RESTLESS IN RECOVERY FROM BRAIN SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS BECNEL   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENICE, Fla. _ Like a restless tiger pacing the center ring,
Gunther Gebel-Williams prowls around his Venice home.
</P>
<P>
   The 65-year-old circus legend had surgery to remove a cancerous
brain tumor 3 1/2 weeks ago, but his family says that's not enough
to slow him down. Every morning Gebel-Williams goes in for
radiation treatment. Every afternoon he looks for something else to
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day he came by my house and started vacuuming,''
says his daughter, Tina Del Moral, laughing and shaking her head.
``Then he was plucking weeds in the yard, and we're like, `C'mon,
Dad.'''
</P>
<P>
   His famous blond hair, shorn on the left side for surgery, is
slowly growing back. Friends say he remains tanned and fit, upbeat
as always.
</P>
<P>
   Gebel-Williams isn't doing interviews _ that's the one part of
circus life he never enjoyed _ but he is approaching recovery with
the single-mindedness he brought to his famous tiger-and-elephant
act. For years he was the greatest performer in ``The Greatest Show
on Earth'' _ the Ringling Bros. and Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord of the Ring'' retired from performing in 1990, but
has continued to tour and work behind the scenes with his son,
Mark, who inherited his father's tiger act. In December, when
Ringling begins rehearsals in Tampa for another tour,
Gebel-Williams would like to rejoin the circus.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his mind, he can do anything,'' says Kenneth Feld, the
Ringling owner who brought the German performer to America in 1969.
``He has done anything and everything; he's a historic
individual.''
</P>
<P>
   In Venice and nearby Sarasota, former winter headquarters of the
Ringling circus, plenty of people know just how big a star
Gebel-Williams is.
</P>
<P>
   For those who didn't grow up in a circus town, here's a clue.
Think Michael Jordan _ Michael Jordan and Cal Ripken.
</P>
<P>
   When people say ``Gunther,'' there's no doubt who they mean.
He's acknowledged as the finest wild animal trainer in circus
history, the man who broke the old mold of the lion tamer subduing
ferocious beasts with a whip and a chair.
</P>
<P>
   In the center ring, Gebel-Williams would coax a 500-pound tiger
into leaping onto the back of an elephant. He was lithe and sexy,
too, baring his chest, draping a leopard around his neck and
flashing a brilliant smile.
</P>
<P>
   For all the glamour, he was also astonishingly tough and
durable, even by the demanding standards of the traveling circus.
For more than 20 years and 12,000 performances, he never missed a
show.
</P>
<P>
   Feld often watched his star perform just hours after being
scratched or bitten, usually while trying to break up a fight
between animals. He needed hundreds of stitches during his career,
though he was never badly mauled by one of his big cats. Much
later, in 1996, he had heart valve replacement surgery.
</P>
<P>
   With Gebel-Williams, no matter what happened, the show went on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget, in the late '70s, Memphis, Tennessee, his
foot was smashed, caught in a railroad coupling,'' said Feld. ``He
worked that night sitting in the first row with his foot propped
up, commanding the elephants with just his voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the worst I saw him hurt, and the most amazing
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Huey, Ringling vice president of public relations,
remembers Gebel-Williams on tour. Every day he'd ask the great
trainer how he was doing, and every day the answer was the same:
``Fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always larger than life,'' said Huey. ``Walking into a
room, walking into a hospital, he has a presence. I saw him the day
after surgery and we were talking. I asked him how he was doing,
and he said, `Fantastic.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gebel-Williams' wife, Sigrid, says her husband is a surprisingly
good patient. He's trying to take it easy, doing things like
watching his grandson swim in the family pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never listened to anyone in his life, but he listens to
doctors,'' said Sigrid. ``He's just like a little lamb.''
</P>
<P>
   The circus star has been enjoying sports on TV. During Wimbledon
the family compared his close-cropped hair with Andre Agassi's.
They were all inspired by cancer survivor Lance Armstrong's victory
in the Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   Gebel-Williams' cancer treatment will include more than six
weeks of radiation therapy. Sometime in September he'll have
another MRI.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest thing about his time at home, family members agree,
is being apart from his son, the circus and the animals he's
trained and worked with for most of his life.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Tina, says the only animal around the house in
Venice is her black poodle, Mousi.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be? The great circus animal trainer, with time on his
hands, working with . . . a poodle?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not yet,'' she says, laughing, ``but I'm sure that'll come
up.''
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Becnel writes for The Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.,
which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
This article was distributed by The New York Times.)
</P>
<P>
   l
</P>
</TEXT>
