<HEADER>
A0863 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-VANDY-PREVIEW-080     08-02 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-VANDY-PREVIEW-0803-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC coaches think Vanderbilt has potential to stir up league
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - This isn't the same old Vanderbilt.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Florida coach Steve Spurrier, who was talking to
Commodores coach Woody Widenhofer at the Southeastern Conference's
spring meetings in Destin, Fla. Spurrier was telling Widenhofer
that Vanderbilt should have beaten his Gators last season when
Georgia coach Jim Donnan walked into the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, they should have beaten us, too,'' Donnan said.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Widenhofer says his team could have won four more games
last season. The Commodores had fourth-quarter leads against
Alabama and the Bulldogs, and they outgained the high-powered
offenses of Florida and Kentucky by at least 100 yards each.
</P>
<P>
   The Commodores found a way to lose those games and finished 5-6.
It was the program's 17th consecutive losing season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a pretty good year last year in terms of building up
our confidence and esteem,'' said Widenhofer, who enters his fourth
season at Vanderbilt. ``We lost several close games. (But) it is
not the same old Vanderbilt. There's a new atmosphere at
Vanderbilt. Our players have gained a lot of confidence in
themselves and learned that they can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt's 1999 season wasn't completely fruitless. The
Commodores rallied from a 14-0 deficit to beat Mississippi in
overtime 37-34, the school's first SEC road victory in five years.
If not for a failed fake punt against Georgia, Vanderbilt might
have been playing in its first bowl game since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we've turned the corner,'' Vandy tight end Elliott
Carson said. ``We haven't gone to a bowl game yet, but we had a
come-from-behind win and won an SEC road game last year. I think
we've gotten over the hump. We've just got to finish games. All of
the pieces are there.''
</P>
<P>
   They're certainly there on defense. Vandy returns nine starters
from a unit that ranked 24th nationally. Inside linebacker Jamie
Winborn is a candidate for All-America, and senior Jimmy Williams
is one of the SEC's top cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt averaged 22.9 points per game last year, its highest
scoring output since 1987, and the offense should improve this
season. Quarterback Greg Zolman is being pressured by Florida
transfer Tim Olmstead and redshirt freshman Benji Walker. The
offensive line returns three starters and nine of the team's 10
linemen have had the benefit of redshirting.
</P>
<P>
   Highly regarded recruit Chris Young of Batesville, Miss., should
bolster a receiving corps that lost top pass-catcher Tavarus Hogans
to graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt will have to overcome one of the leagu. ``If they
ever start winning a few games, they might beat everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   VANDERBILT
</P>
<P>
   Location: Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment: 5,885.
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Woody Widenhofer, 10-23 in three seasons at Vanderbilt,
22-54-1 overall.
</P>
<P>
   Nickname: Commodores.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium (capacity): Vanderbilt Stadium (41,448).
</P>
<P>
   All-time record: 521-475-50.
</P>
<P>
   Conference championships: None.
</P>
<P>
   1999 record (overall, conference): 5-6, 2-6 in SEC East.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule: Sept. 2 vs. Miami (Ohio); Sept. 9 at Alabama; Sept. 16
vs. Mississippi; Sept. 23 vs. Duke; Sept. 30 at Auburn; Oct. 7 at
Wake Forest; Oct. 14 at Georgia; Oct. 21 vs. South Carolina; Nov. 4
vs. Florida; Nov. 11 at Kentucky; Nov. 25 vs. Tennessee.
</P>
