<HEADER>
A0864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CAR-HOTRODS-WWF-NYTR &LR;      08-02 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-HOTRODS-WWF-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAGSTERS WRESTLE WITH A NEW IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By RICH RUPPRECHT   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SONOMA, Calif. _ Jerry Toliver drives a hot car and not just
because he leads the Funny Car point standings over the legendary
John Force.
</P>
<P>
   Toliver drives ``The Rock,'' the same name as the World
Wrestling Federation champion. Toliver, who is relatively new to
drag racing at age 49, heads the WWF drag racing team, which means
not just gearheads are hanging around Toliver's racing cars.
</P>
<P>
   Toliver is part of a tag team. Jim Epler drives the ``Kane''
car, also the name of a WWF wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   Force, Tolliver and Epler will be among the fan favorites here
this weekend at Sears Point in the NHRA Fram Autolite Nationals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a definite crossover in the two sports,'' Toliver
said. ``We go to a lot of the wrestling matches and they come to
some of our races.''
</P>
<P>
   While no official surveys have been done, it doesn't take a
rocket scientist to figure out the male demographic group 12-34
will include many wrestling fans who are also drag racing buffs.
</P>
<P>
   Toliver said he had met people connected with the WWF through
bodybuilding and later approached the William Morris talent agency,
which also happened to have the WWF as a client. A few months later
Toliver was walking around the race circuit, holding up The Rock's
world championship belt.
</P>
<P>
   Toliver was born in Compton, Calif., and grew up hanging around
his uncles Jack and Art Chrisman, who are members of the NHRA Drag
Racing Hall of Fame. His grandfather was the head of the racing
team.
</P>
<P>
   Toliver raced street hot rods as a youth, but said he never had
the money or backing to get into drag racing earlier in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to have done this 20 years ago, but the timing wasn't
right,'' Toliver said. NHRA competition is not cheap. The top teams
will spend $5 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Toliver spent seven years in drag boat racing, competing in the
Alcohol Hydro category for the International Hot Boat Association.
Toliver went over 220 mph in the boats, but in 1995 broke his back
and hand in a crash. He switched to conventional drag racing the
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to be in a car, but economically it just
wasn't possible until then,'' said Toliver, who is CEO of the
Toliver Corp., a chemical transfer and packaging company with
terminals on the East and West coasts. What began as a one-man
company is now a multi-million dollar business. It enabled Toliver
to fulfill his drag racing dream.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1997 season Toliver purchased Gary Clapshaw's Funny
Car operation and then received his Nitro Funny Car license in
January of 1998. Later that year he obtained sponsorship from Mad
Magazine/DC Comics/Warner Bros. The cars of his team were the
Alfred E. Neuman and Spy vs. Spy racers. Suddenly, fans were paying
attention to Toliver's team.
</P>
<P>
   Toliver then acquired the more lucrative WWF sponsorship before
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Mad Magazine operation kind of opened their
eyes,'' Toliver said of Vince McMahon's WWF. ``My budget got much
bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   What Toliver accomplished was to link up with one of the most
popular forms of entertainment (some bristle when you call
wrestling a sport) around.
</P>
<P>
   The same time Martha Stewart went public with stock offerings,
so did the WWF. Wrestling is just one part of what is officially
called World Wrestling Federation Entertainment Inc. ``It's kind of
like a soap opera,'' Toliver said of WWF wrestling. ``I watch it
and I think a lot of people have their favorite wrestlers and want
to know how they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Toliver, wrestler Steve Austin, the ``Stone Cold'' car
that Toliver drove, and the WWF racing team appeared on the ``Regis
and Kathie Lee Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year when Toliver drove the ``Stone Cold'' Steve Austin
Funny Car, Epler drove ``The Undertaker.'' No word yet on the names
of next year's cars.
</P>
<P>
   Toliver won his first NHRA Funny Car race on the last week of
the 1999 season. This year he's won three times and reached the
finals six times.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend in Seattle he lost a close match with Force in the
semifinals. Toliver said his close friendship with Force turns to a
strong rivalry only when they climb into their race cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great ambassador of the sport,'' Tolliver said. ``I
consider him a best friend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
