<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-AIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICERS WITH AIDS TRY TO KEEP DISEASE A SECRET
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT28 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is a new fraternity growing within the clannish
New York Police Department, but most of its members are so ashamed
by what they share that they have never met and do not even know
one another's names.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is that all of them have the virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   To their fellow officers, they are indistinguishable from the
rest of the 40,000 men and women who police New York City, but in
their own minds, AIDS has set them apart. For many, it weighs them
down not only with the fear of death, but also with a secret they
are desperate to keep from their fellow officers.
</P>
<P>
   They are afraid, they say, that they will be banished from the
wider police fraternity, a sort of blue reservoir of strength that
they are used to turning to for solace. They cannot imagine telling
their colleagues they have a disease that many officers believe is
an affliction only of gay men, drug addicts, prostitutes and the
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear is that they would isolate you and cast you aside and
say they don't want to work with you,'' said an officer who tested
positive a year ago and has since watched as fellow officers, even
her friends, have treated HIV-positive prisoners with derision. ``I
wish the people I work with could know,'' the officer said, ``but I
just don't think they would understand.''
</P>
<P>
   The HIV-positive officers include a middle-age white man who
lives in the suburbs with his wife and children, who said he tested
positive for the virus after being bitten by an infected suspect; a
Hispanic single mother of two, who said she caught the disease from
her former husband, also a police officer; and a young black man
who is openly gay and says he is unsure how he contracted the
virus.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies, arts organizations and even professional sports
teams have been forced to deal with AIDS over the last 20 years.
Police departments are no different. Police officials in Chicago
and Los Angeles, for example, say that officers who are infected
with HIV or who have AIDS are treated like any other officer with a
serious illness.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, officers who test positive for HIV can turn to
the department's Early Intervention program for counseling and
referrals, and to a police union group called the Members'
Assistance Program.
</P>
<P>
   Many are referred to a man who has become the department's
unofficial AIDS counselor, Stephen P. Yurcik, a retired officer who
tested positive in 1990 and saw his wife, also a New York police
officer, die from the disease two years later. Yurcik said he had
the backing of both the department and the police union for his
group, Positive Police.
</P>
<P>
   While the department cannot say how many officers have tested
positive for HIV or are already suffering from AIDS, Yurcik, the
police union and a gay officers' group estimate that there are
anywhere from two dozen to more than a hundred.
</P>
<P>
   Yurcik counsels 15 officers, referring them to treatment,
guiding them through their self-education about the virus and
sharing his experiences with them.
</P>
<P>
   Several of those 15 officers talked to a reporter on the
condition that their names and other identifying information be
withheld.
</P>
<P>
   Although by law workers cannot be compelled to tell their
employers that they have AIDS or any other disease, Yurcik said
that one of his messages was that they could trust the department.
</P>
<P>
   But even the officer who contracted the virus after being bitten
is adamant that his condition remain a secret, despite the
department's official acknowledgment that his illness resulted from
a line-of-duty injury, a risk faced by every officer who patrols
the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to keep it to yourself,'' the officer said. ``It's
something you really don't want other people knowing, because you
don't want people to look at you differently.''
</P>
<P>
   The officer said he was devastated when he learned he had
contracted the virus, and he credits Yurcik for helping him and his
family through some of the most difficult times.
</P>
<P>
   Yurcik said he believed that greater awareness about officers
with AIDS and better education about the disease within the
department would encourage officers to come forward and,
eventually, would help reduce the stigma they feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the cruelty and maliciousness of cops, their humor,''
Yurcik said. But he said he also knew the kindness of his fellow
officers, and he is still moved when he talks about the help he got
after his wife died.
</P>
<P>
   Yurcik said that in 1992, he told an officer he worked with that
his wife was dying of AIDS and that he had tested positive for HIV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him to go back and tell the guys. He went back and told
everybody,'' Yurcik said. ``They were totally blown away. And I
just got flooded with calls. And it was genuine _ you can tell with
these things.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Most of the people that get the confidence to tell
their partners are surprised to see how they react.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a message that Patrick J. Lynch, the president of the
Patrolmen's Benevolent Association, also wants to get out. He said
that he had met with Yurcik and that he wanted him to address the
union's more than 500 delegates so they, in turn, could educate the
rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   But the officers who have tested positive for HIV say their
instinct to hide is only reinforced when they see their colleagues
treat HIV-infected citizens or prisoners with cruelty and
indifference.
</P>
<P>
   One officer listened to colleagues complain that their tax
dollars were being wasted on AIDS treatment and research.
</P>
<P>
   Two officers who agreed to be interviewed said their decision to
remain silent was greatly complicated by fears that if they
themselves were shot or injured, they could infect a colleague or
someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``My God, what if I get cut?'' said the Hispanic officer who is
a single mother. ``What's going to happen? I was afraid of getting
someone else sick. What if I have a car accident?''
</P>
<P>
   Yurcik said that there were no documented cases of the disease
being spread through mouth-to-mouth resuscitation, and that even in
instances in which an officer was shot or badly cut, the likelihood
of a colleague's being infected from contact with the blood was
almost nil.
</P>
<P>
   Still, every officer is trained to take precautions, like
avoiding unprotected contact with blood by using equipment like
rubber gloves, which are standard issue in every patrol car, and
masks.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Yurcik's friends credit him with opening their eyes
about both disease and prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Frank R. Favilla, who grew up with Yurcik in Queens,
says his friend's illness has had a profound effect on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My best friend is sick,'' he said, his eyes betraying some of
the sadness that has come with his education. ``The whole thing, it
changes you. You get older, you get wiser and you realize that
people aren't sick because they're bad people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1902EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
