<HEADER>
A0870 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-BUDGET-UPDATE-NYT     08-02 1417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-BUDGET-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS: The New York Times is planning several pages of GOP
convention-related stories for Thursday, Aug. 3. The New York Times
News Service will file the following stories and photos tonight in
the ``p'' news file. Stories are scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.
For repeats or information, call 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927.
HELD: GOP-DELEGATES.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-RDP-NYT (Philadelphia) _ A convention roundup: Gov. George
W. Bush makes his calibrated entry into Philadelphia on Wednesday
morning, the day delegates at the 37th Republican National
Convention are to select him as their nominee for president. Bush
and Dick Cheney are to receive their party's official nominations
tonight, and Cheney will speak to the convention.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: An early, 900-word version of the roundup has moved and
will be updated with a longer version written by Richard L. Berke,
with quotes from late speeches; complete text of Dick Cheney's
speech will be available at the New York Times on the Web:
www.nytimes.com)
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-BUSH-NYT _ Man in the News profile: Just six years ago, when
George W. Bush ran for governor of Texas, even his own parents
expected him to lose; it was his younger brother Jeb who held the
family's confidence. Friends and family members say that the elder
Bushes worried that George W. would be forced to bow again, as he
had several times before, to failure. But that story had a surprise
ending: While Jeb lost, George won. And in the process, George
Walker Bush launched himself, without any grand plan or intricate
forethought, on a trajectory that on Thursday will place him in the
spotlight as the Republican nominee for president, continuing along
what historians may some day recall as one of the most remarkable
paths ever taken to the White House. By Nicholas D. Kristof and
Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   3,200 words; an abridged version will also move.
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT6, 17.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-CONSERVATIVES-NYT _ These are complicated times for social
conservatives. They feel they are winning on their core issues at
this convention, but some of them clearly miss the red meat
rhetoric and partisan edge of conventions past, replaced this week
by the Bush campaign's relentless appeal to the center. There was,
unmistakably, a wave of grumbling among conservative ranks, but
inside the conservative movement there is an overriding desire to
win in November. So social conservatives are focusing on the
victories they have won here _ a strong anti-abortion platform and
the selection of a conservative running-mate, Dick Cheney. By Robin
Toner. 1,300 words
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT23, 24.
