<P>
   GOP-MANAGERS-NYT _ How the convention managers are maintaining
discipline. Four years ago, speakers at the Republican convention
in San Diego were required to sign pledges promising to stick only
to the script approved by convention organizers. This year,
convention speakers _ all carefully screened in advance _ said they
have been told in the broadest guidelines what they should talk
about. They have also been told what they should NOT say: harsh
attacks that might invite comparisons to the Republican convention
of 1992. And while speeches are required by convention auditors, as
they are called, the main concern seems to be making sure that the
speakers keep to time, and not disrupt the snappy pace of a
convention that is meant to have the feel of a fast-paced
television spectacular. By Adam Nagourney. 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-FRANKS-NYT _ In the land of the deep pockets, New Jersey's
Republican candidate for the Senate, Rep. Bob Franks, is the poor
man's candidate, scratching around for funds. By David M.
Halbfinger. 600 words.
</P>
