<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0871 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DIABLO-GAME-2TAKES-NY     08-02 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIABLO-GAME-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPULARITY OF FANTASY PC GAME DIABLO II RIVALS HARRY POTTER'S
LATEST CHRONICLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ It came out just recently, a highly anticipated
sequel to a best seller filled with stories of wizards and
sorcerers. Revenue has topped $50 million so far, reviews have been
good, and fans, who waited impatiently for their new heroes to
arrive, are thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire,'' right?
</P>
<P>
   Right _ and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth installment of the Harry Potter series is not the
only fantasy-filled hit this summer. On July 3, five days before
Harry Potter arrived in stores, Blizzard Entertainment, which is
based here, released Diablo II, a Dungeons and Dragons-like
computer game in which players battle a demon to save the world.
</P>
<P>
   So far, even though Blizzard marketed Diablo II only to serious
game players, it has sold more than 1 million copies worldwide, at
an average retail price of more than $50. The 70,000 copies of the
$70 collectors' edition, which was offered before the game was
officially released, have sold out.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of revenue, that puts Diablo II within striking
distance of the Potter book, which sold nearly 3 million copies in
its first weekend in stores, according to Scholastic, its
publisher, but often at deep discounts to the cover price of
$25.95. Diablo II is on track to be one of the top-selling computer
games.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Diablo II, which is designed for older teen-agers and
adults, has hardly registered on the media radar screen. And while
Potter and his creator, J.K. Rowling, have won praise around the
globe for drawing videogame-crazed and television-besotted young
people back to reading, games like Diablo II draw condemnation for
ensnaring players in a morbid worldview and gluing them
antisocially to a computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``A medal should be struck for Rowling,'' said the novelist
Sidney Sheldon, the former national spokesman for the Coalition for
Literacy, in a typical observation. ``For this woman to come along
and excite millions of children about reading today is a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon, whose sometimes steamy books have sold more than 300
million copies worldwide, said he believed that video games were
``getting so dark and so cruel; the object is to kill somebody, and
I think that is dreadful.''
</P>
<P>
   Diablo II is rated ``mature'' by the Entertainment Software
Rating Board, the equivalent of an R rating for a movie: few games
receive more restrictive ratings. A rating of mature means Diablo
II is supposed to be sold only to players who are 17 or older. But
many children and younger teen-agers play the game as well,
according to Mike Morhaime, president of Blizzard, a subsidiary of
Vivendi, the French company that is buying Seagram and its
Universal Studios operation in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while the game is hardly nonviolent, it is ``Harry Potter
and the Goblet of Fire,'' not Diablo II, that opens with the murder
of a 76-year-old man. And it is Diablo II, not ``Harry Potter,''
that gives young people worldwide the opportunity to interact with
each other in real time over the Internet, solving problems and
battling monsters together.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many Diablo II players say they are also avid readers of
science fiction and fantasy. And like Harry Potter, the characters
in Diablo II are ultimately fighting evil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Potter'' and games like Diablo II may have more in
common than many people realize, said Robert Coover, a Brown
University English professor and experimental novelist who is among
the leaders of efforts to find new ways to write on the Internet.
``I don't like the sense that book reading is good and computer
game playing is not,'' Coover said.
</P>
<P>
   In Diablo II, players pick one of five character types and then
try to complete increasingly difficult quests assigned to them by
computer-controlled characters in the game. There are four worlds
to conquer, and along the way, players must strengthen their
characters, finding better weapons and armor and learning new
skills they will need to battle increasingly sinister creatures. In
practice, players spend much of their time killing or dodging
skeletons, zombies and other monsters, and many of the quests are
themselves nothing more than hunting expeditions for evil
creatures.
</P>
<P>
   But in contrast to ``first-person shooter'' games like Doom, in
which players feel as if they are looking through the eyes of a
character whose sole purpose is to kill as many other players and
characters as possible, Diablo II is what video game experts call a
third-person game. In these, players view their characters and the
game's world from above, as if watching from a low-flying plane,
and the violence is not particularly graphic.
</P>
<P>
   ```Harry Potter' and Diablo II are both fantasy _ it's an escape
for people,'' said Bill Roper, a producer at Blizzard who helped to
lead the development of the game.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Diablo takes at least 50 hours to solve, according to Morhaime,
Blizzard's president. ``People take a lot of pride in their
characters,'' he said. ``There's a big sense of accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   In e-mail interviews, several players of Diablo II echoed that
view.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the hook is character development, and in Diablo's
case, hunting for items,'' wrote Caton Little, a 27-year-old player
from New Zealand. ``The story's not too important, although
hackneyed back-stories turn me right off.''
</P>
<P>
   As a measure of the seriousness with which some players treat
their characters, Blizzard's manual offers a special warning to
gamers who play Diablo in ``hard core'' mode, in which they cannot
revive characters killed during the game. As a result, one mistake
in hard-core mode can end weeks or months of a player's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blizzard Entertainment is in no way responsible for your
hard-core character,'' the manual tells players. ``Blizzard will
not and does not have the capability to restore any deceased
hard-core characters. Don't even ask. La-la-la-la-la, we can't hear
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many games, Diablo allows players to interact with each
other over the Internet, another part of its appeal, players said.
At Blizzard's Battle.net Web site, Diablo players can interact or
compete at no cost, joining each other's quests or battling for
supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the assumptions that often gets made with computers is
that they alienate and isolate people,'' said Robert Nideffer, a
professor at the University of California at Irvine who specializes
in the study of art and computer science. ``In fact, players are
actively participating with other people in a very social space.''
</P>
<P>
   Nideffer is one of a small but growing group of academics,
including Coover of Brown, who argue that games are worthy of study
for what they tell about how people interact with computers and the
future of technology.
</P>
<P>
   The game market remains small compared with other media. About
170 million game cartridges and compact discs were sold last year,
compared with more than 1.5 billion general-interest books,
according to PC Data and the Book Industry Study Group.
</P>
<P>
   But while book sales are flat or declining and movie admissions
are barely rising, sales of games are surging. The number of games
bought for PCs tripled between 1993 and 1999, and for the first
five months of 2000, computer game sales are more than 10 percent
higher than last year, according to PC Data, a research firm in
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The growing game market has not escaped the attention of Warner
Brothers, which is working to develop a game based on the Harry
Potter series. At the same time, Blizzard is working with Pocket
Books to release a three-part series of books based on the Diablo
games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
