 For Release THURSDAY AMs, August 3, 2000  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-STRIKE (Johannesburg) _ Workers shut down factories,
stores and white-owned farms with a strike to protest a breakdown
of order in Zimbabwe, where months of political violence have left
dozens dead and the economy in a shambles. By Kurt Shillinger. 700
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GOP-WOMEN (Philadelphia) _ Across the floor of the Republican
National Convention, delegates wave posters and sport buttons that
say ``W is for Women.'' But those visual aids aren't really
necessary, because almost everything about the 2000 GOP gathering _
the women speakers, the videos filled with children, the
compassionate themes repeated again and again at the podium _ is
aimed at female voters. By Mary Leonard. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-ANALYSIS (Philadelphia) _ What doesn't work for the press
about the GOP show may be exactly what makes it effective outside
the hall. By David M. Shribman. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-MONEY (Philadelphia) _ The money is flowing at the GOP
convention, something that's OK with some people, but that's seen
as a perversion by others. By Glen Johnson. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-INSIDE (Philadelphia) _ The Texas delegation is trying, with
mixed success, to keep its outsized instincts in check. By Sam
Allis. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MA-GENETIC-PRIVACY (Boston) _ Lawmakers are expected to pass a
sweeping genetic privacy bill that would create strict prohibitions
against genetic discrimination in banking, housing, health
insurance and employment and give patients almost total control
over genetic test results. By Raja Mishra. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DUNKIN-TOGOS (Undated) _ Looking for explosive growth, the
British parent of Dunkin' Donuts plans to aggressively roll out
``combo'' stores that put a Dunkin' Donuts under the same roof with
Togo's sandwich shops and Baskin Robbins ice cream. By Chris Reidy.
1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
