<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENTINE'S VOTE GOES TO THE MAN HE KNOWS, NOT THE CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is not as if George W. Bush needs to convince Bobby Valentine
that he can manage the country. Valentine is a registered
Republican who last voted for the other ticket, for George
McGovern, in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   No, Valentine made it clear Wednesday in his Shea Stadium office
before the Mets concluded an 8-1 homestand by edging the Reds, 2-1,
that he is a W. man, all the way to November, the 1992 dismissal in
Texas notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were third, two games behind Oakland, which wound up
winning the division,'' Valentine said, his this-is-between-us
smile tempting you to read between the lines. ``But there were all
these higher expectations.`
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were 45-41 at the time, it was only July, but
Valentine was in his eighth year with a team that had never won its
division. His retrospective, seen from the high ground of a
better-paying job and another playoff race, is that ``they probably
needed to make a change, a little acceleration, even if it didn't
work.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Bush, who inherited Valentine when he became the
Rangers' managing partner in 1989, did not have some coach or
functionary stick his head into Valentine's office and suggest he
pack up, as another George with Republican party ties has been
known to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I always thought was different than what I expected was
that he worked within the structure,'' Valentine said of Bush. ``I
figured he would be the one to say, `OK, we have a five-game losing
streak, so we're going to wear a different color uniform today.' He
didn't. That is, he recognized that there were part-owners, a team
president, a general manager.''
</P>
<P>
   So Bush had Tom Grieve, the general manager and Valentine's good
friend, break the news, and then summoned Valentine into his
office, where the future governor said, ``If you have any
complaints, I want to hear 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said, ``When someone gives you a closed-end statement,
what are you going to say? I think what I did say was, `I
understand what you're doing, but I don't agree.' And after that,
what I always appreciated was that we spent a lot more time talking
about family, about more important things.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine never did learn if his firing was a Grieve idea that
Bush agreed with or a Bush idea that Grieve had no choice but to
agree with. He settled on its being a ``collective decision,''
which made him more comfortable when the hotel room telephone rang
in Pittsburgh last May at 7:30 a.m. and the candidate said, ``I've
got a meeting this morning but let's work out when I get back.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, it turned out, was in town to make peace with John McCain
after their bitter primary campaign. The governor and the manager
hit the weights, just as they used to in the Rangers' clubhouse
before the players would come in. They had lunch, Bush seemingly
more interested in the Mets than in McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, that was another thing that surprised Valentine about Bush.
He was never a sports-talk-radio caller disguised as an owner, not
the type to suggest they trade two utility infielders and his
presidential father's autograph for Don Mattingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He actually immersed himself in the game, in the organization,
from A ball on up,'' Valentine said. ``Sometimes it would be a
little scary. He would ask if we could use some guy on another
club's bench who really could have filled the need of a
curveball-hitting pinch-hitter. I'd look at Grieve and say, `Did
you tell him that?'
</P>
<P>
   ``What I really liked about him was that he didn't control
conversations. He'd show off his intelligence most with his wit. He
listened a lot but he had a wonderful presence. When he did say
something, it was like E.F. Hutton, and he was usually outside the
status quo. If I had a five-man rotation, he would say, `Have you
thought about going with a sixth starter in the hot weather?'
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times when we were losing, not drawing and some of
the investors were worried about the return on their dollar. I just
felt he always knew how to act, that he had good judgment. He knew
the difference between right and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Before starting a road swing that begins Friday night in Arizona
and ends next week in Houston, Bush country, the Mets have Thursday
off. Valentine will watch the convention acceptance speech. People
ask him all the time, he said, why they should vote for Bush, but
he doesn't want to come off as some cable network partisan. He
admits to knowing ``more about the man than I do about the
candidate.'' That will be enough for him in November, though: the
memories of a man who studied baseball, a conservative who canned
him with compassion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1909EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
