<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0894 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-GENETIC-PRIVACY-BO     08-02 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-GENETIC-PRIVACY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE TO GET STRICT GENETIC PRIVACY LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts lawmakers are expected to pass a sweeping
genetic privacy bill that would create strict prohibitions against
genetic discrimination in banking, housing, health insurance and
employment and give patients almost total control over genetic test
results.
</P>
<P>
   The bill had been languishing on Beacon Hill for much of the
year until legislators, apparently spurred by the July announcement
that scientists had deciphered much of the human genetic code,
engaged in furious negotiations over the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The House passed the measure, considered by many to be among the
strongest in the nation, on Monday night, and the Senate is
expected to pass it unanimously Thursday. Several agencies in Gov.
Paul Cellucci's adminstration have given the bill a positive review
but Cellucci was at the GOP Convention in Philadelphia Wednesday
and unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic testing may one day be able to predict diseases and even
aspects of personality, such as temper and intelligence. Already,
tests can identify people who have a higher chance of suffering
from certain cancers and a handful of other maladies. The
increasing prevelance of these tests have prompted worries that
they could be used to discriminate against people who might be seen
as costly medical risks, potentially disruptive or simply
undesirable for whatever reason.
</P>
<P>
   Its centerpiece is a broad prohibition against genetic
discrimination in obtaining loans, purchasing housing, purchasing
health insurance and applying for jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also require written consent from a patient
before the results of a genetic test could be given out to anyone
but attending physicians. This is considered the highest standard
of privacy protection.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is modeled after civil rights statutes that ban
discrimination on the basis of race, and indeed many of the bill's
most vocal backers were traditional civil rights groups who
consider the human genome a 21st century addition to their turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``The catalyst for this was quite frankly was the Human Genome
Project,'' said Senate Majority Leader Linda J. Melconian
(D-Springfield). ``It became pretty clear this was serious
business, that it was 21st century technology that needed consumer
protections.''
</P>
<P>
   The privacy legislation was jump-started after scientists in
Washington announced in July they had virtually completed
identifying the long string of molecules that directs the
development and functioning of the human body.
</P>
<P>
   Reseachers are now turning to the daunting task of sifting
through this genetic clutter for the individual genes that regulate
almost every aspect of human life. Hundreds of genes have been
identified already but there are estimated to be between 50,000 and
100,000 of them.
</P>
<P>
   As researchers identify more genes and discover how they work,
genetic testing will be able to tell doctors more and more about a
patient's life prospects.
</P>
<P>
   After the genome announcement, privacy advocates circulated a
letter urging action on the genetic privacy bill then sitting idly
in a House committee. They were worried the bill would be forgotten
in the hub-bub of the negotiations over a new Red Sox ballpark. To
their surprise, almost 100 legislators signed the letter and the
bill had new life.
</P>
<P>
   Life insurance companies, which use health testing to calculate
the risk of covering people, resisted the legislation, arguing that
the bill would deprive them of an important business tool.
</P>
<P>
   To an extent, their concerns were heeded: the bill does not, as
many privacy advocates wished, permit people to block life insurers
from accessing genetic test results. Instead it establishes a
commission to study the issue for two years and report back to
Beacon Hill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0896 &Cx1f; taf-z
s a BC-EDLIFE-RURAL-SCHOOLS(     08-02 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDLIFE-RURAL-SCHOOLS(3TAKES)$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADITION AND EXPERIMENTATION IN AMERICA'S ONE-ROOM SCHOOLHOUSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mont., Neb., Calif., P a .)  (For release Sunday, Aug. 6.) 
 By    JODI WILGOREN    c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLOOMFIELD, Mont. _ School doesn't start until the Mullets
arrive. Today, they are late, so we wait.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Whitmer, 6, is going round and round on the rickety
pentagon a local welder built out of $46 worth of pipes half a
century ago. Julia Lindquist, a seventh-grade loner, is sitting by
herself, contemplating the gaping sky and the wind pushing waves
through the grassy field. The boys are shooting hoops, as usual.
They let Monica Hostetler, 14, play, to even out the teams _ first
when there are only three of them, then again when there are five.
In between, she hangs at the other end of the makeshift court,
lobbing jumpers into the net.
</P>
<P>
   It's 10, 12, maybe 15 minutes past 8 a.m. when the forest-green
1998 Oldsmobile Regency pulls into the dirt driveway and the
Mullets tumble out: Marshall, the eighth-grader; Winston, a year
younger; Merrilee, who is 11; and Sterling, age 9. They live the
farthest from the white clapboard schoolhouse, 11 miles down gravel
roads across the empty plains, so their lateness might be
forgivable, except that it holds everybody else up.
</P>
<P>
   As the Mullets pull backpacks, musical instruments and lunch
boxes from the trunk, the boys on the blacktop hurry to land one
more basket. Linda Borntrager, the teacher, is standing on the
schoolhouse steps, one hand on the hip of her faded jeans, the
other clasping the old cowbell, ready to ring. It's time to raise
the flag, say the Pledge of Allegiance, start another day at
Bloomfield School.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're absent, we really have declined enrollment for the
day,'' Borntrager, 48, said about the Mullets, laughing. The family
accounts for four of her 13 students, and two more are Mullet
cousins. Children at Bloomfield ``just have to learn how to be
flexible,'' she added. ``That's a good skill in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloomfield School, which opened in 1908, is one of nearly 400
remaining public one-room schoolhouses in the nation, at once a
nostalgic remnant of the past and a modern outlet for educational
experimentation.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the number of tiny rural schools has plunged in recent
years, the fundamental aspects of teaching and learning inside them
_ including multi-age classrooms, peer tutoring, interdisciplinary
projects and keeping students with the same teacher for more than
one year _ are being copied in large school systems across the
country. Small classes and, especially, small schools are
increasingly seen as crucial to students' success in the early
grades, leading many urban educators to create islands within large
school buildings that attempt to foster the intimacy and individual
attention of schools like Bloomfield.
</P>
<P>
   And, with the Internet, long-held concerns about the narrow
curriculum available in an isolated one-teacher school are fading.
</P>
<P>
   ``One-room schools really represent, I think, the best model for
training American children for the first through the eighth
grades,'' said Andrew Gulliford, director of the Center for
Southwest Studies at Fort Lewis College in Durango, Colo., who is
the nation's leading expert on one-room schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of ego development, in terms of character, in terms
of personality, in terms of the well-rounded individual fitting in
with the group, country schools are very efficient _ they helped
train generations of Americans,'' added Gulliford, author of the
definitive book on the subject, ``America's Country Schools''
(University of Colorado Press). ``In a one-room schoolhouse, every
child counts _ they've always counted, whether it was 1890 or 1990.
How can you say that in most modern educational systems today? It's
just not true.''
</P>
<P>
   It is 10:50 a.m. on a Tuesday, a couple of hours after I've
arrived here amid the cattle ranches and wheat farms, and
Borntrager is deep into an eighth-grade math lesson on symmetry,
using a mirror and a book of drawings to show how even complex
shapes can sometimes be divided exactly in half.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny &UR;  &LR; Whitmer, meanwhile, is hunched over a first-grade reader.
Sterling Mullet, the third-grader, is copying contractions into his
notebook. Brady Boese, 12, and Matthew Kanagy, 14, are suffering
through a quiz on probability and percentages, while Brady's twin
brother, Kirk, is pondering a work sheet titled ``Remembering
Details,'' based on the novel ``Where the Red Fern Grows.''
</P>
<P>
   Julia Lindquist, a seventh-grader, has her nose stuck in ``The
Call of the Wild,'' legs outstretched, ankles crossed, and Winston
Mullet, 13, is methodically computing fractions and decimals.
Daniel Whitmer, six years older than Kenny, is tackling problems
from a math text, and Keith Hall, 13, is drawing conclusions _ at
least according to the paper on his desk _ from ``Red Fern.''
Clayton Unruh has his seventh-grade spelling workbook open to a
crossword puzzle. MerrileeMullet, the fifth-grader, is in the back
of the room, using the computer to type sentences she made up from
a list of new vocabulary words.
</P>
<P>
   It could be educational chaos, but all is quiet except for the
ceiling fans spinning overhead and the teacher's low-voiced prompts
to the two students at her half-moon table in the corner. Most of
the children have pencils moving, pages turning. Julia, Keith and
Daniel occasionally stare blankly out the large windows at the
endless brown earth. And every so often, one of the boys pops up
from his desk, carrying a book or a paper over to Mrs. B. with a
question.
</P>
<P>
   Eyes searching behind his wire-rim glasses, Brady wants to know
which number should be the numerator as he forms an algebraic
equation to answer the question: 18 is 30 percent of what number?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a quiz, Brady, so you're going to have to figure it out
on your own,'' the ruddy-cheeked teacher tells the tow-headed twin.
``One thing is to try both and then use your sense.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   By 11, it's time for a different math ``class'' _ Julia and
Keith, seventh-graders who lag behind, and Merrilee, a fifth-grader
a bit advanced for her age, stand at the chalkboard adding and
subtracting fractions. Four different reading groups have already
cycled through Mrs. B.'s station this morning. At 11:15, the
children race outside for calisthenics, led by Kenny, as much the
school's mascot as one of its students. They fold their legs into a
pretzel stretch, then run around the edge of the wheat field that
lies beyond the school's large yard in a haphazard training regimen
for the coming track meet with nearby one-room schools. Today, the
twins will have to wait until after lunch for math.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just do kind of a rotation,'' Borntrager said with a shrug.
``I think my goal is to try to make sure everybody's doing
constructive work almost all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Borntrager, who is paid $26,000 a year _ twice what she made
when she started at Bloomfield 17 years ago _ often has as many as
25 different lessons to prepare each day. During the 1999-2000
school year, her 13 students were in six grades, but she sometimes
subdivides the older students according to ability or interest.
``The Red Badge of Courage'' and ``The Call of the Wild'' are
novels of similar difficulty, for example, and Borntrager taught
them at the same time so the reading groups would have only three
or four students (and to appease animal lovers uninterested in gory
wars).
</P>
<P>
   At Bloomfield, students spend most of the day working by
themselves at their desks, old-fashioned wood-topped tables with
attached chairs arranged in rows. Borntrager relies heavily on
textbooks and work sheets she has collected over the years; she
rarely lectures to the group, instead running mini-classes in her
corner, most lasting no more than 10 minutes. A teacher's aide
often helps the younger boys with reading or art projects in a
separate corner, or stands by an individual student's desk,
administering a vocabulary test in the most nonthreatening way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids who come out of Bloomfield have real good study
stills,'' said Cindi Hostetler, Monica's mother, who teaches music
and serves as a part-time aide at the school, earning the minimum
wage. ``They know how to go back to their desks and go to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Borntrager does not assign homework, but students who fall
behind must finish their work after school. At the high school in
Richey, about 20 miles away, Bloomfield graduates often rise to the
top of their classes. Last spring, alumni of the school won the top
awards for freshmen, sophomores and juniors at the Eastern Montana
Math Meet.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, students from elementary schools with fewer than 40
students tend to outperform their peers on standardized tests in
every subject. During the 1997-98 school year, in the fourth and
eighth grades, more students from Montana's small schools were
rated ``advanced'' or ``proficient'' _ and fewer were ``novice'' or
``near proficiency'' _ than their counterparts in the subjects of
reading, math, language arts, science and social studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're showing there is small class-size ratio and
individual teacher contact with kids,'' said Lance Melton,
executive director of the Montana School Boards Association.
</P>
<P>
   One of the advantages parents and educators see in one-room
schools is the natural tailoring of the curriculum to children's
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody gets left through the cracks,'' said Mrs. Hostetler,
whose husband and two older children also graduated from
Bloomfield. ``If you're a smart kid, they take you where you can
go. If you're struggling, you get the individual attention.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what brought Keith Hall to Bloomfield last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in the Portland, Ore., suburbs, Keith bounced among
nine different schools, including one with 3,000 students. He was
learning very little, but getting into plenty of trouble. ``They
were just shoving him through,'' said Phyllis Mullet, his
grandmother and guardian.
</P>
<P>
   Keith spent the summer of 1999 on Mrs. Mullet's farm here,
hunting, fishing and tooling around on a four-wheeler. After
another year of fighting at home and at school, he returned to
Bloomfield School two weeks before school let out in May, raising
the school's enrollment by 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   He reads at about a third-grade level and misspells even basic
words like ``reason'' (reazer), ``other'' (outer) and ``touch''
(tuch). But Keith, one of two Bloomfield students who take Ritalin,
is a sweet boy who stays after school to help Mrs. B. move
furniture, a smart kid who is energized by tactile science projects
like identifying bone fragments from owl pellets and building
rockets out of soda bottles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other schools were junk,'' said Keith, whose dark-brown
buzz cut is a remnant of his city brashness. ``This one, it's
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``At my old school, it would take them half the year just to
know you. There was, like, 32 kids in my class, so it was kind of
hard to ask the teachers questions,'' he added. ``Here, they keep
track and stuff. They tell you, `Do you have this reading or this
done?' There, they never tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
