A0898 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-UGA-RECEIVERS0803     08-02 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-RECEIVERS0803 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After delays, 2 prized wide receiver recruits set to join
Bulldogs
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. - Georgia football coach Jim Donnan finally gets to
remove the shrink wrap from two of his most prized recruits this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Brown and Durrell Robinson both signed with the Bulldogs
in 1999, but had to sit out last season after they failed to
qualify academically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of those guys will really help our team,'' Donnan said.
``They're unproven, and they've still got to do it on the field,
but I think they'll give us a very talented receiver corps this
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a Parade All-American and the Journal-Constitution's
state player of the year in 1998, did not enroll at Georgia until
January. Brown was ruled ineligible after he failed to pass an
English class at Carrollton High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard, but I didn't dwell on it for too long,'' he said.
``It's over now, so I'm just trying to go on with my life.''
</P>
<P>
   After Brown enrolled, he wasn't allowed to practice this spring.
He took part in voluntary summer passing drills and gets his first
official workout on Friday with 13 other freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This summer has helped me a lot,'' Brown said. ``I wasn't able
to do much during the six months between high school and coming
here. My hands and passing routes were a little bit rusty.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 6 feet 2, 185 pounds, might be Georgia's fastest
receiver. He has been timed at 4.38 seconds in the 40-yard dash and
held the state long-jump record of 24-9, broken this year. Donnan
has called Brown a ``gazelle, a pure athlete who can fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, 6 feet 2, 207 pounds, isn't as fast as Brown (4.51
seconds in the 40), but Robinson has more upper-body strength and
experience. He was a partial qualifier last season and practiced
with the team, but under NCAA rules he wasn't allowed to play in
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating,'' Robinson said. ``I wanted to be out
there helping my teammates win games. But I think I still got
better as a player and person last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's receivers struggled last season. Without much speed at
receiver, defenses loaded the line to stop the running game.
Terrence Edwards, the first Georgia freshman since 1978 to lead the
team in receiving, often saw double-coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, the addition of a couple of speed guys on the
perimeter will help our big-play potential and also our running
game,'' Donnan said.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Quincy Carter says he's looking forward to finally
seeing his new receivers, which include redshirt freshmen Damien
Gary of Athens and Michael Johnson of Tulsa, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Durrell's going to have an advantage over Reggie because he's
been in full pads for almost a year,'' Carter said. ``He's gone
through two-a-days and spring practice. But I don't think it's
going to take Reggie long to catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: Will the Dawgs passing game fly this season?
www.accessatlanta.com/shared/
</P>
