<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0899 &Cx1f; taf-z
s a BC-EDLIFE-RURAL-SCHOOLS-     08-02 1862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDLIFE-RURAL-SCHOOLS-3RDTAKE-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BLOOMFIELD: tell you.' ' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1917, there were 196,000 one-teacher public schools in the
United States. At last count, in 1996, there were 380.
</P>
<P>
   Spread throughout 32 states, one-room schools are concentrated
in Nebraska, which has 128, and Montana, with 81. But while schools
throughout the rural Midwest and Mountain States have been
consolidating, California has seen a 22 percent growth in the
number of one-room schools in the last five years, fueled in part
by flexible work schedules and telecommuting policies that allow
families to pursue frontier living again. At the same time, Amish
and Mennonite communities, among others, have been opening private
one-room schools, which total nearly 1,200; about a third are in
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Among the public schools, average enrollment in 1996 was 9.4
students, according to a study by researchers at Brigham Young
University in Provo, Utah. The teachers typically had more than 10
years of experience, with three to five years in their present
classrooms, the study showed, and about a third of them lived in a
room or trailer attached to the school.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Dawson County, a 2,358-square-mile expanse of empty
plains and badlands that was once called the gateway to Montana,
there were 138 rural schools in 1919, according to a fading book
chronicling their history. A ledger kept by the county
superintendent shows that in 1955, the county had 47 teachers. That
dwindled to 32 over the next decade, then to 21 in 1969. When
Borntrager arrived at Bloomfield School in 1983, she was one of
nine teachers in the county; today there are three.
</P>
<P>
   The attrition is mostly about economics, as fewer and fewer
families find that they can survive farming the arid land. There
are now 53 stops on the 44-mile postal route around Bloomfield;
once, there were two routes, with 80 families each.
</P>
<P>
   But Bloomfield, a one-gas-station outpost 247 miles from the
Billings airport _ and 27 miles from the nearest McDonald's _ is
also losing students to home schooling, which is increasingly
popular among the area's religious Mennonites, and to the schools
in Richey, the nearest town, where students can play on basketball
and volleyball teams. In the fall, the Boese twins and Clayton
Unruh plan to enroll at Richey, leaving Borntrager with just eight
students. The next kindergartner on the horizon is Elizabeth
Nissley, who will not enroll until the fall of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably why I'll stop teaching,'' Borntrager said with
a sigh one afternoon during the eight-mile drive from school to her
modest house, a double-wide trailer with an addition her husband
built. ``We're going to run out of kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, Bloomfield School was packed with 40 students, and voters
approved a special tax to create a second classroom. Now the two
rooms are combined into a 35-by-60-foot space, filled not with
children but with an upright piano, project tables for art and
audio, and three computers, with a library of 4,000 worn paperbacks
around the perimeter. In the basement, there is enough open space
to hold gym class indoors.
</P>
<P>
   The first Bloomfield School burned in 1918. Another fire felled
the new one a decade later. The third and current building got
electricity in 1948 (after years of running a wire from a 32-volt
battery at the store down the road) and indoor plumbing in 1950,
although the outhouse, with separate wood-lidded toilets for boys
and girls, still stands out back.
</P>
<P>
   ``This, to me, doesn't look like a school,'' said Jeff Whitmer,
77, Kenny and Daniel's grandfather and the unofficial historian of
Bloomfield School, from which he graduated in 1936. ``This, to me,
is just like a big living room.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitmer built the merry-go-round in 1954 or 1955, after the
ladies of Bloomfield discovered that $46 would not buy them much
playground equipment. He rode on the giant stride, a kind of swing
made of a metal pole with link chains hanging off the top, when it
was built in the 1930s. Back then they rode horses to school, or
sleds in winter. It would take a while for the coal furnace to warm
up, so the water bucket in the hallway would be frozen solid each
morning. There were no janitors; the children cleaned the classroom
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our classroom had four rows of desks and a big bench at the
front for the teacher,'' Whitmer said. ``The teacher would holler
out, `Fourth-grade arithmetic!' and you'd march on down. You were
told to shut up about twice, and then you were hit upside the head,
or hit with a book.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's discipline is somewhat softer. Occasionally Borntrager
will look up from her corner and say, ``Quiet, please, guys,'' or,
``People, there's too much talking in here,'' but there are not a
lot of rules in her classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Borntrager, who was born in Hebron, N.D., rode a horse four
miles each way to Farmer's Valley, a one-room schoolhouse, through
fifth grade. After attending the state university in Fargo, N.D.,
she worked as a waitress, then for the telephone company in Denver
and in Arizona. After divorcing her first husband, she returned
home to get a degree in elementary education. When she fell in love
with a farmer-rancher from these parts, the teacher's desk at
Bloomfield was vacant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'd like teaching in a big classroom, with all
the other things that go with it,'' said Borntrager, whose three
children are among the 28 students who have graduated from the
school since she arrived. ``The teachers' lounge. The rigidity as
far as the classroom timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably like the kids in a sense,'' she added. ``I like
the ability to have that freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Living in a community where the drivers of every passing car
acknowledge each other with a half-wave, Borntrager is surrounded
by her successes _ and cannot walk away from students who are
struggling. Looking out at her classroom today, she can see the
kindergartners the seventh-grade boys used to be, remembers when
Clayton Unruh announced that he could not read ``Red Fern'' because
it was too long, and how it turned out to be his favorite book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to spend two weeks in the fall figuring out where
these kids are, and I can be, in the back of my mind, planning
during the summer,'' she said. ``We don't have to spend any time
getting to know each other in the fall. We can get right on to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny, his blond bangs almost hiding his ice-blue eyes, is
paired with Monica, whose metal-filled mouth and experiments with
eyeliner betray her entry into adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   ``What color do you want?'' the eighth-grader asks her protege
as they begin to plan their bottle rocket for the end-of-the-year
launch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can pick this time,'' Kenny says generously, then suggests
that each name a favorite color to combine in the decorations.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny picks yellow. Monica picks orange.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yellow and orange?'' Kenny squeals. ``Those are my favorite
colors!''
</P>
<P>
   Monica gets the construction paper. Kenny names the project the
Rocketeer. She draws the lines, he tries the scissors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to make it actually shoot up in the air,'' she
tells him confidently, then adds, ``I don't know exactly how.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny concentrates, chews a lip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't cut straight,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing I didn't draw straight, huh?'' she responds.
</P>
<P>
   ``How'd you know I couldn't cut straight?'' Kenny asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know,'' Monica says. ``That's good. That's what gives
it character.''
</P>
<P>
   The rocket project is a classic one-room schoolhouse lesson. For
Kenny, it is good practice with shapes. For Sterling, the
third-grader, it is real-life application of the concepts of
aerodynamics, thrust and liftoff in his science text. The older
students have researched the space shuttle on the Internet. There
will be practice with fractions as the students decide how much
water to put in the bottles. And, it's all about teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge of teaching at Bloomfield School is finding things
that are interesting to a boy of 6 and a girl of 14 _ and everyone
in between. There are few options for parts in the Christmas
pageant, which is a tradition here. But the peer tutoring, like
pairing Monica and Kenny, often creates the most magical moments of
learning. And while it can be lonely to be the only girl of a given
age, the small, multi-age setting limits peer pressure; children
have little choice but to get along.
</P>
<P>
   Before moving to Bloomfield, ``I got picked on a lot,'' said
Julia, whose skull was malformed at birth and has required several
surgeries, leaving a prominent scar on the top of her head.
</P>
<P>
   Julia, 13, draws beautiful pictures of horses and is writing her
11th book in a series about mining, but, ``for some reason, I kind
of get along better with younger kids,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like watching cartoons and playing with toys. Merrilee and
Sterling and Kenny and I can really have conversations,'' she
added. ``Probably when I get into high school, I'll stay by myself
a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   In gym, Cori Schultz, the teacher's aide, tries to separate
brothers and create games where the first-grader won't just get
mowed over by the eighth-graders. Instead of traditional kickball,
they put a garbage can at home plate, and kickers score points
according to what base they reach before the fielders land the ball
in the bucket (I had to play to even out the teams, and triumphed
with a home run).
</P>
<P>
   After two days of designing and building the bottle rockets,
with their ever more elaborate noses and fins, it was time for the
launch. We placed the homemade launcher around second base, and
lined up. The eldest Mullet sat atop the swing set with a video
camera, Matthew Kanagy stood ready to release the bottles, and
Keith primed the pump. The rest of the students scattered to see
which rocket would fly highest and farthest, which would twirl and
spin, and which would fall flat.
</P>
<P>
   Keith's masterpiece, its two-foot cardboard cylinder festooned
with a picture of President Clinton, floundered; too heavy. The
Mountain Dewzy, by Winston and Matthew, performed a spectacular
loop-the-loop before sputtering out. Monica and Kenny's Rocketeer
looked pretty but had an unremarkable ride. The cleanest, strongest
rocket was the unlikely, simple design by Julia and Sterling, who
filled their bottle half full and used the maximum amount of air.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel's was the biggest disappointment. Its small orange wings
and white cone head could not stand up to the stiff wind. He
planned to fill the bottle five-eighths full of water, but some
spilled out. And Daniel only used four pumps _ in retrospect,
clearly not enough.
</P>
<P>
   He moped around the field alone awhile, ignoring the other
rockets as they flew overhead. If only he could try again. He would
use maximum air, less water. Design a stiff cardboard cone to cut
through the wind. Waste less time on the useless paper fins. And,
definitely, not go first, before the kinks are worked out of the
launching system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you say we're doing this again next year?'' Daniel asked
the teacher, hopefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to do it next year?'' Borntrager replied. Well, why
not?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
