<HEADER>
A0900 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-WILDFLOWER-JOHNSON-HN     08-02 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILDFLOWER-JOHNSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES AGAINST LADY BIRD JOHNSON WILDFLOWER CENTER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BILL MURPHY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Harris County probate judge ruled Wednesday that the
Lady Bird Johnson Wildflower Center cannot collect a $500,000
pledge made by late Houston socialite Faith Bybee.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Rory Olsen granted summary judgment in favor of the
executor of Bybee's estate, Chase Bank of Texas, which has refused
to honor the pledge.
</P>
<P>
   The center, located in Austin, sued Chase, saying Bybee's pledge
in 1990, when she was 90, created a contract that the estate should
be required to honor. Chase Bank's position was that this pledge,
like many other pledges to charities, didn't create a contract and,
moreover, that Bybee notified the center she didn't have the money
to honor it long before she died.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gratifying decision because the lawsuit was one that
never should have been brought,'' said Chase's lawyer, Bill Ogden.
``Part of what makes the case so sad is that most charitable
organizations have more civility than that, more compassion than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Mayfield, lawyer for the center, said, ``It's unfortunate
that Mr. Ogden wants to try this case in the media. It was Chase
Bank that acted inappropriately in denying a valid claim'' by the
center.
</P>
<P>
   Bybee, Mayfield said, ``had every intention of honoring her
pledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Olsen didn't provide a written explanation of his ruling. He had
asked lawyers on both sides for additional briefs addressing issues
related to statute of limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Ogden argued the center had four years from the time Bybee made
the pledge, or until 1994, to bring a breach-of-contract suit.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield argued the center filed the suit within the four-year
time frame because he said the statute of limitations didn't begin
ticking until Bybee died in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The suit pitted the center started by Johnson against the estate
of her friend. The center, named in honor of the former first lady,
works to preserve native flowering plants on public lands.
</P>
<P>
   Once it became clear the center was gearing up for a suit, a
nephew of Bybee wrote to Johnson and tried to explain matters to
her, Ogden said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson wrote back that she didn't want `` `to pursue the matter
of Faith's pledge to the center in any manner that will cause
public embarrassment to anyone or tarnish the reputation of Mrs.
Bybee. I personally want to see this resolved quickly and without
anyone going to court,' '' according to Ogden's pleadings.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield said, ``Mr. Ogden is quite fond of quoting that letter
out of context.'' The lawyer said that when the letter is read in
its entirety, Johnson makes clear she and the center's board
members have a responsibility to seek money the center believes it
is owed.
</P>
<P>
   Ogden said the Houston Museum of Fine Arts and McNay Museum in
San Antonio didn't sue the estate for pledges made by Bybee.
</P>
<P>
   Bybee's ``reach clearly exceeded her grasp at times,'' Ogden
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement released before Olsen made his ruling,
center director Robert Breunig said, ``The Wildflower Center has
attempted to resolve this matter without resorting to the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Bybee died with an estate worth $997,000.
</P>
<P>
   But Ogden says that on paper, Bybee may have appeared to have
$997,000, but she was actually in debt. When her late husband died
before her, he set up his estate in such a way that his wife could
draw money from it, Ogden said. This arrangement was done to
achieve tax savings.
</P>
<P>
   But what it meant is that she owed his estate $1.5 million when
she died, Ogden says. Chase has said it will pay this debt, and the
$1.5 million in her husband's estate would then go to the Bybee
Foundation, slated by both his and his wife's wills to be their
primary beneficiaries, Ogden said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bybee Foundation is dedicated to the preservation of Texas
pioneer arts and history. Faith Bybee was an authority on Texas
history and antiques.
</P>
<P>
   The center has argued Chase was wrong to give everything to the
foundation when it could have honored all or part of Bybee's pledge
to it.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield said he is unsure whether the center will appeal. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
