<HEADER>
A0901 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-GOP-FORD-BOS &LR;      08-02 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-FORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD RECOVERING FROM TWO MINOR STROKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA AND JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Former President Gerald Ford was comfortably
recuperating in a hospital after apparently suffering two minor
strokes, casting a slight pall over what has been an otherwise
cheery Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   His primary caretaker, Dr. Robert Schwartzman, chief of
neurology at Hahnemann University Hospital, said Wednesday that the
87-year-old Ford was ``much better than he was this morning,'' and
``should totally recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford's speech remains slurred and his balance off-kilter, but
his doctors said they expect him to eventually recover all of his
physical abilites. He has no brain damage, and his cognitive
abilites are unimpaired, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford will remain hospitalized for five to six days, while tests
are run to determine the extent and precise location of the
blockage of blood flow to his brain, his doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ford appears to be stable, stroke specialists said the
next two days are critical, and the aging ex-president cannot be
definitively pronounced out of the woods without several successive
days of improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's doctors said his minor brain-stem strokes were likely the
product of atherosclerosis, the buildup of fatty deposits blood
vessels, typically caused by high blood pressure, smoking, high
cholesterol or diabetes. But otherwise, his prognosis was good.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's saying that he feels great and would like to get home.''
Dr. Carol Thomas of Hahnemann University Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   News of Ford's malady generated quick bipartisan expressions of
sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president spoke with Mrs. Ford to express his concern and
best wishes for a speedy recovery,'' said President Clinton's
spokesman Elliot Diringer.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Ford, the 38th president, sat with his wife,
Betty, with George and Barbara Bush, and with Nancy Reagan as
Republican convention-goers paid tribute to the three living GOP
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Bush said in a statement: ``It was a joy to sit next
to him at the convention (Tuesday night). ... Once again, we were
reminded of his dececncy and all that he did at a crucial time in
our nation's history.''
</P>
<P>
   After a triumphant arrival in Philadelphia Wednesday, George W.
Bush also called Mrs. Ford to convey his concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was saddened to hear that President Gerald Ford was admitted
to the hospital after the glowing tribute he received (Tuesday
night),'' the GOP presidential nominee said in a statement.
``Americans love Gerald and Betty Ford for their integrity, wisdom
and compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford's condition was intially misdiagnosed as a sinus infection.
He checked into Hahnemann University Hospital's emergency room
Wednesday at 1 a.m. complaining of pain in his tongue, and sought
only pain relief, said doctors.
</P>
<P>
   His personal doctor had been following his condition and
reported the symptoms to the hospital. They diagnosed it as an
acute sinus infection, gave him pain killers and released him.
</P>
<P>
   Later that morning, journalists and friends noticed his slurred
speech and often puzzling responses to questions. On C-SPAN he
answered a question about Iraq by holding forth on onions.
</P>
<P>
   At 9 a.m., Ford walked back into the hospital under his own
power. Mrs. Betty Ford told doctors she had noticed his slurred
speech for several days, and they quickly concluded the
ex-president had suffered a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Hahnemann officals said their treatment
during Ford's first visit to the hospital was appropriate. They
said the did not conduct tests for a stroke at that time because of
incomplete information from Ford and his personal physician.
</P>
<P>
   Some stroke specialists said the activity Ford engaged in before
his stroke treatment _ interviews before jostling cameras and hot
lights _ may slightly hamper his recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is being treated with drugs that help unclog arteries.
Doctors said the crucial task now is to identify the exact nature
of his stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incumbent on the doctors to settle the issue of what
caused the stroke in order to prevent a more serious stroke,'' said
Dr. Philip J. Kistler, director of stroke service at Massachusetts
General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Ford took office in 1974, after Richard M. Nixon resigned as
president to avoid being impeached for Watergate. Ford pardoned
Nixon, a controversial decision that clouded his tenure. In 1976,
he lost the presidency to Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Zuckman reported from Philadelphia and Mishra from Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
