<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0906 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-GOP-MONEY-BOS &LR;      08-02 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-MONEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVENTION CRESTS ATOP A WAVE OF DONATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GLEN JOHNSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Robin Cook wended his way through the floor of
the Republican National Convention with all the appropriate
credentials hanging around his neck. But the only one he truly
needed was pinned to the lapel of his crisp blue blazer.
</P>
<P>
   Against a black field was a gold elephant and the words:
``Republican Regents.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, that nametag confers singular status as the most
elite of party donors, the 139 people and corporations who have
contributed $250,000 or more to Republican causes since January
1999. It carries with it an all-access pass to the best hotels,
meals and parties around Philadelphia, a city bustling with lavish
spreads and entertainment ranging from The Temptations to Hank
Williams Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The critics bray, but Cook, a Boston novelist with a specialty
for medical thrillers, defends his sort of big-ticket giving. He
says he's not buying access, but supporting good leadership in the
form of Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quite impressed with the whole Bush clan, and I'd like to
see that kind of integrity in the White House, so I don't have to
be embarrassed when I go over and meet with my friends in Europe,''
he said shortly after the convention was gaveled to order.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Makinson, head of the Center for Responsive Politics, a
Washington campaign finance watchdog, thinks the money both in
Philadelphia and the Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles
in two weeks perverts the political process.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can put together a $400,000 bash with shrimp and
caviar, you have an advantage over everyone not doing it. When
those groups come back to Washington to really undertake the
business of government, they know they are not just walking into
the door as any other person,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Republican and Democrats expect to spend over $100
million presenting their presidential and vice presidential
nominees. With the US Treasury and local governments providing only
about $28 million to each party, a hefty share of the rest will
come from corporate sponsorships and private donors.
</P>
<P>
   Individual donations to presidential candidates are capped at
$1,000 for the primaries and $1,000 for the general election, but
``soft-money'' donations to political parties remain unregulated
despite attempts by campaign finance reformers such as Senators
John McCain of Arizona and Russell Feingold of Wisconsin, and
Representatives Martin T. Meehan of Massachusetts and Christopher
Shays of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations were briefly banned from helping defray convention
expenses, but in 1984, federal regulators changed the rules so
companies could make unlimited donations to host committees, the
civic groups that arrange much of the convention-week activities.
The donations were also made tax deductible, to be treated as a
marketing expense.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the money flow is the presence of top lawmakers,
government decisionmakers and corporate interests at conventions.
Their attendance provides the opportunity to both thank past donors
and cultivate new ones, as has happened in Philadelphia this week.
</P>
<P>
   The National Republican Congressional Committee raised $1.75
million and rewarded its donors with 345 hotel rooms in prime
locations. The contributors also received passes for a hospitality
suite, a golf tournament and a concert by Earth, Wind &AMP; Fire.
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific Railroad laid a half-mile of railroad track
outside the First Union Center and placed 30 vintage railroad cars
right next to the convention hall for parties. It lent a Pullman
car to House Minority Whip Tom DeLay of Texas, who is using it as a
hospitality suite for his ``Gold Plus'' contributors, those who
have donated $50,000 to his political action committee. Besides the
donors, the only ones allowed admittance are members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert was both the host and honoree
Tuesday at a luncheon in the Pennsylvania Convention Center. He
invited 1,000 people who have supported his political action
committee, ``Keep Our Majority.''
</P>
<P>
   The event was sponsored by Akin, Gump, a top Washington law and
lobbying firm, as well as the National Beer Wholesalers and
Retailers and the United Distillers and Vintners. The guest of
honor was Dick Cheney, the GOP vice presidential pick, and the
emcee was former Representative William Paxon of New York, now a
member of Akin, Gump.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, there was also a fund-raising luncheon featuring the
party's presidential choice, Texas Governor George W. Bush, that
was expected to raise up to $10 million. And earlier this week,
there were dueling corporate-sponsored parties for Represenatives
W.J. ``Billy'' Tauzin of Lousiana and Michael G. Oxley of Ohio, who
are battling to become the next chairman of the House Commerce
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conventions are about politics, getting the message out, but
they're also a celebration of a lot of hard work and grassroots and
party leaders who get together every four years to tell war stories
_ and spend the week going to good parties,'' said Ronald Kaufman,
a Bush confidant and Massachusetts national committeeman.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had received ``hundreds'' of invitations.
</P>
<P>
   Similar attention is paid to Cook and his fellow Regents. They
sit atop a caste system that includes Team 100, the $100,000
donors, the Presidential Trust, whose members have donated $20,000,
and the Eagles, people who have given $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Team 100 members had more than two dozen perks and events to
choose from this week, according to The Associated Press, which
obtained letters mailed to the donors.
</P>
<P>
   They had dinner their first night with Hastert, Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott and other congressional leaders at the
Philadelphia Museum of Art, the AP reported. The next day, it was
breakfast at City Hall with strategists from the Bush campaign,
followed by a fashion show at the Academy of Music and a cocktail
reception with GOP members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday they enjoyed a round of country-club golf with
senators, congressmen, governors and former Cabinet members.
Thursday there's brunch with Bush's father, former President Bush.
President Ford had been scheduled to attend before he was
hospitalized Wednesday after suffering two mild strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Even though their $15,000 donations place them at the bottom of
the pecking order, the Eagles are treated like royalty, as well.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday they had lunch at Ardosson, Robert Montgomery Scott's
famed Villanova home, enjoyed reserved motorcoaches to and from the
convention hall and had a special late-night concert featuring
Lynard Skynard. All week the Eagles are free to drop by a
hospitality suite at their hotel, the Park Hyatt in Center City.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman, the Massachusetts committeeman, dismisses those who say
the cash flow erodes democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party can foot the bill for the convention itself, but
every four years, every major business or political leader comes
together in one of two places,'' he said. ``If you're Chrysler
trying to sell automobiles or Voter.com trying to reach a political
audience, what place is there better to go?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0907 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-COYOTE-UGLY-REVIEW-LA     08-02 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COYOTE-UGLY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIT BY THE UGLY SHTICK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 1 star 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A ``coyote ugly'' person is one who is so physically ghastly
that, upon waking up hungover with him or her asleep on your arm,
you would gladly gnaw that appendage off _ like a coyote caught in
a trap _ to escape rather than awaken or have to speak to that
monstrosity ever again. Similarly, ``Coyote Ugly'' the movie is so
narratively ghastly that, were you handcuffed to your seat, you
would cheerfully bid your arm adieu and chew your way to freedom to
avoid allowing any more idiocy to seep into your central nervous
system.
</P>
<P>
   Piper Perabo stars as Violet, an innocent, small-town Jersey
girl with dreams of making it big in New York Ci... see, I can
tell, I've lost you already. Through the usual series of
contrivances, she ends up working as an uber-attitudinal
bartender/dancer at Coyote Ugly, which is sort of a Chuck E. Cheese
for misogynists (women do patronize the place, however, but only
when called for by the, um, plot).
</P>
<P>
   The other women at the bar are defined by the one character
trait Gina Wendkos' script allows them: Lil (Maria Bello), the
tough boss with a heart of _ well, !ital!something; Rachel (Bridget
Moynahan), the grouchy one; Cammie (Izabella Miko), the shopaholic
(yes, there's a trying-on-clothes montage); and Zoe (Tyra Banks),
the law student _ anyone who saw Banks' pre-Oscar ceremony
performance would know to fear for the legal profession. Director
David McNally shoots their bartop dancing two ways: above the
waist, so you can see the actresses, and below the waist, so you
can see their stand-ins' precision hoofing.
</P>
<P>
   To prove she can write pointless scenes for both genders,
Wendkos also gives Violet a boyfriend (Adam Garcia) and a
disapproving dad (John Goodman, playing another variation on his
patented fat-guy-who-can't- say-no-to-junk-food character _ no
offense, John, but maybe Hollywood's trying to tell you something).
</P>
<P>
   It's Perabo's movie and she knows it, all too well; her perky,
quirky performance is far too exhaustingly calculated to charm. Her
unrelenting emoting, particularly during the scenes designated in
the script as ``sad,'' makes this the first movie that could've
used an eyebrow wrangler. Similarly annoying in ``The Adventures of
Rocky and Bullwinkle,'' Perabo was but a cameo in ``Battlefield
Earth'' from winning the summer's Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coyote Ugly'' is, at its heart, an R-rated movie aimed at frat
boys shoehorned into an ungainly PG-13 body _ which means,
essentially, it has none of the gratuitous nudity that movies of
this ilk are generally expected to have. Which, obviously, wouldn't
make the movie any better, but it would at least give its target
audience a reason to sit through it.
</P>
<P>
   So you can look at the movie one of two ways: that the movie
becomes high-minded in its refusal to commit to its sleazy
sensibility, or that since it's still clearly cashing in on said
sleazy sensibility, its inability to follow through simply
underscores the filmmakers' cynicism and gutlessness. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``Coyote Ugly'' (PG-13; language, sexual situations). &QL; 
The stars: Piper Perabo, Adam Garcia, Maria Bello, Bridget
Moynahan, Izabella Miko, Tyra Banks. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by David McNally. Written by Gina
Wendkos. Produced by Jerry Bruckheimer. Released by Touchstone
Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 45 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
