<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0909 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-HOLLOWMAN-FEATURE-LAD     08-02 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWMAN-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT SEEING IS BELIEVING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SANDRA BARRERA 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before it could be seen, ``Hollow Man'' needed some fleshing
out.
</P>
<P>
   It took 11 years to get the right script and develop the
computer technology that put the guts and bones on this project.
What gave it life was a director who could combine the elements
without sacrificing technology or softening the demonic central
character.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Verhoeven relishes that sort of challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch filmmaker, whose last project was the 1997 film
``Starship Troopers'' and who is currently in talks to do the
sequel to his sexually charged ``Basic Instinct'' (even though he
doesn't normally do sequels), is admittedly drawn to projects that
explore the dark side of human nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollow Man'' is a suspense-thriller about a cocky young
scientist who injects himself with an invisibility serum being
commissioned for top- secret study by the government. The bad news
is the serum is irreversible. That leaves the now-invisible
scientist with only one choice _ to become a monster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story was really about a man deteriorating because of the
power of invisibility,'' says Verhoeven.
</P>
<P>
   The film, opening citywide today, parallels the centuries-old
writings of Plato, who said that a man who becomes invisible will
steal, rape, kill and anoint himself god among men, much as
Sebastian does when he becomes the Hollow Man.
</P>
<P>
   Movies have always had a fascination with invisibility on the
screen, as exemplified by the 1933 film ``The Invisible Man,''
which was considered a special-effects wonder in its day.
</P>
<P>
   Verhoeven admits the idea of a murderous invisible man appealed
to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably why I took the script,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Hooking Verhoeven was the easy part, says producer Douglas Wick.
It was the long process of bringing the project to the screen that
was difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollow Man'' was Wick's baby. No stranger to revolutionary
effects _ he is credited with producing such visual extravaganzas
as ``Stuart Little'' and ``Gladiator'' _ Wick knew computer
technology could provide a new perspective to the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every movie has its stumble factor. When you get to an
invisible man, the bad version of invisibility is really silly.
Remember `Memoirs of an Invisible Man'?'' Wick says, referring to
the 1993 film starring Chevy Chase and Daryl Hannah.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest thing about this is to make the audience believe
the experience all the way through.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollow Man'' stars Kevin Bacon as Sebastian Caine, the dynamic
and powerful government scientist who secretly uses the serum on
himself. When his colleagues Linda McKay (Elisabeth Shue) and
Matthew Kensington (Josh Brolin) try to turn him in, all hell
breaks loose.
</P>
<P>
   All this happens under the anonymity of his invisibility, thanks
to the new software developed under the watchful eye of visual
effects supervisor Scott Anderson and his team at Sony Pictures
Imageworks.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who has worked on special-effects giants like ``Babe''
and Verhoeven's ``Starship Troopers,'' admits all his other
projects are dwarfed by what was done in ``Hollow Man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think everyone understands how hard it was to do, and
it's really not their job to understand it,'' says Anderson. ``They
just have to enjoy the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Scanning every inch of Bacon's body allowed the visual artists
to show his transformation from flesh to muscle to skeleton to
invisible man and almost back again.
</P>
<P>
   Only Sebastian's outline is visible in water or smoke scenes.
But in reality, Bacon was in almost every scene of the movie
wearing different-colored body suits specific to the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all me,'' Bacon says. ``Whenever I'm there, you hear the
voice, you see the CGI (computer graphics imaging), you see the
water man, you see the smoke man, you see the rain man, you see the
electrodes, you see the sheath. I was there for every single
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The only scene that required a greater imagination was, perhaps,
during a mad gorilla scene in the early part of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Verhoeven _ who went so far as to remove his
trousers for the coed shower scene during the filming of ``Starship
Troopers'' as an act of camaraderie with his actors _ is a great
motivator.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're trying to look at the gorilla or you're trying to
imagine what it is,'' says Bacon, ``all of a sudden he's screaming
and jumping around the set like a gorilla. He has a mercurial kind
of personality. It explodes at any minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon describes Verhoeven as director who has a
single-mindedness when it comes to getting a job done. He is also
compassionate. He shut down production for six weeks to allow Shue,
who had torn her Achilles tendon doing gymnastics off the set, to
heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a director is a consumptive kind of job, and it requires
an amazing amount of focus, which he has,`` Bacon says. ``The guy
is tireless. I never saw him slow down or get distracted or just
not really have a day where he wasn't just insanely committed to
getting this thing done.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
