<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0916 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-INDIA-KIDNAP-ART-2TAK     08-02 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-KIDNAP-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA MOVIE GOD FORCED INTO ROLE OF HOSTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGALORE, India _ The legendary outlaw Veerappan, a lean man
with a twirling, jet black mustache, has ranged through the vast
jungles of South India for a generation, slaughtering elephants for
their ivory tusks, smuggling out perfumed sandalwood and playing
Robin Hood to the forest dwellers, the authorities say.
</P>
<P>
   For the past decade, hundreds of policemen have been dedicated
to nothing but hunting him down. He is wanted for killing dozens of
them, as well as strangling his newborn daughter to silence her
telltale cries.
</P>
<P>
   He has eluded capture, but life on the run has taken a heavy
toll. He is in his 50s now, an aging brigand with asthma and a bad
stomach who has made no secret of his desire to come in from the
cold and live a normal life.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday he put into action what the police are calling his
boldest, most diabolical plan yet to win a pardon for his crimes.
He abducted Rajkumar, a beloved movie star whose half-century-long
career portraying Hindu gods, kings of yore and heroes of every
kind has endowed him with a mythical stature of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Veerappan, who like many South Indians, including his captive,
goes by only one name, took Rajkumar to his jungle lair and has
kept silent about what he wants, letting the drama build. But the
police expect his demand to be simple: his freedom for Rajkumar's
life.
</P>
<P>
   A notorious gangster kidnapping a matinee idol would transfix
the public of any nation, but perhaps only in India would it
provoke mobs of fans to stone passing cars, blockade major roads
with flaming tires, press shopkeepers to pull down their shutters,
and bring life in a bustling metropolis to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   That is just what happened on Monday and Tuesday here in
Bangalore, the heart of India's booming information technology
industry and one of Asia's fastest-growing cities. Most people went
back to work Wednesday, but schools remained closed, a ban on
public gatherings stayed in place, traffic was light and anxiety
remained palpable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bangalore is a cosmopolitan town, like Bombay,'' said U.R.
Ananthamurthy, a novelist and poet writing in Kannada, the native
tongue of most people in the state of Karnataka and the language
spoken by Rajkumar in his more than 200 films. ``It belongs to the
modern world system and thinks it can ignore mass psychology. But
it forgets that other reality that lurks within.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in South India, movie stars and their millions of fans can
be compared to religious deities and their devotees. Rajkumar, 72,
who came from a low-caste family and became a symbol of regional
pride, has inspired a huge and committed following.
</P>
<P>
   In Bangalore alone he has hundreds of fan clubs organized down
to the neighborhood level, like a political machine. But unlike
N.T. Rama Rao of Andhra Pradesh or M.G. Ramachandran of Tamil Nadu,
film stars, now dead, who became the chief ministers of their
states, Rajkumar has stayed out of politics _ and is all the more
trusted by his fans because of it.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands have flocked to his home weeping and chanting slogans
for his release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worship Rajkumar as a god,'' said Nagaraj, a somber
22-year-old who pumps gas for a living. He wasn't being purely
metaphorical.
</P>
<P>
   South Indian movie stars who choose to play virtuous heroes and
mythological figures from the great Hindu epics are identified in
the minds of their audiences with those values, said Sara Dickey,
an anthropologist and author of ``Cinema and the Urban Poor in
South India'' (Cambridge University Press, 1993).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier in India for humans to become deities than in some
other cultures,'' Dickey said, ``certainly more than in the Western
Judeo-Christian traditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The drama is so like the plot of one of Rajkumar's films, and
the pairing of these two larger-than-life characters so perfect _
Rajkumar in his familiar role as the gentle hero and Veerappan as
the swashbuckling villain _ that the line between life and art
seems almost to have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Both men have gained maximum visibility in their respective
dominions. And for the police officers who have spent years chasing
Veerappan, the knowledge that he has Rajkumar is chilling.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a cunning, ruthless criminal,'' said Maj. Gen. Shankar M.
Bidari, an inspector general in the Karnataka state police who
spent more than three years in the mid-1990s commanding 200 men in
pursuit of Veerappan. ``He wants to escape the clutches of the law,
and he will sacrifice anybody. He's tired. He's desperate. And he
knows there's no way out for him.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Veerappan has survived on his wits all these years in forests so
dense that the only way through them is on paths trod by elephants.
At the peak of his power in the 1980s he employed thousands of
people in his sandalwood lumbering empire and more than 100 armed
gangsters to keep everyone in line, Bidari said.
</P>
<P>
   Veerappan and his henchmen knew the ways of the jungle and
mimicked the calls of birds and deer in a system of warning signals
that helped them dodge the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The people who lived on the fringes of the forest often
protected Veerappan because he was their patron. He gave them jobs,
helped the poorest among them to pay for their daughters' weddings,
built temples, and kept meddlesome bureaucrats away with
well-placed bribes, the police say.
</P>
<P>
   But his murderous tendencies became more pronounced as the years
went by, and in 1990 the states of Tamil Nadu and Karnataka set up
teams of officers to pursue the Veerappan gang into the jungles
that span their border.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, Veerappan stands charged with 141 murders but
is still at large _ a fact that goads his pursuers. Still, he has
been forced into a nomadic life that has worn him down, and cost
him most of his men, the police say. Dozens have been killed in
encounters with the police, and more than 100 have been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Under interrogation, some have described their gang leader's
life as one of unceasing movement, with never more than a night of
sleep in any one camp. When it rains, he has only plastic sheeting
over his head. He eats dal and rice, buried at different spots in
the jungle, and wild boar and birds hunted in the jungle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to walk briskly in the forest,'' said C. Dinakar,
director general of the Karnataka state police, adding with
satisfaction: ``Now we have received information that he's slowed
down. He has breathing problems and diseases of the colon from
cooking in dirty water.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
