<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0917 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-PROTESTS-0803-COX     08-02 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-PROTESTS-0803-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLICE, PROTESTERS FACE OFF AGAIN IN SWEATY, EDGY PHILADELPHIA
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Police and protesters faced off at tense
demonstrations all across this sweaty, edgy city Wednesday but
avoided the violent clashes and snarled streets of the previous
day.
</P>
<P>
   Watched by legions of police, roaming bands of dissidents waved
placards and shouted slogans from morning to night but mostly
remained peaceful. The protests were miles from the heavily secured
sports arena where the Republican National Convention is being
held, but several occurred on sidewalks outside of hotels where
delegates are staying.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators opposed to the death penalty chanted ``You say
death row. We say hell no'' near the entrance to an arena where
Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush attended a noon
fund-raiser. Protesters against international corporations and the
World Bank blocked a sidewalk near City Hall. Hundreds of
demonstrators for dozens of causes pounded makeshift drums, danced,
chanted and waved signs in Franklin Park, near Chinatown, while
squads of police stood across the street with buses ready to haul
lawbreakers to jail.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, at least 350 people were arrested and detained,
police said. Police Commissioner John Timoney was one of 15
officers slightly injured in clashes with protesters. The jailed
activists were not expected to be released until after the
convention ends Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are folks we know. They came in on buses hell-bent on
causing disruptions,'' Timoney told the Associated Press. ``The
vast majority are not cooperating with police by not giving their
names. We have lots of Jane and John Does.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the protesters are members of a confederation of
anarchists called the ``Revolutionary Anti-Capitalists;'' the group
also calls itself the ``Black Bloc.'' They organize over the
Internet and communicate by cell phones on the street. Clad in
black or cut-off camouflage fatigues and sometimes wearing ski
masks or bandanas over their faces, they adopt fanciful nicknames
and distrust reporters as much as they do police.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to talk about the Black Bloc,'' said ``Ferret,''
who wore a T-shirt saying ``Anarchist Soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were playing some yesterday,'' he said of the fights with
police. He said he was a veteran of the anti-globalist protests in
Seattle and Washington, D.C., and presented a rumpled piece of
paper about why he came here for the Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Direct democracy starts here, in the streets of
Philadelphia,'' it said. ``No matter who they elect, we are still
ungovernable.''
</P>
<P>
   The activists have aroused anger rather than sympathy in the
Philly populace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Philadelphia. Protest was born here,'' said Willie
Jones, a security officer at the Municipal Building. ``But this is
not normal protest. This is violence. They have the right to free
speech but they don't have the right to come here to tear up our
town and endanger people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Law-abiding citizens are being intimidated,'' said Jones,
standing beside a newly cleaned statue of former Mayor Frank Rizzo
that had been painted by protesters.
</P>
<P>
   The police _ widely criticized for beating and kicking a
carjacking suspect earlier this summer _ are now being widely
praised for restraint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually you only hear about the bad cops, not the ones just
doing their jobs _ standing there and taking abuse from these
people,'' said Brian McIntosh, manager of Cosi Sandwich Bar in
Center City. ``Nobody knows what they're protesting about. I don't
think they even know.''
</P>
<P>
   While the conventioneers are spending freely in restaurants and
hotels, other businesses are suffering because of the disruptions.
Police on Wednesday had blocked the sidewalk on both sides of
Mickey Padel's news stand at the corner of 17th and Market Streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can get here and this is usually my busy time,'' he
lamented at mid-morning. ``But I'm scared, too. Did you see what
happened yesterday?''
</P>
<P>
   The protest scenes contrast starkly to the GOP convention seen
on television. While the air-conditioned First Union Center is full
of mostly middle-aged men and women in business suits and silly
political gear, the sweltering street protests often feature young
tattooed, body-pierced activists in black cut-offs and T-shirts
with the sleeves ripped off. Working 12-hour shifts, the police are
hot and tired but struggling to maintain good humor.
</P>
<P>
   Pedaling from protest to protest in sweat-stained uniforms, a
bicycle patrol co-opted a favorite protest chant: ``What do we
want? Soap. When do we want it? Now,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   For online information: www.unity2000.com
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
