<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0918 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-INDIA-KIDNAP-2NDTAKE-     08-02 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-KIDNAP-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 BANGALORE, India: dirty water.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since 1994, Veerappan has made several attempts to surrender in
exchange for a pardon. In 1996 and 1997, he kidnapped batches of
people and demanded amnesty, but eventually freed his hostages when
he was refused. Then for several years, he simply dropped out of
sight _ until Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:30 p.m., he and 11 of his gunmen strolled into Rajkumar's
farmhouse in the village of Gajanur in Tamil Nadu, just six miles
from the edge of the forest. The movie star was sitting on a couch
with his wife watching the local news. The couple recognized
Veerappan's trademark mustache.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are you taking us?'' his wife, Parvathamma, recalled
asking. ``We've never done anything to you. We will give you
whatever we have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want only Sir,'' Veerappan replied respectfully, promising
that he would take care of her husband and proclaiming himself one
of the movie star's fans, and then threatening to kill him if she
notified the police after they left.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want me, take me,'' she said her husband firmly replied.
``But don't harm anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Veerappan gave Rajkumar an audiocassette and instructed her to
take it to the chief minister of Karnataka. He then picked up the
elderly actor's spectacles, tucked them into a pocket and led him
away, dressed only in loincloth, shirt and sandals. Three other
hostages were also taken.
</P>
<P>
   Parvathamma Rajkumar and two of her servants drove through the
night in a lashing rainstorm and reached the chief minister's
residence here in Bangalore after 2 a.m. Monday. They had called to
alert him.
</P>
<P>
   The tape revealed the kidnapper's only request: that an official
emissary be chosen to visit him and convey his demands. Later that
day, the Karnataka chief minister flew to Madras to meet with his
counterpart in Tamil Nadu. They agreed to dispatch a magazine
editor, R. Raja Gopal, as the emissary.
</P>
<P>
   Gopal headed into the jungle the next day, Tuesday, and has not
yet been heard from. Meanwhile, messages from Rajkumar's family
have been broadcast on All India Radio in hopes that he and his
abductor will hear them on the transistor radio that Veerappan
carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appeal to you in all humbleness and with love and affection
to send him home soon,'' Rajkumar pleaded. ``He has knee pain.
Don't make him walk. I trust in you.''
</P>
<P>
   On the streets outside the star's home, his fans gathered in
mute, anguished clumps Tuesday and Wednesday, though policemen
waving long wooden sticks kept chasing them away.
</P>
<P>
   As one fan, Byalapp Chandrashekar, 28, put it, ``We don't like
to see our god suffering.''
</P>
</TEXT>
