<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Dr. Laura on TV is just what her supporters deserve
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I suppose it behooves those of us who have often grumped against
the right-wing cultural warriors who harry the producers and
sponsors of art and entertainment they dislike to defend Dr. Laura
Schlessinger from the gay- and human-rights activists who are
ganging up on her and undermining a proposed TV show featuring her.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, speaking up for her does not require actually speaking
well of Schlessinger, who uses her radio call-in show to espouse a
biblical moral absolutism that might give even some of the sterner
prophets the willies.
</P>
<P>
   To the poor souls who have muddled their way into the richly
assorted messes all of us are capable of and have come to her for
aid and succor, Schlessinger's inevitable advice is: Tough. Serves
you right. Pull up your socks.
</P>
<P>
   This woman could curdle the milk of human kindness at 100 yards
and never break stride.
</P>
<P>
   She has been especially contemptuous of gays and lesbians and of
efforts to enact legal protections against anti-gay discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Granting legal rights to homosexuals, she has said, would be the
same as enacting rights for bestiality and pedophilia. She has
dismissed gays and lesbians as ``a biological error.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Schlessinger does not call for ostracizing, much less
hating and certainly not for hurting gays and lesbians. Her
attitudes no doubt reinforce folks already disposed toward
homophobia and gay-bashing, but they do so obliquely and in kind
with a myriad of other similar social negatives.
</P>
<P>
   Her offenses, though real and deserving vigorous rejoinder, do
not merit the media equivalent of capital punishment. They are,
after all and alas, the commonplace of many pulpits.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign to scuttle Paramount's planned program has so far
cost the project and Schlessinger's radio show such sponsors as
Procter &AMP; Gamble, Toys ``R'' Us, United Air Lines, Kraft, General
Foods and more.
</P>
<P>
   The mission is the flip side of the boycotting tear that
televangelists and others professional indignants of the right were
on through the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's `` Pocahontas'' was boycotted by the Southern Baptists
for showing ``earth-worshipping paganism.'' Disney was boycotted,
too, for making movies for grown-ups that the right disliked and
for extending benefits to the partners of gay and lesbian
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Wildmon's Mississippi-based American Family Association
boycotted Calvin Klein because of its underwear ads, K-mart because
its Waldenbooks subsidiary carried books and magazines Wildmon
disapproved of, Mennen and Clorox for sponsoring ``Miami Vice'' and
``Knot's Landing,'' the many sponsors of ``Murphy Brown.''
And...well, there were many more, but that's enough.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial TV and its sponsors are jumpy enough as it is without
being driven to even greater excesses of timidity by boycotters
trying to boss the medium into their various versions of
righteousness.
</P>
<P>
   If enough viewers to make the deal feasible want to watch
Schlessinger on TV, let them. It would serve them right.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
