<HEADER>
A0925 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-GOP-WOMEN-BOS &LR;      08-02 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-WOMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP MESSAGE TARGETS WOMEN VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The middle initial in George W. Bush's name used
to stand for Walker. This week, it stands for Women.
</P>
<P>
   Across the floor of the Republican National Convention,
delegates wave posters and sport buttons that say ``W is for
Women.'' But those visual aids aren't really necessary, because
almost everything about the 2000 GOP gathering _ the women
speakers, the videos filled with children, the compassionate themes
repeated again and again at the podium _ is aimed at female voters.
</P>
<P>
   It is a huge contrast to past GOP conventions, when Republicans
let the angry rhetoric of cultural warriors, pro-gun militants,
defense hawks, and abortion opponents set the party's tone. It
scared off many women, pollsters said, and helped create the gender
gap that elected Bill Clinton in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new Republican Party,'' Celinda Lake, a Democratic
pollster who studies gender voting, said here this week. ``There
has never been a Republican leader who understands the targeting of
women the way George W. Bush does. If anybody can capture the
women's vote, he can.''
</P>
<P>
   Lake's latest poll shows Bush and Democrat Al Gore in a
statistical dead heat among women voters. With Bush 16 points ahead
among male voters in the same poll, the wooing of women has become
the central mission of both presidential campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican convention is a big national showcase for Bush,
and he is not missing an opportunity on any of its four nights to
demonstrate he is both an advocate for women's concerns, from
education to health care to Social Security, and a man at ease with
strong, smart women.
</P>
<P>
   It was a calculated move by the campaign to have Laura Bush, a
former librarian and elementary-school teacher, tout her commitment
to early-childhood education during a warm testimonial to her
husband on the convention's opening night. Tuesday night, it was
Barbara Bush _ not the former president _ who introduced their son
and welcomed the conventioneers to Philadelphia, which Mrs. Bush
quipped was ``the city of motherly love.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's main purpose, in remarks beamed in by satellite from
Gettysburg, Pa., was to set the stage for two more accomplished,
prime-time convention speakers: Condoleezza Rice, who Bush
described as ``a brilliant woman and my chief foreign-policy
adviser,'' and Elizabeth Dole, the two-time Cabinet secretary who
Bush said was a ``a pioneer and a role model for so many of our
daughters.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole made sure her national-security speech touched women when
she said, ``Freedom empowers the heart. It levels walls and
shatters ceilings, including glass ceilings.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, two single mothers, a female farmer, and a
30-year-old woman who is a successful high-tech entrepreneur joined
what has been a weeklong cavalcade of women speakers extolling the
Republican Party's positive, caring public policies. On stage, the
most visible members of the unpopular GOP Congress have been the
convention co-chairs, Representatives Jennifer Dunn, a moderate
from Washington state, and J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, a black man.
</P>
<P>
   The scowling House leadership _ Representatives Dick Armey and
Tom DeLay of Texas _ are nowhere to be seen, and the GOP's expected
biting, partisan attacks on the Democrats and the Clintons have not
been heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``When women look at George Bush and Dick Cheney, they don't see
a harsh conservative, which has been the face of the Republican
Congress,'' said Linda DiVall, a Republican pollster and
strategist. ``They see the face of conservatism that is much more
optimistic and, quite frankly, one that will not dismantle
government programs at every stage and every opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention message and messengers are very much in sync with
what pollsters know about women voters: They like civil politics,
moral leadership, and effective government. They worry most about
the economic and physical security of their families, educational
opportunities for their children, and the pressures of juggling
tasks at work and home.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Hall Jamieson, a political analyst at the Annenberg
Center for Public Policy at the University of Pennsylvania, said
the convention's theme, ``Renewing America's Purpose. Together,''
sends a strong signal to moderate women voters that the GOP is
inclusive and concerned about children and families.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theme is symbolically consistent and very well executed,''
Jamieson said.
</P>
<P>
   But is it sincere? Marie Wilson, who heads the White House
Project, a nonprofit group trying to promote women for high
elective offices, said she fears women have become ``vote objects''
for the major political parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned that both parties are looking at women as vote
objects rather than real partners in democracy and governing,''
Wilson said. ``We are not just constituents. We are not just people
to be made to feel better.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Republican women who support gun control, federal
family-planning programs, and abortion rights say the party
platform crafted by Bush and approved by the convention Monday does
not reflect the image of a kinder, gentler GOP. Some say Bush has
not reassured women with his running mate choice of Cheney, who as
a congressman voted against the Equal Rights Amendment, the Clean
Water Act, and federal funds for the Head Start program.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the choices George W. Bush is making, he is showing us what
he believes and what is important,'' said Doris Wilson of
Washington, a Republican vice president of the National Women's
Political Caucus. ``And women aren't really important.''
</P>
<P>
   Women delegates, many who have been working in the GOP for many
years, insist there is something new afoot _ a tone, an attitude,
certainly a unity that is driven by an overwhelming desire to find
a way to win in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is better than it has ever been for women, and it is not
just words and rhetoric,'' said Sue Anne Gilroy, Indiana's
Republican secretary of state. ``There is a true, genuine, and
substantive effort to change the party's direction and put together
a coalition that can win.''
</P>
<P>
   This marks the fourth convention that June Hartley, Oregon's
national GOP committeewoman, has attended, and none has been as
upbeat and positive as this one, she said. She likes Bush's
integrity and experience, and she isn't concerned that as a woman,
she disagrees with some of his stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother always said, `if a man agrees with you 100 percent
of the time, he is either henpecked or not very smart,'' Mrs.
Hartley said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0927 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CANADA-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      08-02 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHTIST SHOCKS CANADIANS BY FLIRTING WITH SEPARATISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES BROOKE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Stockwell Day's summer vacation in Quebec was going
well. Day, the rising star of Canada's right, appeared daily on
French-language television, chatting in Francais with his
language-immersion teachers, fielding reporters' questions about
his politique fiscale, or posing for photographs with the eternal
friend of language students, le dictionnaire Larousse.
</P>
<P>
   Then the athletic Day, a former treasurer from Alberta, clumsily
stepped on a classic Quebec land mine.
</P>
<P>
   With newspapers reporting ``informal negotiations'' between his
party, the Canadian Alliance, and the Bloc Quebecois, whose stated
goal is to make Quebec an independent nation, Day refused to rule
out teaming up with the Bloc in a coalition after general
elections, expected next spring, in order to dislodge the governing
Liberals.
</P>
<P>
   ``An unholy alliance with people who don't believe in the
country,'' fumed Allan Rock, Canada's health minister and an
aspirant for leadership of the Liberals.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred by Day's hurried disavowal of any electoral alliance,
Stephane Dion, the leader of the Liberal government's unity drive,
said, ``It's playing with Canada, and you don't play with your
country.''
</P>
<P>
   As Canada continues to be haunted by the lingering separatist
threat, the sharpest rebukes came from some of Day's closest
backers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Canadian Alliance leader needs to stop playing footsie
with Quebec separatist leaders right now,'' thundered the editorial
page of the National Post, which has usually been a star-struck
cheerleader for Day.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Tuesday, Conrad Black, chairman of the
National Post, said the strategy would not work. ``It makes it too
easy for the Liberals to represent him as a separatist fellow
traveler, ambiguous about the future of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The misstep comes as Day's party, the Alliance Canadienne, as it
is called here, starts to expand beyond its western roots, becoming
Canada's dominant conservative party. In an Angus Reid poll
released last weekend, the Alliance had more than doubled its
support since March, winning 24 percent of the voters polled, the
highest for any opposition party in almost five years. The poll
also indicated that the Alliance is now the most popular opposition
party from the Pacific Coast to the Ontario-Quebec border.
</P>
<P>
   In Quebec, Canada's second most-populous province, the poll
indicated that in two months, voter preference for the Alliance had
risen from 1 percent to 8 percent. In this socially liberal
province, Day has avoided talking about his opposition to abortion,
gay rights and gun control. Instead, he has focused on issues dear
to Quebec's voters, like cutting taxes, reducing parole for
criminals and deporting illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Day, long an advocate of decentralism, has pitched
his anti-Ottawa message to Quebec's ``soft nationalists'' _ the
one-third of voters here who want more autonomy, but not outright
independence. He advocates, for for instance, giving provinces
control over the tax money they raise for health, education and
social welfare.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, his tax-cutting ideas (Day advocates a flat tax)
seem to be translating well here, winning favorable editorials from
the Montreal daily La Presse and the business weekly Les Affaires.
</P>
<P>
   Overlooked in the flurry of denials and cartoons about games of
``footsie,'' Michel Gauthier, leader of the separatists, denounced
Day as a vote poacher. Gauthier warned his followers about the
perils of a summer romance with this handsome language student,
saying Day was ``trying to seduce Quebec voters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0928 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-FORD-ART-1STLD-WR     08-02 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-FORD-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD EXPECTED TO MAKE FULL RECOVERY AFTER MINOR STROKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: Leads with 14 grafs to update with hospital new conference,
fresh quotes; pickup graf, Ford appeared ...; subs byline.) 
 By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Former President Gerald Ford suffered a minor
stroke Wednesday morning, hours after being honored at the
Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   He was expected to make a full recovery, said doctors at
Hahnemann University Hospital, where the former president was in
the intensive care unit.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, 87, first went to the hospital at about midnight Tuesday,
after leaving the convention, where he had been honored in an
emotional tribute. He complained of pain on the right side of his
face and was diagnosed with a sinus infection, given antibiotics
and released. Hours later, he returned with additional symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday evening, hospital officials
defended the decision to discharge Ford and dismissed questions
about whether doctors missed symptoms of a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The care that was given at that time was appropriate to the
symptoms he had,'' said Dr. Stephen Klasko, the hospital's clinical
dean. ``It's very unfair to the physicians and president Ford's
family to dissect the medical record.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford returned to the hospital at 9 a.m. Wednesday &UR; , &LR;  and doctors
determined he had suffered a small stroke in the lower part of the
brain, where unconscious actions like swallowing and balance are
controlled. Wednesday he suffered weakness in his left arm, balance
problems and slurred speech.
</P>
<P>
   But the former president should have no permanent neurological
damage, said Dr. Robert J. Schwartzman, head of neurology at the
hospital. ``The president should totally recover,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford was being treated with anti-coagulant drugs to reduce
clotting, the doctor said, and he was expected to be in the
hospital five to six days.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very calm and collected about it and he was cooperative
in his care,'' Schwartzman said.
</P>
<P>
   Calvin McDowell, a spokesman for Ford, said former first last
Betty Ford was staying in the room next to her husband's. He said
Gov. George W. Bush had requested permission to visit, but was
refused along with others who had attempted to visit or call,
because the former president needed rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is able to take calls, but we are trying to insist he get
some rest,'' McDowell said. ``We are not in a position for anyone
to interrupt his rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford first went to the hospital around midnight Tuesday and was
treated for a sinus infection. McDowell had said a wax build-up had
led to the infection.
</P>
<P>
   Ford left the hospital at 1:36 a.m., but asked to be taken back
hours later after complaining of feeling ``uncomfortable, McDowell
said. ``We just thought we had a routine sinus infection, but then
he had other problems and he was brought back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford appeared frail as he sat in a VIP box at the back of the
First Union Center on Tuesday night along with his wife, former
President George Bush, former first lady Barbara Bush and other
prominent Republicans. He was visibly moved when a video-taped
tribute to him was displayed on the large screens inside the hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``When uncertainty troubled our nation, President Gerald Ford
renewed America's confidence,'' Gov. George Pataki of New York
said, introducing the tribute. ``His strength, his strength and
integrity defended our values at home in an ever-changing world.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd cheered when Pataki invoked ``President Ford's steady
leadership and Mrs. Ford's gentle grace.''
</P>
<P>
   He rose and waved to acknowledge the cheers of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Ford did not address the convention, and told C-Span that this
would be the last convention he and his wife would attend, calling
it a ``concluding appearance to indicate our support.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 1953EDT &QL; 
