r f BC-DOT-COMMERCE-HNS &LR;      08-02 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOT-COMMERCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN FRANCISCO'S DOT-COMMERCE CONTINUES TO THRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco's dot-commerce has grown nearly
500 percent in the past five years, generating nearly $5.7 billion
in revenue last year, according to a recent study.
</P>
<P>
   ``This survey shows me San Francisco's digital industry is
strong, it's a major player, and it's good for the city,'' said
Marie Jones, director of economic development for the San Francisco
Partnership, the nonprofit economic development agency that
conducted the survey.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jones and the San Francisco Partnership, the
digital industry includes software developers, Web site developers,
digital content developers, Web site portals and e-commerce firms,
including B2C (business to commerce) and B2B (business to
business).
</P>
<P>
   For the purpose of the survey, the community did not include
Internet workers at established, global companies such as Charles
Schwab and Gap.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its sheer size, San Francisco's digital economy proved
to be surprisingly profitable and diverse.
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of revenues, 51 percent of digital firms in The
City are profitable today, the survey said, dispelling the myth
that most dot-com firms were running out of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``And a lot of that revenue is sales to business, so it's not
the squishy side of the industry,'' said Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The report also suggested that 24 percent of digital industry
employees were minorities, although 20 percent of the work force
had no college
</P>
<P>
   degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenges the firms are facing are recruiting and
retaining employees,`` said Jones. ``Over 45 percent of the
surveyed firms said that was their biggest challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   That pressure on the work force manifests itself in local
salaries, said Jones, whose survey showed that compensation for
upper management, systems administrators and graphic designers in
the digital industry was more than 30 percent higher in San
Francisco than elsewhere in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the average upper management salary in the city is
$151,769, a 77 percent premium on the national average.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're not making it in salary, stock options are the
next best thing. According to the survey, 88 percent of all the
digital industry employees in San Francisco receive stock options
as a benefit of employment, as opposed to a third nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do our local dot-coms have to pay more for their
talent, the space they rent goes for a premium. The typical digital
industry firm pays $32 per square foot per month and occupies more
than 10,000 square feet of space. Coupled with low vacancy, those
high rents are the biggest disadvantage facing the city's
dot-commers, the survey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
