<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIAS-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSTRUCTION FIRM NAMED IN NEW BIAS SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMAL E. WATSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ An international construction firm recently ordered to
pay $1.3 million to settle racial discrimination and sexual
harassment claims has been accused by a Bay State man of of racism
while he worked for the company at a government construction site.
</P>
<P>
   Terrence A. Townsend, 36, who is black, alleges in a civil
lawsuit that while working for Foster Wheeler's Boston office he
was repeatedly subjected to racial slurs and had to use portable
toilets defaced with KKK graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   After Townsend complained to managers, his attorney says a white
co-workers handed him a hangman's noose and allegedly told him,
``The noose is for you in case you get out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 1995 and 1997, while monitoring air quality for Foster
Wheeler at an Environmental Protection Agency construction project
in Stratford, Conn., Townsend said he endured a hostile racial
climate that his superiors refused to do anything about.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that he and other black employees were repeatedly
given heavier workloads, more undesirable assignments, and paid far
less than their white counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Townsend, who quit Foster Wheeler two years ago and now works
for another construction company, outlined his allegations in the
suit filed in Suffolk Superior Court. A trial is expected to begin
next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working at the site really put a lot of stress on me,'' said
Townsend, of suburban Canton, Mass. ``It's hard to believe that
this kind of discrimination still happens, especially on a
government contracted site.''
</P>
<P>
   Alastair Davie, a spokesman for Foster Wheeler, which is based
in New Jersey and employs 10,000 workers worldwide, refused comment
on Townsend's suit and would not discuss the company's policy on
workplace discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesperson at the EPA, which provided the contract to Foster
Wheeler for the Conneticut project, did not return several phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Darryl Nelson, a black man working in Foster
Wheeler's Chicago office, accused the company of fostering a
racially hostile environment for minority workers.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's case, first filed with the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission, was eventually transfered to federal court, and in
January, a U.S. district court judge entered a $1,325,000 million
judgement against Foster Wheeler.
</P>
<P>
   The judgment expanded the financial payment to include 100
former African-American and female employees in Foster Wheeler's
Chicago office whom the court found had been discriminated against.
</P>
<P>
   Foster Wheeler was also ordered to implement an anti-harassment
policy, provide anti-discrimination training to its work force and
make periodic reports to the EEOC regarding any racial or sexual
harassment complaints against the company.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret A. Burnham, a prominent Boston civil rights attorney
who represents Townsend, said her client initially filed a
complaint with the Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   But he withdrew the complaint and decided to sue the company
instead for the ``mental distress and emotional harm'' that he
suffered due to the alleged discriminatory practices.
</P>
<P>
   Townsend said he interpreted the noose as a threat that he would
suffer physical violence on the job if he decided to stay with the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of incidents are fairly widespread across the
country,'' said Burnham. ``This one was particularly egregious
because Terry was personally targeted. This was not just a generic
act.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials had warned the construction industry following
the Nelson trial that workplace discrimination would not be
tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racial and sexual harassment are particularly vicious forms of
discrimination _ as illegal at muddy construction sites as the
factory floor or in the carpeted office suite,'' said John C.
Henrickson, an EEOC attorney in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday a federal Labor Department spokesman said government
contracts can still be awarded to companies that have been found to
discriminate, but only if the infraction was a first-time or minor
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really does amount to how gross the violation is and how
often it occurred,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   But Townsend, who now works as a technical specialist for GZA
GeoEnvironmental Inc. of Newton, believes firms found by a court to
have practiced or condoned discrimination should be barred from
receiving government contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the government has to be more cautious in the
hiring of contractors,'' he said. ``They should look not just at a
company's performance, but on their ethics as well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
