<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0936 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-IRELAND-HAUGHEY-TRIMS     08-02 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-HAUGHEY-TRIMS(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PRIME MINISTER FACES INQUIRY
</HEADLINE>
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ Each weekday morning, he is chauffeured in a pale blue
Mercedes to Dublin Castle. It would seem a fitting mode of travel
for a former prime minister of Ireland, a man of regal bearing
whose very face, with those hooded eyelids and that dramatic sweep
of silvery hair, is as identifiable in this country as the castle
itself.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles J. Haughey comes to discuss the state of his
financial affairs rather than affairs of state _ from the witness
stand, at a tribunal that is exploring the relationship between
this once-dominant political figure and various businessmen who,
over the years, handed him and his subordinates hundreds of
thousands of dollars in checks and cash.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal has estimated that Haughey (pronounced HAW-hee)
received as much as $10 million in contributions to cover his huge
debts and expensive tastes, and it is poring over his personal
banking records to determine whether he used his public office to
benefit his benefactors. Haughey and his lawyers have not yet
addressed the central thrust of the inquiry, but they are expected
to maintain that he did nothing untoward for the money, which they
will argue totaled no more than $7.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The seamiest allegations center on a fund that Haughey
established in 1989 to send his political ally and close friend,
Brian Lenihan, who has since died, to the United States for a liver
transplant. About $100,000 from the fund covered the transplant and
related costs, but the whereabouts of at least another $125,000 is
unclear _ although there is evidence that some was spent on
Haughey's personal expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal will ultimately present a report to Parliament that
probably will join other efforts to tighten relatively new public
ethics laws. Michael Moran, a government spokesman, said that
revelations regarding Haughey and other politicians have already
contributed to legislation seeking further reform.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the daily proceedings of the tribunal, which
began a summer recess on July 28 and will reconvene in September,
feed a growing list of allegations of public corruption.
</P>
<P>
   There are nine sitting tribunals and 11 other inquiries,
investigating everything from the contamination of blood products
to decades-old allegations of child abuse in public institutions.
</P>
<P>
   But the most prominent investigation centers on off-shore bank
accounts, cozy public-private relationships and blurred lines
between political donations and personal gifts _ all of which lead
inexorably back to this 74-year-old man twirling his gold-rimmed
glasses as he ponders embarrassing questions posed in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a Nixon figure in Irish public life,'' said Dermot
Keogh, an author and professor of Irish history at National
University of Ireland in Cork. ``He is a flawed talent.''
</P>
<P>
   An accountant from Dublin and the son-in-law of former Prime
Minister Sean Lemass, Haughey rose quickly within the dominant
political party, Fianna Fail (FEE-na FALL) to serve in various
ministerial capacities in the 1960s. He is credited with several
progressive measures, from ensuring that widows and children were
included in estate matters to providing free electricity and public
transportation to the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   He spent several years in political isolation _ charged with,
and then acquitted of, conspiring to import guns to be used in
Northern Ireland. In 1979 he returned, gaining control of Fianna
Fail and emerging as prime minister, a position he held, on and
off, for nine years. He was both blamed and praised for economic
ebbs and flows and is generally credited with jump-starting the
Northern Ireland peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, the matter of his wealth vexed and amused the
nation. Haughey earned a modest salary as a member of the
Parliament, yet lived on a Dublin estate, owned a small island off
the southern coast, and relaxed on a yacht called the ``Celtic
Mist.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1992, various controversies had become too much for even
Haughey's allies to countenance, and he was forced to step down as
prime minister. With characteristic flourish, he said farewell to
public life with a quote from ``Othello'': ``I have done the state
some service, they know't; no more of that.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as Haughey was settling in as elder statesman, the
Dunne family, owners of the country's largest department-store
chain, became concerned with the spending habits of the company's
chief executive, Ben Dunne. Inquiries led to the discovery that
over the years Dunne had given Haughey a sum now estimated at $2.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   At first Haughey told an investigating tribunal in 1997 that he
knew nothing of the matter and that a close adviser had handled his
financial affairs to free him ``to devote my time and ability to
public life.'' But the accumulated evidence forced Haughey to
concede that he had misled the tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dunne's testimony of an incident in 1991 was particularly
damaging. He said he visited the prime minister and found him
looking depressed. To cheer the leader up, he said, he handed him
checks totaling $260,000. His recollection of Haughey's response
has since entered national lore: ``Thank you, big fella.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the tribunal found no evidence that Haughey had
assisted Dunne in exchange for the gifts, it expressed great doubt
about the former leader's testimony. ``It is quite unacceptable,''
the tribunal said in its final report, for an elected official _
particularly a prime minister _ to be ``supported in his personal
lifestyle by gifts made to him personally.''
</P>
<P>
   A criminal charge of obstruction was lodged against Haughey, and
he was forced to pay more than $1 million in back taxes and
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Now another panel is digging deeper into his murky finances to
determine whether the showers of money influenced the performance
of his public duties.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And so, for the last 18 months, some of Ireland's best-known
public figures _ from multimillionaire businessmen to Bertie Ahern,
a former Haughey lieutenant and current prime minister _ have made
their way up the cobblestone path to Dublin Castle to share their
tantalizing pieces of the puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Haughey faithful have found the revelations unsettling.
Testimony has shown that when he was elected prime minister in late
1979, Haughey and his aides spread the word that he needed money,
fast: he owed more than $1.3 million to Allied Irish Bank. Within
weeks, he was able to give more than $930,000 to the bank, which
charged off most of what was still owed.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A property developer, in typical testimony, testified that he
contributed $475,000 to the cause after being summoned by the prime
minister to his estate. Another developer testified that in 1989 he
handed Haughey four checks for about $31,000 each _ one for the
Lenihan transplant fund and the three others for Fianna Fail. But
according to the tribunal, the party only received a portion of the
money, and none of it was deposited in the transplant fund.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, testimony has shown that contributions to the Lenihan
fund went into a so-called leader's account that Haughey used for
such personal needs as tailor-made shirts from Paris and dinners at
an exclusive French restaurant in Dublin. Evidence that Lenihan's
medical costs were fully covered has not created a groundswell of
support for Haughey, no more than have reports that he has prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Keogh, who has written several books on modern
Ireland, said the revelations of the tribunal demonstrate the
extent to which Haughey and his allies corrupted the values of a
government founded a generation earlier by people who believed in a
``communitarian democracy.'' The country needed to be modernized,
he said, ``but he did it in a way that weakened and undermined the
state of governance, and the citizens' confidence in the
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryle Dwyer, a historian who has written several books about
Haughey, said, though, that Haughey is not the first leader to
believe that he should focus on public affairs while others tend to
his finances. Dwyer also said that, given the many other cases of
political scandal, Haughey's indiscretions are more symptomatic
than causal _ and that Irish politicians have long had the power to
enact reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he has done wrong he should be nailed and, I rightly feel,
jailed,'' Dwyer said. ``I just don't like the hypocrisy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As others contemplate his legacy, Haughey comes daily to Dublin
Castle and tries when possible to contain the harm already done. At
times he has claimed to be overwhelmed by all the paperwork. At
other times he demonstrates the acumen for which he was once
famous, quibbling with the nuances of certain words _ even the
nuances of punctuation _ that appear in old bank memoranda
portraying him as an unrepentant debtor who was not above
mentioning his station in national politics.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when two hours have elapsed _ a time limit established in
deference to his age and illness _ Haughey is excused. A few
minutes later, the blue Mercedes carrying a small man in the
passenger seat pulls away from Dublin Castle, whose refurbishment
he oversaw when once in power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
