<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS DEFEAT REDS 2-1 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Six weeks ago, John Franco was called into a tie game
at Shea Stadium. He allowed one run, recorded one out and left with
the bases loaded. Then Armando Benitez came in and gave up a grand
slam. That was the last time either of those Mets pitchers allowed
an earned run.
</P>
<P>
   Franco, Benitez and Turk Wendell shut down the Cincinnati Reds
Wednesday to give the Mets and Al Leiter a 2-1 victory, completing
an 8-1 homestand in which they did everything but gain significant
ground on the Atlanta Braves in the National League East. The Mets
trailed Atlanta by five and a half games before the Braves' game
last night at Arizona; they were six back before the homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Ventura's two-run home run in the first inning gave Leiter
and the bullpen all the necessary run support. Leiter improved to
12-4 by working seven strong innings, and seven innings are all the
Mets need these days. If they have a lead by then, they believe
they will win. ``That's a really good feeling to have,'' first
baseman Todd Zeile said.
</P>
<P>
   Mets relievers allowed only two earned runs in 212/3 innings on
this homestand, and they have been brilliant for three weeks. The
current group has an earned run average of 0.99 since the All-Star
Game, and it is easy to see why the Mets have been able to win by
one or two runs in 10 of their last 13 victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what everybody envisioned early in the year, that the
bullpen would be one of our strong points,'' Franco said. ``We
picked it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest games on the homestand, catcher Todd Pratt said,
were the two victories over Montreal in a doubleheader last
Thursday. In the first game, Grant Roberts, a rookie, gave up seven
runs in less than two innings. But four relievers held down the
Expos to make a comeback victory possible. In the nightcap, Mike
Hampton pitched a complete game.
</P>
<P>
   A rested bullpen helped the Mets win their next two games
against St. Louis, and Bobby J. Jones pitched a complete game in
the finale on Sunday against the Cardinals, resting the bullpen
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're rested, confident and shortening the game,'' Manager
Bobby Valentine said. ``I think that adds to the confidence of the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   After Leiter struck out the side in the seventh inning
Wednesday, completing a stretch in which he retired 18 of 19
hitters, Franco came in to face the top of the order in the eighth.
He got two outs, then had two strikes on Ken Griffey Jr. when Zeile
moved closer to the line at first, protecting against an extra-base
hit. Griffey bounced one to the spot Zeile vacated for a single,
and Wendell was summoned.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Wendell had allowed a run-scoring triple to Dante
Bichette, the only batter he faced. He faced Bichette again
Wednesday, throwing one pitch that Bichette grounded to first,
ending the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez worked a 1-2-3 ninth for his 27th save, and after the
game he gave credit to one of his setup men, Franco.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Franco doesn't do the job, I don't do the job,'' Benitez
said. ``We have good communication. What he's doing, it's great.''
</P>
<P>
   What is Franco doing? ``Just trying to get outs and get the ball
to Armando,'' he said. And what is working? ``Just everything,
really,'' Franco said. ``The change-up, the fastball's moving in
and out, just trying to throw strikes and let them put it in play.
We've got guys behind us that are pretty good fielders.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those guys is Mike Bordick, the veteran shortstop
acquired from Baltimore in a trade last week. In the fourth inning,
Bordick reached up to spear a hard grounder from Pokey Reese that
shot up over his right shoulder on one hop. Such plays are almost
routine with Bordick, who played his first game with the Mets last
Saturday, the same day that Ventura, the third baseman, another
excellent fielder, was activated from the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have missed Ventura's bat this year. Bothered by a
bruised right rotator cuff, Ventura slumped before the All-Star
Game break and did not feel better the first day after it. He did
not make much of Wednesday's homer _ ``I'd rather be lucky than
good,'' Ventura said, quizzically _ but acknowledged how much the
Mets need him, especially when he bats fifth, behind Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you bat behind Mike,'' he said, ``you don't want people
to walk him. The job for the person batting behind him is to make
sure they pitch to him and give him pitches to hit, and you have to
be getting singles and everything else to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Ventura batted third while Piazza rested. Ventura's
home run was his 17th, second only to Piazza on the Mets. But he
has only 39 singles, and he said he wanted to be more consistent in
getting base hits. The Mets, who have the second-best record in the
National League, can wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought all of Robin's swings today were Robinesque,''
Valentine said. ``There's no doubt that he's a guy we're counting
on, depending on, and we're going to jump on his back a few times
before this thing's over. Today was one of those days.''
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen also carried its load, just as it has for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're clicking pretty well,'' Wendell said, ``but we know we
can still pitch a little better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
