<HEADER>
A0943 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-COYOTEUGLY-TEX     08-02 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-COYOTE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPOWERED WOMEN IN STILETTOS? THAT'S A HOWL
</HEADLINE>
 UGLY-TEX  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a rambling article in the August issue of ``George,'' Kate
Bohner writes about ``stiletto feminism'' _ the idea that women
should be able to make their sexuality work for them, and still
have complete control of their lives. Bohner was inspired, in part,
by ``Coyote Ugly,'' and she quotes the movie's producer, Jerry
Bruckheimer, as saying, ``This is a film about women who go for
what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, baloney. Bruckheimer may be hyping ``Coyote Ugly,'' but he's
spreading horse hockey. ``Coyote Ugly'' is about re-inventing
``Flashdance'' with Maxim cover models wearing tight,
midriff-baring clothing, dancing on bar tops, setting carefully
stunt-coordinated fires and pouring alcohol, water and ice on
everyone, especially themselves. And for most of its running time,
it has the good sense to know it.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, as the ads say, its women call the shots, but if
``Coyote'' is empowering, it's not because of ``stiletto feminism''
but because it follows a well-trodden trajectory. To put it in the
movie's mentality, it's just a story about a lil' ol' small-town
gal who makes it in the big, bad city. Keen observers might note
that a couple of the ``empowered'' women are stuck in
one-dimensional, underwritten roles and that although Violet, our
protagonist, vanquishes the stage fright that hinders her success,
she overcomes her other problems not through any special effort,
but because they all kind of solve themselves.
</P>
<P>
   That said, much of ``Coyote Ugly'' is stupid fun, sublimely
silly until it veers recklessly into absurdity and dime-store
sentimentality. It's no wonder the bar scenes dominate the
previews; they crackle with such energy that they overwhelm the
rest of the movie, even when they are just a notch shy of
incoherent. And Gina Wendkos' screenplay _ reportedly punched up by
Carrie Fisher in an uncredited rewrite _ partially makes up for the
hokeyness of its plot by actually including lines that have a
certain level of wit, an increasing rarity in a movie culture in
which passing gas passes for humor.
</P>
<P>
   But boy, does that script load down poor Violet, played by
relative newcomer Piper Perabo, who's cursed with such a girlish
voice that she seems more likely to dance on a junior-high
cafeteria table than a Manhattan bar. Violet is an aspiring
songwriter who's too shy to perform her own stuff _ just like her
late beloved mother. Mom died five years previously, leaving Violet
alone with her lovable lug of a father (John Goodman), who is, of
course, reluctant to let his only daughter leave their little New
Jersey town and tackle the Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   Over in New York, Violet tries to shop around a demo tape,
stumbling into a romance with a charming Australian short-order
cook (Adam Garcia) along the way. She also stumbles into a job at
Coyote Ugly, where she has trouble fitting in until her quick mouth
and peacemaking skills convince the boss that, yes, Violet has what
it takes to be a Coyote, too.
</P>
<P>
   Everything's fine until the screenplay decides to provide
obstacles for Violet to overcome _ and most viewers will be able to
spot them a mile away, because the script isn't so much written as
it's charted on a graph, with all the characters in Violet's orbit
having their own points A, B and C. Some of those characters _
fellow bartenders Cammie (Izabella Miko) and Rachel (Bridget
Moynahan), and Coyote Ugly alumnus Zoe (Tyra Banks) _ are
prominently featured in the ads, but in the movie they're barely
ciphers, identified by one-word characteristics and probably
sharing less than 20 lines of dialogue among them. Only former
``ER'' player Maria Bello, as Violet's tough-as-chewing-gum boss,
shows much spark beyond the rowdy bar scenes.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Flashdance'' comparison might seem like a cheap critical
shortcut, except that Bruckheimer also produced ``Flashdance,'' and
you know he's out to duplicate that movie's success. It's not for
nothing that director David McNally's shots include a sexy
silhouette and a sensual bar-top dousing. Nevertheless, the movie
looks like a hit, and it's likely to do for Perabo what
``Flashdance'' did for Jennifer Beals. Um ... just what did
``Flashdance'' do for Jennifer Beals, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   ``Coyote Ugly'' is rated PG-13 for sexual situations, scattered
foul language and lots of alcohol. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FILM: ``Coyote Ugly'' &QL; 
SCORE: 21/2 on a 1-5 scale &QL; 
DIRECTOR: David McNally &QL; 
STARS: Piper Perabo, Adam Garcia &QL; 
LENGTH: 94 minutes &QL; 
RATED: PG-13 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
