<TEXT>
<P>
   These stories from the Republican National Convention in
Philadelphia are moving to all points.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved except GOP-MAIN and GOP-FORD.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GOP-DIVERSITY and CVN-LEADERS are scratched.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GOP-MAIN _ PHILADELPHIA _ Vice-presidential nominee Dick
Cheney's acceptance speech and an address by Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott highlight the convention agenda. (Herman).
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GOP-SPEECH _ PHILADELPHIA _ George W. Bush arrives in the
convention city on the eve of his acceptance speech, one of the key
events that will shape the voters' view of him in the fall
campaign. (Heath).
</P>
<P>
   CVN-BULLOCK _ PHILADELPHIA _ One goes out of his way to get
along with people. The other seemed to craft a successful career by
figuring out how not to get along with people. But somehow George
W. Bush, the gregarious one, and Bob Bullock, who thrived on
closed-door confrontation, became fast friends. Thursday night, in
the kind of bipartisan symbol coveted by the Bush presidential
campaign and more poignant to Texans that the rest of the country
will know, Jan Bullock, the widow of Democratic Lt. Gov. Bullock,
will introduce Bush as he accepts the GOP presidential nomination.
(Herman)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-FORD _ PHILADELPHIA _ Former President Gerald Ford, 87,
suffered two small strokes Tuesday night during a Republican
convention salute to former GOP presidents. Ford was hospitalized
but doctors said chances for a full recovery were good. (Galloway).
</P>
<P>
   CVN-PROTESTS _ PHILADELPHIA _ Police and protesters stared off
at tense demonstrations all across this sweaty, edgy city
Wednesday, but avoided the violent clashes and snarled streets of
the prevous day. (Dart)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-SKYBOX _ PHILADELPHIA _ Viewers who have felt the urge to
pound their fists at their TV screens when watching politicians now
have another outlet for their frustrations: Thanks to Internet
video, they can talk back in a chat room and get a response even as
they watch. That's just what happened here the other night when
Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge when to a pioneering cyberworld skybox
at the Republican National Convention. (Glass)
</P>
<P>
   CVN _ GOPTV _ ATLANTA _ With the broadcast networks barely
showing up, it's been up to CNN, PBS and CSPAN to carry the
Republican convention. And as hard as CNN and PBS are trying, there
have been times when CSPAN, with its devotion to the podium and
commentator-free zone, has told the real story. Plus looking ahead
to Thursday. (Kloer).
</P>
<P>
   CVN-MONEY _ PHILADELPHIA _ Rep. Mike Fasano is one of Florida's
80 alternate delegates here, but as of Wednesday he still had not
stepped foot onto the convention floor. That's because Fasano, who
is coordinating his party's House campaigns, has been spending his
time in the lobby of the Loew's Philadelphia hotel, joining state
Rep. Tom Feeney, R-Oviedo, in meetings with big GOP contributors.
By Friday, Fasano expects to have enriched the Republican Party of
Florida by $100,000. (Gelbart).
</P>
<P>
   CVN-NOTEBOOK _ PHILADELPHIA _ Tidbits from the convention.
(Staff).
</P>
