u i BC-RUSSIA-MEDIA-NYT &LR;      08-02 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S GAZPROM MOVES TO TAKE CONTROL OF MEDIA GROUP CRITICAL OF
GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By SABRINA TAVERNISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A senior Russian official said Wednesday that the
government-controlled company Gazprom is negotiating to acquire the
entire media empire of Vladimir Gusinsky, the Kremlin's most
outspoken critic.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Vladislav Surkov, deputy head of the
presidential administration, confirmed what had been speculated for
days: that Russia's natural gas company Gazprom may take over
Media-Most by calling in debts.
</P>
<P>
   Media-Most owes hundreds of millions of dollars to Gazprom, and
the companies have been haggling over Media-Most's value.
</P>
<P>
   Media-Most has hired foreign auditors and wants to establish
what the company is worth, believing the debt would entitle Gazprom
to only a small percentage of the company, according to company
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Gazprom argues otherwise, saying that the debt should be
exchanged for all of Media-Most.
</P>
<P>
   Though the talks are inconclusive so far, journalists and
political analysts said the Kremlin is trying to assert control
over Russia's three biggest television networks.
</P>
<P>
   The government has begun talks with magnate Boris Berezovsky on
his 49 percent stake in the country's biggest television network,
ORT. He has mentioned a willingness to sell.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Gazprom and Media-Most, ``talks are being
conducted, they are already drawing to a close,'' said Surkov.
``It's possible that in exchange for these debts the entire holding
will be transferred to Gazprom.''
</P>
<P>
   The move against Media-Most by Gazprom, 38 percent of which is
owned by the government, apparently shows that though President
Vladimir Putin has promised the country's richest men that the
state will not take away their assets, he may have other ways to
reduce their influence.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's statement highlights the conflict between the
Kremlin and Gusinsky, who has been under pressure since May when
masked law enforcement officers raided his offices in central
Moscow. He was jailed for a while in June, though the criminal case
against him was dropped last month.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the struggle is control over Gusinsky's media
assets, which include NTV, a large television network, and a new,
American-made satellite, as well as Itogi news magazine, Echo
Moscow radio station, and the Sevodnya newspaper. The current talks
will determine how much of the business Gusinsky is left with, or
whether he's left with none.
</P>
<P>
   Control of the media business might not extend to NTV, however,
because it is registered as a separate legal entity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though their political interests may not be made public, de
facto they exist,'' said Boris Makarenko, deputy director of the
Center for Political Technologies, an independent Moscow-based
think tank. ``When a company friendly to the government acquires a
controlling interest in Media-Most, the government accomplishes its
goal. Media-Most as a hotbed of political opposition will cease to
exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Media-Most denied that the talks focus on handing control to
Gazprom, and said it is striving in the talks to agree to a
valuation for the company. Media-Most values its assets at more
than $2 billion, while Gazprom says the figure is much lower.
</P>
<P>
   Gazprom has extended loan guarantees totaling about $380 million
to Media-Most, and already owns, directly and indirectly, just less
than 50 percent of the media company. Media-Most is also
negotiating with foreign investors for capital, which _ if
successful _ could release it from government pressure.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Gazprom asked Media-Most to pay the debts after Putin,
on a trip to Europe, remarked on the question of why Gazprom had
become a creditor in the first place. In the same month, Putin
reasserted Kremlin control over the gas monopoly, installing a
close adviser, Dmitry Medvedev, as chairman of the board.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the state's rocky relations with Gusinsky, recent
attacks on some of the country's most powerful businessmen are not
a systematic state policy, said Surkov, of the presidential
administration. Law enforcement authorities have acted too rashly
in the recent spate of investigations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin has said there won't be any review of privatization and
the law enforcement agencies now understand that,'' Surkov he said.
``It's the role of the government to hold back these unhealthy
tendencies.''
</P>
<P>
   One powerful business leader, who requested his name not be
used, said Putin has not distanced himself entirely from big
business, as he has not yet pushed out Roman Abramovich, a close
friend of Boris Yeltsin's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not equal distance from all of the oligarchs yet,''
said the executive, who attended a meeting Putin held on Friday
with Gazprom's top business leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
