<HEADER>
A0950 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-GOP-SCHLAFLY-SPI &LR;      08-02 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-SCHLAFLY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHLAFLY VOWS TO REMAIN VIGILANT AGAINST ABORTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ During four decades as a high-profile Republican
activist, Phyllis Schlafly has made it her vocation to stand
athwart what seemed to be irreversible historical trends, and cry:
``Stop!''
</P>
<P>
   History has often swung the way of the Illinois activist and
mother of six who has been a steadfast opponent of abortion, and
who masterminded the campaign that blocked ratification of the
Equal Rights Amendment to the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday _ at a lunch with nearly 1,000 paying guests, Schlafly
basked in her latest victory _ a Republican Platform 2000 that
maintains word-for-word the anti-abortion language adopted by the
GOP in 1984, 1988, 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``God bless her!'' cried unsuccessful GOP presidential candidate
Alan Keyes as he was honored with a Pro-Life Patriot Award by the
National Republican Coalition for Life, an organization founded by
Schlafly.
</P>
<P>
   Schlafly, 75, was a national co-chair of Pat Buchanan's GOP bid
for the presidency in 1996. Although Buchanan has bolted to the
Reform Party, Schlafly is backing the GOP, and vowing vigilance
that the Bush-Cheney ticket does not back off from the
anti-abortion cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done all right so far,'' Schlafly said in an
interview. ``It is important for us to keep on them to give us what
we want.''
</P>
<P>
   Does she feel any tugs toward Buchanan? ``The important thing is
to defeat Al Gore,'' Schlafly replied.
</P>
<P>
   Schlafly first made waves in 1964 when her book, ``A Choice Not
An Echo,'' was published. It argued that the Republican Party had
lost one presidential election after another due to what she called
the ``me too'' attitude of its Eastern establishment and not
sticking to its convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Victory, she maintained, lay in the unbending conservatism of
Arizona Sen. Barry Goldwater.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater won the GOP nomination, but lost the 1964 election by
16 million votes to Lyndon Johnson. Schlafly was rebuffed in a
subsequent bid for the presidency of the National Federation of
Republican Women. She also lost a race for Congress from southern
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   It took 16 years, but the conservative movement swept to victory
in 1980, putting in the White House a man who rose to national
prominence in the Goldwater campaign _ Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   While using her Eagle Forum to fight the ERA, Schlafly also was
an early, passionate advocate of an anti-ballistic missile system
and space-based defense. Missile defenses are a key part of Bush's
defense and national security platform.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Schlafly cited the GOP platform committee's
unwavering stand on abortion. It even rejected language
acknowledging legitimate differences of opinion on the issue. ``The
good news is not only that we won, but that we won big and more
decisively than ever before,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Schlafly told her audience Wednesday that its work will not end
with Bush's election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to continue to urge him to be as steadfast in naming
pro-life judges as President Clinton has been steadfast in naming
pro-abortion judges,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0951 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GOP-CONSERVATIVES-ART     08-02 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CONSERVATIVES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVES ARE PLEASED BUT MISS OLD-TIME RHETORIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT23,24 _ are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888- 346-9867. 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ These are complicated times for social
conservatives. They feel they are winning on their core issues at
this Republican National Convention, but some of them clearly miss
the red-meat rhetoric and partisan edge of conventions past,
replaced this week by the Bush campaign's relentless appeal to the
center.
</P>
<P>
   There was, unmistakably, a wave of grumbling in the conservative
ranks _ about the shortage of strong conservative voices on the
stage, about the prime-time convention speech awarded to an openly
gay member of Congress, about the lack of a stronger and more
direct condemnation of the Clinton-Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   But inside the conservative movement, as in the Republican Party
more broadly, there is an overriding desire to win in November. So
social conservatives are focusing on the victories of Philadelphia
_ notably, a strong anti-abortion platform and the selection of a
running mate, Dick Cheney, who is a staunch anti-abortion
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Some argue that the Bush campaign has merely repackaged core
conservatism into a more inclusive appeal; others say that they may
well have to remind George W. Bush of his conservative commitments
once he is elected; all agree, passionately, that he is infinitely
better than Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   So, the Rev. Jerry Falwell and other leaders were putting out
the word that it was time to hold ranks, maintain discipline and
help the Bush campaign win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our people have just got to grow up,'' said Falwell,
when asked about the grumbling in an interview on Wednesday. ``We
have a platform that is strongly pro-life, pro-family, pro-strong
national defense. We have a presidential candidate and a
vice-presidential candidate, both of whom are pro-life, pro-family
and pro-strong national defense.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Our crowd needs to get into the battle, keep their
mouths shut and help this man win.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Sigerson, chairman of the Nebraska Republican Party and a
longtime member of the Christian Coalition, noted: ``You know, in
1992, all the left-wing Democrats were mad at Bill Clinton. They
didn't like a lot of the things that Bill Clinton stood for because
he was a New Democrat. But what did they do? They shut up, because
they knew that although he was not as left wing as them, at least
they thought not, they knew if he got elected they could still get
most of their programs through. And they did.''
</P>
<P>
   The unease among some social conservatives bubbled up on the
convention floor on Tuesday night when a small group of Texas
delegates protested in silent prayer while Rep. Jim Kolbe of
Arizona, who is gay, spoke on trade. Cathie Adams, president of the
Texas Eagle Forum and one of those protesting delegates, said that
Kolbe's selection was ``all about affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams added, alluding to social conservatives: ``We're not the
favored sons. That's very apparent and that makes me sad. I think
the core of the Republican Party is what the governor needs to get
elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Colleen Parro, director of the Republican National Coalition for
Life, said of the Kolbe choice, ``If they wanted diversity, why
didn't they ask Alan Keyes to speak?'' Keyes, who was a contender
in the Republican primaries, is black and staunchly conservative.
</P>
<P>
   And Chuck Donovan, acting president of the conservative Family
Research Council, described the proceedings this week as a ``Sally
Field convention _ you love me, you really love me.'' But he
quickly added: ``In terms of substantive action, the platform and
the choice of Cheney, social conservatives have every reason to be
pleased. And if you've got to choose something, take the substance
over the symbol.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Bush is elected, Donovan added, ``We'll certainly be there
with the fire that's in the platform and say, `This is the fire
we're going to hold your feet to.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Family Research Council gave the platform good grades for
reasserting the party's opposition to legalized abortion, its
endorsement of tax cuts, its defense of traditional marriage and
and its declaration that homosexuality is ``incompatible'' with
military service.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Reed, a former executive director of the Christian
Coalition and now a top Bush adviser, said in an interview on
Wednesday that ``social conservatives have become increasingly
mature and sophisticated about the political process and understand
that a political party is not a church, and that becoming a
governing majority requires that you work with others with whom you
occasionally disagree. And if there wasn't a full understanding of
that eight or 10 years ago, there certainly is now.''
</P>
<P>
   At a crowded rally on Tuesday at a downtown hotel, the Rev. Pat
Robertson, founder of the Christian Coalition, highlighted the
stakes for religious conservatives in the coming election, focusing
on the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five people can decide the destiny of unborn children,''
Robertson thundered. ``Five people can decide whether we can pray
or not pray.'' He added, ``It looks as if two or three of those
unelected officials are getting ready to retire or go on up to that
great court in the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Promising a re-energized Christian Coalition campaign this fall,
with 75 million voting guides distributed through the churches,
Robertson told his cheering audience, ``We need to have the
election of a man who will appoint righteous judges to the court of
the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The paramount importance of the abortion issue was cited again
and again by social conservatives this week. Well before he had the
nomination, Bush signaled that he would support the current
abortion plank, which calls for a ban on the procedure without
exception, and the appointment of judges who support the ``sanctity
of innocent human life.'' Bush says he personally would allow
abortion in cases of rape, incest or when the life of the woman is
in danger.
</P>
<P>
   And while Bush says he does not have a litmus test for the
appointment of judges, a New York Times/CBS News poll taken in late
July showed that conservative Republicans overwhelmingly expected
him to appoint Supreme Court justices who would vote against
abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Tobias, political director of the National Right to Life
Committee, said on Wednesday afternoon, ``We're really very pleased
with the way things are going.'' Asked about the scant mention of
abortion from the convention podium, she replied: ``We're keeping
everything in perspective. We got the important things, and we're
very happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
