<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0952 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-GOP-CHENEY-BOS &LR;      08-02 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CHENEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY GOES ON THE ATTACK IN SPEECH TO CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GLEN JOHNSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ After Republicans spent two days casting
themselves as a kinder, gentler party, Dick Cheney dug into the
Clinton administration Wednesday in his vice presidential
acceptance speech, reprising Al Gore's famed line from 1992 and
declaring, ``It is time for them to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Wyoming congressman and defense secretary used his
first major address back in the political spotlight not only to
acknowledge his unexpected role as George W. Bush's running mate,
but also to serve notice that he will be more than just the loyal
running mate the Texas governor sought.
</P>
<P>
   While the names of President Clinton and Bush's Democratic
opponent, Vice President Al Gore, were not uttered during the first
half of the convention, Cheney showed he will not shrink form the
attacking role that Gore took on in 1992, as did Dan Quayle,
President Bush's running mate in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we going to make of the last eight years?'' Cheney
said in remarks prepared for delivery to the thousands inside the
First Union Center and, more importantly, the millions more
watching on television. ``I look at them and see opportunities
squandered.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, poking at Gore with the line that became a delegate chant
during the 1992 Democratic National Convention in New York, he
added the applause line: ``The wheel has turned. It is time for
them to go.'
</P>
<P>
   The 59-year-old Cheney had been head of a $9 billion company,
the Halliburton Co., until Bush asked him to help find a running
mate and then settled on Cheney himself last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to tell you that I never expected to be in this
position,'' Cheney said in remarks he largely wrote himself. ``But
now I am back in the arena and let me tell you why: I have been
given an opportunity to serve beside a man who has the courage and
the vision and the goodness to be a great president: Governor
George W. Bush,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those expected in the convention hall was Bush's father,
former President Bush, who plucked Cheney from the House in 1989
and appointed him defense secretary. In that role, Cheney achieved
his greatest fame, serving alongside Generals Colin Powell and
Norman Schwarzkopf to assemble that 28-nation allied coalition that
defeated Iraq after it invaded Kuwait in 1990. Both Powell and
Schwarzkopf addressed the delegates earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been in the company of leaders,'' Cheney said. ``I know
what it takes. And I see in our nominee the qualities of mind and
spirit our nation needs and our history demands. Big changes are
coming to Washington. To serve with this man, in this cause, is a
chance I would not miss.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has lived in Dallas for the last five years, coinciding
with Bush's election as Texas governor in 1994. He offered a
testimonial to Bush's style of governance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush doesn't accept old lines of argument and division. He
brings people together, reaching across the partisan aisle to do
the people's business. He leads by conviction, not calculation. You
will never see him pointing the finger of blame for failure; you
will only see him sharing credit for success,'' Cheney said.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Bush was watching the speech from his hotel room in
Center City, several miles north of the convention hall. The
governor will address the delegates Thursday night, and he has been
trying to stay rested so he delivers a strong performance.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Cheney were reunited in Philadelphia at midday
Wednesday, when the two were the star attractions at Republican
National Committee luncheon expected to raise up to $10 million for
the party.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney did not speak, but he and his wife, Lynne, joined Bush
and his wife, Laura, on stage before the governor paid tribute to
his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a man of enormous integrity, great depth, solid
judgment. He's really fun to be around. I care for him a lot.
America's going to care for him a lot. I'm proud to call him friend
and this great man, I'm going to be proud to call him `Mr. Vice
President,''' Bush said to an ovation.
</P>
<P>
   The speech came at a time when Democrats have been hammering
Cheney for a compiling a staunchly conservative voting record
during his six terms in Congress. They argue that clashes with
Bush's attempt to recast the party as more moderate ``compassionate
conservatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Craig Thomas, Republican of Wyoming, said he doubted the
speech would change many minds about Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll just reestablish what people pretty much know,''
Thomas said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
