<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0955 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-WALSH-INTERVIEW-AZR &LR;      08-02 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALSH-INTERVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-WALSH-INTERVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    `BLOOD SIMPLE' STAR TALKS(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL FRIDAY, AUG. 4. PLEASE DO NOT USE UNTIL
THEN)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Coen brothers scored a coup when they recruited M. Emmet
Walsh to star in their 1984 low-budget thriller, (beginitalic)Blood
Simple.
</P>
<P>
   (enditalic)After all, he was veteran actor. And he really knew
how to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did six movies one year, and they killed me in five of
them,'' Walsh said in an interview. ``I said, `Are they hiring me
because I'm talented, or because I give them a wide target?'''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, 65, passed along his sage advice to another actor in
(beginitalic)Blood Simple(enditalic), which is being re-released on
the big screen Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (him) to die in a comfortable position,'' Walsh said.
``You're going to be there for three days. If you die in an awkward
position, they're going to have to keep going back to it, and
you're going to cramp.''
</P>
<P>
   If you've seen more than a few American movies, you've probably
seen Walsh, a noted character actor who has played a variety of
roles, from the deranged, can-shooting sniper in (beginitalic)The
Jerk (enditalic)to Harrison Ford's laconic boss in
(beginitalic)Blade Runner(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, who got his big break opposite Dustin Hoffman in
(beginitalic)Straight Time(enditalic), said he's always amazed at
how people remember his lines, like his graphic description of a
car accident in (beginitalic)Raising Arizona(enditalic), another
Coen brothers' movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this spherical object in the road,'' Walsh's
character opines. ``And it wasn't a part of the car.''
</P>
<P>
   For (beginitalic)Blood Simple(enditalic), Walsh gave some
personal touches to his character, a seedy private detective who
favored yellow leisure suits and straw cowboy hats.
</P>
<P>
   As a metaphor, Walsh kept acting even as flies landed on him.
That was especially hard in one scene, which included some not so
freshly caught fish among the props.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your instinct is to swat (the flies). It just drove you
crazy,'' Walsh said. But rather than lose a take, ``I just let them
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh didn't have much of a take on (beginitalic)Blood Simple
(enditalic)when the Coen brothers first called his agent in the
early '80s. Joel and Ethan Coen were green rookies. They couldn't
even pay him. Eventually, he agreed to do the movie for a small
percentage of the gross, not that he thought there would be any.
</P>
<P>
   ``The character was kind of fun,'' Walsh said. ``I thought, I'll
flesh this guy out, this Sydney Greenstreet type of thing, and in
seven or eight years somebody's going to offer me the character in
a real movie, and I'll have an idea how to play him.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, who was filming the Meryl Streep movie
(beginitalic)Silkwood (enditalic)in Dallas at the time, made the
trek back and forth to Austin, where (beginitalic)Blood Simple
(enditalic)was shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said the set was a riot. The director of photography,
Barry Sonnenfeld (who would go on to direct (beginitalic)Get Shorty
(enditalic)and (beginitalic)Men in Black(enditalic)) had never used
a 35mm camera before. Much of the prop and special effects work was
done by volunteers from the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you turned around, they were reinventing the
wheel,'' Walsh said. ``It was like, how do you put rain on a
windshield?''
</P>
<P>
   The Coens were stumped when it came time for Walsh's character
to blow smoke rings. Walsh, a non-smoker, tried without success.
The Coens brought in a machine, but it also failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, the assistant prop girl, this little Texas farm girl
says, `Give me that cigar. I grew up with five brothers, and we
spent all our time behind the barn.' She takes the cigar and blam,
she knocks out a smoke ring{hellip}I thought isn't this wonderful,
this is the way movies get made.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, who won an independent film award for his part in
(beginitalic)Blood Simple, (enditalic)admits he never expected the
movie to take off. At the time, he placed its chances as ``slim and
nil.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't lucky, but they were lucky,'' he said of the
Coens. ``You can't be 27 and 29 years old and make a movie that
good.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it worked out better than Walsh ever expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time the Coen brothers do a new movie, they talk about
(beginitalic)Blood Simple (enditalic)again and they talk about
me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So what do they ask?
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he dead?''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
