<HEADER>
A0957 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-PALESTINIAN-CAMP-ART-     08-02 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALESTINIAN-CAMP-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIAN SUMMER CAMPS FEATURE DRILLS IN KIDNAPPING AND
AMBUSHING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT15,16 are being sent to NYT photo clients. Map
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NABLUS, West Bank _ It is summer camp time for 25,000
Palestinian teen-agers, and unusual camps they are, too. As run by
the men who handle psychological warfare for Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, they allow no horsing around in the dormitory,
no fun-in-the-sun by a cool lake, no rousing sing-along beside a
campfire.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there is the chance to stage a mock kidnapping of an
Israeli leader by masked Palestinian commandos, ending with the
Israeli's bodyguards sprawled dead. Next, there is the mock attack
on an Israeli military post, ending with a sentry being fatally
stabbed. Finally, there is the opportunity to excel in stripping
and reassembling a Kalashnikov rifle.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of the latest Camp David talks, a summer that was
supposed to produce a final peace settlement between Israel and its
Palestinian adversaries, the Palestinians' idea of a teen-age boys'
camp is a reminder of how deep old enmities run. At 90 two- and
three-week camps on the West Bank and in the Gaza Strip, youths
from towns and villages already ceded to Israel by Arafat's
Palestinian authority are learning the arts of kidnapping,
ambushing and using assault weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``As President Arafat says, this is the generation that will
plant the Palestinian flag on the walls of Jerusalem,'' said Dr.
Wajieh Affouneh, a 49-year-old dental graduate who joined Arafat's
Fatah organization in a refugee camp, and in the 1970s and 1980s
participated, so other aides said, in some of the operations that
made the Palestinian cause synonymous with attacks on Israeli and
other targets. Affouneh is now a top man in the ``political
guidance'' department of Arafat's National Security Forces, the
armed police unit permitted under the Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
   In the camps around this biblical town 35 miles north of
Jerusalem, the mood is a throwback to the days before Arafat joined
Israeli leaders in the peacemaking that faltered last week at Camp
David.
</P>
<P>
   In two weeks of talks, President Clinton was unable to bridge
the gap between the sides on crucial issues including Jerusalem,
Jewish settlements on the West Bank, the future borders of Israel
and a Palestinian state, and the fate of three million Palestinian
refugees dispersed around the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Since the current cycle of talks began in Oslo in 1993, both
sides have made generous use of the tactics of bluff and and have
still made impressive strides toward peace. But the display today
in the yard of what was once a notorious Israeli prison seemed more
than old-time propaganda, even if there was an element of that.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   To a visitor, what the youths and their mentors had prepared for
a graduation parade on Thursday appeared to be steeped more in the
Palestinian mindset of the 1970s than the conciliatory postures of
today.
</P>
<P>
   In the mock kidnapping acted out by the youths, an Israeli
politician or general _ precisely who was never made clear _ walked
across the old prison yard surrounded by eagle-eyed security men.
Suddenly a reporter approached with a tape recorder. The kidnap
target stopped, only to be grabbed by the reporter, now flourishing
an imitation pistol. As the VIP was dragged off, other mock
kidnappers shot seven of the supposed Israeli's bodyguards dead.
</P>
<P>
   For 1,000 Palestinian youngsters standing in neatly ordered
platoons, cheering, the enactments seemed like ripping good stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, many predicted that their generation would someday
take up arms against Israel over Jerusalem. At indoctrination
sessions in the camps, the youths have been told that Arafat, at
Camp David, rejected U.S. proposals that would have given the
Palestinian Authority a foothold in parts of Jerusalem, demanding
that Israel surrender the entire eastern half of the city it seized
in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Fikri Fouad, a 15-year-old village boy, said Palestinians had
learned during the Oslo peace process to live with a split view of
Israelis _ ``as people that we can make peace with, but still our
enemies, too.'' He added: ``If we can get Jerusalem without
weapons, it is better. But if there is a need to liberate Jerusalem
with weapons, we will be ready for that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we are being taught here to handle weapons,'' he
said, ``so that we can fight for our country if we have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Other youths offered opinions that would be grist for the mill
of Israeli politicians like Ariel Sharon, the hawkish former
general who has tried to stir a political groundswell against Prime
Minister Ehud Barak since Camp David by accusing him of endangering
Israel with his acceptance of U.S. proposals on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Tuesday, Sharon, calling the city
``Israel's eternal and undivided capital,'' said any Palestinian
foothold there would encourage Arafat to press the ``real''
Palestinian goal of recovering Tel Aviv and Haifa, along with the
rest of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Suleiman Nubaim, 16, said the Camp David talks had given new
relevance to what he and his friends had been taught about the
exploits of the freedom fighters, or ``fedayeen,'' the name taken
by Palestinian guerrillas of the pre-Oslo period. Like many youths,
he said he wanted to join the Palestinian forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
