<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURIED-BODY0803-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Husband kills wife for refusing his advances
 &HT;    By Bill Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Edward William Heckman's wife, Janet, was already dead
and buried in a shallow grave in their yard near Jonesboro, Ga. on
July 26 when he called a sister-in-law in Las Vegas and claimed his
wife had flown to Chicago, according to Clayton County police.
</P>
<P>
   But when Janet Heckman could not be reached in Chicago, where
her husband said she had gone to oversee repairs to a condo the
couple owned, her sister, Susan Pantle, called police Sunday,
Detective Todd Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Police then went to the couple's shaded ranch house to talk to
the husband, said Detective Sgt. Johnny Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Heckman told police his wife of 37 years was out of town, and
officers initially found nothing suspicious, Robinson added. But
late Tuesday afternoon, Heckman, 64, confessed to killing his wife,
who would have turned 59 on Tuesday, with a hunting rifle after she
allegedly refused to have sex.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said Edward Heckman told police that he and his wife
engaged in ``a shoving match'' on the bed when she rebuffed his
advances and that he reached for the rifle he kept under their bed.
``He says he kept it there for personal protection,'' Murphy added.
</P>
<P>
   Police have found no history of domestic violence in the
household, and neighbors said the couple kept to themselves and did
not socialize. ``It appears their problems revolved around sex, or
the lack of it,'' said Detective Scott Sperrazza.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said Heckman had been arrested in the early 1990s in
Clayton County and Atlanta on charges of soliciting for
prostitution, but he could not provide any details of those
arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pretty much kept to themselves and weren't very
neighborly people,'' said Paula Burnham, a college student spending
the summer with her mother next door to the couple's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lived in the neighborhood for 19 years, and they were
here when we got here,'' Burnham added.
</P>
<P>
   After confessing to investigators, Heckman led police to a
3-foot-deep grave covered with brush and limbs next to the house,
Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   The victim's body was wrapped in a blanket.
</P>
<P>
   ``He broke down and admitted to killing her about 9:30 p.m. last
Wednesday,'' Robinson said, adding that Heckman shot his wife in
the chest and head with a German-made Mauser rifle.
</P>
<P>
   Police dug up the grave on the south side of the house and found
Janet Heckman's body.
</P>
<P>
   The couple had no children, Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Heckmans were already in the neighborhood of spacious,
tree-shaded brick homes when another neighbor, Jesse Newcomer,
arrived with his wife 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't speak much,'' Newcomer said. ``He told us when we
first came here that `We're real private people. We don't watch
what our neighbors do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Heckman used to work for Eastern Airlines, Newcomer said, and
his wife ``worked in a lawyer's office, I think a paralegal or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the wife and I ever said a word to each other,''
Newcomer said. ``I'd see them driving out occasionally and she
would wave.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
