<HEADER>
A0960 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-SPACECOWBOYS-TEX     08-02 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SPACECOWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG SHOTS CONQUER SPACE MOVIE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Space Cowboys'' is probably the closest we'll ever come to a
cinematic equivalent of Mount Rushmore. Not only are its four stars
_ Clint Eastwood, Tommy Lee Jones, Donald Sutherland and James
Garner _ iconic actors, but their craggy faces already seem to have
been carved out of granite. These are four men who've earned
respect; you expect them to be minted onto some commemorative coin.
</P>
<P>
   The actors, however, don't make the mistake of taking themselves
that seriously _ and for at least half its length, neither does
``Space Cowboys.'' The movie might seem to be the polar opposite of
another weekend opener, the young-female-bartenders-in-love
fandango ``Coyote Ugly,'' but the films do have one thing in
common: a lack of conviction in their own absurdity. Neither movie
is very plausible, yet at some point, each goes awry by beginning
to believe that its story could really happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Space Cowboys' '' basic premise _ that four senior-citizen
astronauts would be recruited for an outer-space mission _ is
acceptable; after all, John Glenn set a precedent for this nearly
two years ago. Unlike Glenn, though, these guys have been waiting a
long time for their first trip; way back in 1958, when they were
hot-dogging test pilots (introduced in an entertaining,
black-and-white prologue), a chimpanzee usurped their opportunity
at a space mission. Eastwood's character, Frank Corvin, has been
ticked off about it ever since.
</P>
<P>
   But now it's the present, and an aging, wounded Soviet satellite
threatens to topple toward Earth unless someone can work out the
bugs in a device that Corvin designed. Naturally, he's a little
suspicious that his technology wound up on a mysterious Soviet
satellite during the height of the Cold War, but he passively
accepts the explanations for this. When he's called on to help fix
the gizmo, he insists that he be sent into space to do the job,
along with his old crewmates who were gypped by the chimp.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood, who also directed, has a good time with this, as
Corvin travels out to assemble his posse: preacher Tank Sullivan
(Garner), roller-coaster designer Jerry O'Neil (Sutherland), and
stunt pilot/longtime rival Hawk Hawkins (Tommy Lee Jones). Each is
reintroduced in vignettes that are blessed with rowdy,
self-deprecating humor, as is most of the first half of the movie,
which puts the four through the training paces they need for flying
the space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they learn to fly the thing in a month, and that's a
little hard to swallow, but the movie's air of self-mockery helps
blow by that little plot flaw. Ken Kaufman and Howard Klausner's
screenplay provides plenty of hints at duplicity on the part of
NASA weasel Bob Gerson (James Cromwell), who burned Corvin and his
team back in 1958 and seems likely to do so again. And a sweet
romance begins to develop between mission director Sara Holland
(Marcia Gay Harden) and Jones' character. The screenplay also has
many amusing, off-color and/or macho moments _ and then the darn
thing has to turn serious on us.
</P>
<P>
   It's when the movie goes into space that it takes on its
gravity, providing a change in tone and plot twists that we won't
reveal here. This shift might be OK, except that the second half is
even harder to buy into than the first _ even the laziest
fourth-grade science-fair slacker might have trouble dealing with
the explanations and solutions on display here. This has been a
problem with many of Eastwood's recent starring movies. He's
willing to toy with his feel-lucky-punk image, but only to a point,
and that seems to cloud his vision of the movies' ridiculousness.
``Space Cowboys'' is at least a little more self-aware of its
silliness than ``True Crime,'' perhaps 1999's most preposterous
movie, and 1997's nearly as absurd
cat-burglar-catches-president-with-his-pants-down flick ``Absolute
Power.'' But ``Space Cowboys'' becomes less fun when it gets down
to business.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to dislike it, though, because of its cast. Eastwood
gets more than enough chances to squint and hiss one-liners; the
guy has been breaking rules for more than 40 years, long before
``Dirty Harry'' was losing count of how many shots he fired, and
he's still a joy to watch when he clicks. Jones, more cheerful,
open and good-ol'-boy than he has been in a while, proves to be an
apt foil for Eastwood; when they brawl, it brings to mind the
good-natured machismo of the fistfights in John Wayne's more
lighthearted movies.
</P>
<P>
   Sutherland and Garner have less to do, but each does it with
laconic ease, barely breaking a sweat as they reduce the movie's
younger actors (Loren Dean and Courtney B. Vance as fellow
astronauts) from supporting status to background wallpaper. All
four leads look like they're having the time of their long careers,
and their attitude is contagious. You could spend an evening
picking this movie apart, right down to the beautiful lunacy of its
closing shot, but the good vibes emanating from the cast make all
kvetching irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Space Cowboys'' is rated PG-13 for strong language, violence,
sexual innuendoes and backside nudity. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FILM: ``Space Cowboys'' &QL; 
SCORE: 3 1/2 on a 1-5 scale &QL; 
DIRECTOR: Clint Eastwood &QL; 
STARS: Clint Eastwood, Tommy Lee Jones, Donald Sutherland, James
Garner &QL; 
LENGTH: 123 minutes &QL; 
RATED: PG-13 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
