r e BC-FILM-HOLLOWMAN-TEX     08-02 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HOLLOWMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FX-CELLENCE ASIDE, THIS `MAN' LOOKS VERY FAMILIAR
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By TODD CAMP 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It doesn't take a formula for invisibility to see right through
director Paul Verhoeven's violent, sexy and occasionally clever
special-effects showcase, ``Hollow Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all its promises of genuine chills combined with saying
something about the effects that invisibility might have on the
human psyche, it's really just the same old stuff we've come to
expect from Verhoeven: special FX laid on so thick they come just
short of ceasing to be special; graphic, bloody and over-the-top
violence; and the unapologetic exploitation of naked flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Now don't get me wrong, I don't necessarily have a problem with
any of those things. After all, I loved Verhoeven's menacing giant
bug movie, ``Starship Troopers.'' What I do mind is squandering a
nifty premise while giving audiences the old bait-and-switch;
commercials bill ``Hollow Man'' as some kind of stylish new
approach to a Hollywood cliche instead of what it really is,
``Friday the 13th Part Whatever: Jason Disappears.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all its faults, you certainly can't blame star Kevin
Bacon. As self-centered genius Sebastian Caine, Bacon oozes cocky
villainy. He makes almost as much of a largely faceless role as
Claude Rains did in James Whale's 1933 classic ``The Invisible
Man.'' Suffice it to say Rains didn't have to deliver a performance
while enduring the kind of FX-oriented torture Bacon experienced.
</P>
<P>
   As the head of a secret Pentagon-funded research group, along
with project chiefs Linda (Elisabeth Shue, as his feisty ex-wife)
and Matthew (Josh Brolin, as her new secret lover), the
megalomaniacal Caine plots to keep the success of the invisibility
formula's animal testing from the military in order to leap right
to human testing. And you can guess who the first eager volunteer
to pull a disappearing act might be.
</P>
<P>
   But as any Hollywood experiment in mad science has taught us
(not to mention almost every other invisible man movie), something
goes ``horribly'' wrong. Caine disappears all right, but it's the
reappearing that proves to be the tricky part.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't take long before the lure of his awesome new
power, combined with the drug's side effect of increased aggressive
tendencies, leads Caine to try just about anything, including the
extermination of his team, to keep his secret.
</P>
<P>
   Let's be honest. As with most movies dealing with invisibility,
the thing that attracts audiences is special effects, and on that
front, ``Hollow Man'' doesn't disappoint. Apart from the expected
shots of empty clothes and footprint indentations in the carpet,
expect a new twist on the old bandaged head treatment, along with a
startlingly gruesome approach to clearing out. You see, the process
works from the outside in, offering a somewhat grisly ``visible
man'' anatomy lesson as the formula works its way through the
bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   As for the film's remarkably bloody pick-'em-off-one-at-a-time
finale, we might have suggested a better motto than, ``The gore the
merrier.'' How 'bout, ``Less is more?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollow Man'' is rated R for graphic violence, nudity,
suggested rape and strong language. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FILM: ``Hollow Man'' &QL; 
SCORE: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale &QL; 
DIRECTOR: Paul Verhoeven &QL; 
STARS: Kevin Bacon, Elisabeth Shue, Josh Brolin &QL; 
LENGTH: 114 minutes &QL; 
RATED: R &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
