<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0962 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-GM-FUEL-ECONOMY-ART-6     08-02 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-FUEL-ECONOMY-ART-630(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL MOTORS TO BATTLE FORD ON FUEL ECONOMY FOR SPORT UTILITY
VEHICLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTIAC, Mich. _ General Motors challenged Ford Wednesday to a
battle over which company can deliver bigger improvements in fuel
economy, particularly for sport utility vehicles, the least
efficient vehicles of all.
</P>
<P>
   Ford committed itself last week to an improvement of 25 percent,
or almost 5 miles per gallon from approximately 18 mpg now, as the
average for its sport utility vehicles over the next five years.
General Motors announced Wednesday that no matter how much Ford
improved the energy efficiency of its sport utilities by 2005, GM's
sport utilities would average even more miles to the gallon by
then.
</P>
<P>
   The announcements affect half of all the sport utilities sold in
the country _ about 800,000 by each automaker.
</P>
<P>
   GM also upped the ante, saying that the overall fuel economy for
all its light trucks _ a category including minivans and pickups as
well as sport utilities _ would be better than Ford's in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``GM will still be the leader in five years, and in 15 years for
that matter,'' said Harry Pearce, GM's vice chairman, at a news
conference Wednesday in this Detroit suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Ford had said last week that it would improve the fuel economy
of its minivans and pickups, and planned future announcements to
say by how much after performing additional engineering studies.
Pearce's comments Wednesday effectively pre-empted Ford's next
move, by committing GM to exceed in average light truck fuel
economy whatever Ford does. The world's two largest automakers make
nearly half the nation's minivans and pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers have been trumpeting the occasional fuel-economy
improvement in various models for years, but have typically offset
these gains by making other vehicles more powerful and less
efficient. The GM and Ford announcements mark the first time that
big domestic automakers have committed themselves voluntarily to
significant increases in the average fuel economy of large classes
of vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Why, after two decades of no significant improvement in the fuel
economy of light trucks, are GM and Ford reversing course? Both
companies said their market research had found growing interest in
better fuel economy.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign automakers are stepping up their sales of sport
utilities and showing that they do not have to be gas guzzlers,
partly because the foreign brands are often based on lightweight
car underbodies instead of cheap but heavy pickup truck
underbodies. GM and Ford also worry that the government might
require higher fuel economy; the automakers helped narrowly defeat
such a plan in Congress two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   But another big reason for GM's declaration seemed to be a
nervousness that last week's news conference by Ford had burnished
Ford's reputation for environmental responsibility, which might
help Ford sell more cars and light trucks. ``What annoys me is the
perception that seems to come from that press conference that Ford
is somehow the environmental leader,'' Pearce said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Nasser, Ford's chief executive, said last week that the
planned improvement in fuel economy would save the typical sport
utility customer about 1,700 gallons of gasoline, or 80 trips to
the gas station, over the first 10 years of vehicle ownership. The
effect on the nation's overall oil imports and emissions of global
warming gases, while small at first, would grow as the more
efficient models gradually replace the behemoths now on the road.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler and Asian automakers declined to join Ford and
GM in promising fuel-economy gains, saying that they already had
better gas mileage, partly because they did not sell models as big
as the Ford Excursion and GM's Chevrolet Suburban. ``We'll let them
do the tit for tat,'' said Michael Aberlich, a DaimlerChrysler
spokesman.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0389 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0963 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-GM-FUEL-ECONOMY-ART-6     08-02 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-FUEL-ECONOMY-ART-630(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PONTIAC, Mich.: DaimlerChrysler spokesman. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Love, Toyota's national regulatory affairs manager, said
the Japanese automaker would focus on the gas mileage of individual
models. ``We'll try to have class-leading fuel economy in every
segment we're in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists hailed GM's position. ``That's huge _ Ford
placed its bet and GM anted up and we've got a real race here,''
said Jason Mark, the transportation co-director at the Union of
Concerned Scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ford last week, GM said Wednesday that it would improve
fuel economy without resorting to the auto industry's favorite
loopholes in the 1990s: Building vehicles so heavy that they are
exempt from federal fuel-economy rules, and claiming gas mileage
credits for vehicles that have the capability to burn either
gasoline or nearly pure ethanol, even though ethanol is not
available in most of the country. GM also said that, like Ford, it
would achieve almost all of its improvement through changes in
conventional, gasoline-powered engines, rather than by switching to
potentially dirty diesel engines or introducing partly electric
engines for which consumer demand is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   GM provided more technical details than Ford, saying it planned
to change all of its big V-8 engines over the next several years to
use a technology tried in desperation and abandoned during the
depths of the oil crisis that followed the Iranian revolution in
1979. The technology involves turning off four of the engine's
eight cylinders except when maximum power is needed for
acceleration or towing.
</P>
<P>
   This approach was discredited when GM tried it in the early
1980s because the engine controls then were slow to sense changes
in the driver's need for power, so there was a long lag when
drivers tried to accelerate. The latest microprocessors adjust the
number of cylinders in use faster than a human being can appreciate
the change, said Stephen G. Poulos, a GM engineer.
</P>
<P>
   GM also said it would introduce in some of its light trucks a
technology known as a continuously variable transmission. This
replaces a conventional four-speed automatic transmission, and is
in use on a few very small cars, mainly overseas. But the
technology, for which drivers do not sense any gear changes at all,
has been improving lately for use on larger vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Pearce also displayed a large pickup truck and a city bus that
were each powered by a hybrid system of a gasoline engine and an
electric motor. The hybrid pickup truck will be 15 percent more
fuel efficient than current models and the hybrid bus will be 50
percent more efficient. Many electric vehicle enthusiasts say that
even bigger efficiency gains will be possible, and that hybrid
systems could someday reduce considerably the nation's energy
needs.
</P>
<P>
   But GM is concerned that customers may take a while to accept
hybrids as household vehicles, and is not counting on hybrids to
play more than a very small part in its overall improvement in
light truck fuel economy by 2005, said Jeffrey Kuhlman, a GM
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Pearce said GM's current sport utilities go 6 percent farther
than Ford's on a gallon of gasoline, on average. He did not promise
that GM would beat Ford by a similar percentage in 2005, raising
the possibility that GM could keep the lead but improve its fuel
economy by a little less than Ford's 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials said they were unsure whether GM's current sport
utilities were ahead in fuel economy. In midmodel year reports to
regulators on the 2000 model year, GM and Ford have both reported
that their light truck fleets are averaging 20.9 mpg.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford welcomed GM's overall willingness to compete on fuel
economy. ``It's good for the ecology, it's good for the customer,''
said Ken Zino, a Ford spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Pearce, who has overseen public policy and technology issues at
GM for four years, mentioned repeatedly Wednesday his irritation at
the attention that Ford had received for its commitment to greater
fuel economy at a news conference in Washington last week. He
chided Nasser, Ford's chief executive, for having flown to
Washington to make his announcement at the National Press Club.
``We've got them beat in SUVs and they know it, and maybe that's
why they felt compelled to be in the Press Club,'' he said,
speaking at GM's Truck Design Center here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
