<HEADLINE>
SPEEDY GOODWIN HELPS DODGERS ROLL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Todd Hollandsworth made his presence felt Tuesday
for Colorado. Tom Goodwin took his turn Wednesday afternoon at
Three Rivers Stadium, and he showed why the Dodgers wanted him.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin, the speedy leadoff batter Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
sought, reached base in each of the first four innings as the
Dodgers built an eight-run lead and cruised to an 11-5 victory over
the Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin walked three times, added a base hit, scored twice,
drove in two runs, stole a base and took the extra base when the
opportunity arose.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just try to get on base, but the hard part is what the
other guys do,'' Goodwin said. ``They have to get the clutch hits,
and make the contact and all that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (57-50) concluded their 10-game road trip 6-4 and
they've won five of their last six series. They played the last
three games in a 24-hour span, winning the final two.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a game for Goodwin,'' Johnson said. ``That's as good as
it gets. His first four (plate appearances), you talk about
sparking the club. I think both guys were covering (second) at one
time. That's what speed does. It forces the defense to move around.
He took the extra base.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin was the centerpiece of the Dodgers' win, but he was far
from the only offensive force. Shawn Green hit a three-run homer
off Pirates starter Jose Silva (7-5) to give the Dodgers a 3-0 lead
three batters into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Cora ended his torrid road trip with three more hits and
four RBI. Cora, whose lackluster offense has held him back, went 11
for 24 (.453) with 11 RBI in the 10-game trip, raising his average
to .271. He entered the trip without an RBI in a month.
</P>
<P>
   Also, right-hander Darren Dreifort (8-7) won his fourth
consecutive start and improved to 4-0 since the All-Star break,
though this outing wasn't as dominant as his previous two. Dreifort
had his scoreless-innings streak snapped at 19 when he surrendered
a one-out, two-run homer to Alex Ramirez in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   But buoyed by 11 runs in the first four innings, Dreifort didn't
need to be particularly sharp. He allowed five runs on seven hits
in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I got caught up with being too patient,'' Cora said.
``I know I have to put the ball in play. Right now, I'm getting
into a situation where I'm hitting what I want to hit, not what
they want me to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin, who went 0 for 4 with three strikeouts and a walk in
his Dodgers debut, showed his dazzling speed in the first inning
when he went from first to third on Mark Grudzielanek's single to
left. Green followed with his 18th homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, Goodwin walked and moved to third when
Pirates left fielder John Vander Wal misplayed Grudzielanek's
single. The Dodgers went ahead 5-0 when Goodwin scored on Gary
Sheffield's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   And Goodwin's speed and aggressiveness on the basepaths rubbed
off on his teammates, especially in the third, when Dave Hansen and
Cora scored on Goodwin's infield single. Goodwin's high chopper
went over the pitcher's mound and off shortstop Enrique Wilson's
glove. Cora never stopped running and scored from second to put the
Dodgers ahead 8-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked back and saw (Wilson) missed it, and I'm a middle
infielder so I know how it works over there,'' Cora said. ``You
have to take advantage, and when he missed it you have to pick up
the ball and make a perfect throw. Everything has to go right to
get an out, so you stay aggressive and I scored.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
