u f BC-MINDSPRING-CHRONOLOGY     08-02 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING-CHRONOLOGY0803-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A chronology of Mindspring
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   1994
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 24: Charles Brewer incorporates MindSpring Enterprises.
Founding the company in his Ansley apartment, Brewer scrawls a list
of ``core values'' he wants the new company to follow. MindSpring
launches service in June. Brewer, a Louisville, Ky., native with a
degree from Amherst College, runs the operation himself for months,
emerging periodically to walk Louie, his three-legged dog, in
Ansley Park. In two months, he chalks up 60 customers.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 17: MindSpring says ITC Holding Co. of West Point has
become a major shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 31: MindSpring finishes year with revenue of about
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   1995
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 1: MindSpring has more core values than employees: nine of
the former, eight employees.
</P>
<P>
   July: Michael McQuary joins company from Mobil Chemical. Within
two months he becomes chief operating officer. Later, he is named
president of MindSpring.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 6: MindSpring has 9,000 customers.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 31: Company finishes the year with revenue of $2.23
million.
</P>
<P>
   1996
</P>
<P>
   March 13: MindSpring goes public, selling 1.95 million shares at
$8 per share.
</P>
<P>
   July 14: With 21,500 subscribers, MindSpring reaches 170
employees. Brewer says he no longer knows them all.
</P>
<P>
   1998
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 1: MindSpring reports its first profit as its stock crests
past $64.25 a share. Company completes 1998 with revenue of $115
million.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 11: MindSpring buys Sprynet, one of the nation's largest
independent Internet service providers, paying up to $45 million
for the company previously owned by America Online.
</P>
<P>
   1999
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 6: Brewer says the company's growth makes it harder to
maintain the values on which he founded the company. ``I compare it
to gravity. The bigger we get it seems like there's a force trying
to suck us back to being like any other company.''
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 7: MindSpring announces a $245 million deal to acquire
pioneering Internet service provider Netcom. Based in San Jose,
Calif., Netcom's 500,000 subscribers double MindSpring's subscriber
base and make it one of the biggest ISPs in the country.
</P>
<P>
   April 5: Forbes magazine names MindSpring one of the most
dynamic companies in the Internet service and content category. The
company shares the list with Yahoo, America Online, Amazon.com,
eBay, NetGravity and Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   April 14: MindSpring raises approximately $469 million from a
secondary public offering.
</P>
<P>
   May 25: Brewer tells MindSpring shareholders' annual meeting
that the company's goal is to be the biggest ISP after America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 23: MindSpring announces $3 billion merger with
California-based EarthLink, creating the second-largest Internet
service provider after AOL. Charles Brewer becomes chairman,
surrendering day-to-day responsibility for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 22: MindSpring announces plans to stay in Midtown
post-merger, moving to new quarters in Pershing Point Plaza at
Peachtree and 17th streets.
</P>
<P>
   2000
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 4: Final shareholders meeting of MindSpring Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   July 27: EarthLink reports revenue of $230.9 million for the
quarter ended June 30. EarthLink lost $50.9 million, or 43 cents
per share, during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday: Brewer resigns from the company he founded.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
