<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-NADER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
NADER BLASTS GOP AND DEMOCRATIC CONVENTIONS AS `POLITICAL ORGIES' &HT;    By TIMOTHY SPENCE
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Presidential candidate Ralph Nader on Wednesday
denounced the Republican and Democratic conventions as
corporate-paid ``political orgies'' and dismissed criticism that he
will siphon votes from Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Nader, the Green Party candidate, unleashed his
anti-establishment offensive at two separate appearances across
town from the GOP convention, where Republicans were poised to
nominate Texas Gov. George W. Bush for president and former defense
secretary and oil industry executive Dick Cheney as his running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican national convention is costing some $63 million,
of which about $50 million was contributed by businesses and
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Nader aimed some of his harshest criticism at Gore and other
Democrats, accusing them of abandoning the party's traditional core
_ workers and lower-income people _ and of co-opting Republican
issues under President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats are decaying from within,'' he said in an
interview. The party is ``a shell of what it once was.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing in a city brimming with galas, tours and receptions
for Republican delegates and politicians, many of the events
sponsored by corporations, Nader said the national political
conventions exclude most working Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a political carnival where the political powers shake
down the corporations and the corporations buy future political
favors,'' Nader said of the GOP convention, adding that it would be
the ``same in Los Angeles'' where the Democrats hold their
nominating convention beginning Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Polls have shown Nader gaining among liberal Democrats and
environmentalists, especially in key Western and Midwestern states.
He has picked up support from rank-and-file members of organized
labor who are upset over the Clinton administration's support for
normalized trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   Gore officials, meanwhile, have said the interest in Nader is a
fluke that will dissipate as the November election nears.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide polls show Nader winning about 7 percent of voters in
a four-way race against Gore, Bush and Pat Buchanan, the nominee of
the Reform Party. A recent poll shows Nader garnering 9 percent in
California, a must-win state for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Party hopes to have Nader on the ballot in 45 states
by election day, Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Nader's withering criticism of Clinton and Gore has prompted
some Democrats to accuse the Green Party candidate of taking votes
away from Gore. Nader's liberal agenda calls for national health
insurance, restrictions on corporate donations to politicians,
taxes on stock purchases and more governmental protection of the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Nader, responding to a reporter's question, denied that he would
draw votes away from Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Democrats can't beat George Bush without my help, then
they are not even a party worthy of any recognition,'' he said,
adding that he sees little difference between the policies of the
parties. ``For 10 years now the Democrats have become very good at
electing very bad Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they continue to do that,'' he said, ``they deserve to be
replaced.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a cheering audience of high school and college
students attending a conference sponsored by Youth in Action, a
nonpartisan group based in Los Angeles, Nader said young people
should be ``turned onto'' politics to combat apathy and corporate
influence in the political system.
</P>
<P>
   Nader urged young people to help ``build a new progressive
politics'' to elect candidates ``who not only say what they mean
but mean what they say by getting corrupt money out of our
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the current system ``has produced these political orgies
called Democratic and Republican conventions'' that manifests ``a
charade of presumed concern for everyday people.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nader, best known as a consumer advocate who in the 1960s
tangled with General Motors over auto safety and later took on the
nursing home industry, ran a hapless campaign for president in
1996, registering less than 1 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But this time he says he is serious. The campaign has
organizations on 600 campuses and plans to add 400 more this fall.
He said the campaign has raised more than $1 million and that he
has visited all 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``There comes a point when you've got to do your part,'' he
said. ``The process keeps decaying. Our government keeps getting
hijacked by corporate money. We don't gave a real grass-root
government and political parties out fighting for the people.''
</P>
<P>
   (Timothy Spence can be reached at 202-298-6920 or via e-mail:
tim(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
