<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-POWER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAINING FOR ELECTRICITY, CALIFORNIA MAY RESORT TO ROTATING
BLACKOUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four years after it led the nation into a sweeping deregulation
of the electric industry, California is at the brink of a breakdown
in its power supply.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, as a heat wave caused electric demand to soar
across the West, the nation's most populous state nearly ran out of
power for the third straight day. To reduce the strain on
California's electric grid, regulators ordered utilities to curtail
supplies to big commercial users that have agreed to cut their
electric consumption in times of shortage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the state was on the verge of imposing rolling blackouts
of homes and businesses. That step has been taken only eight times
around the country in the last 17 years, usually because of extreme
weather or power plant failures, says the North American Electric
Reliability Council, which supervises the Canadian and American
power grid.
</P>
<P>
   What disturbs California utility executives and regulators is
that this week's crisis has come even though none of the state's
power plants or transmission lines have failed and temperatures
around the state have been hot, but hardly extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, demand for power surged along with the
California economy. But utilities, fearing they would be unable to
recover their costs as the state moved away from regulations that
guaranteed them profits, stopped building power plants, leaving the
state's power supply simply no longer able to keep up with peak
demand, they said.
</P>
<P>
   California's electric industry has reached the ``ragged edge''
of failure, said Robert Glynn Jr., the chairman and chief executive
officer of the PG&AMP;E Corp., whose Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric unit
delivers electricity to more than 13 million people in Northern
California. ``There's just barely enough supply to go around.''
</P>
<P>
   So far this summer, the California Independent System Operator,
a nonprofit state-chartered agency that manages the electric grid,
has scrounged up just enough power each day to meet demand. So the
lights have stayed on, except for a blackout in San Francisco in
June related more to local transmission problems than the statewide
shortage.
</P>
<P>
   But with supplies exceptionally tight, the wholesale price of
power has skyrocketed in the state. That has caused electric bills
in San Diego, where the retail price of power now fluctuates
directly with the wholesale market, to more than double, stirring
consumer anger and calls for the industry to be reregulated.
</P>
<P>
   The supply of electricity is also tight in New York and in New
England, which have faced spot shortages this year. Nationally,
power reserves have steadily decreased since 1992, with the
electric industry in the midst of a complex transition from
regulation to competition. But a surge in plant construction seems
likely to ensure that supplies and reserves will begin to increase
next year in most of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system is tight around the country, but there's been an
enormous supply response,'' said Jeffrey Skilling, president of
Enron, the Houston company that is the world's leading trader of
electricity and natural gas. ``In the next year or two, in most
parts of the country, there will be surplus capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   Not in California, where a combination of politics and geography
has left the situation especially acute.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, with deregulation looming and Southern
California stuck in a recession, utilities stopped building, or
even designing, new plants. No new plants have been built in the
state for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   California's economy has surged in the last five years, a boom
led by Internet and high-technology companies, which are voracious
power users. And growth is even more vigorous in the Pacific
Northwest, Arizona and Nevada, making it harder for California to
import the power on which it has relied.
</P>
<P>
   All that adds up to a squeeze that gets tighter every time an
e-commerce company in Palo Alto turns on its servers, or a new
office building opens in Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   The California Energy Commission, a state agency that licenses
new power plants and predicts the state's energy demand, says
California has a 10 percent reserve margin for this summer's
expected peak electric demand, assuming all its plants and
transmission lines are working perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   But plants and transmission lines often run at less than their
theoretical capacity. As a result, the state's reserve power margin
has already fallen below 5 percent a half-dozen times on hot days
this summer, forcing the Independent System Operator to begin
cutting power to some big commercial customers. On Tuesday, the
tightest day yet this summer, the reserve margin fell as low as 3
percent at 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   So far this summer, the state's reserve has remained above the
critical 1.5 percent margin that would trigger an even more
critical condition in which the Independent System Operator orders
utilities to begin rotating blackouts. How long the blackouts would
last would depend on how much demand needs to be curtailed, said
Ron Low, a spokesman for PG&AMP;E. But Low said the utility would try
to keep blackouts to less than two hours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
