<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANDARD CHARTERED BANK ANNOUNCES GLOBAL CUTBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Britain)   By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Standard Chartered PLC, a London-based bank with most
of its operations in Asia, announced a severe global cutback
Wednesday that would eliminate 5,000 positions, or about 20 percent
of the staff, to help lower costs.
</P>
<P>
   Such cuts, which tend to increase a company's stock price, have
been made by other big banks worldwide in recent years. But
Standard Chartered's cutback was coupled with an announcement that
its earnings in the first half of the year had been lower than
expected, and the bank's shares fell more than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Standard Chartered said the cost-cutting, to include a
streamlining of its data-processing centers, would itself cost $715
million in severance and other expenses. It is projected to produce
savings around $105 million next year and $255 million annually
from 2003 onward.
</P>
<P>
   The bank said 6,000 jobs would be eliminated and 1,000 others
created. Of the special expenses, about $150 million will be used
to integrate Grindlays Bank, which Standard Chartered bought for
$1.3 billion in April as part of a planned Asian expansion. The
company said the purchase made it the leading international bank in
southern Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Though it does relatively little business in Britain, Standard
Chartered has operations in Hong Kong, Singapore, Malaysia, India
and other parts of Asia, where recovery from the financial crisis
of 1997-98 has benefited banks that do business there, like the
rival HSBC, by making it easier for individuals and companies to
repay loans.
</P>
<P>
   But, while HSBC reported a better-than-expected increase of 31
percent in its first-half profit this week, Standard Chartered's
profit increase seemed less robust, Investors compare the two banks
because of their similar emphasis on emerging markets _ shielding
them somewhat from the rough-and-tumble competition of retail
banking in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Standard Chartered said the Asian recovery had allowed it to set
aside less money for potential bad debts _ equivalent to $246
million compared with $360 million in the period last year. This
saving increased first half-profit 25 percent above the level of a
year earlier, to the equivalent of $346 million. Analysts, though,
had forecast a 31 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   Rana Talwar, the bank's chief executive, maintained that the job
cuts had been under consideration for 18 months and would affect
personnel throughout the bank's operations. The reductions matched
job cuts by banks in the United States, Britain and Germany,
reflecting competitive pressure that make traditional banking
operations less profitable.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the Bank of America has said that it will
reduce its work force by 9,000 to 10,000, and Dresdner Bank of
Germany is eliminating 5,000 jobs, or about 10 percent of its work
force. Barclays Bank recently stirred protests from British
customers and politicians with plans to close scores of small
branches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
