<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-FORD03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FORD IMPROVING AFTER STROKE
 &HT;    By JIM GALLOWAY
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Former President Gerald Ford was improving
Wednesday after being hospitalized for at least one stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians at the hospital where he was treated were peppered at
a news conference with questions about his diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   The 87-year-old Ford arrived at Hahnemann University Hospital
Wednesday morning under his own power, accompanied by his wife,
Betty, and U.S. Secret Service agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Ford is improving. He's much better than he was this
morning, when I evaluated him for a small brain-stem stroke,'' said
Dr. Robert Schwartzman, chief of neurology at the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartzman and other doctors said it was ``possible'' that Ford
might have suffered at least one other stroke in the days before,
while attending the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Ford was among three Republican presidents honored at the
convention on Tuesday, and the Ford family was included in the
opening prayer of Wednesday's session.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at the hospital said Ford can talk easily, but that his
speech is still slightly slurred and he is still experiencing some
problems with balance.
</P>
<P>
   They predicted the former president will regain both in full,
saying no serious brain damage has occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's saying he feels great, and wants to go home,'' said Dr.
Carol Thomas, director of the hospital's neurocare and stroke
program. Betty Ford, 82, has been staying in a room next to the
former president.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's traveling back and forth to his room,'' said Calvin
McDowell, a member of the president's advance staff. ``She's doing
excellent. She's the anchor that's very much in control of her
family. The Ford children, Michael, John, Steven, and Susan, were
keeping in touch by phone.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is expected to remain hospitalized for five to six days,
and has been put on anti-clotting medication.
</P>
<P>
   The diagnosis of stroke came on Ford's second visit to the
downtown hospital, which had been designated for treatment of VIPs
during the four-day convention.
</P>
<P>
   The former president and Michigan congressman first went to the
hospital after Tuesday evening's convention session and was
released within a half-hour with what doctors said at the time was
an acute sinus infection.
</P>
<P>
   While there, he complained to emergency room physicians of a
sharp pain in the right side of his face. ``All he was seeking was
pain relief for that night,'' said Dr. Wayne Satz, director of the
hospital's emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen Klasko, the hospital's clinical dean, said Ford's
condition changed after he was treated and released, and that the
first diagnosis was appropriate based on the symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartzmann said that on Wednesday morning, when Ford returned
with his wife, Betty, she gave doctors more information about her
husband's symptoms in previous days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family is very satisfied with his care,'' said Klasko.
</P>
<P>
   Ford aide McDowell said ``virtually everyone imaginable,''
including the White House, had called the hospital to inquire after
the former president, who brought the country from the brink of a
constitutional crisis following the resignation of President
Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell said Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who accepts the
Republican nomination for president Thursday night, had asked to
visit, but all visitors were being turned away.
</P>
<P>
   Aides and a national television audience may have watched the
former president's symptoms unfold.
</P>
<P>
   During a C-SPAN interview Tuesday morning, Ford appeared
confused at times. He answered a question about racial diversity by
talking about Michigan's diverse economy, and a question about Iran
by talking about onions.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in a CNN interview, the former president appeared to slur
his speech as he rebuked President Clinton for entering the
campaign fray by attacking Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Simmons, a special assistant to Ford at his home in Palm
Desert, Calif., told the Associated Press that he was concerned
after watching the former president on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could tell right away something was wrong. His speech was
not as sharp and clear and it normally is. I told my wife it looked
like he had a stroke or something,'' Simmons said.
</P>
<P>
   &Cx1f; The stroke occurred in the back of the brain, and affected the
area that controls balance and such activities as swallowing.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is officially listed in ``serious and improving'' condition
in the hospital's neural intensive care unit.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said the former president suffered from no other health
ailments, other than a thickening of the arteries often associated
with aging.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartzmann said Ford took the news of his stroke in a ``very
calm, very collected'' manner.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Brain Attack Coalition: http://www.stroke-site.org
</P>
<P>
   American Heart Association:
http://www.americanheart.org/Heart_and_Stroke_A_Z_Guide/stroke.html
</P>
<P>
   Jim Galloway's e-mail address is jgalloway(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
