<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0971 &Cx1f; tad-z
a p BC-CVN-FORD-OBIT-HOLD-CO     08-02 1428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-FORD-OBIT-HOLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOLD - ADVANCE OBIT FOR GERALD R. FORD
 &HT;    NOT FOR PUBLICATION
 &HT;    Eds: This is an advance obit for Gerald Ford. Do not run unless
he dies.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gerald R. Ford, an unelected president of the
United States who restored stability and honor to the White House
amid Watergate scandals, died (PUT DAY AND LOCATION HERE) at the
age of (PUT AGE HERE).
</P>
<P>
   Ford became America's 38th president during the depths of the
Watergate affair, taking office upon the resignation of President
Richard Nixon. He lost the presidency in a close election two years
later to Jimmy Carter, then the former governor of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Ford automatically became president at around 11:30 a.m. on Aug.
9, 1974, the moment Nixon's resignation letter reached Secretary of
State Henry Kissinger.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Ford was sworn in by then-Chief Justice Warren E.
Burger and, in a televised speech from the White House East Room,
made the statement the country longed to hear and the one for which
he would always be remembered:
</P>
<P>
   ``My fellow Americans, our long national nightmare is over. Our
constitution works. Our great Republic is a government of laws and
not of men. Here the people rule . . .''
</P>
<P>
   And before a month was out, he took his most controversial
action as president, granting Nixon a ``full, free and absolute
pardon. . . .for all offenses against the United States which he. .
. .has committed or may have committed'' during his years as
president.
</P>
<P>
   The pardon, which Ford knew would stir deep anger among many
Americans and partisan criticism in Congress, was in many ways
typical of a quiet, dogged politician known for plowing ahead even
when he knew his actions would be unpopular.
</P>
<P>
   Years after leaving office, Ford, an avidly partisan Republican,
would declare that the president he admired most was an equally
partisan Democrat, Harry Truman. And the two would share a
reputation _ as men who navigated through public life on the basis
of directions from internal moral compasses, rather than according
to opinion polls or a perception of political climate.
</P>
<P>
   Born Leslie Lynch King Jr., son of Leslie and Dorothy Layer
Gardner King, on July 14, 1913, in Omaha, Neb., Ford grew up in
Michigan. His parents separated two weeks after his birth and his
mother took him to Grand Rapids to live with her parents.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 1, 1916, Dorothy King married Gerald R. Ford, a Grand
Rapids paint salesman, and they began calling her son, Gerald R.
Ford Jr., although his name was not legally changed until Dec. 3,
1935. He was 14 years old before he knew that Gerald R. Ford was
not his biological father.
</P>
<P>
   He attended the University of Michigan and was a star lineman on
the university's national championship football teams in 1932 and
1933. In 1934, he was named the team's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   In a column he wrote a year ago for The New York Times _ in
which he went against the mainstream of his party and spoke out for
affirmative action _ Ford recalled a game between his Michigan
Wolverines and the Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets in which the Atlanta
school ``reputedly'' wanted the Michigan team's only black player
dropped from the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Michigan team were adamant that their black
teammate take the field, Ford wrote, but in the end, he chose not
to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``His sacrifice led me to question how educational
administrators could capitulate to raw prejudice,'' Ford wrote.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving his B.A. degree in political science and
economics at Michigan, he turned down pro football offers from the
Detroit Lions and the Green Bay Packers to enter the Yale Law
School, serving as an assistant football and boxing coach.
</P>
<P>
   Two future U.S. senators, William Proxima of Wisconsin and
Robert Tat Jr. of Ohio, played on Yale football teams he helped
coach.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from law school, Ford joined the Navy and
served during most of the major campaigns in the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   His biography on the Gerald Ford Library Web site notes that his
``closest call with death came not as a result of enemy fire,
however, but during a vicious typhoon in the Philippine Sea in
December 1944. He came within inches of being swept overboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Discharged as a lieutenant commander in 1946, Ford returned to
Grand Rapids. In 1948, he decided to challenge the incumbent
Republican for Congress and won by a large margin.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Representatives would be his political home for the
next 25 years. He served on the Public Works and Appropriations
committees and became House minority leader in 1965, unseating Rep.
Charles Hillock of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   His reputation as a social conservative grew as he led
Republican opposition to many of the liberal programs of
then-President Lyndon B. Johnson between 1965 and 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Irked at Ford, Johnson was quoted as saying the House minority
leader had played in too many football games ``without his
helmet.''
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson also showed his regard for Ford by appointing him to
the Warren Commission, which investigated the assassination of the
late President John F. Kennedy. Ford became the last surviving
member of the commission, which was headed by then Chief Justice
Earl Warren.
</P>
<P>
   Ford supported Nixon in the 1968 and 1972 elections but never
realized his goal of becoming speaker of the House, where
Republicans failed to gain a majority during his service there.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 12, 1973, following the resignation of Vice President
Spiry Agene, who pleaded no contest to tax evasion charges, Nixon
announced that he would nominate Ford for vice president. It was
the first time the Constitution's 25th Amendment, providing for
filling an empty vice president's office, was invoked.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were not unanimously supportive, with many calling
Ford a man of mediocre ability and limited vision, but he was
overwhelmingly confirmed by both the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Proxima observed that although he thought the new vice president
had been wrong on almost every issue, ``he is a man that the
country may be looking for. He has the kind of wholesome sincerity,
the kind of loyal consistency that many voters may be looking for.
. . .''
</P>
<P>
   Only slightly over a year later, after succeeding Nixon, Ford
would nominate Nelson A. Rockefeller, one of America's richest men,
to succeed himself as vice president. For the first time in its
history, the country had both a president and a vice president
chosen under the 25th Amendment, rather than a national election.
</P>
<P>
   Ford survived two assassination attempts as president. Both
times, the assailants were women _ Lynette ``Squeaky'' Forme and
Sara Jane Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably the most athletic president in history, he acquired the
image of a stumbling klutz, thanks in part to a new television
show, ``Saturday Night Live,'' on which comedian Chevy Chase poked
fun, week-after-week, at the president because of a pair of events
that might otherwise have faded from notice: Ford's stumbling on
the steps of Air Force One and an errant golf shot that hit a
spectator on the head.
</P>
<P>
   When the two met at an event, Chase observed, ``You're a very
funny president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a very funny suburb,'' Ford snapped back, referring to
the Washington suburb, Chevy Chase, Md.
</P>
<P>
   But the klutz image and the Nixon pardon were part of heavy
political baggage Ford took into the 1976 election, and with Sen.
Robert Dole of Kansas as his running mate, he lost one of the
closest presidential races in U.S. history to Carter.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening line of his inaugural address, Carter recognized
Gerald Ford's legacy: ``For myself and for our nation, I want to
thank my predecessor for all he has done to heal our land.'' Seated
behind him, Ford wept quietly.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving office Gerald Ford continued to speak out on
public affairs, lecturing in over 170 colleges and writing numerous
opinion pieces for newspapers and magazines. His autobiography, ``A
Time to Heal,'' was published in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   The Gerald R. Ford Foundation sponsors a pair of national
journalism awards, one for stories reporting on the presidency and
the other for stories about national defense issues. Winners in
2000 were Carl Cannon of the National Journal for stories about the
presidency and Russell Carollo of the Dayton Daily News for writing
about defense issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford Library web site can be accessed at:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.lbjlib.utexas.edu/ford/
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
