<HEADER>
A0974 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BC-ISLAND-SUIT-HNS-HN     08-02 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-ISLAND-SUIT-HNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BC-PADRE-SUIT-HNS  
JURY SAYS LAWYER SWINDLED MEXICAN FAMILY 60 YEARS AGO
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ A Wall Street lawyer swindled members of a
pioneer family out of oil and gas profits he made after buying a
coastal island from them more than six decades ago, a jury said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After four days of deliberations helped along with a calculator,
an all-Latino jury found that New York City lawyer Gilbert Kerlin
acted with malice when he conspired to deny members of the
Mexican-American Balli clan their share of more than $36 million in
mineral rights from Padre Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we have opened the door for a lot of Hispanic people in
South Texas,'' said Pearl Balli Mancillas of Brownsville, who has
pursued the claim in and out of court for 25 years. ``I feel really
good we were right all this time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more than the money,'' said Rebecca Gomez Sexton, an
heir who represented herself. ``It's the preservation of the family
name, our heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   But a huge amount of money is potentially at stake in this case,
and in a number of others arising over old Spanish land grants in
South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Balli clan and other pioneer Mexican families who settled
South Texas have long claimed they were dispossessed of their land
_ either at gunpoint or by courthouse chicanery _ after waves of
Anglo settlers poured into the region following the war with
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The Ballis are seeking $11 million in oil royalties, past
interest and attorney's fees from Kerlin and his oil companies.
Kerlin, now 90 and retired, took the stand for eight days during
the six weeks of testimony and defended his dealings with members
of the Balli clan, some of whom were paid as little as $10 for
their land.
</P>
<P>
   The jury's 10-2 verdict awarded the Ballis almost $1.2 million
in compensatory damages and gave their legal team $1.5 million.
State District Judge Pat McDowell, a visiting judge from Dallas,
told the jury to return Monday when they are expected to take up
the issue of punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it! I felt confident the whole time,'' said a joyous
Alma Santos, the owner of a suburban Houston beauty parlor whose
mother, 80-year-old Delores Balli, is one of the plaintiffs. ``This
is history, and we certainly put a chapter in the book.''
</P>
<P>
   The 278 plaintiffs in the historic case are descendants of an
18th century priest, Nicolas Balli, who was given the deserted
coastal island by King Carlos III of Spain in 1765.
</P>
<P>
   Still awaiting their day in court are another 200 members of the
Balli clan who intervened in the case and will have their claims to
the oil and gas wealth of Padre Island heard in a later phase of
the trial, the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an isolated case. It just didn't happen to the
Ballis. It happened to the Longorias, to the Hinojosas, the
Trevinos, it happened to a lot of people,'' said Pearl Balli
Mancillas.
</P>
<P>
   Also on McDowells's court docket is a pending land dispute in
Kenedy County, filed by 1,000 Balli heirs. Balli heirs say leases
filed in South Texas courts indicate that land, once part of the
King Ranch, was never sold by the family. Some of that branch of
the Balli family tree came to hear Wednesday's jury finding in a
show of support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more battles to come ahead,'' vowed Maria Isabel
Perales of Mission, a Balli heir and a plaintiff in the Kenedy
County dispute.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Padre Island property, it was 1938 when a
young Gilbert Kerlin was dispatched to Brownsville to buy the
narrow barrier island on instructions from his uncle, Frederick
Gilbert. But Kerlin ultimately wound up with the property, which
today is a major tourist draw dotted with hotels and condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   The land acquisition was the first case for Kerlin, a recent
graduate of Harvard Law School. He tracked down 60 members of the
Balli clan and paid to execute 12 deeds that conveyed the island to
the lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Court records showed that 22 members of the family were each
paid $10 cash by Kerlin, who won't reveal what the others were
paid. The deeds gave the Ballis a share of future royalties on the
oil and gas beneath the island, but Kerlin never handed the money
over. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; During the trial, an oil expert hired by the Ballis testified
that Kerlin earned $36.6 million in royalties from the properties,
and the Balli share should have been $6.3 million, plus interest.
</P>
<P>
   Kerlin, retired from Shearman &AMP; Sterling, one of the nation's
oldest and most prestigious Wall Street firms, was not present for
the verdict. Citing a gag order, his attorneys would not say if he
planned an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Knopp, an author and history professor at the University
of Texas-Brownsville, said he was ``a little surprised'' at the
verdict because many observers felt the evidence was weak.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there was a feeling the Balli cause was helped by a
sympathetic South Texas jury, he said. And while injustices
occurred, Knopp noted many Mexican-American families lost their
holdings in South Texas because they chose to sell or were unable
to pay property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``These other families are claiming they were somehow cheated
out of their land some 150 years ago,'' said Knopp, referring to
the period when Texas became a state. ``And certainly there were
cases where that happened, but there were a lot of other cases
where economic circumstances, cultural misunderstandings, led to
the gradual loss of land belonging to Tejanos.''
</P>
<P>
   The Balli case, filed in 1993, was first dismissed when
attorneys for the family failed to pursue it. Then it was revived
by Houston attorney Hector H. Cardenas Jr., who was part of the
four-lawyer team who tried a case which many predict will make
legal history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, a lot of eyes were watching this case,'' said Rob
Johnson, an Austin attorney on the Balli legal team.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
