<SLUG> BC-SCI-MEDICAL-DEVICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA CRACKS DOWN ON RECYCLED MEDICAL DEVICES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Minn.)   By KENNETH CHANG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration said Wednesday that it would
begin requiring that recycled medical devices originally intended
to be used only once meet the same regulatory standards that they
did when manufactured.
</P>
<P>
   The requirements apply both to companies that clean and
repackage the devices for subsequent uses and hospitals that do the
work themselves. The practice of reusing disposable devices,
including catheters, syringes and biopsy needles, has spread in
recent years as a cost-cutting move. It is impossible to say
exactly how widespread the practice is, but recycled devices are
believed to account for only a small portion of the medical device
market.
</P>
<P>
   The major third-party reprocessing companies welcomed the
regulations, saying they would dispel lingering doubt about the
safety of the recycled devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's a good thing,'' said Ronald Nordquist, president
of SterilMed Inc. of Minneapolis, a medical device reprocessor.
``It should force people that are substandard out of this
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Device manufacturers have argued that the reuse of devices
designed to be disposable can pose a health risk to patients.
</P>
<P>
   The new guidelines do not go far enough, said Josephine
Torrente, president of the Association of Disposal Device
Manufacturers. ``The policy has some significant gaps in it,''
Torrente said.
</P>
<P>
   Device reprocessors say the manufacturers' concerns are related
more to competition and profits than to patient safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an economic issue for them,'' said Pamela Furman,
executive director of the Association of Medical Device
Reprocessors. ``Their objective from the beginning has to make
reprocessing go away.''
</P>
<P>
   The reprocessors' association estimates that the annual sales of
their members now total $20 million, a small fraction of the
multibillion-dollar medical device market. Boston Scientific, one
of the major manufacturers of single-use devices, had sales of
nearly $3 billion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals have cleaned and reused disposable devices for about
20 years, said Larry Spears, an enforcement official with the FDA's
Center for Devices and Radiological Health. Companies specializing
in the cleaning and repackaging of single-use devices first
appeared about a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Stories of reused catheters that broke inside patients during
surgery led to hearings in Congress on the issue last year and a
review by the General Accounting Office.
</P>
<P>
   FDA officials said they started reviewing the issue last year,
because more complicated types of disposable devices were now being
reused. ``We questioned in our own minds whether those could be
effectively reprocessed,'' Spears said. ``We felt there was a need
to look more closely about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new guidelines, reprocessors and hospitals that clean
and reuse devices must register with the FDA, and the agency, which
has been inspecting reprocessing companies, will also begin
inspecting the hospital reprocessing operations.
</P>
<P>
   If a device required an agency review before being introduced to
the market, the reprocessed device would have to undergo the same
review. Depending on the nature of the device, recyclers have six
to 18 months to submit safety data to the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers' association says a gap exists in the
guidelines because if a new device does not require FDA approval,
the recycled version also escapes review. A biopsy forceps, a
device used to collect a small tissue sample for cancer tests, is
exempt, but Torrente said studies had shown that forceps were
particularly difficult to clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite that, they will be reused in patients without FDA
review,'' Torrente said. ``That's an enormous gap in patient
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Torrente said a second concern was that the FDA had not yet
clarified what data it would require in its reviews. ``Patients
deserve to have this review standard made transparent,'' she said.
``We're asking for regulations that will ban all unsafe
reprocessing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
