u p BC-GOP-NJ-FRANKS-NYT &LR;      08-02 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-NJ-FRANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOB WHO FROM WHERE? BATTLING OBSCURITY, UPHILL ALL THE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Nev., Fla., Neb., Mass., Ariz., Calif., Texas, Conn.,
Ky.)   By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Sen. Mitch McConnell, the chairman of the
Republican Senate campaign, was introducing the party's candidates
for open seats at a luncheon here Wednesday. He pointed to John
Ensign of Nevada, Bill McCollum of Florida and Don Stenberg of
Nebraska, then searched the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is anyone else here?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Franks!'' shouted the men from New Jersey, sitting near
their overlooked friend.
</P>
<P>
   Franks has had that kind of week.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Convention was supposed to be a chance
for Franks, a four-term congressman from northern New Jersey with a
low profile even in his home state, to grab some needed attention
for his underdog Senate campaign against Jon S. Corzine, the
Democratic multimillionaire who spent $35 million of his own money
in the primary alone.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, when Franks was to give his three-minute speech
from the convention floor, the daily schedule had him listed as
Gary Franks of Connecticut, who is not even a congressman anymore.
Franks humbly began his remarks _ a biting attack on Corzine, who
he said ``makes Ted Kennedy look like Barry Goldwater'' _ by
acknowledging his own obscurity: ``You don't know me, but you
probably have heard of my opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks' turn at the podium might have received a fair amount of
attention in the New Jersey news media, always hungry for a local
angle. But about the time he was speaking, Sen. Robert Torricelli
was abandoning the Democratic race for New Jersey governor. So
Franks found himself quoted, if at all, in stories about other
people.
</P>
<P>
   At least his fund-raising efforts have not been fruitless.
Monday night, Franks was the guest of honor at a $1,000-a-person
party _ all that for hot dogs and an open bar _ aboard a Cape May,
N.J., ferry that had made a detour to Camden, N.J. The event raised
more than $100,000, Franks said.
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday morning, Franks was introduced by former Sen. Bob
Dole at a mixer of big-ticket contributors organized by the
Republican Leadership Council, a group that helps finance moderate
candidates. ``We just picked up another 15 to 25 checks,'' Franks
said as he emerged from the hotel suite.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Franks and his finance director, Laura Slomka,
have been networking with party rainmakers in California,
Connecticut, Florida and elsewhere to hold fund-raisers for the
Franks campaign in the next several weeks. The first two, in Dallas
and Houston, will be given by Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The next month or so will be critical for Franks, whose aides
say he must raise $8 million to $10 million to stand a chance
against Corzine. So at every opportunity, he is reminding listeners
of Corzine's liberal platform and even more liberal campaign
spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the lens through which people outside of New Jersey are
looking at this race,'' he said. ``I can get up there and blah-blah
about the marriage penalty, or I can get their attention for 180
seconds and establish the stark contrast between Jon Corzine and
Bob Franks, the Republican they've never heard of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 2035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0404 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0978 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-CARMIKE0803-COX     08-02 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARMIKE0803-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Debt-laden Carmike reels on industry woes
 &HT;    By Robert Luke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Nervous investors Wednesday unloaded shares of
Columbus, Ga.,-based Carmike Cinemas, causing the stock to lose
more than half its value.
</P>
<P>
   The frenzied selling came a day after the company disclosed that
one of its lenders blocked it from paying $9 million in interest
due Tuesday on senior subordinated notes. The company, which
borrowed heavily to finance new theaters, said it will try to
renegotiate the terms of its loans and look for new sources of
financing.
</P>
<P>
   Carmike's shares fell to a 52-week low of $1.31 before finishing
at $1.50, down $1.75, or 53.8 percent. The shares had traded as
high as $33.06 two years ago. Nearly 1.5 million shares changed
hands, or about 27 times average daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   Carmike officials, who couldn't be reached for comment, sought
to reassure investors. In a filing Tuesday with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, the company said it should be able to generate
positive cash flow and meet its current debt obligations during the
next 12 to 24 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not currently experiencing liquidity problems, and we
are hopeful that our bank lenders will work with us to establish
reasonable covenants that are more consistent with the economic
downturn in our industry and the company's expected financial
performance,'' Chief Financial Officer Martin Durant said in the
filing.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure the company will be able to pay its debts, Carmike
said it will eliminate new movie theater development, curtail
renovation and expansion of existing theaters and theater
acquisitions, increase management control over expenditures and
aggressively sell surplus assets.
</P>
<P>
   The company had planned to spend about $22 million this year to
build, expand and renovate theaters. Last year it spent about $170
million, opening 24 theaters with 313 screens, adding 39
auditoriums to existing theaters and retrofitting another 59
auditoriums.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the level of last year's spending was stiffer
competition. The opening of new multiplexes by competitors _ with
digital surround sound and stadium seating _ threatened to draw
audiences away from Carmike's older facilities.
</P>
<P>
   To finance its projects, Carmike borrowed. Long-term debt
totaled $466.3 million as of Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Box office strength helped to fuel the expansion, not only at
Carmike but other theater chains as well. But ticket sales lately
have come under pressure, putting many of the companies in a
financial bind.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, during the last three weeks in June we saw a
sharp downturn in box office receipts as a result of unexpectedly
weak and disappointing film performance as compared to the prior
year,'' said Michael W. Patrick, Carmike's president and chief
executive, in the SEC filing.
</P>
<P>
   He added that while the company is ``continuing to actively
negotiate with the bank lenders, the company is considering all of
the options available to it.''
</P>
<P>
   One analyst identified Wachovia Corp. as the senior lender that
blocked the interest payment Carmike was about to make on its
notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wachovia is making a concerted effort to scrub their credit
reserves, asking, `What's at risk?''' PaineWebber analyst
Christopher Dixon told Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry has excess capacity, and the stocks have been in
a free fall,'' Dixon said. ``This isn't a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman at Wachovia, Vince Scanlon, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Winston-Salem, N.C.-based Wachovia, which has significant
operations in Georgia, last month posted a 43 percent drop in
second-quarter profit. That's because it boosted its reserves
against bad loans by $200 million. The parent of Wachovia Bank said
slower economic growth was making it harder for some corporate
customers to keep up loan payments.
</P>
<P>
   Nonperforming assets as of June 30 were $298.7 million, up $52.6
million from the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Carmike Cinemas was organized in April 1982 after the leveraged
buyout of its predecessor, Martin Theatres, by Carmike's present
management.
</P>
<P>
   Carmike's officers and directors, including the Patrick family,
control the company through their ownership of Class B shares,
which aren't publicly traded. The Class A shares are listed on the
New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
