<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ STUMBLES UNDER HIGH-TECH WEIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Nasdaq stock market stumbled Wednesday as
skittish investors sought safety in blue chip stocks or headed for
the sidelines waiting for Friday's report on the job market in
July.
</P>
<P>
   Although the decline in the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite
index was modest, 27.06 points, or 0.7 percent, to 3,658.46,
analysts found little reason for optimism. They said that
high-technology shares, especially semiconductor companies, were
prone to summertime slumps and that stocks carrying high prices
relative to earnings seem most vulnerable to rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still not a very high level of conviction that the
economy is slowing enough that the Federal Reserve can stop tapping
the brakes,'' said Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer at the
First Albany Corp. The Fed, which has pushed short-term rates up
six times in the last 13 months, is scheduled to meet next on Aug.
22. The government's tally of early-summer employment and other
economic reports will figure in the Fed's decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 80.58 points, or 0.8
percent, to 10,687.53. Hewlett-Packard jumped 4|, to 112{, and IBM
increased 4[, to 114 11/16. Exxon Mobil rose 1{, to 81 7/16; and
Home Depot rose 1[, to 53[.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index gained 0.60 of a point, to
1,438.70.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were buoyed by news that sales of new homes fell for a
third consecutive month to the lowest pace in 2{ years and by
comments from William Poole, the president of the St. Louis Federal
Reserve Bank, whose benign view of inflation risks implied that the
Fed might be able to forgo further rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's poor performance seemed to cast a pall over the
market in general. Dell Computer skidded 2, to 39 9/16, after being
downgraded by an analyst at U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray, who
questioned projected revenue growth. Cisco Systems, the biggest
drag on the S&AMP;P 500, fell 2\, to 60 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous amount of negative sentiment,'' said
Matthew W. Johnson, chief Nasdaq trader at Lehman Brothers. ``Some
people are taking money off the table,'' he added, while others are
switching into more defensive positions, such as provided by
established companies in oils, pharmaceuticals and utilities.
</P>
<P>
   While investors hope the Fed can rein in the strong economy to
avoid inflation, the risk is that profit growth will be lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street's consensus forecast that S&AMP;P 500 operating
earnings will grow 12 percent to 15 percent annually is more than a
stretch,'' a Chase Securities report stated this week.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, investors displayed a hearty appetite for new
issues, more than three dozen of which are slated to reach the
market this week. Floware Wireless, Genaissance Pharmaceuticals,
California Pizza Kitchen, Opnet Technologies and Entravision
Communications all climbed to handsome premiums in their first day
of trading.
</P>
<P>
   One of the day's biggest winners was the Sapient Corp., which
jumped 16 15/16, to 120 13/16, after announcing
better-than-expected earnings and a 2-for-1 stock split.
</P>
<P>
   A prominent casualty was Cigna, which dropped 4 11/16, to 96
9/16, after it said earnings growth was being hurt by problems in
disability insurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
