<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0983 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SNAPPLE-AD-COLUMN-NYT     08-02 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNAPPLE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SWEET UNION OF SOFT DRINK AND CONFECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a critical report released last year, the Center for Science
in the Public Interest referred to soft drinks as ``liquid candy.''
Now there's a minitrend toward producing what might be called solid
soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is Snapple Beverages, a unit of the Triarc Cos.,
which is introducing a line of Snapple candy this fall. The concept
came from two entrepreneurs who thought that the unusual Snapple
flavors _ like peach tea, Mango Madness and pink lemonade _ might
translate well into candy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the image of Snapple, which was fun and quirky and
innovative and different, lent itself to the industry,'' said Scott
Semel, who founded Cody Kramer Imports, based in Blauvelt, N.Y.,
with Reid Chase. ``Most candy licenses are event-driven or
character-driven, and not brand-driven. We solicited three or four
brands with our idea, and Snapple was our first choice because it
made the most sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Other companies are pursuing similar paths. Jelly Belly makes
three jelly bean flavors derived from soft drinks: Dr Pepper, A&AMP;W
root beer and A&AMP;W cream soda. All three brands are owned by Cadbury
Schweppes. ``It is a wave of the future,'' said Susan Fussell, a
spokeswoman for the National Confectioners Association. Other
examples include Hi-C fruit chews, made by Brach Confections, and
Sunkist fruit chews, which are produced by the Ben Myerson Candy
Co., she said.
</P>
<P>
   The soft-drink industry and the candy industry have both
experienced flat to little growth over the last several years, and
more manufacturers are trying to increase their sales in
convenience stores, so cross-marketing may have special appeal. On
the other hand, candy brands have been crossing over for some time
to other food categories; Snickers became an ice cream confection
several years ago, and other Mars brands turn up as ingredients in
McDonald's desserts and other ice cream concepts.
</P>
<P>
   Cody Kramer approached Triarc in June and fairly quickly
obtained a licensing agreement. The companies would not disclose
the terms, but, typically, brand owners receive a percentage of
sales from licensing their names.
</P>
<P>
   The candy has evolved into several forms. Snapplets are hard
candies packaged in Lifesavers-style rolls, as well as in bags.
Then there are Snapple Beans, which closely resemble jelly beans,
and Snapple Fruits, which are reminiscent of Gummi bears. A fourth
product, Snapple Whirls, is also similar to Gummi bears.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits are abundant, both for the licensee and the brand
owner, Semel said. ``It raises brand awareness in places where it
hasn't been,'' he said. ``You could be checking out of a grocery
store and see a Snapplet roll at the counter, and it will visually
enhance the brand in your mind. There's an intangible value to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the object-permanence factor. ``You drink a drink
and it's gone in 30 seconds,'' Chase said. ``But a bag of candy is
going to stay with you. You'll have it in your house or on your
desk, and it's going to be in front of you for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cody Kramer began as an importer of Lindt chocolate, pastilles
and other luxury products. Then the company ventured into
private-label candy manufacturing, producing tins of hard candy for
clients like Old Navy and Williams Sonoma. But those categories
represented the fringes of the candy business, and the founders
wanted to find a third area to develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when the idea of licensing came into our heads,'' Semel
said. Other brands he wanted, but didn't get, include Ben &AMP; Jerry's
Homemade Inc., the Vermont ice cream company that was acquired by
Unilever PLC earlier this year for $326 million. Efforts to license
brands like Cherry Garcia and Chunky Monkey went nowhere, Semel
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, ``Snapple has been tremendous to work with,''
Chase said. ``They are constantly coming up with ideas for
promotions, how we can work with their beverage distribution. A
pizza parlor may have a Snapple machine, but there is not typically
candy in there.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Semel expect their company's sales to grow to $40 million
next year, up from $22 million this year, with about $12 million to
$15 million of next year's sales coming from Snapple candy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great idea,'' said Fussell, the spokeswoman for the
confectioners group. ``It combines two things that are already
popular, candy and beverages.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
