<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news
file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; DADA DEAREST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -- The Society for the Prevention of Abuse Toward  &UR; Zeppo Marx &LR; ,
of Rochester, N.Y., told Wireless Flash that August is Zeppo Marx
Awareness Month.
</P>
<P>
   -- In response to a letter to the editor in The Chronicle
detailing the energy-saving benefits of turning a toaster on its
side while making toast, four members of the Institute for the
Advancement of Rotational Studies have submitted a written report
on a related investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IARS found,'' says a letter signed by  &UR; Steven Miller &LR; ,
 &UR; John &LR;  and  &UR; Laurie Durand &LR;  and  &UR; David Strauch &LR; , ``that sport utility
vehicles that had been turned on their sides produced measurable
savings over those that had not been rotated.'' The benefits:
better fuel efficiency, less fuel consumption, fewer traffic
fatalities, lowered gas emissions. ``Moreover, when rotated SUVs
were de-rotated, these benefits were reversed, confirming earlier
results.''
</P>
<P>
   -- San Francisco actor  &UR; Brian Freeman &LR; , an African American,
received an e-mail notice from a casting agent for a Los Angeles
audition for a Northwest Airlines print ad. ``We are looking for
authentic full races. ... Korean, Thai, Filipino, Afro-American,
Chinese, Japanese. Must be attractive, clean-cut, have a business
look and own a business suit. Again, just be true to their ethnic
race (100%).''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the product?'' asks Freeman. ``Separate but equal
business class?''
</P>
<P>
   -- Two of the writers of ``Scary Movie,'' a spoof on such scary
movies as ``Scream,'' have been hired by Independent Pictures'
 &UR; Cary Woods &LR; , who made ``Scream,'' for a ``teen movie genre''
spoof. A spoof of the spoof-writing business may loom ahead, says
inside.com.
</P>
<P>
   -- SelfCare, which sells various products purported to help with
stress, is offering 25 percent off to residents of Philadelphia and
Los Angeles during the political conventions.
</P>
<P>
   -- Reading that  &UR; Charlton Heston &LR;  was recently treated for
alcohol abuse,  &UR; Bob Lacey &LR;  foresees a new organization: AA-AAA-NRA,
for alcoholics who need rides to gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -- Listening to Monday night's NPR convention coverage,  &UR; Lisa &LR; 
 &UR; Aliferis &LR;  heard  &UR; Melissa Block &LR;  interviewing Rep.  &UR; Henry Hyde &LR; ,
R-Ill., after which anchor  &UR; Scott Simon &LR;  thanked him for the
segment. Hyde thanked Simon in return and said he'd enjoyed meeting
``your charming young lady.'' Both Simon and Block laughed, and
Simon respectfully told him that NPR calls her a ``good reporter.''
Block added that Hyde was wearing a nice tie, and Simon noted it
flattered his eye color.
</P>
<P>
   -- The spa that ministered to  &UR; Lynne Cheney &LR;  denies the
Washington Post's report that she's a  &UR; Hillary &LR; -hair wannabe, and a
reader says the word on  &UR; Iman &LR; 's belly is her husband's name in
Arabic. An Arabic reader confirms that the word -- read right to
left in Arabic -- could be a calligraphic  &UR; Bowie &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   -- Jump magazine reports that  &UR; Britney Spears &LR;  has installed a
tanning bed on her tour bus.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; INSIDE THE ROADSHOW &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An ``Antiques Roadshow'' insider says that  &UR; Dan Rather &LR;  and a
``60 Minutes II'' crew came to Tulsa, Okla., to film the show for a
segment, and many of the appraisers were worried that some kind of
expose is planned.
</P>
<P>
   Most people interviewed thought his questions rather inane, says
the source, but still worried that it was a setup. ``They have sent
crews to about three shows, and it is possible they have some
negative material they are holding back while they gather footage
and quotes to round it out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Roadshow,'' PBS' most successful series ever, no longer has
thousands of people waiting in line because it uses Ticketmaster to
distribute a set number of free tickets about six weeks before it
comes to town. This, the insider writes, is ``just as well, since
we were turning away up to 15,000 people in some cities, causing
near fits in the downtown streets of America's heartland.''
</P>
