<HEADLINE>
BEHIND THE SCENES, OIL INDUSTRY'S RED CAVANEY IS RUNNING THE SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Wednesday, Aug. 2, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADV: With photo of Cavaney (NNS6). 
 By MILES BENSON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Big business and big money are working overtime
at the Republican convention _ in all the obvious places, and some
not so obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Big-time Washington lobbyists are behind the scenes doing the
nuts-and-bolts work that keeps the convention running smoothly, and
their clients happy.
</P>
<P>
   Take Red Cavaney, for example. His name _ it's Red on his
business cards _ does not appear on the official list of the senior
convention management team. But behind the scenes, he is the man
running the public convention show.
</P>
<P>
   As director of official proceedings for the 2000 Republican
National Convention, Cavaney is one of a cadre of powerful business
representatives who show up every four years to play important, but
very low-key, roles at the convention, said Republican National
Chairman Jim Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   Cavaney is president and chief executive officer of the
Washington-based American Petroleum Institute, the oil industry's
trade association and lobbying arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the people who put the program together, see that
the convention speakers are brought in and rehearsed and the sound
system is up and running,'' Nicholson said. He said he doesn't even
know how Cavaney got the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just one of the volunteers,'' Nicholson said. ``Most of
them have been doing it for a long time. This is maybe his fifth
convention.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, it's my eighth convention, but my fourth as director
of official proceedings,'' said Cavaney, who heads a team of 200
volunteers who work behind the curtains of the convention stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the people who take the program concepts and we
implement everything, actually direct the show, what occurs on the
podium,'' Cavaney said.
</P>
<P>
   Gavel to gavel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work with the participants and speakers, walk them through
what they will be doing, help develop their speeches, work with
teleprompters and speech coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Cavaney's chores here reinforce his close contacts and access to
a lot of important Republican officeholders. And his convention
role is further evidence of the close linkage between the oil
industry and the Republican ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush was an oil company executive before he
entered politics. Dick Cheney, his choice for vice president, is
president of Halliburton, a huge international oil services
corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Cavaney's oil industry credentials are irrelevant, Nicholson
insists. ``He could be in the garment business and still be running
official proceedings. He's a guy who was brought up through the
system who was once a junior helper who eventually took over the
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Cavaney, 57, served on the White House staff under Presidents
Richard Nixon, Gerald Ford and Ronald Reagan. He took over the
American Petroleum Institute in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Cavaney downplays the strategic usefulness of his position for
his lobbying activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was doing this even before I was a lobbyist,'' he said. ``I
do it because I just believe people should participate in the
public policy process, vote, and give their time and energy.''
</P>
<P>
   He admits, ``It's a wonderful opportunity to network and to see
old friends, but I'd not say it has any direct effect'' in future
lobbying activities. Cavaney and other veteran Washington lobbyists
he sees pitching in here already know most of the public officials
they are working with.
</P>
<P>
   But some critics say there is much more to it than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are cementing the relationships that are going to be
useful when everybody gets back to Washington,'' said Larry
Makinson, director of the Center for Responsive Politics, an expert
on the role of connections between money and politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are seeing inside the convention is the public
campaign, the scripted campaign. What we are not seeing outside the
hall is the phantom campaign where the real action is taking place
connecting politicians with lobbyists and fund-raisers. That's not
open to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Other big behind-the-scenes players are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Dean Griffin, the convention's chief technology adviser, is a
honcho at Andersen Consultants, which furnished $850,000 worth of
in-kind services to the GOP extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   _ James Wray, a Washington lobbyist with a wide array of
corporate clients, is the key liaison man between the GOP
convention and the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   _ Edward W. Gillespie, a big-bucks lobbyist who once worked for
and still acts as an adviser to House Majority Leader Dick Armey,
R-Texas, is in charge of orchestrating message and theme harmony
among the candidate and supporting speakers. It is his job to look
at the speeches and entertainment and be sure they convey what Gov.
Bush wants them to convey.
</P>
<P>
   _ Andrew Card Jr. is co-chairman of convention operations. A
former White House deputy chief of staff under President Bush, Card
is now General Motors Corp.'s top Washington lobbyist. Card's
convention backup is William Timmons, a premier Washington lobbyist
for blue-chip clients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
