<SLUG> BC-GOP-BLACKTURNOUT-1,000&AMP;ADD-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTE FOR BUSH _ OR AT LEAST DON'T VOTE AGAINST HIM 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Wednesday, Aug. 2, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADV: With photos of Abdul-Malik (NNS7) and of Jackson (NNS8). 
 By JONATHAN TILOVE  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Few expect the Republican presidential ticket to
gain many more black votes as a result of the party's concerted
effort to complement Gov. George W. Bush's call for ``compassionate
conservatism'' with a deluge of dais diversity.
</P>
<P>
   But some political analysts believe the party may be hoping it
can at least take the edge off black animus toward them and, in the
process, excite fewer African-Americans to turn out to vote against
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing Republicans can do with black voters without too
much destablizing their conservative support is help them to stay
at home,'' said political scientist Lorenzo Morris of Howard
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``By making Bush seem less threatening, Republicans may make it
harder to mobilize (black voters) and to demagogue as anti-black,
positions of the Republican Party,'' said Louis Bolce, a political
scientist at Baruch College in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   It is safe to say that the GOP message has not yet been
meaningfully received just across the Delaware River in Camden,
N.J., the oppressively poor, almost entirely black and brown city
where Bob Dole received 1,091 votes in 1996 (4 percent), and where
is it is unlikely that George W. Bush will do much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they come out to vote, they won't be Republicans,'' said
Gilbert Shepherd, a former school board member and seller of
reptile shoes. For Republicans here and across the nation, in that
``if'' may lie the best test of whether their call for inclusion
pays off in the black community.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know that they're not going to get any significant number
of black votes,'' said David Bositis, an expert on black politics
at the Joint Center for Political and Economic Studies in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Bositis and others suggest that the primary target of the
Republicans' new emphasis on inclusiveness are moderate whites, who
do not like to think of themselves as part of a party that they
think is racially exclusive or insensitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party wants to appear reasonable on race. In
the old days they were the anti-black party, or the party that
anti-black people rallied to,'' Bositis said.
</P>
<P>
   Bolce notes that the late Republican strategist Lee Atwater, who
was so successful at bringing white Southerners into the Republican
Party,had predicted in the 1980s that if Republicans could claim
even 20 percent of black votes, the South would be securely theirs.
</P>
<P>
   But this many years later, that 20 percent remains an elusive
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for them to get 10 percent,'' said Charles Bullock,
a political scientist at the University of Georgia. ``A better hope
for them is that black participation will be down a bit.
</P>
<P>
   The black vote has become even more crucial in recent years, as
turnout has risen, as the defection of white voters to the
Republican Party has gone about as far as it can go, and as the
country becomes, day by day, less overwhelmingly white.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Republicans) stay the way they are right now, there will
be a solid Democratic majority in 10 years,'' Bositis said.
</P>
<P>
   Black voters were considered crucial to Democrats winning the
governorship in several Southern states in recent years, most
recently Mississippi, where Ronnie Musgrove last year won by a mere
8,000 votes. There are also significant numbers of black voters in
the swing states likely to be most hotly contested this fall.
</P>
<P>
   But Bositis does not believe even a kinder, gentler GOP can hope
to keep black voters from turning out for the Democrats this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to affect turnout,'' said Bositis. He noted
that the Democratic Party has proven masterful at bringing black
voters out. A leading architect of those efforts has been Donna
Brazile, a black woman who is now Al Gore's campaign manager. In
key contests, each black voter is repeatedly contacted, including
programmed phone calls from the likes of President Clinton and the
Rev. Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   This October will also see the Million Family March in
Washington, which has set as a goal registering 1 million new
voters, and there is the possibility that the Rev. Louis Farrakhan,
the man behind the march, may express a candidate preference. This
too could have consequences. In the 1996 presidential election _ a
year after the original Million Man March _ black male turnout was
up 1.7 million, and Bositis thinks the two were related.
</P>
<P>
   In Camden, Zawdie Abdul-Malik, who heads the local Million
Family March organizing committee, has set his own goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at about 5,000 (new registrants),'' said
Abdul-Malik, a local Democratic ward leader, who has been honored
by the state party for his prodigious work registering voters.
Right now, out of more than 35,000 registered voters in Camden,
only 891 are Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Malik, who serves on the school board and is considering
running for mayor, may be a Democratic activist, but he is
considering voting for Green Party candidate Ralph Nader this year.
Four years ago he wrote in Farrakhan for president.
</P>
<P>
   A black colleague on the school board, and fellow civic
activist, Rosemary Jackson was a Perot voter in 1992, and would
have considered Bush were it not for his enthusiasm for the death
penalty. ``Actually I like Bush,'' said Jackson. ``I think he is
different from the traditional Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is unimpressed by Vice President Al Gore. ``Nah, no,''
she said. So, while she will vote in November, she may skip the
presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   But in Charleston, S.C., the Rev. Joseph A. Darby, the pastor of
Morris Brown AME Church, does not expect too many in the black
community to stray from Gore or sit it out.
</P>
<P>
   Darby has been watching the convention from home, he said,
noting, sardonically, ``It's a real soul fest.''
</P>
<P>
   But Darby, who is an official with the South Carolina NAACP,
said some of the delegates to this convention (all white with the
exception of one black alternate) are the same folks he has been
fighting back home over the Confederate flag.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   When you get beyond the ``black floor show'' at the convention,
Darby said, there are very few blacks on the convention floor.
</P>
<P>
   This is true. According to the Joint Center's count, there are
85 black delegates at this convention, 4 percent of the total. And
yet, that is more than twice the black share of all Republican
votes in the last presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a whole lot of brothers hanging,'' said Shannon Reeves, a
black delegate from Oakland, standing with his delegation on the
convention floor. ``I'm just out here trying to represent.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves last heard George W. Bush speak in July at the NAACP
national convention in Baltimore. Showing up, he said, is half the
battle. The new ``open door'' at this convention will help. But it
will have to be sustained over the years and complemented by
performance. He does not expect it to yield much in the way of
tangible results when the votes are counted this November in
Oakland, where Democrats will win a commanding victory.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``I want a big turnout anyway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
