<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-ISLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER DEFRAUDED PRIEST'S HEIRS OF OIL ROYALTIES ,  JURY RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Spain)   By   ROSS E. MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A Texas jury has found that a New York lawyer
defrauded several hundred relatives of a 19th century priest over
six decades ago and now owes them millions of dollars in oil
royalties and interest, according to a decision announced Wednesday
in Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of Padre Nicolas Balli and his nephew Juan Jose Balli
had sued the 90-year-old lawyer, Gilbert Kerlin, in 1994, charging
that Kerlin had promised to pay mineral royalties to their families
when he began acquiring title to their properties on Padre Island,
just east of Brownsville, in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   The island, rich in oil and natural gas, is named for Padre
Balli, who received title to the land from King Carlos III of
Spain. Padre Balli died in 1829, leaving most of the land to his
nephew.
</P>
<P>
   Kerlin had argued during the trial that Padre Balli's nephew had
sold the land, approximately 60,000 acres, in 1830 and that the
titles he acquired from the Balli family descendants were thus
invalid.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers for the family produced evidence during the trial
that Kerlin and his lawyer, F.W. Seabury, had used the titles to
back up their claims of ownership when selling surface and mineral
rights to the land.
</P>
<P>
   In the decision announced Wednesday, the jury found that Kerlin
had conspired with Seabury, now deceased, to defraud the
unsophisticated Balli landowners by refusing to pay mineral
royalties as called for in the deeds of sale.
</P>
<P>
   The jury found that Kerlin and Seabury had acted with malice in
another transaction, involving 7,500 acres of surface rights to the
island, by claiming to represent the Balli heirs while gaining
possession of the land in a 1940s lawsuit but never informing them
of their ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, the Balli family honor is restored,'' said Hector
Cardenas, a Balli descendant and one of the lawyers representing
the family. ``This isn't the end of the process, but we're very
happy with the jury's decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Balli ancestors have asked for $11 million in unpaid
mineral royalties, interest and lawyers' fees, plus an unnamed
amount in damages for fraud, the actual amount to be paid has yet
to be determined, said lawyers involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury has given us nearly everything we asked for, but
there are some differences in the way they want to calculate the
royalties,'' said Robert Johnson, one of the plaintiffs' lawyers.
``We haven't calculated what the various awards made today by the
jury amount to yet, but it's safe to say that the families will
receive several million dollars at least.''
</P>
<P>
   Over $1.5 million in legal fees were also awarded to the
plaintiffs' lawyers, said Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Another lawyer involved said the family's legal team estimates
that unpaid royalties and interest alone will exceed $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   The jury will begin deliberations about punitive damages on
Monday, said Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Contacted Wednesday in New York, Kerlin, citing an order by the
presiding judge in the case not to talk about the lawsuit, would
say only, ``We've still got a long way to go yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
