<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0992 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-POWELL-LOBBYISTS     08-02 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-POWELL-LOBBYISTS-LEWIS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLIN POWELL'S SECOND CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Thursday, Aug. 3, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By CHARLES LEWIS    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``Some in our party miss no opportunity to roundly
and loudly condemn affirmative action that helped a few thousand
black kids get an education,'' Colin Powell told the Republican
convention this week, ``but you hardly hear a whimper when it's
affirmative action for lobbyists who load our federal tax code with
preferences for special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   His defense of affirmative action got all the attention, but his
challenge was twofold because he was also criticizing politicians'
giveaways to corporations, which, in turn, contribute to those
politicians' campaigns. Though this challenge could have been
leveled at both Democrats and Republicans, let's start with the
GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney, the party's vice presidential nominee, complained
about the oppressive, wasteful, inefficient role of big government
throughout his political career. But while he has been the chief
executive of Halliburton, a Dallas oil services company, few
businessmen have benefited more from federal government help.
</P>
<P>
   In the five years that Cheney has run Halliburton, the company
and its subsidiaries have received $2.3 billion in federal
contracts, up from $1.2 billion during the five years preceding his
tenure. Halliburton also received $1.5 billion in guaranteed or
direct loans from the Export-Import Bank and the Overseas Private
Investment Corp. In the five years before Cheney joined the
company, it received only $100 million from these government
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   How did Halliburton double its federal contracts and increase,
by a factor of 15, the amount of direct or government-guaranteed
loans? The company may attribute its success to other factors, but
is it a coincidence that in the past five years, Halliburton gave
$1.2 million to the two political parties and individual members of
Congress? According to the Center for Responsive Politics, the
company also increased its Washington lobbying: its costs
mushroomed from $280,000 in 1996 to $600,000 last year. As
Halliburton's fortunes have risen, so, too, have Cheney's, who
after five years at the helm is worth about $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Like Cheney, Gov. George W. Bush talks of the importance of
self-reliance and getting government out of the way of private
initiative _ unless, of course, there is a little ``affirmative
action'' for your company.
</P>
<P>
   His success in business was also famously tied to government
largess. Bush made $14.9 million from the sale of the Texas Rangers
baseball team, a 25-fold return on his investment of $606,302. The
team's phenomenal rise in value was directly tied to a new stadium
financed by more than $200 million in public subsidies and tax
incentives. Taxpayers didn't get a return from the Rangers' surging
new revenues. The profits went almost exclusively to the team's
owners.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans hold no monopoly on hypocrisy. Despite the move
of his campaign operation from Washington to Nashville, Vice
President Al Gore is still close to the lobbyists on K Street. His
closest confidants and campaign advisers are lobbyists for all
kinds of corporate interests. His $30 million in 1999
contributions, a Democratic record for fund-raising in a year
before a presidential election, didn't come from backyard
barbecues.
</P>
<P>
   Gore says that as president he would reform the campaign finance
system. Yet he has clung steadfastly to legalistic evasions about
the nature of both the notorious White House coffees, which
collected $26.4 million for the Democratic Party from 1,544 people
who sought face time with the president and vice president, and the
Buddhist monastery event, which he has said was nothing more than
``community outreach.'' Such sustained sophistry is tiresome and
does not speak well for an administration that claims to want to
clean up the system.
</P>
<P>
   So while I hope that both the Democrats and Republicans take the
second half of Colin Powell's message seriously, I won't hold my
breath. Certain kinds of ``affirmative action'' are not going
change much anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   (Charles Lewis is the founder and executive director of the
Center for Public Integrity, a nonpartisan research group.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
