<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN PRESS BARON CONTEMPLATES HIS FORTUNE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ So what is Conrad Black going to do with his bags of
money now that he has sold most of the crown jewels of Canada's
newspapers in one fell swoop?
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you remember that cartoon character, Scrooge McDuck?''
Black said, answering a question with a question. ``Do you remember
how he used to get into his little bulldozer every morning and plow
back and forth over his gold coins? Well, maybe I will just sit and
look at it for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back to 1969, when he bought a tiny English-language
paper in Quebec, Black, now 55, said, ``I started in this business
30 years ago with an investment of $500.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the present, he said of the deal announced this
week: ``It was time in the history of my country, and time in my
own history, to make things shipshape, to get rid of the debt, to
get a bit of a cash box to work from, to enjoy life a little
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Few pundits in newspapers today predicted an easy-chair life for
Black, a Napoleon buff who has run his newspaper empire from a
chair once owned by his military hero. As Black trims his sails in
North America _ a sale of his community papers in the Chicago area
is believed to be imminent _ Canadians say they believe that he
will turn his energies to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   A holder of dual British and Canadian citizenship and owner of
the Daily Telegraph of London, Black could seek new European
investments for the company that on Monday bought most of his
Canadian newspapers, the CanWest Global Communications Corp., now
Canada's largest media company.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting extensively about the deal for the first time since
it was announced, Black said in a telephone interview Tuesday night
that the sale to CanWest would leave his company, Hollinger Inc.,
on a solid financial footing. ``We will go from $1.7 billion in
debt to zero plus $500 million in cash, perhaps a bit better than
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Hollinger stock had bounced back from depressed
levels in recent months, he said he was selling his newspapers
``fairly close to the top of the economic cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   Black also justified his heavy selloff here, saying he was
``overexposed in Canada.'' In a separate interview with the
National Post, his Toronto-based newspaper, Black added, ``The
reputation of Canada is not particularly great among American
investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Americans have poured billions into the Toronto Stock
Exchange this year, helping it to rise faster than the New York
exchanges, Black said his pool of buyers was artificially limited
by Canadian laws that discourage foreigners from buying Canadian
newspapers. Noting that Canada is essentially off limits to
American newspaper chains, he complained, ``With these ridiculous
foreign-ownership rules in Canada, you can't get much equity.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel Asper, the chairman of CanWest, has predicted that the
editorial line of his newspapers will be ``balanced,'' a word
rarely found in the lexicon of Black, a crusty, conservative press
baron who has been described by detractors as a thesaurus that
walks like a man.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Black snorted at newspaper characterizations of
Asper as a ``social democrat,'' saying that he and his new business
partner see eye to eye on economic issues and recalling that he
first met Asper 25 years ago when he was writing a personal tax
column for the Winnipeg Free Press. Questioned further, he
acknowledged having had ``a bit of wrestling match with Izzy'' over
the National Post, which in less than two years has established an
intellectual beachhead for conservative, free-market changes in
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   After the wrestling was over, ownership of the National Post was
split 50-50 between the two business groups. Black, who is to be
chairman of the newspaper for five years, says it sells 330,000
copies daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under our arrangement, he has no ability to change it,'' Black
said of Asper and the editorial line of the Post, which has become
a cheerleader for the Canadian Alliance, the nation's new
tax-cutting party. Asked if the editorial line would change, he
stressed, ``Zero, nothing, not one millimeter.''
</P>
<P>
   But leaders of Canada's ruling Liberal Party, a frequent target
of criticism from the editorial pages of Black's newspapers, were
elated at news of the purchase by Asper, a longtime centrist
Liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the sale ``the best news they had had in a long time,''
Lawrence Martin, a Southam News political analyst, wrote from
Ottawa of the Liberals: ``Even a measured neutrality will be viewed
by the prime minister as a major plus over the treatment he felt he
was receiving before the newspaper sale.''
</P>
<P>
   The government of Prime Minister Jean Chretien has not given the
slightest hint that it will move to block the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto is home to one of the toughest newspaper wars in the
English-speaking world, a three-way battle among the National Post,
the Globe and Mail and the Toronto Star. On Tuesday, the Globe and
Mail printed on the top of its front page a large, full-color
cartoon of Asper grinning and preparing to dine on a prostrate
Black, who was depicted stuffed and spiced, with a sprig of parsley
in each ear. The headlines read: ``Asper: Mogul and a half'' and
``Black: Only half a mogul.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its gloating, the Globe and Mail now stands alone,
virtually the only major English-language Canadian newspaper that
does not have ties to CanWest, which has a Canadian network of
television stations broadcasting coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   After a day of reflection, the Globe and Mail came out Wednesday
with an editorial salted with crocodile tears and headlined:
``Black to fade.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Canada does not have so many larger-than-life characters
that it can afford to lose any of them cheerfully, the notion of a
vanishing Conrad Black is rather affecting,'' the editorial said.
In a service to readers, it warned that some Canadians ``will
experience the disorientation that follows the abrupt end of a
toothache.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
