<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1003 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-EARTHLINK0803-COX     08-02 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTHLINK0803-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brewer saddens tech community
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Charles Brewer, who resigned Wednesday as chairman of
EarthLink Inc., has been distancing himself from the company since
the merger of MindSpring and EarthLink in February.
</P>
<P>
   In a news release issued late Wednesday, Brewer said he left the
company to pusue other interests. Brewer was chairman and CEO of
MindSpring Enterprises, the Atlanta-based Internet service provider
he started in his basement in 1994. When MindSpring merged with
EarthLink Networks to become EarthLink Inc. on Feb. 4, Brewer took
a step back from day to day operations and became chairman of the
new company.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer has sold his holdings in EarthLink, including 2.9 million
shares the company bought from him as part of it's stock repurchase
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The company will continue to be Atlanta-based said EarthLink CEO
Garry Betty. A Georgia native and Georgia Tech grad who has
maintained a home in the Atlanta suburb of Sandy Springs for more
than a decade, Betty said his commitment to the city was as strong
as Brewer's. ``My roots in this town go way back. My passion and
commitment to Atlanta is no less, and EarthLink will continue to
play a big role in the Atlanta tech community.''
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink founder Sky Dayton, who left the company to found the
business to business incubator eCompanies, will step back in as the
new chairman of the board. No other positions are affected by
Brewer's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sky's passion has always been for the Internet and the
Internet experience,'' said EarthLink president Michael McQuary who
held the same title at MindSpring and is a close friend of
Brewer's. ``Charles was more interested in how the company was run.
Charles would work at a cheese factory if it was run right. ``
</P>
<P>
   Employees, interviewed Wednesday night said that Brewer would be
missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you meet him, he has an air about him. He seems so
energetic. You meet him and you think I want to know this guy,''
said Ty Welch, who has worked for the Internet provider for five
years and now is in charge of training call center workers on the
East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Welch said even the lowest level workers feel drawn to Brewer.
However, he said the merger hadn't changed the company's direction,
and he didn't expect Brewer's departure to change it either.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey Milton, who has worked for EarthLink for six months,
said ``I am mostly just surprised. We all have a personal
attachment to him.''
</P>
<P>
   John Waln, customer service representative there, said: ``It's
sad, the company is built on his core values and beliefs. However I
don't think that will change.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who follow the company and have known Brewer for years
said Brewer had gradually faded into the background after the
EarthLink merger.
</P>
<P>
   As the public face of MindSpring in its heyday of aggressive
growth and soaring stock prices, Brewer was a familiar presence,
not only in Atlanta, but to faithful viewers of financial news
channels.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, Brewer became a legend for starting a litte Internet
company in his basement and watching it grow one of the top ISPs in
the country. All the while, he adhered to his ``core values and
beliefs'' that guided the compaupermarkets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Brewer finally made the decision to merge with EarthLink
last year, many MindSpring subscribers and shareholders feared
that, without Brewer's sense of purpose, the company would lose the
quirky appeal and commitment to customers that was its hallmark.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the merger, Brewer said he understood that in
order to grow, MindSpring would have to give up a little bit of its
style.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was one thing missing from our (corporate)
personality, I would say it was competitiveness,'' he said in an
interview last January. ``I always wished we were more competitive.
EarthLink has a more aggressive edge. Some blending of that could
turn out a hybrid that is better than what we each had
individually.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the merger he stuck around to make sure these things
were going to keep going,'' said analyst Miles Russ of
Atlanta-based Robinson Humphrey. ``He just went on the board of
Humana (a health insurance company based in his hometown of
Louisville, Ky.) and he probably has some other things cooking. He
hasn't been very visible to the investment community since the
merger.''
</P>
<P>
   Russ said he only knew Dayton by reputation, but ``knowing what
a good job he did with EarthLink, I think it's a good sign for the
markets. He's run one of the top ISPs in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Sadler, an analyst at FAC Equity in Boston, said he wasn't
surprised by Brewer's departure. ``He's made his money, and he has
no desire to run the company at this stage. The timing of this is
pretty typical. ``
</P>
<P>
   Sadler also thinks Dayton's appointment to chairman was a good
move for EarthLink. ``It seemed that Sky had pretty much washed his
hands of EarthLink to run eCompanies. Maybe (EarthLink) realized
that with the stock at the price where it's at, something needs to
be done. Sky has had a very creative hand in the past and he may
have some ideas about the future. The company needs some strategic
direction, and it's quite possible Sky has some good ideas. I think
he will be a welcome addition.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty said that even though Dayton was working his ``day job''
at eCompanies he has been a very active member of the EarthLink
board. ``We are happy to have Sky step in and resume his role as
chairman,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton left the company after the EarthLink merger to start
eCompanies in Santa Monica. Dayton who founded EarthLink in
California 1995 _ the same time Brewer was launching MindSpring in
Atlanta _ is credited with many innovations in the Internet access
arena that most users take for granted today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the first ISP to offer a software package to allow
people to connect right to the Internet in the summer of 1995,''
Betty said. Dayton also had the idea to create EarthLink software
that defaulted to an EarthLink homepage.
</P>
<P>
   `` From a personal standpoint, I'm sad to see Charles leave,''
said Frank Gristina, also of Robinson Humphrey. ``He built such a
great legacy, but the legacy certainly continues, with someone as
experienced as Sky Dayton at the helm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll challenge us to do better and drive us nuts,'' McQuary
said. ``Just the way Charles used to drive us nuts. ``
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
