<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1004 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-TV-GOP-COVERAGE-NYT &LR;      08-02 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOP-COVERAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVENTIONS' TV AUDIENCES SHRINK, BUT IS REDUCED COVERAGE THE
REASON? 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1984, ABC shocked news purists by inserting a rerun of a
canceled series, ``Hart to Hart,'' in the middle of one night's
convention coverage. The same year an ABC News executive, Jeff
Gralnick, labeled the conventions ``dying dinosaurs.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, CBS skipped one night entirely to cover baseball's
All-Star game. In 1996, Ted Koppel of ABC yanked his ``Nightline''
crew from the Republican convention one night early, declaring
there was too little news.
</P>
<P>
   For two decades, the amount of convention coverage has been a
testy issue. This year, the debate has only intensified as the
broadcast networks have further cut back on the hours devoted to
the convention, saying that viewers are uninterested. Over the
first two nights of this year's Republican convention, the ratings
seem to back them up. But whether the falloff in audience is a
result of viewers losing interest or the broadcast networks simply
offering them less to be interested in is a matter of some debate.
</P>
<P>
   The chairmen of both parties confronted network executives at a
panel discussion in Philadelphia Sunday accusing them of shirking
their civic duty by drastically curtailing the number of hours of
live coverage. The chairmen argued that by deemphasizing coverage,
the networks were sending the message that the conventions are not
newsworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Network executives dismissed that charge. ``I reject that
chicken and egg theory,'' said Andrew Heyward, the president of CBS
News. ``I do not think people are less interested because we're
covering less, but because they find the conventions less
compelling.''
</P>
<P>
   For Tom Brokaw, the NBC anchor, who has covered every national
political convention since 1968, the blame lies squarely with the
decisions made by the parties to eliminate all semblance of
suspense or debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are covering them differently because there's no `there'
there,'' he said. ``The parties have drained all the drama out of
the proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   With network coverage reduced at the same time that the number
of cable news channels has expanded, exact comparisons of this
year's audience with the past audiences are difficult.
</P>
<P>
   But there are signs of lack of interest. Even though CBS and NBC
tried a bait-and-switch technique the first two nights to try to
lure viewers _ by folding the coverage inside its news magazines _
the audience defected in huge numbers as soon as convention
coverage started. ABC, the one network duplicating its coverage
from 1996, saw its ratings fall about 25 percent, compared with the
first two nights four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   On CBS, the program ``60 Minutes II'' offered a repeat segment
on dot-com millionaires for the first half-hour and drew a 4.6
rating. That fell to a 4.1 once the convention coverage came on.
(Each rating point represents just over 1 million homes.)
</P>
<P>
   The falloff was more drastic at NBC, where a ``Dateline''
segment on nursing homes drew a 7.2 rating in the first half hour.
The second half hour of convention coverage lost almost half that
audience, falling to a 3.8 rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here you had John McCain, one of the heroes of the campaign,
speaking and, zowie, half the audience is gone,'' Heyward said.
</P>
<P>
   He also cited CNN's falloff in viewers from 1996 _ a decline of
35 percent the first night and 17 percent the second night. Partly
this is due to increased competition from Fox News and MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   CNN executives argued that they have been totally satisfied with
the ratings so far. ``We got a big bounce over our normal
ratings,'' said Susan Binford, the spokeswoman for CNN. ``And we
increased our numbers from the first night to the second. We think
the networks are engaging in a self-fulfilling prophecy in sending
out the message that the conventions are boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Money is not at the heart of the network decisions to cut back,
Heyward said, though he said network expenses in covering the
event, put at $15 million each in the 1980s, are now down to single
digit millions.
</P>
<P>
   Heyward said, ``If things don't change, I could see a scenario
where the candidates' acceptance speeches become the only events
covered live in 2004.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 2102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
