<SLUG> BC-CVN-KENNEDY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXANS, `LOUD AND PROUD,' PUTTING ON A GLITZY SHOW IN PHILLY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BUD KENNEDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ In a late-breaking news bulletin from the
Republican National Convention, the three major networks have
learned that Texans can look really stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Texans can look stupid waving their cowboy hats and howling like
drunken cowboys at a wet T-shirt contest. Texans can look stupid
praying, as a few did Tuesday night in a petty protest against a
gay congressman giving a speech about free trade. Texans can even
look stupid when sitting still, particularly if adorned with Lone
Star flag sequined jackets and enough rhinestones to temporarily
blind Brit Hume.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. John McCain even asked the Texas delegates to sit down
and stop waving their hats during his speech Tuesday night.
Supposedly, he couldn't see the TelePrompTer.
</P>
<P>
   If only he could have calmed them down to start the week.
</P>
<P>
   And those get-ups. I'm not sure who is the worst-dressed here _
the Texas delegates or the street protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Eastland, an Arlington alternate and the city's favorite
anti-tax crank, only grinned about the Texans' hokey show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're loud and we're proud,'' he said. ``Hokey? We're Texans.
We LIKE hokey.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of hokey: At the time, he was standing in an old Army
National Guard mounted cavalry horse barn, at a party featuring
barbecued brisket, pork ribs and plenty of Shiner Bock. On stage,
Jerry Jeff Walker had just finished singing ``London Homesick
Blues'' and was going into ``Up Against the Wall Redneck Mother.''
</P>
<P>
   It may or may not console you to know that this party for Ennis
Congressman Joe Barton and 1,400 invited guests was thrown by
America's gas utility companies.
</P>
<P>
   It's not even the largest Texas barbecue this week.
</P>
<P>
   At a convention where the star is Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the
only serious conflict of the week may be at the buffet tables. Call
it the Battle of the Barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   For Wednesday's smoker showdown, Barton chose fellow Aggie and
Texas House candidate Charlie Geren of Fort Worth, who weighed in
with 450 pounds of beef brisket, 120 pounds of chicken and 120
pounds of sausage from his Railhead Smokehouse restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barton tried my barbecue at a party once, and he liked it,''
Geren said, hustling to keep the meat warm with Sterno pots because
there was no place to connect a power generator in the 1916-vintage
Pennsylvania State Armory cavalry barn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hope I can keep these Yankees from puttin' sauce on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Geren is not the only North Texas pitmaster in town. Dallas
barbecue caterer Eddie Deen, partner in the Ranch Hand BBQ
restaurant in Terrell, was firing up his pit Wednesday to feed the
national press corps traveling with Bush. Deen, a cousin to the
Deen Meat Co. family in Fort Worth and former Mayor Edgar Deen,
catered beef for 15,000 at both Bush inaugurations in Austin. A
local newspaper called him ``W's man for BBQ.''
</P>
<P>
   Deen studied molecular biology at A&AMP;M. ``I've spent a lot of
time figuring out how different smokers and different heat
temperatures affect the protein molecule,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up here, though, what's important is to put on a good Texas
show.''
</P>
<P>
   The final cowboy throwdown will be Thursday night after the
convention, when House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Ennis throws a
party starring Brooks &AMP; Dunn and serving Capital Q barbecue from
Washington _ with help from Bush's new hometown hangout, the
Citrano Bros. Coffee Shop Cafe in McGregor near the Bush spread in
Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Citrano was headed to town Wednesday. He's bringing a
smoker and barbecue fixin's for 4,000.
</P>
<P>
   He'll cook with hickory wood. If it runs low, he can stoke the
fire with all those hats.
</P>
<P>
   (Bud Kennedy is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7538, or e-mail:
budk(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
