u a BC-KANSAS-SCHOOLS-NYT     08-02 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KANSAS-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS REJECTS SCHOOL BOARD CANDIDATES WHO FAVOR CREATIONISM
</HEADLINE>
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Voters in Kansas have repudiated the state school
board's removal of human evolution from the state science
standards, making it all but certain that the decision will be
overturned.
</P>
<P>
   In a Republican primary on Tuesday, the voters defeated three
conservative candidates who supported the decision, made by the
Kansas Board of Education a year ago. In the first board election
since then, voters chose instead three moderate Republicans who
pledged to return evolution to the science standards. And those
three will be running in November against Democrats who also
support evolution. The election assures that there will be a
majority on the board supporting evolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think parents want their kids to have a strong competitive
education,'' said Sue Gamble, a moderate Republican who defeated
the school board chairwoman, Linda Holloway, a conservative. ``The
message was that that includes a full set of science standards and
that includes evolution.''
</P>
<P>
   While the board vote last August did not prevent schools from
teaching evolution, leaving that decision to schools, it
effectively removed evolution as the sole explanation for the
origin of species, as well as the Big Bang theory of the origin of
the universe, from state student assessment tests, a move was
intended to discourage teachers from spending time on those
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's 6-4 decision was considered one of the most
significant victories for those who believe that the species were
created by God or conservatives who favor an ``intelligent
designer.'' Proponents of such theories have stepped up their
activism, prompting states like Kentucky and Oklahoma to dilute the
teaching of evolution in one way or another. Many other states,
wrestling with evolution debates of their own, had their eyes on
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas has been sort of ground zero,'' said Ralph G. Neas,
president of People for the American Way, a civil liberties group
that supports the teaching of evolution. ``And a lot of states will
be taking a look at this very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue had transformed a normally obscure election into a
lightning rod for proponents and opponents of evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigns that normally raised no more than a few hundred
dollars received tens of thousands of dollars in contributions,
some from out of state. Candidates took the unusual step of running
television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   And Democrats switched parties just to vote in the Republican
primary, which, in heavily Republican Kansas, often determines who
will win in November. One Democratic school board member, Bill
Wagnon of Topeka, even campaigned for Gamble, even though she faces
a Democratic opponent in November.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, only one of the four conservatives running won,
Steve Abrams of Arkansas City, a board member who helped write the
standards approved last year. In a fifth district, Wagnon, was
unopposed in the Democratic primary, but faces a conservative
opponent in November. The remaining five board seats were not up
for election this year.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway, the former chairwoman who lost her seat in the
district that includes Kansas City suburb of Johnson County, said
she ``had no idea it would be that much of a defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Holloway, who believes that evolution can be taught alongside
creationism or other theories, said, ``There is clearly still a
misunderstanding of what we did. There is still this stereotype
that this is religion and this is science. It was much more
complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   She blamed ``this elite group in Washington that have an agenda,
the National Academy of Sciences and other science groups. They
have an agenda to get evolution presented as hard dogmatic fact. It
is pure dogma and it is pure propaganda.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she raised $90,000 to Gamble's $36,000, Holloway said
she was ``outspent'' because Greg Musil, a moderate Republican
candidate for the congressional district that borders Kansas City,
ran campaign ads criticizing the board's decision. (Musil lost to
state Rep. Phillip D. Kline, who will face the incumbent Democratic
congressman, Dennis Moore.)
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I'm very elated about is I don't believe the
discussion about evolution will ever be the same again,'' Holloway
said. ``People are looking at it with a more critical eye rather
than swallowing it hook, line and sinker.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillip E. Johnson, a law professor at the University of
California at Berkeley who believes that the universe is so complex
that there must have been an ``intelligent designer,'' said, ``I
think that the academics and the journalists succeeded pretty well
in embarrassing the people of Kansas and there was a sense that
`people are laughing at us, people think we're rubes, industry
doesn't want to come here anymore.'''
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``This is very heavy-handed intimidation. You may scare
people, but if anything, it may make people more likely to stand up
for their cause.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Kansas and across the country, science educators rejoiced
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am relieved and I'm also thinking that we're back on the
road to reality and sanity,'' said Al Frisby, a biology teacher at
Shawnee Mission Northwest High School in the Kansas City suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Frisby wore a tie that summed up his feelings. It
featured three see-no-evil, hear-no-evil, speak-no-evil monkeys,
with hands covering the eyes, ears or mouth. A fourth monkey's
mouth was agape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like the first three monkeys represent the conservative
school board members,'' he said. ``They had their eyes closed, they
had their ears closed, they had an agenda they were trying to
follow. And I'm the monkey at the bottom, saying, `Wow, it's
remarkable.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
