<HEADER>
A1011 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-     08-02 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERGES MAKES MOST OF HIS OPPORTUNITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Right-hander Matt Herges remembers the conversation
in the Dodgers' clubhouse a month into spring training as if it was
just the other day.
</P>
<P>
   There was no room for Herges on the roster. There was no hope
for him as a 30-year-old rookie in an organization filled with
veteran relievers who had a much better track record. Herges
couldn't argue.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Herges is 8-0, has a 3.00 ERA, and is in the starting
rotation for a pennant race. That's the news manager Davey Johnson
delivered Wednesday when he announced lefty Carlos Perez was being
shipped to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Johnson) has given me opportunities, and as a ballplayer,
especially in the minor leagues where guys just want a chance, one
chance, so I don't want to disappoint him,'' said Herges, who will
start Tuesday against the Chicago Cubs. ``When I think about it,
it's overwhelming a little bit. I've never been more excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Herges made the Dodgers roster in spring training because
Johnson was worried about getting innings from his starters,
particularly Orel Hershiser and Perez. So he went with 12 pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   But even after that, Herges' standing with the Dodgers wasn't
cemented. He was expected to be sent to the minors after the
season-opening four-game series in Montreal. The Dodgers, in fact,
had arranged and paid for his plane ticket to Albuquerque but then
changed their minds. The club decided to send Perez to the minors
and activate Geronimo Berroa.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when Herges returned to his hotel room in New York there
was a fax waiting for him. It was his itinerary to leave for
Albuquerque, which was inadvertently sent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very easy decision for me because the guy has pitched
as good as anybody on the staff,'' Johnson said. ``The guy has
pitched very well, and we want to improve our chances to win every
fifth day.''
</P>
<P>
   JEFF THANKS JEFF: When Dodgers closer Jeff Shaw earned the 150th
save of his career in Tuesday's win in the second game of a
doubleheader against the Pirates, he wanted to make sure kudos were
given to someone who's helped him along in his career path.
</P>
<P>
   While with the Cincinnati Reds, Shaw spent a lot of time picking
the brain of injured closer Jeff Brantley. Shaw went on to save a
league-best 42 games in 1997, saved 48 the next season and had 34
saves with the Dodgers last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it weren't for (Brantley) getting injured I would have
never got the opportunity,'' said Shaw, who has five saves and
hasn't allowed a run in nine appearances since the All-Star break.
``I would have been setting up in '97 and who knows where I'd be. A
lot of it goes to him because he could have easily rehabbed
somewhere else. But he sat right there beside me in '97 and taught
me how to close.''
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: As expected, the Dodgers activated utility
outfielder F.P. Santangelo and placed infielder Chris Donnels on
the 15-day disabled list with an injured right shoulder. But
Santangelo won't be available until Tuesday's game against the
Chicago Cubs because he's serving his five-game suspension from the
Wrigley Field fiasco. Donnels was batting .300 in nine games,
mostly appearing as a pinch hitter. ... Eric Karros started 103 of
the first 106 games but was given Wednesday off. Dave Hansen
started at first base. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
