<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECRUITING-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: WITH EXECUTIVES IN DEMAND, RECRUITERS DEMAND EQUITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: Vivek Wadhwa, in second graf, is cq.) By REED ABELSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Relativity Technologies began a search in the spring for a
new president, its equity was in great demand. Even before
negotiating with job candidates, it had to deal with the demand for
a stake from the executive search firms.
</P>
<P>
   Well aware that competition for top talent is fierce, Vivek
Wadhwa, the company's chief executive, planned to hire one of the
top firms. When he contacted two of them, Heidrick &AMP; Struggles
International and Christian &AMP; Timbers, he was surprised to find
that they wanted more than just a six-figure cash fee. Each asked
for a sizable equity position in his company, an up-and-coming
software developer based in Cary, N.C., that eventually plans to go
public.
</P>
<P>
   Wadhwa considered the price, nearly half a million dollars, too
high and refused. Instead, he chose Kathy Forbes, who runs a small
recruiting business in Atlanta. ``It's become insane,'' he said.
Companies like his are no longer selecting search firms, he says,
so much as the firms are picking them.
</P>
<P>
   Giving away an equity stake began as a way for companies without
much cash to compensate lawyers, consultants and recruiting firms.
But deluged with work in a tight labor market, executive recruiters
increasingly demand _ and get _ equity as a condition of performing
a top-level search for many private companies aiming to go public
or others whose stock seems particularly appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've created this mantra: `You want to work with us, we have
to get equity,''' said Ted Martin, the founder of his own
recruiting firm in Chicago. In choosing an assignment, recruiters
now routinely consider how well a client's stock might do,
especially given the recent market swings. ``With all these new
technology companies, everybody wants to be in because you want the
home run.''
</P>
<P>
   Few executives seem to have taken Wadhwa's stance, refusing to
hand over a significant share of their company, but some have
bristled at the arrangement. ``You are going to run into clients
who think you're smoking weed,'' Martin admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiters are well positioned to get what they want. Venture
capitalists and other investors are flooding start-ups with
capital, allowing companies to throw around large sums to pay
somebody to help run the business. Top recruiters have typically
demanded the equivalent of a third of the executive's first-year
pay package. With the booming stock market, those packages have
increasingly included a hefty portion of stock options or warrants,
and recruiters have begun in the last year or two to ask for a
third of that equity as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``These search firms are incredibly busy,'' said Charles
Johnson, a venture capitalist with Noro-Moseley Partners in
Atlanta, who generally recommends that the companies his firm has
backed pay the prevailing rate. An investor in Relativity, Johnson
suggested Heidrick for that search.
</P>
<P>
   Wadhwa, though, was surprised by the overheated environment for
his company's first major search. No neophyte, he had helped found
another company, Seer Technologies, in 1990 before leaving in 1997
to found Relativity and had spent more than 25 years in the
technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   Although the position of president had been open for more than a
year, after Matthew Szulik left in 1998 to become the president of
Red Hat, Wadhwa had been in no rush to fill it. As Relativity began
contemplating an initial public offering of stock, Wadhwa felt the
need for someone to help run the company. ``What I needed was a
good operations executive,'' he said. ``I hate details.''
</P>
<P>
   He initially turned to his board for some names, but soon
decided to approach an executive recruiter to find a president and
chief operating officer. He had met Jeff Christian of Christian &AMP;
Timbers, and had been impressed. ``Jeff was my first choice,''
Wadhwa said. ``He was in the lead by a mile.''
</P>
<P>
   Wadhwa had expected to pay about $100,000 for Christian's
services, but Christian also demanded equity equal to about a third
of what the new president would get in his first year. The least he
would take was 75,000 shares, according to Wadhwa. Those options
were worth $375,000, since the shares had been valued at about $5
each during the latest round of financing.
</P>
<P>
   Christian said search firms were entitled to an equity position
for their work. ``The philosophy that we had was there were lots of
ideas and lots of money, but there was a shortage of talent,'' he
said. Receiving warrants or options aligns his firm's interests
with those of its clients and the candidates it is recruiting, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Search firms are becoming a little more like venture guys,''
he said. Wadhwa ``did not value the relationship of a good search
firm as others did.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Luke of Heidrick &AMP; Struggles also wanted cash and equity,
Wadhwa said. Heidrick declined to comment. But the firm does not
conduct searches for a chief executive or chief operating officer
for pre-public technology companies unless it receives warrants,
according to a spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   At the suggestion of Johnson, the venture capitalist, Wadhwa
then contacted Forbes. She, too, was interested in equity. ``I like
having skin in the game,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the other recruiters, though, Forbes proved willing to
negotiate because she was more interested in the exposure the
search might offer. The two eventually struck a deal in which she
would get just 5,000 options, worth perhaps $25,000, and an $80,000
fee. ``It was worth it in this case,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wadhwa was initially concerned about going with a less-
established recruiter, Forbes said she would devote more time and
energy to the task than the better-known firms. She quickly
supplied him with a list of names. Within weeks, Relativity hired
Michael J. Espina, who had been a senior executive with Computer
Associates International.
</P>
<P>
   Espina said he was not looking for a job and had turned away
calls from other recruiters. Even though Forbes was not at a ``big
name-brand'' firm, she was persistent, he said, and got him to
schedule a short meeting, which stretched on for six hours. About a
month later, he was on board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
