<HEADLINE>
TREASURY GIVES 30-YEAR BOND A REPRIEVE, AND PRICE FALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The 30-year bond received a reprieve Wednesday, and
its fate is now probably in the hands of the next administration.
</P>
<P>
   In its announcement of the details of its quarterly auction of
Treasury notes and bonds, the government did not put the 30-year
bond, the one-time benchmark for Treasury interest rates, on the
endangered-species list, which surprised some investors.
</P>
<P>
   But some longtime bond market analysts, who have been reluctant
to believe that a president and Congress could keep government
surpluses running long enough to pay off most of the government's
$3 trillion of publicly held debt, now think that the demise of the
30-year bond is nigh.
</P>
<P>
   It is now possible, said Louis Crandall, chief economist at R.H.
Wrightson &AMP; Associates, to say that the public debt will shrink so
much in the next few years that the only bonds that might be left
will be those hoarded by investors unwilling to sell them back to
the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for this is the sheer size of the government surplus,
which is now forecast to be $211 billion in the 2000 fiscal year,
which ends Sept. 30, and $228 billion in the 2001 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   About a month ago, President Clinton announced that the
projected surplus for the 2001 through 2010 fiscal years would be
slightly less than $4.2 trillion. Of that, $2.3 trillion is
expected to come from the Social Security system and the rest,
almost $1.9 trillion, from general tax receipts. Democrats and
Republicans both consider the Social Security surplus off limits
for tax cuts or spending programs. So that leaves $1.9 trillion to
finance the tax cuts and spending increases that the two parties
will fight over.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the demise of the 30-year bonds more plausible is
that it is not practical to sell them when the publicly held debt
could be eliminated in just more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   So the pressure on the 30-year bond has been growing since last
August, when the Treasury first announced that it was considering
buying back some of its longer-term debt and would reduce the
amount of 30-year bonds it issued.
</P>
<P>
   The actual buybacks began early this year, and so far the
Treasury has repurchased $17.5 billion of bonds with remaining
maturities of 15 to 25 years. By the end of this year, the total
should approach $30 billion, with two buybacks of $1 billion to $3
billion each month.
</P>
<P>
   And some investors apparently thought that the Clinton Treasury,
in an effort to highlight its success in wiping out government
deficits and starting to pay off the public debt, would have
announced the next step for the 30-year bond Wednesday. When they
were disappointed, the price of the 30-year bond dropped a full
point as its yield, which moves in the opposite direction, jumped
to 5.79 percent, from 5.72 percent on Tuesday. The bond rallied
late in the day and finished down 18/32, to 106 30/32, with the
yield at 5.76 percent. The 10-year note rose 2/32, to 103 26/32;
its yield fell to 5.97 percent from 5.98 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement these investors were waiting for was that the
Treasury would actively consider no longer issuing 30-year bonds,
similar to the announcement it made in May about one-year bills.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Gensler, the undersecretary of the Treasury for domestic
finance, said there was no need for any significant change either
in the Treasury's reduced pace of issuing new Treasury bills, notes
and bonds, or in its plan for buying back existing debt. He said
the reason was the large amount of government debt that the
Treasury had paid off so far _ $360 billion over three years _ and
the fact that the amount of maturing Treasury debt was still high
next year, $464 billion, and the year after, $382 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury did announce one small change: It will now include
callable Treasury securities in its buyback program. A callable
security can be repurchased on demand by the Treasury at a certain
date before its maturity. The Treasury also said it would buy back
securities with remaining maturities of 10 years or more.
</P>
<P>
   With the 30-year bond down to new issuance of just $15 billion a
year _ $5 billion of that next week _ a decision on its fate cannot
be far.
</P>
<P>
   Gensler, however, said Wednesday that it was Treasury policy
``to give the market ample notice should we decide to eliminate or
curtail a particular issue. We will continue to follow that
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is likely that the next administration will decide the
fate of the 30-year bond. The current one has one more chance, at
the next quarterly news conference announcing Treasury intentions,
on Nov. 1, the Wednesday before Election Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
