<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-INT-COLUMN0803-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spanish teams still spending
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The spending spree in Spain continues. And the arms
race between mortal enemies Real Madrid and Barcelona is heating up
to what could be astronomic proportions by the time the transfer
period ends later this month.
</P>
<P>
   A week after Madrid pried Portuguese midfielder Luis Figo right
out from under it, Barcelona used most of the world-record $56
million transfer fee to reshape its attack. The Arsenal midfield
duo of Emmanuel Petit and Marc Overmars cost a combined $43
million, and young Spanish midfielder Gerard Lopez comes from
Valencia for another $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Barca made world player of the year Rivaldo the
richest player on the planet by re-signing him to a three-year deal
worth around $6 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Real Madrid hasn't slowed down, either. A Madrid sports daily
reported Tuesday that Real is vying for Zinedine Zidane, the French
midfield maestro. The proposed deal is $50 million and midfielder
Flavio Conceicao, who led Deportivo La Coruna to the Spanish title
and is a prime target of Juventus, Zidane's employer.
</P>
<P>
   Argentine midfielder Fernando Redondo, facing the prospect of
reduced playing time with Madrid because of recent acquisition
Figo, quickly moved to AC Milan for nearly $17 million.
</P>
<P>
   Valencia, European runner-up to Real Madrid, is staying busy,
too, albeit more modestly. French captain Didier Deschamps and
Atletico Madrid castoff Ruben Baraja will replenish the midfield,
and Slovenian striker Zlatko Zahovic signed for a bargain at $8
million.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the dizzying activity has been a two-nation
deal. In Spain and Italy, the egos of flamboyant club chairmen are
providing equally gluttonous fans with star-studded lineups, no
matter the price. It also helps that clubs can sign their own
television contracts, providing the richer clubs with even more
cash.
</P>
<P>
   In England, TV revenues are shared and teams are run as
button-down, bottom-line businesses, not glorified social clubs.
That mentality prevails even at Manchester United, the richest club
in the world. Its crosstown rival at Manchester City, just promoted
to the Premier League, dropped $6.5 million Tuesday for Paulo
Wanchope, West Ham's Costa Rican striker. It wasn't much less than
United spent for French goalkeeper Fabien Barthez, its only major
addition.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Petit and Overmars from Arsenal wasn't
surprising, because they had been unhappy with the London club. But
after only a season in the Premier League, 20-year-old striker
Robbie Keane is leaving Coventry City for Inter Milan, where his
playing time isn't guaranteed. A $20 million transfer fee was too
hard to pass up. Keane joins a crowded front line of Christian
Vieri, Ivan Zamorano and newly signed Turk Hakan Sukur; Ronaldo
might miss another season with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Stewards of the English game have been bemoaning influx of
foreign players in recent years. The greater worry might be the
exodus of some of its best homegrown talent to the continent.
</P>
<P>
   BLATTER: ROTATE CUP SITES
</P>
<P>
   FIFA boss Sepp Blatter will unveil his plans for rotating World
Cup sites today when the executive committee convenes in Zurich for
a three-day FIFA Congress. The reception could be chilly. It is
essentially the same 24-man gang that voted 12-11 last month to
award the 2006 site to Germany over South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The one abstention, New Zealand's Charles Dempsey, resigned his
post under pressure, and the South African organizing committee has
vowed to push for an arbitration process. Blatter, who spent
enormous political capital campaigning for South Africa, said the
2006 decision won't be overturned but the World Cup should be
hosted evenly across all six confederations in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ENGLAND: GINOLA GOES TO VILLA
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, he was the Premier League's player of the year.
But last season, French midfielder David Ginola quickly fell out of
favor with Tottenham manager George Graham. On Monday, he completed
a move to Aston Villa and parted with some choice words for the
taciturn Graham, who responded in kind.GERMANY: EFFENBERG SAYS NO
</P>
<P>
   Despite persuasions from new coach Rudi Voller, Bayern Munich
midfielder Stefan Effenberg says he won't play for Germany again. .
. . Borussia Dortmund defender Stefan Reuter will miss three months
with a knee injury, putting a dent in new coach Matthias Sammer's
rebuilding efforts. . . . Alexander Zickler netted a hat trick as
Bayern Munich routed Hertha Berlin 5-1 Tuesday to win the German
League Cup.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: VICTORY EASES ANXIETY
</P>
<P>
   A convincing, emotional 3-1 victory over Argentina last
Wednesday put Brazil back on track in World Cup qualifying and
might have saved the job of coach Wanderley Luxemburgo. But he
still has a tall task, with one-third of the South American
schedule complete. Two goals from Vampeta paced Brazil in Sao
Paulo, but Luxemburgo, who has employed a revolving door roster,
doesn't have a lethal striker to play with Rivaldo. Captain Cafu
has feuded openly with the coach, and the Brazilian press is still
obsessed about a loss to Paraguay last month, only the second,
ever, in qualifying for Brazil. An Aug. 15 trip to Chile could be
revealing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
