<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-BUSH-ART-ABRIDGED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE W. BUSH: A MAN OF PARADOXES AND SURPRISING ACCOMPLISHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: A longer version slugged GOP-BUSH is also moving.)  
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT6 and 17 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF and FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Six years ago, when George W. Bush ran for
governor of Texas, even his parents expected him to lose. Friends
and relatives say that the elder Bushes worried that George W.
would be forced to bow again, as he had several times before, to
failure.
</P>
<P>
   But that story had a surprise ending: George W. won, and in the
process launched himself, without any grand plan or intricate
forethought, on a trajectory that on Thursday will place him in the
spotlight here as the Republican nominee for president, continuing
along what historians may some day recall as a most remarkable path
to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is almost an accidental candidate, a cocky and cheerful
fellow who drifted through much of his life and who was largely
unknown in America until he assumed his first political office in
1995. Yet he now leads the polls and will have, if elected, one of
the thinnest resumes in public service of any president in the last
century.
</P>
<P>
   There still is a great deal about his beliefs and leadership
style _ about the kind of president he would be _ that remains
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   He is a man who sometimes tortures the English language,
puzzling audiences with references to the ``vile'' hemisphere''
(instead of ``vital'') and tailpipe ``admissions'' (instead of
``emissions''), and mystifying a group of schoolchildren during
National Perseverance Month with when earnestly counseled them,
``You've got to preserve,'' as if they should all rush out to can
tomatoes. His odd grammar syntax challenges journalists trying to
quote him, because his subjects and verbs often disagree.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he has a dazzling charm, tremendous social skills, a bold
self-confidence, growing political savvy, great popularity among
the Texans who know him best _ and a past littered with opponents
who underestimated him. Those who have worked with Bush, Democrats
as well as Republicans, mostly say that contrary to all the jokes,
he is smart, shrewd and a quick study.
</P>
<P>
   The paradoxes go on. He is the law-and-order candidate, the
amiable governor who presides over a stream of executions, the
preacher of traditional moral values, the mover behind a convention
that called for giving young people the ``moral strength'' to
resist drugs. And yet he was arrested twice in college for pranks,
and he avoided military service in Vietnam, abused alcohol and
dances around questions in ways that suggest that he used illegal
drugs himself.
</P>
<P>
   He steers a profoundly conservative path. And yet he can startle
lily-white Republican audiences full of stout women in pearls with
sympathetic remarks about Mexican immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   He is the ultimate outsider candidate, dripping with scorn about
the ways of Washington and disdainful of Ivy League institutions,
always deeply proud of his frontier roots in the rattlesnake
country of Midland, Texas. And he is the ultimate insider
candidate, a Yale and Harvard graduate whose Rolodex brims with the
names of corporate and political titans.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Republicans, he rejects quotas used for affirmative
action as unfair. Yet he himself was a beneficiary of the
affirmative action enjoyed that in the 1950s that helped boys like
him get into high schools like Andover or colleges like Yale,
because their fathers had gone there before. If Bush has an
ideology, it is personal, not political; it is simply loyalty. It
is a deep loyalty to his father and to friends who have stood by
him and his family. Many of his top aides have been friends for
many years or decades, and loyalty was again a subtext when Bush
chose as his running mate Dick Cheney, the defense secretary under
President Bush. The Texas governor was not merely going to restore
honor and integrity to the White House, as he pledged in many a
stump speech. He was going to reunite the personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Better than virtually any other politician in America today,
Bush reflects Kipling's ideal _ ``If you can talk with crowds and
keep your virtue, or walk with kings _ nor lose the common touch.''
He has already hobnobbed with Queen Elizabeth II and gets along
equally brilliantly with beer-bellied baseball fans; he would be a
gold medalist in small talk if it were an Olympic sport. Yet he is
the scion of one of America's great most prominent political
families.
</P>
<P>
   (The word ``dynasty'' is taboo around the Bushes, arousing such
annoyance that its mention sometimes turns Bush's charm congealing
into something close to icy fury. But Bush is a direct descendant
of President Franklin Pierce on his mother's side and of a more
recent president on his father's side.)
</P>
<P>
   Bush often seems an echo of Shakespeare's Prince Hal, the
likable but dissolute son of King Henry IV. Hal sobers up when he
inherits the crown as Henry V _ and ultimately becomes a model
leader who is a better ruler for his past wildness. One of the most
interesting questions about Bush is whether he will grow in the
same way.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there are signs that he has matured as power
approaches. For much of his life, his awesome people skills were
undermined by his volatile temper, his sharp tongue, his tendency
to hold grudges. But when he ran for governor in 1994, his
opponent, Ann Richards, thought it would be easy to goad him into
losing his cool and humiliating himself; instead he surprised his
friends and rivals alike with his steadiness under pressure and a
new-found discipline.
</P>
<P>
   That discipline and self-restraint were have been evident in a
taut campaign this year, in which Bush kept his temper in check and
relentlessly stayed ``on message.'' After a divisive primary
season, he managed better than many had expected unite the
Republican Party and get what he wanted in this convention.
</P>
<P>
   His name and connections helped him, of course, and without them
it is difficult to imagine that he would be a candidate today (a
proposition that Bush does not really argue with, although he hates
to talk about it).
</P>
<P>
   Bush's self-confidence leaves him one of the least neurotic
people on the planet, and also one of the least inclined to examine
himself. He glides along, glibly and optimistically, confident that
his innate cleverness will make up for whatever else he lacks,
deliberately ignoring the slings and arrows of his outrageous good
fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't read half of what you write,'' he told the press corps
on his campaign plane last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't listen to half of what you say,'' one of the
reporters shot back.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's apparent,'' Bush replied, ``in the other half of what I
read.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
