   C.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA: MISSION TO WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   The new, democratic leaders of Croatia have been granted the
official visit to Washington that the late president, Franjo
Tudjman, was never allowed. President Stipe Mesic and Prime
Minister Ivica Racan, opposition leaders elected this year, are
scheduled to arrive on Monday for meetings with President Clinton
and other administration officials. They have moved Croatia away
from Tudjman's strident nationalism and closer to Western aims in
the Balkans, but face huge fiscal problems and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG: MIGRANT PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Angry migrants from mainland China set a fire inside Hong Kong's
immigration headquarters after being refused papers that would have
allowed them to remain in the former British colony. Forty-six
people were injured in the blaze, which erupted after the migrants
doused the 13th floor with a flammable liquid. The right of
mainland Chinese to live in Hong Kong has been a volatile issue
since Beijing overturned a local court ruling that granted
residency to some migrants.  &QL;
</P>
