<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRIS-AOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING BLOCKED MAIL, MARKET RESEARCHER SUES E-MAIL PROVIDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Calif.)   By LAURIE J. FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harris Interactive Inc., the nation's largest online market
research company, has filed a lawsuit against America Online and
other e-mail service providers charging those companies unlawfully
blocked e-mail from Harris to its survey participants.
</P>
<P>
   Harris says the service providers all subscribe to the Realtime
Blackhole List, an e-mail blocking service maintained by Mail Abuse
Prevention System, or MAPS, a not-for-profit company that tracks
e-mail abuse. The purpose is curbing unsolicited mass e-mail, known
as spam. MAPS, of Redwood City, Calif., is also named as a
defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Harris officials insist that the company does not send
unsolicited e-mail, and that all its participants register to take
part in its surveys. All survey participants, they said, have
several chances to opt out.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed on Monday in U.S. District Court for the
Western District of New York, seeks an injunction removing the
block on its e-mail, and unspecified monetary damages. The suit
names more than a dozen companies, including Microsoft's HotMail,
Bellsouth, Juno Online Services and Qwest Communications. A hearing
for a temporary restraining order is scheduled for Thursday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Wednesday, MAPS officials said they were
surprised by the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we have every right to keep a list of people we
choose not to accept mail from,'' said Kelly Thompson, a
spokeswoman for MAPS, which was founded three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said that MAPS did not itself block e-mail, but rather
that it keeps a list that e-mail service providers and other
companies can use to decide whom they should block. She confirmed
that Harris Interactive was on the Realtime Blackhole List, which
includes 3,000 names, because the company does not employ a purely
``opt-in'' approach. Harris counters that it gives users several
direct and easy opportunities to remove themselves from Harris'
participant list.
</P>
<P>
   The suit is not the first complaint filed against MAPS. Last
month, Yesmail.com, an e-mail marketing firm, sued MAPS for being
included on the Blackhole List, but that suit was put on hold after
both sides agreed to work together to clarify their approach to
mass e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, however, insists it does not use the Realtime
Blackhole List as part of its anti-spam activities, and said that
there was no basis for Harris Interactive to have named AOL in its
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, said Rich D'Amato, a spokesman for AOL, ``We are
confident our spam-fighting techniques are entirely appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato said ``it was possible'' that AOL was blocking e-mail
from Harris, but added that AOL would only take such action if
Harris violated AOL's spam-fighting standards, not those of MAPS.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon S. Black, chairman and chief executive of Harris
Interactive, said Harris had no other options but to file a
complaint, calling the MAPS actions ``completely arbitrary and
capricious.'' MAPS, he said, has no right to ``unilaterally
decide'' on appropriate anti-spam standards for the industry. ``The
whole thing is absurd, but costly absurd,'' he said. ``We sued in
part because we're as offended by the process as we are by the
action.''
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail blocking comes at a particularly bad time for Harris,
which is preparing for two major election-related projects in
September, including creating a survey site for the Commission on
Presidential Debates. ``This will make it difficult to do our
Election 2000 Project,'' Black said, referring to a huge online
survey of voter preferences.
</P>
<P>
   Harris' suit also includes an antitrust complaint against AOL,
given that its own online market-research company, Digital
Marketing Systems, is a direct competitor to Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Harris Interactive, based in Rochester, N.Y., conducts more than
1.5 million surveys every quarter. Of Harris Interactive's 6.6
million registered participants, roughly 2.7 million are affected
by the block, Black said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
