<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   California Short of Power In an Age of Deregulation
</P>
<P>
   Four years after it led the nation into a deregulation of the
electric industry, California is at the brink of a breakdown in its
power supply. The nation's most populous state nearly ran out of
power for the third consecutive day. What disturbs California
utility executives and regulators is that this week's crisis has
come even though none of the state's power plants or transmission
lines has failed, at a time when temperatures around the state have
been hot but hardly extraordinary. The state's power supply simply
can no longer keep up with peak demand, they warn.
</P>
<P>
   Proxy Companies Plan to Merge
</P>
<P>
   Georgeson Shareholder Communications, the world's largest proxy
solicitation company, will announce Thursday that it has acquired
Corporate Investor Communications, the third-largest concern in the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Adviser to Celebrities Pleads Guilty
</P>
<P>
   Dana C. Giacchetto, the money manager who promised Hollywood
stars and other artists a safe investment haven, pleaded guilty to
fraud and acknowledged that he misappropriated some of his clients'
money. Giacchetto, 37, faces 46 to 57 months in prison and a fine
of $10,000 to $100,000, as well as restitution payments to fraud
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Falls in Flight to Blue Chips
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index slumped as skittish investors sought
safety in blue-chip stocks or headed for the sidelines waiting for
Friday's report on the job market in July. The Nasdaq composite
fell 27.06 points, or 0.7 percent, to 3,658.46. The Dow Jones
industrial average rose 80.58 points, or 0.8 percent, to 10,687.53.
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index gained 0.60 point, to
1,438.70.
</P>
<P>
   30-Year Bond Receives a Reprieve
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the details of its quarterly auction of Treasury
notes and bonds, the government did not put the 30-year bond on the
endangered species list, surprising some investors. The yield of
the 30-year bond rose to 5.76 percent from 5.72 percent. The yield
on the 10-year note fell to 5.97 percent from 5.98 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Book Publishers in Deal to Combine
</P>
<P>
   Harry N. Abrams agreed to pay about $6 million to acquire the
assets of Stewart, Tabori &AMP; Chang, combining two prominent
publishers of illustrated books.
</P>
<P>
   New-Home Sales Fell 3.7 Percent in June
</P>
<P>
   Sales of new homes fell 3.7 percent in June, to the lowest level
in two and a half years, government figures showed. And in a
separate report, the Conference Board said its index of leading
economic indicators _ a gauge of economic performance over the next
six to nine months _ was unchanged in June, the third consecutive
month without an increase.
</P>
<P>
   AOL Is Sued Over Blocked E-Mail
</P>
<P>
   Harris Interactive, the online market research company, has
filed a suit against America Online and other e-mail providers,
contending those companies unlawfully blocked e-mail from Harris to
its survey participants.
</P>
</TEXT>
