<HEADER>
A1034 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-FORD-HEALTH-1STLD     08-02 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-FORD-HEALTH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
PRESIDENT FORD APPARENTLY STRICKEN BY TWO STROKES &HT;    (EDS: Recasts lead)
 &HT;    By ERIC ROSENBERG
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Physicians treating former President Gerald Ford
for two small strokes said Wednesday that they expect him to
``totally recover'' and be released from a local hospital in
approximately five days.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, 87, checked into Hahnemann Hospital Tuesday night and was
initially diagnosed as suffering a sinus disorder. He was given
antibiotics to take over the next several days and released.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford, who became president when Richard Nixon was forced to
resign in 1974, returned under his own power, briefcase in hand,
Wednesday morning as his condition worsened. Doctors confirmed
after additional tests that he had suffered the strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Schwartzman, the hospital's chief of neurology, said
that by Wednesday afternoon Ford still was dizzy and had slurred
speech and trouble swallowing. But the neurologist added that
``President Ford is improving. He is much better.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Ford, who will remain hospitalized for ``five days or
so,'' probably suffered one stroke on Monday and another on
Wednesday. Schwartzman said he expected Ford, who had been
attending the Republican National Convention across town, to
``totally recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Ford, the former president's wife, was at his side and was
``very upset but fine,'' Schwartzman said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who was nominated for president by
convention delegates Wednesday night, said in a statement that
``America loves Gerald and Betty Ford for their integrity, wisdom
and compassion.'' Bush also spoke to Mrs. Ford by phone as did
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore said in a statement that he joins with
all Americans ``in holding President Ford and his family in our
thoughts and prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctors defended their initial decision to send Ford home
Tuesday night, saying that his symptoms were identical to those of
an ear infection. Releasing Ford ``was appropriate for the symptoms
he had last night,'' said Dr. Stephen Klasko, another neurologist
at Hahnemann.
</P>
<P>
   The type of stroke Ford suffered, likely a cerebral thrombosis,
is not usually fatal but can sometimes result in temporary or
permanent physical ailments such as numbness in the limbs and
speech impairment or, in more severe cases, reduced cognitive
skills.
</P>
<P>
   Strokes occur when sections of the brain are deprived of oxygen,
which is needed to sustain cellular life. There are two broad
categories of strokes _ those caused by blockages in arteries in
the brain, which account for roughly 84 percent of all strokes in
the United States, and those caused by ruptured blood vessels in
the brain, which account for 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The latter is more deadly, usually killing half of people who
are stricken, according to Dr. Abdul Nassief, who is on the faculty
at Washington University's stroke center in St. Louis. It was this
type of stroke that killed Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., last month.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, however, was apparently stricken by the less serious
variety, which is often called a ``brain attack.'' Schwartzman said
it occurred near the base of his brain. Other experts said the
location offers the president a good prognosis because that region
does not govern a person's cognitive capabilities or the body's
most crucial organs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a stroke happens at the base of the brain, a person has a
better outcome,'' said Nassief, adding that there is an 80 percent
chance of recovery in such cases. Still, a series of strokes to the
same region of the brain can lessen chances of a full recovery, he
said, leaving the victim with such physical ailments as numbness or
paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   Much like an arterial blockage near the heart that can lead to a
heart attack, this type of stroke occurs after arteries in the
brain have built up sediments that clog their passageways. When the
blood flow is reduced or restricted, the brain is then deprived of
oxygen, killing nerve cells. As the cells die, the part of the body
that they control also is affected.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartzman told reporters that said the former president has a
general hardening of the arteries that usually occurs with
advancing age.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, who is active in numerous health-related charities, last
year recorded a 30-second public service announcement for use on
Michigan television and radio to educate viewers and listeners
about the danger from strokes.
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Heart Association, strokes killed
159,791 people in 1997 and are the third largest cause of death in
the United States behind heart disease and cancer. Strokes are also
the leading cause of long-term disability in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Some 600,000 people suffer a stroke each year. Women account for
61 percent of stroke fatalities. An estimated 4 million Americans
have survived stokes.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be contacted at 202-298-6920 or via e-mail:
eric(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
