<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERLOOKED ROYALS PITCHER MAKES YANKEES TAKE NOTICE
</HEADLINE>
  By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first time Blake Stein visited Yankee Stadium two
years ago, he kept his jacket on while he sat nervously in the
bullpen because he did not want any raucous fans to see the name on
his Oakland Athletics uniform. Some of Stein's teammates warned him
that the fans would verbally harass him if they found out who he
was, so Stein kept his jacket buttoned and tried to remain
anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Stein, who is now with the Kansas City Royals, was not anonymous
Wednesday, and everyone noticed the name on his uniform because he
frustrated the New York Yankees in meandering to a 4-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was a listless day at Yankee Stadium. The sun finally poked
through and it was warm, dry and humid, weather suitable for
playing baseball or taking a nap. The Yankees did more of the
latter against Stein.
</P>
<P>
   While Stein stymied the Yankees on one run and two hits in eight
innings, some Yankees did not feel as if they had been dominated
because Stein walked six and allowed base runners in eight innings.
But Stein stopped the Yankees in a rare way, feeding them fastballs
as he fell behind in the count and then getting them to sock
harmless fly balls to the deepest parts of the Stadium in left
field and center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps me realize I do have a place here,'' Stein said. ``I
can pitch in the big leagues. The Yankees are one of the best teams
in baseball for the last four or five years and one of the best
this year. To come in and pitch this way is a really good
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees looked sluggish when the Royals rapped Denny Neagle
for three runs in the second inning, and they never really
recovered. Neagle's first pitch of the game produced a broken-bat
single, and his second pitch resulted in a bunt single. After three
pitches, Neagle furiously rubbed a baseball and waved to the fans
in the right-field bleachers who chanted his name. He should have
waved for help because it got stickier after his 21-pitch first.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle told Roger Clemens that he hates having difficult innings
early in games because it drains him. Sure enough, four of the
first five Royals clubbed hits in the second inning, and three of
them scored. Neagle did not have a decent slider or fastball, and
he felt helpless while losing for the first time in his four starts
as a Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has those days when they struggle,'' said Neagle, who
gave up three earned runs and 11 hits in seven innings. ``I felt
like it was going to be one of those days where I battled. I
battled and kept us in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Not really. Because of Stein, the Yankees were barely in the
game. So Stein, who entered the game with a 7-13 record and a 5.89
earned run average in his career, topped Neagle, who had been 2-0
with a 2.25 ERA in three starts for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You scratch your head, you wonder how that could happen, but
you watched it first hand,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``A
guy goes out there as big as Stein and he can have his way.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein turns 27 today, and the fans behind the dugout definitely
knew who Stein was this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were saying, `Good job, don't ever do it again,''' Stein
said. ``When someone walked in the ninth, they said they'd hate to
see me lose this one, but it would be all right. They were pretty
complimentary.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
