<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1041 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-FORD-ART-2NDLD-WR     08-02 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-FORD-ART-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD EXPECTED TO MAKE FULL RECOVERY AFTER MINOR STROKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Leads to update with more information, Ford's condition as
serious and improving, background on strokes in general; subs
byline.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr. 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Former President Gerald R. Ford was admitted to
the neurological intensive care unit of Hahnemann University
Hospital here Wednesday after suffering what doctors said was at
least one small stroke over the last three days.
</P>
<P>
   After a day of tests, he was listed in ``serious and improving''
condition, with the prognosis good for full recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president should totally recover,'' Dr. Robert J.
Schwartzman, the hospital's chief neurologist, said in a briefing
late Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, who is 87 and served as the nation's 38th president, was
in Philadelphia for the Republican National Convention. Only hours
before being admitted to the hospital, near the city's center, he
had been given a rousing salute by convention delegates for his
brief, generally calming and healing stewardship of the nation in
the embarrassing aftermath of Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   Ford arrived at the hospital at about 9 a.m. Wednesday,
complaining of dizziness, weakness in his left arm and an inability
to speak without slurring his words. He was admitted, hospital
officials later said, after an imaging scan indicated he had
suffered at least one stroke in the brain stem in the rear of his
head.
</P>
<P>
   It was Ford's second visit to the hospital in less than 10
hours, his first having occurred around midnight when, accompanied
by his usual Secret Service security detail, he walked in on his
own complaining of sinus pain. He was given some pain medicine and
released.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials defended their decision to release him
without further tests, saying they felt that they had sufficiently
responded to the symptoms they saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he sought was some pain relief,'' Dr. Wayne Satz, the
hospital's chief of emergency medicine, said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what was different about the symptoms that led to a sinus
infection diagnosis first and later a diagnosis of a stroke, Satz
said the symptoms were more acute in the second hospital visit and
that Ford's wife, Betty, had reported that Ford had also felt ill
earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, before heading for Philadelphia, Mrs. Ford told
doctors, Ford saw a doctor in Colorado, complaining then, as later,
of head pain.
</P>
<P>
   In the convention hall on Tuesday night, while Ford was being
honored, he appeared visibly tired and in one interview noticeably
slurred his words.
</P>
<P>
   News that he had been hospitalized injected a somber note into a
convention that up to then had been one big joyful celebration of
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Hahnemann doctors said they were treating Ford with
blood-thinners in an effort to diminish the likelihood of future
strokes. In someone his age, they emphasized, there was a greater
danger of another stroke than in someone younger.
</P>
<P>
   But a minor stroke is not unusual at that age.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartzman said Ford was ``perfectly awake, functioning
mentally _ that's not a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the former president, Calvin McDowell, said Ford
was ``very alert and ready to go home.'' Should he continue to
recover without any complications, hospitals officials said, he
might be released in five or six days.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is able to take calls,'' McDowell said, ``but we are trying
to insist that he get some rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartzman said he did not think Ford had suffered any brain
damage from the stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will all clear, mainly in his balance center,''
he added. ``That should all recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Brott of the National Stroke Association, said it was
possible that the signs and symptoms Ford spoke about in his visit
to the hospital Tuesday night, when he complained of pain in his
face, dizziness and sleeplessness, would not have immediately
suggested to doctors that a stroke had occurred. Symptoms described
by a patient, Brott said, are often ambiguous and might point to a
cause more likely than a stroke, like an infection.
</P>
<P>
   On the same point, Schwartzman said that a mild stroke ``looks
like an inner ear infection sometimes, sometimes it's hard to tell
the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   A stroke is usually caused by a blood clot blocking a vessel in
the brain, so that cells beyond the blockage do not receive
nutrients, and can thus be injured or die.
</P>
<P>
   The cells affected in Ford's case are in the lower back of the
brain where motor activity, like balance, is controlled.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, when the stroke is small, the damaged brain cells
can recover or the killed cells can be bypassed so that other
healthy cells can perform the same function, leading to complete
recovery.
</P>
</TEXT>
