<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1045 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-1STLD     08-02 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE SETBACKS FOR ISRAEL'S BARAK AS FOREIGN MINISTER RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This version subs for the earlier story by Christopher S.
Wren) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak took another battering
Wednesday in the wake of the Camp David summit meeting when his
foreign minister resigned over Barak's willingness to compromise
with the Palestinians on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister also faced four separate bills in the
Knesset, or parliament, calling for new elections that passed by
the same number of votes that would be needed to topple his
government in a no-confidence vote. The bills had no immediate
impact, but they served to further embolden the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of Foreign Minister David Levy was not
unexpected. He had threatened to quit Wednesday if Barak did not
bring the right into a national unity government. And Levy, who is
known for his keen sense of which way the prevailing political
winds are blowing, had switched sides before when he resigned as
foreign minister from the cabinet of Barak's predecessor, Benjamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, once a commando used to operating alone in enemy
territory, appeared unfazed, even cocky in the face of his latest
challenges, moving with a bouncy step and tight smile through the
tumult in the parliament. At one point, he sat next to Levy _ who
had just resigned with a fiery speech _ clapped him on the back and
shook his hand.
</P>
<P>
   With the parliament now in recess for its three-month vacation,
Barak and his dwindling supporters hope to reach some kind of an
agreement with the Palestinians, and possibly then go to new
elections on the prime minister's own terms, with the elections
serving as a kind of referendum on the peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a few more weeks the dust will settle,'' Barak said. ``We
may have three months to try and consolidate either the peace
negotiations or the government, and this may be the 90 days of the
most important period in the present Israeli agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be able to broaden the base of the government and
continue into the future to achieve our objective,'' said Barak,
with apparent confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Yossi Sarid, a longtime peace advocate and chairman of the
10-seat Meretz party, which has supported Barak's government,
added: ``We have to gain time now, that is the recipe. We have to
gain a few months in order to gain something much more important,
because time won't do its part if we don't do ours. The time will
allow the achievement of an agreement with the Palestinians, and
this is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   But Limor Livnat, a stalwart of the right-wing Likud, shouted
scornfully, ``Don't try to pull any fast ones while the Knesset is
on recess.''
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the conservative Likud party, Ariel Sharon, warned
on Tuesday that what he called his ``Jerusalem Coalition'' would
``stand on guard,'' ready to call parliament back into session if
any agreement threatening Israeli sovereignty over all of Jerusalem
appeared likely.
</P>
<P>
   Before his resignation Wednesday, there had been signs that Levy
was seeking to return to his old home in Likud. During the Camp
David meeting, while he was acting prime minister in Barak's
absence, Levy made a sympathetic visit to hunger-striking settlers
outside the prime minister's residence.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Levy spoke of the ``grave situation'' that had
developed because of the introduction of the once-taboo subject of
Jerusalem at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things touch upon the soul of the people,'' he said.
``It turns out that we are talking about the very heart of ancient
Jerusalem. We are talking about things that the vast majority of
the people are connected in their soul, their past, present and
future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say that the fact of an announcement that we would get
access to the Western Wall takes us backward to the time before the
establishment of the Jewish state,'' Levy added. ``Regarding the
Temple Mount, the Holy of Holies, they refused to understand the
connection of the Jewish people to the Holy of Holies. That is a
denial of our past in this land.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, five bills were introduced Wednesday calling for
dissolution of the parliament and new elections. But because they
will be referred to a committee controlled by Barak, the measures
can be bottled up and produce no immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
   The first bill, introduced by Likud's Silvan Shalom _ who said,
``the `prime minister of the people' has become the prime minister
of one man _ Ehud Barak'' _ received 61 votes in favor, 51 opposed
and six abstentions. Three similar bills each received the same
totals, and as some members drifted away, a final bill received 60
in favor, 47 opposed and six abstentions.
</P>
<P>
   Barak reportedly criticized his colleagues in the One Israel
party during a meeting Wednesday afternoon for not putting up a
decent fight, saying they were coming across as whining and
defeatist. Their problems did not reflect a state of total
collapse, he said, adding the faint-hearted should step aside.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, parliament Speaker Avraham Burg _ a potential
rival _ warned Barak that he was keeping too many decisions to
himself and would stand alone if he did not take other Labor Party
leaders into his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   In the immediate speculation over who would be named foreign
minister, the public security minister, Shlomo Ben-Ami, figured
prominently because the dovish history professor has been a senior
negotiator in the peace talks and meets frequently with Palestinian
security officials. There was also talk of Sarid, the Meretz party
chairman, but he is said to want to regain the Education Ministry
post he resigned in the vain hope of keeping the Shas Party, with
its crucial 17 seats, in Barak's coalition. Shas quit the
government on the eve of the Camp David meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The problems Barak has had in contending with recently changed
election procedures, which have resulted in a fragmented parliament
of small parties that pursue their own interests, were on full
display again Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The five ultra-orthodox members from the United Torah Judaism
party were clumped in the back of the chamber not taking part in
the vote, saying they were under orders from their spiritual
leader, Rabbi Shalom Yosef Elyashiv, to abstain.
</P>
<P>
   Shouting Likud members descended on them and threatened that if
they did abstain, Likud would vote against a bill they have
sponsored granting additional government benefits to large
families. The five votes were duly cast against Barak.
</P>
<P>
   The parliamentary sessions have become so emotional that Burg,
in his summing up of the summer session, expressed concern that the
tension might lead to fisticuffs on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a prayer in my heart, it is that I won't be the
first Knesset speaker in whose term of office there was violence in
the Knesset,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
