<HEADER>
A1051 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-GOP-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS     08-02 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE'S THE BEEF? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and p coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, they are the party of Lincoln, lest we forget.
</P>
<P>
   The only mildly unexpected occurrence in the surprise-free
Republican National Convention this week has been the persistent
effort of the GOP to keep all of us from staring underneath that
big tent George W. Bush keeps talking about.
</P>
<P>
   For the Republicans, it's minority week.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Powell made sense. Everyone likes the idea of Colin Powell
_ perhaps because almost no one knows where he stands on any
substantive political issue. But Condoleezza Rice? Can you honestly
say you knew who she was before Tuesday?
</P>
<P>
   I wonder, though, when the Republicans will get beyond trotting
people out and turn to doing something that might be meaningful for
people of color. For now, as only Rev. Jesse Jackson would put it,
``You got Colin Powell making speeches, but you got Trent Lott
making policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell, whose public political pronouncements have been mostly
confined to his brave support for volunteerism, finally embraced
the role so many have longed for him to play: front man, for a
party that has had few prominent black faces up front.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, Bush's chief foreign policy adviser, followed Powell on
Tuesday night by assuring us that her candidate is a tough guy who
will stand tall against our enemies, never mind all that talk about
his lack of ``gravitas.''
</P>
<P>
   National political conventions long ago mutated into television
shows, then pep rallies, a moment to put forth the best possible
face of a candidate. For the Republicans, still smarting from the
lessons of eight years ago, that means convincing America that they
aren't the party that hates women, minorities, and gays. Bully for
them.
</P>
<P>
   Between Reconstruction and the Depression, many blacks regularly
voted Republican, largely out of loyalty to the president who freed
the slaves. FDR changed that, and the civil rights movement that
followed made the exodus permanent. Despite all the social changes
of the past two generations, nothing has ever shaken the allegiance
of most of black America to the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, Bush has spent a considerable part of his down time
since he vanquished John McCain attempting to prove that
``compasssionate conservatism'' has something to say to those who
have long had no use for his party.
</P>
<P>
   He has offered to overhaul the Immigration and Naturalization
Service, to make it more compassionate to immigrants. He has touted
the improved test scores of black students in Texas. His campaign
has made sure we know he got 27 percent of the black vote when he
won election to his second term as governor in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Still, W. has a tough row to hoe. Both his father, in 1992, and
Bob Dole, in 1996, barely broke into double digits among black
voters. Given the enormous popularity of the Clinton presidency
among blacks _ a popularity I'm not sure Clinton's policies fully
deserve _ George W. Bush doesn't figure to do much better than the
first George Bush. Bill Bradley thought he could make a run at the
black vote running against Al Gore in the primaries, and he has
been on vacation for months.
</P>
<P>
   Black America has a strange relationship with both parties, but
especially the GOP. Even black Republican candidates, such as they
are, win only sporadic support from black voters. That isn't an
accident, and no roster of speakers will be enough to change it.
</P>
<P>
   But the token gestures just keep on coming. If not for a traffic
accident and a few other mishaps, Massachusetts Republicans would
be patting themselves on the back right now for recruiting Jack E.
Robinson as a Senate candidate, even though under the best of
circumstances he would have absolutely no shot at toppling Edward
M. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder what the minority voters who are meant to be swayed by
the images flickering on their TV screens will find in the
Republican platform to bolster a belief in George W. Bush. I wonder
if he believes his revolving-door death penalty policy is just the
thing to make me feel safer and more secure. I wish he would talk
in something other than platitudes about how he would pick his
Supreme Court nominees. And as long as he and his supporters are so
comfortable invoking legacy, I can't help remembering that part of
his father's legacy is Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans seem to be having themselves a fine party, and
I'm glad to see some blacks on the guest list. But I have some
questions about what happens when the party's over.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Adrian Walker's e-mail address is walker(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
