NYT-08-02-00 2151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0453 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      08-02 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: EVEN BY CONVENTION STANDARDS, GOP SHORT ON
SPECIFICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ It is all so murky, the rhetoric here, that you
might think yourself back in the presidential campaign of 1952,
when Dwight D. Eisenhower promised, ``I shall go to Korea,'' but
supplied no details about what he would do to end the war once he
got there.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe 1968 or 1972, in the heyday of Richard Nixon, another
campaigner often short on specifics. Confident that he was well
ahead of Hubert Humphrey in 1968, he told the nation he would end
the war in Vietnam, but he never bothered to say what he had in
mind. Four years later, more confident, he stayed off the stump,
running the first Rose Garden campaign.
</P>
<P>
   This year, en route to the nomination for president, Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas has hammered the Clinton administration's foreign
policy, suggesting that it has been inept, ill-focused and lacking
in clear priorities.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech in Washington on May 23, he said ``the world has
changed faster than United States policy'' and called for a fresh
approach to nuclear weapons and a more comprehensive missile
defense system. At other times he has hinted he would spend less
energy on humanitarian missions and more on dealing with great
powers like China and Russia and with America's allies.
</P>
<P>
   But the first three nights of a Republican convention that Bush
had promised would lay new ideas before the American people,
including a night designated as an occasion to discuss national
security, produced few details of what a Bush administration might
do overseas. The speeches have been vague even by the lax standards
of convention oratory, an art form that was tailor-made for
bloviation.
</P>
<P>
   Most of what has been said dealt with Bush's personal qualities,
not with policy _ grist for People magazine, not Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``No specifics, no nuance,'' said the historian Michael
Beschloss. ``I think the lack of content may be unprecedented. They
argue that Bill Clinton paid less attention to foreign policy than
any president since Herbert Hoover, which may be fair. But they
have given no example here of how they would lead or where they
would go.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be that Bush himself will fill in the gaps when he
appears before the convention on Thursday night. But if so, he will
change the pattern that has emerged this week.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Colin Powell, chairman of the joint chiefs of staff
during the war in the Persian Gulf, talked almost exclusively about
domestic affairs, including the ills afflicting urban areas, the
need to pay more attention to the education of the nation's
children and the problems of minorities. Only at the end did he
look overseas, assuring the delegates that Bush ``will not repeat
the mistakes of the past and let our insurance policy, our armed
forces, fall into disrepair.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's speeches consisted mostly of similar generalizations.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Schwarzkopf, who commanded American troops in the Middle
East in the war, said that American military strength had withered
since then. But he gave no prescription for rebuilding it, except
to voice a wish for ``another commander in chief named George Bush
with Dick Cheney on his team.'' Cheney, nominated Wednesday night
as Bush's running mate, served as defense secretary during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona, whom Bush defeated for the
nomination, said that Bush ``knows well that there is no safe
alternative to American leadership, and he will not squander this
unique moment in history by allowing America to retreat behind
empty threats, false promises and uncertain diplomacy'' _ an
indirect indictment of Clinton, presumably, but one unaccompanied
by even shadowy proposals for policy initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's main foreign-policy adviser, Condoleezza Rice, was only
slightly more forthcoming. She said that Bush would not regard the
American military as ``a global police force,'' without a clue as
to where and under what circumstances troops should be used; she
promised that Bush would move at the earliest possible date to
institute ``the deployment of effective missile defenses,'' without
saying when that might be, and asserted that Bush ``recognizes the
challenge the Chinese government poses to our interests and
values,'' without outlining how that challenge might be met.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what she said sounded like cheerleading, as when she
praised Bush _ ``the George W. Bush that I know'' _ as a man of
``uncommonly good judgment'' who is ``focused and consistent'' and
knows ``that we Americans are at our best when we exercise power
without fanfare and arrogance.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Cheney joined in the chorus, praising Bush in
his advance text as ``a man who has the courage and the vision and
the goodness to be a great president.'' Big changes, he said, are
coming to Washington, after eight years of ``squandered
opportunities.'' He did not name them.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from promising, like almost everyone, to devote more
resources to the armed forces, Cheney also concentrated on life at
home. He talked about education and Social Security and working
together with Democrats to end the air ``of bitterness and ill will
and partisan strife'' in Washington, but not about Europe or Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Like Clinton eight years ago, Bush began the campaign with an
inconvenient dearth of foreign policy experience. Like Clinton, and
unlike Vice President Al Gore, his Democratic rival, he has no
service in Vietnam to dwell upon with pride.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Bush surrounded himself with an impressive array of
national security experts, most of them veterans of past Republican
administrations, including Rice, Paul Wolfowitz, Robert Zoellick
and Richard Perle. (The notable exception is James A. Baker, one of
his father's secretaries of state, whose performance in his
father's unsuccessful 1992 campaign the younger Bush has often
faulted).
</P>
<P>
   In a ``coming-out'' speech at the Ronald Reagan Library near Los
Angeles last Nov. 19, George W. Bush won good marks for what most
experts considered a polished performance. His choice of Cheney
lent further heft on foreign policy to the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   But there remains a long list of issues on which the delegates,
and those across the country following the convention in the news
media, have so far heard little. Among them are strategies for
dealing with the intractable problems of Russia and China, the
issue of expanding NATO further into Eastern Europe, the manifold
complications of expanding free world trade and the doubts that
surround the present requirement that the Pentagon be prepared to
fight simultaneous wars in two different theaters of war.
</P>
<P>
   There are divisions within the Republican Party on issues like
Kosovo that have yet to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush leaves too much unspoken for too long, he may hand Gore
a significant opening. Gore, after all, has had broad experience in
foreign-policy matters, first on Capitol Hill, then in the White
House. And while the Clinton administration has had its flops
overseas, in places like Africa and Haiti, it has also recorded
significant achievements, particularly in its efforts to promote
peace in Northern Ireland and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Bush may have decided that too much talk about foreign
policy is bad business. He has talked often to friends and
acquaintances about his father's loss to Bill Clinton eight years
ago, when the elder Bush focused on foreign affairs and the
Arkansas neophyte emphasized the economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 2156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1056 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-FLA-MACK-ART-NYTR &LR;      08-02 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-MACK-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SEN. CONNIE MACK, GOP CONVENTION IS A HOME RUN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) (Eds: Carl Hulse is a correspondent for the
Washington Bureau of the NYT Regional Newspapers Group.) 
 By CARL HULSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ It is only fitting that one of Sen. Connie Mack's
last political at-bats comes in the city where the name of his
legendary grandfather was synonymous with baseball for half a
century.
</P>
<P>
   For Mack, a Florida Republican who is retiring this year, the
Republican National Convention represents a personal trip around
the bases. His last convention as an elected official is being held
in the city where he was born and spent his youth, regularly
traveling with his parents to old Shibe Park at 21st and Lehigh to
watch the family's Philadelphia Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is completing the circle,'' said Mack, as he reminisced
Wednesday about his namesake grandfather, known to all as Mr. Mack.
</P>
<P>
   A catcher and middling hitter, the original Connie Mack became
manager and owner of the Athletics with the formation of the
American League at the turn of the 20th century. His teams went on
to win nine pennants and finish last 17 times before Mack, then in
his 80s, retired in 1950. The team eventually relocated to Kansas
City and then Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Tall and thin, the elder Mack roamed the dugout in starched
civilian clothes and a straw boater, and appeared a bit austere.
But not in the eyes of his grandson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was my grandfather and he always acted with kindness and
gentleness toward his grandchildren,'' said Mack. His assignment
when the aging manager traveled to Florida for spring training was
to wait in grandfather's room beginning at 5:30 a.m. so he could
provide any assistance needed when Mr. Mack awoke.
</P>
<P>
   Like his grandfather, the senator's name is actually Cornelius
McGillicuddy. And while his grandfather's team once adopted the
Republican elephant symbol as a mascot, Mack's political genes were
inherited from the other side of the family.
</P>
<P>
   A step-grandfather who was also a U.S. senator took Mack, his
parents and siblings to a political luncheon during the 1948 GOP
convention in Philadelphia. Mack, who was 7 at the time, recalls
that for some inexplicable reason he stood up during lunch and
yelled, ``I'm a Republican, I'm a Republican,'' drawing a
grandfatherly rebuke.
</P>
<P>
   ``My political career, without me knowing it, started here in
1948,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mack, the third-ranking member of the Senate GOP leadership,
announced last year that he would not seek a third term this
November, and instead wanted to chart a new course in his life.
Republicans gathered at the convention are bemoaning his imminent
departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``My golly, the Senate is going to miss him,'' former President
Bush told Florida delegates Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mack said the whirl of the convention can still stir his juices,
but that he is not second-guessing himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I listen to George Bush and Dick Cheney, I can feel my
political instincts become charged,'' Mack said. ``But it is a
totally different kind of environment now. I am more of an observer
at this stage than a participant.''
</P>
<P>
   Mack could have been much more. He had allies such as Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi eager to push him for the
vice presidency, but Mack declared firmly that he wasn't
interested. His real shot at the No. 2 spot actually came in 1996,
when he was seriously considered by Bob Dole, who later said he
should have selected Mack instead of Jack Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   Mack said Dole might have been scared off by the prospect of
losing a GOP-held Senate seat if their ticket was elected. Mack
said Dole raised the issue during the interview for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going in knowing we might lose a Senate seat, I'm sure that
was something that Bob Dole, with his years of leadership in the
Senate, certainly considered,'' Mack said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mack political line may not be at an end. His son, Connie,
32, is seeking a state legislative seat in South Florida. He is at
the convention with his father, getting some political tips from a
retiring pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being here together in Philadelphia is very special,'' Mack
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
