<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT ISN'T OVER 'TIL IT'S OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Trot Nixon's parents were still watching on TV back
home in North Carolina. In California, Ed Sprague's wife gave up
after 12 innings and went to bed. Pedro Martinez left Safeco Field
before midnight and returned to the team hotel to rest up for the
next start. Jason Varitek's wife was in Georgia, getting whatever
sleep she could get before their infant daughter woke up again.
</P>
<P>
   It was 3:42 a.m. back in Boston when Varitek squatted for the
271st time and signaled for a fastball from lefthander Jeff
Fassero. Varitek never caught the pitch. Seattle center fielder
Mike Cameron spanked it into the right-field seats and the Mariners
were 5-4 winners in 19 innings. It was the sixth-longest game in
100 years of Red Sox baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's game took 5 hours 34 minutes, there were 508 pitches
thrown by 12 hurlers. Sox manager Jimy Williams used 20 of his 24
available players. Brian Daubach, Morgan Burkhart, and Sprague all
played first base. When it ended at almost quarter of 4 in the
morning, there were still 31,000 homes watching the Sox broadcast
back in New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder how many of 'em threw the remote control at the TV,''
said Sox reliever Derek Lowe. ``There's probably 22,000 at Radio
Shack today getting new controls.''
</P>
<P>
   Sox radioman Joe Castiglione said his producers got calls from
fans listening (on the Internet) in Germany, Australia, Hawaii, and
Samoa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also heard from a lot of police departments,'' said
Castiglione.
</P>
<P>
   Varitek caught all 19 innings. He didn't get to sleep until 5
a.m., woke at noon, and was at the park at 3 p.m. to prep for
Pedro's first pitch Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get to sleep when we got back,'' said Varitek.
``But it takes a little while to wind down. I'm probably not as
light on my feet today, but I'm all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Varitek, Lowe, Sprague, Rich Garces, Rolando Arrojo, Tim
Wakefield (who started the game and went eight innings), and Rheal
Cormier were among the first at the park Wednesday. Batting
practice was optional and many players arrived later than usual.
Wakefield said he was available for relief. Varitek said his legs
were fine.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox catcher is a Bunyonesque figure with legs that could
move a blocking sled carrying Rod Beck and Rich Garces. Varitek
said he never caught 19 innings before. That's more than a
doubleheader. He admitted he was getting a little weary when the
game stretched into the 14th inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to really focus to keep my concentration, defensively,''
said Varitek. ``When the hitters would come up, I was trying to
remember how we got them out the other sive or six times they were
up. We did a good job with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Varitek worked the later innings, a collection of Sox
relievers and bench players _ people who'd already participated _
gathered in front of the enormous clubhouse TV and watched the end
of the game together.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was all of us in here and just nine dudes out there
still playing,'' said Beck, who pitched two innings of perfect
relief.
</P>
<P>
   Varitek won Monday's game with a three-run homer in the eighth
and had a chance to be the hero again, but he popped up the first
pitch he saw from Seattle closer Kazuhiro Sasaki with the bases
loaded and two out in the 19th.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a better pitch than I had the night before when I hit
the homer,'' said the catcher, who went 1 for 9 on the night. ``I
just sliced through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero, Friday's starter against the Royals at Fenway, had been
told before the game to be ready for bullpen duty because it was
his day to throw and the Sox pen went eight innings in relief of
Ramon Martinez Monday. Bryce Florie, who worked three innings
Monday, was the only Sox reliever who didn't pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron was Seattle's leadoff batter in the 12th and saw 11
pitches before driving the fastball over the wall. He fouled off
seven two-strike serves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He fouled off everything I had,'' said Fassero.
</P>
<P>
   Varitek didn't stick around to see Cameron cross the plate.
Varitek walked straight to the dugout as the Mariners (and the
mascot, Moose, who was wearing pajamas) came out to greet their
hero.
</P>
<P>
   The postgame locker room food spread got some extra attention.
There would be no room service when the team got back to its hotel.
There were still a handful of autograph seekers outside the hotel
when the team bus pulled up after 2 a.m., Seattle time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told 'em to go the (expletive) home,'' said Beck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by
e-mail at dshaughnessy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
