u p BC-POLITICAL-SURFING-NYT     08-02 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-SURFING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL SURFING: AT LAST, SOMETHING TO REPORT
</HEADLINE>
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a while, the cable television reporters and Internet
correspondents seemed energized, if a little startled, by the
prospect of actual news to report from the Republican National
Convention. Until Wednesday, as has been endlessly pointed out, the
convention had been a carefully scripted infomercial punctuated by
scattered protests and pundits on autopilot.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly there was the disclosure that former President
Gerald R. Ford had gone to the hospital with what was thought to be
a sinus infection but was actually a stroke. That followed the
beginning of a whiff of a semi-controversy about former President
George Bush attacking President Clinton for attacking his son.
</P>
<P>
   The all-news channels and streaming Web sites suddenly had
something to cut back to regularly (correspondents standing outside
the hospital, promising updates on Ford's condition) and a fresh
bone to gnaw on (whether Bush should have kept quiet).
</P>
<P>
   Some news outlets that had done interviews with Ford on Tuesday,
before he was hospitalized, replayed the tapes throughout the
afternoon, so viewers could watch the 87-year-old former president
slurring his words.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the pundit class was making much of Bush's
remark that he was growing irritated with President Clinton's
attacks on his son. This allowed Democrats and some pundits to
argue that Gov. George W. Bush of Texas apparently needed his daddy
to protect him.
</P>
<P>
   Teapot Dome it was not. But it was about the only spice on the
menu.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, when President Bush and his wife, Barbara,
appeared on ABC's ``Good Morning, America,'' he was promising to be
good. ``They're making a federal case about it,'' he said. ``It's
better to say nothing about it, future, now, nothing, period.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's host, Charles Gibson, however, knew raw meat when he
saw it and prodded once more. ``Not going to talk about it,'' Bush
insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Then Mrs. Bush jumped to her husband's aid, saying that his was
not really a personal attack, just an observation about the state
of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Gibson detected sirloin. Oh, is there something wrong
with the state of the presidency? Has it been sullied? And who
might have been responsible for that?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know who I mean,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush tried to shush his wife. ``They're going to get all over
your case,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There they were, working it out, right on live television. It
was like being a fly on the wall in Kennebunkport, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, though, the pundits seemed to have gnawed
all the meat off the bone. Besides, Governor Bush had finally
arrived in Philadelphia after stalking the convention for three
days, and was himself criticizing Clinton and Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media is making too much of this,'' a former White House
communications director, Don Bauer, said in response to an e-mail
question on a live ``Talk Back'' segment on CNN. ``They love a
sideshow.''
</P>
<P>
   Speakout.com continued its experiment with MSNBC, offering Web
surfers the opportunity to rate the impact of the major convention
speeches as they were being delivered. Those at home could
manipulate bars on their computer screens as a speech was being
given to indicate whether they agreed or disagreed with the
speaker.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict on Sen. John McCain's speech on Tuesday night was
that men and women liked it much the same. Democrats and
independents were put off by the middle of the speech, when the
senator talked about national pride.
</P>
<P>
   This just in: A live Web cam trained on the convention podium at
2:20 p.m. showed two people standing next to a big plant, talking.
It was too dark to see who they were. Another Web cam, at 3:35
p.m., trained on the main entrance outside showed an empty golf
cart and a man leaning against a chain-link fence. His back was to
the camera, but he was wearing a bright green shirt.
</P>
<P>
   In a column for the CNN Web page, Robert Novak disclosed what
had been the unspoken scandal of this convention, the scarcity of
tickets to key events. Seats that once would have gone to party big
shots were going this year to major donors. The Republican
money-raisers have ``hijacked the party,'' complained the Ohio
Republican chairman, Robert Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   For political junkies, Howard Mortman, national editor for the
Hotline, the Web site produced by the National Journal Group,
continued his series of ``Extreme Mortman'' columns, in which he
makes the convention party scene. He wrote of seeing the pundit Ann
Coulter momentarily resist a television reporter's interview
request before she ``succumbed to the temptations of the forbidden
microphone fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   And Lewis Black, a political humorist reporting for the Comedy
Central cable network, complained in a streaming Web feed that he
and his colleagues had been refused floor credentials and had been
reduced to covering the event from a college dormitory several
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had any brains, we could have been on a cruise ship,
watching it on television and sipping cocktails,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   Make ours a double.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 2212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0459 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-HALBERSTAM-NYT &LR;      08-02 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HALBERSTAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND RABBI SHLOMO HALBERSTAM, 92, LEADER OF BOBOV HASIDIM 
</HEADLINE>
   By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Grand Rabbi Shlomo Halberstam, a Holocaust survivor
whose gentle charisma nurtured the exuberant postwar rebirth of the
Bobov Hasidic sect in Brooklyn and around the world, died at
Maimonides Medical Center on Wednesday after a long illness. He was
92.
</P>
<P>
   A regal-looking man with a great silver beard and horn-rimmed
glasses, Rabbi Halberstam was known for his love of dancing with
the Torah and for his artful way of sidestepping the internal
squabbles that plague other Hasidic sects.
</P>
<P>
   But his enduring accomplishment, Judaic scholars say, was
rebuilding the Bobov sect, a group of Jews based in southeastern
Poland that was nearly exterminated by the Nazis during World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   Under 55 years of his consistently conciliatory leadership, the
Bobovers became the leading Hasidic group in Borough Park, which is
the most Hasidic section of Brooklyn. It is a neighborhood, city
planners say, where the fertility rate is double that of New York
as a whole, where families with eight children are not unusual and
where Halberstam convinced ultra-Orthodox Jews that they could
thrive without compromising their way of life.
</P>
<P>
   At his funeral Wednesday, about 6,000 mourners crushed into
Bobover Yeshiva Bnei Zion at 15th Avenue and 48th Street, with an
additional 30,000 or so standing outside in steaming heat listening
to loudspeakers. During the ceremony, many mourners wailed and
ripped their clothing, signifying that the rabbi was like a father
to them.
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam's two sons spoke at the service. Rabbi Naftali
Halberstam, the eldest and the chosen successor in the Bobov sect,
escaped the Nazis with his father and came to New York after the
war. He spoke of his grandfather, the Bobover grand rabbi, who was
killed by the Nazis. The second son, Rabbi Ben Zion Halberstam,
said his father had picked up the ashes from the Holocaust and
created the community that was now mourning him.
</P>
<P>
   The Bobover Hasidim are part of an ecstatic religious movement
of the late 17th century that broke from traditional rabbinical
Judaism for reasons that included objections about materialistic
excess. The various sects among the Hasidim share similar beliefs,
with their differences owing to geographical origin, dress and
style of leadership among grand rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   The Bobovers, whose name derives from a village in southeastern
Poland, tend to look to their grand rabbi more than most other
sects for advice on business, marriage and family matters,
according to William B. Helmreich, a professor of sociology and
Judaic studies at the City University of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobover Hasidim is known for not emphasizing disputes,'' said
Helmreich, author of ``The World of the Yeshiva'' (Ktav, 2000).
``They are considered very open and tolerant to other groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Judaic experts said Halberstam enjoyed extraordinary
success in recruiting Jews in America to the Bobov sect because he
was both nonconfrontational and charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a market economy in America in religion, and whoever
has the charisma attracts the most people,'' said Samuel Heilman, a
professor of Jewish studies and sociology at Queens College.
``Rabbi Halberstam was successful, and the numbers show that.''
</P>
<P>
   Heilman estimated there are 20,000 followers of the Bobov sect,
although some other Jewish leaders said the sect had more than
100,000 members who are concentrated in New York, Montreal,
Toronto, Miami and London.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Satmar and Lubavitch Hasidic sects, which are also
prominent in Brooklyn, the Bobovers have flourished with little
public infighting. A leadership squabble dating to the death 21
years ago of a grand rabbi continues to divide the Satmar sect, and
the Lubavitch movement remains riven by a dispute over whether
their late leader, Rabbi Menachem Mendel Schneerson, was the
Messiah.
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam years ago designated his oldest son as his successor,
Heilman said. At the funeral Wednesday, he said the congregation
enthusiastically welcomed the son as their new leader.
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam arrived in New York in the late 1940s, with only his
oldest son. The rest of his family had been killed. During this
time, according to Heilman, he apparently had a crisis of faith,
shaved his beard and lost his desire to be a rabbi. But he soon
recovered and, Heilman said, his crisis of faith proved
inspirational to many Orthodox Jews reeling in poverty and
psychological distress in the wake of the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of his followers felt that if the rabbi can forgive God
for the Holocaust, then we can, too,'' Heilman said.
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam took great pleasure in dancing and singing. His
dancing frames a recent documentary movie about the Hasidim called
``A World Apart _ Hasidic Life in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam is survived by his two sons and five daughters, along
with many grandchildren and great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
