<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON ASSAILS LAZIO ON `MULTIPLE CHOICE' STAND ON ABORTION
</HEADLINE>
   (With LAZIO) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLD WESTBURY, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton received the
endorsement of Planned Parenthood on Wednesday and used the
occasion to exhaustively criticize Rep. Rick Lazio, her Republican
opponent in the U.S. Senate race, for his position on abortion and
for what she implied was his petulant reaction to her attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you say something that's accurate about someone's record,
if they don't want anybody to know about it, they say it's
negative,'' Clinton told a group of several hundred people at the
State University of New York here.
</P>
<P>
   ``So for weeks now, I have said that he sided with the insurance
companies and voted for the Republican patients' bill of rights
instead of a patients' bill of rights that will hold HMOs
accountable,'' she continued. ``And I mean, my goodness, he just
has gone crazy about that. He had everybody saying that that was so
negative, and so mean. I don't understand it. He's either going to
accept his record, or he's going to have to continue to try to run
away from it and avoid accountability for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Lazio opposed a Democratic version of a so-called
patients' bill of rights that would give patients the right to sue
health maintenance organizations for mistreatment. Lazio supported
a Republican bill that instead would provide tax deductions to help
people pay their medical premiums.
</P>
<P>
   The Planned Parenthood endorsement, from both the national
organization and the New York state chapter, was hardly unexpected
for the first lady. But Gloria Feldt, the president of the national
Planned Parenthood organization, said that the group would have
stayed neutral if Clinton's former opponent, New York City Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, had remained in the race. Giuliani is a strong
supporter of abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once Lazio got in the race, it was an easy decision,'' Feldt
said.
</P>
<P>
   On her second day of a three-day campaign swing through the
heart of Long Island, Lazio's home territory, Clinton also said in
an interview that she thought she would win at least ``parts of''
the area. ``I have no illusions about how difficult it is for a
Democrat or for me to do well in the suburbs,'' she said, ``but I'm
not going to concede one vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said she was startled by the favorable reception she
received this morning at the Hicksville station of the Long Island
Rail Road, where she greeted commuters. ``You know, I've been in
lots of different settings politically for a long time,'' she said.
``And when people really aren't interested in you, or really don't
like you, they let it be known. And I had so many people wishing me
luck, telling me they were going to vote for me. It was a big
surprise to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made her remarks about Lazio during a 40-minute speech
on women's issues, when she said, as she has in the past, that
Lazio is not pro-choice on abortion rights but ``multiple choice.''
Although Lazio generally supports abortion rights, he opposes the
use of government money to pay for abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in choice for all women, not just some women,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was accompanied again Wednesday by her daughter,
Chelsea, who is taking a leave from Stanford University to campaign
with her mother and experience the last months of her father's
presidency. Chelsea, 20, sat next to her mother on the stage during
the introductory remarks at the college, then shook hands and
signed autographs on her own after the first lady's speech.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
