<HEADLINE>
HEADLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
TMS adds Roos School 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Motor Speedway has reached an agreement for its first
road-racing school. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bertil Roos Racing School is scheduled to conduct its array
of programs, ranging from half-day introductory to three-day
advanced driving, on the infield road-course layouts. Classes are
scheduled to begin in November for approximately 35 days of
activity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've signed a lease with Bertil Roos, and that's exciting
news for road-racing fans in our area,'' said Eddie Gossage, TMS'
executive vice president and general manager. ``It gives us another
dimension of racing school you can take here, and they're looking
for a place that's warmer in the wintertime.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The addition of TMS is the final piece of an 18-month Roos
expansion plan that has included the development of programs at
Virginia International Raceway and additional dates at the school's
home facility, Pocono Raceway. The school is headquartered in
Blakeslee, Pa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roos' competition courses are Sports Car Club of
America-approved[ ,] and fulfill the schooling requirements for a
racing license. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They do a great job, and it gives people another reason to
come to Texas Motor Speedway,'' Gossage said. ``We've just added
another 35 tourism days to the community.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gossage also said he is close to signing a second road-racing
school _ believed to be operated by American Le Mans Series founder
Don Panoz _ for an extended term. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got one other school we've come to terms with for
another 100 days,'' Gossage said. ``We haven't signed the paper,
but that will come shortly. There are some other elements to it.
It's more than rental of track time.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
ALMS to switch date &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The American Le Mans Series' debut on the combined oval//infield
road-course at Texas Motor Speedway on Sept. 2 apparently will be a
one-shot deal for the Labor Day weekend. Series founder Don Panoz
told /{On Track/} magazine that the second Grand Prix of Texas will
kick off the 2001 ALMS season at TMS in early March. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That appears to be the case,'' said Eddie Gossage, TMS'
executive vice president and general manager. ``Truth is, we
haven't firmed up anything yet. But if that's what they want to do,
that's fine.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the sports cars run in Fort Worth in March, it will give
Texas Motor Speedway major weekends in four consecutive months:
American Le Mans Series (March), NASCAR Winston Cup//Busch Grand
National (April), Championship Auto Racing Teams FedEx Series (May)
and Indy Racing Northern Light Series//NASCAR Craftsman Trucks
(June). &QL; 
 &QL; 
Truck sponsor signed &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arlington-based Berryman Products has signed on as primary
sponsor for B.A. Wilson and the Sonntag Racing team in the NASCAR
Craftsman Truck Series. The company, which produces automotive
chemicals, will serve as primary sponsor through the rest of the
2000 season and be an associate on the team's Chevrolet in 2001. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who has logged one top-10 finish for the Little
Elm-based team, is 22nd in points. The Carrollton resident plans to
return to Fort Worth for the O'Reilly 300 NCTS race at Texas Motor
Speedway on Oct. 13. The last word There's nothing but one spot in
racing, and if you've ever been there _ No. 1 _ you never want to
settle for second, third, fourth or whatever.'' _ A.J. Foyt, on the
goal for his rookie NASCAR Winston Cup program / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
