<HEADER>
A1069 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-CAR-STURBIN-COLUMN-TE     08-02 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Calendars everywhere have been flipped over to
August, and Gasoline Alley at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway is
reverberating with the sounds of stock-car V-8 engines. It can only
mean that the Dog Days of NASCAR's championship season are upon us.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's scheduled running of the Brickyard 400 here will
begin a stretch of 12 consecutive race weekends that is the longest
stint on the 34-event Winston Cup tour. The next scheduled
off-weekend is Oct. 29, well into football season and one week
after the Cup series mercifully rolls into Rockingham, N.C., for
its second visit to the North Carolina Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Three of 12 races during this run will be contested on Saturdays
_ this weekend's seventh annual extravaganza before 320,000 fans at
the history-laden Speedway; the must-see fender-bending action of
night racing on the high-banked, half-mile Bristol Motor Speedway
on Aug. 26; and the similarly enticing under-the-lights race at
Richmond International Raceway on Sept. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Also included in this marathon is the second and final
road-course event of 2000 at Watkins Glen International on Aug. 13;
all the Labor Day weekend traditions associated with Darlington
Raceway on Sept. 3, and the last of the four restrictor-plate races
at the Talladega Superspeedway on Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The results racked up during this stretch surely will reveal the
identity of the 2000 Cup champion.
</P>
<P>
   Native Texan Bobby Labonte is a tenuous 53 points ahead of Dale
Jarrett, the reigning series champion and winner of the 1999
Brickyard 400. And while third-place Dale Earnhardt's quest for an
unprecedented eighth Cup championship carries a ton of sentimental
weight among NASCAR's fandom, it is Jarrett whom Labonte will need
to beat for his first Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's fourth-place finish in the Pennsylvania 500 at Pocono
Raceway on July 23, combined with Earnhardt's flat-tire induced
25th-place result, allowed the former to pass ``The Intimidator''
and move to within striking distance of Labonte. Jarrett's finish
at Pocono was his 15th top-10 result in 19 starts, including his
lone victory in the season-opening Daytona 500. Jarrett's Pocono
result also was his 10th consecutive top-10 finish of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? It is exactly the same grind-it-out consistency
that carried Jarrett to the 1999 championship by 201 points over
Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   With his victory here last year, Jarrett joined Jeff Gordon as a
two-time winner of NASCAR's richest race and tacked 20 points onto
his championship lead (274 points) over runner-up Mark Martin.
Beginning with his Brickyard 400 victory _ the last of his four
victories in 1999 _ Jarrett recorded nine top-five and 12 top-10
finishes en route to joining his father, Ned, as a NASCAR champion.
</P>
<P>
   The current difference between Labonte and 10th-place Ricky Rudd
is 357 points, second at this juncture of the season only to the
1989 race (343 points) since the inception of the current scoring
system in 1975. Given that fact, Jarrett is pleased to be back at
IMS, one of his most productive arenas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been incredible this year with the competition,'' said
Jarrett, who has two victories, four top-five and four top-10
finishes in six Brickyard 400 starts. ``Being able to get in the
top-five, it shows we have performed reasonably well for the first
half of the season. But we feel like we can perform at a higher
level in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jarrett to overtake Labonte, and draw away from Earnhardt,
he will need to do just that. If Labonte were to continue at his
current pace of scoring 148.7 points per race (approximately
sixth-place finishes), Jarrett would need to average 153 points per
race (approximately fifth-place finishes) to pass him. And
Earnhardt, currently 107 points behind Labonte, would need to
average 156 points per race (approximately fourth-place finishes)
to overhaul them both.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a wide-open race,'' said Jarrett, driver of the No.
88 Quality Care Service/Ford Credit Taurus. ``I think there are
still 10 or 12 that have a legitimate shot at winning the
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning this weekend, the Dog Days of NASCAR will help reveal
the champion's identity ... as Dale Jarrett.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
