A1070 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-CAR-FOYT-TEX     08-02 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-FOYT-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ A.J. Foyt did not single-handedly shape the
mystique surrounding the Indianapolis Motor Speedway. But the
history and traditions of the 2.5-mile rectangular oval would be
considerably less colorful without the contributions of Foyt, the
first four-time winner of the Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his open-wheel racing legacy, Foyt always has
appreciated the competitiveness of NASCAR's Winston Cup Series. And
he was foremost among the Indy-car crowd favoring the addition of
the Brickyard 400 to the IMS schedule in 1994. Foyt, who competed
in that first Brickyard at age 59, returns to the Speedway this
week as a first-time Cup car owner. And although his rookie team is
only beginning to look respectable, there is no doubt that A.J.
``owns'' the Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just bask in the glow,'' said veteran Rick Mast, Foyt's
latest full-time driver. ``It's pretty cool to go to Indy with A.J.
I went there a few years ago on qualifying day with him for the
Indy-car race and watched how these people responded to him. But I
also learned in 1994 when I got the pole ... A.J. was running that
day, and I spent a little bit of time with him. In fact, I asked
him for some advice on that particular day.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning the inaugural Brickyard 400 pole remains the highlight
of Mast's 13-year Cup career.
</P>
<P>
   Mast's eighth-place result at Pocono Raceway on July 23 was the
first top-10 Cup finish as a car owner for Foyt, whose patience and
pride have been stretched by his start-up operation.
</P>
<P>
   Mast made his debut for Foyt in the DirecTV 500 at Texas Motor
Speedway in Fort Worth on April 2. Mast drove the No. 14 Conseco
Pontiac Grand Prix to a 20th-place finish that day, securing a seat
formerly occupied by rookie Mike Bliss and the timeless Dick
Trickle. But when Mast failed to qualify for the subsequent events
at the Martinsville and Talladega speedways, Foyt blew a fuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I said, `I've got to make changes because this
ain't going to fly with myself or with my partner, Conseco,' ''
Foyt said. ``I got pretty disgusted because I'm not going to the
races to watch. If I can't have cars that are competitive and be up
front, that's not my style of racing. I just didn't go home, put my
tail between my legs and say, `Well, I just didn't cut it.' I felt
like I could put a team together that could make a big difference
and be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Foyt's reshaped team features Cup veteran and Texan Phillipe
Lopez as crew chief. Foyt also has started an in-house engine
program headed by builder David Evans. More significant, Foyt has
reassigned nephew Tommy LaMance from his championship and Indy
500-winning Indy Racing League program to the Winston Cup team.
LaMance is general manager of Foyt's Cup organization in Charlotte,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way there, I've got a good report coming back to me 24
hours a day,'' said Foyt, who is not above dreaming about a
Brickyard 400 victory this weekend. ``It would mean a lot to me.
I've been very fortunate at Indianapolis Motor Speedway. To be able
to chalk up a Brickyard ... I know I would be so ecstatic; I
couldn't talk.''
/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0465 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1071 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-HOUSTON-TEX     08-02 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOUSTON-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ Houston, you've become a problem.
</P>
<P>
   It was just 20 years ago under former coach Bill Yeoman that the
Cougars were a force playing in a relic called the Southwest
Conference. Lately, there have been few highs for ``Cougar High.''
While Conference USA provided Houston a safe haven when the SWC
folded, C-USA has had reasons to vote them off the island.
</P>
<P>
   In four seasons in C-USA, Houston has an overall record of 20-25
and an 11-12 league record (highlighted by a shared C-USA title in
1996). Since going 10-1 in 1990, Houston's overall record is
30-67-1. Over the past four seasons, Houston's attendance average
is 19,792.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to develop a way to win consistently,'' Dana Dimel,
the Cougars' first-year coach, said at yesterday's C-USA media
meetings. ``We need to get to where we win seven to eight games
each season and are in the mix for the conference title every year.
We did that at Wyoming, and we can do it at Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Two NCAA probations and a losing decade contributed to the
program's problems. But more than anything, Houston turned away
from Texas' fertile high school talent. Dimel, who for the past 13
years has recruited in the state, plans to change that. In May,
Dimel and his staff visited 700 Texas high schools. The message:
``This is Houston, we're back, we need you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand the science of recruiting in Texas,''
said Dimel, a 10-year Kansas State assistant who was 23-12 in two
seasons at Wyoming. ``We're not going after the blue-chip recruit
that is considering Texas or Texas A&AMP;M. But even eliminating those
players, there's still a ton of talent in the state. We're looking
for good people who can run fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston has the facilities, resources and the recruiting base
to be a solid program. And I think the conference needs us be a
solid contender.''
</P>
<P>
   Dimel isn't on Mission Impossible. Houston was 7-4 last season.
Senior quarterback Jason McKinley has started for three seasons and
appears a perfect fit for Dimel's offense, which features a
one-back set and lots of passing. Just don't expect a return to the
run-and-shoot and high-scoring games, Dimel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year everybody had long faces all the time, coaches and
players,'' senior wide receiver Orlando Iglesias said. ``Now,
everybody is having fun. We had a winning record last year so deep
down we know we have what it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Dimel said September will determine his team's fate in 2000. The
Cougars play at Rice, LSU and Texas with home games against Army
and SMU.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can come out of September with a winning record, we
could have a good season,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Southern Mississippi, East Carolina and Tulane have had
flashes of success on the national scene, C-USA commissioner Mike
Slive said the league needs a healthy Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is Houston a major market and a significant sports
town, it has served as our nexus in the state of Texas,'' he said.
``You have to look a program over a long period, not just a snap
shot. Houston has significant history and tradition. I think
they'll be able to bring back that kind of success.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
