<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1073 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-EQUESTRIAN-COACH-TEX     08-02 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EQUESTRIAN-COACH-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAWN REISS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Mary O'Connell is one of the best equestrian
coaches in the world. She could have stayed in her hometown of
Dublin, Ireland, to teach. Or she could have coached at an elite
East Coast equestrian center. Instead, she chose Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she spends most of the year in Fort Worth freelancing as an
equestrian instructor and travels back to Ireland in spring and at
the end of summer to coach.
</P>
<P>
   For O'Connell, 45, it's the best of both worlds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't miss Ireland that much, because I get to go back quite
a bit,'' said O'Connell, who lives in Fort Worth with her husband,
Daniel, and 8-month-old son, Brendon. ``I like Fort Worth because
it's easygoing in the fast-paced world we live in _ even though the
heat is a bit hard for training horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Known professionally by her maiden name, Mary D'Arcy, O'Connell
will coach the Irish senior equestrian three-day event team at the
2000 Summer Olympic Games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   She has coached at all of the major equestrian championships
since 1990, including England's prestigious Badminton Horse Trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are blessed to have her here, because most of the big names
are on the East Coast or West Coast,'' said Dr. Terri Lindsay, a
student of O'Connell's. ``I would follow her anywhere she goes. She
sees the frustration as you learn and works you through it. She
always leaves you with something positive, so there is something
that always draws you back to her.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell came to Fort Worth in 1983 to work as a consultant for
the now-defunct Talland II, a riding center in Burleson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity was here at the time,'' she said. ``I liked
the town and the people. It was similar to Ireland because it
wasn't fast-moving and I enjoyed the Western heritage and the
Southern hospitality.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell now freelances at the Curragh Equestrian Center in
Fort Worth and at private farms. She occasionally helps local
Western riders who come to her wanting to improve their balance and
to learn ``flying changes,'' where the rider gets the horse to
switch leads during loping, the Western form of cantering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Western riding is a huge factor here, because years ago, with
the farms and ranches, they were outside riding on the farm,'' she
said. ``So they are natural riders.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell returned to Ireland last week to prepare her Olympic
riders for the three-day event, a triathlon of sorts that tests a
horse's and rider's ability in show jumping, dressage (often
described as horses performing ballet) and cross-country
competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Equestrian events made their debut in the Olympics in 1912.
Women were not allowed to participate in the events until 1952.
Now, it's the only Olympic sport where men and women compete
together.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell's experience coaching Ireland's Young Riders (16- to
21-year-olds) three-day event team to their first gold medal at the
1995 European Championships helped catapult her into the Olympics
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's everybody's dream as a coach or an athlete,'' O'Connell
said. ``The whole point of the Olympics is to compete as a
competitor or as a coach. This is a fulfillment of a lifetime's
worth of work.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell's road to the Olympics began at age 10, when a friend
convinced her to take riding lessons. She felt an instant
connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was a little horrified that I didn't go into the
normal pursuits of a lady,'' O'Connell said. ``Like being a flight
attendant, a beautician or a lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   She continued to ride at a local pony club near Dublin, but
stopped for a year when she turned 13. That year was more than
enough, and she hasn't taken a break since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get horses in your blood, its hard to get it out of
you,'' she said. ``After that, you go up to the riding school,
helping out on the holidays, and then you are there practically
every waking hour.''
</P>
<P>
   While in high school, O'Connell learned from the best, taking
the first of six teaching exams with the British Equestrian
Society. It was there that she learned how to teach people of all
ages and skill levels. She completed her training in only seven
years, compared to the 30 years it takes some people to finish.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said she decided to become an instructor because she
could compete and teach for a living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know at the time, but I seem to take to teaching
people,'' she said. ``That's something you discover over time.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell was quite the competitor as well.
</P>
<P>
   Among other accomplishments, she has won the Hunter Championship
at the Dublin Horse Show and placed second at the national
three-day event championship in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to compete in all the disciplines, which is very
hard to do, which meant I was then able to coach all of them,'' she
said. ``If I didn't compete in them, it's like saying can you teach
me to drive a car, if you've never driven one.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
