<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1074 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GARMON-TE     08-02 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GARMON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS GUARD GARMON, SIDELINED SINCE 1998, WORKS TO CATCH UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Kelvin Garmon's right leg bears no visible
reminders of the pain it put him through the past two years. Soon,
though, Garmon will need only to look at his wall to remember how
far he has come.
</P>
<P>
   The titanium rod and four screws that held Garmon's tibia
together for 10 months are being framed, along with the date of his
surgery _ Nov. 8, 1998 _ and the date he was drafted _ April 18,
1999. It will hang in a prominent place in his house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be something special, you know,'' said Garmon, a
former Haltom High School standout. ``It's one of those things that
when you get through it, you've got to be proud of what you did.''
</P>
<P>
   Garmon's football career is healing as satisfactorily as his
leg. After missing about 21 months after suffering a fractured bone
in his lower leg] near the end of his senior season at Baylor,
Garmon returned to competition Saturday when he started for the
Cowboys against the Pittsburgh Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   Garmon, filling in for injured All-Pro left guard Larry Allen,
played 18 plays in the Cowboys' 38-10 exhibition loss. By all
accounts, Garmon held his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to work on reacting to the quickness of the game,''
Cowboys offensive line coach Hudson Houck said. ``He needs to work
on exactly what his job is on each play. There are some real
subtleties that you only can learn through experience. Seeing a
number of different defenses and seeing a number of different
movements out of the defense comes with experience, and we're
trying to give him that.''
</P>
<P>
   Garmon was dealt a bad break on the first series of a 49-6
Baylor loss to Kansas State two seasons ago. In what Garmon calls
``a freak injury,'' he was running down the field when he was hit
by a fallen player. Garmon heard a pop, which was quickly followed
by a jolt of pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your whole body can't move. You just sit there like `uh, oh,'
'' Garmon said. ``When you have an injury like that, the first
thing you think is, `I'm not going to be able to play football
again.' Everything goes by so fast. You think about your family. A
hundred different things go through your mind in a second. You have
to settle down and get rid of the shock before you start thinking
clearly again.''
</P>
<P>
   James Bowden, an orthopedic surgeon in Waco, performed two hours
of surgery on Garmon's leg. When he was finished, Bowden told
Garmon that under the best of circumstances, Garmon could resume
his career in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelvin had a bad fracture with a lot of swelling,'' Bowden
said. ``I told him there was no reason that it ought to affect his
career, but he had to be patient. ...It's not how strong the bone
is, but how strong the leg is. It was unreasonable to think he
could compete at the professional level in a year's time.''
</P>
<P>
   With his college career over and his pro career yet to begin,
Garmon suddenly had a cloudy future. Lying in his hospital bed,
Garmon briefly considered giving up football for a career in
radio/broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time, he thought his football career was over,'' said
Garmon's father, Henry, who lives in Haltom City. ``He was upset.
We encouraged him. We told him it was going to heal back up, and
he'd be ready to play, no problem. It wasn't a career-ending
injury.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a career-interrupting injury, however.
</P>
<P>
   Garmon had expected to be selected by the fourth round of the
NFL Draft. Instead, with no chance to work out for scouts and no
hope of playing football in 1999, Garmon was the 243rd of 253
players drafted last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys put him on injured reserve, where he spent last
season ``chilling'' and gaining weight. Garmon, whose playing
weight is 325-330 pounds, tipped the scales at 365 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   A committed off-season saw Garmon lose pounds and gain strength.
He now can bench-press 500 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a hard worker, and he competes,'' Cowboys right guard
Jorge Diaz said. ``That's what you look for in young guys. He's got
a great future ahead of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Garmon, 23, is a first-year player in a rookie's body. Although
he has served his rookie initiation and no longer is required to be
at a veteran's beck and call, Garmon's NFL experience amounts to
21/2 weeks of training camp and the first quarter of an exhibition
game.
</P>
<P>
   Although he currently has a starting job, Garmon has no
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Garmon will start again Saturday night when the Cowboys play the
Atlanta Falcons in Tokyo, but Allen's fractured right hand is
healing. And right tackle Erik Williams could decide to play this
season, moving Solomon Page back to right guard. Five is a crowd at
offensive guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelvin Garmon is a rookie who hasn't played for two years. He
is a work in progress,'' Cowboys coach Dave Campo said. ``...I
think at this point right now, again it's early and I don't want to
put pressure on him, but I think he's made a tremendous amount of
progress. He has really kind of figured it out. He has figured out
what it takes. I'm pleased with him. That's all I can say. I'm not
going overly crazy, because we've got some other players who can
play, but hopefully, he's going to make enough progress to provide
us some depth.''
</P>
<P>
   It might not be enough to give him a leg up on his training-camp
competition, but at least Garmon again is standing on his own two
feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people look at adversity, sometimes they say, `I could do
it, but I don't want to,' '' Garmon said. ``They say it's easy, but
a lot of people don't do it. When I set a goal, I try to accomplish
it. When things go bad, you don't give up on your dreams. You may
have to work a little bit harder to get back to where everybody
else is, but that's what life is.'' \Nsubheds:Team departs The
Cowboys departed for Japan yesterday afternoon for their game
against the Falcons on Saturday night. The Cowboys never have won a
game on foreign soil, going 0-6-1, including a 34-23 loss to the
Houston Oilers in Tokyo in 1992. \Nsubheds:Diaz holding a
reputation Jorge Diaz, who again will start at right guard
Saturday, led the league in holding penalties two seasons ago. Line
coach Hudson Houck said better technique _ having Diaz use his feet
more _ has cured Diaz's ``bad habit.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz figures a change of uniforms can't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like they were always looking at me,'' said Diaz, who
spent the first four years of his career with Tampa Bay. ``Once you
get a reputation for leading the league in penalties, the refs are
going to target you. They're going to watch you closer than anybody
else. They're not going to let you get away with anything.
Hopefully, this might disguise me. You never know, maybe it's just
a jinx.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
