<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1075 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     08-02 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boxes are stacked all around Dennis Franchione's office, packed
up and ready for the trip to a new home in the John Justin Athletic
Center. TCU football, it seems, is moving up, in more ways than
one.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs are leaving dusty old Daniel-Meyer Coliseum behind for
state-of-the-art facilities down the street. The past is left
behind. The future is golden.
</P>
<P>
   The metaphor is perfect, since the Frogs are also moving into
new digs in the national preseason polls these days, too. You can't
pick up a preseason football publication without finding TCU ranked
in somebody's top 25.
</P>
<P>
   Try it. There they'll be, sitting at No. 21 (the most recent
College Football Writers' poll) or No. 17 (coming in your
``Star-Telegram'' Monday) or even a feisty _ and perhaps slightly
overenthusiastic _ No. 11 in another area newspaper's rankings.
</P>
<P>
   This bandwagon is so overloaded, the tires may go flat before
the opening kickoff at the University of Nevada on Sept. 9.
</P>
<P>
   But standing by, Fix-A-Flat in hand, is Franchione. His days are
already hectic and overfull and the season opener is still more
than a month away. Yesterday he was the keynote speaker at the
Texas High School Coaches Association convention in Houston. By
1:30 p.m., he was back at work in the office he will leave behind
for good sometime in the next 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   That's another interesting metaphor, by the way, but we'll get
back to that one later.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione, as even-keeled as ever, has taken TCU's sudden
notoriety in stride. Excited, yes; hysterical, no. Cautiously
optimistic, yes; starry-eyed, no.
</P>
<P>
   He understands perfectly that the Frogs are the current flavor
of the month. He also knows that could change faster than a snow
cone melts in August once the hitting starts for real.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like I've told our players,'' Franchione said. ``All this
preseason publicity is based on what last year's team accomplished
and how many returning starters we have, but the 2000 team hasn't
done anything yet. The '99 team set the table for us to be
mentioned in this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, we lost some pivotal guys and we have to replace
them. We still have a lot of work to do and some things to figure
out once fall camp gets under way.''
</P>
<P>
   Blah, blah, blah, blah. Coach-speak. That's not going to stem
the runaway optimism and Franchione knows that, just as he
understands why the major polls might favor the Frogs with their
first preseason ranking since the 1960 team opened at No. 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look and see you've got a Heisman Trophy candidate
\RLaDainian Tomlinson\S who led the nation in rushing, and then
you've got one of the 18 finalists for national defensive player of
the year \RDE Aaron Schobel\S,'' Franchione said. ``They see you've
got 10 offensive starters and eight defensive starters back off an
8-4 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then they look at the schedule and say, `Hey, these guys look
like they ought to be pretty good.' We have that potential if we
can stay healthy. But sometimes you're as vulnerable as a couple of
sprained ankles.''
</P>
<P>
   The positives to such a lofty preseason ranking are obvious.
Moving up in the polls is a lot easier if a team starts there
rather than trying to come from back in the pack. Team morale might
be at its highest ever. Ticket sales are up. Fans have been talking
about Tomlinson and TCU football all summer, an unheard-of
phenomenon in these parts.
</P>
<P>
   It's the flip side that worries Franchione.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously expectations are out of control,'' he said with a
nervous laugh. ``I haven't done a good job of managing those
things. People keep talking about us going 11-0 or something.
That's pretty difficult to do. Every year there are teams that try
to do that and very, very few that actually accomplish it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Franchione is smart enough not to poor-mouth his team
either. The Frogs just might be as good as people think. Or even
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, people put some expectations on us, too,'' he
pointed out. ``I was nervous about it, because those kids were
still somewhat fragile from the 1-10 team and we got off to a slow
start. Then we came back and won the last five games and hung in
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '98, we learned how to win. In '99 we learned how to live
with winning and expectations. This team, I think, is prepared for
all this.''
</P>
<P>
   The maturation process for the Frogs started with that 5-0 run
to end the '99 season, including the upset of East Carolina in the
Mobile Alabama Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've known since January or February, when the article came
out in ``The Sporting News'' \Rabout the possibility of the Frogs
going 11-0\S what people are thinking,'' Franchione said. ``Their
whole demeanor is different. We know we have to stay focused and
determined. We know there are no gimmes on our schedule. There's a
maturity there we haven't seen before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best part is the players' attitude. It's like, `We can do
this. We've been there. We've been in these battles. We've beaten
good teams like the USCs and East Carolinas. We can do it again.'''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there's not a game on the schedule the Frogs can't win,
but if you want to make Franchione cringe, just mention 11-0. Then
duck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my favorite topic, you understand,'' he said sourly.
``The worst thing we can do as players is talk about going 11-0.
Everyone hates to hear us say it, but we have to take it a day at a
time and a game at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one coaching homily Franchione can forget to pack. As
true as it may be, at this stage of the game, nobody's buying it.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs are moving into a new neighborhood. Keeping up with
the Joneses just got a lot harder.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
