<HEADLINE>
C-USA COACHES RECEIVE TASTE OF INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ Before meeting with reporters at yesterday's
Conference USA media gathering, the league's players and coaches
spent some time talking to 20 chairs in an empty room. Call it
Virtual Reality Interviewing.
</P>
<P>
   The comments of the coaches and players went live over the
Internet on the conference's Web site (www.c-usasports.com). Later
in the day, more sound and video clips were archived on the Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time we've been able to do something like
this,'' C-USA assistant commissioner Brian Teter said. ``We're
using another element of technology to make things available for
our media and fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the unusual aspect of speaking to an empty room, the
``virtual interviews'' were a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not much of an Internet guy, but I think it's something
that will be good for the fans,'' Southern Mississippi coach Jeff
Bower said. ``But it was kinda tough talking to a bunch of
chairs.'' \Nsubheds:Briefly Southern Miss was a narrow winner in
preseason predictions by the league's coaches. The Golden Eagles
had five first-place votes and 76 total points. East Carolina, with
four first-place votes and 75 points, was picked to finish second.
Louisville was picked to finish third, followed by Memphis,
Alabama-Birmingham, Cincinnati, Houston, Tulane and Army.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into its fifth season, C-USA has four bowl tie-ins. The
league added the Motor City and the first-year Galleryfurniture.com
bowls to its existing roster of the Liberty and the Mobile Alabama.
``The bowls we're affiliated with now reflect our geography,''
C-USA commissioner Mike Slive said. ``Adding those two bowls to
bring us to four has worked out nicely.'' The nine-team league will
pull in a little more than $3.5 million in bowl revenue this
season.
</P>
<P>
   TCU joins C-USA next year, but the school had a presence at
yesterday's media meetings thanks to a stack of the school's
football guides.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama-Birmingham coach Watson Brown said he's one of the few
people who hasn't advised his brother, Texas coach Mack Brown, on
who to play at quarterback _ Major Applewhite or Chris Simms. ``I
did tell him this _ he can send either one of them to me,'' Watson
said. ``Doesn't matter which one, just pick one and send him to
Birmingham.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
