<SLUG> BC-NY-GM-ENGINE-PLANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM WILL BUILD ENGINE PLANT IN BUFFALO AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   General Motors will build a $500 million high-tech engine
manufacturing plant at its complex in the Buffalo suburb of
Tonawanda, saving 600 well-paying jobs through the largest
private-sector investment in western New York state in many years,
Gov. George E. Pataki said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Had the company chosen to build the plant in another state or in
Canada or Mexico, something state officials said GM had been
considering, it would have been a major blow to the Buffalo area
because the 600 blue-collar jobs would have been phased out from
the Tonawanda complex's 3,800 existing jobs.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the Buffalo metropolitan area's unemployment rate was
5 percent in June compared with a 4.3 percent rate statewide. And,
the Buffalo area has been adding jobs at a much slower rate than
the state has over all. In the 12-month period ending in June, the
number of jobs in the area increased by 2,300, or 0.4 percent, the
lowest job growth rate in any metropolitan area in the state. The
job increase rate statewide was 2.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The threat was very strong to move the 600 jobs,'' said
Charles A. Gargano, chairman of the Empire State Development Corp.,
in an interview. ``They said they were looking at different
locations.'' Among the other options, officials said, were the 10
other engine plants the company has in the United States, Canada
and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   State and GM officials said the Tonawanda site was selected for
the plant partly because of what Gargano called the state's
incentive package, which included a commitment to spend $9 million
to upgrade streets around the site and water and sewage facilities.
They also cited an agreement permitting more flexible work rules
that GM reached with the union.
</P>
<P>
   The Tonawanda complex produces four-, six- and eight-cylinder
engines, and Gargano said that GM planned to phase out some of the
old production lines there. The plant to be added at the site is
intended to produce a six-cylinder, all aluminum, inline engine
that will be used in a wide variety of GM cars and light trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the new plant is to begin later this year, and
the plant is scheduled to begin operation in early 2003. Gargano
said the construction alone would provide 600 jobs in the building
trades.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
