<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO APPEARS ON CONTROVERSIAL TALK SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rep. Rick Lazio returned to New York on Wednesday
from the Republican National Convention, and, among other stops,
appeared on the radio talk show of Bob Grant, who once drew
criticism for derogatory remarks about blacks and Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio spent about 20 minutes chatting with Grant and a few of
his listeners on WWOR.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, a commentator for nearly 30 years, was fired from WABC in
1996 for what station managers said was an inappropriate remark
about the death in a plane crash of Ron Brown, the former commerce
secretary. Before that, he publicly feuded with New Jersey's
Republican governor, Christine Todd Whitman, in 1994. Once a
frequent guest, Whitman vowed never to appear again on his show
after a visit in which she objected to Grant's racially charged
rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   He has toned down his commentary _ ``I got a bum rap,'' he said
on Wednesday _ and Lazio's appearance was uneventful.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio was asked friendly and routine questions about his Senate
campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton, and he responded
cheerfully.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference before the show, Lazio sought to draw a
contrast with Grant's past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand for inclusion,'' said Lazio, who appeared on the show
a few times before he entered the Senate race in May. ``I think my
record reflects that very, very clearly. Bringing people together,
finding common ground. I will be responsible for my remarks and
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's aides said he had accepted Grant's invitation as part of
an effort to appear on a variety of television and radio shows.
``Rick does a lot of interviews,'' said Dan McLagan, his chief
spokesman. ``He has been interviewed on over 25 media outlets in
the last 36 hours, from CNN to America's Black Forum to MTV.''
</P>
<P>
   McLagan also noted that Lanny J. Davis, President Clinton's
former special counsel and a supporter of Clinton's candidacy,
appeared on the Grant show last week. Howard Wolfson, a spokesman
for Clinton, said Davis was not a paid adviser and only contacts
the campaign when he is planning to appear on a television show to
speak about Clinton's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson said Lazio should have skipped the show because of
Grant's past.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was willing to run with Pat Buchanan on the Independence
Party line to win votes. He is willing to go on Bob Grant to win
votes,'' Wolfson said. ``I'm beginning to wonder what he won't do
to win votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also appeared Wednesday on the O'Reilly Factor on the Fox
News Channel. In the first installment of a two-part interview that
concludes on Thursday, he answered questions on several topics,
including abortion. Lazio said he is pro-choice, but has been
criticized by Clinton for not supporting public financing of
abortions and opposing late-term procedures.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, he suggested that life begins at conception.
``I believe there is a very special status when there is
conception,'' Lazio said, who added that he nevertheless believes
government should not make abortions illegal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
