A1081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-CHEN-CHINA-CITIZE     08-02 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CHEN-CHINA-CITIZENSHIP-28%&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA BLOCKS CHEN'S EFFORT TO COMPETE FOR U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By JERE LONGMAN with ELLIOTT DENMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eight years after she won the first Olympic race-walking
competition for women as a Chinese athlete, Yueling Chen hoped to
win another medal, this time as a U.S. citizen, at the 2000 Summer
Games in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   However, China has protested her participation as an American,
and given the citizenship requirements of the Olympics, it appears
than Chen will have to watch the Sydney Games as a spectator.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, who competed for China as Chen Yueling but prefers the
Western listing of her name, obtained her U.S. citizenship on April
12. Last month in Sacramento, Calif., she finished second in the
20-kilometer (12.4-mile) walk at the U.S. Olympic track and field
trials, which conditionally qualified her for the Sydney Games in
September.
</P>
<P>
   However, an athlete who has competed in the Games for one
country must wait three years to compete for another country after
gaining citizenship in the new nation. This rule is meant to
prevent Olympic athletes from playing musical chairs with their
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   A waiver can be granted, and frequently has been, but the
Chinese track-and-field federation has declined to issue one.
Tuesday, without explanation, the Chinese Olympic Committee
notified the U.S. Olympic Committee that it supported the Chinese
track federation's decision.
</P>
<P>
   The International Olympic Committee indicated Wednesday that it
would not get involved in this or other similar cases, saying it
was a matter for the Olympic committees of the United States and
China to decide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't arbitrate these cases,'' said Franklin
Servan-Schreiber, an IOC spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Barring IOC intervention, the case appears to be closed, said
Mike Moran, a spokesman for the USOC.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Earlier this year, even after U.S. Olympic officials traveled to
Havana to plead their case, Cuba denied to grant a waiver to Angel
Perez, a canoe-kayaker who had become a U.S. citizen.The IOC did
not intercede in that case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the end of it,'' Moran said Wednesday night.
``I don't think we have any wiggle room.''
</P>
<P>
   One senior IOC official, speaking on the condition of anonymity,
left some small opening, saying that China might be wise to
reconsider its position, considering that Beijing is bidding on the
2008 Summer Games and might not want to anger the United States.
Beijing lost by two votes to Sydney to become the host city of the
2000 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be useful for the Chinese to approve that transfer,''
the IOC official said. ``America is a powerful country and can
always be helpful. People remember things like this. Good faith and
good form shown when things are delicate could make a difference.
Everything is important when you are bidding.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese and the U.S. Olympic committees enjoy cordial
relations, Moran said. Earlier this year, the Chinese granted
waivers for three athletes who had become U.S. citizens, two table
tennis players and a badminton player, he said. The difference is
that Chen has represented China in the Olympics and the others have
not, Moran said.
</P>
<P>
   Chen is the first Chinese woman to win a gold medal in track and
field, and is perhaps the most successful Chinese athlete ever to
attempt to compete for another country, which may explain China's
reluctance to grant her a waiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is clearly higher profile because of her past success,''
Moran said. ``That may be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now living in Escondido, Calif., the 27-year-old Chen said that
China's refusal to let her compete for the United States was
``unbelievably unfair to me.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued through her agent, Derek Boosey, Chen
recalled the words of the French baron, Pierre de Coubertin, who
founded the modern Olympics and said the most important thing was
to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all I want to do,'' Chen said. ``I just want to
compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese Olympic officials could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1992 Summer Games in Barcelona, Spain, Chen won the
inaugural 10-kilometer (6.2-mile) walk for women in a controversial
decision after the Russian walker, Alina Ivanova, crossed the line
first, only to be disqualified for technical violations. Race
walkers must keep one foot on the ground at all times. Three years
earlier, Chen had set a world record in the 10-kilometer walk in 43
minutes 52.1 seconds. After she won in Barcelona in 44:52, a statue
of Chen was erected in her home town of Taeling, in Liaoning
province.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Chen immigrated to the United States, receiving a green
card as an alien with extraordinary ability, and Chinese athletic
officials did not protest the move, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had done all that I could for China,'' she said. ``I had won
a gold medal, and I no longer wished to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   She attended two universities in California and became fluent in
English. She changed her mind about competing and wanted to enter
the 20-kilometer walk, which is making its debut for women, in
Sydney.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 2226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0476 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1084 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      08-02 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPRAISING THOSE EMPLOYEE APPRAISALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Management guru Edward Deming once called performance appraisals
a deadly disease.
</P>
<P>
   Many employees _ and the supervisors assigned to write them _
agree.
</P>
<P>
   The annual employee evaluation, especially when tied to ``and
here's what your raise will be,'' is an atrocious practice.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why:
</P>
<P>
   - Many managers aren't properly trained in how to give
constructive feedback.
</P>
<P>
   - ``One size fits all'' appraisal forms make a mockery of
individual assessments.
</P>
<P>
   - It takes time to do appraisals well, and most managers are too
busy to devote that time.
</P>
<P>
   - Once a year is not enough to provide usable job improvement
guidance to a worker.
</P>
<P>
   - Appraisals are supposed to be self-improvement tools. Instead,
they're often interpreted as punishment and justification for tiny
raises.
</P>
<P>
   - Evals shouldn't be one-way communication. The best ones foster
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of human resource specialists who sell
consulting services and products designed to stop the annual plague
of poorly done appraisals. Chief among their suggestions is the
360-degree, or multisource, assessment.
</P>
<P>
   The very mention, however well intentioned, makes some managers
sweat.
</P>
<P>
   If you think single-source appraisals are time-consuming and
badly done by overstressed, ill-trained supervisors, just think of
the ripple effect when a whole bunch of people _ supervisors, peers
and subordinates _ are asked to weigh in as well.
</P>
<P>
   According to current ``best practice'' thinking, 360-degree
evals are a better way to get a variety of informed opinions about
an individual's work and share good suggestions for improvement. In
some organizations, that happens.
</P>
<P>
   When done right, 360-degree appraisals reduce the chance of
one-on-one bias between a supervisor and his or her employee, and
give a fuller picture of a worker's contributions. When done right,
they give the worker a clearer understanding of his or her
strengths, weaknesses and the impression he or she makes on others.
</P>
<P>
   Those are admirable benefits. But in the real world, the
possible benefits aren't always achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Many appraisal forms aren't individualized enough to be
meaningful. Many don't even measure the sought-after things. Many
evaluators get no training in how to write good evals. And most
supervisors are too busy with their ``real'' jobs to devote
sufficient time and attention.
</P>
<P>
   In the ideal work world envisioned by Deming and a succession of
other appraisal experts, performance evaluations would be
individualized, forward-looking rather than historical,
career-building and supportive.
</P>
<P>
   In the real world, performance appraisals more often are hastily
scribbled tick marks on a page, done on deadline so raises can be
dished out on workers' employment anniversaries.
</P>
<P>
   In the real world, I once watched a lawyer doing his assigned
part to evaluate associates at his law firm. He was checking off
ratings on a pile of standardized appraisal forms _ and watching a
baseball game at the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
