<SLUG> BC-BBN-PEREZ-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE AGAIN, PEREZ DEMOTED TO BULLPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ With manager Davey Johnson's future with the
Dodgers hinging on the final two months of the season, he made a
move Wednesday that signified only winning matters.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, with the blessing of the front office, shifted
high-priced but ineffective lefty Carlos Perez to the bullpen.
Moving into a starter's role will be $200,000-a-year rookie Matt
Herges, who is 8-0 with a 3.00 ERA in a team-high 44 relief
outings. His first major-league start is Tuesday against the
Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Perez is 4-6 with a 5.67 ERA, and the only thing that's kept him
in the rotation this long is his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's decision comes after Perez's second consecutive
abysmal outing against Pittsburgh on Tuesday, when he was pulled
after allowing five runs on nine hits in four innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carlos' outing earned him a trip to the 'pen,'' Johnson said.
``I'm not dealing with that anymore. (Herges) has been a big guy in
my pen, and he takes on a lot of different roles, and he performed
a lot of different roles long man, set-up, close.''
</P>
<P>
   After being pulled from Tuesday's start, team sources said Perez
trashed the clubhouse and got in a shouting match with Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to make this work for a lot of reasons,'' Johnson
said. ``I wanted him to be successful. That's my job. (Tuesday) was
kind of the capper for me. We made a commitment, and I wanted to
make it work. Regardless of contractual status, you want to get
value for that. You want to get performance for value.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite not winning since May 20 and posting a 16.71 ERA in his
last two starts, Perez wasn't happy about the move. But Johnson was
so fed up by Perez that he didn't bother telling the pitcher about
the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a decision, so what can I say?'' Perez said. ``I'm not
OK. I'm not a reliever. I don't understand because it's two bad
starts. He made the move so fast. I wait five days to pitch and
then give up a few runs in the first couple of innings. I felt OK
(Tuesday). I don't know why he took me out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been like this in my career, never pitched like
this. As soon as I get here, too many things change. I get tired
with too much (stuff). I don't understand because it's two bad
starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Herges, 30, has started in the minors, including 21 starts for
Triple-A Albuquerque last season.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Kevin Malone, who signed Perez to a three-year,
$15.6 million deal after the 1998 season, said it was a move that
had to be made for the Dodgers' push toward the playoffs. They
entered the day three games behind San Francisco in the National
League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very logical move,'' Malone said. ``Everyone always
talks about the money. But, money aside, we want our players in the
best position to win. Davey will always be looking at the lineup
and juggling with who's hot and who's not. I think you'll always
see him juggling things.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Perez was miffed about his demotion, he was given many
chances. And he's also had his situation well-chronicled. It began
with a 2-10 record and a 7.43 ERA last season. Perez's status was
in question all winter, and that continued in spring training.
Perez was arrested and charged with driving under the influence
during spring training, then was sent to the minors after bombing
in his first start in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   An injury to Kevin Brown allowed Perez to hang around, but the
Dodgers had to come up with innovative ways to keep him motivated.
Twice, they had him sign papers waiving his right to decline a
minor-league assignment despite having accrued five years of
major-league service time. The Dodgers also shipped Perez to the
bullpen earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   Perez's argument is he left four starts with leads that the
bullpen blew, but the feeling in the clubhouse was supportive of
the switch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't afford to flip a coin and see which Carlos Perez
shows up now,'' second baseman Mark Grudzielanek said. ``It's
crunch time.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
