<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSITY-CONTRACT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOARD AT A MISSOURI UNIVERSITY VOIDS EX-PRESIDENT'S EXIT CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARRENSBURG, Mo. _ Central Missouri State University's board of
governors said Wednesday that it had voided former president Ed
Elliott's controversial exit contract after failing to reach a
buyout agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The board would not provide details because the vote on Tuesday
involved a personnel decision and ``pending litigation.'' One board
member said a lawsuit from Elliott was possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made the best offer we could,'' said board member John
Dralus of Kansas City, part of the majority. ``It wasn't
acceptable, so we needed to look at what was in the best interests
of the university.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's attorney general and auditor had criticized the
lucrative consulting contract as an inappropriate ``golden
parachute.'' Some legislators wanted to cut the university's budget
in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's contract remains a divisive topic statewide and on the
campus in Warrensburg, about 55 miles southeast of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Nickie Foster, president of the board of governors, described
her colleagues as ``polarized.'' The measure passed 4-3, with the
four newest members making up the majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' said Foster, of Osage Beach. ``I feel like
we're losing a valuable asset.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott and his attorney declined to comment Wednesday, as did
Andrew Carroll, the university's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the board voted to renegotiate the exit contract. Last
week, the board unanimously approved a buyout, but Elliott rejected
the proposal on Monday. He submitted a counteroffer that the board
did not accept.
</P>
<P>
   The board and Elliott agreed on a lump-sum payment of $225,000,
but Elliott's counteroffer sought to keep other benefits. For
example, Elliott wanted the option of buying a university-provided
car, while the university demanded the return of all property
within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   As the negotiations continued, the tide of sentiment among some
in the public and on the board of governors had turned against
Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   The popular president announced his retirement in October 1998
after 14 years on the job. Two months later, the board approved a
professional services contract with Elliott, who officially stepped
down on Aug. 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The contract paid Elliott $152,850 in salary and $180,969 in
benefits while he is on sabbatical leave until Oct. 31 of this
year. He was then to get a total of $287,590 in salary and benefits
over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott also was to receive other benefits, such as the use of a
car, computers, a cell phone and other equipment. He and his wife,
Sandra, also received perks such as health benefits and tickets to
campus events, even though she was not a university employee.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year contract was worth $621,000 in salary and
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The contract drew investigators from the state auditor's and
attorney general's offices. Board members later told the auditor
that the contract was justified because of Elliott's fund-raising
skills.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, Gov. Mel Carnahan appointed four new
members to the board of governors. That left only three members who
were part of the board when the original contract was approved.
</P>
<P>
   At the new board's first meeting in April, State Auditor Claire
McCaskill said the deal contained provisions not included in any
higher-education contract in state history.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill was out of the state Wednesday but released a
statement through her office that said: ``The board did the right
thing. Ed Elliott was an outstanding president but his retirement
contract was way out of line, considering it was to be financed
with taxpayer dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   At the April meeting, the counsel to the state attorney general
told the board that precedent made it illegal to raise the salary
of an administrator during his term of service. Elliott's exit
contract could be voided because his original term still had one
year left, the counsel said.
</P>
<P>
   The board said it voided the contract based on that legal
judgment. The new members _ Robert Russell, E. Lenita Johnson,
Janet Sanders and Dralus _ voted to void. Foster, John Lenox and
Lynn Harmon opposed the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Jay Nixon said the university board did the
``proper and responsible thing.'' His office has offered to assist
the board if Elliott sues to restore the exit contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not surprise me if he sought redress from the
courts,'' Nixon said.
</P>
<P>
   The board's decision also found support among state legislators
who had railed against the contract during this year's session.
Rep. Martin Hohulin, a Lamar Republican, even proposed cutting the
university's budget to draw attention to Elliott's contract.
</P>
<P>
   Hohulin said Wednesday that he applauded the board's decision.
But he said universities needed to be more accountable so other
administrators would not receive similar ``sweetheart deals.'' He
said he expected legislators to push measures for greater state
oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a legislator, I don't want to be in the university
administrative business,'' he said. ``On the other hand, I want to
make sure that tax dollars are spent wisely.''
</P>
<P>
   In her audit, McCaskill looked at all severance packages given
in the past five years to top administrators and coaches at
Missouri's four-year public colleges. She found problems in three
of 14 such contracts, but her sharpest criticism was aimed at
Central Missouri State's board of governors.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Harold Caskey, a Butler Democrat, had gone as far as filing
a bill to remove the Elliotts' names from the university's student
union.
</P>
<P>
   Caskey on Wednesday said he had no opinion on the board's vote
but thought the public scrutiny would have a positive effect on
other universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all the criticism gave a heads-up to other
institutions,'' Caskey said. ``I hope they learned that they need
to be very mindful that they are spending taxpayer dollars.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
