<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1091 &Cx1f; kan-z
r p BC-PARTY-GOOP-KAN &LR;      08-02 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTY-GOOP-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LOOK EMERGES AS GOP CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY and STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The story of the Republican National Convention
that ends today is its bid _ through a cross-cultural array of
speakers, entertainers, ideas and promises _ to give a new look to
the Grand Old Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a historic convention'' for the Republicans, said Kansas
City native Hector V. Barreto before speaking to the delegates
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Barreto, a Los Angeles businessman and a campaign coordinator
for George W. Bush in California, said the party's commitment to
minorities is for real.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say that commitment shows in their platform. The
preamble says ``we are the party that ended slavery'' and is home
to all Americans, ``particularly minorites and immigrants.''
</P>
<P>
   The platform further calls for more affordable public housing,
urban renewal, Social Security reform, low-income tax credits and
reduced taxes for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics warn that the GOP must now follow through on its
platform commitments, and they don't believe the party's new look.
Except for the speakers, dancers and singers, they point out, the
convention's delegates are vastly white and largely wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think the Republican convention is a masquerade ball
designed to conceal the real identity and special interest agenda
of the same old party,'' said Dagoberto Vega, spokesman for
Democrat Al Gore's campaign. ``This doesn't reflect the face of
America.''
</P>
<P>
   About 4 percent of the 2,066 convention delegates are black and
1 percent are Hispanic, according to an Associated Press survey.
Men make up 61 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The number of black delegates, about 80, is up from about 50
four years ago, surveys show.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who unlike Republicans have official goals for
minority participation, estimated Wednesday that 20 percent of the
delegates to its upcoming convention are black and 10 percent are
Hispanic. Half are women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ask the state parties to make their delegations look as
much like America as possible,'' said Rick Hess, a Democratic
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, including party nominee George W. Bush, call
Democratic goals ``quotas.'' Critics say that stand, and the
party's opposition to affirmative action, are the main reasons to
doubt the party's attempt to build a new image.
</P>
<P>
   One of the key moments at the convention came Monday night when
retired Gen. Colin Powell challenged the party on affirmative
action. Delegates applauded his comments. But Bush, campaigning the
next day in West Virginia, sidestepped questions about Powell's
stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with Colin Powell that Republicans need to do more to
reach out to minorities,'' he said in an interview with Cox News.
``We've got a lot of work to do. And I agree with him that I'm the
man to do it for the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, Bush's communications director, said Bush what he
calls ``affirmative access'' but opposes race-based quotas because
``he believes quotas divide and Balkanize our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Daryl Duwe, a spokesman for the Missouri Republican Party, said
the system the Democrats use in selecting convention delegates
isn't fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wouldn't guarantee that the most deserving people get to
go,'' Duwe said. ``Those who work hardest ought to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But former Kansas City Mayor Emanuel Cleaver says the
Republicans' drive for diversity is like a husband never bringing
his wife roses and then suddenly bringing her dozens of them when
he falls out of favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've probably overdone it to the point that it doesn't even
look or feel legitimate,'' said Cleaver, who was Kansas City's only
black mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans acknowledge that changing the look of their
convention is not enough to win over minority voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party has to go beyond that,'' said Mark Parkinson who is
at the convention as chairman of the Kansas Republican Party. ``The
public is too sophisticated for there simply to be images not
followed up by action.''
</P>
<P>
   Barreto, who is a former Texan and is on the U.S. Hispanic
Chamber of Commmerce board of directors, said there is reason to
believe Bush could deliver on his pledge to help Hispanic and other
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   As Texas governor, Barreto said, Bush appointed Hispanics to
high offices such as secretary of state. Test scores of Hispanics
have risen during the Bush era, as have the number of
minority-owned businesses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush received more than 40 percent of the Hispanic vote in his
re-election for governor in 1998. He got an estimated 27 percent of
the black vote, according to a survey by several news
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Barrera, president of the Hispanic Chamber of Commerce of
Greater Kansas City, said Bush's efforts to reach out to minorities
is a way to portray himself as a moderate with broad appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the first Republican nominee who does not kow-tow to the
right,'' said Barrera, adding he is not necessarily for Bush.
``It's not just the right thing to do, it's the prudent thing to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Godwin OPara, a black Republican delegate from Wichita, said
Democrats should stop assuming they will get the votes of minority
voters and those voters should not assume Democrats are in their
corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats take them for granted,'' the native Nigerian
said. ``They say, if they don't vote for us, who are they going to
vote for? Republicans?''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Freeman, who is not at the convention but is a black Kansas
City area resident and former Republican congressional candidate,
said Bush is opening the door to minority participation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be disconcerting to Al Gore and the Democratic
party,'' Freeman said. ``We don't have to vote Democratic because
everyone before us has.''
</P>
<P>
   A poll CBS and The New York Times did July 20 found 84 percent
of black respondents planned to back Gore, compared to 6 percent
for Bush, with the rest uncommitted. A poll conducted by Knight
Ridder Newspapers last month gave Gore just a 50-34 percent lead
among decided Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has little chance of getting more overall minority
voters than Gore, modest success could decide a close election,
said Barbara Sinclair, political scientist at the University of
California-Los Angles.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they figure is, if they can cut into the near monolithic
Democratic support, that may be enough,'' Sinclair said.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hattaway, another spokesman for Gore's campaign, said there
are plenty of holes in Bush's Texas record when it comes to looking
after the interests of minority voters.
</P>
<P>
   Hattaway said Bush has never visited the poorest border towns of
Texas, has opposed legislation to curtail hate crimes and has
backed tax breaks for the oil industry while rejecting better
health insurance for low-income families. ``The Republican
convention is an illusion of inclusion,'' Hattaway said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Harold Ford Jr., a Tennessee Democrat, said Bush and
the Republicans have to follow through on the good will they have
tried to create.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even Bush admits his party is not living up to all that it
intends to be,'' Ford said. ``I applaud him. I just hope we can
point to some tangible examples of them actually doing something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
