<SLUG> BC-GASENATE-QUALIFY0803-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jordan abandons Georgia Senate bid
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Airline entrepreneur Lewis Jordan, the self-proclaimed
``fresh face'' some national Republican leaders felt could be their
best chance for reclaiming a U.S. Senate seat in Georgia, abruptly
pulled out of the race Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's typewritten statement, issued nearly four hours after
the close of the first day of candidate qualifying for the seat of
the late Sen. Paul Coverdell, narrowed the contest to two top
contenders: Democratic former Gov. Zell Miller and Mack Mattingly,
a Republican who won the Senate seat nearly 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell died two weeks ago of a brain hemorrhage. A Nov. 7
special election will fill the remaining four years of his term.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am personally honored to have been urged so strongly to
represent the people of Georgia in this important race,'' Jordan
said. ``However, in the interest of party unity and after careful
consideration of what I believe is in the best interest of my
family, I have chosen not to run.''
</P>
<P>
   He could not be reached for further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Republicans can now wage a three-month campaign without
splitting themselves between two major GOP candidates, which could
have given Miller_ appointed by Democratic Gov. Roy Barnes to
temporarily fill the post _ a clearer shot at winning the unexpired
term.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the week, some top state GOP leaders attending the
party's national convention in Philadelphia warned against fielding
more than one Republican candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Jordan, a political novice, opted out. But the
decision likely will give the 56-year-old founder of ValuJet _ now
AirTran Airways _ the option for a future career in statewide
Republican politics, if he so choses.
</P>
<P>
   Reached Wednesday night in Philadephia, Georgia GOP chairman
Chuck Clay first heard of Jordan's decision from reporters. But he
praised Jordan's handling of the situation and said he was both ``a
little bit sad'' and ``relieved'' that Republicans apparently will
have one candidate _ Mattingly _ to rally around in the contest
against Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said I prefer there be a single candidate; we look
stronger if we stay united,'' Clay said. But he also said the
decision not to qualify was totally Jordan's. ``I could 100 percent
support Lewis Jordan. I could 100 percent support Mack Mattingly.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one national Republican hasn't been as generous. U.S.
Sen. Mitch McConnell of Kentucky has said this week that Jordan
appeared to be the stronger candidate because the short,
three-month race ``is one of those occasions where you need a
candidate who can probably self-fund the race.'' McConnell, as
chairman of the National Republican Senatorial Committee, controls
substantial campaign purse strings.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan had told Georgia delegates
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
