<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cartoon museum can keep Mickey
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A judge saved Mickey Mouse from a sort
of museum prison Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Walter Colbath ordered the earliest known drawings of the
world's most renowned rodent be left hanging in the International
Museum of Cartoon Art in Boca Raton. A bank seeking to foreclose on
a loan to the museum had sought custody of the 36 pencil-drawn
sketches. A plan for their transfer would have locked them away in
a special vault at the Norton Museum of Art in West Palm Beach, far
from public view.
</P>
<P>
   Cheers rang out when word of the judge's decision reached the
cartoon museum staff about noon. ``There have been plenty of
hoorays around the building,'' said museum operations director
Jeanne Greever. ``We are pleased, happy and relieved.''
</P>
<P>
   Greever said she's particularly pleased that the valuable
sketches will remain on public display rather than being stuck ``in
a dark closet.''
</P>
<P>
   Colbath said SunTrust's demand that the drawings be moved to a
vault at the Norton would be expensive and place the fragile
artwork at unnecessary risk.
</P>
<P>
   An art conservator estimated it would cost $3,600 to prepare the
36 sketches to be moved.
</P>
<P>
   SunTrust can put a sign next to the cartoon display noting to
the public that the bank is entitled to possession, the judge
ruled.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what we had offered SunTrust two months ago,'' said
Nancy Colman, attorney for the museum. ``We are very excited with
the ruling.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not known if the bank will post a sign or appeal the
judge's decision. The bank's attorney, Lisa Hermann, did not return
phone calls Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Colbath last month granted SunTrust the right to possess the
drawings, but said the court would determine how the transfer of
custody would take place.
</P>
<P>
   The bank said it wanted the art work because the museum has
defaulted on its mortgage. The drawings, valued by the museum at
$3.7 million, were pledged as collateral for the loan.
</P>
<P>
   The museum owes $1.1 million on a $3 million mortgage it took
out in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Boca Raton Councilwoman Susan Whelchel said she has had numerous
calls about whether the city should step in and help the embattled
museum. One way to help would be to place a city library there. The
problem would be parking.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we have this opportunity, I think it might behoove us to
talk about it at the (Aug. 21) council meeting,'' Whelchel said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mickey Mouse drawings appear on six storyboards with six
drawings and were created in 1927 for the animated film ``Plane
Crazy,'' a spoof of the mania with aviator Charles Lindbergh.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the cartoon museum in Mizner Park have increased
since the controversy over the mouse drawings, Greever said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who comes in goes directly to them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
