<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1111 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-DIARY-1STLD-WRITE     08-02 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DIARY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILADELPHIA DIARY: A FUND-RAISER, A FAMILY REUNION AND THE ROCK 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Adds item at end about lost donation) 
ATTN: Conn., N.Y., Ga.  By ALEX KUCZYNSKI AND MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ It is your decision, America.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner at Alain Ducasse for two might set you back $500, but
lunch with Gov. George W. Bush and 3,099 of his best friends on
Wednesday ran to at least twice that at the Pennsylvania Convention
Center.
</P>
<P>
   But who needs foie gras poached in pepper court bouillon when
you can get soggy Caesar salad and a glass of bathtub-warm pinot
grigio (if you were one of the lucky ones).
</P>
<P>
   Bush chose to make his public party debut on Wednesday at the
Republican convention's biggest fund-raiser, which seemed in step
with Wednesday night's convention message of ``prosperity with a
purpose.'' The lunch certainly added to the party's prosperity,
raking in $10 million, party officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his wife, Laura, attended; so did his brother, Gov. Jeb
Bush of Florida, and Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's nephew, George P. Bush, the thinking woman's Ricky
Martin, showed up and flashed his extremely white teeth and spoke
heart-melting Spanish with one woman.
</P>
<P>
   The lunch had the feeling of any fund-raiser: rubber chicken, an
earnest children's chorus (to which no one listened) and lots of
schmoozing. But there was one big difference for most of the donors
at the lunch, at least according to the wife of a governor who
pleaded for anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Safely ensconced in the ladies room, she peered excitedly into
her plastic goody bag, the donor's version of a child's birthday
party bag. The contents: a notepad with a Republican National
Committee logo, a T-shirt and a Kit-Kat bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think for that much money, you'd at least get a
bottle of perfume,'' she complained.
</P>
<P>
   Prosperity, alas, has its limits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Familiar Face Returns
</P>
<P>
   With his familiar mop-top and full face, he could have been Pete
Rose at an old-timer's game the way fans angled for autographs and
snap shots with yesterday's hero.
</P>
<P>
   Newt Gingrich may be out, but he's not down.
</P>
<P>
   He's a member of the convention's overcrowded chattering class,
yakking online, on radio, on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm back to where I was before I was speaker, walking around
spreading new ideas,'' Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   The recent Gingrich idea that got the most attention was
registering online (at Web sites for Macy's and Williams-Sonoma)
for gifts for his coming wedding. But Gingrich said he and his
soon-to-be third wife were simply doing ``what most modern couples
do.''
</P>
<P>
   The ideas that really excite him these days are about science
and technology. He's studying and writing about technology,
advising corporations on strategic planning and, this week,
providing commentary on Fox Television.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich wasn't invited to the convention podium. First off, as
he says, ``the Republican Party hardly needs to build its strength
among white males.'' His brand of conservatism, even within the
Republican Party, often seemed as compassionate as a nail gun. And
since he used his 1996 convention speech to talk most memorably
about beach volleyball, apparently none of this convention's theme
nights seemed like a perfect fit.
</P>
<P>
   So what if he doesn't have a leading role in the convention he
calls the beginning of ``chapter four of the modern conservative
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, the third chapter was entitled ``The Contract with
America,'' he said with a satisfied smile.
</P>
<P>
   Protests Falling Flat
</P>
<P>
   Pity the protester.
</P>
<P>
   The crowds weren't overwhelming. The convention flowed smoothly.
Philadelphia residents actually cheered when the police arrested
them. Phildelphia, so far, doesn't compare to the protests over
world trade issues in Seattle, or even in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle was like a 9, because they declared martial law,''
said Henry Schwab, 27, a self-described traveling activist.
``Philadelphia's like a 4. D.C. was like a 5.5.''
</P>
<P>
   A Hispanic Welcome
</P>
<P>
   One of Bush's first stops on Wednesday was the Philadelphia
Museum of Art for what was billed as a Hispanic welcome event.
Latin music blared. But while Hispanic children were up on the
stage and Hispanics up front, the crowd was filled with a sizable
contingent of blond, non-Hispanic, College Republicans waving
``Viva Bush'' signs.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, David Standness, 21, said he was part of a bunch of
College Republicans who came by bus from Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was introduced by his Hispanic-American nephew, George P.,
who said, ``Are you excited about electing a president who
represents the diversity of our society?''
</P>
<P>
   A Family Reunion
</P>
<P>
   About 60 Bush family members _ all the siblings, the parents,
most or all of the siblings' kids _ planned an early dinner at the
Ritz Carlton. For the Bushes, national political conventions have
become family reunions. One campaign aide who is staying near the
family ay the Wyndham Hotel described the scene as ``very
exuberant, with lots of children running up and down the hall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of fun for the cousins,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rock Growls Back
</P>
<P>
   It ain't easy being mean.
</P>
<P>
   Dwayne Johnson, aka the Rock, introduced Dennis Hastert, the
speaker of the House, at Wednesday night's session. Why?
</P>
<P>
   It seemed appropriate that the World Wrestling Federation's most
celebrated wall of meat, Johnson, would introduce Hastert, who was
once a wrestling coach.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was happy about the invitation. As the Rock was
practicing his recitation on the convention floor (``Can you
s-m-e-l-l what the Rock is cooking?'' he wailed into the
microphone, flexing his shoulders so the seams on his white dinner
jacket swelled), L. Brent Bozell, the president of the Parents
Television Council, was steaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will hurt the Republicans in more ways than they can
possible imagine,'' Bozell said in a telephone interview. ``Any
time a Republican gives a speech about raunch or violence, the
bottom of the barrel stuff, people will be able to point to the
Rock, and his introduction of Hastert, and they will be able to say
that the Republicans sponsored and approved of and celebrated the
biggest superstar of raunch and violence. How vastly stupid can
they be?''
</P>
<P>
   On CNN, the Rock slammed back at Bozell, calling him ``an
extremist who represents a radical organization.'' And he stared
into the camera and chewed out Bozell. ``Grow up,'' he said. ``What
we do is entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   A donation lost, then found
</P>
<P>
   Campaign money is flowing so heavily here that some of it
spilled right onto the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Woodward, a reporter for The Philadelphia Inquirer, said
he found an envelope on the ground outside the convention hall on
Tuesday marked with the words ``$5,000 and Advo.'' Inside the
partly opened envelope he found a $5,000 check made out to ``McHugh
for Congress'' from the Advo political action committee.
</P>
<P>
   Advo Inc. is a direct-mail company in Connecticut, and Rep. John
M. McHugh, a Republican from Watertown, N.Y., is chairman of the
postal service subcommittee of the Government Reform Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward, who found the envelope while walking to The Inquirer's
convention office, tracked down McHugh and gave him the check. ``He
was taken a little aback,'' Woodward said. ``He started talking
about how Advo tried to find lost children and that's their real
passion,'' referring to the company's direct-mail program aimed at
advertising missing children.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward said McHugh explained that he was expecting a check
from company representatives, but that they had apparently dropped
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a lot of money in the scheme of things,'' Woodward
said. ``It's just a little glimpse of the stuff that's happening
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
