</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VACATION-RAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNUSUALLY RAINY SEASON RUINING VACATIONS FROM CAPE MAY TO CAPE
COD 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARIA NEWMAN with EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POINT PLEASANT BEACH, N.J. _ For the first few soggy, gray days
of her family's two-week vacation that started here on Saturday,
Barbara Cagliostro had a simple question: Where is everyone?
</P>
<P>
   Cagliostro, who lives in Armonk, N.Y., said her family had been
coming here for eight years and had never seen it this empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were wondering, is it just the weather, or is it that
people don't want to come to the Jersey Shore anymore?''
</P>
<P>
   As many of her fellow vacationers could have told her, it's the
weather.
</P>
<P>
   From Cape May to Cape Cod, rainy, dank days have turned many
family vacations into waterlogged duds.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Cagliostro was resting on a blue vinyl lawn chair
on the deck of her seaside rental, enjoying the first truly sunny
day of her vacation. The day before, Jenkinson's Beach here was
closed because of the weather. Lifeguards were told to go home
early in the day because it was so overcast. As Cagliostro sunned
herself, her children sold hand-painted seashells to passers-by on
the boardwalk for a quarter apiece: ``Even their sales have been
down,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether Wednesday's sunshine was just a respite
or a turn in the weather. Meteorologists said this July was the
coldest one on record in the New York metropolitan region, and one
of the wettest. And so far, August looks like it might start off
just as damp. Thunderstorms are predicted for Thursday in much of
the area, the National Weather Service said, although the weekend
could be clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be a pleasant summer weekend,'' said Ingrid
Amberger, meteorologist with the National Weather Service in
Brookhaven, N.Y. She said the long-range forecast for August was
for normal rainfall.
</P>
<P>
   At Jenkinson's Beach and Pavilion, the weather has meant fewer
people in the amusement park, fewer crowds to watch the Elvis
impersonators parachuting out of planes, and miserable business for
local shops.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, while much of New England and Long Island has been
drenched, there has been more gray weather than rain here.
</P>
<P>
   Diana Szala of Robbinsville, N.J., in Mercer County, heard the
predictions of rain for Tuesday, but headed to Jenkinson's Beach
with her three nieces anyway. When they arrived, the water was
off-limits to swimmers, but she and her nieces could still sit on
the beach, which is all they wanted to do anyway. And the overcast
day brought a boon: they didn't have to pay the entry fee to get on
the beach, or the $6 for parking.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had been charging, we wouldn't have come on the
beach,'' Szala said. ``What if we had paid $16.50 to get in, and
then in half an hour it rained? We figured if it was nice enough,
we'd just walk on the boardwalk. So we're lucky they're not
charging today.''
</P>
<P>
   People in other parts of the region have been coping with cabin
fever as their vacations were rained on.
</P>
<P>
   In Amagansett, on Long Island, the rain drove Janice Horowitz
and her husband, Richard Bookstaber, to stock up on arts and crafts
projects for their two children. The family began their two-week
summer rental, which they would only say cost them ``thousands,''
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Bookstaber and his children went swimming in the
ocean despite a drizzle. The next day, they went to a bowling alley
that was so crowded the manager was taking reservations, Horowitz
said. She decided to go shopping in East Hampton, but found that
much of the village parking lot was flooded, forcing her to turn
back.
</P>
<P>
   On Martha's Vineyard in Massachusetts, which had a day and a
half of sun between July 16 and July 30, Jill Sacks and her family
from Westchester County, N.Y., have spent much of their time
watching water drip from the kitchen ceiling and mice scurrying
across the floors. The swimming pool _ the main reason why the
family was renting the house _ has overflowed twice.
</P>
<P>
   Sacks said the family had decided to forgo a trip to the
Mediterranean partly because they thought they would spend time in
the pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like September, or the end of August, when the
hurricanes come in,'' Sacks said Tuesday. ``It's driving rain, and
it's relentless.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, finally, the sun shone on Martha's Vineyard for a
few minutes in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   The weather has taken its toll on other outdoor activities. In
the Berkshires in Massachusetts, the renowned Tanglewood music
series has taken a hit because of the rains, said Caroline Smedvig,
a spokeswoman for the Boston Symphony Orchestra, which performs
every weekend in the series.
</P>
<P>
   The concerts usually draw their largest crowds, up to 15,000
people, on Sunday afternoons. But last Sunday, only about 5,100
tickets were sold _ 19 of those out on the lawn, Smedvig said.
</P>
<P>
   In Point Pleasant Beach, some families were taking the gloomy
weather in stride, partly because they could find other things to
occupy their time. Even with the ocean off limits to swimming,
there was the amusement park. Tuesday, children could go on all the
rides for one price of $10. There was also the Jenkinson's
Aquarium, or the arcades and miniature golf. For the grown-ups,
there was the Tiki Bar.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Korey, a police detective from Millstone, N.J., in Monmouth
County, has been checking the weather reports on his laptop
computer, in between going out to the beach with his wife, Karen,
and children Mikayla, 3, and Dave, 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to take the good days with the bad,'' Korey said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second year the couple has rented a house on the
boardwalk for three weeks, and they came well prepared for whatever
nature threw at them. They made two trips from home to stock up
their three-week rental with enough videos and toys, such as a
children's pool, to keep their children busy, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the clouds, it has been warm enough to go swimming,
Korey said. ``Yesterday they could have made a commercial out here,
or a picture for a postcard, because there was no one on the
beach,'' he said. ``It's been great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
