<SLUG> BC-NJ-INFANT-RAPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN IS ACCUSED OF RAPING 4-MONTH-OLD GIRL 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT HANLEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. _ A 4-month-old infant was raped in her baby
sitter's apartment in Passaic last week, and a teen-age relative of
the sitter's was ordered held on $200,000 bail Wednesday on charges
of aggravated sexual assault, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The baby girl underwent surgery for genital injuries inflicted
during the assault, which occurred on July 24, and was hospitalized
for nearly a week, said Boris Moczula, first assistant prosecutor
in Passaic County.
</P>
<P>
   Moczula said county investigators were surprised at the age of
the girl when they first learned of the attack, and verified her
age at St. Joseph's Hospital in Paterson after the surgery. She is
thought to be the youngest victim of a sexual assault in Passaic
County history, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Marios Patino Cabrera, 18, was arrested on July 27.
As he appeared in New Jersey Superior Court in Paterson on
Wednesday, detectives arrested the baby sitter and accused her of
giving investigators false information about the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evidence suggests she knew an assault occurred,'' he said. The
baby sitter, Rosalba Rodriguez, 24, was charged with endangering
the welfare of a child for failing to seek medical help for the
baby and, later, lying to investigators, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cabrera, who works in a clothing factory in Newark, is believed
to be a cousin of the baby sitter's husband and lives in their
apartment in Passaic with several other relatives of the couple.
Moczula said the residents, as well as the victim's family, were
illegal immigrants from Mexico. Rodriguez had served as the
infant's baby sitter since May, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The attack occurred about 11:30 a.m. on July 24, after the
baby's father had left her at Rodriguez's apartment before he went
to work, Moczula said. In midmorning, he said, Rodriguez placed the
baby on her bed to sleep. The assault is thought to have occurred
there, Moczula said.
</P>
<P>
   In early afternoon, the baby sitter called the infant's mother
at work and told her that the baby had bled while being given a
bath. The baby sitter said she thought the bleeding was caused by a
diaper that had been put on backward, Moczula said.
</P>
<P>
   The baby's mother examined her and found injuries to her
genitals. The baby was discharged from St. Joseph's Hospital last
weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
