<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1256 &Cx1f; tad-z
b p BC-CVN-GOP-MAIN03-COX     08-02 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GOP-MAIN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH IS NOMINATED; CHENEY VOWS VICTORY
 &HT;    By KEN HERMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ George W. Bush, governor of Texas and scion of a
political family that includes a former president, on Wednesday
night officially claimed the Republican presidential nomination
that he won in March when he vanquished his last GOP foe.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:03 p.m. EDT, Wyoming cast its 22 ballots for Bush, putting
him over the 1,034 delegates he needed to clinch the nomination. A
four-minute celebration ensued, with delegates dancing amid
bouncing beach balls and sparkling confetti.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates also ratified Bush's choice of Dick Cheney, a former
Wyoming congressman, as their vice presidential nominee. Cheney
accepted and went right after the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we to make of the past eight years?'' he said, ``I
look at them and see opportunities squandered. The wheel has
turned. And it is time. It is time for them to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The final line echoed a chant led by Al Gore at the Democratic
National Convention in New York in 1992, when Bill Clinton won the
nomination. The Clinton-Gore ticket went on to defeat President
George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, a longtime Washington insider who served as defense
secretary for President Bush, may not be the ideal symbol of
change. But he used his prime-time speech to tout Republican
strengths, particularly those of the man who will now lead the
ticket as he tries to avenge the 1992 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see in our nominee the qualities of mind and spirit our
nation needs, and our history demands,'' Cheney said. ``Big changes
are coming to Washington. To serve with this man, in this cause, is
a chance I would not miss.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest, and best change, Cheney said, would begin the
moment White House changes hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``These have been years of prosperity in our land, but little
purpose in the White House. Bill Clinton vowed not long ago to hold
on to power until the last hour of the last day. That is his right.
But, my friends, that last hour is coming. That last day is near,''
he said, drawing a loud ovation.
</P>
<P>
   He also joined in Bush's promise of a new tone in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last eight years that city has often become a scene of
bitterness and ill will and partisan strife,'' Cheney said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's nomination came on the third night of a ``rolling roll
call vote.'' Former President Bush and his wife, Barbara, joined
the celebration as their son secured the nomination, clapping to
the Latino music that filled the arena.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's session began on a more somber note, though,
with Republicans offering their good wishes for former President
Gerald Ford, who was hospitalized after suffering one and possibly
two strokes. Doctors said Ford's prognosis was good.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who will deliver his vision for the party in his
acceptance speech tonight, practiced his key line during a
Wednesday sound check on the massive stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fellow Americans,'' he said as applause welled up from
delegates and others in the First Union Center while the convention
was not in session, ``I accept your nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, Bush said he senses a nation hungry for his
brand of leadership and ready to reject Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you what I am seeing and what I'm feeling. I'm
feeling Americans ready for change,'' Bush said at a Republican
National Committee fund-raising luncheon. ``They don't want four
more years of Clinton-Gore. They want somebody to appeal to our
better angels, not our darker impulses. And that's exactly what
Dick Cheney and I are going to give them.''
</P>
<P>
   At Gore headquarters in Nashville, the Democrats were ready with
an answer to Cheney's question about the past eight years, offering
a chart documenting the nation's recent prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheney helped bring about the days of deficits, debt and
recession in the 1980s. He would help George W. Bush bring them
back,'' said Douglas Hattaway, spokesman for the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is countering with a ``prosperity with a purpose'' message
that was Wednesday night's theme.
</P>
<P>
   Bush arrived in Philadelphia on Wednesday morning and went right
to work on his effort to change the party's demographics, starting
the day with a morning rally aimed at Latinos. Bush was introduced
by nephew George P. Bush, son of Florida Gov. Jeb Bush and his
Mexican-born wife, Columba.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you guys excited about electing a president who represents
the diversity of our society, who we can count on to change the
Republican Party so that it starts to represent our views and our
faces and our diversity?'' George P. Bush asked the crowd, calling
his uncle ``somebody who represents our people, who represents our
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The GOP presidential candidate's first words were in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vamos a ganar,'' said Bush, prior to bringing former foe John
McCain and wife, Cindy, on stage.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who is fluent in Spanish, was telling the crowd, ``We are
going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Juntos podemos,'' Bush said. ``Together we can. Together, we
can make sure every child can read in America. Together, we can
make sure entrepreneurship spreads its wings. Together, we can make
sure el sueno americano es para todos que vivan en esta pais. And
junta podemos ganar en noviembre. Muchas gracias.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's seamless transition into Spanglish told the crowd that
the ``American dream is possible for all those who live in this
country. And together we can win in November. Thank you very
much.''
</P>
<P>
   From the museum steps, Bush went to a far more traditionally
Republican setting, a luncheon gala sponsored by donors, including
lobbyists and corporate sponsors, who paid $1,000 to $250,000 to
enjoy New England crab cakes and Virginia custard.
</P>
<P>
   The event brought the party $10.1 million in unlimited,
unregulated soft money that the party will use to back Bush and
other GOP candidates. There were 109 companies and individuals
listed as co-chairmen, a title earned by giving or raising
$250,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we ask and we ask and we ask again,'' Brad Freeman, a
California businessman and longtime Bush friend, told the audience
of 3,000 at the Pennsylvania Convention Center. ``But we do it all
because it is important.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry McAuliffe, the Democrats' top fund-raiser and convention
head, said the Republicans have been ``shameless'' in their pursuit
of money, particularly soft money, at the convention. The
Democratic National Committee will not raise soft money at its
convention in Los Angeles, which begins Aug. 14, McAuliffe said.
</P>
<P>
   The party will hold one fund-raiser during the Democratic
convention, headlined by Barbara Streisand and Whoopi Goldberg,
which is expected to raise $3 million to $4 million in hard money,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the prime beneficiary of the GOP money, told the donors
their efforts will pay off.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all goes well, you're looking at the next president of the
United States,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
