<HEADER>
A1259 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-CONVENTION-RDP-1S     08-02 1435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-CONVENTION-RDP-1STLD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AND CHENEY NOMINATED TO LEAD GOP BACK TO WHITE HOUSE  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   (EDs: Updates with quotes; pickup: Bush aides said.)   
 By STEWART M. POWELL   
 c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; PHILADELPHIA _ Republicans on Wednesday night formally
nominated George W. Bush to carry their hopes of regaining the
White House in the Nov. 7 election and roared with approval as vice
presidential nominee Dick Cheney hammered the Clinton-Gore
administration with sharply partisan rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, enthusiastically accepting the nomination as Bush's
running mate, quickly shed his legendary cool, telling cheering,
bell-ringing delegates that the Clinton-Gore administration had
``squandered'' opportunities amid prosperity, provided ``little
purpose'' to the White House and wearied the nation with the
``Clinton-Gore routine.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the two-term governor of Texas, watched the formalities
from his hotel suite surrounded by family members, including his
wife Laura, their twin 18-year-old daughters and his siblings _
including Florida Gov. Jeb Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had taken the same stage at the 22,000-seat convention hall
only a few hours earlier to get familiar with the setting for his
own acceptance speech on Thursday night. Bush, saying his 38-minute
address was ``ready to go,'' tested the convention hall sound
system with a stentorian recitation of his most essential line:
``My fellow Americans, I accept your nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   The nominations cleared the way for the front-running campaign
to receive almost $68 million in federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans breathed a collective sigh of relief after word
spread that former President Gerald Ford, 87, was in stable
condition at the intensive care ward of a local hospital after
suffering one and possibly two small strokes. Ford had walked into
Philadelphia's Hahnemann University Hospital under his own power
with a briefcase in hand about 9 a.m. after suffering slurred
speech, dizziness and weakness in an arm Tuesday night. Dr. Robert
Schwartzman, chief of neurology at the hospital, said Ford was
expected to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's address to the GOP convention gave the 59-year-old
former Wyoming congressman a chance to reintroduce himself to
America after being thrown on the defensive by Democratic criticism
of his conservative voting record during 10 years in the House
before becoming President Bush's defense secretary in 1989. Cheney
named President Clinton or Vice President Al Gore at least nine
times in his remarks as part of the GOP strategy to hamstring their
misdeeds. Cheney never mentioned Clinton's sexual dalliance with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky or the impeachment that
followed but referred to the scandal indirectly, saying that Bush,
``a man of principle, a man of honor'' would ``repair what has been
damaged.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney stole a cherished campaign line used by Gore during the
Clinton-Gore campaign that unseated President Bush in 1992,
reciting Clinton-Gore missteps and repeatedly declaring, ``It's
time for them to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Big changes are coming to Washington,'' Cheney promised during
remarks that were crafted with the help of John McConnell, one of
George W. Bush's most experienced speech writers. ``On the first
hour of the first day, (Bush) will restore decency and integrity to
the Oval Office.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, recalling his decision to leave Washington and enter the
energy services industry with Dallas-based Halliburton Corp. in
1995, said that
</P>
<P>
   he had ``never expected to be in this position.'' But Cheney
said that he agreed to undertake his maiden national campaign at
Bush's side because ``to serve with this man in this cause is a
chance I would not miss.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush had announced his selection of Cheney in late July.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney addressed the Republicans on the 10th anniversary of the
Iraqi invasion of Kuwait that brought him to national attention as
a savvy wartime defense secretary during the Persian Gulf War. His
wife of 36 years, Lynn Cheney, introduced him as a ``fabulous
father,'' a patient fly fisherman and man who was rarely a
``chatterbox.'' Mrs. Cheney added: ``He will be a very, very good
vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, Bush's campaign spokeswoman, said the governor
hoped that Cheney's address would ``remind people that Secretary
Cheney is a statesman who brings a depth of experience to the
Republican ticket.'' Hughes said Cheney's congressional voting
record had been ``misrepresented'' by Democratic critics who were
quick to portray the ex-lawmaker as a conservative opposed to
abortion rights, the Head Start early education program, gun
control and strict environmental standards.
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides said they were buoyed by ongoing polling that showed
the Bush-Cheney ticket gaining strength against a ticket led by
Gore. A Voter.com-Battleground survey showed the Bush-Cheney ticket
widening its margin from 8 percentage points over the weekend to 13
percentage points in polling that ended Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Bush led Gore 49 percent to 36 percent in a four-way match-up
that included Green Party candidate Ralph Nader, who had 4 percent,
and Reform Party contender Pat Buchanan who had 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans' formal nomination of Bush and Cheney cleared the
way for their campaign to immediately receive $67.6 million in
federal funds to conduct their campaign through election day. Bush
receives the federal funds despite privately financing his primary
campaign with more than $80 million raised from donors in an
unprecedented financial juggernaut that left rivals, including Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz., in the dust.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Snyder, spokeswoman for the Federal Election Commission
in Washington, D.C., said the Bush-Cheney campaign could receive a
wire transfer of the federal funds from the U.S. Treasury as early
as Thursday, following approval by the six-member commission. The
GOP had already received $13.5 million to stage the convention.
``We're ready to go,'' Snyder said. &QC; 
Federal law provides the presidential candidates from the major
parties equal federal funding after their selection as nominees.
The law limits the candidates to spending that amount, although the
candidates also benefit from unlimited, unregulated so-called
soft-money spending by parties and political action groups on their
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, sweeping into Philadelphia from a five-state, five-day
barnstorming tour of swing states, rang a replica of the Liberty
Bell at the airport and quickly reached out to the nation's
influential Hispanic community by addressing a rally of Hispanic
Republicans in English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Standing before a banner at the Philadelphia Museum of Art that
declared ``a new day'' in Spanish, Bush told several thousand
supporters gathered at the top of stone steps made famous in the
``Rocky'' series of movies that ``there's a better day for America;
there's a better day for all.'' Bush added in Spanish and English:
``Together we can win in November.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also kept up the GOP's torrid pace of campaign fund raising
pace with an appearance at a $10 million luncheon gala that will
benefit the Republican National Committee's efforts to help both
the Bush-Cheney ticket and Republican candidates for the House and
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush stood before a giant projection of the White House's South
Lawn that made it look as though he and Cheney were actually
standing on the lawn looking back toward the executive mansion that
has been inhabited since then-Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton ousted
President Bush in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Bush offered his cadre of well-heeled donors a ``report from the
field'' based upon triumphant visits since last Friday to Arkansas,
Missouri, Kentucky, Ohio and West Virginia. ``Let me tell you what
I'm seeing and what I'm feeling _ I'm feeling America is ready for
a change,'' Bush told his delighted audience. ``They don't want
four more years of Clinton-Gore. ... America is hungry for new
leadership and that is exactly what Dick Cheney and I are going to
give them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush added: ``If all goes well _ if all goes well _ you're
looking at the next president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   GOP chairman Jim Nicholson told the Republican donors that he
had ``never seen a party more united and more resolved to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The violent protests that rocked Philadelphia on Tuesday,
leading to at least 350 arrests, sharply abated Wednesday, with
small platoons of protesters carrying out mostly peaceful
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or via e-mail:
stewart(at) hearstdc.com)
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
