<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVOLUTION-BOARD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE OVER SCIENCE STANDARDS IN KANSAS IS FAR FROM OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE BEEM  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Moderates who have regained control of the
Kansas Board of Education vow to reopen the debate over science
standards that play down the role of evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Come January, at least three moderate Republicans or their
Democratic challengers will join three other moderates on the
board, guaranteeing a shift back toward the philosophical middle
after the board's four-year lean to the right.
</P>
<P>
   And evolution, along with other issues from math to teacher
licensing, will make a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Gamble, who defeated incumbent Linda Holloway, said
Wednesday that she had discussed the future of the standards with
the two other moderate winners and the four board members who voted
against the standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters have spoken,'' said moderate Bruce Wyatt, a Salina
lawyer who beat a conservative for the Republican nod in the 6th
District race.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-member board oversees the state's 304 school districts.
All members serve four-year terms, and half the members face voters
every two years.
</P>
<P>
   The storm over evolution broke a year ago, when the five
conservatives and one moderate voted to adopt science standards
that deleted references to the age of the Earth, the big-bang
theory of creation and some references to evolutionary theory.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the standards said they allowed local districts to
decide whether to teach evolution or another theory. But critics
said the decision set Kansas education back and was an
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   The conservatives have used their five-plus-one majority since
1998 but as early as next week could lose one of those crucial
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, a Republican committee in north-central Kansas
was to recommend a candidate to finish the term of former board
member Scott Hill, a conservative who moved from Abilene to Montana
earlier this year. The appointment would be made by Gov. Bill
Graves, who has allied himself with the moderates and endorsed
Wyatt in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Saline County Republican leaders indicated earlier this summer
that they would like Graves to appoint the winner of the primary.
That's Wyatt, and should he be appointed, he could assume the seat
as early as Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Moderates are calling their near-sweep of the Republican state
board primaries a referendum on solid education, which they say
includes teaching evolution.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, moderates such as Gamble hope to broaden state
assessment tests and try to reclaim the school-to-work program,
which a deadlocked and leery board passed off to another Kansas
governmental agency.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas voters usually favor Republicans in the general election,
but should Democrats win these seats in November it woudn't matter,
predicted Val De Fever, a moderate state board member from
Independence.
</P>
<P>
   All the Democrats, including incumbent Bill Wagnon of Topeka,
have said they want to rescind the new science standards in favor
of those written by science teachers. Those standards would elevate
evolution to a concept unifying all scientific disciplines.
</P>
<P>
   In the November election, only one state board race should focus
on evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Incumbent conservative Steve Abrams of Arkansas City, who helped
write the controversial science standards, won his primary Tuesday
and will face Democrat Wayne Holt of Haysville.
</P>
<P>
   If Abrams wins, he will rejoin one other conservative _ John
Bacon of Olathe _ and a moderate, Harold Voth of Haven, who often
votes with the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said Wednesday that he did not doubt that moderates would
do as they say, but he said he wouldn't support changing the
standards again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be there,'' Bacon said. ``And I'll be part of the
discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually low-profile, this year's five state board races gained
national attention, thanks to the evolution decision. They were
featured on ABC's ``Nightline'' and the ``CBS Evening News,'' among
other programs. Three times in the last year the evolution issue
made the front page of The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the race between Holloway and Gamble came to
symbolize the issue. Holloway was the board's mouthpiece after the
board's August 1999 vote, when national and international media
descended on Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   After conceding defeat Tuesday night, Holloway said she and
other conservatives had taken a stand for academic freedom, for
allowing more than one theory of life's origins to be taught in
science classes, and so launched an idea that can't be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the dogma will stand,'' she said. ``Too many
people have had a chance to think about this (evolution).''
</P>
<P>
   And that's not such a bad thing, said the Rev. Barry Lynn of
Americans United for Separation of Church and State, which
disagreed with the board's decision a year ago. Reopening the
discussion allows science to rebut what Lynn called false
information put out by creationists.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people realize what the nature of general science is,
they reject that far-right view and adopt a sensible middle
ground,'' Lynn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
