<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1261 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NJ-MCGREEVEY-NYT &LR;      08-02 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-MCGREEVEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J.'S MCGREEVEY TIPS HAT TO SUPPORTERS, INCLUDING DEMOCRATS FROM
16 COUNTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Having outrun an attempt by Sen. Robert
Torricelli to sprint past him toward the Democratic nomination for
New Jersey governor, Mayor James McGreevey of Woodbridge took a
symbolic victory lap Wednesday at a news conference in Trenton,
showing off the state and county party leaders who have rallied to
his side.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what unity looks like,'' McGreevey said as he stood
among a group of 50 party leaders and lawmakers who he said
represented both South and North Jersey, as well as cities and
suburbs. It included Democratic leaders from 16 of 21 counties and
many of the party's state legislators.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders were assembled by the state party chairman, Thomas
Giblin, who said that without Torricelli's potentially divisive
efforts for the nomination, the party would be stronger.
</P>
<P>
   McGreevey, who was the party's nominee in 1997 and lost by a
narrow margin to Gov. Christie Whitman, had been moving without
competition toward the 2001 nomination until a few weeks ago, when
Torricelli began an effort to line up Democratic leaders behind his
potential candidacy. But over the weekend, McGreevey secured the
crucial endorsements of leaders in populous Essex County. On
Monday, Torricelli announced he would not run for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli has refused to offer an endorsement for McGreevey,
and mentioned two other Democrats he said might seek the
nomination: Reps. Bill Pascrell of Paterson and Frank Pallone Jr.
of Long Branch. Pallone confirmed Wednesday that he was considering
a run for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But Brad Lawrence, a spokesman for the McGreevey campaign, said
it would be hard to mount a challenge with just the potential
backing of leaders in the five counties not represented in
Wednesday's show of support. Those counties are Camden, Monmouth,
Morris, Passaic and Burlington.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, McGreevey was gracious and stopped short of saying
that he had replaced Torricelli as the ``the 800-pound gorilla'' of
state Democratic politics, adding, ``I have the gray hairs to prove
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the leaders at Wednesday's event was Joseph Ferriero,
Democratic chairman in Bergen County, the state's most populous and
Torricelli's home county. Earlier in the week, Ferriero was in a
quandary, unwilling to oppose a favorite son but still strongly
attracted to the candidacy of McGreevey. When Mayor Sharpe James of
Newark held a news conference with other Essex County Democrats on
Monday to support McGreevey, Ferriero was in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there to show my support for McGreevey,'' he said of his
nervous wait on the sidelines. ``But if Bob Torricelli was a
candidate, I would have to support him because he is our local
senator. But today, with Bob not in the race, I'm free.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence, of the McGreevey campaign, said that in contrast to
the frantic pace of the last two weeks, McGreevey would use the
more leisurely atmosphere of the coming months _ when the
presidential and senatorial campaigns take center stage _ to bring
other Democratic leaders into the fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still some hard work needed to heal,'' Lawrence said,
``but today is the beginning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
