<HEADER>
A1267 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MACQA-APPLE &LR;      08-02 1898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACQA-APPLE </SLUG>
  
 NEW APPLE MONITORS ONLY WORK WITH LATEST G4S
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY HENRY NOOR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE SENIOR WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: &LR; I've been thinking for a while about replacing the 15-inch &LR; 
 &LR; monitor I now have on my Power Mac G4 with an Apple 21-inch &LR; 
 &LR; Studio Display. But when I finally made up my mind last week &LR;   &LR; and
went to the Apple online store to order one, it wasn't &LR;   &LR; there.
What happened, and, more important, where can I get one? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A: If you really want that particular monitor, hurry over to a
different online outlet or your favorite local dealer, and if you
see one in stock, snap it right up _ it'll soon be hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Apple abruptly discontinued its 21-inch model,
along with all the other monitors it had been selling, when it
introduced the G4 Cube and updated the rest of its desktop line at
last month's Macworld Expo. At the same time, the company rolled
three new and improved monitors _ 15- and 22-inch flat panels and a
17-inch CRT _ but they're designed only for the new Power Mac G4s
(including the new G4 Cube); they won't work with the original G4
series, or with any other older Mac.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is that the new monitors rely on a newfangled,
Apple-invented port and cable called the Apple Display Connector
(ADC). It carries not only video signals, but also electric power
to the display and data to and from the two-port USB hubs built
into the monitors' bases. Because the monitors have no other way to
get power, and earlier computer and video card don't have ADC
connectors and anyway don't provide power, there's no way to mix
the old with the new.
</P>
<P>
   That may change: Apple says it's open to talking to companies
that might want to design an adapter that would make the new
displays usable on older Macs (or even PCs, I suppose). But no such
device has been announced yet, and when and if one appears, it
probably won't be cheap, because it will have to include a power
supply.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the new lineup doesn't even include a 21-inch monitor,
and the 22-inch Apple Cinema Display still costs a staggering
$3,999.
</P>
<P>
   I did some checking with Bay Area dealers and online discounters
earlier this week, and most of them still had the discontinued
21-inch display in stock.
</P>
<P>
   But if you can't find one, or you're not quite ready to buy,
don't panic _ dozens of other companies, including such giants as
NEC, Samsung, Sony and ViewSonic, will continue to offer 21-inch
and other displays that work with your G4. They won't match the
color and styling of your system as closely as the old Apple model,
but many of them offer comparable quality, often at lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is a little ironic: It was only last year that Apple
finally abandoned the proprietary display connectors it had been
using since the 1980s (the ``DB-15'' style _ not to mention the
even odder ``high-density'' connector that came with the first
Power Macs in 1994) and switched to industry-standard plugs.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the company hasn't completely renounced these
standards; at least for now only the new monitors are strictly
dependent on the company's latest proprietary scheme. The Cube and
the other new G4s still have a conventional VGA connector alongside
the new ADC, so customers in the opposite situation from yours _
people hoping to use an existing monitor with a new Mac _ don't
need to worry; any standard monitor should just plug and play when
connected to that port on a new G4.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have about 800 dates that I have entered in a database in
AppleWorks. The format is mm/dd/yy. I want to sort these by year.
However, when I sort using the ``Sort records'' command, I get a
list sorted by month first, e.g. January (1), then December (12),
then October (10), next comes February (2) and so forth. I have
been unable to find a process or formula to sort by year, month and
day, in the above format. None of the ``dummy'' books or the Mac's
user manual help. I have tried placing the year first, e.g. yy/
mm/dd. This gives me the year sort, but the months are still out of
sorts. Hope you can help.
</P>
<P>
   A: There are lots of problems with AppleWorks 6, even after two
recent updates, but as far as I can tell, this isn't one of them _
I made several test databases of my own and can't reproduce your
problem.
</P>
<P>
   It's conceivable that some odd extension conflict on your system
is causing it, but my guess is something else: I'll bet that when
you created your database, you made the date field a ``text'' type
field. It's easy to do, because that's the default type in
AppleWorks, and it works for most fields in most simple databases.
But when you sort on such a field, the program won't know it's
working with date information _ it will interpret the data as a
simple string of numbers and therefore put your records in the odd
order you're seeing.
</P>
<P>
   To solve the problem, open your database, go to the Layout menu
and choose ``Define Fields.'' You'll see a screen listing all the
fields in your database, and if my guess is right, you'll see
``Text'' listed as the type next to your date field. To change it
to ``Date,'' click on the field name to select it, then click on
the ``Modify'' button, then choose ``Date'' from the pop-up menu
labeled Type.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've made that change, your data should sort in proper
chronological order.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, if you're using AppleWorks 6.0 or 6.0.3, it's well
worth your while to upgrade to the latest version, 6.0.4. You can
download a free updater at
 &LR; asu.info.apple.com/swupdates.nsf/artnum/n11700 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   PRINTING FAVORITES
</P>
<P>
   Q: I use Internet Explorer 4.5 to browse the Web from my iMac.
I'd like to print out a list of the Web sites on my Favorites menu,
but I can't figure out how. I've even looked in a number of
reference books, but I haven't been able to find any answers. Can
you help?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's a simple question that deserves a simple answer.
Unfortunately, it doesn't have one. I did finally dig up a few
solutions, but none is completely satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, as you evidently discovered, is that IE 4.5 (or
5.0, for that matter) won't print either its Favorites ``pane'' or
its more-detailed Favorites window.
</P>
<P>
   Not finding any pertinent advice in IE's Help file, and seeing
that neither of the two shareware utilities I've previously
recommended for other printing problems _ Net-Print and WebPrint
Plus _ solves this one, I appealed for assistance to the PR person
for Microsoft's Mac applications. An hour or two later, I had an
answer: ``There is not a direct command inside IE that automates
this, but here is a way to print out the Fav's:
</P>
<P>
   From the File menu in IE, choose Open File. Navigate to System
Folder: Preferences: Explorer. Open the file named Favorites.html.
Choose Print from the File menu.''
</P>
<P>
   That works, as long as all you need printed are the names of
your Favorites, together with the brief descriptions many sites
embed in the HTML code for their pages.
</P>
<P>
   What you don't get are the URLs _ the actual Web addresses of
your Favorites. Without them, you or anyone else reading your
printout would have a hard time getting to the sites listed.
</P>
<P>
   But the only ways I found to get a printout including the URLs
are all pretty complicated. The simplest is probably to open the
Favorites page, as above, then choose Source from the View menu. A
new window will open, containing the HTML source code for the page,
which includes the names, descriptions and URLs. You can print that
page right from IE, but you'll probably want to copy its contents
into your word processor so you can get rid of the ugly code
cluttering it up.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative is to take and print a screen shot of IE's
Favorites window. Go to the Favorites menu and click ``Organize
favorites.'' Open any closed folders and, if necessary, adjust the
width of the Name column (by clicking just to the left of the line
that separates the column headers) and of the whole window, so all
URLs will be displayed in full.
</P>
<P>
   Now, to save that screen, you'll need one of the Mac's more
obscure keyboard shortcuts: press your CapsLock key, then,
simultaneously, Command-Shift-4. Your cursor will turn into a sort
of bull's eye. Put it anywhere in IE's Favorites window and click.
</P>
<P>
   That will save a picture of that window, in PICT format, on your
startup hard drive _ it will be saved in the root (main) directory
of your startup hard drive under the name Picture 1 (or Picture 2,
3, whatever, if you've previously created other screen shots).
</P>
<P>
   If you have too many favorites to fit all at once in the window,
scroll down and take another screen shot; repeat as necessary. Now
rename these files to something more meaningful and, if you wish,
move them to a new folder so they won't clutter up your main
directory.
</P>
<P>
   To print them, you can open them with just about any Mac
graphics or word processing program, including SimpleText, the
mini-editor that comes with the Mac OS. To make sure the URLs don't
get spread across a page break, you may want to go to the Page
Setup command on the File menu and switch to landscape (horizontal)
orientation or reduce the scale to less than 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the convoluted procedure, the problem with this
approach is that what you end up with is just a picture, so you
can't edit or even copy the site names or URLs. A third solution
that avoids this problem is to download a $30 shareware utility
called URL Manager Pro, which you can find at
 &LR; www.url-manager.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Install it, then use its ``Get from Browser'' command to bring
in your IE Favorites.
</P>
<P>
   The names and URLs of these sites will be shown in URL Manager
Pro's main window. You could print them from there, but there's a
problem: The program simply cuts off the ends of addresses too long
to fit in two lines. If you enter the truncated URL in your
browser, it won't work.
</P>
<P>
   You can work around this by using URL Manager Pro's Export
command to save the list as text. That way, you'll get the full
URL, along with site names and descriptions, in a tab-delimited
text file. The downside to this approach is that such files are
pretty hard to read unless you import and reformat them with a word
processor or spreadsheet _ yet more steps.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone has a better solution, let me know and I'll include it
next month.
</P>
<P>
   TIP OF THE MONTH
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of great add-on utility programs _ most of them
shareware _ that make it easier to open files, folders and
applications you use regularly, but I've recently discovered one
that's even more flexible. Called Drop Drawers, it lets you line
the sides of your screen with small tabs.
</P>
<P>
   When you move the mouse over them, they slide out to reveal a
``drawer'' where you can store just about anything you use
regularly: Aliases to files, folders and applications, URLs for Web
sites, e-mail addresses, snippets of text (complete with character
styling if you wish), even pictures, movies and sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The program is from Sig Software, and you can get more
information and download a copy at
 &LR; www.sigsoftware.com/dropdrawers/index.html &LR; . If you keep it, don't
forget to pay the $15 shareware fee.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Mac Q&AMP;A runs the first Thursday of each month. Send questions
to Henry Norr at mac &LR; (at) &LR; sfgate.com. Please specify what Mac model
and what version of the Mac OS you're using.
</P>
