<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1269 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WEBCAM-BROADCASTING &LR;      08-02 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBCAM-BROADCASTING </SLUG>
  
 CHATTING WITH SOUND, PICTURES
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY CARRIE KIRBY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;   &LR; When Jayson Agagnier chats online with his
4-month-old nephew, the two sit in front of Internet cameras so
that they can see each other while they talk.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco resident also likes to use a laptop with a
cellular modem and Webcam to capture images of the city's streets _
as viewed from the front of a cable car.
</P>
<P>
   With permission from Muni, he attaches a camera to the front of
a cable car about once a month and beams the images to his personal
Web page.
</P>
<P>
   He can capture only still photos that update every few seconds,
but faster cellular modems will soon be available that will allow
him to broadcast live video as the car rolls from the wharf to
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the fast-moving world of Webcasting.
</P>
<P>
   Internet cameras have been around as long as the World Wide Web
itself. Until recently, plugging a camera into a computer and
broadcasting images of yourself to the world was something only
geeks did. The Web is still full of live cameras showing the
insides of computer labs.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the availability of cheaper cameras and free Web-based
services are making broadcasting pictures and live video onto the
Internet so easy that regular people are using Webcams to share
special moments with family or hold everyday conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Web sites such as SpotLife and Camarades are supplying
everything needed for free online camera use with the hope that Web
broadcasting can be as common a way to stay in touch as e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, a few barriers remain before Webcasting can become
part of our daily lives. For people without broadband Internet
connections, video images move slowly and appear jerky.
</P>
<P>
   And because many free services list all their members in a
directory and don't offer password-protected private
videoconferencing, some broadcasters may find that they are
sacrificing their privacy to go online.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setbacks, it is relatively easy to be a Webcaster.
</P>
<P>
   Today's Webcams are capable of recording still pictures, video
and audio. Unlike digital cameras, Webcams have to be physically
attached to a computer to work.
</P>
<P>
   Users plug the Webcam into the computer and then log on to
SpotLife or a similar Web site, which guides them through an easy
setup process that usually takes about half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't use to be this easy. Before these free Webcasting
services came along, would-be Internet broadcasters had to spend a
lot of time setting up servers and figuring out how to make
pictures appear on their personal Web pages. Now it's not even
necessary to have a Web page to broadcast, because the Web sites
mentioned above provide a place to store video and images online.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Jeremy Schwartz said sharing video online like Agagnier
and his nephew do is the natural next step in the evolutionary
chain from e-mailing photos and greeting cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of rich media (images, video and sound) as a
communications method among consumers is just going to go through
the roof,'' Schwartz said. In a recent report for his employer,
Forrester Research, Schwartz predicted that in five years, when
broadband DSL or cable modem connections are more common, 92
percent of consumers will use visuals and audio to communicate on
the Internet once a month.
</P>
<P>
   The price of Webcams are falling, from about $300 a few years
ago to less than $100. Last month, mainstream Webcam use got a
boost when Compaq began including a Logitech QuickCam and SpotLife
software with each Presario it sells.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Webcam technology is getting better and more fun to
use. Traditional Webcams show photographs, updated periodically _
as slowly as once every 15 minutes, or as rapidly as 30 times a
second.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Webcams have been silent. But now, broadband
connections and free Webcasting services make it possible for
ordinary people to broadcast streaming videos and sound.
</P>
<P>
   Another developing technology, cellular modems, is making it
possible to use Webcams to show the folks at home what you're doing
on vacation. Like cell phones, cellular modems are mobile, giving
Webcasters the freedom to leave their homes and capture outdoor
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Some say Webcam technology still has room for improvement.
Warren Slocum, San Mateo county clerk, and his two children use
Webcams to chat with Slocum's father a few times a week. ``It's not
like a smooth motion picture, but the quality is OK for what it
is,'' Slocum said.
</P>
<P>
   While he and his father found setting up the cameras easy,
Slocum said it took awhile to get used to talking to a camera while
looking at the computer screen. The experience is more like using a
walkie-talkie than a telephone, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get in the rhythm _ one person talks, the other
person listens. You can't be talking simultaneously,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because both Slocum and his father have a Webcam, they both can
see each other while they talk.
</P>
<P>
   Web broadcasters, though, can easily interact with friends who
don't have Webcams by using text chat. Camarades and most other
online Webcam sites offer chat rooms that appear right next to or
below the Webcam image, so the users can chat and view video at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   Others use their Webcams to record video, then send it as an
e-mail attachment or post it online.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone will feel comfortable opening family events or
conversations to the public. While some Webcam services, such as
SpotLife, make it possible to protect broadcasts with a password so
only the intended viewer can see it, other services, such as
Camarades, don't have password protection.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Chlubna, a Camarades user who lives in Pacifica, has
experienced harassment from unintended viewers. In exchange for its
free service, Camarades requires all broadcasters to be listed in
its directory. That means anyone who wants to can see any of the
content.
</P>
<P>
   Chlubna set up a Webcam on Camarades so his girlfriend could see
him from her home in Australia. But he soon began receiving daily
unwanted e-mails and instant messages from men he didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   Recently he posted an indignant message on his page, telling
viewers that he is not ginterested in receiving any comments.
</P>
<P>
   A little unpleasantness is not too large a price to pay in
exchange for the free service, Chlubna said. But he has a warning
for new Web broadcasters: ``Be prepared for harassment. You open
yourself up to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other camera users see things they don't want to see when
browsing through the camera directories listed on Camarades and
other Webcast services. Some sites, such as SpotLife, ban sexual
and violent content. Others, including Camarades, permit adult
content, but only in a designated adult section.
</P>
<P>
   Both SpotLife and Camarades offer special sections for families
and children, but some users complain about cameras displaying
adult material in these special areas.
</P>
<P>
   A host of Camarades' family section, Ohio dad Denver Harris
spends about two evenings a week looking at the different Webcams
listed in his section. Recently he found someone broadcasting adult
content, and he sent the person a stern e-mail asking him to stop.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to using volunteer monitors such as Harris,
Camarades and many other sites encourage viewers to report naughty
broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   Each user page on Camarades has a ``cyberpatrol'' button.
Pushing it takes a snapshot of the broadcast and submits it to
Camarades staff, who will remove the camera from the site if they
deem the image offensive.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at ckirby(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
