<HEADER>
A1270 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-VC-INVESTING &LR;      08-02 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VC-INVESTING </SLUG>
  
 VCS STILL BETTING ON TECH COMPANIES
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY PETER SINTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE SENIOR WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Despite the jittery stock market since March,
venture capital investors continue to pour near record amounts of
money into Internet and other startups.
</P>
<P>
   In the past quarter, 1,054 U.S. companies received $17.2 billion
in venture financing, according to a report issued yesterday by
VentureOne Corp., a San Francisco research firm that tracks VC
investments. The number companies which received VC money was 30
fewer, or 3 percent, and the amount of money was down $1 billion,
or 6 percent, from the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, VC firms have invested almost as much money in
private companies as they did during all of 1999. Midway through
2000, 2,138 companies raised $35.4 billion, just $2 billion less
than the $37.4 billion raised by 3,153 companies during all of last
year.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent April through June quarter, information
technology companies enjoyed their strongest quarter ever,
receiving $10.1 billion, or 10 percent more than the previous
quarter. That increase may come as a surprise since the
technology-laden Nasdaq index declined 13 percent during the same
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recent public-market fluctuations led many industry
watchers to anticipate an overall drop in activity,'' said Sasha
Talebi, VentureOne's director of research. ``But in fact, companies
in most sectors have weathered the storm and continue to receive
financing from their venture backers, as well as valuable advice on
adapting their business models to the current climate.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet-related companies across all industry sectors accounted
for a record 86 percent of all money invested in the past quarter
and 79 percent of all deals. But not all Internet niches are hot.
</P>
<P>
   Investments in infrastructure companies went up 29 percent in
the second quarter after going up 47 percent in the first quarter
from the last quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, e-commerce investment, which fell 50 percent between
the fourth quarter of 1999 and the first quarter of this year, fell
an additional 32 percent in the second quarter over the previous
quarter. That drops dot-com investments to 3 percent of all
Internet investments, the lowest percentage in almost three years.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, VC investors repeatedly have delivered
additional cash to companies that delayed or canceled plans to sell
stock to the public. Yesterday, for example, Linuxcare Inc. of San
Francisco said it raised $30 million in third-round financing from
various VC and corporate backers.
</P>
<P>
   Linuxcare, which provides technical support and services for
Linux operating software, planned to raise $70 million in April
with an initial public offering. But it canceled IPO plans after
Chief Executive Officer Fernand Sarrat resigned as a result of
conflicts with the company's directors and investors suddenly lost
their appetite for many high-tech stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of companies that queued up to go public have gone back
to the venture capital well,'' said Paul Vais, general partner of
Patricof &AMP; Co. in Palo Alto, which led Linuxcare's previous round
of financing in December.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Lambs, who heads Linuxcare's office of the CEO while the
company recruits a permanent replacement to Sarrat, said that the
company's early backers and new ones such as Lehman Brothers
Venture Capital ``stepped up to the plate immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, ``there is no shortage of companies that need
funding and no shortage of funds to be put to work,'' Vais said.
</P>
<P>
   Several VC firms including Spectrum Equity Investors, Softbank
Venture Capital and Mayfield Fund, each raised $1 billion or more
for their latest investment funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen a lot of dot-com fatalities and less willingness to
finance highly speculative business plans,'' said Vais. ``Weak
companies are getting weeded out but that's healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at psinton(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
