<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0503 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1271 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-FORD-STROKE-HNS &LR;      08-02 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-FORD-STROKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Ford recovering from stroke
 &HT;    Former president's condition termed good by doctors
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By LETITIA STEIN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle &HT;    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Former President Ford remained in good condition
Wednesday at a hospital here after suffering one, possibly two,
small strokes while in town for the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Ford continued to experience some imbalance and slurring of
speech into the evening, said doctors who predicted a full recovery
for the 87-year-old former president from Michigan. He remains in
the intensive care unit, a hospital spokeswoman said Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president should totally recover from this,'' said
Robert Schwartzman, chief of neurology at the Hahnemann University
Hospital. ``He has a little trouble with his speech, a little
trouble with swallowing, but he should totally recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford was admitted to the hospital in downtown Philadelphia about
9 a.m. Wednesday when doctors diagnosed a small brain-stem stroke.
He had been treated at the hospital the previous night for pain in
the right side of his face but was immediately released without
further examination.
</P>
<P>
   Based on conversations with former first lady Betty Ford,
doctors said there is cause to believe the former president
experienced an initial stroke earlier in the week, when he was
reportedly off balance.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said Ford exhibited different symptoms when he came to
the hospital Wednesday morning than during his first visit after
his appearance at the Republican convention Tuesday night. Doctors
diagnosed a sinus infection and gave him some antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said Ford will remain hospitalized here for five to six
days to undergo further evaluation. Philadelphia doctors have been
in touch with a family physician who was treating Ford for pain in
his tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said Ford appeared calm and was fully aware of what had
occurred. Betty Ford was upset but holding up well.
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon, Ford was ``saying that he feels great and
that he'd like to go home,'' said physician Carole Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans honored Ford during a tribute to former GOP
presidents at the convention Tuesday night. Ford appeared to be in
fine health, waving with both hands to an enthusiastic crowd.
</P>
<P>
   America's 38th president, Ford assumed office on Aug. 9, 1974,
after President Nixon resigned in the face of almost-certain
impeachment for his involvement in the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Ford was the first American president to serve as both vice
president and president without being elected to either position.
In 1976, Ford was narrowly defeated for the presidency by Jimmy
Carter after pardoning Nixon for any crimes related to Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who arrived Wednesday to claim his
party's presidential nomination, said he called Betty Ford and that
she sounded hopeful that her husband would make a full recovery.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
