<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1272 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDIABYTES-COLUMN &LR;      08-02 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-COLUMN </SLUG>
  
 FORMER DESIGN DIRECTOR AT WIRED HAS GROWN TIRED OF SAN FRANCISCO
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMN BY DAN FOST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ One of the plum jobs in magazine design is about
to open up.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Carter, design director at Wired, is moving to Los
Angeles, leaving big shoes to fill at the groundbreaking magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail, Wired Editor in Chief Katrina Heron said, ``Daniel
is a supremely gifted designer (with a long, though not continuous,
history at Wired) and also a very skilled manager and motivator of
his team _ he will be very difficult to replace.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though plenty of people didn't like it, and still don't,
Wired's pioneering design has left its mark all over tech
publishing. One needs only look to the Industry Standard and
Business 2.0 _ both founded by Wired alumni _ to see the influence.
</P>
<P>
   Carter was at Wired at the start, working under legendary
designers John Plunkett and Thomas Schneider. He left the magazine
after only two years, first starting his own design studio and then
helping to launch the Standard.
</P>
<P>
   When Conde Nast bought Wired in 1998, Carter came back and
helped give the magazine a cleaner, more readable look _ while
keeping some of the trademark edge.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and Heron sought to make Wired ``what it should be
now, a more mature, well-established magazine. It's not a young
teenager screaming for attention, but more of a fast-running
adult.''
</P>
<P>
   He's most proud of April's cover, with its clean, simple design
touting Bill Joy's provocative article, ``Why the future doesn't
need us.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears, though, that two years at Wired is Carter's limit.
He's promised Heron he'll keep working from Los Angeles until the
end of the year, and she said she's in no hurry to fill his
position.
</P>
<P>
   His new wife, Aimee Marquis Carter, is design director for the
Industry Standard's new Grok magazines, which will premiere in
mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   The Carters figure they'll open their own design studio, but
other than that, Daniel Carter isn't sure what path his career will
take.
</P>
<P>
   What the Yountville native does know, at age 31, is that he
needs to leave San Francisco _ partly because he wants to live in a
bigger, more bustling city; partly because he's tired of running
into dot-com millionaires; and partly because he can't afford a
house and was just evicted from his rental for the second time in a
little more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is less about leaving Wired and more about leaving San
Francisco,'' Carter said. ``The factors were numerous.''
</P>
<P>
   DEJA VU: The Industry Standard may have more in common with
Wired than merely its look or its pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MEDIA03 (23968 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The Standard's parent company, International Data Group, said in
November that it was eyeing a potential public stock offering for
the Standard by mid-2000.
</P>
<P>
   That was before the Nasdaq's debacle in April killed most
Internet IPOs, and you don't hear that talk coming out of IDG
anymore. Of course, it's not too hard to think of another tech
magazine that came even closer to an IPO but never got out of the
gate: Wired.
</P>
<P>
   John Battelle was Wired's managing editor at the time of the
failed IPO of 1996, when the market proved unwilling to give big
bucks to an unprofitable enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Does that give Battelle _ the founder and chief executive
officer of the Standard _ any deja vu?
</P>
<P>
   ``Living through Wired got me very, very sure of one thing,''
Battelle said. ``You should never go public until you're ready.
It's not about the market. It's if your company is ready.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Um, wasn't the problem more with the market, not with Wired's
business? After all, within two years of Wired's failed IPO, plenty
of money-losing companies scored huge valuations on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Battelle says the issue is moot, because the Standard has ``four
times the revenue Wired had and a (ship)-load of profits, and a
great management team.'' He says the Standard, in its first two
years, has grown to more than 340 employees and revenue in the
``nine figures'' (read: more than $100 million). Because it remains
privately held, he doesn't have to reveal specifics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only sense of deja vu I might have about Wired was the
rocket ride,'' Battelle said. ``This has been even faster and
bigger than Wired in terms of the raw numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   An IPO, Battelle said, ``is not a requirement of our business,
nor is it something we've ruled out. ... It's one of several
options we continue to consider.''
</P>
<P>
   BACK TO CALIFORNIA: It's moving week for former Chronicle
columnist Herb Greenberg, who has had enough of the East Coast and
is returning to the Golden State _ although not to the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg, a columnist with TheStreet.com, is keeping his job,
but moving from New Jersey to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the great thing about working for an Internet
publication,'' Greenberg said. ``I write from my home in New
Jersey, why not in San Diego?''
</P>
<P>
   His move also reflects that he no longer appears on television,
as TheStreet's show was canceled in a dispute between the company
and Fox, which was airing it. He said he also doesn't need to be
near Wall Street for the kind of reporting he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been a big let's-go-do-lunch type of guy,'' he
said. ``I do the phone. I'm on the phone all the time. It's more
effective. Different journalists have different opinions, but I do
two columns a day. I don't have time to screw around at lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   TAKING PITCHES: It was the sort of event a public relations firm
should dream of, but instead the flacks blew it worse than any
World Series pitch from Mitch ``Wild Thing'' Williams.
</P>
<P>
   A softball team composed of folks from the San Francisco office
of the PR firm Golin/Harris was scheduled to play a media team
consisting of reporters from Newsweek, the New York Times, ZDNet
and National Public Radio, as well as authors and free-lancers like
Po Bronson and Ethan Watters.
</P>
<P>
   The media team, the Elucidators, was at the appointed Presidio
field Monday at 9 p.m., but Golin/Harris never showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``For once we were ready to take their pitches, and they blew
it,'' Newsweek's Brad Stone told Poynter Institute media columnist
Jim Romenesko.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Golin has a spin on the story. ``It just proves we
work harder than the journalists,'' said Golin account executive
Jackie Jones, who hastened to add, ``I'm kidding!''
</P>
<P>
   She said her team figured it was playing some average Joes, not
media heavies. ``If we had known, then not only the 10 players on
the team, but our entire office would have been there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones wants a rematch, but Stone won't hear of it. ``Maybe we'll
meet in the playoffs, and we can settle the grudge then,'' Stone
said in an e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   But don't bet on it: Stone boasts that the Elucidators are 3-1,
while Golin/Harris is 0-4.
</P>
<P>
   MERCS, MORE OR LESS: Readers of certain editions of the San Jose
Mercury News will get an expanded definition of ``local news'' this
month.
</P>
<P>
   According to an internal e-mail, a staffing shortage has led the
Merc to merge its Valley, South Valley and Coast editions into one
big combination ``local and state edition.''
</P>
<P>
   From the memo, I gather that when the copy editors and graphic
designers return from vacation after Labor Day, local news will
once again be local in those particular editions.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Media Bytes appears every Thursday in The Chronicle. Send buzz,
dirt, tips and comments to &LR;   &LR; fostd &LR; (at) &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
