<HEADER>
A1273 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-CONVENTION-MANAGE     08-02 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CONVENTION-MANAGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBTLE CONTROL OVER THE PODIUM
</HEADLINE>
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Like nearly all the speakers who have taken the
sprawling and colorful stage at the Republican convention here,
Melissa Hart, a candidate for Congress from Pennsylvania, made sure
to submit an early draft of her remarks to aides to Gov. George W.
Bush for review and approval.
</P>
<P>
   It was returned, she said on Wednesday, with just one
instruction: Cut it to a minute from 90 seconds, with no direction
on what she should take out.
</P>
<P>
   Her experience was not unusual. The week has been characterized
by rigid displays of discipline, with Bush's lieutenants roaming
the floor with schedules that list the precise second that each
event is supposed to occur, and delegates being handed daily
talking points to guide their interviews with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But the control over what is being said from the stage has taken
a decidedly subtler form, albeit with precisely the uniform result
sought by Bush's aides.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, speeches at the Republican convention in San
Diego were diligently reviewed and monitored by convention
organizers, who insisted that speakers promise to stick to their
script before allowing them to go on. This year, convention
organizers have used a velvet hammer on a receptive cast to achieve
a uniformity of message, as well as a near silence on topics like
abortion, gun control and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The planners have built each night around a specific theme,
carefully choosing elected officials and members of the public who
can speak to that theme. The elected officials are given broad
guidelines on what to say and are told as well what not to say: no
harsh attacks that can recall the convention of 1992. One speaker,
however, was given a pass from that rule: Dick Cheney, who took
several shots tonight at Clinton and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The public figures were asked to submit all speeches for review.
The main concerns of the ``auditors,'' as the convention speech
screeners are called, has been to keep the talks short and upbeat,
so as not to interfere with the snappy, happy production
Republicans organizers are seeking to present to the American
public, according to speakers and convention officials alike.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to suggest that dissidents are clamoring for floor
time. ``There just hasn't had to be the usual arm-twisting,'' one
of Bush's senior advisers said, with clear relief.
</P>
<P>
   These are different times, and Republican leaders have made the
best of them. There are no rebels trying to commandeer the
microphone, and no opposition candidates vying for attention.
Indeed, the most potentially risky moment for Bush's convention
organizers should have been when Sen. John McCain of Arizona, who
lost the nomination to Bush, appeared on Tuesday. But McCain had
submitted his speech to Bush in advance, and not a single change
was demanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the draft,'' said Mike Murphy, formerly McCain's
strategist. ``It went to Bush and I saw the draft after it came
back. I can't remember a single change.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain was one of Bush's sharpest critics in the primaries,
saying at one point that the governor ``twists the truth'' like
Clinton, and he was the only major rival of the Texas governor to
speak at the convention. Yet in this environment, where Republicans
are intent on not doing anything that might distract from the march
to the nomination, McCain was not about to harm his future standing
with the party.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the question of McCain, Bush's absolute control of the
convention has been evident every night in the choice of speakers
and their content, the result of a team that includes Andrew Card,
former secretary of transportation who is chairman of the
convention, and Ed Gillespie, who is in charge of assigning and
reviewing each day's events. With such a free hand, Bush's advisers
built each evening around a theme.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, many speakers said they were given only general
marching orders. Rep. Vito J. Fossella, the Staten Island
Republican, was asked to speak on Social Security, an interest with
which he has been identified in the House and all his life, since
his great-grandfather, James A. O'Leary, a congressman who
represented Staten Island from 1936 to 1944, voted to create Social
Security. ``The conversation was very straightforward: They asked
me if I'd be interested in speaking on Social Security and
Medicare,'' Fossella said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they wanted a positive speech,'' he said. ``That was
it.''
</P>
<P>
   A Republican aide assigned to help work with speakers in 1996
and this year said there was a marked difference in the process
this time. The aide said that one of the main speakers, Gen. Colin
Powell, was allowed to tinker with his speech up to two hours
before he went on. That would not have been permitted when Bob Dole
was nominated by a more divided convention in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would not put a word on the teleprompter until it was
scrubbed,'' the aide said of 1996. ``This time, it seemed all they
were concerned about was the number of words.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a number of speakers said that time, not substance,
seemed to be the top concern of Bush's convention organizers. Sen.
Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania said that when he submitted his
greeting to convention planners for review, they left in a veiled
reference to Specter's support of abortion rights, but asked him to
cut a joke that put a positive spin on W.C. Fields' famously
disparaging remark about the city and his home state, just to save
a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said he told them that he wanted the joke to stay. And
it did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
