<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1275 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-CHIRON-FUTURE &LR;      08-02 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIRON-FUTURE </SLUG>
  
 CHIRON REPORTS SURPRISINGLY STRONG PROFITS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY TOM ABATE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Chiron Corp. reported second-quarter earnings
Wednesday that far exceeded Wall Street's expectations, but
analysts reading between lines wondered whether the biotech giant
isn't headed for a second-half slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   On first reading the numbers looked great, as the Emeryville
firm reported earnings of 30 cents per share, beating analysts'
estimates by 9 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Profits from continuing operations rose to $57 million, up 67
percent from the $34 million (18 cents per share) that the company
reported during the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron said its second-quarter revenues rose to $241 million, up
27 percent from its $189 million in sales a year ago. Chiron's
vaccines business drove the increase, contributing $92 million in
the quarter _ a stunning 136 percent increase over the $39 million
in vaccine sales the company reported this time last year.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts came away from a post-earning conference call
with the impression that Chiron expected its earnings to dip the
rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron issues a 12-month earnings-per-share target to guide
analysts. Before yesterday's announcement, the company's target was
78 cents per share. Yesterday, it raised that figure to between 80
and 85 cents.
</P>
<P>
   This puzzled analysts. The company had already beat year-to-date
earnings expectations by 9 cents. To boost the annual target from
only two to seven cents per share suggests that Chiron expects its
earnings will drop two cents in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what one would read between the lines,'' said Viren
Mehta, a principal at Mehta Partners in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron declined to elaborate on its earnings forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Jim McCamant, who follows Chiron for the Medical Technology
Stock Letter in Berkeley, said analysts were also concerned about a
recent string of disappointments with Chiron's experimental drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for instance, the company halted clinical trials of a
drug for osteoarthritis. In March, one of its heart medications
failed a clinical trial. In September, it paused work on an ulcer
remedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street still has a feeling that Chiron can't get drugs on
the market,'' McCamant said.
</P>
<P>
   McCamant said analysts are also irked that Chiron is still
sitting on more than $1 billion in cash it earned in 1998 after it
sold off a business unit. The company has repeatedly said it
planned to use some of that money to acquire promising late-stage
drugs, ``but it still hasn't done that,'' McCamant said.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Lonergan, Chiron's vice president for investor relations,
emphasized that this was, after all, a very strong quarter. She
said that if Chiron has a problem with Wall Street, it stems from
the company's unusual business model.
</P>
<P>
   Investors tend to value drug and biotech firms based on
blockbuster products, Lonergan said. But Chiron's sales flow from a
series of niche products _ vaccines, a handful of drugs and a new
blood-testing business _ that are obviously profitable without
being home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Lonergan said Chiron's short-term prospects of expanding its
vaccine business in Europe are good, and it is poised to turn its
blood-testing unit into a big revenue engine in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   As for using its cash horde to acquire new products from smaller
startups, she said Chiron has looked and will continue to look but
won't be pushed into buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cash is something we are going to spend carefully, not
just burn,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   McCamant said Chiron also has an ace in the hole that it can't
officially factor into its earnings forecasts. In recent months,
Chiron has won key court battles in a long-running patent fight
with the Swiss drug giant Roche. McCamant believes Roche is on the
verge of settling the dispute _ which would mean a big cash payment
and royalties for Chiron.
</P>
<P>
   Lonergan said Chiron is ``in a real dialogue'' with Roche but
declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron shares gained 13 cents yesterday to close at $44.75. The
report was released just before the market closed.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at abate(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
