<HEADER>
A1277 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WEBSIDE-NEWBABIES &LR;      08-02 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBSIDE-NEWBABIES </SLUG>
  
 WEBCASTING SERVICES HELP END EQUIPMENT HASSLES
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY CARRIE KIRBY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ One problem with personal Webcasting is that the
moments you most want to share with distant relatives _ weddings,
new babies _ are often spent instead buying and setting up
equipment to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing this, services are popping up to help people
broadcast those special moments with a minimum of hassle.
</P>
<P>
   At San Jose's Good Samaritan hospital, many new parents are
introducing their infants with a free service called
BabyPressConference.com.
</P>
<P>
   Months in advance, the parents-to-be give the company e-mail
addresses of friends and relatives. When the big day arrives, the
parents call BabyPressConference.com to schedule a conference
within the following 24 hours. The company then informs the
invitees of the show time, Web address and password.
</P>
<P>
   The parents and baby go to a special Webcasting room in Good
Samaritan's maternity area, where they log into
BabyPressConference.com, smile into the camera, and begin talking
to their audience.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers can type in questions, which appear on the parents'
computer screen. The parents reply, speaking into the camera.
</P>
<P>
   A popular request: Hold the baby closer to the camera so we can
see who she looks like.
</P>
<P>
   The system is so easy to use that parents conduct the news
conference without help from hospital staff.
</P>
<P>
   Since introducing the service in April, Good Samaritan has
played host to 40 Webcasts, with 100 expectant parents signed up,
said Melanie Norall, the hospital's community relations director.
The service is free to the hospital, parents and viewers.
BabyPressConference.com hopes to profit from selling baby gifts to
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   There are glitches, especially if viewers use dial-up
connections. For example, if the video feed freezes for a few
seconds after a question is typed in, a viewer might miss the
parents' answer.
</P>
<P>
   Similar services have been offered for weddings and funerals.
Some wedding chapels and churches Webcast ceremonies. For example,
Las Vegas' A Little White Chapel shows a wedding every six minutes,
24 hours a day, on the Discovery Channel's Web site
 &LR; (www.discovery.com &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   The San Mateo county courthouse Webcast weddings on Valentine's
Day last year but doesn't offer the service on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   In Scottsdale, Ariz., a funeral home, Messenger Mortuaries,
Webcasts funerals on a password-protected site.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at ckirby(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 2327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0509 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1278 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-MAIN-HNS &LR;      08-02 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Bush arrives at convention amid fanfare
 &HT;    Cheney speech questions integrity of Clinton-Gore
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle &HT;    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The tightly scripted Republican convention
Wednesday moved closer to its anticipated climax as George W. Bush
arrived with great fanfare in Philadelphia while his running mate
Dick Cheney roused delegates by questioning the integrity of the
Clinton-Gore team.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's stinging prime-time speech provided the first
opportunity for many voters to hear Bush's surprise pick for vice
president, a former oil executive and Wyoming congressman who
served as President Bush's defense secretary during the Persian
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hoped that his nationally televised performance
would dispel doubts about Cheney sown by Democrats who have have
relentlessly attacked him for being too conservative, too tied to
the oil industry and too close to Bush's father.
</P>
<P>
   The generally upbeat day, however, had a down note as former
President Ford, who attended the convention earlier in the week,
was hospitalized after suffering one or two small strokes. The
87-year old Ford was expected to remain in the hospital for several
days but doctors predicted he would fully recover.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who served as Ford's chief of staff, sent good wishes to
his ex-boss as he began his acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   On the streets of Philadelphia, demonstrations, which had turned
violent the day before, remained peaceful as Bush arrived in the
city and attended a festive Latino rally and later a fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   At the convention, delegates continued their nominating roll
call , with the Wyoming delegation delivering the votes necessary
to put Bush over the top.
</P>
<P>
   And the theme of the evening was ``Prosperity with a Purpose,''
an effort by Republicans to showcase their tax proposals, many of
which are opposed by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   But the evening largely belonged to Cheney, a soft-spoken
Washington insider who last week quit his job as head of the
Dallas-based Halliburton, the world's largest oil field service
company, to join the Bush ticket.
</P>
<P>
   In a sharp departure from Bush's pledge to eliminate attacks on
Democrats at the convention, Cheney offered up a speech replete
with red-meat lines, that included a prediction of the end of the
Clinton-Gore era.
</P>
<P>
   ``That last day is near, '' he said to roars and applause. ``The
wheel has turned and it is time. It is time for them to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The time for them to go'' refrain, was the same chant that Al
Gore led Democratic delegates in at their 1992 national convention
in reference to President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney repeatedly hammered on the integrity theme, pledging that
he and Bush will repair the ethical damage caused by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the first hour of the first day he will restore decency and
integrity to the Oval Office,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney made scant mention of his record during six terms as
congressman, a highly conservative one that Democrats have said
provides evidence he is out of the mainstream. Democrats are
currently running television spots in Philadelphia pointing to a
series of votes including his opposition to Head Start, the clean
water act and a resolution calling for the release of South
Africa's anti-apartheid leader Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   And they have seized on the fact that he was in Bush's Cabinet
as evidence that the candidate's father is really pulling the
strings in his son's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney was introduced by his wife, Lynne, an outspoken critic of
liberal cultural trends. Referring to one her husband's favorite
pastimes, she said, ``one of the keys to understanding Dick Cheney
is understanding fly fishing. It is not a sport for the impatient.
It is not a sport for chatter boxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney also spoke of her husband's devotion to their two grown
daughters, Elizabeth and Mary, who were also in the arena.
</P>
<P>
   Mary, who is gay, has caused a stir in part because her father
has opposed gay related legislation including allowing gays in the
military. Furthermore, Republican delegates once again endorsed a
party platform that does not endorse legal protections for gays.
</P>
<P>
   A former lesbian-gay corporate relations manager for Coors
Brewing Co., Mary Cheney has taken some time off to help her
father's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gay rights is one of the hot button social issues that has
severely divided Republicans over the years.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday members of the Texas delegation protested the fact
that an openly gay Congressman Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz, was allowed
to address the convention by silently praying during his speech.
</P>
<P>
   Cathie Adams, a delegate from Dallas and president of the Texas
Eagle Forum, said she did not want to comment on Mary Cheney's role
in the convention.
</P>
<P>
   But she said, ``I have sadness for the family.''
</P>
<P>
   The third evening of the convention stressed economics, a tricky
theme for the Republicans, who must convince voters in a time of
prosperity that they should reject the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   While tax cuts have long been a central tenet of Republican
economic philosophy, polls show voters less enthused about such
proposals at a time when their stock portfolios and 401K retirement
accounts are reaping rich returns.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush has proposed a tax cut, since the primaries he
rarely talks about it as a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Republicans in Congress have pushed through a
series of smaller targeted tax cuts aimed at reducing the burden on
married couples and the families of the deceased that they believe
will sell well with voters. Clinton has threatened to veto the
elimination of the marriage penalty and estate taxes claiming they
will eat up too much of the projected surplus.
</P>
<P>
   At the convention the party featured average voters to highlight
a number of their economic proposals, including a farmer, a small
business owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost we believe in tax cuts, ''said retiring
Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, who waged a brief campaign for president
last year.
</P>
<P>
   They also touted Bush's plan to revamp the Social Security
system by letting younger people invest a portion of their
retirement taxes in the private market. Democratic presidential
candidate Al Gore has attacked the plan, claiming it would be too
risky and expensive.
</P>
<P>
   And at their daily news conference in Philadelphia, Democrats
trotted out several labor and tax experts, as well as as former
``Golden Girls'' star Rue McLanahan to criticize Bush's retirement
plan and other stands.
</P>
<P>
   They singled out Bush's belief that state's should be able to
opt out of federal minimum wage laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is extremism with a smile,''said McLanahan.
</P>
<P>
   Irasema Garza, director of the Women's Bureau at the U.S. Labor
Department and a South Texas native,said Bush seems to be oblivious
to the fact that so many Hispanic women and children are suffering
on the Texas-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   Garza urged Hispanics to look beyond what she called ``Brown
Day'' at the convention, where the party spotlighted several Latino
acts and speakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``For God's sake, all they have to do is look at his
record,''she said. ``Forty percent of Latino children live in
poverty. There is no inclusion. We have never been part of that
party.''
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
