<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHEDULE MIGHT FAVOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Only 53 games remain in the Angels' 2000
season. Of those, 32 are on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 13 teams the Angels will visit between now and season's
end, eight have winning records.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Angels are off to Cleveland for a three-game series
beginning Friday, and if they're to to make up ground on Oakland in
the American League wild-card race, it's going to be against teams
in the Central Division. The team's record suggests that can be
done _ the Angels are 18-13 against AL Central opponents this
season.
</P>
<P>
   NICKNAMES: There's nothing particularly new about nicknamed
baseball teams. It's a tradition perhaps as old as the game itself.
</P>
<P>
   There was the ``Murderer's Row Yankees'' of 1927; the ``Gashouse
Gang'' Cardinals of the 1930s; the ``Miracle Mets'' in 1969; and
the ``We are Family'' Pirates of 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Angels will find their way into that group. Their
penchant for playing close games may deserve some recognition.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, 10 of the club's last 20 games have ended in one-run
decisions. In those games, the team is 5-5 and 23-18 overall _ the
most one-run games in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 11 of the Angels' 20 games since the All-Star break
have been decided in the seventh inning or later.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Angels have 27 come-from-behind wins, and 15 of
those came in their final at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly the ideal way to win, although manager Mike
Scioscia thinks it builds character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel comfortable with that, but I have a lot of
confidence in our ability to come back,'' he said. ``It is a grind
though and it does become mentally taxing to try to come back they
way they have time after time. But they keep doing it and meeting
the challenges. But, I'd much rather see them get out in front and
stay in front.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 2337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0514 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1286 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-POLITICAL-SURFING-1ST     08-02 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-SURFING-1ST-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL SURFING: AT LAST, SOMETHING TO REPORT
</HEADLINE>
 
(Adds a new four-graph top, changes for transition in fifth graph,
eliminates last paragraph of story. ) By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps it was when the musician Kenny Gamble stepped to the
microphone and yelled _ ``Peace, everybody'' _ and then,
dissatisfied with the lackluster response from the Republican
delegates, forcefully added: ``Did you hear me? I said, peace!''
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps it was when Rep. Joe Scarborough of Florida brought
his rock band, the Regular Joes, to the stage at the Republican
National Convention and warmed up the crowd with a little poetry,
``Unite, not divide, so once again we can look at the White House
with pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it was when Fox News tracked down a giddy delegate
wearing a hat that had a live plant on its crown and a slender
chain hanging from the brim along with a four-inch ``E.'' What did
it mean? ``Bush,'' she said, pointing to the plant. ``And chain-E,
Cheney.''
</P>
<P>
   But surely CNN's Bernard Shaw was not alone when he shook his
head with disbelief, asking, ``The Republican convention?''
</P>
<P>
   The cable television reporters and Internet correspondents
seemed energized, if a little startled, by the prospect of actual
news to report from the Republican National Convention. Until
Wednesday, as has been endlessly pointed out, the convention had
been a carefully scripted infomercial punctuated by scattered
protests and pundits on autopilot.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly there was the disclosure that former President
Gerald R. Ford had gone to the hospital with what was thought to be
a sinus infection but was actually a stroke. That followed the
beginning of a whiff of a semi-controversy about former President
George Bush attacking President Clinton for attacking his son.
</P>
<P>
   The all-news channels and streaming Web sites suddenly had
something to cut back to regularly (correspondents standing outside
the hospital, promising updates on Ford's condition) and a fresh
bone to gnaw on (whether Bush should have kept quiet).
</P>
<P>
   Some news outlets that had done interviews with Ford on Tuesday,
before he was hospitalized, replayed the tapes throughout the
afternoon, so viewers could watch the 87-year-old former president
slurring his words.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the pundit class was making much of Bush's
remark that he was growing irritated with President Clinton's
attacks on his son. This allowed Democrats and some pundits to
argue that Gov. George W. Bush of Texas apparently needed his daddy
to protect him.
</P>
<P>
   Teapot Dome it was not. But it was about the only spice on the
menu.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, when President Bush and his wife, Barbara,
appeared on ABC's ``Good Morning, America,'' he waspromising to be
good. ``They're making a federal case about it,'' he said. ``It's
better to say nothing about it, future, now, nothing, period.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's host, Charles Gibson, however, knew raw meat when he
saw it and prodded once more. ``Not going to talk about it,'' Bush
insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Then Mrs. Bush jumped to her husband's aid, saying that his was
not really a personal attack, just an observation about the state
of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Gibson detected sirloin. Oh, is there something wrong
with the state of the presidency? Has it been sullied? And who
might have been responsible for that?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know who I mean,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush tried to shush his wife. ``They're going to get all over
your case,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There they were, working it out, right on live television. It
was like being a fly on the wall in Kennebunkport, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, though, the pundits seemed to have gnawed
all the meat off the bone. Besides, Governor Bush had finally
arrived in Philadelphia after stalking the convention for three
days, and was himself criticizing Clinton and Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media is making too much of this,'' a former White House
communications director, Don Bauer, said in response to an e-mail
question on a live ``Talk Back'' segment on CNN. ``They love a
sideshow.''
</P>
<P>
   Speakout.com continued its experiment with MSNBC, offering Web
surfers the opportunity to rate the impact of the major convention
speeches as they were being delivered. Those at home could
manipulate bars on their computer screens as a speech was being
given to indicate whether they agreed or disagreed with the
speaker.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict on Sen. John McCain's speech on Tuesday night was
that men and women liked it much the same. Democrats and
independents were put off by the middle of the speech, when the
senator talked about national pride.
</P>
<P>
   This just in: A live Web cam trained on the convention podium at
2:20 p.m. showed two people standing next to a big plant, talking.
It was too dark to see who they were. Another Web cam, at 3:35
p.m., trained on the main entrance outside showed an empty golf
cart and a man leaning against a chain-link fence. His back was to
the camera, but he was wearing a bright green shirt.
</P>
<P>
   In a column for the CNN Web page, Robert Novak disclosed what
had been the unspoken scandal of this convention, the scarcity of
tickets to key events. Seats that once would have gone to party big
shots were going this year to major donors. The Republican
money-raisers have ``hijacked the party,'' complained the Ohio
Republican chairman, Robert Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   For political junkies, Howard Mortman, national editor for the
Hotline, the Web site produced by the National Journal Group,
continued his series of ``Extreme Mortman'' columns, in which he
makes the convention party scene. He wrote of seeing the pundit Ann
Coulter momentarily resist a television reporter's interview
request before she ``succumbed to the temptations of the forbidden
microphone fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   And Lewis Black, a political humorist reporting for the Comedy
Central cable network, complained in a streaming Web feed that he
and his colleagues had been refused floor credentials and had been
reduced to covering the event from a college dormitory several
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had any brains, we could have been on a cruise ship,
watching it on television and sipping cocktails,'' Black said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 2337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
