u p BC-GOP-NADER-NYT &LR;      08-02 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-NADER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NADER LETS HIS FEELINGS KNOWN AT REPUBLICAN CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ It took the presence of Ralph Nader _ consumer
advocate, professional gadfly and himself a candidate for president
of the United States _ but something finally happened here
Wednesday night that, one assumes, was not in the Republican Party
script.
</P>
<P>
   Right in the middle of the presidential roll -call, Nader
charged out on the convention floor, plopped himself in front of
the Florida delegation, and began tearing into the Republican Party
and its candidate for president, George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why am I here?'' Nader asked as he found himself in the midst
of a rolling mosh pit of delegates and reporters. ``I wanted to
observe this thing in action. This is the most specular display of
cash-register politics in the history of our country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The message,'' he continued, patiently answering questions
from any reporter who had one, ``is to go home and rethink what
they're doing to the country when they sell the political system to
corporate interests.''
</P>
<P>
   As a rule of thumb, Green Party candidates for president of the
United States are not allowed on the tightly guarded floor of the
Republican convention, where everyone _ even elected Republican
leaders _ wear credentials strung around their neck. Nader was
displaying a broadcast media credential, courtesy of a reporter
from WBAI, a Pacifica Radio station in New York, who took him out
on the floor for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Although polls show that Nader's campaign has cut into support
for Vice President Al Gore, his venture Wednesday night onto the
floor was met with something less than an enthusiastic reaction
from the Florida delegates, who seemed a little shocked to realize
what was going on in front of them. First there were chants of
``Go, Bush! Go, Bush!''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Mel Martinez, a delegate from Orlando, stepped forward to
thrust a Bush-Cheney sign into his hands. Nader courteously thanked
him for the souvenier, and promised to relish it.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, with pedestiran traffic at a complete stop, Al
Cardenas, stepped forward. ``Excuse me, Mr. Nader: I'm the chairman
of the Florida delegation and this is our area,'' he said. He
informed Nader that he would be welcome to join the Republican
Party, but in the meantime, he said, it was time for Nader to go.
And, with a little prodding from other Republican delegates on the
floor, he did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-02-00 2339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000802.0516 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1291 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-BULLOCK-GHOST-HNS     08-02 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-BULLOCK-GHOST-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even in death, Bullock's presence will reign
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democratic legend's widow to address GOP convention
</P>
<P>
   By CLAY ROBISON &QL; 
and ALAN BERNSTEIN &QL; 
c. Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ In life, Texas legend Bob Bullock haunted the
dreams _ and sometimes the waking hours _ of legislators, lobbyists
and even governors because of his dominant role in the state's
lawmaking process.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the late lieutenant governor's spirit may start to haunt
his longtime political home, the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a supernatural world, Bullock's specter certainly
will be hovering over the Republican National Convention tonight,
(-- THURSDAY AUG. 3-- ) applauding George W. Bush's leadership
credentials and a friendship that transcended partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock's widow, Jan, will do the honors. She will speak to
Republican delegates and a national television audience in a salute
to Bush just before he accepts the GOP presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said that he also will talk about Bullock in his
acceptance speech to bolster his efforts to appeal to Democrats and
independents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Bullock was going to reappear. I just didn't know when
or where,'' state Sen. John Whitmire, D-Houston, quipped in a
telephone interview about tonight's mentions of Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   Whitmire was a key legislative committee chairman who often felt
Bullock's footprint on his backside.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Bullock, still a close friend of Bush and his wife, Laura,
said that her husband, if he were alive, would probably be on the
stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the governor had asked him, he would have,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Austin political consultant George Christian, a Democrat who
supports Bush and knew Bullock well, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, the lifelong Democrat ``may have had to hold his
nose around some of the (Republican) delegates, though, and they
may have had to hold theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   In her first address to a national political convention, Jan
Bullock said that she will discuss her husband's friendship with
the governor and the ``way they worked so well.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Bullock, a crusty Democratic veteran of four decades in
Texas politics often did not get along with governors from his own
party.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of many in Austin, he and Bush hit it off almost
immediately when the Republican stepped into the governor's office
in 1995. Bullock and Democratic House Speaker Pete Laney were
instrumental in delivering the legislative victories Bush now brags
about in his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock became a mentor and a personal friend to Bush. And as
early as 1996, Bullock encouraged him to run for president. He said
Bush would make a ``great president.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullock died at age 69 in June 1999, five months after retiring
from office and only a few days after Bush had launched his
national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In a eulogy, Bush praised the late Texas leader for reaching out
to a ``green governor, across parties and generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Associates of Bush and Bullock say that Bush actually reached
out first, meeting with Bullock several times before the Republican
had won the 1994 gubernatorial election to promise that he would
continue Texas' bipartisan lawmaking tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that he (Bullock) was first of all intrigued that Bush
was so brash'' and confident of winning the election, said Tony
Proffitt, a longtime Bullock spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine there was a little bit of feeling each other out,''
Christian said, noting that associates of both men were initially
surprised that their relationship developed so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bullock was irascible and tough to deal with, but Bush
understood how to work with him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some people, Christian added, believe ``that had more to do with
his (Bush's) success as governor than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   To the chagrin of many Democrats, Bullock endorsed Bush for
re-election in 1998 over Democratic challenger Garry Mauro, even
though Mauro had worked for Bullock and Bullock was godfather to
one of Mauro's children.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democratic Party Chairwoman Molly Beth Malcolm criticized
Bush for resurrecting Bullock's name for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it offensive that George Bush doesn't have any problem
continuing to use and embellish a story about a man who can no
longer speak for himself,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm said that Bullock's backing of Bush was based on
personal relationships, not on politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats supporting George Bush are an exception. They are a
small minority of the total Democrats in Texas,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitmire, said he will vote for Vice President Al Gore, the
likely Democratic nominee, for president. But he said it was fair
game for Bush to use his ties to Bullock to reinforce the message
that he is a uniter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very legitimate position to stake out,'' Whitmire said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't undo the facts. The political rhetoric is political
rhetoric, but the facts are that Governor Bush had an excellent
relationship with both parties in Texas. Speaker Laney and
(Lieutenant) Governor Bullock worked closely with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it is correct for the Bush people to draw contrasts
from his working relationship in Texas with how the system is run
in Washington, where they barely speak to each other,'' Whitmire
added.
</P>
<P>
   Admitting to some pre-speech nervousness, Jan Bullock said she
was ``really happy to be able to support George and Laura. They're
such extraordinary people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty independent (politically). I vote for the person,
rather than the party,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   During his first legislative session as lieutenant governor in
1991, Bullock appointed only Democrats to Senate leadership
positions. He started appointing Republicans in 1993, as Republican
strength in the Senate started to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``By 1993, (Bullock) was compassionate,'' said state Sen.
Florence Shapiro, R-Plano, playing off Bush's campaign theme of
compassionate conservatism. ``You know the old expression _ better
late than never.''
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
