<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1294 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-DEATH-PENALTY-HNS &LR;      08-02 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-PENALTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Clinton postpones execution date of South Texas killer
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle &HT;    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has postponed the federal
execution of a convicted South Texas killer to give him time to
seek a presidential reprieve under new federal clemency guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Former drug dealer Juan Raul Garza was to be executed Saturday
for three murders committed in the early 1990s while he was a drug
runner. He would have been the first federal prisoner to be
executed since 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Houston attorney Greg Wiercioch said his client was ``obviously
pleased'' with the postponement until Dec. 12 and was reviewing the
new guidelines, issued Wednesday, in preparation for filing a
clemency petition. He will ask Clinton to commute Garza's sentence
to life in prison without a chance for parole.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential postponement was expected. Clinton's spokesman
Jake Siewert said last month that the president planned to delay
Garza's execution in light of the Justice Department's tardiness in
issuing guidelines on death-penalty clemency petitions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ordered the department last spring to issue the new
guidelines. He said existing procedures, which had applied to all
federal prisoners, set no firm deadlines for filing clemency
petitions in capital cases.
</P>
<P>
   Such a free-wheeling schedule failed to account for condemned
defendants' special need for quick resolution of their requests due
to their imminent executions, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   A federal jury in Brownsville in 1993 convicted Garza, a major
drug dealer in South Texas, of killing three associates to further
his illegal business. He was sentenced to death under the federal
1988 Anti-Drug Abuse Act, which lets prosecutors seek the death
penalty against ``drug kingpins'' who kill as a stock in trade.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court refused to hear Garza's appeal in November
1999.
</P>
<P>
   In his clemency petition, Wiercioch said he anticipates arguing
to the president that Garza's death sentence was unfair in light of
similar federal prosecutions. In those cases, prosecutors did not
seek the death penalty even though the defendants had killed more
people than Garza had, Wiercioch said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney added that he is awaiting a Justice Department
survey on the ethnic composition of federal death row inmates. The
government's results, expected within the next few weeks, might
enhance his argument that death sentences are sought and meted out
more often against Hispanics, such as Garza, and other minorities,
Wiercioch said.
</P>
<P>
   Garza, who moved more than 7,000 pounds of marijuana through
South Texas from 1982 to 1992, killed Erasmo de la Fuente, whom
Garza blamed for losing a marijuana shipment, and de la Fuente's
associate Gilberto Matos. Following those 1990 slayings, Garza
killed Thomas Albert Rumbo the next year when Rumbo agreed to help
authorities after being caught helping to ship marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Garza sits on death row in Terre Haute, Ind., one of about 20
condemned federal prisoners, including Oklahoma City bomber Timothy
McVeigh. These prisoners can avail themselves of the new clemency
rules after they exhaust all their court appeals.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines do not carry the force of law and the president
remains free to disregard them so long as he does not violate a
defendant's constitutional rights.
</P>
<P>
   Under the guidelines, condemned convicts may petition only once
for clemency unless ``exceptional circumstances'' come to light
after the request is filed. Other federal defendants are permitted
to reapply a year after a clemency denial.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines allow condemned defendants 30 days from the date
their execution is scheduled in which to ask the president to
commute their sentences. The new procedures presume quick action by
the president.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-day clock for Garza will not start until the guidelines
are printed in the Federal Register, the official recorder of U.S.
agency actions. The guidelines' publication is expected soon.
</P>
<P>
   All petitions and supporting documents go first to the Justice
Department's office of pardon attorney, as is the current practice.
</P>
<P>
   In a new provision for capital cases, the defendants' lawyers
may ask to appear before the pardon attorney to plead their cases.
But victims and prosecutors also have an opportunity to testify
before the pardon attorney in opposition to the clemency requests.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
