<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-WHITE-SOX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS TOP WHITE SOX ON 13-HIT ATTACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers had 13 hits against the Chicago
White Sox last night, and there seemed to be a story behind almost
every one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the 13 hits support pitcher Rick Helling in a 7-2
victory against the White Sox, but it gave insight into how the
Rangers are coping offensively with the recent loss of Ivan
Rodriguez and David Segui. For a team that just lost its two
leading hitters in the course of nine games, the Rangers are still
scoring runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this team is going to hit, regardless,'' first baseman
Rafael Palmeiro said. ``I really believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers finished 5-4 on the homestand, batting .298 and
scoring 57 runs. That's an average of 6.3 runs per game, not bad
for a team that lost Rodriguez in the first inning of the first
game and traded Segui to the Cleveland Indians halfway through the
homestand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've still got some good hitters on this team,'' catcher Bill
Haselman said. ``If we put together some good at-bats, we're more
than capable of having some big innings and that's what we've been
doing lately.''
</P>
<P>
   The big inning yesterday was a four-run third inning, and once
again Haselman and Gabe Kapler were in the middle of it.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler had a run-scoring double in the third to extend his
hitting streak to 16 games, and he's batting .379 in that stretch.
Haselman, who had a run-scoring single on his way to a 3-for-4
night, is hitting .342 in his past 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler's double came right after the White Sox walked Palmeiro.
Manager Johnny Oates said, with Rodriguez and Segui gone, one of
the keys to the Rangers' offense in the final two months will be
finding some hitters who can protect Palmeiro. He was walked three
times last night and is on pace to walk a career-high 102 times
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not getting any pitches to hit right now,'' Oates said.
``He's going to have to be patient, but it's important someone
protect Raffy. He's our big gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Kapler: ``I see it as a big challenge. Obviously I don't
care if I'm as hot as a firecracker the rest of the year, teams
would still rather pitch to me than Raffy. But it's still a great
challenge. I just have to harness my anger when I see somebody
pitch around somebody to face me. I don't like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Greer could also help, and he snapped out a minor slump
with a 3-for-4 effort.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox didn't pitch around Palmeiro in the seventh, and
he led off with a double against left-handed reliever Kelly Wunsch.
Kapler moved him to third with a grounder and, with the Rangers
leading 4-2, that set up what Oates said was the biggest hit of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   With left-hander Ricky Ledee due up, Oates sent up right-hander
Chad Curtis to pinch hit, and he singled through the drawn-in
infield to make it 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   The at-bat showed two things. One is the Rangers may want to
look at Ledee, but Oates is still going to make every move
necessary to win the game. Second, it showed Curtis, despite not
being happy with less playing time, still has a role to fill.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a valuable part of the club,'' Oates said. ``I've got a
roster of 25 players, and I'm going to do everything I can to put
everybody in a situation where they can succeed, just like if we
were one game out.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Curtis, ``As long as I'm here, I'm going to do everything I
can to help us win.''
</P>
<P>
   Haselman brought home Curtis with a double to left-center, and
Mike Lamb made it 7-2 with a single to center. Lamb was 2-for-4
last night, raising his average to .297, the highest by a rookie in
the majors this year.
</P>
<P>
   He's part of the reason why the Rangers lead the American League
with a .291 team batting average. Despite all else, they can still
hit.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
